<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVOTI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS TESTIFY THEY DID NOT SEE A CHOKE HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York City police sergeant and another police
officer testified Monday that they did not see Officer Francis
Livoti use a choke hold to subdue Anthony Baez in December 1994,
when Baez died after an arrest in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   But during five hours of withering cross-examination by a
federal prosecutor, the sergeant, William Monahan, conceded that he
and Livoti had met with their lawyers in the offices of the police
union to hear Livoti's version of the incident before Monahan gave
statements to police investigators and the Bronx district
attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-examination of Monahan came on the first full day of
the defense case in the trial of Livoti in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan. Livoti, who was acquitted in 1996 of criminally
negligent homicide in the death but was dismissed from the police
force after an administrative trial, is charged with one count of
depriving Baez of his civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that Livoti used a choke hold as he
attempted to arrest Baez after a confrontation sparked by a
late-night touch football game, in which a football repeatedly hit
a police cruiser outside the Baez family home. Livoti's lawyer
denies that his client ever used a choke hold, which is banned by
the Police Department, and contends that Baez died of a severe
asthma attack after resisting arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Although federal prosecutors did not accuse Monahan directly of
a cover-up Monday, one prosecutor told the jury last week that it
might hear testimony from police officers ``who covered up what
happened on Cameron Place on Dec. 22 in order to protect a fellow
officer and in order to protect themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor who conducted the cross-examination, Andrew
Dember, told Judge Shira Scheindlin out of the jury's presence
Monday that the government believed Monahan had ``failed
miserably'' in supervising Livoti, and that his failures raised
questions about the credibility of his testimony absolving Livoti
in Baez's death.
</P>
<P>
   After court, Monahan declined comment about the day's
proceedings. ``I'm tired of talking,'' he said. ``I'm done for the
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Livoti's lawyer, Stuart London, said in a brief interview
afterward that he disagreed strongly with the prosecution's
assertion that Monahan had failed to properly supervise Livoti. ``I
don't see where that failure is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was right there when Livoti needed assistance and came
right over to help,'' London said, referring to the sergeant's
testimony that when Livoti and Baez began to struggle, Monahan got
out of their patrol car and went to his fellow officer's
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   London said the government's use of the word failure is ``a
conclusion that's not supported by the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, on direct examination, Monahan testified that after the
struggle in which prosecutors contend that Baez was choked, he saw
Baez, handcuffed, stand up and walk briefly, with assistance from
Livoti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer Livoti had his arm underneath Anthony Baez's armpit,
and they took two or three steps towards the curb,'' Monahan
testified.
</P>
<P>
   Baez's knees then buckled, Monahan said, and despite Livoti's
best efforts to support him, Baez ``went down to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Another officer, Anthony Farnan, testified Monday that he, too,
had seen Baez moving after he fell to the ground, that Baez was
``definitely not'' unconscious, and that Livoti had not used a
choke hold.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Monahan's testimony that prompted the government's
strongest attacks on the credibility of police. Dember elicited
testimony from the sergeant that he had met with Livoti in the
headquarters of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association about a week
after the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``During your meeting with the defendant that day, isn't it true
that he went through in your presence the complete story about what
he remembered happening?'' Dember asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went through it together,'' Monahan said, adding that
Livoti gave him a demonstration of how he had held Baez before they
fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it for our attorneys, who were present,'' Monahan said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Dember asked Monahan about earlier warnings that
Livoti had received from the commander of the 46th Precinct
regarding the use of excessive force against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Monahan acknowledged that he was aware generally of his
responsibility to monitor Livoti's interactions with civilians, but
that he had not focused on them that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``At any point during that night,'' Dember asked, ``did the
instructions you received from the commanding officer of the 46th
Precinct ever cross your mind?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I remember, no,'' Monahan replied.
</P>
</TEXT>
