<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-SECURITIES-COX     06-23 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SECURITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williamson land speculator at risk of losing securities license
 &HT;    By Dylan Rivera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ State regulators are trying to revoke the
securities license of Pohl, Brown &AMP; Associates Inc., which controls
5,000 acres of commercial land in Williamson County, Texas. Company
officials refused to allow inspectors to freely examineadvertising
records, complaints from investors and other information during a
surprise inspection in December, said David A. Grauer, director of
enforcement for the State Securities Board.
</P>
<P>
   Gary F. Brown, vice president of Pohl, Brown said company
officials are willing to make the records available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not deny them access to anything,'' Brown said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Grauer would not say why the Securities Board was seeking the
records. He said enforcement officials inspect partnership records
as part of investigations and in routine checks for compliance with
state laws. Pohl, Brown manages more than 50 limited partnerships _
groups of investors who pool their money, in this case to buy land.
Pohl, Brown tries to sell the land at a profit. If the license were
revoked, the company would not be able to seek investors for such
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a disagreement over how securities officials
are allowed to inspect partnership records, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   When three Securities Board investigators visited the company on
the morning of Dec. 10, Brown was overseas and Bill Pohl, the
company president, was meeting with investors in Houston, Texas. A
receptionist and real estate brokers for the company were in the
office on the 10th floor of the Tower of the Hills building, 13809
Research Blvd. in Northwest Austin, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't say specifically what they wanted to see,'' Brown
said. ``They just said 'everything.' Well, everything's a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he and Pohl spoke with investigators by telephone and
told them they could return the next day, when Pohl was due back,
to review the appropriate records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to just open our file cabinets to whoever wants
to come in,'' Brown said. ``We thought they would come the next
day, and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has never faced an effort to revoke its license
before, Brown added.
</P>
<P>
   Though he wouldn't comment on specifics of the case, Grauer, the
enforcement director, said Pohl, Brown officials did not allow free
and unlimited access to partnership records, as is required by law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular allegation here . . . goes to the very
integrity of the inspections process,'' Grauer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities Board regulates limited partnerships, stock
offerings and other forms of securities statewide, Grauer said. The
agency's officers are allowed to make surprise visits to inspect
securities dealers' records, similar to the way health department
inspectors visit restaurants to test for cleanliness and food
quality, Grauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealers should be aware that we will not tolerate obstructions
of agency investigations,'' Grauer said. ``If a dealer refuses to
permit our inspections, which are designed to protect investors, we
will seek swift and decisive sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   The proceedings would take away the securities dealer license
held by Pohl, Brown and used by its agents, Pohl, Brown and Michael
T. Leggett. The Securities Board revoked 17 dealers' licenses in
the fiscal year ending August 1997, Grauer said.There are more than
100,000 securities agents statewide, many of whom work under one
dealer license, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A California company has a contract to buy 80 percent of Pohl,
Brown's holdings in Williamson County. Grauer said any action on
the securities license would not affect land sales.
</P>
<P>
   Making surprise inspections is crucial to the Securities Board's
investigations, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the very essence of the inspections,'' Grauer said.
``There is no opportunity to sanitize or otherwise secrete any
documents.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if company officials promise to allow
investigators to see their files after the initial visit, Grauer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Securities enforcement officials had hearings in February and
May before Ann Landeros, an administrative law judge with the Texas
Office of Administrative Hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Landeros will forward findings of the investigation and any
recommendations for action to Securities Commissioner Denise Voigt
Crawford. Crawford's decision can be appealed in state district
court, Grauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Pohl, Brown attorney Dudley McCalla did not return phone calls
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   If Pohl, Brown's license is revoked, the company could apply for
a new one at any time, Grauer said. When reviewing an application
for a new license, Securities Board officials would consider
information from the license revocation hearings, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Investors in some partnerships with Pohl, Brown have filed a
class-action suit alleging that company officials misled them into
buying shares of partnerships and didn't tell them about offers to
sell land the partnerships own.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hemphill, an attorney representing the plaintiffs, said he
didn't know much about the Securities Board investigation but that
it doesn't appear the allegations will affect the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do allege that they didn't disclose some information to
investors that they should have,'' Hemphill said. ``I think that's
different than whatever they're alleged of doing here.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Securities Board was seeking information at Pohl,
Brown's offices, officials with the Texas General Land Office were
trying to sell 446 acres in Northwest Austin to Madron Investments
Ltd. _ a major client of Pohl, Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Agency spokesman Ron Calhoun said land office officials did not
know about the Securities Board proceedings against Pohl, Brown.
But he said the proceedings probably were not relevant to the land
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan Rivera writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Staff writer Kim Tyson contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
