<HEADER>
A1651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOSPITAL-BACTERIA-     06-23 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSPITAL-BACTERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITALS FORGE AN ALLIANCE TO FIGHT ANTIBIOTIC-RESISTANT BACTERIA

</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jolted by the rapid spread of bacteria that resist
antibiotics, New York City's business community and six top
hospitals are forging a novel alliance to detect, identify, and, if
all goes well, reduce the bacteria's levels in the city's
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, health experts nationwide have been
cautiously worrying about the threat posed by the increasing
immunity of the bacteria, which can cause potentially fatal
diseases like tuberculosis and pneumonia and serious infections
like strep or staph.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of death from resistant bacteria is relatively low,
most experts agree. But the new alliance recognizes a growing
concern about not only the bacteria, but also about a potential
side effect: that a public health issue may have economic
consequences as well. A major concern for the alliance is that
patients fearing infection will shun New York's otherwise respected
hospitals, harming an industry that is one of the city's economic
mainstays.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the initiative is the notion _ widely assumed
but scientifically unproven _ that New York City has more strains
of drug-resistant bacteria than most other parts of the country, or
at least that some strains appear in the city first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if New York has a bigger problem than other places,
it's going to affect the competitiveness of our hospitals,'' said
Willa Appel, president of the Policy Center of the New York City
Partnership, the city's leading business group, which is overseeing
the project.
</P>
<P>
   There are other cost concerns in a city where the health care
industry is the largest private employer. A recent study by the
Lewin Group, a Washington-based health care consultancy, estimated
that staph infections alone cost $435 million to treat in the New
York area in 1995. In general, patients with infections must be
hospitalized longer, erasing the savings associated with managed
care and other cost-cutting measures.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Kreiswirth, an infectious-disease expert who runs a
laboratory in Manhattan that identifies bacteria and is involved in
the project, said the issue of resistance to antibiotics also
raises questions about many medical procedures that are profitable
to hospitals, like triple-bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hospitals which make money on these procedures will start
having major problems,'' Kreiswirth said, ``and I don't know how
the HMOs are going to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The initiative focuses its efforts on hospitals, where the risk
of infections is far greater than in the general population.
Hospitals are by definition centers for sick people and, with so
many antibiotics in use, the bacteria most likely to survive are
those that have developed resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Appel said the project would cost more than $1 million for the
first two years, and she is seeking federal and state grants to pay
for it.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is at an early stage. The most concrete _ and
unusual _ accomplishment is the hospitals' agreement to share
information about infections that they are normally reluctant to
discuss with each other. To address that concern, the information
in the project would not be public, and in fact, the names of the
hospitals would be available to only a few people involved.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the project is to enable hospitals to detect
and identify new bacterial strains before they spread, Appel said.
To do that, the program would standardize the databases of the
hospitals, which would plug in information about their infections
and in return be able to find out about infections at other
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The project also calls for the hospitals to create uniform
methods of identifying various bacteria and to report the quantity
and types of antibiotics they dispense, to determine whether
greater use correlates with greater resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the rate at which people are developing infections
in hospitals rose 36 percent from 1975 to 1995, according to a
study released earlier this year. Of the 36 million hospital
admissions that year, there were 1.8 million infections contracted
in hospitals, according to the Federal Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention in Atlanta. Infections contributed to the deaths of
88,100 of those patients, and experts say infection was the direct
cause of death in perhaps a quarter of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 70 percent of those 1.8 million infections were caused
by bacteria with some resistance to one or more antibiotics. It is
uncertain how many people die from bacteria that cannot be treated
with antibiotics, but experts say the number is surely rising.
</P>
<P>
   There are no comparative statistics for New York City or New
York State.
</P>
<P>
   Among the questions the project seeks to answer is whether New
York indeed has more resistant bacteria than other regions do.
Experts have speculated that the city's role as a magnet for
business and worldwide immigration contributes to the problem,
especially because many immigrants come from nations where
antibiotic use is much more widespread than in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1653 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MURDOCH-DODGERS-L     06-23 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MURDOCH-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH'S STYLE SHAPES DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- If you're trying to figure out whose fingerprints
were on the shotgun that blasted Los Angeles Dodgers Manager Bill
Russell and Executive Vice President Fred Claire out of their jobs
Sunday, look 15 miles west of Dodgers Stadium to Culver City.
</P>
<P>
   That's where media mogul Rupert Murdoch's offices are on the
20th Century Fox lot and where he works when he's on the Left
Coast. It's most likely that's where Murdoch made the decision to
pull the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, team President Bob Graziano made the move late
Sunday after consulting with News Corp. President Peter Chernin and
Co-Chief Operating Officer Chase Carey. But to conclude that
Murdoch, the self-made billionaire who built News Corp. into a
worldwide empire from scratch, had no influence in sacking Russell
and Claire would be naive, financial analysts said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be surprising if this did not go all the way to
Murdoch,'' said analyst Steven Cesinger of investment bank Greif &AMP;
Co. ``He's obviously got to be concerned about how the team is
being run, given the dismal performance so far this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's management style, more than anything, reflects a
willingness to upset the status quo, even in a tradition-bound
enterprise like Major League Baseball. Consider that when Murdoch
completed the $311 million buyout of the Dodgers, Chernin and Carey
promised News Corp. would respect the team's traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Dodgers have:
</P>
<P>
   --Gotten rid of free meals for the press and Dodgers executives.
</P>
<P>
   --Shaken up the cathedral-like atmosphere of Dodger Stadium by
bringing in between-innings rock music and plenty of advertising.
</P>
<P>
   --Traded two of the team's most popular players, Mike Piazza and
Hideo Nomo
</P>
<P>
   --And become the first team this season to fire the manager and
operations chief.
</P>
<P>
   For those who know Murdoch, though, one of the big questions
about the summer house-cleaning was a simple one: What took so
long?
</P>
<P>
   ``Murdoch paid a hefty price for the team,'' Cesinger said.
``Above all, he's a performance-oriented owner, so if something's
not working and you've got a better idea, there's no time like the
present to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of Russell and Claire argued that the team has
suffered through an unusually large amount of injuries and bad
luck. Other critics of the firings say that making a mid-season
switch amounts to throwing in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch trackers respond that those kind of concerns don't
matter in Rupert's world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the track record of Russell and Claire had been
anything to write home about, and the team looks like it's been in
disarray,'' said analyst Arthur Rockwell of Drake Capital
Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew that Murdoch's people were eventually going to
bring in their own people. He didn't buy the team to learn how to
run it. His people already know what's involved with undoing and
building up sports teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch, whose empire is valued at more than $30 billion, has a
reputation as a workaholic and micromanager who promotes executives
who reflect his own bottom-line sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   So the firings don't necessarily mean that Murdoch has been
hanging out in the Dodger clubhouse with Tom Lasorda -- who became
Claire's replacement with the title interim general manager -- but
rather Graziano, Carey and Chernin have adopted the
go-for-the-jugular Murdoch style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carey and Chernin have a certain rough edge to them and
they're easy to picture as working in that kind of environment with
a rough and tumble approach to business,'' Rockwell said. ``These
are the sort of guys who have filtered up through the ranks and
gained Murdoch's confidence by doing things in his style.''
</P>
<P>
   The firings confirmed the fears of many longtime Dodgers fans.
Murdoch's ownership clearly means wrenching changes after four
decades of cautious operation by the O'Malley family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization has always had this deep emotional attachment
to its heritage from the Brooklyn days, but this is a new era,''
said retail consultant Frederick Marx, of Bloomfield Hills, Mich.
``Murdoch has a willingness to part with convention. He's all about
the bottom line and giving the public what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts note that Murdoch generally operates his far-flung
empire effectively because his strategies make sense on a long-term
global basis. ``It doesn't matter where the venue is,'' Marx said.
``He's kind of the Marco Polo of our age.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver sports consultant Dean Bonham said none of Murdoch's
actions have surprised him. ``News Corp. is doing exactly what I
expected them to do, which is making the moves that you make when a
sports team is part of a conglomerate.''
</P>
<P>
   Key among those goals is expanding the reach of the Fox
networks, Bonham said, citing Murdoch's stated goal of using the
Dodgers and sports assets as a ``battering ram'' to set up
pay-per-view and cable networks in new markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidly, I would not be surprised to see the Dodgers lose $20
million a year for the next five years,'' Bonham said, noting that
News Corp. was willing to lose up to $150 million a year on pro
football broadcasts simply to elevate the status of the Fox
Broadcasting Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Dodgers have been doing doesn't make sense if they
were owned by an individual, but my gut instinct tells me that it
makes sense for News Corp., which owns 72 companies on five
continents,'' he said. ``The Dodgers are an important piece of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one analyst said the firings are more a reflection of
the industry than Murdoch's management style.
</P>
<P>
   ``These firings may be more of a testament to the whole
direction of sports with the growing need to win immediately,''
said David Carter, a Los Angeles sports consultant.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
