<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSHAWK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOSHAWK NOT LIKELY TO BE LISTED AS ENDANGERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ In a major decision affecting Western forests, the
federal government today is expected to refuse _ for the third time
_ calls by environmentalists to list the Northern goshawk as an
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   That decision would be a blow to environmentalists, but a
blessing for the embattled timber industry in Arizona and New
Mexico, already decimated by two federal injunctions in recent
years aimed at protecting the Mexican spotted owl and other
creatures that live in old-growth forests.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Clark, director of the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, is
expected to announce the decision today based on a recent review
conducted by the agency's regional office in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   That review was done, in part, by Richard Reynolds, a researcher
for the U.S. Forest Service who has advocated against placing the
goshawk on the federal Endangered Species List.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really outrageous is that logging on the national
forests is what's driving the goshawk extinct. The fact that they
put the Forest Service in charge . . . when it's the Forest Service
that (approves) logging the trees, shows you how corrupt this whole
process has become,'' said Kieran Suckling, executive director of
the Southwest Center for Biological Diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Tenney Jr., vice president of Precision Pine and Timber
Co., one of the state's few remaining logging firms, said he would
welcome a decision not to list the goshawk.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my view, the Forest Service has put in place guidelines
to protect the goshawk, and they are working,'' said Tenney, who
served on the committee that helped develop those guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   While it does not explicitly recommend against listing the
goshawk, the new goshawk review by the Fish and Wildlife Service
concludes that current protections appear adequate and there should
be enough habitat for the goshawk to avoid extinction.
</P>
<P>
   In a critique of that review, Suckling charged that Reynolds'
involvement was ``a profound violation'' of scientific review
policies since Reynolds is the chief author of goshawk management
policies currently used by the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Reynolds has conducted much good research on northern
goshawks, and is certainly an expert in the field,'' Suckling said,
``he also has a conflict of interest, which makes his presence on
the team inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds, who has focused his work for more than seven years on
the forest north of the Grand Canyon, did not return calls to his
office.
</P>
<P>
   However, in an interview last year, he said he did not believe
listing the goshawk was warranted, despite findings in his research
that goshawk numbers are in decline.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said he found that intensive, almost clear-cut logging
during the 1980s of the forests north of the Grand Canyon wiped out
habitat for goshawks and their prey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned. (But) if you were to ask me, `Do you recommend
or do you not recommend that the species be listed,' I would not
recommend it at this time,'' Reynolds said last year.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter last week to Clark, Suckling called the wildlife
agency's goshawk report ``deeply flawed,'' a ``violation of the
Endangered Species Act'' and ``a recipe for litigation'' for
failing to include the best science available.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Knudsen, biology supervisor for the Portland office, said
he didn't know whether the goshawk would be listed as an endangered
species, and declined to answer any additional questions.
</P>
<P>
   Suckling's group first petitioned the Fish and Wildlife Service
in 1991 to list the goshawk _ a bird of prey with short wings and a
broad tail. &QL; 
made for intricate maneuvering through forests.
</P>
<P>
   The Fish and Wildlife Service denied the request in 1992 and
1996, but both times was overruled by senior Judge Richard Bilby of
the U.S. District Court in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling last year, Bilby chastised the Fish and Wildlife
Service decisions as ``arbitrary, capricious and unlawful'' and
``an abuse of (Fish and Wildlife's) discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Fish and Wildlife to conduct a third review of
the goshawk, which he said ``may be endangered'' based on previous
opinions by Fish and Wildlife's Phoenix research office and a
consultant to the Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Fish and Wildlife Service's) actions have only served to
lengthen the amount of time until goshawks may be listed,'' Bilby
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released this month, Martin Taylor, an ecologist and
assistant professor of agriculture at the University of Arizona,
said goshawks in the West meet ``the best available criteria for
endangered species'' and ``are at risk from loss of habitat,
primarily from logging on federal lands.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor criticized the Forest Service guidelines, saying that,
since they took effect in 1992, ``goshawk populations have declined
sharply in the south and central West.'' &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
