<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTNEY-SERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDS, FAMILY PAY TRIBUTE TO LINDA MCCARTNEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Linda McCartney died of breast cancer in Tucson,
Ariz., on April 17, a spokesman for Sir Paul McCartney, her
husband, asked that the family be allowed to grieve privately. For
six weeks, that was what the McCartneys did, mostly at the family
farm in West Sussex, England.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday evening, Sir Paul, his four children and 400 invited
friends and relatives gathered at Riverside Church to pay tribute
to Ms. McCartney and celebrate her achievements as a campaigner for
animal rights and vegetarianism, and as a photographer, mother and
wife. It was the second such gathering this month. The first was in
London on June 8.
</P>
<P>
   Although England was her home during her 29-year marriage to Sir
Paul, her roots were in New York. She grew up in Scarsdale, and
before marrying she was a prominent rock photographer in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ringo Starr nor George Harrison was expected to attend
the New York service, as they did in London, and neither was
spotted, nor was Yoko Ono, John Lennon's widow. Sir Paul and the
children, Heather, Mary, Stella and James, arrived at 8:20, 10
minutes before the memorial was to begin. But apart from the
McCartneys, Diane Sawyer, Mike Nichols and Ralph Lauren, few
celebrities were seen entering the church.
</P>
<P>
   Like the London memorial, the tribute Monday was a private
affair, with a guest list of around 400, said Joe Dera, Sir Paul's
spokesman. The church can hold 1,800. Reporters were not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the McCartneys, many of whom were nearly as fond of Ms.
McCartney as of her husband, were also asked to wait outside the
church. About 300 were on hand, some from as far away as Michigan
and California. A few brought posters that said ``Forever in Our
Hearts'' or ``Go Veggie for Linda.'' Others held candles.
</P>
<P>
   For the occasion, several large portraits of Ms. McCartney, 56
when she died, were arrayed across the nave, which was festooned
with flowers, said the Rev. Robert Gentile, an official at the
church.
</P>
<P>
   The program for the memorial, provided by Dera, listed the
singers Chrissie Hynde and Neil Young among the speakers. Ms.
Hynde, like Ms. McCartney, has been a vocal proponent of
vegetarianism and opponent of using animals for food or scientific
testing. Other speakers included the 1960s model Twiggy, as well as
Ms. McCartney's brother, John Eastman, and her two sisters, Laural
Malcolm and Louise Weed. Sir Paul was scheduled to offer his own
comments at the end of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Also part of the service was a brief appearance by a brown and
white dappled appaloosa, Ms. McCartney's favorite riding horse.
</P>
<P>
   The program included plenty of music. The service began with a
lone bagpipe player performing ``Mull of Kintyre,'' a song Sir Paul
wrote in the early 1970s. The Loma Mar String Quartet played
several of the songs Sir Paul wrote for his wife, including ``The
Lovely Linda,'' ``Somedays,'' ``Maybe I'm Amazed,'' ``Calico
Skies'' and ``My Love.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boys Choir of Harlem sang Sir Paul's song ``Blackbird'' and
the gospel hymn ``His Eye Is on the Sparrow.'' The choir and the
congregation were scheduled to join in versions of the hymn ``All
Things Bright and Beautiful'' and the Beatles song ``Let It Be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
