<SLUG> BC-HOFFA-DECISION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ALLOWS HOFFA TO REMAIN IN RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge Monday upheld a federal monitor's decision in
April not to disqualify James Hoffa from running for the teamsters'
presidency, although the judge criticized some of Hoffa's behavior
in the 1996 election as ``disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal monitor, Michael Cherkasky, chose not to disqualify
Hoffa even though he found Hoffa was responsible for failing to
report almost $40,000 in campaign contributions accurately and had
not testified truthfully about receiving a $1,000 donation from a
former president of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters.
</P>
<P>
   Cherkasky had fined Hoffa $16,767, or 10 percent of the $167,675
in free services that Cherkasky said Hoffa had received from his
communications director. But the judge, David Edelstein of U.S.
District Court in Manhattan, ordered Hoffa to pay a fine equal to
the whole $167,675.
</P>
<P>
   Edelstein called Hoffa's concealment of the contribution and his
failure to report other donations accurately ``worrisome and
suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   David Lyle, a Hoffa spokesman, said he could not comment upon
Edelstein's decision because he had not seen it. Hoffa has denied
that he lied to the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Carey's 1996 victory over Hoffa for the union presidency was
overturned by federal monitors who ordered a new election. It is
scheduled for this summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
