A1693 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-1STLD-WRI     06-23 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONE CHINA' POLICY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs for updating, rewriting throughout0 CLINTON IS PRESSED ON (sw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China's foreign minister on Tuesday called on
President Clinton to make a public statement during his state visit
this week restating American opposition to any move by Taiwan
toward independence.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference on Tuesday morning the minister, Tang
Jiaxuan, also called on the United States to halt sales of advanced
weapons like fighter planes and defensive missiles to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States should take concrete action to match the
commitments it has made on Taiwan with deeds,'' he said, referring
to the sale of advanced arms.
</P>
<P>
   Tang's statements broke no new ground and reflected the
overriding position of Taiwan, considered here as a renegade part
of the Chinese motherland, in Chinese foreign policy. But they did
disclose one of the key unresolved issues between the two countries
for a summit meeting that is expected to stress positive images and
gloss over differences.
</P>
<P>
   While Washington supports a ``one China'' policy and opposes
Taiwan's independence, Taiwan enjoys strong support in the
Congress. It appears extremely unlikely that China will get the
promise it seeks.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Tang gave an upbeat assessment of the coming visit,
which the Chinese government hopes will improve China's image in
America and foster closer economic and political ties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect the visit to be crowned with a complete success,''
Tang said. ``It will propel China-United States relations into a
new stage of growth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese leaders are well aware, Tang said, of what he called
the ``discord and noises'' in the United States coming from critics
of the administration's policy of engaging China. But he said: ``I
am convinced this does not represent the desire and conscience of
the vast majority of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Tang also responded to the attacks on Clinton's willingness to
be greeted in Tiananmen Square, where the military crushed student
demonstrations in 1989. He said that the spot _ a plaza on the edge
of the square in front of the Great Hall of the People _ was the
routine site for greeting foreign heads of state and that if
President Jiang were not to meet Clinton there, it would be ``a
lack of courtesy.''
</P>
<P>
   The foreign minister also brushed aside calls by some democracy
advocates in China for Clinton to meet with their representatives.
The so-called dissidents, Tang said, ``usually are people who have
violated the criminal law of China.'' He noted that Clinton has
already indicated he will not seek a meeting with any political
dissidents during this visit.
</P>
<P>
   On other issues to be discussed, a senior Chinese trade official
said on Monday that China hoped to make progress toward joining the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But in contrast with earlier hopes that entry could be clinched
by now, the official, Shi Guangsheng, minister for foreign trade
and economic cooperation, said there was no timetable. His reaction
to American statements that China was far from satisfying
requirements for opening its markets to outsiders was mild.
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``we will continue to hope for positive and
substantive progress'' toward agreement on entry into the trading
body.
</P>
<P>
   ``China wants to join the WTO because this is necessary for our
own economic reform and opening up,'' Shi said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization sets global trade rules. Its 132 member nations
must reduce barriers to trade and investment, and in turn they are
given better trading conditions in other member countries.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday in Beijing the chief American trade negotiator,
Charlene Barshefsky, said it had become clear that Chinese leaders,
preoccupied with domestic economic dangers, were not ready to make
the major changes needed. Besides general tariff levels, American
officials are especially concerned about barriers to agricultural
imports and to foreign involvement in financial, accounting,
tourism and other service industries.
</P>
<P>
   China has portrayed entry into the trade body as a political as
well as an economic goal, and has sometimes lambasted the West for
imposing what China considers unfair requirements. But on Monday
Shi, consistent with a general effort by officials to minimize
conflict, kept his complaints muted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
