<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA FAILING IN TREATMENT OF TROUBLED KIDS, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ For years, people have criticized how the state takes
care of children in Maricopa County who are poor and mentally
troubled.
</P>
<P>
   A report to be released Tuesday shows how bad it can be:
</P>
<P>
   _ A 4-year-old on seven different types of drugs, including one
strong anti-psychotic drug. There's no system in place to determine
if this child is overmedicated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Psychiatrists unwilling to counsel children who have been
sexually abused because they don't think they can help the child
within the system's 90-day deadline. Talking about the abuse _
without resolving anything _ could cause more harm than good, they
believe.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents turning custody of their children over to the state
because they feel individuals can't fight the system to get care
for their children.
</P>
<P>
   The state-run system is ``content to provide `poor care' in the
right way rather than `good care' the wrong way,'' the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In affable _ yet scathing _ tones, the report, conducted by a
panel of state-approved experts, outlines how 61 percent of
children don't get the mental health services they need.
</P>
<P>
   The report confirms what parents, lawyers, judges and others
have said for years, said Anne Ronan, an attorney with the Center
for Disability Law.
</P>
<P>
   The center in 1991 filed a complaint in federal court about
children's care; the state last year agreed to have an independent
review rather go back to court.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office said it would review the report today and
would have a plan to deal with some of the problems in two weeks,
said Francie Noyes, press secretary for Gov. Jane Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Noyes said Hull was disappointed but not surprised by the
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Baldwin, assistant director for behavioral health
services, agreed that the report pointed out the state's
shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have made a lot of improvements, in the way that we
try to serve more people. . . . If people wish to see this report
as `I told you so,' that's fine,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers analyzed computer records for 7,746 Medicaid-eligible
children enrolled in ComCare.
</P>
<P>
   They interviewed more than 100 people involved in the system and
scrutinized how 42 children get care.
</P>
<P>
   While praising individual efforts of some case managers, the
report paints a picture of a system driven by budget concerns
rather than human beings _ even though ComCare, the non-profit
agency responsible for the system _ was taken over by the state
last year.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, half of the 42 children whose cases were
reviewed in depth had their services ended, reduced or changed
substantially _ and in at least half of those cases, there weren't
any clinical reasons for doing so.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, reviewers said the state needs to find out why
kids were getting too many medications without any clear-cut
justification.
</P>
<P>
   Reviewers also found that there weren't any plans to make sure
children were getting the least amount of medications.
</P>
<P>
   And parents' reports of adverse side effects were ignored, the
report found.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 42 children whose records were looked at in-depth, 71
percent were getting medications.
</P>
<P>
   Ten children were on four or more drugs. Of those, one was
considered low need of services, six were moderate need and three
were high need.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said the state would consider having the for-profit
company that replaces ComCare develop plans to check on possible
overmedication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a child is on multiple medications is not in
itself a problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the survey found that children were able to get into
the state-run system, but from there, they weren't able to get the
right kind of services _ frequently because staff members weren't
doing the right kind of assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Evaluations were usually done after psychiatrists spent 15 to 30
minutes interviewing a child. Children didn't go through
standardized testing nor did caseworkers go to the children's
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment plans for the children seemed to be copied from a
manual of mental disorders rather than being tailored to their
needs, the review noted.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one child who had extensive developmental
disability didn't get accurately diagnosed as having mental
retardation.
</P>
<P>
   Children with the most complex cases seemed to suffer the most,
reviewers noted.
</P>
<P>
   One therapist used ``talk therapy'' with a non-verbal child and
another tried using hypothetical situations to draw out a child who
had an IQ of 50. Children with IQs below 67 are considered mentally
retarded.
</P>
<P>
   The system tends to prescribe a lot of medications in these
complex cases, reviewers found.
</P>
<P>
   Once in the system, parents and children found that their needs
were often disregarded. They wouldn't be reminded of appointments.
</P>
<P>
   There was little follow-up between inpatient and outpatient
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   And changes in care would happen often: one child had three
different therapists in eight months, reviewers found.
</P>
<P>
   Parents were excluded from discussions about their children's
care. Their signatures were often added to treatment plans after
they had been discussed, reviewers noted.
</P>
<P>
   And if parents tried to change the plan, they faced a
bureaucratic, hard-to-understand, 20-page appeals process,
reviewers found.
</P>
<P>
   There were no mechanisms in place to see how many people were
denied services or had those services reduced or terminated.
</P>
<P>
   The system's plan for determining and improving the care doesn't
meet national accreditation standards, reviewers found. &QL; 
Jodie Snyder can be reached at 444-8667 or at
jodie.snyder(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
