A1696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAVES-MAIN23-COX     06-23 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yanks resilient against Maddux, bullpen
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Greg Maddux slept here Sunday night. It was an
unsound night's sleep. When he awoke Monday morning, Maddux had a
crick in his neck. By late evening, the Braves had themselves one
nagging pain in the neck: Another late-inning loss to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Once Maddux left after six innings, the Yankees scored three
runs off Dennis Martinez in the seventh. Tim Raines' two-out,
two-run double erased Atlanta's 4-3 lead and helped give New York a
6-4 win before 53,316 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That denied Maddux (10-2) a ninth straight victory and his 100th
as a Brave. It also gave the Yankees Round 1in this week's
four-game set and prolonged Martinez's misery in the Bronx. He's
now 0-7 lifetime in Yankee Stadium, 2-19 in his career against the
Yanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one pitch from getting out of it, but he didn't,'' said
Bobby Cox, who was ejected in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   If this was a World Series preview, Maddux might sleep in
another hotel bed come October. When he woke up Monday, his neck
hurt. ``I just got a crick in it,'' said Maddux, who gave up three
runs for the first time in 11 starts, since he last lost April 26
in Colorado. ``Slept on it bad. I thought it would loosen up in
warmups. It didn't. I was aware of it on every pitch, but I could
still pitch. It's not why I gave up the (nine) hits and runs, by
any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux attributed that to the Yankees themselves. To the four
straight two-out singles in the third inning that offset Gerald
Williams' two-run double in the top half. To the three one-out hits
to right in the sixth that offset Javy Lopez's RBI single earlier
that inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're smart hitters, man,'' said Maddux. ``They made
adjustments very well. They don't let you get 'em out the same way
twice, don't necessarily look for the same pitch every situation,
or on the same count.''
</P>
<P>
   After Chipper Jones' seventh-inning single gave Atlanta its
third and last lead, Maddux was finished after 87 pitches. ``His
neck was killing him,'' said Cox, who had had Kevin Millwood on
alert as a spot starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Enough's enough,''' said Maddux. ``For the first time
all year, it wasn't any fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It was joyless when Martinez _ whom Cox hoped would work two
innings and then Kerry Ligtenberg the ninth _ walked two of the
first three batters he faced. After getting Tino Martinez to pop
up, Martinez threw a 2-2 fastball. Raines drove it far beyond
Andruw Jones to the center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if Andruw was playing too shallow,'' Martinez
said. ``But when he hit it, I didn't think that ball would go over
his head. But that was the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I play there all the time,'' Jones said. ``I was playing
perfect, right where I need to play. He just hit that ball perfect
and I had no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
