</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS COULD MAKE A MOVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Whatever separates the Los Angeles Lakers
from the Western Conference champion Utah Jazz, don't expect them
to make up the difference overnight. Or at least, not over
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could trade up in the NBA draft, could unload a
couple of out-of-favor former starters and steal headlines away
from the Clippers and their No.1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more likely, the Lakers could simply stick to the
predictable, wait their turn and grab whomever's available at No.26
in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't such a bad thing. They got Vlade Divac at No.26 in
1989 and have seen nice returns on other latter-round pickups, from
A.C. Green at 23rd in 1985 to Elden Campbell at 27th in 1990 and
Derek Fisher at 24th in 1996. Not to mention second-round steal
Nick Van Exel, chosen 37th overall in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``The draft is such that there seems to be a gray area in the
late teens to early 30s, where you may be able to pick up a player
that, under normal circumstances, would be drafted (in the top
20),'' general manager Mitch Kupchak said of the '98 draft.
</P>
<P>
   That gray area gives the Lakers two chances to grab at least one
player with a chance to make the team. They pick again five slots
later, at No.31 _ the result of a previous deal that let them swap
second-round picks with Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' third and final selection will come at No.45,
obtained from New Jersey in previous trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we'll be able to get a player, maybe two players,
that make our team,'' Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the sting of Utah's 4-0 sweep of the Lakers in the
conference finals, the team that won 61 games last season is on
course to remain largely intact for next season. Management is
standing by coach Del Harris, who has one year left on his
contract, and it so far has not jumped at the dozens of trade
offers made in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the belief remains the Lakers will unload point guard
Nick Van Exel, a disappointment in the playoffs, and perhaps
underachieving Elden Campbell and his $7 million salary.
</P>
<P>
   A deal could be consummated on draft day but more likely _
especially in Campbell's case _ will have to wait until later this
summer, when teams can clear salary-cap room by renouncing rights
to free agents. Teams are also wary of making deals with a lockout
looming and a new collective-bargaining agreement on the way and
possibly changing the cap rules drastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some possibilities to move up (in the draft), and it
has to make sense. Obviously, we've run across nothing to date that
makes sense, because we haven't done anything,'' Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   Their shopping list Wednesday is fairly vague and Kupchak is
touting the ``best available talent'' philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could use a point guard to back up Derek Fisher if
Van Exel is dealt, a power forward if Campbell is traded. They
could use an ace perimeter shooter no matter what else transpires.
Otherwise there are no gaping holes, save for possibly replacing
small forward Rick Fox, who might leave the salary- capped-out
Lakers for a long-term contract elsewhere. The Lakers can only
offer Fox $1.2 million for one year, but Kupchak is hopeful Fox
will return.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Lakers are well over the salary cap, they will be
limited this offseason to grabbing free agents who will sign for
the NBA minimum, about $300,000. That means any major improvements
this offseason will have to come via trade _ either before the
lockout that figures to begin next week or after it concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Lakers will concentrate on their current roster.
They are expected to exercise an option on forward Corie Blount.
Subject to the lockout, they will also try to negotiate contract
extensions for Kobe Bryant and Derek Fisher, who are both entering
the final season of their three-year rookie deals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1708 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI &LR;      06-23 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVEN CHANCE FOR SAVE, OWNERS BLOW IT WITH BUD SELIG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a master stroke.
</P>
<P>
   How in the world did the lords of baseball come up with the idea
of Bud Selig as permanent commissioner of baseball?
</P>
<P>
   The choice was as inspired as appointing Dennis Rodman minister
of fruitcake. Or selecting Bobby Ayala the king of ball one.
</P>
<P>
   It's called playing to strength.
</P>
<P>
   Who better than Selig to preserve baseball's status quo?
</P>
<P>
   Selig hasn't actually taken the job yet. But media reports last
week indicated that the deed, despite his denials, is all but done,
awaiting only Selig's disposal of his franchise, the Milwaukee
Brewers. The official announcement might happen at the All-Star
Game, which will allow baseball to distribute a single piece of
confetti to every attendee for the appropriate response.
</P>
<P>
   Selig has made out like he has been resisting this nomination.
But the look on his face is of an Elks Club conventioneer being
lured by a strip-show barker.
</P>
<P>
   He has been the consensus choice among owners for the job since
it opened up the first weekend after the last ice age. He might
well be the only person who would willingly accept collect calls
from the lords of baseball, a group as pleasant and cooperative as
a dryer full of wolverines.
</P>
<P>
   Even the lords know how unmanageable they are. This was how one
of their number, the late Edward Bennett Williams, then-owner of
the Baltimore Orioles, greeted Peter Ueberroth when he took the
commissioner's job in 1984:
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the den of the village idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 14 years since, nothing has happened to invalidate
Williams' description. So no one is better qualified to maintain
this disorder than one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   The lords prefer baseball matters this way. Peter Gammons of the
Boston Globe this week quoted a prominent American League owner
telling Selig some time ago, ``I'm not letting anyone new come into
my business.''
</P>
<P>
   A perfect summary for baseball's fundamental attitude toward
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Any competent outsider brought in as commissioner would insist
upon massive reorganization, changes in by-laws, fresh initiatives
in marketing, labor relations and race relations, and institution
of a philosophy of industry stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   Sound like Selig to you?
</P>
<P>
   That's why he's the commish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite appearances to the contrary for the average fan, the
lords have no sense of urgency for the big fix. Two reasons: Most
are too busy with their other empires to care, and whatever
operational losses are sustained annually, if any, are more than
recouped at time of sale.
</P>
<P>
   When the Texas Rangers were recently sold for $250 million, more
than twice what Gov. George Bush paid for the franchise in 1989,
you have all you need to know about baseball being an equity
business and not a cash business.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Dodgers for $310 million, which includes their
spring training facility and some L.A. real estate, to Fox was
another example of the value of sports franchises well apart from
any red ink on the annual income statement.
</P>
<P>
   So there is relatively little need for concern, even when, for
example, the game is flirting with debacle in expansionist Florida.
Apart from the well-chronicled hara kiri performed by the Marlins,
Devil Ray officials are wondering whether a mistake was made in
putting a franchise in Tampa. The first-year team's attendance
average of slightly more than 30,000 is sixth in the American
League, despite all the novelty, special promotions and a rich
baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to expand, along with the creation of interleague
play, was spawned simply by the desire for immediate money rather
than from a strategic plan that would help the game grow. They were
Band-Aid responses to help repair the damage from what will be
Selig's cross to bear forever: The disastrous 1994 strike.
</P>
<P>
   As commissioner-without-portfolio-or-judgment, he presided over
a mistake that four years have not healed. Attendance, revenues and
ratings have still not recovered to pre-1994 levels, yet baseball
continues to entrust leadership to him.
</P>
<P>
   Selig's lack of ability to do the job has nothing to do with
being a puppet for owners. That's the very definition of the job,
and fans who think he should be somehow an independent guardian are
naive.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's David Stern is a puppet of owners too, as are all
sports commissioners. But Stern has demonstrated repeatedly a
vision for the sport that has been accepted by owners, players and
new fans, and has gone about delivering on the vision.
</P>
<P>
   Despite mistakes and complaints along the way, the NBA is an
unqualified business success because Stern made imperative a
league-wide business commitment to the greater good, and backed it
with riches for all.
</P>
<P>
   While Stern gets his greatest test in the coming weeks as his
labor agreement begins to fall apart, he will not have to dig out
from a two-decade avalanche of selfishness and shortsightedness
that has buried baseball.
</P>
<P>
   With Selig in charge, baseball has given itself a teaspoon to
dig a tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
