<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1709 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SAHALEE-SPI &LR;      06-23 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SAHALEE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF COURSE WON'T GET ANY EASIER FOR PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They are West Coast courses ripe with trees on
every hole, tight fairways, several steep inclines, doglegs right
and left, and a well-fertilized rough that can swallow balls
skipping only inches off course.
</P>
<P>
   Both have two par-fives converted to par-fours for championship
play, and both place a premium on shot-making over distance off the
tee.
</P>
<P>
   One is laden with history, the other has history waiting to be
made.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Club Lake Course and Redmond's Sahalee Country Club,
site of this year's PGA Championship Aug. 10-16, have so much in
common that many of the players who completed the U.S. Open here
Sunday, might believe they are in time warp.
</P>
<P>
   If the Open was a preview of things to come at Sahalee, you also
might expect to hear players complaining about course conditions in
Redmond as they have about Olympic, where no players managed to
break par over the 72-hole event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you set Sahalee up like this?'' Fred Couples asked himself
Sunday after finishing the Open 17-over par. ``Yeah. But if they
set it up like this, you will hear people complain because they
don't know a lot about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Couples, who estimates he has played Sahalee 15 to 20 times
while growing up in Seattle, believes comparisons between the two
courses will immediately be evident once players start making their
way to Redmond for early practice rounds. Despite his score at
Olympic, Couples says he doesn't mind such a tough test of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun,'' he said. ``It's very challenging, but we
should have more tournaments set up like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the two courses are set up in similar fashion, they have
subtle differences.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee has numerous fairway bunkers, Olympic one. Sahalee has
ponds and water that come into play on five holes; Olympic has no
water hazards on the course, despite its location next to Lake
Merced.
</P>
<P>
   The other big difference is the size of the greens. Olympic's
are postage-stamp size with pin placements that can be downright
evil and surfaces that, when dry, make it nearly impossible to put
the brakes on a shot. Sahalee's greens are quite a bit bigger with
more tiers and undulations, which means that statistics for hitting
greens in regulation should be quite high when compared to Olympic.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this course had bigger greens, it wouldn't be as tough,''
Couples said. ``But that's the beauty of it. ... And they were
fairly soft for the U.S. Open. If not, it would have been
borderline ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The most obvious comparison between the two courses lies in the
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic's cyprus, pine and eucalyptus trees stand like ancient
sentinels along the fairways, casting stick-figure shadows across
the course without impeding the flight of balls unless shots stray
right or left.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee, on the other hand, has trees that are so dense in
places that rain doesn't even penetrate, and designer Ted Robinson
strategically left trees jutting into the fairways on several key
holes.
</P>
<P>
   The par-5 11th, for example, has a couple of trees in the
fairway ready to knock back any attempt to reach the green in two
strokes for an eagle. It is a hole that some of the pros are
already complaining about _ two months before the PGA even gets
under way.
</P>
<P>
   Like Olympic, Sahalee will take the driver out of the hands of
the long hitters, such as Couples, Davis Love III, John Daly and
Tiger Woods. In fact, players just might keep their drivers in the
bag for all but two or three holes on the entire course.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee is quite a bit more narrow than Olympic, with just 21
acres of fairway to the Lake Course's 60 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freddy, Davis and Tiger aren't going to hit driver more then
two or three times here,'' Loren Roberts said before the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who played Sahalee last summer after playing in the
Fred Couples Invitational at Inglewood, added: ``I think it will be
the same thing up there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Acton, Sahalee's former head pro, knows the two courses
will draw comparisons by the very fact that they are on the West
Coast. Never before has the West Coast hosted two of golf's four
major events in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   And while Olympic has hosted three U.S. Opens and numerous other
events in its 61-year-old history, Sahalee has only hosted one PGA
Senior Tour event, a handful of amateur events and local or
regional tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Players expected Olympic to be tough, but Sahalee has yet to
build such tradition in its 29-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side of the coin is, how do you get tradition?''
Acton asks. ``You get tradition by having hosted several major
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, at some point, you will have to host your first. I'm
sorry, but that's how you do it, and (Olympic) has hosted its first
at some point in time, and so has Pebble Beach and every other one
that is considered a great golf course.''
</P>
<P>
   If comparisons are any measurement, then Sahalee should be up to
the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sahalee is going to be kind of a controversial golf course,''
Acton said. ``It's a course that takes the driver out of (a
player's) hands a lot of the time. It's very tight and there's a
lot of places where there's a tree in the way. So it's a lot
different from what they are used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the players are going to love it, and a lot of the
players are going to hate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Olympic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
