<HEADLINE>
A NO-RING CIRCUS 
HUGGING HENRY 
RYDER RUMORS DENIED 
WEDDING BELLS FOR BOTHA 
STUDYING POLLOCK
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH GLENN COLLINS, STEWART KAMPEL AND ALAN FEUER  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ladies and gentlemen and children of all ages, step
right up and see the latest casualty of the New York real-estate
boom, Le Cirque du Soleil.
</P>
<P>
   After pitching its blue-and-yellow tent at Battery Park City for
the last 10 years, the Felliniesque troupe is looking for another
home in Manhattan. Jacques Marois, the general manager of the North
American division of the circus, said that the Battery Park City
Authority had advised them that construction will begin in the fall
on land the 2,250-seat tent has occupied since March. He also said
that the agency had asked the circus to look for space outside
Battery Park City because there are no other undeveloped sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way this wonderful circus could stay is if we revised
our master plan, and a developer were willing to incorporate a
permanent home for Cirque du Soleil in a future building,'' said
the president of the authority, John Lamura.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe is looking for a 300-foot-by-550-foot space for its
tent, as well as space for trailers and support vehicles. ``We have
talked with a variety of landlords,'' Marois said, ``but nothing we
have seen is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Highly Quotable
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hugged Henry Kissinger,'' Dr. Ruth Westheimer bubbled
at a cocktail party preceding the American Foundation for AIDS
Research's tribute to the broadcaster Larry King at the Plaza
Hotel, ``so I'm already in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, she has the former secretary of state to thank for
the title of a book she plans to write with Steven Kaplan, a
historian, ``Power Is the Ultimate Aphrodisiac.''
</P>
<P>
   What does Kissinger think about saying something that Dr.
Westheimer turned into a book title?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every smart-alecky remark I make haunts me for the rest of my
life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Matched Pairs?
</P>
<P>
   The third finger of Winona Ryder's left hand may draw stares at
a party Tuesday night at the National Museum of the American Indian
in lower Manhattan. Miss Ryder is one of the hosts of the party for
the New York premiere of ``Smoke Signals,'' the first
feature-length film written, directed and acted by American Indians
and the winner of two awards at the Sundance festival in January.
</P>
<P>
   But about her ring finger: The Internet has been buzzing with
speculation that Miss Ryder and Matt Damon are engaged. The
chat-room rumors were fueled by the Australian weekly New, which
quoted Kyle Pelt, a longtime friend of Damon's, as saying that
Damon had popped the big question ``and she had said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Miss Ryder's spokeswoman, Mara Buxbaum. ``She's not
engaged,'' Ms. Buxbaum said. ``It started as a rumor on E! Online
last week. It's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitched
</P>
<P>
   P.W. Botha, the former president of South Africa, married
Barbara Robertson, a 57-year-old legal secretary, Monday in South
Africa. They met while he was promoting his autobiography. Botha's
wife, Elize, died of a heart attack last year. He was engaged to
Reinette Te Water Naude for several months, but they broke up amid
newspaper reports that she was seeing someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Into the Picture
</P>
<P>
   The actor Ed Harris has spent three nights this month at Jackson
Pollock's house, preparing for a forthcoming film about Pollock,
the pioneering Abstract Expressionist, and his widow, Lee Krasner.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was gone before the start of a $2,500-a-person party for
the house (which is in the Springs section of East Hampton, N.Y.)
the other night in Southampton. But Helen Harrison, the director of
the Pollock-Krasner House and Study Center, said that Harris had
left behind an unfinished pack of unfiltered Camels, Pollock's
brand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
