</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-FIRINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FIRE FIELD MANAGER, GENERAL MANAGER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLAIRE SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers, a franchise noted for its continuity
when owned by the O'Malley family, continued its ferocious makeover
following the takeover by the Fox Group, firing general manager
Fred Claire and manager Bill Russell Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Claire was the longest-serving major league general manager and
had been with the Dodgers organization since being named publicity
director in 1969. Russell, who was ousted before he could complete
his second full season, was also a fixture in Los Angeles, having
played shortstop for the Dodgers for 18 seasons. It was the first
midseason shake-up to hit the Dodgers' dugout for non-health
reasons since Leo Durocher bolted the Brooklyn team for the New
York Giants in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissals opened the way for the return of Tommy Lasorda,
who was asked to replace Claire on an interim basis and engineer a
solution to the Dodgers' dismal 36-38 season. Lasorda, elected to
the Hall of Fame after a successful 20-year stint as Dodgers
manager, had reluctantly moved to the front office in 1996 after
heart surgery and was replaced in the dugout by Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, who was serving as a Dodgers vice president, will now
oversee another of his former players in Glenn Hoffman, the
Dodgers' manager at Class AAA Albuquerque, who was promoted on an
interim basis to replace Russell and asked to finish out the
season.
</P>
<P>
   While the first inclination was to assign the seismic changes to
the ambitions of a new regime, Peter O'Malley, the former president
and club owner, who is now the Dodgers' board chairman, insisted
that was not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been asked probably 100 times the hypothetical question _
`Peter, if your family still owned the club would you have done the
same thing? _ and the honest answer is yes,'' O'Malley said during
a news conference broadcast from Los Angeles. ``I've been
disappointed in the team's performance, felt we were flat and have
been for some time. I think it's time for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   The reemergence of O'Malley's good friend, Lasorda, proved as
intriguing as the Dodgers' decision to step out of character by
dismissing a manager.
</P>
<P>
   The men who recommended the change _ O'Malley and the Dodgers'
president, Bob Graziano _ predate the Fox regime. And their actions
dovetailed nicely with the long-standing desire of Lasorda, a
mainstay of the franchise under the old ownership, to become the
club's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Explained Graziano, the 13-year club executive who succeeded
O'Malley: ``Over the course of the last several weeks I have spent
many, many hours thinking about how to get this team back on track.
The last couple of weeks I have spent countless hours with Peter
O'Malley, getting his advice on the best way to right this team.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers lost three of four games against a struggling
Rockies team in Colorado this past weekend and fell 12 1/2 games
behind the first-place San Diego Padres in the National League
West, the fates of Claire and Russell were sealed. ``Once I made
that decision, it did not make any sense to wait until the end of
the season, or three days, four days,'' Graziano said.
</P>
<P>
   Once Claire and Russell were informed of the decision Sunday
night, both O'Malley and Graziano met with Lasorda, who, Graziano
said, ``has always told me that if I ever needed anybody to step in
and help me, he was there for me.'' As for Lasorda, O'Malley said:
``Tommy always told me it wasn't my job he wanted _ fortunately.
Someday I'd like to be general manager _ no hurry, but I'd like to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda bubbled with joy, saying ``when I accepted this role, I
accepted it with a great deal of gratitude and enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Lasorda and Hoffman are able to shed the interim labels
by improving the team's fortunes remains to be seen. Should
Lasorda's stake be set more firmly than the Dodgers indicated
Monday, there could be ramifications for the Mets. Mets manager
Bobby Valentine is a Lasorda protege, began his big league playing
career with the Dodgers and has never hidden his admiration for the
franchise. Even though Valentine is in the first year of a
three-year contract extension, there will inevitably be speculation
he may look to move to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Mike Piazza, the all-star catcher traded by the
Dodgers to the Marlins amid a contract dispute and then sent from
Florida to the Mets. Piazza is Lasorda's godson, and that
connection may play big when the potential free agent resumes his
pursuit of a $100 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   The dismissal of Claire and Russell were major moves for a a
team that stood as the last bastion for a family-owned baseball
dynasty. The O'Malley family, which had owned the team from 1950
until this spring, had employed only four managers _ Charlie
Dressen for three seasons, Walter Alston for 23 years, Lasorda for
20 and then Russell. As for general manager, Claire's 12-year
tenure was the longest consecutive active run in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   Yet since turning the team over to Fox and Rupert Murdoch in
March, the team has subtracted not only old standards, also some of
its highest profile players. With injuries and the loss of those
traded, the Dodgers have foundered. ``I'm going to challenge this
team to go forth and play the kind of baseball they're capable of
playing,'' Lasorda vowed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 0051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
