r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     06-23 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST EPISODE IN FOX VENTURE INTO BLUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Today's episode of the Fox melodrama, As The Blue
Fades, begins with a shot of four men sitting at a table, waiting
to put on a show for the assembled multitudes.
</P>
<P>
   On one end sits the titular head of the Los Angeles Dodgers,
Peter O'Malley. He is there to lend a reassuring presence, an
all-is-well air, to the fans at home. He really has no other duties
in the organization since selling the team lock, stock and bullpen
to the Fox Group.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end sits young blood, Bob Graziano, the likeable
new President of the Dodgers. He is as sincere as a summer day is
long, but there is no getting around the shadow Fox casts over his
domain, much as the Cigarette-Smoking Man casts his shadow on
Mulder and ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Next to Graziano sits Glenn Hoffman, the new character just
introduced. When Fox officials hear that the Dodgers have hired
Hoffman as their manager, they will reply ``Dustin?'' in unison.
</P>
<P>
   And between Hoffman and O'Malley sits the new interim General
Manager, Tommy Lasorda, just back from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Those attending Monday's press conference to announce the latest
changes in Dodger culture said the proper and respectful things.
They expressed their gratitude to the men just launched, General
Manager Fred Claire and Manager Bill Russell, and their confidence
that things will get better. But one was still left looking for
simple answers.
</P>
<P>
   Simply stated, Claire and Russell fell out of the Fox loop,
assuming they were ever in it. And two years after being nudged
into retirement ostensibly for health reasons after suffering a
heart attack, Lasorda has returned with a vengeance. He is in the
loop, and in fact may have given the loop its latest spin.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few people involved in the sale of Dodgers who had
contacts on both sides of the third base line was Lasorda. He has a
long friendship with Wall Street wizard Michael Milken, who is
friends with Rupert Murdoch and Fox COO's Chase Carey and Peter
Chernin.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Lasorda said he was scheduled to fly to Boston Sunday
with Milken on personal business before the bodies were found.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining why Lasorda was named the interim General Manager,
Graziano stressed that the club ``wanted Tommy more intimately
involved in baseball decisions.'' Later, he elaborated. ``Tommy has
a tremendous knowledge about baseball, and the fact was we weren't
using it.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was retired after his heart attack, O'Malley and Claire
both said the club wanted to make good use of Lasorda's baseball
knowledge. But Lasorda has basically been sent out and about as an
ambassador of the organization. The baseball trips he made often
were to scout prospects or kids in the low minors.
</P>
<P>
   He returned to L.A. Sunday from a trip he made to Glen Falls,
Montana, and Yakima, Washington, checking up on kids light years
away from the major leagues. Claire and Russell rarely sought his
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda acknowledged that he has contacts within the Fox Group,
and that some of the people there felt he wasn't being used
properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' he said. ``When they bought the club, they
wanted to make sure I was still here and the club was taking
advantage of my knowledge. A few of them figured I should have been
(used more).''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Lasorda angrily denies that he did anything to get
Claire or Russell fired. ``I never said a bad word about them.''
</P>
<P>
   A baseball source said he didn't believe Fox was looking to fire
Claire or Russell. But it did know the team it had bought was in a
malaise, and that it had deepened since the wake-up call that was
the Mike Piazza trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Fox people knew coming in is that the team was
underachieving,'' said a baseball source. ``And the person that had
their ear most was Lasorda.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Fox directed Graziano and O'Malley to fire two
and hire Lasorda remains to be seen. The group does not micro
manage the team as much as some believe. If it had some kind of
blueprint, it certainly wouldn't have been to hire Lasorda as G.M.
(ital) after (end ital) clearing Piazza and Hideo Nomo from the
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Lasorda might have influenced both situations
differently than he did. ``That's a hypothetical question,'' he
said. ``I wasn't the guy back in April.''
</P>
<P>
   Graziano said he spoke with Fox officials on Friday and
indicated he was leaning to making a double-switch. ``I told them
(Carey and Chernin) we were leaning in this direction,'' said
Graziano. ``The final decision came down Sunday after hours of talk
with Peter (O'Malley).''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard for anyone to say that Claire and Russell were
wronged. Claire has been the G.M. since 1987, and the last world
title and postseason win came in 1988. Russell may not have been
handed a full plate of talent, and may not have had as much impact
on the personnel he had as other managers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers didn't seem to be headed anywhere under his
stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we came to a decision, we felt there was no reason to
wait until the end of the season,'' said Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one can't say where they're headed now. They have a
manager who has never won on the minor league level, and a G.M. who
is 71, and both are labeled interim.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano said the team is committed to search for a full-time
G.M., and that Hoffman will be considered as a candidate based on
this half-season. One assumes, though, that Lasorda will be hard to
budge from the G.M. job now that he's got it.
</P>
<P>
   He always wanted to be G.M. If his heart were to go out
tomorrow, he likely would prefer that it happen on the job as the
G.M. as opposed to, say, Yakima.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of talent here,'' Lasorda said. ``The challenge
we have is to get them to play the way they're capable. I accepted
this job with the idea that we would get things going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good. I'll do whatever the Dodgers want me to do. If I
do a good job, we'll see where it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   And we'll be watching. Don't touch that dial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
