<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1731 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-HNS &LR;      06-23 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSKOWITZ-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MickeyHerskowitz
</P>
<P>
   Heroics lacking, &QL; 
both early and late
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
YOU can think about it for another day before sending in your
ballot to give the Astros a nickname worthy of their gift for
late-inning comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   Not this night. A gangly lefthander who will turn 23 in August,
Eric Milton, stifled the Astros on two singles for six-plus innings
Monday, and Minnesota's Twins didn't crater in the last of the
ninth, and there went Houston's three-game winning streak. The
score was 5-3, which makes it sound as if the Astros put up a
better battle than they did.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball, as you probably know, is a sport in which the defense
can't score. Which is a pity because the Astros made half a dozen
fancy fielding plays but had only one productive swing at bat. Brad
Ausmus planted a 1-0 pitch off reliever Mike Trombley with two on
in the seventh, getting Houston on the board and cutting the Twins'
lead to a run.
</P>
<P>
   Milton looked as if he could toy with the Astros all evening,
until his control took a hike. With two out, he walked Carl Everett
and went to 3-and-0 on Sean Berry, and manager Tom Kelly went to
his bullpen, apparently not wanting to risk a major misstep by the
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, that dishonor went to Trombley, who finished walking
Berry and then served up the third homer of the year to Ausmus, a
rocket shot that barely cleared the fence in left. The roar of the
crowd, 23,168 of them, indicated that another late-night Astros
rally might be in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros' bats were like those air blowers in the
restrooms, enough to dry your hands but not enough to generate real
heat. Except for the blast by Ausmus, the Astros didn't get a
runner past first base until Jeff Bagwell singled to lead off the
ninth, stole second and went to third on a grounder. He was still
there when the game ended.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Twins were collecting eight of their 10 hits off
Jose Lima, including Terry Steinbach's solo homer in the second.
Milton seemed to be pitching well enough to make that run stand up,
but the Twins collected four doubles and three of them led to runs.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom dwellers drive in runs
</P>
<P>
   It didn't do much for the Astros' self-esteem when Minnesota
scored twice in the fourth with two out, on singles by Dennis
Hocking, a .153 hitter, and Milton, who ripped a grounder up the
middle for the first run batted in of his big-league career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brad got us back in it,'' lamented manager Larry Dierker,
``but it hurt when the eighth hitter and the pitcher got two-out
hits, and then they add the insurance run in the ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   The rookie came into the game with a 3-6 record and an earned
run average over 5.00. But this was a case of Milton's Paradise
Won, or perhaps lost and found. In any case, the Chuck Knoblauch
trade is suddenly looking a whole lot more promising for the Twins.
</P>
<P>
   When they gave up their All-Star second baseman to the Yankees,
young Milton was one of the four warm bodies the Twins received in
return. The 6-3, 200-pound Pennsylvanian had been named New York's
minor-league Pitcher of the Year in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, himself a child prodigy in the salad days of the
Houston franchise, was impressed with Milton's efficiency. ``He
showed us a 92-mile-an-hour fastball on the outside corner and a
good changeup,'' said Dierker. ``I was glad when they took him
out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Twins are still a game under .500 and in a rebuilding cycle.
If anything is going to speed up their progress, it has to be the
pitching, because this team doesn't have much muscle. Steinbach's
homer over the lottery sign in left field gave their starting
lineup a total of 30 home runs, leaving them only three behind Mark
McGwire of the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Lima goes sour
</P>
<P>
   You had to figure that if the teams were going to play long
ball, the advantage clearly belonged to the Astros. But for most of
the night, the Astros looked as if they had been watching too much
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who had given the Astros' starting rotation an
early-season lift, was rocked hard by the Twins and was fortunate
to strand three runners in scoring position. Craig Biggio saved him
once by getting a force at second, making a throw while flat on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not his best game,'' Dierker said of Lima, in a
slight understatement, ``but he gave us innings. A lot of times, he
can give up four runs and win because we'll score.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not one of those times, and the Astros may need a new
game plan against a Minnesota team struggling to be ordinary. In
their only series a year ago, the Twins won two out of three.
</P>
<P>
   You know the Astros are not going to win many games when Biggio
provides one of their highlights by batting for nearly five
minutes. He was at the plate for 14 pitches, fouling off eight,
before lifting a pop fly to short.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
