<SLUG> BC-NY-STABBING-DEATHS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-BOYFRIEND ARRESTED IN FATAL STABBING IN QUEENS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 25-year-old Queens man who police said stabbed his
former girlfriend and her parents, killing her mother, in a jealous
rage on Sunday was arrested Monday morning after he was found
hiding in the back yard of a friend's house in Dutchess County,
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Robert Parsell, was returned to Queens and held on
charges that he stabbed his former girlfriend, Heather Grech, 20,
and then killed her mother, Kathleen, 55, and seriously wounded her
father, Tristan, 54, when they tried to rescue her, said Chief of
Detectives William Allee Jr. Police said Parsell had become enraged
after being spurned by Miss Grech.
</P>
<P>
   The Queens district attorney, Richard Brown, said Parsell would
be charged with second-degree murder and attempted murder for the
attack, which occurred just before 7 a.m. Sunday in the living room
of the Grech family home at 69-26 61st Rd. in Middle Village,
Queens. ``Each suffered multiple stab wounds in what can only be
described as a blood bath, a jealous rage,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said that Parsell grew desperate last week after Miss
Grech left him and moved with their 18-month-old son back to her
parents' home. His sadness turned to rage, they said, when he heard
that she had seen another man.
</P>
<P>
   Parsell asked Mrs. Grech to help him set up a meeting with her
daughter. When he arrived, Parsell pulled out a knife and stabbed
Miss Grech two dozen times, severing her liver and puncturing a
lung, police said. Her mother was killed and her father seriously
wounded when they intervened. ``Her mother came to her assistance
and quite possibly saved her child's life,'' Allee said.
</P>
<P>
   Heather's older brother, David, 22, woke up to the sounds of
screams and chased Parsell away.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives tracked Parsell to a friend's home in Beacon, N.Y.,
about 60 miles north of the city. At the request of New York City
police, officers from the Beacon Police Department began staking
out the house around midnight, said Lt. Paul Schettino of Beacon
police. At around 1:30 a.m., he said, they saw someone matching
Parsell's description walking around the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tried to elude them,'' Schettino said. ``He tried to hide
near a boat in the back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   In Queens, Parsell's friends gathered outside the 104th Precinct
station house as he was led out in handcuffs. One friend, Marc
Harris, 20, said Parsell could not bear the thought of being
separated from Miss Grech and their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was crying on the phone to me all week,'' Harris said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
