<HEADER>
A1738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-astroslede-HNS &LR;      06-23 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-astros </SLUG>
 lede-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Twins rookie 
hurls and hits 
way to victory
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
The scouting report on Minnesota rookie Eric Milton was pretty much
on the money.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old lefthander had his fastball in the 92-mph range
Monday night and mixed in an impressive changeup, just like the
intelligence report said. There was just one other minor thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew exactly what he could do, only he just did it better
than he has been doing,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said Monday
night after Milton and two other Twins relievers combined on a
four-hitter in a 5-3 victory over the Astros at the Astrodome. ``I
was happy when they took him out.''
</P>
<P>
   That's about the only chance the Astros had.
</P>
<P>
   Milton (4-6), who hadn't won since May 15, retired the first
eight batters he faced and 20 of 25 before being lifted with two
out and a 3-0 count on Sean Berry in the seventh inning. The Astros
scored their only runs of the game shortly after Milton's exit on a
three-run homer by Brad Ausmus off Mike Trombley.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Aguilera pitched a scoreless ninth for his 15th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had a scouting report that said (Milton) had trouble
throwing his breaking ball for strikes,'' Astros first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said. ``He didn't have much trouble throwing anything for
strikes tonight. He mixed the ball in and out, changed speeds well
and made us put the ball in play. We just didn't hit.''
</P>
<P>
   With interleague play matching teams only once a year, it
doesn't give hitters a chance to adjust to pitchers. That could not
have been more evident in the first 6 innings, when Milton allowed
only a pair of singles to Jose Lima and Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The loss halted the Astros' three-game winning streak and gave
the Twins a 3-1 record at the Astrodome over the last two seasons.
The Astros are 5-2 against the American League in 1998 and 9-13 in
interleague play since its inception last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would want to play the Astros every day.
Just look at the numbers,'' said Minnesota manager Tom Kelly.
``You've got Craig Biggio, a terrific player, and Ricky Gutierrez
having a great year. Add in Jeff Bagwell, Derek Bell and Moises
Alou, and that's a real solid lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   But the above quintet went 2-for-19 Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Astros righthander Lima (7-4) was the first six-game winner in
the National League but hasn't been the same since with a 1-2
record, 4.23 ERA and four no-decisions in his last eight starts.
Lima gave up four runs and eight hits in seven innings, falling
victim to a couple of bad pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 2-0, Lima left a fourth-inning changeup over the middle
of the plate to Dennis Hocking, who deposited the pitch into left
field for a run-scoring single. The shortstop, who took second on
the throw home, entered the game batting .140 with no RBIs in 44
lefthanded at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Three pitches later, Lima threw an 0-2 fastball to Milton, who
singled home Hocking with his third hit in six interleague at-bats
this season.
</P>
<P>
   All five of Minnesota's runs were scored with two out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't pitch badly,'' Ausmus said of Lima, who matched a
season high with seven strikeouts before leaving after seven
innings. ``They happened to score four runs, and we didn't produce
any offense. It looked a lot worse on the scoreboard. Generally,
four runs for this team is something that can be overcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Steinbach gave the Twins an early lead with a bases-empty
home run in the second inning, and Matt Lawton's RBI double in the
third made it 2-0. Lawton added a two-out RBI double off reliever
Reggie Harris in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, the little mistakes you make in the game cost
you,'' said Lima, who failed to get victory No. 8 for the third
straight start. ``I tried to stay strong and keep the ballclub in
the game, but we came up short. I was real disappointed. I should
have won that game 3-2 or 4-3. I made the mistakes and paid the
price. I didn't worry about it after giving up two runs, not even
three runs. This club is going to score a lot of runs for me.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case Monday. The four hits were the fewest by
the Astros since they had four in an 8-1 loss to Cincinnati on June
12.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros avoided the shutout in the seventh with a two-out,
three-run rally. Milton walked Carl Everett and was charged with
walking Berry before being replaced by Trombley. Ausmus then
connected on his third home run of the season, a drive over the
left-center-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Twins threatened to put the game out of reach in the eighth
inning off reliever Doug Henry. Henry, who had not pitched in nine
days because of soreness in his right shoulder, gave up a leadoff
single to Marty Cordova. Orlando Merced reached on a fielder's
choice, and after Steinbach grounded out, Todd Walker walked. Henry
escaped the jam when Hocking flied out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had one last chance in the ninth when Bagwell reached
on a leadoff single to extend his hitting streak to 11 games. But
it was too much to ask the Astros for yet another comeback in their
last at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have many opportunities,'' Bagwell said. ``Getting
Milton out of there was our only chance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
