<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEFEAT BRAVES, 6-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A midseason series against the Atlanta Braves, New
York Yankees Manager Joe Torre suggested on Monday afternoon, feels
more like an exhibition than a prelude to October. But three hours
later, Yankee Stadium rippled with emotion, every at-bat squeezed
sweat from the hands, and the ghosts of World Series past and
future haunted the place.
</P>
<P>
   When Tim Raines ripped a two-run double against reliever Dennis
Martinez in the seventh inning on Monday night, the pivotal hit in
the Yankees' 6-4 comeback victory, it was natural to recall how the
Yankees had exploited the Atlanta bullpen in the 1996 World Series.
It was easy to imagine how they could do it again, if the Yankees
(51-18) and the Braves (50-26), who have the best records in their
leagues, meet again this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' goal two years ago was to hang in against Atlanta's
starting pitchers, whether it was Greg Maddux or Tom Glavine or
John Smoltz. Just hang in, keep it close, until the Braves were
forced to go to their bullpen, the soft underbelly of the National
League's reigning dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   It was a familiar stratagem on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux started for the Braves and, bothered by a stiff neck that
he had awakened with, he labored uncomfortably through six innings,
throwing 87 pitches. With Atlanta leading by a run, 4-3, Maddux
asked out of the game. ``I was aware of my neck every pitch,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez replaced Maddux for the seventh inning, having a
dubious history in Yankee Stadium. Despite many seasons in the
American League, not one of his 243 victories occurred at this
place. Even at age 43, however, Martinez is perhaps the most
reliable middle reliever in the Atlanta bullpen, particularly now
that Mark Wohlers is in the Gulf Coast League trying to sort
through his problems.
</P>
<P>
   All night, the Yankees' hitters had picked away at Maddux enough
to hurt him, forcing him to throw pitches, to go deep in counts.
Some of them punched hits to the opposite field. And they proceeded
to do the same to Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch drew a walk to lead off the seventh with a
seven-pitch at-bat; in the Yankees' dugout, David Cone said later,
there was a sense that the game had just turned in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter tried and failed to bunt Knoblauch to second, but in
flying out, he made Martinez throw six more pitches. During Jeter's
at-bat, Atlanta Manager Bobby Cox was ejected for arguing a
foul-ball call _ and Torre thought of the final game of the '96
World Series, when Cox was also ejected.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill was next, with 61 at-bats against Martinez in his
career, ``probably more than anybody else,'' O'Neill said. He knew
it would be a matter of getting ahead of Martinez, preventing him
from getting into a position where the veteran pitcher could throw
something nasty and make O'Neill chase it. O'Neill walked on five
pitches, the cheers of 53,316 building with each pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could've been a post-season game,'' Torre said later.
``Everything was a high-wire act.''
</P>
<P>
   Relievers were warmed up in the Atlanta bullpen, but no change
was made. Opposing managers have usually brought in lefties to face
the trio of the left-handed-hitting O'Neill and Tino Martinez and
the switch-hitting Raines, but the Braves stuck with the
right-handed Martinez, rather than trust their left-handers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of tough when they left Dennis in the game,'' said
Andy Pettitte, who started and pitched six and two-thirds innings
for the Yankees. ``It was a good situation for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez fell behind no balls and two strikes, fouled off a
pair of two-strike pitches and then reached a full count before he
fouled out on the eighth pitch of his at-bat. Dennis Martinez had
thrown 26 pitches in the inning. Each Yankees hitter was setting up
the next.
</P>
<P>
   Raines was next, two outs and two on. Torre had started Raines
in left field rather than the rookie Ricky Ledee because he wanted
someone with experience to face Maddux, a four-time Cy Young award
winner. Raines was also quite familiar with Martinez, his high leg
kick, his torso cocked forward, the plug of tobacco packed into his
left cheek. Raines had seen all that, having 5 hits in 20 previous
at-bats against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to hit the ball hard there,'' Raines said.
``When 50,000 are cheering, you want to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   Raines swung and missed at a 2-1 curve, then stepped out.
O'Neill, leading off first, checked the outfielders. All were
playing shallow, cheating in a bit to give themselves a chance to
throw out a runner at home on a ground single.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez fired a fastball _ his 33d pitch of the inning _ and
Raines ripped it to dead center. As soon as Andruw Jones, the
Atlanta center fielder, turned his back, O'Neill knew and Torre
knew that Jones would not catch the ball. Both Knoblauch and
O'Neill scored, and the Yankees led, 5-4. The Yankees added another
run on an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, walked
through the clubhouse afterward, a hint of a grin on his face. ``We
can only think about one thing,'' he said. ``The World.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Series, he meant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
