<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEVIUS-NEVIUS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA KNOWS HOW TO PUT ON A GOLF OUTING 
BY C.W. NEVIUS
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Bay Area has just about perfected the
concept of hosting the U.S. Open. The tickets sold out in nothing
flat. The setting was spectacular and the finish was sensational,
with Payne Stewart's putt on the final hole curling an inch away
from forcing a playoff.
</P>
<P>
   And best of all, in two years we get to do the whole thing
again. The Open travels to Pinehurst in North Carolina next year,
but it will be back at Pebble Beach in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   So start saving now. In two years you will need to take out a
second mortgage to purchase a U.S. Open sweatshirt at the
merchandise tent. And that's a best-case scenario. Other bests and
worsts from Olympic:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST EXAMPLE OF WHAT A DOWN-TO-EARTH GUY U.S. OPEN CHAMP LEE &LR; 
 &UR; JANZEN IS: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; At 12:30 on Sunday afternoon, a couple of volunteers and a
reporter were standing on a deserted dirt trail between the
clubhouse and the 1st tee. A guy in a golf cap comes huffing and
puffing up the hill, straining under the weight of a huge tour golf
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't you have a caddie?'' asked one of the volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' he said, ``but he doesn't seem to be able to find his
way to the clubhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Janzen, on his way to the 1st tee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORST MANNERS BY A LOCAL CROWD: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; The relentless taunting of Scotland's Colin Montgomerie, who may
be a rabbit-eared, red-faced, bundle of exasperation on the golf
course, but who is candid, thought-provoking and a stand-up guy off
it. Those louts calling him ``fat boy'' have no idea what they are
talking about and probably couldn't give you a good reason for
their behavior if you cornered them.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST TACTIC MONTGOMERIE COULD HAVE TAKEN TO WIN OVER THE &LR; 
 &UR; LOCALS: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Because some of them appeared to be upset that he played so well
in the Ryder Cup, maybe he should have thrown his matches. If you
can't stand watching the Americans lose, have them play someone you
are sure they can beat, like Iran in soccer. Whoops, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST EXAMPLE SHOWING THE PROS ARE NOT THAT MUCH BETTER &LR; 
 &UR; THAN US HACKERS: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; On the 10th tee on Friday, 1996 U.S. Open champion Steve Jones
yanked his drive dead right, into a tree. It bounced out into the
fairway, but as several smirkers pointed out, it covered no more
than 100 yards on the 422-yard hole.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORST EXAMPLE SHOWING THAT WE HACKERS ARE JUST AS GOOD &LR; 
 &UR; AS THE PROS: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Jones then took out a 3-wood, crushed the ball in front of the
green, chipped up to one foot and made the putt for par.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST EXPRESSION OF WHAT THE OPEN IS REALLY LIKE FROM &LR; 
 &UR; SOMEONE IN THE TRENCHES: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; After his effort on Sunday, Olin Browne gets the nomination for
philosopher-king of the Tour. Browne finished 15-over-par, did a
dance of relief on the 18th green, threw his ball to the crowd and
then said the following:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is such a fry-off for the week. You can't get enough air in
your lungs, there's not enough blood to your head. You get so tired
of just grinding so hard every single day. And you let up for a
moment, and it kicks your butt. Because if you don't pull off the
exact shot you tried, you are dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the 18th. It's a 3-iron and a wedge and you stand on
the tee and you are scared to death. You finish and there is just
this extraordinary sense of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST REPLY TO FANS WHO SAY THEY KNOW JUST WHAT BROWNE IS &LR; 
 &UR; TALKING ABOUT: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; From Browne _ ``They don't have any idea.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORST EXCUSES (FOUR-DAY TOTAL DIVISION): &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Tiger Woods. The greens were too bumpy, the pin positions were
``almost illegal,'' and the rough was too tough. At one point he
blamed a gust of wind for making his putt stop a good four feet
short. Woods has improved immensely in public relations in many
ways, but no one is going to buy this ``poor me'' act.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST ``TIN CUP'' OUT-TAKE: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Mark Carnevale, the guy who quit his job at Merrill-Lynch after a
single day to embark on a long, strange trip through mini-tours and
other countries, held on to make the cut. He slumped to a 78 on
Sunday but still earned $25,578, some $6,000 more than he picked up
over the first 14 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST, AND MOST SURPRISING, ADMISSION FROM THE USGA: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Friday, they confessed that the pin placement on the 18th green
was unfair, too hard and a mistake. Astonished pros swooned.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST NEWCOMER: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; Matt Kuchar in a landslide. Now there's a smile that is going to
make a lot of money. And as he showed when he took the microphone
to accept his low-amateur medal, he says all the right things, too,
with flair and a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEST FINAL WORD FROM OLIN BROWNE: &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR; ``Playing in the U.S. Open is abusive. It is a very, very
difficult test of all facets of the game, every single day. But you
know what? It is too hard a course for a fluke. For all the whining
and groaning you hear, the guy who plays the best _ and gets a
couple of breaks _ is the guy that wins.''
</P>
<P>
   And isn't that all we want?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
