<SLUG> BC-GLF-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USGA SCORES OPEN A `10-PLUS' 
BY PAT SULLIVAN
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN FOLO-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR;   &LR; When the Olympic Club and the U.S. Golf
Association sat down Sunday night to compare notes on the 98th U.S.
Open golf championship, the club's tournament committee was anxious
for feedback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked them how they felt the tournament had gone, on a
scale of one to 10,'' general chairman John Hurd said yesterday.
``They said, `10-plus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That was gratifying, to be sure, to club members involved with
the tournament, but it was no guarantee that the USGA will be back
in 10 years or so. For one thing, an entire segment of the club
doesn't want it back.
</P>
<P>
   While not a ``split'' among the membership, differences of
opinion on the Open do exist. ``There's always a group that feels
put upon,'' said Hurd, who was back behind his Walnut Creek desk on
Monday, catching up on his non-Olympian life as a consultant in
environmental-resource management. ``But the club also has an
obligation to the community and to the city. And there are only a
handful of places in the country that can host an Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exposure is just unbelievable. I thought the city looked
great (on the telecast). I didn't realize it, but it rained in San
Diego last Tuesday. That just as easily could have been here.''
</P>
<P>
   It costs $2,500-$7,000 in initiation fees to join the Olympic
Club. Most of its 4,700 members are those who frequent the
seven-story athletic facility and socializing center on Post near
Mason. Only about 1,500 members hold golf privileges, for which the
fee is $25,000. The waiting list within the club for those
privileges is 10-12 years.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA paid the club a sum in the low millions to ``rent the
hall'' for the week, and staffers will be remaining at the USGA's
field office for six to eight weeks to oversee the ``teardown,''
Hurd said. The USGA also has promised to take an active role in the
restoration of Harding Park, used as a parking lot for 7,000 cars a
day during the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The huge Open merchandising tent _ Logo City _ was strictly a
USGA operation. But the club did play a role, Hurd said, in the
corporate village effort managed by Mimi Griffin (an ESPN women's
basketball commentator) that set an Open record _ 51 separate party
tents, plus another large one with 80 tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mimi was a power,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service was held last night and funeral services are
today (10 a.m, St. Charles Church in San Carlos) for Rick Maguire,
Olympic's Open Committee vice chairman, who died early Thursday at
age 50 following a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the good ideas for the tournament came from Rick,''
Hurd said. ``We lost a cornerstone.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; MISCELLANY:  &LR; The 1999 Open will be played at Pinehurst No.2
in Pinehurst, N.C. Tickets went on sale yesterday, by mail only.
For information, call (800) 336-4446. . . . Working in will-call
was an eye-opener for volunteer Jeanne Paparelli, who found out
that there are those confused about the concept. ``Some people
expect us to call someone for them or call them a cab. One man
wanted us to drive him to the clubhouse.'' . . . The Open was
viewed worldwide, so media tent volunteer Bob Seeger wasn't
surprised when he received a phone call Friday from Kuala Lumpur.
When he informed the caller about tee times ``tomorrow,'' the
caller said, ``You know, of course, it's already tomorrow here.''
Replied Seeger: ``Oh. Who won?'' . . . The PGA Tour resumes
Thursday with the Western Open in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
