<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WARRIORS' </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARRIORS SWEAT OVER HUGHES 
BY DAVID STEELE
</HEADLINE>
 DRAFT-SFCHRON   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Gary Fitzsimmons, the Warriors' assistant
general manager and one of the NBA's most astute talent scouts,
late last week tried to handicap the upcoming NBA draft. He figured
the first two players picked would be point guard Mike Bibby and
center Michael Olowokandi, probably in that order by the Clippers
and Grizzlies. Then, he said, ``(Numbers) three and four become
really the swing picks in the draft, and that will really determine
what's available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   How right he was. The Nuggets pick third in Wednesday's draft,
and the Raptors pick fourth _ followed by the Warriors at No.5.
</P>
<P>
   As of Monday, Denver and Toronto were aggressively shopping
their picks; league sources are saying that Toronto and Vancouver
are discussing swapping picks, with the Raptors ending up with
Olowokandi and the Grizzlies with Michigan forward Robert Traylor
and guard Doug Christie.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that deal does not happen, the signs point to the
Raptors being wholly unimpressed with what is available at their
current draft position.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the Warriors to be waiting breathlessly on the Raptors'
final decision. Four players sit atop the Warriors' wish list,
roughly in this order: Saint Louis shooting guard Larry Hughes,
North Carolina swingman Vince Carter, North Carolina forward Antawn
Jamison and Kansas power forward Raef LaFrentz. Kansas swingman
Paul Pierce would make five, but only in the highly unlikely event
that he falls through the cracks amid all the wheeling and dealing
above them.
</P>
<P>
   Indications are that Hughes is the player the Warriors are
sweating over most; they paid a great deal of attention to the
6-foot-5 guard at the predraft camp in Chicago earlier this month,
and they like his combination of two-guard and point guard skills.
In his lone college season, the 19-year-old Hughes averaged 20.9
points, 5.1 rebounds, 2.4 assists and 2.2 steals.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Garry St. Jean has noted repeatedly that he has
no problem taking a player at a position the Warriors already have
filled (meaning that Jamison or LaFrentz have a chance).
</P>
<P>
   But with both backcourt positions in flux _ they're trying to
trade Latrell Sprewell, are prepared to lose Jim Jackson to free
agency and desperately need a starting point guard _ the Warriors
could stick Hughes into the lineup immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a very good upside,'' St. Jean said recently.
``He has the potential to be a big point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Chicago camp, Hughes told Basketball News that the
Warriors were one of the ``one or two teams'' that had tracked him
closely. ``I've gotten every indication that they wouldn't mind
having me,'' he said of the Warriors. ``I've heard a lot of things
about them. I think there's a real good chance that's where I'll
wind up.''
</P>
<P>
   There's just as good a chance, however, that a team could jump
ahead of them into Toronto's spot and take Hughes. The Mavericks,
and ex-Warriors boss Don Nelson, are also hot after him, and they
choose sixth overall (although reports indicate that Nelson could
also trade down, pick up an extra first-round choice and get his
hands on the rights to German sensation Dirk Nowitzki).
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the Warriors insist they will not be disappointed
with whoever they get at No. 5. They have not been scared off by
Jamison's lack of power-forward size nor his undemonstrated
perimeter game. Carter's athleticism intrigues them, as does the
fact that he played three years at a top-notch, proven program.
LaFrentz would be a longshot, partially because his position is one
the Warriors hope to fill through other avenues.
</P>
<P>
   The draft is one of three paths the Warriors can take to improve
on last year's disastrous 19-63 season. The others are a Sprewell
trade and free agency, both signing their own free agents and
bringing in others.
</P>
<P>
   Influencing these paths are the type of players available
through each. The draft (at least from where the Warriors sit)
happens to be the best source of shooting guards, with free agency
the favorite for a power forward and trades the best way to get a
point guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an understanding of what we'd like to do via the
draft, via free agency and through trades,'' St. Jean said. ``And
as one (acquisition) comes, and we look at that, then look at what
comes next, we can make it all fall together. It may not be a
perfect formula right now in terms of order, but we think we can
bring it together.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
