<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMGERS OFFENSE IS SNAKEBIT IN SHUTOUT LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The rash of poor performances by the Texas
Rangers rotation concealed the recent growth of an unattractive
wart.
</P>
<P>
   The American League's most productive lineup ceased production.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who endured their ninth defeat in the past 12
games, were shut out for the first time in 92 contests in a 6-0
loss to the expansion Arizona Diamondbacks Monday night at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers managed only nine base runners on seven hits and two
walks. Shortstop Kevin Elster, who hit ninth in the order,
collected three of those hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers afterward praised Diamondbacks right-hander Andy
Benes, who surrendered only six hits and one walk during eight
scoreless innings. Yet, it also should be noted that this lineup
hit only .241 during its past 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to battle through it,'' Rangers first baseman Will
Clark said. ``That's what we're in the process of doing right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance by Benes (6-7) and one inning of scoreless
relief from left-hander Efrain Valdez represented the first shutout
thrown against the Rangers since former Detroit right-hander Scott
Sanders accomplished the feat Sept. 9, 1997, at Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't have too many good swings against him,''
Rangers manager Johnny Oates said of Benes. ``We just never got the
offense going. We didn't have too many base runners, and we didn't
hit too many balls hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers had only four at-bats with runners in scoring
position. The first four hitters in the lineup _ center fielder Tom
Goodwin, second baseman Mark McLemore, left fielder Rusty Greer and
right fielder Juan Gonzalez _ failed on each occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Benes mesmerized the Rangers with all four pitches _ especially
the two breaking pitches _ in his arsenal: fastball, slider,
curveball and changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I kept the ball down and threw the ball
exceptionally well,'' Benes said. ``I went out and pitch, which is
what I expected to do, and _ after eight innings _ they hadn't
scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps one base-running mistake by Rangers third baseman Luis
Alicea kept the Benes-Valdez shutout intact. Alicea ran into an out
at third base attempting to stretch his third-inning double into a
leadoff triple. Right fielder Karim Garcia and second baseman Andy
Fox combined for two accurate throws to retire Alicea. The mistake
became more pronounced after the ensuing single by Elster.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point in the ballgame,'' Oates said, ``that's a big
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander John Burkett (4-8) gave the Rangers' struggling
rotation a shot in the arm with seven quality innings, but he ran
into a matchup too much for his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're solid one through nine,'' Benes said of the Rangers'
lineup. ``Their No. 9 hitter hit three BBs off me. You know whoever
is up there is going to be tough, so you just have to make more
quality pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Benes' 128 pitches fit that description.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a good lineup,'' Clark said. ``It takes a very
well-pitched ballgame to do that against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but it might take just a little less at the moment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
