u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-ORIOLES-NYT &LR;      06-23 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES TOP METS, 7-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ New York Mets Manager Bobby Valentine was not around
long enough to see Brian McRae and Butch Huskey rifle back-to-back,
second-inning home runs off Mike Mussina at Camden Yards on Monday
night. Or, for that matter, to see the Orioles respond with shots
by Rafael Palmeiro and Cal Ripken Jr. off Bobby Jones on their way
to a 7-2 victory over the Mets in which Mussina retired the last 22
Mets he faced.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Valentine wasn't present for the latest installment
in the Mets' lengthening slump was that he had been ejected in the
top of the second for arguing a called third strike on John Olerud.
</P>
<P>
   But the question being asked around baseball on Monday night was
whether Valentine will be around with the Mets next season if Tommy
Lasorda, suddenly back in a prominent role with the Los Angeles
Dodgers as their interim general manager, beckons Valentine to come
West. Valentine is under contract with the Mets through the year
2000, but Lasorda is his mentor and the Dodgers are the team he
started out with and the team many in baseball think he truly wants
to manage.
</P>
<P>
   And it was not just Valentine who had to answer questions about
his future on Monday night. For with Lasorda back in the picture,
the question of where Mets catcher Mike Piazza will be playing next
season becomes increasingly intriguing as well.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is a free agent after the season, and while it was the
new owners of the Dodgers _ the Fox Group _ who stunningly traded
Piazza in May, there is nothing to prevent Piazza from going back
to Los Angeles next year. And since Piazza is very close to Lasorda
_ Piazza is his godson _ the notion that the Mets are in a strong
position to sign the catcher to an expensive long-term deal may no
longer apply.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his situation on Monday, Valentine said: ``I
have one of the greatest jobs in the world. And I'm not desirous of
any other job.'' When asked about Piazza's situation, and the Mets'
chances of re-signing him, Valentine was less emphatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's different than it was before,'' he said. ``Not
necessarily meaning that he's less likely to sign with us now. But
there will be more talk about a possible return'' to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   That discussion has apparently started on the sports-talk shows
in Los Angeles. But Piazza contended that he was not thinking about
the past or the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very much involved in my present situation with the guys
on this team,'' Piazza said. He said he was looking at Monday's
developments in Los Angeles _ Bill Russell and Fred Claire were
replaced as manager and general manager by Glenn Hoffman and
Lasorda _ ``as any outsider would.''
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the Mets have the inside track on re-signing
Piazza, because, as General Manager Steve Phillips said on Monday,
nobody else can formally negotiate with the All-Star catcher until
two weeks after the World Series ends. That is when eligible
players are allowed to declare free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' Phillips said, ``we will make that effort prior to his
electing for free agency. I don't want to do hypotheticals. We will
make every effort to sign Mike. Our goal is to keep him here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Mets are not believed to have had any negotiations
with Piazza, other than a get-acquainted meeting with one of his
representatives in Miami on May 26, four days after Phillips
acquired the catcher from the Florida Marlins, who had obtained him
a week earlier in a blockbuster trade with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers let Piazza go because they presumably did not want
to meet his asking price of a $100 million contract. Will the Mets
be willing to go that high? And how long will Piazza wait to hear
from the Mets before he decides to test the free agent waters after
the season, regardless of any offer the Mets propose.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, at least, Valentine represents a more clear-cut
situation because he is in the first year of a three-year, $2.1
million deal that he signed last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no escape clause or option to do anything else,''
Phillips said. ``It's a straight three-year contract. And Tommy
doesn't have his choice for anybody in baseball to manage.''
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Lasorda won't try, especially since
Hoffman, like Lasorda, is considered an interim replacement. After
all, when Lasorda was asked at his Hall of Fame induction last
summer who would be his preference for manager should he ever wind
up the general manager of a team, his answer was Valentine. And one
thing is certain: What happened in Los Angeles on Monday will
create a distraction for the Mets until the Valentine and Piazza
questions are clearly answered.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the Mets, losers of five of their last six, are not a
team that needs distractions right now. Their back-to-back homers
against Mussina on Monday night were the only thing that stood
between the pitcher and a perfect game. He retired the first five
Mets he faced, gave up the home runs to McRae and Huskey, and then
retired the next 22 batters to close it out, with only three Mets
hitting the ball out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's two-run home run put the Orioles ahead, 3-2, in the
third and Ripken hit a solo shot to make it 4-2 in the fourth, as
Jones, mired in a little slump of his own, fell to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   And that was it for the Mets, who often don't know where their
next run is coming from and who now can't be sure who their
manager, or catcher, will be next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
