<SLUG> BC-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO DODGERS-STYLE CHANGES FOR RANGERS _ YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The Midnight Massacre swept through the Los
Angeles Dodgers late Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   While longtime Dodgers officials were just beginning to mourn
the passing of former general manager Al Campanis, the new Fox
bosses were unceremoniously dumping both general manager Fred
Claire and manager Bill Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's dismissal was hardly unexpected. His team was two
games under .500, 12 1/2 games out of first place and 17-16 since
the big trade with the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Claire's dismissal was a little bit of an eye-opener, but then
Rupert Murdoch's errand boys have been moving quickly since taking
over less than three months ago, having already traded their best
player and marquee pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   So far their actions have made Yankees owner George Steinbrenner
look like the model of patience.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it can be sometimes when rich boys who are used
to getting their way take control of a new toy.
</P>
<P>
   But of course that can't happen here, not when Tom Hicks has
been saying all the right things since taking over the Rangers and
waxing poetic at every turn about his confidence in Tom Schieffer,
Doug Melvin and Johnny Oates.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Rangers have slipped lately in the American
League West, nobody should be worried about a few baseball scalps
being hung in the same Hicks trophy case as a certain University of
Texas football coach.
</P>
<P>
   Should they?
</P>
<P>
   ``I put that pressure on myself regardless of who owns the
ballclub,'' Melvin said. ``I know the responsibilities of being a
general manager and I don't know if I've ever been in a situation
where I felt I could take it easy and have no pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put pressure on yourself to do your best. Whether you have
to do it immediately, I haven't got that sense. But I know Mr.
Hicks likes to win. He didn't buy this team just to be a member of
Major League Baseball. He wants this team to be one of the top
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   But then there were the comments Oates made over the weekend
after watching Todd Van Poppel and Matt Perisho pitch against the
Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Van Poppel was terrible, allowing five runs in two innings, and
afterward Oates said, ``What we saw today is unacceptable at the
major-league level. Actually it's unacceptable at any level.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who saw the performance said the manager was being
charitable, but such blunt criticism is still unusual for him.
</P>
<P>
   On the performances of Van Poppel and Perisho, Oates said, ``We
call two guys up and they don't go five innings between them. If
that's pressure on them, I'm sorry. We owe it to our fans to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Monday he was simply being honest. He also said he
feels no more of an urgency to win now than he did under the
previous ownership group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come to the ballpark to do the best job I can and my
expectations are the same, regardless of who owns the ballclub,''
Oates said. ``If we were 12 1/2 games behind and I still felt that
I had done the best job I could, then I would still feel good. But
if I felt I hadn't done the best I could, it would be tearing me
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates went through an ownership change midway through his
previous job. It was not a pleasant experience.
</P>
<P>
   Oates had led the Orioles to two winning seasons when Peter
Angelos bought the team in 1994. Oates led them to a 63-49 record
that year but Angelos, after publicly stating his manager wasn't
fit to lead, fired him at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through that before,'' Oates said. ``There was a
time where I had to be a major-league manager and I felt I had to
do the job or else. Not any more. I have confidence in my ability
to manage and I'm going to give this job everything I've got. If I
don't, I probably should be doing something else anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said despite what has happened lately, he actually feels
encouraged about his ballclub, especially now that Mark McLemore
and Kevin Elster are off the disabled list and Darren Oliver will
be activated Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be all right,'' Oates said. ``You look at those
three guys \RRick Helling, John Burkett and Aaron Sele\S and add
Oliver and that gives us four guys who give us a chance to win. Add
Todd or somebody else and we'll be fine. Overall, for the long
haul, I'm enouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin and Oates proved in 1996 they can win a championship
together. Last year proved that glory can be fleeting.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers Midnight Massacre reinforces what every baseball
official knows and that is, no owner _ good or bad _ remains
patient forever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
