<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN SETS TERMS FOR RETURN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Now that Phil Jackson has announced he will no longer
coach the Chicago Bulls, Michael Jordan has reversed his field and
said he will return to the NBA for another season if Scottie Pippen
and Dennis Rodman re-sign with the Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, Jordan said he wouldn't play for any coach
other than Jackson, and would retire if Jackson was no longer
coaching the Bulls. But yesterday Jackson said his nine-year stint
as the Bulls coach is over, leaving Jordan to re-evaluate his own
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Scottie Pippen and Dennis Rodman will come back, but it
will take some time for them to think about it,'' Jordan said while
speaking yesterday at a youth basketball camp at the Austin
Convention Center. ``But I think there's a chance they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to continue playing, but I want to play with the same
guys that I've been playing with. If not, it's been great. Those
things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson cleaned out his office yesterday at the Bulls' practice
facility in Deerfield, Ill., after turning down an offer from team
owner Jerry Reinsdorf to return as coach. After signing a one-year,
$6 million contract last summer, Jackson said this season would be
his last. He never wavered from that, telling his players from the
start of training camp that this was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel happy,'' Jackson said. ``I'm glad to be on my way out
of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jordan, ``If that's his decision, then I respect it.''
</P>
<P>
   And unless Pippen re-signs with the Bulls, the two who have been
together for all six titles will be going their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much longer this is going to last,'' Jordan
said of his 13-year career. ``It may be this year, or in five
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bulls fans believe Chicago has at least another NBA championship
left, and would like to see Jordan, Pippen and Rodman stick around
for another coronation. Yesterday, at least, Jordan left that door
slightly ajar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches may not be the same and the players may not be the
same,'' he said. ``But that would be like starting over.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would consider being a player/coach for the Bulls,
Jordan explained that he does enough coaching at home with his
sons, Jeffrey and Marcus. Jeffrey is 9 years old, and Marcus 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Between my two boys, that's probably as much coaching as I can
get,'' Jordan said. ``But things change. When I look back on my
career _ not that it's over with _ it'll be with happiness,''
Jordan, 35, said. ``I've had a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan told the 700 children yesterday: ``If I don't ever see
you again _ and I'm pretty sure I will _ make sure you listen to
your parents, your teachers, your grandparents and your guardians.
And don't ever give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still enjoy the game, and there are a lot of young players
in the league that still need some lessons,'' Jordan said. ``But
I've had a great time. If it ends today. I have no regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Jordan was actually outdone by the Mavericks'
Michael Finley. who helped his team beat Jordan's, 117-111, in a
game at Southwest Texas State in San Marcos. Jordan, the obvious
fan favorite, had 39 points, but missed two jumpers in the final
minute that could have put his team back in the game. The sellout
crowd of 8,000 didn't care though, as they cheered his every move
as the soundtrack from Jordan's movie, ``Space Jam'', played every
time he scored.
</P>
<P>
   Finley finished with 51 points, making 10 3-pointers from the
shorter college 3-point line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
