<SLUG> BC-NJ-BUDGET-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN AND LEGISLATIVE LEADERS AGREE ON BROAD OUTLINE OF STATE
BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JENNIFER PRESTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Republican legislative leaders and Gov. Christie
Whitman agreed on the broad outlines of a new $18.2 billion state
budget on Monday that would increase spending by more than $1
billion for public schools, state colleges, open space preservation
and a handful of other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers largely followed the spending plan that Whitman
first outlined in February, but they did reject a few of her
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   These included their decision not to eliminate the sales tax on
long-distance calls made within the state. They rejected proposed
cuts in the prescription program for low-income elderly residents.
And they stopped an effort by the Whitman administration to
eliminate some state jobs and turn them over to private
contractors, which Whitman said would save $6 million.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative leaders added almost $100 million in spending to
the governor's proposed budget for the fiscal year that begins July
1. The spending increases include $20 million for school
construction costs, $10 million for municipalities to keep down
property taxes, $10 million more to help maintain state parks and
$8.5 million in additional aid for middle-income school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in agreement on 99 percent of this budget,'' said Pete
McDonough, chief spokesman for Whitman. ``We will review the bill
after it is introduced and the governor will make her
determinations about line-item vetoes after the bill is passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The budget is expected to be considered by the budget committees
in the Senate and the Assembly on Thursday. It is expected to be
voted on by both houses early next week. Whitman is expected to
sign the new budget into law before the new fiscal year begins.
</P>
<P>
   State officials expect to end the current fiscal year on June 30
with a surplus of almost $1 billion and they estimate more than
$700 million in new revenues in the next fiscal year. The state's
economic boom has fueled budget largesse. The spending increase is
more than 6 percent over this year's state budget and is the
largest spending rise in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman was unsuccessful in persuading lawmakers to raise the
gasoline tax by 2 cents a gallon to help pay for the preservation
of a million acres of farm land and other open space in the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   But there is $50 million in the budget for the purchase of open
land. And Whitman and Republican legislative leaders have agreed on
a plan to borrow $1.4 billion in the next 30 years to meet the
governor's goals for preserving open space. The proposal, which
would go to the voters for approval in November, would cost
taxpayers about $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman administration officials and lawmakers said that the $50
million allocated in the new budget would be enough money for now
because the program would not begin until January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
