<SLUG> BC-HKN-MOOG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOOG RETIRES, SET TO SETTLE IN NORTH TEXAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Moog carved out a significant following in four years as
the Stars' top goalie. Now, he's looking to carve out a home in
North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Moog announced his NHL retirement Monday, leaving behind a
guaranteed $1.5 million remaining on a contract with the Montreal
Canadiens in order to spend more time with his family in Coppell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said throughout my career that it isn't about
money,'' Moog said. ``Throughout these last few years I said each
season that if I didn't have the desire to play anymore, I would
quit. And right now, I don't have that desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog, 38, cited a variety of reasons that ranged from nagging
injuries to missing his family. After leaving the Stars as a free
agent last summer, Moog lived out of an apartment in Montreal for
one season while his wife Karla and three daughters lived in
Coppell, where Karla works as a substitute teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is retired, Moog said he and his family will spend
at least the next two years in Texas, where he will take a more
active role in running the Fort Worth Brahmas minor-league team, of
which he is a partial owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to be more involved, but it won't be on a daily
basis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Moog is expected to contribute in ways that draw on his
visibility as a hockey icon in North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's obviously some things that I can do for the Brahmas
because of what I've been able to accomplish,'' he said. ``And I
think any time you're trying to sell hockey, it's good to have
hockey people involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Moog retires with a 372-209-88 record, seventh on the all-time
wins list, and has the highest winning percentage (.621) of any
goalie to win 300 games. As a member of the Edmonton Oilers, he
helped earn three Stanley Cups (1984, '85 and '87), although mostly
as a backup to teammate Grant Fuhr. Moog was the No. 1 man in
earning the Boston Bruins the Jennings Cup in 1990 for lowest
goals-against average and in taking the Bruins to the Stanley Cup
Finals, where they lost to the Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   While Moog said he has plenty to do with the Brahmas _ most
important, he said, is helping to select a new general manager _ he
said he'll likely take a step back from hockey for a while.
</P>
<P>
   When Moog decides to return, Stars general manager Bob Gainey
said that he has a standing offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he left here last year, we told him that were interested
in working something out with him,'' Gainey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
