A1757 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-23 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX WILL KEEP STIRRING POT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Dodgers' new general manager
said Monday, ``No, I don't foresee a great deal of changes.''
</P>
<P>
   From which we might learn something about Tom Lasorda even after
lo, his 49 years with the team.
</P>
<P>
   Either we learn he is a quick study, immediately applying the
first rule of front-office survival _ which is to avoid setting
impossible expectations in the way of trades and free-agent
signings. This is plausible, seeing that he's had his eye on this
job for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Or we learn he is so out of touch with the demands of his
office, somebody needs to sit him down with a job description and a
Dodgers roster.
</P>
<P>
   At the stadium press conference announcing that he is replacing
Fred Claire and Glenn Hoffman is replacing Bill Russell as manager,
Lasorda said the Dodgers have ``a lot of talent ... they just
haven't played up to their capabilities.'' Therefore, no major
changes are required.
</P>
<P>
   On this dubious point, the new Dodgers management team seemed in
general agreement. Peter O'Malley, embodying the old guard,
endorsed the thinking of first-year president Bob Graziano: ``I was
disappointed with the team's performance. I thought it was flat and
had been flat for some time.'' If the players could just unflatten,
no major changes would be required.
</P>
<P>
   But, heck, if no major changes were what the Fox Group wanted,
the owners could have stuck with Claire. And if no major changes
were what the team needed, it wouldn't have begun Monday night's
game in Anaheim 12{ games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda, in his own quiet way, makes it clear he might like to
erase the ``interim'' from his title at the end of this season. If
he's serious about winning the job and if he's serious about making
the Dodgers competitive in 1998, he'll try to make his mark as soon
and emphatically as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The spoils of the Mike Piazza trade in May improved the batting
order, at least on paper. The Hideo Nomo trade in June got rid of
the dead weight in the starting rotation. Now it's time to work on
the rest of the pitching staff, which is so undistinguished, it
must be called the worst in the Dodgers' 40 years in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that where the Dodgers are concerned, the more
things change, the more things are likely to change. The firings of
Russell and Claire only portend more upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   Were these smart moves? Even if you like and respect both men,
it's hard to argue with the facts. Under Russell, the Dodgers'
record is deteriorating for the second straight year. Under Claire,
the last great Dodgers moment occurred nearly 10 years ago. Few
managers and general managers get longer to produce results.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it took non-``baseball men'' like Graziano and the Fox
Group to remind sleepy Dodgers fans: You have to fire a manager
once every 44 years or so, just to keep people on their toes.
</P>
<P>
   What's unclear is whether Graziano is blaming the general
manager, Claire, for failing to procure good-enough players, or
blaming the field manager, Russell, for failing to win with players
who are good enough.
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems to be yes _ either, or both, whatever,
something had to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question is what happens this winter. Do both Lasorda
and Hoffman keep their jobs? Does neither? Lasorda but not Hoffman?
Hoffman but not Lasorda?
</P>
<P>
   The favorite, at this point, has to be neither.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano hung an ``interim'' tag around Lasorda's neck,
presumably as a reminder to Tommy, whose role is partially to help
find a permanent general manager. Listening to him talk Monday,
promising to fire up the team but making no mention of the tasks
normally associated with a GM, Lasorda sounded more like the new
manager than Hoffman did.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hoffman, although his title is not officially interim,
everything else suggests an October expiration date. Not having
been a local favorite as a player, or publicly groomed to manage
the Dodgers, he can be moved out of the way if a big-name manager
comes available. Mike Scioscia or Reggie Smith, the Dodgers coaches
most eligible for promotion, wouldn't have been so easily shunted
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the report last month in a Rupert Murdoch-owned New
York tabloid, that Florida Marlins manager Jim Leyland and GM Dave
Dombrowski would come to the Dodgers, makes a lot of sense.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, the Dodgers can advertise the most visible and
desirable manager and GM jobs in baseball. Leyland is almost
certain not to be back with the Marlins. Davey Johnson, if he
hasn't been hired elsewhere by then, will have been out of managing
for a full year.
</P>
<P>
   Who will be sitting in whose chair next opening day? Predictions
are pointless in the new Dodgers order. All that's for sure is that
change will beget more change, and whether or not anybody will
admit it, that's good.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
