<HEADER>
A1759 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LASORDA-COLUMN-LA     06-23 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LASORDA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS LASORDA REALLY READY FOR THIS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tom Lasorda remembered that day 11 years ago when
his old friend Al Campanis was fired and his own dream of becoming
the Los Angeles Dodgers general manager ended.
</P>
<P>
   He was sitting in the visiting manager's office at the Houston
Astrodome and crying, partly for Campanis, whose racially
insensitive remarks on national television could never be taken
back. But there was much more.
</P>
<P>
   As Fred Claire flew in from Los Angeles to take over the
baseball operation, Lasorda also knew he'd never get the job he
really wanted, with his beloved Bobby Valentine as the manager.
</P>
<P>
   Campanis' forced resignation was the most traumatic moment in
Dodgers history until Sunday when his death became a footnote in
the firing of Claire and manager Bill Russell. Strangely, it also
was the day Lasorda, now 70, finally became the Dodgers general
manager, summoned late at night by a worried club president Bob
Graziano for the job of fixing a terribly broken team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Al died, I felt so bad, not just because he was so
important in my life but because of the way people remember him,''
Lasorda said. ``Now I have his old job. It is quite an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a real plan laid out at Monday's news conference to
announce the changes, no closer on the way, no new ace to take the
place of Ramon Martinez. But when he addressed the team for 45
minutes before its game against the Angels in Anaheim, Lasorda was
back on stage, part evangelist, part carnival barker, all Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   That is what he brings to the team now, 13{ games behind San
Diego in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   He inherits a team that is in a great position to mail in the
rest of the year. The Dodgers have a $57 million payroll and plenty
more tied up in long-term contracts. He has a pitching staff that
looks great for a night and awful for a week.
</P>
<P>
   He has new manager Glenn Hoffman, who played 13 big-league
seasons, but gets a team that is injured and indifferent.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda's title of general manager also carries the disclaimer
``interim.'' There is a good chance the Dodgers just see him as
bridge to Pat Gillick or Andy McPhail, prototype GMs with records
of success.
</P>
<P>
   There also are concerns that Lasorda's resume does not qualify
him for the position, which has become increasingly technical the
past decade. He threw hours of batting practice to Steve Garvey and
Ron Cey, talked Orel Hershiser into greatness and took an average
team to the 1988 World Series title. Seems pretty tame compared to
designating a player for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Lasorda never shied away from the crowds. When 100 fans followed
him into a bathroom at the 1991 World Series, he stopped to sign
autographs. When his players bet him he couldn't lose weight, he
dropped 40 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But GMs rarely carry a high profile. There is little theater in
the Rule 5 Draft. They sit in meetings and bargain with agents. For
every John Smoltz one steals for Doyle Alexander, there are 500
first-round picks who have to be released.
</P>
<P>
   But the past two years have been difficult for him since
stepping down as manager. He became a vice president for kissing
babies. The club sent him to Korea and the Dominican Republic,
basically to be Tommy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did whatever they asked, gave speeches, went to dinner with
sponsors,'' he said. ``And that was fine. I've been here 49 years
and I wouldn't trade a minute. But there was something more I
wanted to do. I wanted to help build a team, for the fans and for
the city of Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed to lose that lovable side, often appearing surly
at public appearances. It was no secret that his long friendship
with Russell became strained. He had trouble letting go of the
limelight and the lineup card. Many in the organization think he
undermined Russell with the new owners.
</P>
<P>
   Campanis is gone and so are the O'Malleys. Valentine has a
three-year deal with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Nice dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
