<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERLEAGUE WARNING: IT IS STILL ONLY JUNE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Let's get two things straight right off the bat, ash
or maple or whatever your preference:
</P>
<P>
   1. This is not a rematch of the 1996 World Series. These New
York Yankees and Atlanta Braves are not the Yankees and Braves of
1996, and this is June 1998, not October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   2. This is not a preview of the 1998 World Series. Yes, the
Yankees and the Braves could conceivably play each other in the
World Series come October, but this is June. The makeup of the
teams is not necessarily the same as it may be in October, and the
intensity of the competition is not what it would be in October.
</P>
<P>
   With those disclaimers out of the way, by all means enjoy the
four-game series the Yankees and the Braves began at Yankee Stadium
on Monday night. The disclaimers are simply to make sure that no
one tries to make more of the games here and in Atlanta than should
be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of us might even make it to the World Series,''
said Tom Glavine, a member of the Braves' vaunted pitching
rotation. ``This doesn't mean anything come July, never mind
October.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees won the first game, 6-4, because Greg Maddux had a
painful neck that limited him to six innings and the Braves'
bullpen could not hold a 4-3 lead. If there is a difference between
these two outstanding teams, if there is one edge the Yankees would
have if these teams were to play in the World Series, it is in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard, especially with the lineup we have, to get a
complete game, said Andy Pettitte, the Yankees' starter on Monday
night. ``Our bullpen gives us an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Cox, the Braves' manager, was looking for two innings from
Dennis Martinez, a 43-year-old grandfather. But the often reliable
Martinez did not even make it out of the seventh inning, walking
two and giving up a two-out, two-run double to Tim Raines.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw 30-some pitches to get two outs,'' Cox said. ``That's
not like Dennis. One thing he can do is throw strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Cox had defended his relievers, saying every
team blows a game now and then. But the Braves are working without
their flame-throwing closer, Mark Wohlers, who is in Florida
working on his inconsistent and ineffective pitching, and no one
has assumed his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes teams go through this,'' said Chipper Jones, the
Braves' third baseman. ``Relievers struggle for a certain period,
and you have to do the bullpen by committee.'' This committee,
however, needs a leader. ``It's up to somebody down there to step
up and take it upon themselves to be the man who's going to shut
the door when our starters can't go nine,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' starters all are capable of going the distance, but
even they don't do it too often. They have twice as many complete
games as anyone else in the National League, but their total is 12
in 76 games.
</P>
<P>
   If these teams are indeed heading for the World Series, the
Braves got a glimpse of what they face on Monday night. But this
was only one of 162 games on the regular-season schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Some amateur sports psychologists might suggest that teams in
these circumstances do consider the games important because each
wants to deliver a message to the other _ if they do play in
October, don't forget who was superior in June.
</P>
<P>
   But that idea works better in theory than in practice. In 1988,
the psychologists might recall, the New York Mets clearly
established their superiority over the Los Angeles Dodgers, winning
10 of their 11 regular-season games. Came the league championship
series, and the Dodgers were the team that went to the World
Series, the Mets the team that went home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the fuss rages.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were doing that during the Montreal series,'' Cox said,
discussing the exaggerated emphasis placed on these games, ``and
all I was thinking about was beating Montreal. You look at the
schedule in spring training and say: `Boy, that will be a fun
series in New York. We get to go to Yankee Stadium.' That's as far
as it goes. Joe's trying to win a division; that's what we're
trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Joe Torre, the Yankee manager, said he could not
wait to get the week over with. His week, though, will be far worse
than Cox's because the Yankees play the Mets this weekend, and that
is their most important series of the year, maybe even including
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now that's an interesting thought. If the Yankees were to lose
all three games to the Mets but win the World Series, would George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, consider this a
successful season?
</P>
<P>
   With all of the talk about the World Series preview, it should
be recalled that last June, the Braves and the Orioles played each
other, then went on to achieve the best won-lost records in their
leagues. Their World Series preview, however, turned out to be no
preview at all.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team made it to the World Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
