</HEADER>
<BODY>
 BBA-RED SOX-PHILLIES--BOS  
 EXTRA PUSH GETS PHILLIES BY RED SOX
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Larry Whiteside  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Monday night, the Red Sox got a painful reminder that you can't
score too many runs at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The point was driven home in a 9-8 loss to the Philadelphia
Phillies before a crowd of 33,592 who were mostly glued to their
seats for all 10 innings it took to complete the first of four
interleague games between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, no lead was safe. Philadelphia went up, 3-0, only
to see the Red Sox go ahead with a solo run in the first and five
more in the fourth. Boston built an 8-3 lead with solo home runs by
Troy O'Leary and John Valentin. That should have been enough to pin
Philadelphia starter Curt Schilling with his eighth defeat, but he
got away clean, even though he did allow eight earned runs for only
the second time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling's teammates refused to lose, scoring six times against
Tim Wakefield and then finishing the job against the Red Sox
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia tied the game at 8-8 on a solo home run in the
eighth by Mark Lewis off Rich Garces. In the 10th, the Phillies
took advantage of Tom Gordon with three singles and a walk to plate
the winning run. Gregg Jefferies knocked in Alex Arias with a
two-out base hit, after Troy O'Leary had saved the Sox _ it seemed
_ by throwing out pinch runner Kevin Sefcik at home on Doug
Glanville's hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really know what's going to happen,'' said Sox
manager Jimy Williams. ``They score three to go ahead. The next
thing you know we're ahead by five. They fought back, too. That's
why this game can humble you.''
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind by three in the first inning, Boston came
roaring back against Schilling, who was once Red Sox property and
is now one of the NL's toughest pitchers. Nomar Garciaparra got one
back in the bottom of the first. He tripled, extending his hitting
streak to 14 games, and scored on a base hit by Mo Vaughn. Boston
really came on in in the fourth and fifth innings, scoring seven
times to turn a 3-1 deficit into an 8-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of folding, Philadelphia went on the attack, sending
Wakefield to the showers with a three-run spurt in the sixth. In
the seventh, John Wasdin was charged with a run, and the cushion
suddenly was one, 8-7.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Lewis hit a blast off Garces over the left-field
screen, depriving Wakefield of a chance at victory and taking
Schilling off a giant hook. Schilling escaped despite allowing 12
hits. He did strike out 10 and walked none.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon entered in the 10th, and right away there were signs of
trouble. A single by Kevin Jordan was followed by a sacrifice bunt
and a walk. Glanville followed with a single to left, but Sefcik
was thrown out as catcher Scott Hatteberg survived a full-scale
crash that earned a standing ovation. But when Jefferies singled to
right, a faster Arias beat the throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got behind a couple of the hitters,'' said Gordon. ``When
I'm ahead, I can use my curveball. It didn't happen tonight. You
hate to lose but these things will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox just have to take this one in stride, said Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss,'' he said. ``But we're not perfect. We're
not machines. You have to put this behind you. We've been playing
well. I expect to see Garces back in that spot again. He's pitched
well. Just pick it up and keep going. You can't hang your head. You
have to just keep on pushing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
