<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-FILMLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GODFATHER OF CELLULOID LOCATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City is taking a pounding from the movie
industry this season, what with an overgrown lizard squishing it, a
tsunami engulfing it and an asteroid bopping it hard enough to make
anyone wish he had a bunker of his own.
</P>
<P>
   This, some are convinced, is Hollywood's way of saying it really
loves us. Maybe there is something to that. Cinematically speaking,
New York is hot. There were 213 feature films shot here last year,
a record, and while the Mayor's Office of Film, Theater and
Broadcasting will not say how 1998 is shaping up, the city seems to
be doing well enough.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't, the Kaufman Astoria Studios in Queens would
presumably not be planning to expand, and a couple of young
entrepreneurs would not be trying to build a large movie studio in
the Brooklyn Navy Yard. They are far enough along to have received
City Hall's go-ahead, provided they also get the necessary private
financing by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attraction for a lot of writers and directors is the city
itself,'' said James Rutherford, a managing director at J.P. Morgan
and the project's financial adviser. Now, once the New York
exterior shots are taken care of, actors and crews usually trek
back to Los Angeles for the indoor scenes. In theory, a
Hollywood-style operation in the Navy Yard would keep them hanging
around, and spending money, the whole time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to make it easy for the people who want to be
here,'' Rutherford said.
</P>
<P>
   New York's appeal to moviemakers goes back a long way, a point
that was reaffirmed the other day when the American Film Institute
came up with its 100 best American films of all time.
</P>
<P>
   The howls of protest over this list were immediate and, many
would say, justified. How, they asked, did ``Dances With Wolves''
qualify (No. 75) but nothing by Ernst Lubitsch or Preston Sturges?
The absence of any Audrey Hepburn movie other than the plodding
``My Fair Lady'' (No. 91) is reason alone to arouse suspicion; take
it from someone who has been in love with her since he first saw
``Breakfast at Tiffany's.''
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the Top 100 includes many indisputably great
films, and nearly a quarter of them, 23, are set in this city,
entirely or in part. All were not shot here. But even if filmed on
sound stages, New York was their backdrop, including No. 1,
``Citizen Kane,'' and No. 100, ``Yankee Doodle Dandy.''
</P>
<P>
   No other place is remotely as popular, and the city does even
better in the Top 50, where it figures in 15 films, or 30 percent.
Among them are the first two ``Godfather'' movies (ranked Nos. 3
and 32), ``All About Eve'' (16) ``Raging Bull'' (24) ``Annie Hall''
(31) ``Rear Window'' (42) and ``Taxi Driver'' (47).
</P>
<P>
   (Confession: Rigorous standards were bent slightly to include
No. 50, ``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.'' On their way to
Bolivia, Butch and Sundance stopped by Coney Island.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Manhattan's a small island, and so many people
of diverse backgrounds share it, is one reason the city's such a
great destination for film makers,'' said Bruce Goldstein, who has
put together several programs of New York movies for the Film Forum
in Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein traces New York movies from the 1920s and 30s, when
neighborhoods like Orchard Street and Park Avenue were used to
establish class differences, through the New York films noirs of
the 40s and 50s, to the falling-apart city of the 70s: a
nightmarish vision, he says, that ``didn't stop even when things
got better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's so visual,'' he said. ``It always has been, and it
still is. Every studio back lot had a New York street, not a Boston
street or a San Francisco street.''
</P>
<P>
   He, for one, has little use for a ``best'' list that leaves out
a searing New York film like ``Sweet Smell of Success.'' But there
are compensations. One could argue that the three top-rated films
all make important nods to the city: ``Citizen Kane'' and ``The
Godfather'' for sure, in first and third place, but also
``Casablanca,'' ranked No. 2 and not included in the earlier count
of 23 New York films.
</P>
<P>
   You are perhaps shocked, shocked, to hear that the city figures
in that Humphrey Bogart classic? It does.
</P>
<P>
   When a German officer speculates about taking over New York,
Bogart tells him, ``There are certain sections of New York, major,
that I wouldn't advise you to try to invade.'' With that Gotham
spirit, World War II was won.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
