<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BRASS, SAME RESULT FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Somewhere in Glendale Monday night, Bill
Russell got a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The deposed Los Angeles Dodgers manager didn't lie in bed,
wondering how his team _ and bullpen in particular _ could blow a
four-run, seventh-inning lead to the Anaheim Angels. That was
interim manager Glenn Hoffman's job now.
</P>
<P>
   In Hoffman's debut, the Angels rallied for one run in the
seventh, four in the eighth and one in the ninth on Tim Salmon's
bases-loaded walk to beat the Dodgers, 6-5, Monday night before
43,491, the biggest crowd in Edison Field history.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have now won 19 of 22 and moved 3{ games ahead of
Texas in the AL West. The Dodgers fell a season-worst 13{ games
behind San Diego in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes left the game leading 4-1 after
giving up a double to Gary DiSarcina leading off the eighth. Scott
Radinsky came in to replace Valdes, and three batters later, the
game was tied at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad doubled in one run, Dave Hollins singled in another
and Jim Edmonds doubled home Hollins to tie the game at 4.
</P>
<P>
   Greg McMichael replaced Radinsky and struck out Tim Salmon, but
Cecil Fielder followed with a single to right field, scoring
Edmonds for a 5-4 lead and what seemed would be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival, looking for save No.24, retired the first two
batters in the bottom of the ninth. He then fell behind 2-0 to
pinch-hitter Matt Luke, who the lined Percival's next pitch 10 rows
up into the right-field bleachers to tie the game at 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   But it only delayed what seemed to be inevitable, the way things
have been going for both teams. In the bottom of the ninth,
McMichael walked Justin Baughman to lead off the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman went to second on DiSarcina's sacrifice bunt. After
Erstad was walked intentionally, Craig Shipley, a former Dodger in
the game as a defensive replacement, struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman then brought in left-handed reliever Mark Guthrie, who
walked Edmonds to load the bases. Hoffman summoned right-hander Jim
Bruske to face Salmon, who walked on a 3-1 count to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers catcher Charles Johnson staked Valdes to a 4-0 lead
almost single-handedly. Johnson, batting only .211 entering the
game, singled in the second and fourth innings and doubled in the
sixth off Olivares. Each hit scored a run, the fourth run coming in
on an error.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Dodgers had only four hits, all off Olivares,
until Luke's homer in the ninth off Percival tied it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Angels' clubhouse was a place of refuge.
While the horde of media gathered in around the Dodgers' clubhouse
and dugout, the Angels got ready for Monday's game in peace, except
for the sounds of Kool and the Gang's ``Celebration'' blaring from
the elaborate sound system.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Angels are in first place and the Dodgers are
struggling to remain in the race. But the Dodgers are still the
center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I'm concerned, it's never going to change,'' said
Angels outfielder Garret Anderson, who grew up in the San Fernando
Valley. ``That's just the way it is, the way it's always going to
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's too much tradition in Dodger history for us to get in
front of them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of World Series experience as an
organization,'' DiSarcina said. ``It's a strong organization. I
look at it as an abnormal year for them. It's always like there's a
stamp of approval on the Dodgers, because they've won. You can't
blame the fans for wanting to support them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the shadows,'' Edmonds said. ``It's nothing we
can change. It's something we've dealt with, and are going to have
to deal with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
