<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHEMICALS-FOUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CACHE OF CHEMICALS FOUND IN BRONX HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DAVID W. CHEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Police officers responding to a report of a burglary
in the Bronx on Monday afternoon discovered several boxes of rare
chemicals, some of which were radioactive and flammable, the
authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The chemicals, found in the basement of a house at 4543 Bronx
Boulevard in the Wakefield section, included small quantities of
napalm, carbon 14, radium 226, chlorine 35, krypton 85, strontium
90 and cesium 135, said Charles Sturcken, chief of staff of the
city's Department of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency personnel initially evacuated about 15 people from
seven adjacent houses, taking them to Public School 16 under the
auspices of the Red Cross. But by late Monday night, the
authorities, after determining that the materials emitted only low
levels of radioactivity and that there was no immediate danger,
allowed the people to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't enough to make a bomb,'' said an investigator who
spoke on the condition of anonymity, referring to the radioactive
materials. ``It was about the same amount as you'd find in a
dentist's office.''
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors and investigators identified the resident of 4543
Bronx Boulevard as Carl Natanagara, 30, who neighbors described as
reclusive. They said Natanagara's father, who died recently, had
worked at Nuclear Research Corp., a Dover, N.J., company that
supplies radiation monitoring equipment. Natanagara's mother, they
added, now lives in a nursing home in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   All the chemicals, which environmental officials said were
safely stored, bore the label of the Nuclear Research Corp.,
Sturcken said. On Monday night, officials said company
representatives were at the scene and working with the authorities
to remove the chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what, if anything, Natanagara
planned to do with the chemicals, some of which are used in Geiger
counters. But investigators speaking on the condition of anonymity
said that the chemicals might have been in the house for as many as
15 years, and that Natanagara might not have been aware of them. By
early Tuesday morning, the police had not filed any charges against
Natanagara.
</P>
<P>
   The police said that the incident began shortly before 1 p.m.
when they received calls that someone had broken into Mr.
Natanagara's home. When the police arrived, Natanagara told them
that he had locked his keys inside and had kicked open the door to
gain access, said Detective Robert Samuel, a spokesman for the
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   When the police entered the house, they noticed a box labeled
``radioactive,'' Samuel said. An inspection of the box revealed
low-level radioactive material used to calibrate Geiger counters.
Officers also found 2 pints of napalm, 15 gallons of hydrochloric
acid, a .22-caliber handgun, a .22-caliber rifle, black powder and
various types of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the police could not identify some of the chemicals,
Samuel said. As a result, they called in an army of public agencies
_ including the FBI, the city Department of Health and the city
Office of Emergency Management _ to monitor the situation while
they evaucated the neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
