<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 02:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1786 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-23 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' DEFENSIVE LAPSE LIFTS PADRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Say this for the Mariners. If they haven't exposed
their various warts enough times for their followers, they trot
them out at regular intervals seemingly just to reinforce the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at the Kingdome, another Mariner castoff succeeded
on the mound against Seattle, and the M's damaged themselves with
another mysterious defensive lapse in a 5-3 interleague loss to San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Stop us if you've heard this one before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of game we've been losing,'' said Alex
Rodriguez, the Mariner shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Then he reconsidered. ``Blowouts, too,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Hitchcock, dealt out of Seattle after the '96 season so
the M's could add a right-handed arm in Scott Sanders, tightroped
through six innings of two-hit ball and left with a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't get the victory because he allowed a Rodriguez solo
homer, his 26th, and the Padre setup men were less overpowering
than usual. The San Diego closer had no problems, however;
presented a 5-3 lead in the ninth, Trevor Hoffman recorded his 23rd
straight save of the year and 31st over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner left-hander Jeff Fassero failed in his seventh straight
try to get his sixth victory. He hasn't won since May 16.
</P>
<P>
   But, aside from Hitchcock's pitching, what 41,571 Mariner fans
will likely take away from the game is another unspeakable
defensive play that nudged a 1-0 San Diego lead to 3-0, from which
Seattle never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Padre Greg Vaughn doubled and Ruben Rivera
walked. Catcher Jim Leyritz, who made it into town at 2 a.m. Monday
after being traded from Boston, lofted an eminently catchable ball
into short right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' said Fassero. ``I thought I was out of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   But second baseman Joey Cora wove uncertainly after the towering
pop and right fielder Jay Buhner, playing deep, appeared to think
Cora had it under control. He didn't, waving futilely at it as
Buhner charged in, and the gift double gave San Diego two runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly what happened,'' said Mariner manager Lou
Piniella. ``Jay's leg has been bothering him, as you know. The ball
was up there a long time. But I don't know what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock quickly gave back one-third of the lead on Rodriguez'
homer, and left after the sixth with a 3-1 lead. The M's tagged
three balls to the warning track against him and drilled another
back to the box that he turned into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he lowered his earned-run average to 3.63.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have real good command,'' Hitchcock said. ``But it
seemed like when I needed to, I got out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   It went to the eighth tied 3-3 after Rodriguez's two-run double,
when San Diego put the screws to the M's, with the help of another
near-miss play, this one a little more understandable.
</P>
<P>
   First, hitter extraordinaire Tony Gwynn, whom Fassero had
retired three straight times, managed to squeeze a pivotal walk
from the Mariner starter, checking his swing on a 3-2 slider that
dipped low and outside. A lesser hitter than Gwynn probably strikes
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe up an inch and he swings at it,'' sighed Fassero.
``Obviously, he was going out to get it. He just held up enough to
check his swing.''
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Ken Caminiti then chipped a wedge shot that was
headed over the left shoulder of Rodriguez, who instead turned to
his right. By the time he could try to compensate and glove it on
the other side, it was falling for a hit, sending Gwynn to third.
Rivera's double down the left-field line then plated both Padre
runs, sending the National League West leaders to their 50th
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an opportunity to make a very good play, but I came up
short,'' Rodriguez lamented. ``In your eyes, it might have been a
good game for me, but in my eyes, it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I read it. I messed it up. I blew it. That's a play
that has to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The M's had a gasp left in the eighth, putting two runners on
with one out. But Dan Wilson, mired in a 6-for-38 slump, grounded
into a force and pinch-hitter Russ Davis struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock didn't get the victory, but he's on a club 24 games
over .500, not one 15 games out of a division lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I didn't understand,'' he said, referring to
the trade, ``about three days before it, I talked to Lou in Tampa,
and he said he was comfortable going with four lefties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it make baseball sense? Yeah, it does.''
</P>
<P>
   And these days, with the finale of the series at 3:35 p.m.
Tuesday, the M's will take baseball sense wherever they can get it.
</P>
</TEXT>
