<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANGEL2-LADN(WRITETHROUGH) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE IN HOFFMAN'S DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Somewhere in Glendale Monday night, Bill
Russell got a good night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The deposed Los Angeles Dodgers manager didn't lie in bed,
wondering how his team _ primarily the bullpen _ could blow a
four-run, seventh-inning lead to the Anaheim Angels. That was
interim manager Glenn Hoffman's problem now.
</P>
<P>
   In Hoffman's debut, the Angels rallied for one run in the
seventh, four in the eighth and one in the ninth on Tim Salmon's
bases-loaded walk to beat the Dodgers 6-5 Monday night before
43,491, the biggest crowd in Edison Field history.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have now won 19 of 22 and moved 3{ games ahead of
Texas in the AL West. The Dodgers fell a season-worst 13{ games
behind San Diego in the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman probably didn't get much sleep Monday considering the
events of the day, which he termed bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a few people that become managers go through this,''
Hoffman said. ``I wouldn't trade it for the world, except for one
thing _ a win in the ninth. It is not a perfect situation right
now, but we're trying to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and the Dodgers attracted most of the attention before
and after the game, but Angels manager Terry Collins said he can
live with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nobody wants to pay attention to us, that's fine,'' he
said. ``I know one thing _ I want to play in October. Then people
will notice us. We'll be happy to get a couple wins, sneak out of
town and stay out of your hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers starter Ismael Valdes left the game leading 4-1 after
giving up a double to Gary DiSarcina leading off the eighth. Scott
Radinsky came in to replace Valdes, and three batters later, the
game was tied at 4. Darin Erstad doubled in one run, Dave Hollins
singled in another and Jim Edmonds doubled home Hollins to tie the
game at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Greg McMichael replaced Radinsky and struck out Salmon, but
Cecil Fielder followed with a single to right field, scoring
Edmonds for a 5-4 lead and what seemed would be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival, looking for save No.24, retired the first two
batters in the top of the ninth. He then fell behind 2-0 to
pinch-hitter Matt Luke, who lined Percival's next pitch 10 rows up
into the right-field bleachers to tie the game.
</P>
<P>
   But it only delayed what seemed to be inevitable, with the way
things have been going for both teams. In the bottom of the ninth,
McMichael walked Justin Baughman to lead off the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Baughman went to second on DiSarcina's sacrifice bunt. After
Erstad was walked intentionally, Craig Shipley, a former Dodger in
the game as a defensive replacement, struck out. Hoffman then
brought in left-handed reliever Mark Guthrie, who walked Edmonds to
load the bases. Hoffman summoned right-hander Jim Bruske to face
Salmon, who walked on a 3-1 count to win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to control my emotions in that situation,''
Salmon said, ``and not get too jumpy.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Charles Johnson helped Valdes and the Dodgers jump out
to a 4-0 lead. Johnson, hitting only .211 going into the game,
singled in the second and fourth innings off Angels starter Omar
Olivares, and he doubled in the sixth. Each hit scored a run, the
fourth run coming in on an error.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Dodgers had only four hits off Olivares, until
Luke's homer in the ninth off Percival tied it.
</P>
<P>
   Pervical (1-2) got the win over McMichael (1-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``I assume that was what playoff atmosphere is like in
Anaheim,'' Salmon said. ``I've never seen it before. That's what it
was like in Seattle a couple years ago (in the one-game playoff).''
</P>
</TEXT>
