<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GIANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS OUTSLUG A'S 
BY STEVE KETTMANN
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ If Kevin Mitchell had his way, the A's and
Giants would have it out in a vacant warehouse somewhere,
splattering each other with paint-ball pellets. If they did, it
wouldn't look much messier than Monday night's 12-8 Giants victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants busted out with a season-high nine-run rally in the
fifth, making the most of the A's weak bullpen; every Giants
starter scored a run; and the A's lost three different players to
injury: starter Kenny Rogers, Mitchell (back spasms), and catcher
A.J. Hinch (elbow).
</P>
<P>
   Losing Rogers after three sharp innings to a strained oblique
muscle doomed the A's. ``That was a terrible break,'' A's manager
Art Howe said. ``That changed the whole complexion of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   All that mayhem should have left both teams on cruise-control,
but instead they both kept banging out hits all game long,
including a Rickey Henderson solo shot in the eighth and a leadoff
double from Matt Stairs in the ninth, giving him his first career
four-hit game.
</P>
<P>
   But once Stairs reached base in the ninth, Giants closer Robb
Nen went to work and gave the fans something to cheer about. That's
right, it was the second-largest crowd of the season at the
Coliseum, 36,096, and these people were Giants fans, cheering for
J.T. Snow's defensive-replacement appearance late in the game (a
stirring moment) almost as loudly as they cheered Henderson's homer
and the fireworks that followed.
</P>
<P>
   As Nen made quick work of Mike Blowers, Jason Giambi and Rafael
Bournigal in the ninth, the fans in the first deck rose to their
feet and cheered like crazy. Soon it was over and Kirk Rueter (9-3)
had his fifth straight victory, leaving him with three more wins
than any other Giant starter.
</P>
<P>
   Once Rogers left the game, the Giants celebrated like kids whose
parents have just left town for a week's vacation. Rogers held them
to one hit and precious few good swings, but going against reliever
Aaron Small gave the Giants a whole different look. Small found a
way to get out of the fourth without mishap, despite Barry Bonds'
one-out flare double to shallow right, but ran out of luck in the
nine-run, eight-hit fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jones started the inning with a double, Marvin Benard
sacrificed him to third, then eight straight Giants hitters reached
base, none of them wasting much time before lunging at fat
offerings. Small gave up seven runs in 11/3 innings, lifting his
ERA to 7.25 and raising the question ``How much more of him do the
A's need to see?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the quickest nine runs I've ever seen scored,''
Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``That was the quickest I've seen
since the Big Red Machine did it to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That should have ended the game, right then and there, but oh
no, not hardly. The A's scored five runs in the sixth to make it a
9-6 game, rookie shortstop Miguel Tejada falling a few feet shy of
a grand slam that inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got right back in the ballgame,'' Baker said. ``I'm glad
our guys had their hitting shoes on because THEIR guys sure did.''
</P>
<P>
   The rally might have had a little more oomph to it if Ryan
Christenson had not pinch-hit for Mitchell, who left with a sore
back, and if Izzy Molina had not pinch-hit for Hinch, who left with
a sore left elbow. That isn't a knock on Molina, who came through
with a pinch single to center to keep the rally alive. But the
sense that the A's were dropping like flies did not help their
prospects, even though after the game the word was Hinch and
Mitchell should both be available soon.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Buddy Groom came out in relief of left-hander Mike
Mohler in the seventh with two runners on base, and shortstop Rey
Sanchez liked Groom's first pitch so much, he launched it over the
left-center-field wall for a three-run homer. Even that didn't
quite end it, but it was one more sign that the A's couldn't win
just by throwing up more runs, not without Rogers in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to see anybody get hurt,'' Baker said.
``Certainly Kenny Rogers is one of the best pitchers around. When
your starting pitcher gets hurt that early, you have to go to the
bullpen early and that makes it tough the next night and the next
night.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
