<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1812 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOACHUM-OBIT-SFCHRON &LR;      06-23 1864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOACHUM-OBIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSAN YOACHUM, CHRONICLE POLITICAL EDITOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By KENNETH J. GARCIA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; Chronicle Political Editor Susan Yoachum, who
covered two decades of electoral campaigns with the same passion,
determination and irrepressible spirit she later brought to her
fight against breast cancer, died Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum, who had battled the disease for seven years, was 43.
</P>
<P>
   She died, surrounded by family members, at home in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  ``The Chronicle newsroom is a sad place today,'' said
Managing Editor Jerry Roberts. ``In Susan, we have lost a tough
reporter, a stylish writer, a beloved friend and colleague and,
most of all, a remarkable human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum was renowned on the campaign trail for her tenacity, her
humor, her sophistication and her competitive knack for seizing on
scoops and breaking stories. She often worked around the clock
while on the road, filing dispatches for numerous editions.
Diagnosed with cancer in 1991, she continued to work, and her
editorial output remained remarkably prolific and diverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great loss for journalism, it is a great loss for
humanity, and for all of us who are women, it is a loss of one of
the great ones,'' said Sen. Dianne Feinstein. ``I know of no one
who fought a better fight against cancer with such overwhelming
determination. She inspired literally everyone who talked with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Board of Supervisors adjourned Monday in
Yoachum's memory, and Mayor Willie Brown said Tuesday he will order
all flags on city buildings flown at half-staff in her honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She embodied the highest ideals of public service,'' said
Supervisor Michael Yaki. ``To face her illness the way she did was
a testimony to the kind of human spirit we would all like to see in
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Yoachum revealed in a first-person story that her
cancer had returned and was spreading through her body after being
in remission for several years. Her moving disclosure prompted a
health columnist for the Wall Street Journal to call her ``a
real-life Murphy Brown'' for her courage in sharing her private
battle with hundreds of thousands of readers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her work has has been a lighthouse beam through the fog of
local and national politics,'' the Journal's Marilyn Chase wrote.
``She stands as a model of professionalism and courage in the
workplace. The lesson for colleagues of cancer survivors:
Professionalism doesn't disappear with a diagnosis.''
</P>
<P>
   As political editor, Yoachum understood prepackaged candidates,
prearranged conventions and predictable stump speeches. She could
sniff out a story, a fib, a hint of scandal or a dodged question
with uncanny speed. She kept her competitors running and the
politicians running harder.
</P>
<P>
   She had a passion for political campaigns and a healthy, if
skeptical, view of career politicians. In the often-raucous world
of campaign reporting still largely dominated by men, she showed
that she was more than a match for ``The Boys on the Bus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved politics, and she hated hypocrisy,'' said Phil
Trounstine, political editor of the San Jose Mercury News, where
Yoachum covered politics during the 1980s. ``She was tough, sharp
and fair and a great friend. Everyone in the political press corps
loved and respected Susan Yoachum. She was just a wonderful human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Born on May 12, 1955, in Dallas, Texas, Susan Gail Yoachum was
the daughter of Betty and the late Charles G. Yoachum. She
graduated in 1975 from Southern Methodist University in Dallas with
bachelor's degrees in journalism and political science. She was a
reporter for the Dallas Morning News, the Independent Journal in
Marin County and the San Jose Mercury News, where she was part of a
team that won a 1990 Pulitzer Prize for breaking news. She joined
The Chronicle in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest political dramas of the '80s and '90s were
published under her byline.
</P>
<P>
   She covered national, state and local politics for The
Chronicle, and her assignments included the 1992 presidential
campaign, the governor's races in 1990 and 1994, the 1991 San
Francisco mayoral race and the 1992 U.S. Senate race. She wrote
in-depth about issues, from affirmative action to abortion, from
the tobacco tax to the hazards of toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum was promoted to political editor in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In August, she was named journalist of the year by the Northern
California chapter of the Society of Professional Journalists. Some
400 people honored her at that awards banquet with repeated
standing ovations _ and many tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my moment,'' Yoachum said that night, in an emotional
acceptance speech. Days later, her illness suddenly worsened as the
cancer entered its final phase.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a journalist and a role model, Susan has been an
unparalleled asset to the Bay Area,'' said Sally Lehrman, chapter
president.
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum was an evocative writer and a voracious reader whose
love of language surfaced at an early age: She became the National
Spelling Champion in 1969, winning her crown by correctly spelling
the word ``interlocutory.''
</P>
<P>
   As a journalist, she communicated the drama of American politics
_ its joys, intrigues and deceptions _ in her stories. She was also
an articulate, funny and in-demand national political analyst on
both television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   A true daughter of Texas, Yoachum lapsed into a sly southwestern
drawl whenever it suited her purpose. Her refreshing candor and
insight _ along with tough questions, usually delivered with a
disarming smile _ made her a popular and frequent guest on programs
ranging from CNN's ``Inside Politics'' to news shows on virtually
every Bay Area radio and television station.
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum earned a widespread reputation for her integrity and
balance _ which won her the respect of the elected officials and
insiders she covered.
</P>
<P>
   A tribute to her fairness came as news of her illness spread.
Sources and contacts across the political spectrum called to offer
their prayers, support and help.
</P>
<P>
   ``She paid attention and listened and sought both sides and was
always looking to be fair,'' recalled Ken Khachigian, a political
consultant who has worked for many Republican candidates, ``I have
no idea what her own political leaning was, which says something.
There was a reporter in her heart.''
</P>
<P>
   After undergoing treatment for tumors both in 1991 and 1992,
Yoachum remained cancer-free until the spring of 1997 _ a five-year
period that cancer specialists say indicates a ``cure.'' But a few
weeks later while making a call on a story, she felt a lump in her
neck. She immediately went to her doctor. Soon after, she learned
the cancer had returned.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, the cancer was spreading through her body so
fast that the last round of chemotherapy seemed to do little but
make her more ill. But she managed to file for the paper one last
time, offering a withering view of the gubernatorial debate on May
13 that was marred by a technical glitch.
</P>
<P>
   If not for a 10-minute television blackout, she wrote, would
viewers have bothered to ``watch Al Checchi again duck the question
of why he was evidently too busy in the '90s to vote. ... Or was it
simply an `X-Files' moment, complete with alien abductions?''
</P>
<P>
   Her prose was as amusing and trenchant as ever.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, she dubbed Democratic candidates Feinstein and Barbara
Boxer _ who would become the first pair of women from the same
state to serve in the Senate _ ``the Thelma and Louise of American
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, she took aim at President Clinton during his
annual address.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his fifth State of the Union address last night, the
president came perilously close to giving a strong, memorable
speech. Then he kept talking for another 30 minutes,'' she wrote.
``The speech delivered more promises than most could count and more
preaching than some would want.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum wrote and spoke with authority, optimism and a friendly
accessibility that belied her toughness. She knew her way around a
smoke-filled room, a council chamber or the back of Air Force One.
No one intimidated her, and everyone knew it. She never shied away
from a good story _ or a fight with sources or editors to get it
into the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Yet of all the battles she encountered, the most difficult was
her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have metastatic breast cancer,'' she wrote last September.
``It's a tough word to spell and an even harder one to say, but its
meaning is rather simple. It means a runaway train is careening
through my body.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know that I'm scared _ and that I feel good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum's raw pain touched countless women with breast cancer _
and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many others, I cried when I read Susan Yoachum's stark
accounting of her life with metastatic breast cancer,'' one reader
wrote in a letter to the editor. ``I know it will not only help
those who are similarly stricken, but the goals of better cancer
research and treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum did not hesitate to make such connections about the
disease _ or to be an ardent advocate for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   She frequently spoke to local women's groups and political
organizations, introducing herself with the phrase, ``I'm a breast
cancer survivor.'' It was her chance to give a human dimension to a
medical headline _ and to give hope to those who had been there.
</P>
<P>
   That advocacy became the hallmark of her last years. She sweetly
goaded her newspaper colleagues to sign up for cancer fund-raising
runs in Golden Gate Park. She critiqued books about cancer for The
Chronicle's book review section.
</P>
<P>
   ``This book,'' she wrote in a September 1995 review, ``closely
parallels what it is like to undergo cancer treatment in this
country today: good intentions, great uncertainty _ and not many
answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing about the 180,000 women who get breast cancer each year,
she said:
</P>
<P>
   ``I want there to be a face that goes with these statistics. It
certainly doesn't have to be my face; it can be the face of someone
you surely know and love who has had her life torn apart by this
disease. This carnage has to stop. I write to plead for more and
better research, for more and better treatment. Like too many women
before me, I write to plead: Find something to save my life. To
save all of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Brown, who had known Yoachum since her days as a reporter
in Sacramento when he was Assembly speaker, said she was a friend
as well as a journalist. ``Early on, when she wrote about her
illness, it was one of the first times anyone with breast cancer
put it out there,'' Brown said. ``I imagine her comments saved a
lot women's lives by alerting them to get checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Yoachum is survived by her husband, Mike Carlson; her mother,
Betty; and her brother, Charles, of Dallas, and his family.
</P>
<P>
   Funeral arrangements are being made for later this week. The
family requests that contributions in her name be sent to The
Breast Cancer Fund, 282 Second St., San Francisco 94105; or to the
Ernest Rosenbaum Cancer Research Fund, Mount Zion Health System,
3330 Geary Blvd., San Francisco 94118.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
