A1832 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NORTHIRELAND-ELECTION     06-23 1774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORTHIRELAND-ELECTIONS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN IRELAND'S VOTERS TAKE NEXT STEP ON ROAD TO PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK VIVIANO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COUNTY ARMAGH, Northern Ireland _ When the guns fall silent,
peace isn't beyond the imagination on a spring morning in Armagh.
Along the banks of the River Bann, winding its sleepy way through
lush emerald hills, the only sound as dawn breaks is the buzz of
honeybees rising in the mist.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Northern Ireland goes to the polls again, to elect
a governing assembly authorized by May's ``yes'' vote on a peace
settlement. The novelty of tranquil mornings in Armagh _ ``Bloody
Armagh'' in the violent chronicle of Ireland's ``Troubles'' _ hangs
in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Much will depend on people like George Savage, 56, a local
councilman from the Ulster Unionist Party, and Dara O'Hagan, 30, an
assembly candidate on the ticket of Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   They are canvassing opposite ends of the sectarian divide as the
election approaches, determined to win as many seats as possible
for their respective parties in the 108-seat assembly. But the
larger purpose, for both, is to silence the gunshots and bomb
blasts of Armagh forever.
</P>
<P>
   Like O'Hagan, Savage has spent his entire life here: nearly half
a century as a dairy farmer, a decade as a councilman _ and 14
years as a soldier in the Ulster Defense Regiment, a 97-percent
Protestant army, hunting Catholic republicans in the hills above
the Bann.
</P>
<P>
   One of the men he hunted was O'Hagan's father, Joe O'Hagan, a
leading IRA man who eluded hundreds of army patrols in the Armagh
hills before he was finally captured in the 1960s and sent to
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IRA and the British fought each other to a standstill.
Nobody won,'' Dara O'Hagan says. ``We have to recognize now that
the time for fighting is over, and that republicans must manage the
transition from rebellion to power, from waging war to
administering a just peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The election and the next few months, says Savage, ``will
present us with our sole opportunity in a lifetime to look to the
future, not back over our shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Their words frame the immensely difficult task that lies ahead _
a quest for justice that is not mired in the unresolved conflicts
of the past, a quest for the future that is not ambushed by a
generation born to the gun.
</P>
<P>
   The two quests will converge in County Armagh, a scant 10 days
after the election, at the portals of Drumcree Church one mile west
of the River Bann.
</P>
<P>
   On the first Sunday of every July since the 18th century,
thousands of Protestants have marched to and from Drumcree in
commemoration of the 1795 founding of the Orange Order, the
80,000-member lodge that is the largest unionist organization in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes the right of the Orangemen to march. The issue
is the route, and it is a compelling symbol of the power that
unresolved history wields in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange Order has long insisted on parading down Garvaghy
Road, in the Armagh town of Portadown, through the heart of a
neighborhood that is 100 percent Catholic. Accompanied by uniformed
pipe bands _ and often protected by the armored cars of the Royal
Ulster Constabulary _ the marchers sing of Protestant triumphs over
``Fenians,'' an epithet for Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are up to our necks in Fenian blood. Surrender or you'll
die!'' one of the songs proclaims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The route is chosen to humiliate us, to remind us that we are
second-class citizens in our own country,'' says Breandon
MacCionnaith, an independent nationalist councilman in Portadown.
``There is no good reason why they can't march from Drumcree down
another road.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Protestants, any tinkering at all with such rituals is
unacceptable. The parades are intrinsic to the unionist identity;
provincewide, there are more than 3,000 of them in a ``marching
season'' that pivots around early July.
</P>
<P>
   The British government backed the Orange Order last year,
deploying heavily armed security forces to clear Garvaghy Road for
the marchers. The parade was followed by weeks of rioting, in what
has become an annual response to Drumcree.
</P>
<P>
   This year, London's position on the march route remained in
doubt as the elections neared, and the Garvaghy Road residents
association has invited Catholics from all over the island to join
them on July 5 in blocking the parade.
</P>
<P>
   On May 31, the Orange Order's youth wing paraded down Garvaghy
Road in a preliminary march. They were met by 400 Catholic young
people throwing rocks, bottles and Molotov cocktails. Three
civilians and 11 police officers were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Unless a compromise on the July 5 event is achieved very soon,
the scene has been set for a much more serious confrontation less
than two weeks after the election. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for a peace-loving, but loyal unionist politician
like George Savage is to push for compromise on the march issue
without appearing to abandon two centuries of Protestant tradition.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for his Sinn Fein counterpart, Dara O'Hagan, is to
press for a basic human right _ the right of Catholics not to be
humiliated in their own front yards _ without taking her own
community back down the road to an endless exchange of provocation
and violent response.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for the entire province, says Mark Neale, 32,
Savage's fellow unionist councilman, ``is that our history has bred
entrenched cultures of grievance and revenge in Northern Ireland,
and we must escape them.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a ``culture of secrecy'' to contend with, says
Armagh County attorney Rosemary Nelson, that has hidden the deeds
and strategies of paramilitary and security forces behind a thick
veil.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to nationalism and unionism, `securitism' is part
of the legacy of Irish history,'' says Nelson, a prominent critic
of police abuses in the province. ``As long as it goes
unchallenged, a genuine civil society is beyond reach.''
</P>
<P>
   In principle, everyone who wants peace believes that the book
must somehow be closed, that the atrocities of the past must be
forgiven if not forgotten _ that the cultures of grievance, revenge
and secrecy must give way to a genuine civil society.
</P>
<P>
   But no one is sure how to accomplish that goal without appearing
to betray the 45,000 people, Catholic and Protestant alike, who
were killed or wounded in sectarian conflicts over the past 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness is rare in Northern Ireland. It would be rare in any
place with such a toll. Since 1969, more than 3,200 people have
died in Northern Ireland from sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we know the truth about what happened in those years,
behind the veil of secrecy, it will be impossible to build a new
society,'' says Paddy Kelly, 35, a Belfast human rights activist.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims are entitled to the truth _ the victims of the
state security apparatus, as much as those of the IRA and the
loyalist paramilitaries.''
</P>
<P>
   History, she points out, has not ended simply because 70 percent
of Northern Ireland's people voted ``yes'' on a referendum for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the referendum, hardly an hour passes in an Armagh
town without a British patrol dodging down a shopping street in
full battle gear, faces smudged with black camouflage paint,
assault rifles loaded and aimed.
</P>
<P>
   As the chill Armagh winter waned into an unusually sunny spring,
hardly a day passed without a reminder that the book is not closed
yet: a 26-year-old Catholic father of two beaten to death in
Portadown; two Protestant-owned shops bombed by rogue IRA units;
bombs tossed at Royal Ulster Constabulary posts in the middle of
the night; the May 31 battle on Garvaghy Road.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers and the paramilitary fighters from both sides who
oppose the peace pact are still on war alert. They _ and their
victims _ are mostly young.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 percent of those who are under 30 in Northern
Ireland have never attended a school with someone from across the
sectarian chasm.
</P>
<P>
   Very few Catholics work in Protestant-owned businesses or in the
swollen security force that has tried to keep the two communities
from tearing each other apart, which is one reason why the
unemployment level among Catholics is 21/2 times that of
Protestants.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Ireland wants peace. The referendum was eloquent and
clear on that simple, unelaborated point. But it is in the
elaborations that peace will succeed or fail, and in much of Armagh
they speak of a land that remains deeply divided.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement reinforces the separation of Catholic and
Protestant into their traditional power blocs, nationalism and
unionism,'' says republican leader Bernadette Devlin McAliskey,
explaining why she voted ``no'' in the referendum. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In June 1998, the towns of Armagh offer virtually no model for
the creation of a joint society. It is amid the honeybees and
grazing cows of the rural countryside, says George Savage, that a
glimmer of hope shines.
</P>
<P>
   With his background in the Ulster Defense Regiment and as a
politician arguing the unionist cause, Savage might be expected to
hate his Catholic neighbors as thoroughly as the loyalist gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   He might be expected to rank high among the unforgiving, since
the night one year ago when his 30-year-old son, George, Jr., was
jumped by five assailants outside a Portadown disco. His skull
fractured, he hung between life and death for a week and has not
yet fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But Savage is a farmer, and the elemental demands of the earth
and his own herd of 80 cows have taught him lessons that are not
yet understood in Armagh's towns.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy cows, and the rich Irish grass that nourishes them, are
neither unionist nor republican.
</P>
<P>
   About three fourths of the farmers in Savage's constituency are
Protestant, a quarter Catholic. But the conduct of their days is
determined by the land and the cows, not by religion or a choice
between flying the Irish tricolor or the Union Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ulster's farmers meet all the time, talk all the time. They
don't talk about politics or religion _ their concerns are things
like pasturing and livestock prices and the quality of various
feeds,'' says Savage. ``They meet in the fields, they meet at the
border with farmers from the Irish Republic, they meet when their
tractors cross paths.''
</P>
<P>
   Savage paused, wiped a handkerchief across a brow deeply
furrowed from half a century in the sun and blustery winds of rural
Armagh. ``Farmers know that they have always had more in common
with each other, Protestant and Catholic, than they ever will with
anyone in Dublin, Belfast or London.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
