<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-NYT &LR;      06-23 0510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GRAND-CENTRAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
115-FOOT GOZILLA BILLBOARD DRAWS PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sighs do matter.
</P>
<P>
   And that is how preservationists have greeted the appearance of
an enormous new billboard in the main concourse of Grand Central
Terminal featuring a 30-foot Godzilla claw _ with sighs of
exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   The banner darkens three soaring, arched windows over the east
balcony that had been uncovered as part of the $196 million
renovation of the terminal by the Metropolitan Transportation
Authority. First planned in 1990, the project is now nearing
completion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really regret the decision to install the banner,'' said
Jennifer J. Raab, chairwoman of the New York City Landmarks
Preservation Commission. ``Since such effort was taken to expose
the wonderful architecture of Grand Central, to obscure it at this
point is really unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Sexton, president of the Municipal Art Society, the
civic group that has been a leader in the fight to preserve the
Beaux-Arts landmark, said, ``The MTA is covering up some of its
best work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's self-defeating,'' Sexton said. ``They're doing a
wonderful job with the terminal. Why besmirch it?''
</P>
<P>
   In response, the MTA offered assurances that the billboard was
temporary and did not augur a return to the days when the concourse
looked like a merchandising carnival, filled with kiosks and signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not the kind of advertising that would ever be accepted
once the terminal is done,'' said Tom Kelly, a spokesman for the
MTA. Rather, he said, it was permitted for one month, since the
concourse is still under reconstruction. The authority will earn
$100,000 from the billboard.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Raab said the commission, which must approve alterations to
the structure, was ``relieved that the banner is temporary and that
they have committed not to do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The 115-foot-long vinyl mesh banner promotes ``Godzilla,'' which
is distributed by Sony Pictures Entertainment, and a very slim new
laptop computer from Sony Electronics. Referring to both, the
advertisement declares, ``Size does matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jodi A. Yegelwel, senior vice president of TDI, which sells,
posts and maintains the advertising at Grand Central, said the
billboard coincided with a recent computer trade show in New York,
PC Expo, and would be removed July 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great opportunity for Sony to reach a target market
during a very important month,'' she said. ``It was probably the
highest-profile ad location in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   But the banner is also an opaque curtain over windows that have
only recently filled the terminal with daylight after years of
obscurity: first, blacked out to accommodate a Kodak sign, and then
lost amid the scaffolding for the reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a temporary return to the bad old days,'' said Francis
Morrone, an architectural historian who leads tours of the terminal
for the Municipal Art Society. ``It's as though Godzilla himself
had descended on Grand Central.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
