<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WILLIAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS' SALARY APPROACH RUBS WILLIAMS THE RIGHT WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKILLMAN, N.J. _ Jayson Williams was more than happy to deliver
good-natured barbs at his employers today at a celebrity golf
tournament, saying it would take $1 billion to re-sign him.
</P>
<P>
   When reality set in, the Nets learned that Williams' agent, Sal
DeFazio, had set the salary standard Monday by grouping Williams,
who earned his first All-Star berth this past season, with Patrick
Ewing, Shaquille O'Neal, Alonzo Mourning, Hakeem Olajuwon, Dikembe
Mutombo and David Robinson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who earned $2.5 million last year, is seeking a
seven-year deal believed to be worth approximately $15 million a
season.
</P>
<P>
   Those six players' average salaries last season was $12,961,667,
topped by Ewing's $20.5 million. But their complete pacts average
even more, with Ewing and O'Neal each earning approximately $17
million a year and Mourning pulling in $15 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at those top five or six guys, that's where he
belongs,'' DeFazio said. ``I think if you look at where those guys
are, take their average salaries, what they're going to be earning,
look at those numbers and it pretty quickly tells you where he
belongs and what he deserves.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rowe, the Nets president, and John Nash, the general
manager, were here at the Cherry Valley Country Club, jokingly
reminding Williams and DeFazio that the general managers of the
teams who are sure to place calls to DeFazio on July 1 were nowhere
to be found on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   With little leverage this time around, the Nets know they need
every bit of Williams' loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're showing some sincerity about me coming back,''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Nets do not seem averse to dealing in the
stratosphere, provided that the two sides are allowed to negotiate
on July 1 and there is no lockout. The Nets' unstable ownership is
prepared to offer more money than is has ever offered to a player,
exceeding the nine-year, $80 million offered Derrick Coleman before
settling on a seven-year, $63 million deal with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a value that we've placed on Jayson for a number of
years,'' Rowe said. ``It's a healthy offer. It's more than we've
offered any other player to my knowledge in our history. If he is
unhappy with that, he is perfectly allowed and would be encouraged
to test the market to see if in fact that's a going rate. And if he
comes back and finds out it was in fact a decent rate and wants to
sign with us, we'll have a great dinner and do it very quickly.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Williams has never made a secret of his desire to stay in New
Jersey, close to where he grew up in New York and close to his
family and friends. And if the Nets treat him fairly, he maintains
that he will be back next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Nets offer me fair value, then the case is closed,''
Williams said. ``If the Nets come to the number that Sal and I have
spoken about and then somebody came with a number that is higher,
I'm still staying in New Jersey, I'm not going to hold them over a
barrel.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
