<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 10:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-CHESS-STAR-ART-     06-23 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-CHESS-STAR-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR A BRONX KNIGHT, MANY CHESS PRIZES STILL TO WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Kwadwo Acheampong been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-1243 or 1927.)  
(gm) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here is Fritz Gaspard, chess coach, on his chess
star:
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling you get from him is that he has this world view.
He has an open mind to all different kinds of chess positions, and
is willing to try anything that looks reasonable. He's also willing
to do the work that's involved. If he decides he wants to play a
certain opening, he'll go out and research it, and not just play
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Any weaknesses? ``Maybe some overconfidence. And basically, his
nerves. He puts a little bit too much pressure on himself
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Understandably. Our chess star is Kwadwo Acheampong, 14, of the
South Bronx, co-captain of the Middle School 118 All-Star Knights,
winners last month of the 1998 National Junior High School
Scholastic Chess Championship in Phoenix. This is a big deal; elite
New York City schools like Hunter and Dalton have traditionally
reigned supreme in chess. Next month the All-Star Knights travel to
Moscow for the World Youth Games.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Kwadwo (pronounced KWAD-jo) will start ninth grade at
Phillips Academy in Andover, Mass., on a full scholarship. (He
turned down Exeter, Deerfield and the Bronx High School of
Science.) He has already appeared on ``Good Morning America'' and
``The Rosie O'Donnell Show.'' His mother is a hairdresser, an
immigrant from Ghana; his father, a onetime cab driver, also from
Ghana, deserted the family when Kwadwo was 5. Kwadwo, born in
Harlem, wants to be a lawyer, like Johnnie Cochran _ ``If he can do
it, I can too'' _ or President of the United States. Today he is
speaking at Middle School 118's graduation, as salutatorian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people tend to underestimate me,'' Kwadwo said in an
interview during chess practice last week, after the All-Star
Knights had analyzed a 1986 world championship game between Gary
Kasparov and Anatoly Karpov. ``But a lot of people call me a born
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   There are lessons here, before we get to Kwadwo.
</P>
<P>
   One, chess in inner-city schools promotes academic success. ``It
taught me how to discipline myself,'' said Kwadwo, who has played
chess since first grade, initially to try to beat his older sister,
Akua, 16. ``It taught me critical thinking. It taught me how to
attack weak points.''
</P>
<P>
   Two, it is important to have a mother whose life centers on the
education of her children. ``If I had gotten the chance, I would
have done better than I did,'' said Kwadwo's mother, Agnes Osei,
whose stepfather did not let her go to college in Ghana. ``I was
not going to let that happen to my children. I knew from the
beginning that they were very smart.''
</P>
<P>
   Three, there are many paths to success. After 18 months of
preparation at Stuyvesant High School's Math/Science Institute,
which consists mostly of minority students, Kwadwo did not score
well enough on the admissions test for entry to Stuyvesant, the
elite public high that was his dream. ``It was a disappointment,''
he said. The best prep schools in America didn't care at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see why they grabbed him when they met him,'' said
Bruce Ravage, the director of the Math/Science Institute. ``This is
the kind of kid you really want to afford an opportunity to.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week in a sweltering MS 118 classroom, in
the East Tremont section of the Bronx, Kwadwo was sophisticated,
sure of himself, poised _ and in pain about a father who seems to
have rediscovered his successful son. ``He's basically trying to
reinsert himself into my life,'' Kwadwo said. ``He calls a lot, but
so much has been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and coaches say that one of the most striking things
about Kwadwo is his adultlike bearing, much in evidence at an
awards ceremony last week held by Chess-in-the-Schools, a nonprofit
group that sponsors the All-Star Knights and brings chess to 22,000
disadvantaged students in New York. Even though Sunil Matabeek, 13,
was Chess-in-the-Schools' Player of the Year (based on his No. 1
ranking), Kwadwo, whose ranking fluctuates between second and
third, was the clear spokesman. He made two speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chess has always been very important to me,'' he said, in
speech No. 1, as he presented a gift to the All-Star Knight
coaches. ``It has allowed me to leave the streets of New York City,
to explore the nation, and this summer, the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Speech No. 2 was to accept the Scholastic and Chess Excellence
Player of the Year award. ``When I go away to boarding school,''
Kwadwo said, ``I will not forget what you all have done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwadwo first played chess with the team at Community Elementary
School 70 in the Bronx, which won the state elementary school
title. But when he moved on to sixth grade at MS 118, he discovered
the school didn't have a chess team. He and three other players
started one, and went on their own, in sixth grade, to the 1996
state championships in White Plains. To everyone's astonishment,
they came in second. Chess-in-the-Schools dispatched coaches to MS
118 the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Andover hasn't had a competitive chess team, but as Kwadwo told
one of his coaches, ``They do now.'' He also said he felt
comfortable when he visited Andover because there were plenty of
minority students and a ``homey'' atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Now he says the kids on the street in the Bronx tell him, ``When
you become rich and famous, don't forget about us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
