<SLUG> BC-LEARNING-BRODERBUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING CO. TO ACQUIRE BRODERBUND SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Learning Co. said Monday that it had agreed
to acquire Broderbund Software Inc., a rival producer of
educational software, in a stock swap valued at $420 million.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is the latest and largest in a new wave of
consolidation in the educational and consumer software market.
Through a series of acquisitions and aggressive marketing tactics,
the Learning Co. and Cendant Software Inc., which includes the old
Davidson and Knowledge Adventure brands, have emerged as powerful
runners-up to the Microsoft Corporation in this part of the
software business.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund, despite popular titles like ``Myst'' and the Carmen
Sandiego series, has struggled in recent years, hurt by the
Learning Co.'s and Cendant's price cuts and by its own failures to
generate fresh products.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Broderbund said it expected to report a loss for
the third quarter, ended on May 31, and that it had retained the
investment banking firm of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette to explore
strategic alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund ``has been getting squeezed, and the irony of it is
they've been getting squeezed by Learning Company,'' said Stephen
Fleming, an analyst with Banc-America Robertson Stephens. ``Now
that Learning Company owns them, you will probably see a more
constructive, collaborative effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Learning Co. shares closed today at $24.875, down 12.5 cents,
while Broderbund shares rose $2.25, to close at $18.75, both in
Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the deal, the Learning Company will issue
0.80 of a share for each of Broderbund's 21 million shares
outstanding. Based on Learning Co.'s closing stock price of $25 on
Friday, the deal values Broderbund at $20 a share, or $420 million.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin O'Leary, the Learning Co.'s president, said the combined
business ``will have access to a data base of over 20 million
registered end-users who have purchased one of our products and
desire to hear about more offerings, which will allow us to build
our presence in the online and Internet channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Broderbund, which is based in Novato, Calif.,
fought a losing battle with Softkey International, based in
Cambridge Mass., to acquire the old Learning Co., creator of the
Reader Rabbit educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   Softkey took the name Learning Co. and, through the aggressive
use of debt financing and stock swaps, built a portfolio of leading
consumer and educational software titles.
</P>
<P>
   Broderbund's chairman and co-founder, Douglas G. Carlston, has
voted to approve the acquisition, the companies said, as have the
Learning Co.'s major shareholders, the Thomas H. Lee Co. and Bain
Capital Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
