<HEADER>
A2067 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROKENHEART24-COX     06-23 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROKENHEART24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Healing teen-age heartache
 &HT;    By Ricardo Gandara
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Catherine Fohn remembers sitting on her
daughter's bed _ the 14-year-old's heart was broken for the first
time _ and no words would come out. Just tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to hold her like a baby to tell her everything would
be OK, but I couldn't,'' the mother says. ``Instead, I was in
shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Unknowingly, Fohn's compassion helped her daughter. All too
often, however, parents fumble their way through dealing with a
child who has been hurt in a relationship. They say or do the wrong
things. It's a critical time for pre-adolescents and teen-agers
because they are seeking support and understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, I told Sarah how much I loved her,'' says the mother of
seven children, ages 5 to 19. ``I wanted to convey that I had been
through this before. I explained that I didn't know why these
things happen''
</P>
<P>
   It helped Sarah. ``She listened, cried, hugged me and gave me
time to be alone,'' says the daughter, who will be a high school
sophomore this fall. ``The only thing she didn't understand is that
I would feel that way at 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Psychologist Carl Pickhardt says young love is a serious family
matter. ``Love at 13, it's just as powerful and to be respected as
love at 30,'' he says. ``The larger issue is that parents often
discount their children's feelings by saying, `Oh, they're just
children. What can they know?'''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah is doing fine now because she continued her friendships,
stayed focused in school and remained involved in her family. ``You
want a child to stay engaged in her relationships and activities in
school. This way, they are distracted,'' Pickhardt says.
</P>
<P>
   Family counselors say talking to a child and listening is
critical when dealing with a broken heart. The power of physical
contact _ holding a hand or giving a hug _ is not to be
underestimated. It makes a child feel loved and better prepared to
deal with rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's OK to cry with them,'' Catherine Fohn says.
</P>
<P>
   Love starts early, even before children become teen-agers. They
want the independence to explore life and relationships, but they
don't have the skills to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's time to cope with loss, girls deal better with
heartache than boys, Pickhardt says. ``Girls are more socialized.
They have more capacity to talk out their feelings. Thus they deal
with pain better and more directly. Boys don't have that history.
Boys are about proving themselves and competing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Melanie Price-Bennett agrees. She has a daughter, 18-year-old
Brandi, and a son, 15-year-old Carlisle. ``Boys have a hard time
letting parents be part of it. It is like pulling teeth,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   Her son was 12 when he and his first serious girlfriend mutually
decided to break it off. It was not until later that she learned of
the depth of his hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all came out through something else that happened,'' says
the mom. ``That's when I knew that he had been hurt bad. All of a
sudden, he was my vulnerable and sensitive little boy, not a big
tough guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pickhardt warns parents that boys don't cope well when they've
been dumped. ``Boys take it much harder and are often more
vulnerable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The psychologist who's written several books including
``Parenting a Teen-ager,'' says boys hide their feelings and can
display anger. ``He's at risk to act out on that anger by
threatening a girl, spreading rumors, vandalizing something and
even getting physical,'' Pickhardt says.
</P>
<P>
   Those are more reasons for parents not to ignore boys who have
had their hearts broken. If their behavior or comments suggest
anger, get professional help. Don't take threats of any kind
lightly.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Gandara is a staff writer for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
