</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2068 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEO-DOME24-COX     06-23 3555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEO-DOME24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dome on the range near Italy, Texas
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITALY, Texas _ The rest of the world is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The world sees square, where you see round. The world sees ugly,
where you see beauty _ for what could be more beautiful than an
egg, a breast, a supremely functional curve? Maybe the world sees
you as eccentric, even a kook, for isn't that usually the lot of
the visionary? You know that you're closer in spirit to Galileo
(from that other Italy) than to those extremists such as David
Koresh or the Republic of Texas types _ the ones who have given the
rugged individualism of the Lone Star State such an unfortunate
spin.
</P>
<P>
   You are a practical man, likely the most practical you know. As
the cliche would have it, you have built a better mousetrap _ in
this case, the dome as the progressively practical domicile _ and
you've been waiting a quarter-century for the world to beat a path
to your door.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, that door has been on the outskirts of Italy, an
hour's drive south of Dallas off Interstate 35, where the signpost
welcomes visitors to ``The Biggest Little Town in Texas.'' Your
workshops have drawn dreamers and schemers from coast to coast, and
from Puerto Rico to Saudi Arabia, most of them hoping to capitalize
on your vision of the future as dome sweet dome. They pay you $750
per workshop to have you show them how to build a dome on your
property _ so they then can build their own.
</P>
<P>
   Every time you read another newspaper headline about a tornado
destroying a town or a hurricane ravaging a region, you shake your
head at the tragic waste. Because you believe to the depths of your
soul that your domes will withstand conditions that turn
conventional homes to splinters.
</P>
<P>
   You are David B. South. You were raised in Idaho, where you
developed a boyhood interest in dome technology and invented the
process for what you would market as the Monolithic Dome. You
became a Texan by business philosophy. You originally followed your
dreams to California _ as so many do _ but found your enterprise
entangled in the red tape of a state enmeshed in bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have built in most of the states, and I really like the
business climate in Texas,'' explains the short, stocky and
good-humored South, a 59-year-old engineer and computer programmer
turned entrepreneur, as we sit in the three-domed business office
that serves as the nerve center of Dome Park. The office feels a
little like a futuristic cave. ``Texas is kind of a throwback: You
leave me alone, and I'll leave you alone. When you're doing
business, the handshake still means a lot more in Texas than it
does in some other places. ... You've got to have a place, and
Italy's as good as any.''
</P>
<P>
   From the exit off I-35, Dome Park looks like it's in the middle
of nowhere, just down the road from the inevitable Dairy Queen.
Italy is a few miles east, a town of less than 2,000. What does the
community think of its domed neighbor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect the community's a little incredulous, but I wasn't
really trying to get a response out of the community,'' South
replies. ``I came here as a place to do business.'' The perfect
shape
</P>
<P>
   From the highway, kids don't see it as a place to do business.
They see the seven domes strung together as a caterpillar, with the
face painted on the garage door, and they figure it for some sort
of playground or children's attraction. Maybe an insect equivalent
of Chuck E. Cheese. During the first few dozen times I drove past
it on trips to Dallas, I looked at the cowboy boots painted on the
side, kicking up their heels, and thought the place must be some
sort of peculiar roadhouse dancehall.
</P>
<P>
   At Dome Park, they call it Bruco: The Texas Italian Caterpillar;
``bruco'' is the Italian word for caterpillar. Inside Bruco is the
manufacturing plant where Monolithic Constructors makes what South
has dubbed the Airform. Let's think of the Airform as a big balloon
of untearable fabric _ the key to the entire concept of the
Monolithic Dome. Once the Airform is inflated, it is sprayed inside
with three inches of polyurethane foam insulation, reinforced with
steel rebar, which is then covered in concrete. The Airform
continues to serve as the structure's outer shell, a waterproof
membrane.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a pure dome, unlike the earlier and more prevalent
geodesic domes that first caught South's fancy. The early '50s
brainchild of R. Buckminster Fuller, the geodesic dome is actually
a series of flat surfaces, a bunch of connected triangles, in an
attempt to duplicate nature's ideal architectural model: the egg.
As dome enthusiasts have long recognized, no shape provides more
strength through less surface material. Where the geodesic dome
offers the illusion of curvature, South aspired to authentic
domedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they're sort of the same shape, they are vastly
different animals,'' he explains. ``Engineering-wise, the geodesic
is totally different, using square materials to make an
approximation of a dome. Monolithic, on the other hand, has very
little square materials involved. It's an actual, pure dome, smooth
like an egg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't invent the dome,'' he continues. ``We've been having
igloos and all kinds of domes for thousands of years. What I did is
invent this technology where we could inflate a balloon, go inside
the balloon, out of the weather, and then spray it with the
polyurethane, tie the rebar and spray it with concrete to give it
structure. And it's the symbiotic relationship of all these pieces
that I have my patents on.''
</P>
<P>
   Residential domes are the last frontier for South, who began by
building big industrial facilities, where the big money is. He
patented the process with his brothers Barry and Randy South in
1975. Appropriately enough for their native Idaho, their first dome
was a potato-storage building, 105 feet in diameter and 35 feet
tall. It has since become a factory for the manufacture of
waterbeds.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, South built his first dome home for his family, the
8,000-square foot ``Cliffdome'' on the banks of the Snake River.
The Souths' home was something of an Idaho tourist attraction,
drawing tens of thousands of visitors, as the nine South children
became adept at conducting impromptu tours. (One of those
offspring, Nanette, was crowned Miss Idaho in 1985.)
</P>
<P>
   David South subsequently split from his brothers, who continue
to conduct business from Idaho Falls as Dome Technology. That
business focuses mostly on the construction of industrial and other
facilities, while David has become more of a missionary _ training
builders, conducting workshops, selling Airforms, spreading the
word that the building of tomorrow is available today.
</P>
<P>
   In the compound outside Italy that serves as the research and
development site, there are domes wherever the eye turns _ from
storage sheds to one-room efficiencies to the 2,700-square-foot
``Charca Casa'' residence _ ``House by the Pond'' _ where South
lives with his wife, Judy. It is like living in a parallel universe
_ one in which all the square corners and right angles have been
rounded off. There is even a domed doghouse (which the Souths
couldn't resist when they saw it at Wal-Mart).
</P>
<P>
   ``The dome shape really confronts people,'' says 29-year-old
David South Jr., the company's information systems manager, who
lives down the road from his parents in a smaller dome. ``You
almost have to make a determination about it. When people are
confronted by a dome, they say, `Why would anyone want to live in
one?' And that opens the door for us to explain all the
advantages.''
</P>
<P>
   The Souths number those advantages like commandments: The dome
is air-tight, sound-proof, energy-efficient, virtually
indestructible and no more expensive to build than a conventional
home that isn't nearly as insulated or weather-resistant. The dome
makes a powerful statement of independence, in a world in which
conventional wisdom so often translates into conformist medi-
ocrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an embryonic industry,'' says South the father. ``It
just takes time. It'll never be pushed, but the more it's noticed,
the more we sell. We have to teach people how to build it, and then
we have to teach people that they want it. And then we teach more
people how to build it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people it's like what Wernher von Braun said ; `If you
want to have a baby, you can't get nine women pregnant for one
month.''' 'God's presence'
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, Rob Delamater became a dome convert through church.
In particular, Our Lady's Maronite Catholic Church on East 51st
Street, just north of the airport. Delamater was hired as project
manager for the construction of the domed church, which duplicates
the shape and spirit of an Old World Catholic Eastern Rite
cathedral. His research on dome construction led him to the
Internet, which led him to the Monolithic Dome (www.monolithic
dome.com)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is safe in all aspects and fire-resistant,
lightning-resistant, wind-resistant,'' says Delamater. ``They are
safer than any other building. There's nothing for the wind to grab
hold of.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to put this church on the Web as a model
church,'' he continues. ``It's an Old World church, and the dome
represents the head of Christ. It would have cost $80,000 for a
steel dome, but this one is only $45,000.''
</P>
<P>
   On the street adjacent to the construction site is a sign
reading ``Thou Shalt Not Park Here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our roots are in the Middle East, the Holy Land,'' says Father
Don Sawyer, the priest of the 200-family parish. ``Theologically,
contrary to Gothic style, this architecture represents that God is
with us _ like a mother hen, hovering. The dome is God's presence
among his people.''
</P>
<P>
   Contracted to build his first dome, Delamater assumes it won't
be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has all kinds of creativity that is left up to the
architect,'' says Delamater. ``It takes imagination not to make it
look like a ball in the ground. Other than that, it has all the
possibilities in the world.'' Where crackpots live Look inside a
domed home, and you're likely to find someone who considers himself
a maverick, a free thinker, maybe even a crackpot _ someone, at
least, who refuses to be confined by the boxes of conventional
society or even to live in one. If such folks are out of step with
the rest of the culture, they consider this a point of pride rather
than a source of worry. They figure that the rest of the culture is
just a few steps behind and will catch up eventually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're a little weird,'' says Ken Hanson, a former
elementary school principal who built his dream house last October
outside Hondo after he and his wife, Nola, both retired from the
San Antonio school district. ``I had always envisioned building a
dome. I really like the concept; they will withstand a 400-mph
wind, and we wanted something that is very energy-efficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody looked at us like we're crazy, but to me it made
more sense than building square or rectangle. You know, your head's
not a square, and God decided to put the most precious organ we've
got in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Quickly discovering that if ``you talk to an architect about a
dome, they have no concept; they've never been trained,'' the
Hansons found the road to domedom through a trip to Dallas, when
they saw the caterpillar and decided to stop on a whim. They
learned from South that another Texas retiree named Bill Click had
built his own dome in Bandera after attending a workshop, and that
he wanted to go into business building domes for others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had worked for 10 or 12 years trying to design an
energy-efficient home, before a friend introduced me to the
Monolithic Dome,'' says Click, a former welder and instructor for
Amoco Oil. ``Right away, I realized there was no way I could build
a conventional home that was anywhere near as insulated. Plus, it's
completely fire-resistant because it's all concrete. The real
attractions are the economics and the security of it. We're still
struggling with the insurance companies because they don't know how
to write a policy on a place with no roof, no fires and no need of
replacement costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Any other drawbacks?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's a little tough is the decorating,'' he
admits. ``You're not used to a curved wall, and it's hard to hang
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   The dome that Click built for himself has 1,734 square feet. The
home he built for the Hansons last October is a double dome
connected by a breezeway foyer with a little more than 1,800 square
feet. Hanson says their residence looks a little like a brassiere
from the air, and that they were thinking of painting nipples on
the domes to amuse pilots flying private planes into the nearby
airport. Click says he already has 12 more customers who are
interested in having him build dome homes for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are crazy not to build these,'' insists Hanson, a
former principal. ``The cost is recovered in 20 years (through
savings in utility bills), and the building will still be here in
500 years. If the people in Jarrell had built these, there wouldn't
have been any casualties.'' A conspiracy theory 'In engineering,
you always want to simplify,'' said Walter Burnham, owner of the
Rocky Mountain Dome Co., which he started three years ago in Idaho
after years of building subdivisions through conventional
construction. ``Instead of having 30,000 different pieces, we've
only got four materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnham became a convert to dome technology through his
experiences from rebuilding in areas that had been struck by
disaster. ``I knew that something had to happen after seeing all
those schools devastated and churches leveled,'' he continued. A
self-described UFOlogist, he believes that the dome is the shape of
progress, a progress impeded through a conspiracy of corporations
that have too much to lose in profit if the simplicity of the dome
prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're living in a land of image, and image says that an old
house with a point on top is home,'' he says. ``We're going up
against these corporate giants that have invested billions of
dollars in promoting the idea that `This is the home.' '' Waiting
for disaster Those who peer into the future and see a sea of
spheres where boxed homes used to be figure that we can't be more
than a few natural disasters and an energy crisis from popular
domedom. They see that domes have increasingly become the norm for
new construction of arenas and stadiums. (The Austin Ice Bats are
the latest team looking to build a ``monolithic-type dome,'' says
organization president Ed Novess, on Auditorium Shores or
elsewhere.)
</P>
<P>
   Domophiles believe that the brave, new world of residential
development is just around the corner. They talk of homes that can
withstand tornado winds and bomb detonations, of energy efficiency
that can cut utility bills in half.
</P>
<P>
   So, why doesn't everybody want to live in a dome?
</P>
<P>
   Because, South admits, it looks like a dome. When you've lived
since birth in a world that is square, there's considerable
resistance to coming around to round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're born and slapped on the butt and dropped into a square
crib,'' South says. ``And from then on, we live in a square world.
We've just gotten used to square _ square beds, square rooms,
everything is square. People like to go to church in a
unique-looking building, or to sporting events. They love to go to
a Hyatt hotel because it's unique inside. But where they live, they
are more fashion-conscious, and they want to stay closer to what
they're used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a long time to convert mama to a dome,'' he
continues. ``But since we've been down here, there have been a
significant number of women who will drag their husband in here and
say, `Honey, this is what I want.' Because she's worried about
safety first, energy efficiency second, and what it looks like
third. You ask me what will be the driving force? One of these days
we're going to have a natural disaster, like a hurricane that will
come ashore and kill 10,000 or 100,000 people. And that will be the
driving force.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that you're rooting for a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no, no,'' says South the son with a laugh. ``But what we
figure is, if a tornado is going to land, let it be on our
building.'' The money problem 'You just have to overcome the fears
of these buildings, the marketability,'' says Gary Clark, the
company's vice president of construction, as he leads a couple of
dozen workshop attendees through the construction of a dome. ``If
the average Joe America wants to find a loan company that will
finance a dome, it can be a problem. Who would buy the dome if you
wanted to sell it?''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge of getting a conventional mortgage is that a
property's value is typically determined by ``comps'' _ the price
for which comparable houses in the area have been selling ,
typically three comps within the previous six months. Since domed
homes are often unique to an area, there are no comps through which
to determine their resale value.
</P>
<P>
   Those who build must either pay cash, put down a heftier than
usual down payment or indulge in creative financing. An
architectural dome enthusiast in Arizona is offering free plans to
any developer who will build a subdivision of at least 150 homes,
figuring the concept will then spread like seeds in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks want to see how many similar houses have been sold,''
Clark continues. ``And people who build domes don't sell them ;
they live in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Who are these people?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have individuals who are not trying to follow the standard
mold,'' he responds. ``We have people who are interested in it for
ecological aspects. We have people who are interested because of
self-sufficiency and safety. We have engineers interested in the
designer aspects. And we have retirees on a fixed income who are
interested in keeping their utility bills low.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have a lot of people who say, `I'd really be
interested if they just didn't look like domes.' Well, you can make
a dome look awfully attractive. All you have to do is throw a lot
of money at it.'' Deluxe dome home
</P>
<P>
   To that end, discussion inevitably turns to the ``Eye of the
Storm,'' the Taj Mahal of Domedom, the residence that Huiet and
Helen Paul built on Sullivans Island, S.C., after Hurricane Hugo
destroyed their previous home. It's a two-story, four-level
structure with a curved (naturally) staircase in its center, and it
encloses 5,000 square feet of living space. It cost more than
$600,000 to build, and sits on a lot valued at $625,000.
</P>
<P>
   See, say the dome enthusiasts, the Pauls could have built
anything, and they chose this. It has since withstood two lesser
hurricanes that found Sullivans Island evacuated. Except for the
Pauls, who felt safer in the ``Eye of the Storm'' than they would
have fleeing from it. An igloo or a shoebox? 'I've seen plenty of
estate homes that cost $500,000 or $600,000 that are virtual clones
of each other,'' says Michael Wesley, an Austin-based information
technology consultant who attended a recent workshop in Italy with
hopes of building his own dome and starting a business to build
others. ``With domes, everyone can be as creative as your
imagination. Builders don't want anything to do with it because
they don't want to change their standard way of doing things.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think, `Why would I want to live in an igloo?' My
argument to that is, `Why do I want to live in a shoebox?' ''
</P>
<P>
   How did Wesley become a convert?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd been looking more at geodesic structures, but I subscribe
to Dome Magazine, saw an ad for Monolithic Domes, and they just
seemed like an easier way to build,'' he replies. ``It's a very
simple process. There's an Airform to inflate, some concrete to
mix, some foam to mix, and that's just about it. At the workshop,
we got plenty of hands-on experience, with the opportunity to
understand the entire process and to network.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to teach and train and push, push, keep on
pushing,'' says South, using the lunch break of his long workshop
day to preach the gospel of the dome. ``At one time, I wanted to
build all the domes, and it can't be done. The only way we're going
to see it done is to get a thousand dome builders. My goal is to
see the domes being used. When we made the decision to train and
teach, it did two things simultaneously. It gave us a bigger pool
of builders, but it also gave us a bigger pool of salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are going to run around and go into the school
boards and pound on the desks, and there'll be a lot of domes sold.
Unfortunately, it has taken a little longer than I thought, but
it'll come.''
</P>
<P>
   When?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe not in my lifetime, but it'll happen,'' he insists.
``It's gotta happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the domed cave that serves as an office, the future is
already here. If you are David B. South, you can close your eyes
and see domes all over the countryside, eggshells where little
boxes used to be _ developments, neighborhoods, entire cities of
domes. If the rest of the world continues to think square, you know
that this is a mass delusion. For you know that the world is round.
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese is a staff writer for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
