A2073 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-FORCEONE24-COX     06-23 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCEONE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``If history had wings . . .''
 &HT;    By Dale Huffman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A woman in a pink dress with white daisies, who
remembered when President John F. Kennedy's body was flown from
Dallas to Washington, D.C., in the plane, spoke quietly, almost
reverently to her female companion. ``If the insides of this plane
could only talk. My goodness, the stories we would hear.''
</P>
<P>
   The two were among about 900 who visited the U.S. Air Force
Museum to tour the original Air Force One and to take a personal
look at the plane that winged presidents around the world.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Vice President Al Gore, who made the last official state
flight aboard this Air Force One last March said, ``If history had
wings, it would be this aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Some call the Boeing 707, which traveled more than 5 million
miles since it was put into service in 1962, the world's most
famous aircraft. After serving presidents, heads of state and world
dignitaries for 36 years, the plane called Special Air Mission
26000 by the Air Force is open for public inspection in the Air
Force Museum annex.
</P>
<P>
   The plane promises to be a star attraction.
</P>
<P>
   As the steady line of folks worked their way through the plane's
aisles, protected with plastic windows from ceiling to floor to
keep visitors from touching furniture or equipment, you hear the
same thoughts repeated in different ways: ``I think that is where
President Johnson stood when he was sworn in after President
Kennedy was shot. I think that is where President Kennedy's casket
was put. I think that is where Jackie Kennedy sat on the way back
from Dallas still wearing that blood-splattered dress.''
</P>
<P>
   The fateful Dallas trip in November 1963 when President Kennedy
was assassinated and President Johnson sworn into office will stand
out as the plane's most memorable hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of history here,'' said Orville Howard, 72, to
his grandson, Tim Fox, 12. They had come from Frankfort, Ind., to
see the plane. ``I wanted Tim to see this. For those of us who
remember the dark days when President Kennedy was assassinated,
this brings a bit of closure, in a way. And it is just amazing to
think of the famous people who have been on this incredible plane.
So much history here.''
</P>
<P>
   Cy and Audrey Laughter plan to visit the plane soon. The
Laughters were supporters and friends of President Richard Nixon,
and remember the time they had lunch on the plane as it was parked
at Andrews Air Force Base in 1969. ``It was a gift from President
Nixon to us to lunch there,'' Laughter said. ``The plane brings
back many memories for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferdinand McElroy, 32, of Springfield brought his two kids and
two neighborhood youngsters to see the famous plane Monday. ``I
think it is important for the young ones to have a sense of
history,'' McElroy said. ``Things happened on this plane that
shaped the future of our world.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Works, on hand as a greeter for visitors to the plane, said
she is moved every time she boards the plane. ``I get a chill,''
she said. ``There's something about it that just gets you.''
</P>
<P>
   E CONTACT Dale Huffman at 225-2272 or e-mail him at
dale_huffmancoxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
