<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DONATED-EMBRYOS24-COX     06-23 0361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DONATED-EMBRYOS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Donated frozen embryos save Florida couple from childlessness
 &HT;    By Eliot Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ A couple has been selected to receive six
frozen embryos offered for donation last December and will have
them implanted in late July, according to the lawyer who conducted
a nationwide search.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Charlotte Danciu would not identify the couple except
to say they aren't from South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   A Broward County couple who identified themselves only as Donna
and Ron offered last December to donate the embryos, frozen for
seven years after Donna had one child from an implantation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's very excited,'' Danciu said. ``We want to
encourage other people to do this. These were the ones, and it
worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Danciu said she received about 50 legitimate inquiries. Many
were eliminated for medical reasons or because they didn't meet the
couple's requirement that any children be raised in a Christian
family. Interviews determined the final cut.
</P>
<P>
   Danciu also said other couples have since inquired about
donating embryos.
</P>
<P>
   The donation comes as the medical industry wrestles with the
ethics of infertility, a $2 billion-a-year business. While selling
embryos for profit violates medical ethics rules, some clinics
reportedly sell eggs left by patients and fertilized by donor sperm
to desperate couples. Ethicists have said the practice could lead
to ``designer babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron, a 43-year-old production manager, and Donna, a 41-year-old
homemaker, had tried for 15 years to conceive. In 1989, doctors
fertilized 15 embryos and implanted four. One took: young Ronnie
was born in May 1990.
</P>
<P>
   It was a difficult pregnancy, and Donna almost died, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple concluded they wouldn't try again, but they did
nothing about the nine remaining embryos, which were frozen. Donna
later learned a vial containing three embryos had broken, and the
clinic planned to begin charging $600 a year for storage.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the couple decided to give the embryos away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1120EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
