<HEADER>
A2081 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN24-COX     06-23 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: So much for vacations...
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio. The toughest part of being a schoolteacher is
summer vacation. Sounds a little odd, I know, but it's the truth.
Too
</P>
<P>
   much free time. Too many decisions to make.
</P>
<P>
   The most strenuous one of all is about getting up in the morning
- as in when to, or even whether to. I love not having to wake up
at 5:45
</P>
<P>
   with Big Ben jitterbugging in my ear and I look forward to
summer when my sleeping arrangements move from a sensible, indoor
bed to a hammock
</P>
<P>
   on the upstairs screened porch. I can snooze away in the
treetops enjoying the nighttime skies and sounds. The luxury of
cool evenings and
</P>
<P>
   good books bids me stay awake a little longer. No wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, my bucolic reveries are invariably short-lived because
just as I'm settling down, my back yard is coming to life.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere around the witching hour, the `possum comes for a
drink but since he's too short and can't fly, it's impossible for
him to reach
</P>
<P>
   the birdbath - even on tippytoes (I've watched him). That's when
the dish gets shoved off of its pedestal and lands with a
resounding thud
</P>
<P>
   upside down in the pansies. First time it happened, I scrambled
out the wrong side of the hammock just in time to see Mr. Possum's
fat backside
</P>
<P>
   waddling off into the herb garden.
</P>
<P>
   Three nights in a row I was jump-started out of a sound sleep by
a thirsty `possum. Belatedly, good sense set in. Why not give him
his own
</P>
<P>
   water dish? That old crock in the garage would be just the
ticket. I cleaned it, filled it, and put it next to the birdbath.
And it worked.
</P>
<P>
   No more crashes in the night...but!
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever heard a `possum drink? ``Shluurp! Shlooop! Slop!
Slop!'' The first night I heard the racket, I pulled the comforter
over
</P>
<P>
   my head figuring Godzilla was on the loose and had decided to
make my backyard his refuge. ``Shlop! Shluurp!'' I couldn't help
but wonder: How
</P>
<P>
   thirsty can a dinosaur get?
</P>
<P>
   Serene summer's evenings, when the sun is setting and the
neighbors have stopped torturing me with steaks-on-the-grill
smells,
</P>
<P>
   just beg to have windows flung open and doors onto screened
porches left ajar to welcome the night air. My cats like it too. By
nature they are
</P>
<P>
   nocturnal creatures, but by edict (mine) they are also
housebound, and so the closest they come to experiencing nature in
the raw is through
</P>
<P>
   the screens - usually on the downstairs back porch which just
happens to be directly under my sleeping aerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rrroooowww! Spaat! Hissst!'' It's four in the morning and the
girls (Stella, a 13-year-old white, and Biddy, a 9-year-old mouthy
</P>
<P>
   Siamese) are having a little disagreement with a gentleman
caller from a couple of houses down. I give them five minutes to
settle it or until I
</P>
<P>
   hear the sound of claws climbing screens, before I roll out and
go to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Woo-wow!'' That's the interloper. ``Wooo-oo!'' I think he's
telling the ladies how good looking he thinks they are and asking
them to come
</P>
<P>
   out for a moonlight frog chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eee-YOW!'' That's Biddy shrieking like a fishwife.
Translation: Get your fuzzy feets off my back steps RIGHT NOW, you
ugly hairball! The
</P>
<P>
   girls ain't long on manners. I intervene before the neighbors
start throwing old shoes at all of us. ``Go home, Mr. Thomas,'' I
holler. He's
</P>
<P>
   surprised to hear a people voice from somewhere in the treetops
and skedaddles. I roll over and pull the comforter back over my
head. It's
</P>
<P>
   cold out here.
</P>
<P>
   At exactly 5:45 I hear footsteps approaching. Clomp! Stomp! Onto
the sleeping porch. There's a scurrying sound as Biddy turns three
</P>
<P>
   circles before making a pass at the porch rail. Scuttle! Scrape!
Thump! She misses and goes back in the house to soothe her dignity
and pretend
</P>
<P>
   it never happened. She'll be back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I feel eyes on me which is a little unnerving
considering I'm abed and most improperly attired. I peek out and
there's
</P>
<P>
   a squirrel hanging by his toenails from the gutter, watching me.
I blink. He clucks.
</P>
<P>
   Galumph! Scrabble! Thunk! Biddy's back and she's made it onto
the rail. The squirrel doesn't move. His chatter gets louder. More
footsteps
</P>
<P>
   approach. Stella has left her favorite bunny-watching basement
window and come to join the fun. She makes the rail in one pass -
thanks to
</P>
<P>
   agility and the fact that she weighs only half what her Siamese
sister does.
</P>
<P>
   Now, both cats are chatting up one very vocal and absolutely
fearless squirrel...and I'm wide awake. ``I might as well try to
sleep in
</P>
<P>
   a zoo,'' I mumble as I roll over and try to squeeze out an extra
five minutes. Nobody's listening.
</P>
<P>
   So much for decisions.
</P>
<P>
   And so much for vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
