 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY COMMENTARY BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These columns for release Wednesday, June 24, 1998, are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Oh, those wacky congressional Republicans. House
Republicans vote to do away with the entire, complete, whole
federal tax system of the United States of America in just five
short years, and the same day Senate Republicans, as a public
health service, prove that tobacco really, really is addictive.
(Teepen, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MSKUBE-COLUMN _ I go where they tell me to go, so I'm packing
for a trip to Central America, although it rather sounds like metro
Atlanta. There's a difference between a tourist and a real
traveler, and I know which one I am. Show me your ruins. Where's
your best restaurant? Pulitzer winner Michael Skube's weekly
lifestyle commentary. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
6/22.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio. The toughest part of being a
schoolteacher issummer vacation. Sounds a little odd, I know, but
it's the truth. Too much free time. Too many decisions to make.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Over all these years, I've misspelled names
and places, and gotten dates wrong, even matched the wrong person
with an event. And made some bad decisions. But never
intentionally. Neither have any of the people I've worked with. All
this comes to mind because of Patricia Smith, the Boston Globe
columnist and Pulitzer Prize finalist, who was exposed recently as
fabricating quotes, people and events, and forced to resign.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service) MOVED. EMBARGOED UNTIL 6/24.
</P>
