<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, June 24, 1998, are
moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Highlights of tomorrow's TV viewing.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   GEO-DOMES _ ITALY, Texas _ You are a practical man, and you've
been waiting a quarter-century for the world to beat a path to your
door. Since 1990, that door has been on the outskirts of Italy, an
hour's drive south of Dallas off Interstate 35, where the signpost
welcomes visitors to ``The Biggest Little Town in Texas.'' Your
geodesic dome workshops have drawn dreamers and schemers from coast
to coast, and from Puerto Rico to Saudi Arabia, most of them hoping
to capitalize on your vision of the future as dome sweet dome. They
pay you $750 per workshop to have you show them how to build a dome
on your property _ so they then can build their own. (McLeese,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCEONE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A woman spoke quietly, almost
reverently to her female companion. ``If the insides of this plane
could only talk. My goodness, the stories we would hear.'' The two
were among about 900 who visited the U.S. Air Force Museum to tour
the original Air Force One and to take a personal look at the plane
that winged presidents around the world. (Huffman, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLAHEAT-CATTLE _ TALLAHASSEE _ Florida's cattle ranchers will
likely become the latest victims of the state's continuing heat
wave, adding to the $80 million in crops already lost this summer,
Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford said. ``We have not been this
desperate in Florida in 50 years.'' (Date, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LAMBORGHINI-SUED _ FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ John Martin, 31, of
Fort Lauderdale, filed a lawsuit in federal court charging the
Automobili Lamborghini company, maker of his 1997 Diablo Roadster
model, with knowingly selling him a defective car. (Hiaasen, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DONATED-EMBRYOS _ BOCA RATON _ A couple has been selected to
receive six frozen embryos offered for donation last December and
will have them implanted in late July, according to the lawyer who
conducted a nationwide search. Attorney Charlotte Danciu would not
identify the couple except to say they aren't from South Florida.
(Kleinberg, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BROKENHEART _ Family counselors say talking to a child and
listening is critical when dealing with a first broken heart. The
power of physical contact _ holding a hand or giving a hug _ is not
to be underestimated. It makes a child feel loved and better
prepared to deal with rejection. (Gandara, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (d category)
</P>
<P>
   0624READY _ Dayton's Ready Food Review panel gives the word on
flat chicken. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   0624GOOD _ Food shorts. (Heller, Dayton Daily News) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   TECHTOOLS _ ATLANTA -- I haven't looked at Microsoft Publisher
in several years, and my first glimpse of Publisher 98 was
something of a shock; it appeared to have been dumbed down rather
severely. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/22.
</P>
<P>
   TECHREPORT _ But times have changed. Now there are cordless
phones for home and wireless phones for the road. Along with those
advances come some potential problems. For instance, you can't be
in two places at once -- at least, not yet -- and if you are on the
road, you're missing calls at home. Oh, sure, you have an answering
machine or voice mail, but to get the messages you'll either have
to go home or remember to dial in. (Kanell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/22.
</P>
<P>
   CYBERSCENE _ ATLANTA -- Long before there were brave surfers
navigating cyberspace, there were men -- and women -- who went to
sea in boats. Whether you are an old hand or just now considering
taking up boating, you can use the sea of information on the World
Wide Web to set a fun and safe course. (Husted, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/22.
</P>
<P>
   JUSTFORFUN _ ALTANTA _ The Velo 500 from Philips is a hand-held
PC whose price and functions land it midway between a personal
digital assistant and a laptop PC. Using Windows CE (the pared-down
version of Windows) as the operating system and 24 megabytes of
memory, the Velo can perform many of the tasks of a portable PC,
including light word processing, connecting to the Internet and
sending and receiving e-mail. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED 6/22.
</P>
<P>
   MACNEWS _ ATLANTA -- If you're looking for a powerful yet
inexpensive alternative to Microsoft's Word 98, check out Nisus
Writer. You can try out Nisus Writer by downloading a free demo
from the company's Web site at
http://www.nisus.com/nisus(underscore)writer.html. Give it try
before automatically opting for Word 98. (Haddad, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED 6/22.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
