   In Korea, where American and Chinese troops once battled, we are
now working together with China in the Four Party Talks aimed at
finally realizing a permanent peace on the peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   China has also released on medical parole to the United States
such prominent dissidents as Wei Jingsheng and Wang Dan, signed the
U.N. Covenant on Economic, Social, and Cultural Rights, and has
pledged to sign the U.N. Covenant on Civil and Political Rights.
</P>
<P>
   However, many differences remain. We continue to push for more
progress on our nonproliferation, trade, human rights and energy
and environment agendas. Clinton's visit offers an opportunity to
energetically press for such progress. Meanwhile, we have seen
China move in the right direction, toward greater acceptance of
international norms.
</P>
<P>
   In our determination to address these challenges, we must not
ignore the achievements. And to make further progress, expand
cooperation and advance our national interests, we should continue
our engagement with the Chinese people and government through firm,
forceful and patient diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   On regional and global issues, in the areas of nonproliferation,
economic cooperation and even human rights _ where much more
progress is still needed _ the achievements are real, and our
policy is working.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Madeleine Albright is the U.S. secretary of state. She wrote
this article for ``The Challenge of China,'' a project of MSNBC and
New York University's Center for War, Peace and the Media.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
