<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-US-FRIENDSHIP-N     06-23 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-US-FRIENDSHIP-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 WHY AMERICA and CHINA MUST BE FRIENDS  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089.  By LI ZHAOXING  
 c.1998 MSNBC and the Center for War, Peace and the News Media  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   We are at the threshold of a new millennium. Since the end of
the Cold War, the world has undergone profound changes. The
international situation on the whole is moving toward greater
relaxation. Peace and development, economic prosperity and social
progress _ all these have become the common desire of all nations
and the imperatives of our times.
</P>
<P>
   But there still exist many destabilizing factors in the world.
The planet we call home is far from a tranquil and peaceful land.
How to bring a peaceful, stable and prosperous world into the 21st
century is a huge challenge facing all of us.
</P>
<P>
   China and the United States are two great nations. One is the
largest developing country and the other is the largest developed
country. Both are permanent members of the U.N. Security Council.
The two countries share common interests in maintaining peace and
stability both in Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   We share great responsibilities in promoting global economic
cooperation, preventing proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction, cracking down on international terrorism, drug
trafficking, cross-border crimes and many other areas.
</P>
<P>
   There is huge potential for cooperation between China and the
United States in the areas of economic cooperation and trade,
science and technology, education, culture, energy, environmental
protection, legal and military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent nuclear crisis in South Asia, China and the
United States had very fruitful cooperation and reached a common
strategy in dealing with the situation. In the ongoing Asian
financial crisis, China and the United States have conducted
dialogues on several occasions and contributed a great deal in
their respective ways to stabilize the financial situation in the
region, which has won wide appreciation and acclaim from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   These developments demonstrate that the strategic importance of
China and the United States has not diminished, but increased. The
potential for both countries to cooperate in various fields is
expanding, not dwindling.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government attaches great importance to China-U.S.
relations and places it on top of its foreign-relations agenda.
Over the years, China has made tremendous efforts to improve and
develop this important connection because we believe maintaining a
sound and stable linkage between the two countries not only serves
the interests of our two peoples but also the peace and development
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, as we differ in social system, history, cultural
background and level of economic development, it is natural that
there are differences between us. The key is that these differences
should be bridged or narrowed through dialogue on the basis of
equality and mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   If we cannot resolve them immediately, we should put them aside
and not let them stand in the way of seeking common ground and
further strengthening our ties. We should learn to agree to
disagree.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan is the most important and most sensitive issue in
China-U.S. relations and is at the heart of the three joint
communiques between our two nations. U.S. leaders have reaffirmed
on many occasions America's commitment to the ``one China'' policy
and to the three joint communiques.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has also undertaken that it does not support
``two Chinas'' or ``one China, one Taiwan,'' it does not support
the ``independence of Taiwan,'' and it does not support Taiwan's
entry into the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   History shows that if the Taiwan question is handled improperly,
it can be the biggest obstacle to the sound growth of our ties. It
is our hope that the United States will honor its commitment on the
question of Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   It is very unfortunate that at the moment when China and the
United States were intensively preparing for the visit to China by
President Bill Clinton, we heard some noises in China-U.S.
relations. Some people even spread rumors and fabricated stories
with ulterior political motives. This is really an appalling
development.
</P>
<P>
   We hope that the political leaders in both China and the United
States should once again show their wisdom, courage and strategic
vision, as did our leaders in early '70s. We should work together
to overcome the interference and, relying on the consensus reached
between our respective leaders, expand our common ground, increase
trust, reduce difference and press forward toward our goal: to
bring a stable, healthy China-U.S. relationship into the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Li Zhaoxing is China's ambassador to the United States. He
wrote this article for ``The Challenge of China,'' a project of
MSNBC and the New York University Center for War, Peace and the
News Media.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
