<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2175 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-COMPLEX-CHANGIN     06-23 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COMPLEX-CHANGING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWARD A U.S.-CHINA BALANCE OF POWER FOR THE 21ST CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT SCALAPINO  
 c.1998 MSNBC and the Center for War, Peace and the News Media  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   On the eve of President Bill Clinton's visit to China, he is
being admonished not to visit Tiananmen Square, site of the 1989
bloodshed, and to press Beijing to permit full religious freedom
and other human rights.
</P>
<P>
   By overwhelming votes, the House has voted to ban the sale of
missile and satellite technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Clinton will be balancing a complex array of competing
interests on his China trip. But this is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
   China has long been a contentious and prominent subject of
debate in American domestic politics. The debate over who ``lost''
China spawned McCarthyism in the early 1950s. Open conflict in
Korea between China and the United States intensified the
bitterness. It took two figures with unassailable anti-Communist
credentials, Richard Nixon and Henry Kissinger, to begin the
process of normalization, powerfully aided by the Cold War and
Beijing's growing apprehensions about Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre of pro-democracy demonstrators in Tiananmen Square
caused a resurgence of American anger. Thus, candidates Clinton and
Gore used China against President George Bush in l992, accusing him
of coddling dictators. Today, it is Clinton who is accused by
critics of appeasing Beijing and risking security breaches by
authorizing the sale of high-tech products having military
applicability.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when U.S.-China relations can affect the entire
Asia-Pacific region _ including such crucial issues as North and
South Korea, nuclear proliferation and the Asian economic crisis _
domestic politics guarantees that the relationship will remain
controversial.
</P>
<P>
   On China, there are many and varied domestic constituencies. An
important portion of the American business community _ the aircraft
industry, electronics firms and other high-tech operations _ have
long lobbied for fuller access to the China market, citing the
policies of other nations and the advantages of a China that is
increasingly linked to the international marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Agricultural producers also have a strong interest in the China
market. These forces are heard when the yearly issue of renewal of
Most Favored Nation treatment is debated.
</P>
<P>
   Among conservatives, however, there is a strong anti-China
strain and a tendency to cast China in relatively static,
absolutist terms. More importantly, human-rights groups that span
the political spectrum _ joined by a significant portion of the
U.S. media _ scrutinize China's human-rights record.
</P>
<P>
   These groups remain unsatisfied with ``token actions'' such as
the release of dissidents like Wang Dan. Tibet is an issue evoking
powerful feelings, driven by an understanding that Tibetan culture
as well as civil rights are being progressively crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating the picture is Taiwan, which enjoys a
generally favorable image in the United States as a society that
has successfully combined economic growth and democracy, and hence
should have its desires recognized.
</P>
<P>
   Only a minority of American scholars and journalists espouse the
``China threat'' position, arguing that confrontation is inevitable
with an emerging, assertive China. Most accept a more complex view,
seeing China as capable of taking diverse roads in the future, with
American policy being a potentially significant factor in
determining which road.
</P>
<P>
   They argue that it is desirable to build a mix of incentives and
deterrents to promote regional and global cooperation. They assert
that efforts at containment would isolate the United States, not
China, and abet the extremist cause.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing came to a fuller recognition of the nature of American
politics long after Taiwan. Hence, its attention to the U.S.
Congress and public has grown recently, along with questions about
the tactics used in seeking greater influence, an issue earlier
raised with respect to the Taiwan lobby.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, both Beijing and Taipei are now engaged in seeking
support at many levels within U.S. society. Meanwhile, in China,
domestic politics is also a factor in foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, among whom certain military and senior party
officials are to be included, remain skeptical of close ties with
the United States, citing the risks of ``spiritual pollution.'' And
the current force of a resurgent Chinese nationalism makes itself
felt within the younger generation and among Chinese intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, criticism of America's purported effort to maintain ``a
unipolar world'' is coupled with an oft-repeated insistence that
there must be no interference in China's internal affairs. The
sovereignty of the nation-state must be absolute.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Chinese pragmatists welcome the decline in ideological
barriers to the outside, and the growing interaction with their
American counterparts. And they are becoming more vocal.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in both the United States and China, internal divisions
and debate over our bilateral relations will continue. Yet it is
likely that the governments of the two nations will opt for
policies that seek to maximize cooperation, while subjecting
differences to extensive negotiations. Mutual criticisms, official
and unofficial, will be voiced.
</P>
<P>
   Yet America will increasingly recognize that China is changing.
Leninism is giving way to authoritarian pluralism. Politics is
still controlled in varying degree, but a civil society apart from
the state is emerging, with diverse interests being voiced. The
economy is increasingly mixed, with the private sector rising in
importance. Communication with such a society is possible.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, U.S.-China relations will reflect a broader and
more complex pattern of international relations. In the 21st
century, on a widening range of issues _ from economics and
security to the environment _ nations like the United States and
China will be able to fashion common policies, working together,
both bilaterally and multilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   But given the unresolved issues, nationalist passions and
political divisions, the simultaneous maintenance of a balance of
power is required to discourage a resort to force.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on this combination, and counting also on the domestic
problems that will take priority and the growing economic
interdependence of all nations, we can hopefully relegate to
history the global wars of the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Robert Scalapino is Robson research professor of government
emeritus at the University of California, Berkeley. This article
was written for ``The Challenge of China,'' a project of MSNBC and
the New York University Center for War, Peace and the News Media.) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
