<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTAL ROLE CAN'T BE A PASSIVE ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ An update on adolescent hijinks in suburban
Albany:
</P>
<P>
   _ A high school junior is charged with a misdemeanor after,
according to the police, he sent an e-mail to the mayor of Cohoes,
threatening to kill him. And, the police say, after the kid
threatened to gun down his classmates.
</P>
<P>
   His father's response: ``This is a big joke. This is a very good
son, and everything is all right.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Five seniors are accused of slipping into Duanesburg High
School through a window after hours and breaking into the lockers
of other students.
</P>
<P>
   The response of the parents of one kid: ``They removed only
school-owned textbooks ... from lockers and stacked them on the
school-owned floor of the school-owned cafeteria, not taking them
off school premises. Explain to us how that becomes a burglary in
the third degree?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Seventeen seniors break into Bethlehem High School. According
to the police, they destroyed a dozen classroom locks, damaged 10
desks, plugged up two drinking fountains and poured cooking oil on
the tile floors of several corridors.
</P>
<P>
   Total damage _ about $3,200. When the kids were barred from
graduation exercises, the reaction of the parent of one high school
student was: ``It seems to me that the administration's response
has not carefully weighed the potential impact on the lives of
these students ... Are we as parents and educators willing to hold
ourselves blameless when behavioral anomalies result in destructive
events?''
</P>
<P>
   As the school year winds down, things like this are happening
all over the country. High school kids are getting weird, and their
parents are getting even weirder. All of which, I think, raises
this crucial question:
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it time for this society to require a license for
parenting? After all, in most places you need a license to raise a
dog. Raising a kid is less important? Or, at least, shouldn't there
be some test _ even an oral _ to determine if a would-be parent
knows right from wrong and possesses some small inclination to
transmit that information to a boneheaded, hormone-soaked
adolescent?
</P>
<P>
   Having raised two kids _ and possessing a finely-honed
appreciation of how challenging that chore can be, especially
during their teen-age years _ I never cease to be amazed at the
attitudes some parents adopt when their kids do something stupid,
destructive and/or dangerous to others. Not to mention when those
kids commit serious crimes in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Take the kids last year who burglarized Burnt Hills-Ballston
Lake High in the Albany suburbs to keep the school from opening
after Christmas break. One set of parents fought that suspension
all the way to the New York state education commissioner. Take the
parents in Fultonville-Fonda, another Albany suburban area, who
were infuriated when the school board tried to keep a few would-be
bombers off the high school football squad. Hey, say parents like
this, boys will be boys, won't they? After all, they're just kids.
</P>
<P>
   Well, Billy the Kid was a kid; that's why they called him that.
Before a lawman named Pat Garrett finally killed him, Billy the Kid
gunned down 20 men.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so maybe that was only a little teen-age horseplay.
Nonetheless, this was not a nice person.
</P>
<P>
   Billy the Kid probably didn't see himself that way. He probably
figured that, OK, so I get a little out of hand occasionally. I'm
really a good guy, though.
</P>
<P>
   What he never understood, apparently, was that you are what you
do. If you kill, then you're a killer. If you steal, then you're a
thief. If you commit burglary, then you're a burglar.
</P>
<P>
   It's natural for any kid to distinguish what he does from who he
is. The prisons are jammed with guys who can't connect what they
did with who they are. But if it's not the responsibility of a
kid's parents to tell him that what he does defines him, then just
whose job is it?
</P>
<P>
   If you're not up to that, then you have no business whatever
splashing around in the gene pool.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
