<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CRUISE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON A CRUISE TO MEXICO, ELATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE COOPER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE ELATION _ One of Carnival's Fun Ships is called the
Celebration. While this one is the Elation, most people aboard the
855-foot ocean liner are celebrating one thing or another.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Kellys _ Pat and Peggy from Beeville, Texas. For their
37th wedding anniversary, Peggy wanted a cruise, and the Elation,
Carnival's newest ship, offered a way to see the Mexican Riviera at
a leisurely pace. Its seven-day itinerary to Mexico from Los
Angeles calls at Puerto Vallarta, Mazatlan and Cabo San Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Pat was a happy cruiser, celebrating a $250 Slots Tournament
complete with a ``solid gold'' plastic trophy and an Elation watch.
</P>
<P>
   The Kellys might have gone to Las Vegas, but ``I'd much rather
do a cruise,'' Peggy said.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise lines are hoping others think the same. Indeed, the
``Most Popular Cruise Line in the World'' has its big, splashy
theme hotels, gambling, sunshine, pools, buffets and shows. The
Elation has all that _ and you're floating.
</P>
<P>
   Mary and Jon Jaso, honeymooners from Orange County, Calif., had
never cruised before. They represented the first-timer market that
Carnival actively pursues. Maybe that's why this particular cruise
was 108.5 percent filled _ that's more than two people to a cabin,
according to Carnival spokesman Tim Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   That translates into 2,215 people on board during a late April
floating party to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The twentysomething Jasos _ she's a nursing student and he's an
electrician _ asked me to take their picture when we met on deck
the second day of the cruise.
</P>
<P>
   That's another nice thing about cruising; you meet many people
from different walks of life. Midway through the week you find
yourself nodding and smiling to everyone, joining new friends for
lunch or a stroll around the deck.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Jasos, with a dark tan and white-blond hair, was the
picture of the happy honeymooner. The couple shared an iced bucket
of Coronas and enjoyed the band playing Calypso music on deck near
the pool.
</P>
<P>
   Around the pool on the Lido deck, with its distinctive water
slide, the smell of coconut-based suntan lotion permeated the air.
So did cigar smoke from the playful group of adults at poolside.
</P>
<P>
   At 3 one afternoon a line formed for the slide _ all adults _
and when the band struck up a particularly playful tune, the line
began to dance and sing.
</P>
<P>
   Cocktail servers, wearing bright pink shirts and blue shorts,
were kept busy hawking special drinks with names such as Caribbean
Breeze ($5.75, and you keep the plastic glass), Goombay Smash and
Riviera Delight.
</P>
<P>
   There are three pools on the Elation. The Promenade deck pool is
quieter; this is where the serious sunbathers/readers gather. On
the Verandah deck, there is a wading pool for little kids near a
piece of playground equipment.
</P>
<P>
   More families are choosing to cruise year round with children.
The Camp Carnival program is a big draw with cruising families. The
programs, which operate from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m. (with some
after-hours specials), is for children 2 to 17. Carnival's Fantasy
Class ships, of which Elation is the newest, are the first to have
space designed with children in mind.
</P>
<P>
   There were about 130 children on board my cruise, while an
Easter cruise carried 400 youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   June and Ron Piltz, of Anchorage, Alaska, dropped off 4-year-old
Josh in Camp Carnival. While the Piltzes stood hesitantly watching
the children and the caregivers, little dark-eyed Josh went right
into the playhouse and then moved to the computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation is a Fantasy-class ship, seventh in a fleet of eight
70,000-ton vessels. Paradise, the final ship in the series, which
will be the industry's first non-smoking ship, will set sail this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   This is the only ship based in Los Angeles to do a seven-day
Mexican Riviera cruise, said Carnival spokeswoman Jennifer de la
Cruz.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation also is the first Carnival ship to feature the
Azipod propulsion system, which pulls the ship through the water
rather than pushing it like a conventional system. Azipods
eliminate the need for rudders, long shaft lines, conventional
drive units and stern thrusters. They also make the ship easier to
steer and maneuver. Noise and vibration are reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The ship is dazzling with its fiber-optic stars and soaring
atriums. There are a lot of neon and high-contrast colors. In the
bright red, white and black Jekyll and Hyde disco, the eyes glow
and the heads of the 8-foot sculptures swivel. In Duke's Bar (named
for Duke Ellington), there's a giant Statue of Liberty head as
decoration.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything on the Elation was cause for elation. One of the
glass-enclosed elevators did not work and there was only one iron
(but two ironing boards) in the laundry room on the Upper Deck.
</P>
<P>
   Kavita Panjabi, whom I met at the Coketail Party, had damaged
luggage and clothing items missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guest expectations may be a little bit higher,'' said
Elation's hotel director, Keith Bunton.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel director is a relatively new position, less than 10
years in the cruise industry. It replaces the job of head purser
(think Gopher on ``Love Boat'').
</P>
<P>
   Bunton, a native of New Mexico, has had experience in resorts in
Guam and Reno, Nev. The Elation is his first brand-new ship in five
years with Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `wow factor' that I get very enthusiastic about,
especially from couples who never thought they could afford a
cruise,'' Bunton said.
</P>
<P>
   In yearly gatherings of other Carnival hotel managers, Bunton
said he learned ``there's never a problem _ only challenges.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
