<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2228 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIAGRAVATION-HNS &LR;      06-23 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIAGRAVATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPOTENCE PILL CAN CAUSE PLENTY OF VIAGRAVATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Viagra is helping men overcome impotence. So why
do some of them still feel deflated?
</P>
<P>
   ``A pill is not going to solve a relationship problem,'' said
Dr. Stanley Bloom, a urologist and director of the Men's Sexual
Health Center in Livingston, N.J. ``Lack of sexual activity in a
relationship can be due to other issues besides lack of an
erection.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two months since Viagra made its way into thousands of
bedrooms across the country, doctors and psychologists say they are
starting to see some unexpected side effects from the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Like complaints about wives who don't want sex or want too much.
Men who are using the drug not with wives but with girlfriends.
Women who are sneaking the pill for themselves and demanding equal
attention to their problems. Couples who believe life was a lot
simpler when they could just turn out the light and roll over.
</P>
<P>
   The honeymoon is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good erections don't fix bad relationships, unfortunately,''
said Dr. James Barada, a urologist and the director of the Center
for Male Sexual Health in Albany, N.Y. ``In some cases, it just
makes things worse. You've added a negative stimulus to a
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, Barada acknowledges he's written
prescriptions for men who ``don't want their partners to know
they're taking the pill.''
</P>
<P>
   With two other impotence pills awaiting approval by the Food and
Drug Administration, Barada expects to hear more about the impact
on relationships of these and other treatments for sexual
dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a brave new world,'' he said. ``This represents a new
phenomenon. Viagra in one fell swoop has removed the stigma in
talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And people are talking. On late-night television, in locker
rooms, around water coolers and even to attorneys. Consider the $2
million lawsuit filed in New Jersey last month by Roberta Burke.
She blames Viagra for prompting her partner to leave her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He now thinks he is a young man in the body of a 70-year-old
man,'' Burke's attorney told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Sex in the '90s has just gotten more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us are concerned,'' said Howard Ruppel, the executive
director of the American Association of Sex Educators, Counselors
and Therapists in Iowa. ``There will be people who are unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the disappointment is wrapped in hyped-up expectations
around the drug. For months, men and women waited for the FDA to
approve the drug, manufactured by Pfizer Inc. As the company's
stock went up, so did the hopes of couples affected by erectile
dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does take a toll on relationships,'' said Mark Hillman, a
psychotherapist in Clifton Park, N.Y. ``It creates anger, hostility
and, in some cases, doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Therapists and doctors credit Viagra for helping couples realize
they aren't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Two men in five have problems getting an erection at age 40.
Nearly seven in 10 at age 70. Estimates place the number of
American men suffering from erection problems at between 20 million
and 30 million.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Viagra has proved to be one of the most popular drugs
ever, with doctors writing 570,000 prescriptions during its first
month on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The pill isn't 100 percent effective and it's no substitute for
desire, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   Clinical trials show the drug improved erections in about 72
percent of men. But those improved erections don't necessarily
correlate with a return to satisfactory intercourse, either from a
physical or psychological point of view.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Haffner, the director of Sexuality Information and
Education Council of the United States in New York City, has heard
both positive and negative stories about the drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard of one couple who has gotten engaged and another
couple where undue pressure has been put on a woman who isn't
interested,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She believes too much emphasis has been put on finding a medical
solution to sexual problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If every man who has gotten a prescription in the last month
had sat down and talked with his partner ... sex would be a lot
better now than before the prescription,'' she said. ``What we
really need to do is talk to our partners.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases, therapists believe Viagra has the potential to
exacerbate problems in a relationship, especially as they relate to
desire, the frequency of sex and ideas about intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   What they're talking about is libido or a lack of it, an issue
that's preoccupied humankind for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the quest for the perfect aphrodisiac, which has driven
people to try everything from Spanish fly to rhinoceros horn in
hopes of boosting desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viagra doesn't help with that,'' said Robert Athanasiou, the
medical director at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in upstate New
York and a certified sex therapist. ``It doesn't increase desire.
It implements desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Among married couples, desire discrepancy is often one of the
thorniest problems to sort out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for someone with normal desire to understand
how someone else might not be interested in sex,'' he said. ``That
kind of thing, we don't have a drug for.''
</P>
<P>
   At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are hopeful that Viagra will help solve some of the
mysteries surrounding sex and open up the conversation,
particularly in response to some women's concerns about their
problems, from vaginal dryness to difficulty reaching orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of activity in the next several
years on female sexual dysfunction,'' Bloom said. ``The scientific
community is going to take a hard look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinical trials are already under way on how Viagra affects
menopausal women.``The mechanism of Viagra is increased
bloodflow,'' Bloom said. ``In principle, it should work in the
female sexual organ. I think there's a lot of promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Urologists across the country are hearing stories about women
experimenting with the drug, and in some cases, getting their
doctors to write prescriptions for it. But Bloom cautions against
the off-label use of the drug by women of child-bearing age.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows what the effect may be on the fetus,'' he said.
Viagra's impact on sex and relationships is also uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruppel, of the American Association of Sex Educators, Counselors
and Therapists, believes couples need to be open and honest about
what they want out of their sexual relationship from ``a peck on
the cheek to ... pull the phone out of the wall, lock the door and
don't bother me until Monday sex.''
</P>
<P>
   And that kind of emotional intimacy can't be bought at a
drugstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all is said and done, the pills won't do it completely,''
Ruppel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1314EDT &QL; 
