</P>
<P>
   &UR; WOMEN AND SEX: ON THIS TOPIC, SCIENCE BLUSHES &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 1,300 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By GINA KOLATA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the recent introduction of Viagra, the impotence pill made
by Pfizer, the world has changed. Suddenly there is a pill for men
who have trouble getting and maintaining erections. Almost as
suddenly, drug-company scientists, wondering whether Viagra or
something like it can enhance sex for women, are asking academic
scientists what is known about women's sexual responses. The answer
is not much, writes Gina Kolata, who reports on science and
medicine for The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-WOMEN-AND-SEX-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAUGING THE RISK FACTORS IN THE SEARCH FOR A PERFECT FACE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One B&AMP;W shot of a patient recovering from facial
plastic surgery is available for purchase and can be sent to you
electronically. Also available, a graphic depicting the number of
procedures (face lift, eyelid surgery, breast augmentation and
liposuction) performed in 1992, 1996 and 1997 by surgeons who were
members of the American Academy of Plastic and Reconstructive
Surgeons.
 &UR; By SUSAN GILBERT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The number of liposuction operations increased 215 percent to
149,042 from 47,212 between 1992 and 1997, according to the latest
statistics from the American Academy of Plastic and Reconstructive
Surgeons in Arlington Heights, Ill. Plastic surgeons performed
32,607 breast augmentations in 1992; five years later, they did
122,285. As the numbers show, cosmetic surgery is soaring thanks to
baby boomers who are looking longer in the mirror and seeing sags
and wrinkles. But what are the hazards? Susan Gilbert, who writes
regularly about health for the Science Times section of The New
York Times, reports.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-PERFECT-FACE-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR INFERTILITY TREATMENTS, NOW YOU'RE COVERED, NOW YOU'RE NOT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,700 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One color shot of Dr. Cecilia Schmidt-Sarosi in
her own fertility practice _ standing by a bed, surrounded by
medical equipment _ is available electronically. &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE ADAMS LANG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It took Carla and Bruce P. three and a half gut-wrenching years
of invasive medical treatments and more than $40,000 of their
savings before Carla got pregnant in April. That makes them part of
a small but growing population that beat what the New York State
Task Force on Life and the Law recognizes as the ``disease'' of
infertility. The odds can be long when it comes to infertility
treatment, reports free-lance journalist Anne Adams Lang. And the
odds of having insurance cover what is needed can be even trickier.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-INFERTILITY-CONTROVERSY-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S ENOUGH TO MAKE YOU SICK, THE WAY PATIENTS ARE TREATED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,200 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One B&AMP;W illustration showing a bandaged wrist is
available for purchase and can be sent to you electronically. &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT LIPSYTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of battling doctors, billing clerks, HMOs? May be it's
time to organize, or ``unionize,'' the only unorganized part of
medicine _ the patients! _ writes Robert Lipsyte, author of ``In
the Country of Illness: Comfort and Advice for the Journey.'' ``Our
imperfect union of imperfect people will include the measured
brand-testing of the Consumers Union and the muscular intimidation
of the teamsters' union under Jimmy Hoffa,'' he writes in this
sardonic feature.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-PATIENT'S-FEAR-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEN. ARE WOMEN BETTER OFF WITH THEM, OR WITHOUT THEM? &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One B&AMP;W photo showing a senior couple kissing
beneath the branches of a tree is available electronically. &QL; 
 &UR; By NATALIE ANGIER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Are men worth it? More precisely, is the maxim true about
marriage being good for a man's health but hazardous for a woman's
_ or is it a sly old spinster's tale? Do we live better with men or
without them, and which life will be longer, and which will simply
seem longer? Natalie Angier, a science writer for The New York
Times who is completing a book about women's bodies, takes a crack
at answering these questions.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-IS-MARRIAGE-WORTH-IT?-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LITTLE KNOWLEDGE, A LOT OF AGONY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By KATHLEEN McAULIFFE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, a much-wanted pregnancy at age 37 prompted
medical writer Kathleen McAuliffe to seek prenatal testing. The
grainy picture on the ultrasound machine showed a glorious baby.
But the results of her amniocentesis were ominous. The fetus was
male and appeared to be normal _ except for an alteration on one
chromosome. If even a fraction of a gene had been nicked or
scrambled, the consequences could be terrible. The child might be
born deformed or retarded and suffer from multiple disabilities. In
this poignant feature, McAuliffe leads readers into the murky world
of genetics and recounts her personal plan of action.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-TERROR-TEST-AMNIOCENTESIS-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WITH ALTERNATIVE MEDICINE, PROFITS ARE BIG, RULES ARE FEW &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,400 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One color montage of a woman's body is available
electronically. &QL; 
 &UR; By KAREN STABINER &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Marcie Rothman, 51, takes three Body Wise Female
Advantage nutritional capsules _ an arsenal of 22 ingredients
marketed as the natural answer to menopause. And she's not alone.
Like many women her age, Rothman is helping to support a $4 billion
alternative-remedy industry by dosing herself with nontraditional
treatments. But how safe are they? And just how effective? Karen
Stabiner, a Los Angeles-based writer who is the author of ``To
Dance With the Devil: The New War on Breast Cancer,'' reports.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RESEARCHERS FINDING NEW WARINESS ON WALL STREET &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (1,100 words) &QL; 
 &UR; ART FOR PURCHASE: One B&AMP;W photo showing Melissa Wilmoth, a
securities analyst, in her office at Salomon Smith Barney is
available electronically. &QL; 
 &UR; By LESLIE EATON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bright hopes but poor performance help explain Wall Street's
ambivalence toward women's health-care companies, reports Leslie
Eaton, a financial reporter who covers Wall Street for The New York
Times. In the early 1990s, biotechnology companies, including some
concentrating on women, were the hottest stocks on Wall Street. But
few lived up to investors' expectations, and their high-flying
stocks plunged.
</P>
<P>
   SLUGGED: BC-EXTRA-WOMEN'S-HEALTHCARE-WALL-STREET-NYTSF
</P>
<P>
   FOR PURCHASE INFORMATION, call CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.
</P>
<P>
   Many Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
</TEXT>
