<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-LITHUANIA-COX     06-23 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-LITHUANIA-COX </SLUG>
   -$ADV27 
 &HT;     FOREIGN JOURNAL: LITHUANIA REFLECTS ON CRUEL SOVIET PAST IN KGB
MUSEUM
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Saturday, June 27 And Thereafter.
 &HT;     By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILNIUS, Lithuania _ It is a grim, frightfully intimate job
performed by Juozas Aleksiejunas. He gives guided tours of his
former hell.
</P>
<P>
   The 76-year-old Aleksiejunas escorts visitors around Lithuania's
appallingly well-preserved KGB prison, a lingering monument to the
bleak, brutal days of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt ill when I came back here,'' he said of his first
glimpse of the prison in 1992, almost 50 years after his
incarceration. ``People who left this building after interrogation
here just wanted to see it torn down. But if you tore it down the
evidence would be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lithuania, the first of the three small Baltic states which
broke away from the Soviet Union in 1990, looks back with this
unique museum to the KGB, the feared security apparatus which kept
dissidents in check and punished any notion of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of its capital, the Lithuanian government has
preserved the brownstone building in all its horrific detail _ from
the suffocating isolation chambers to the barren interrogation
rooms. Now, the prison goes by the name of the Genocide and
Resistance Center.
</P>
<P>
   In one corner is the wholly preserved padded cell where torture
took place, a room well insulated to mask the inmates' agonizing
screams from the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   In another is the ``wet'' cell, where prisoners were stripped
naked and forced to squat for hour after hour on a small metal
platform while frigid water flooded the concrete cell floor beneath
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who were brought here, their cases were already
decided,'' said Aleksiejunas, who began working at the museum as a
volunteer and now receives a small salary to augment his pension.
</P>
<P>
   He was a nationalist partisan fighter in the 1940s who spent
four months in the prison in central Vilnius before being exiled to
Siberia, one of an estimated 350,000 Lithuanians who were
imprisoned and banished by the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the spot in a gloomy concrete cell where he was
forced to squat for hours under questioning while being beaten.
</P>
<P>
   And then, to emphasize his point, he invites his visitor to
assume the position for only 45 uncomfortable seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Lithuanians are eager to assert their nationality and
their liberty from the Soviet past. They want alliances with the
European Union and with NATO that will remind them and the world
that they are no longer shackled to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is that message stronger than in the dank, dark recesses
of this museum, which preserves the thick stone walls, bare light
bulbs and heavy steel doors of its infamous place in history.
</P>
<P>
   Grainy black-and-white photos display the fighters who did not
survive their stay. Between 1944 and 1947, an estimated 700 people
were executed at the prison, most of them shot in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Such ruthlessness by the KGB diminished the armed resistance but
did not stifle the underground antagonism towards the Soviets. Over
the decades of Soviet rule, a steady stream of patriotic writing
was circulated, some of it on display at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955 an anonymous writer penned: ``They keep our hearts
pinched as with red-hot pliers and they wash their hands in the
blood of our brothers and sisters. Perhaps this independence day
will free our young hearts when the tricolor (flag) waves.''
</P>
<P>
   Aleksiejunas was a member of Brothers of the Forest, a
resistance group which first fought the Soviets, whose Red Army
occupied Lithuania in 1940, then the Nazis who followed a year
later, and then the Soviets again, who drove the Germans out at the
end of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested in 1945, charged under the notorious Soviet
Article 58 -- betrayal of the socialist state. Three years later,
his parents also paid for his resistance activities. They were
deported to Siberia and their family farm in Lithuania was
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy to be convicted under Article 58. If you were
chatting with three friends and you were talking about cars,
perhaps you might have said that American cars are better than the
Russian ones. If one of your friends was an informant, you ended up
in jail for treason,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksiejunas spent 18 years in various prisons and labor camps,
including Vorkuta, nearly 1,200 miles northeast of Moscow, a link
in the infamous Soviet gulag.
</P>
<P>
   But the jail in Vilnius was among the worst of it, he recalls,
because here he lost many of his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to keep the memories, to tell people about the
past,'' he said. ``Because without the past there is no future.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For clients of the New York Times News Service &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2273 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-LITHUANIA-COX     06-23 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-LITHUANIA-COX </SLUG>
   -$ADV27 
 &HT;     FOREIGN JOURNAL: LITHUANIA REFLECTS ON CRUEL SOVIET PAST IN KGB
MUSEUM
 &HT;     With photos to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;     Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;     For Use Saturday, June 27 And Thereafter.
