<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2304 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-GARRITY-BOS     06-23 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-GARRITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME'S GARRITY PREPPED FOR THE PROS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WALTHAM, Mass. _ Anyone who played against Notre Dame's
basketball team last season is aware of sophomore guard Keith
Friel. The son of former University of New Hampshire coach Gerry
Friel was the second leading scorer for the Irish last season with
an average of 10.8 points. That meant he gave opponents some cause
for concern when they debated whether to put all their efforts into
stopping Notre Dame's scoring sensation Pat Garrity.
</P>
<P>
   Most teams, however, opted for zeroing in on Garrity, with good
reason. The senior accounted for 33 percent of ND's offense and was
the fifth leading scorer in Division 1, averaging 23.3 points. He
also watched many of his better efforts go to waste: The Irish
finished 13-14 last year, and Garrity finished his final season as
he did the previous three _ devoid of an NCAA tournament
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, his efforts caught the attention of many coaches whose
efforts to stop him were in vain, including Celtics coach Rick
Pitino. Garrity scored a game-high 25 points on 8-for-15 shooting
(including 9 for 11 from 3-point range) in an 80-56 loss to
Pitino's Wildcats Dec. 14, 1996, in Lexington, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't surprising to see the 6-foot-9-inch, 231-pound forward
among those the Celtics worked out Friday at Brandeis University.
They were among 10 teams who brought Garrity in for a workout, and
many analysts expect him to be selected in the top half of the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   After that Kentucky-Notre Dame game, Pitino said, ``He can play
at the next level. He moves well without the ball and he gets
everyone's attention. It's hard to score when you are the focal
point of all the defenses. But, he still puts up the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   That was Garrity's junior season, when he began emerging as one
of the more fundamentally sound, deft scorers in the nation. He
finished the season averaging 20.1 points and was Big East player
of the year. But the team garnered only a berth in the National
Invitation Tournament, his only postseason appearance.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you have to hand it to Garrity for starting in all of
the 111 games he played at Notre Dame _ a school record. ``He knows
what it's like to be called upon and be productive night after
night because he was about all they had to go to,'' said Celtics
general manager Chris Wallace. He added that Garrity has benefitted
from the tutelage of Notre Dame coach John MacLeod, former coach of
the Dallas Mavericks and Phoenix Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a finished product. He's fundamentally sound,'' said
Wallace. ``He's probably a stronger, more forceful version of Don
MacLean in that he can shoot the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity said MacLeod helped prepare him for the next level,
running offensive plays that MacLeod ran in Dallas and Phoenix. He
taught Garrity the importance of footwork and being able to read
and react to screens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are two things we did here that were beneficial
to him,'' said MacLeod. ``First of all, we run 99 percent
man-to-man defense, which is what they do in the pros. Secondly, we
emphasize the running attack, and getting the big men out on the
break and filling the lanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reminds me of Dave DeBusschere in that he can shoot it well
from the outside, he can play the power forward spot, and he
rebounds well. And he's not afraid to shoot the ball, which is a
quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Garrity finished with 2,085 career points, third highest in
school history behind Austin Carr and Adrian Dantley, and he is the
leading scorer in Big East history among players who have played
three seasons or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Garrity is one of the toughest players that we've ever
faced because he moves so well without the basketball,'' said Miami
coach Leonard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   But even his toughness couldn't get the Irish into the NCAA
tournament: The team hasn't made it to the Big Dance since the
1989-90 season.
</P>
<P>
   Garrity was born in Las Vegas but took up basketball while his
father, a former football player at Air Force, was stationed at
Shaw Air Force Base in Sumter, S.C. Garrity took up the sport in
his sophomore year because the high school didn't have football. He
honed his skills playing pickup games against enlisted men. His
family moved to Monument, Colo., and he averaged 27 points and 12
boards in leading Monument to a state title. But he was virtually
overlooked by many college recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because I was so skinny,'' said Garrity. ``I was 6-9,
and I weighed 190 pounds. Once I started lifting between my senior
year in high school and my freshman year, I made up that gap and
was able to compete at the major college level.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until Garrity began participating in summer
basketball tournaments that he began considering the NBA. He was
the leading scorer on the United States Under-22 team that finished
fifth in the World Champioships, averaging 11.8 points. ``After my
junior year (the NBA) became a goal of mine,'' said Garrity. He
graduated from Notre Dame with a pre-med major of professional
studies with an emphasis on biology and chemistry. He finished with
a 3.68 grade-point average and was an Academic All-American his
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   But Garrity makes no bones about where his career goals are
focused. Asked if he wants to be a doctor some day, he said, ``Not
really. I came in as a science major; that's what kept my attention
in college. But this (playing in the NBA) is what I want to be
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
