</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, June 24,
1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday,
June 24, 1998. We will update this budget at 6 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   Separate feature and commentary budgets move at 10 a.m. EDT
Monday-Friday. Separate sports and business budgets move at 5 p.m.
EDT Monday-Friday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456. The night news editor, until 10
p.m. EDT, is Todd C. Duncan at 404-582-7282.
</P>
<P>
   With questions about Washington-originated material, please call
our Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON _ XIAN, China _ Clinton to arrive in China
tomorrow on one of longest, most controversy-ridden presidential
tours in American history. (Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   CHINDIG _ XIAN, China _ China's Buried Warriors. A historical
feature on Xian's terra cotta figures that Clinton will visit
first. We hope to wrap this around an interview with the obscure
farmer who found one of the world's great historical treasures in
1974 and now just signs autographs. (Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-HISTORY _ ``The Longest Presidential Visits'' _ would
include Woodrow Wilson's trip to Paris for the League of Nations,
Clinton's trip to China, and other long ones. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-TRAVEL _ WASHINGTON _ Once an out-of-reach destination for
frugal travelers, east Asia is now more accessible than ever.
Tumbling currencies due to Asia's economic woes have resulted in
deep discounts on airfares, hotel rooms and package tours. With
intra-Asian travel at a near halt, airlines and tour operators are
looking to fill up empty seats and hotel rooms with Western
travelers. Once in Asia, Americans will find their dollar stretch
with drastically-reduced merchandise. The best news for travelers:
Thailand, Singapore and Malaysia. But even Japan, which has
traditionally been exorbitantly priced, is now affordable as the
yen's value descends to rock bottom. Here's just one example: 4
nights. Included is roundtrip airfare, a half-day sightseeing tour
where you'll visit the Golden Buddah in Bangkok. You'll stay at the
Royal River Hotel. Excursions can include a visit to one of
Thailand's snake farms, elephant rides or a trip to a remote hill
tribe. Besides the above, included in the price is an airport
welcome by an English speaker, hotel taxes and service charges and
bonus miles. $850. Last year, the trip would have cost you $1,200.
(Abulhassan, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-TRAVEL-BOX _ WASHINGTON _ Comparison data on airfares,
hotel rates and travel package prices for several destinations in
Asia. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Rescheduled. Moving in both the (i) International and (t)
Travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   GAHEAT _ Georgia's stifling early-summer heat wave shows no
signes of easing, with afternoon temperatures well into the 90s -
and above - forecast at least through the weekend. Heat and high
humidity has forced Atlanta fire officials to call out extra
firefighters on routine fires and prompted warnings for dangerously
high heat indices in middle and south Georgia. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POLICE-SCANDAL _ Allegations by a former Atlanta policedeputy
chief that top brass may have manipulated the city's crime
statistics is dividing the Atlanta Police department into opposing
camps with some officers siding with Capt. Louis Arcangeli and
others siding with Chief Beverly Harvard, but most agree that the
flap has given the department a black eye, one it can not afford
following problems that include federal extortion charges against
several officers in 1996 and as far back as a cheating scandal in
the 1970s. (Longa, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FLAHEAT-CATTLE _ TALLAHASSEE _ Florida's cattle ranchers will
likely become the latest victims of the state's continuing heat
wave, adding to the $80 million in crops already lost this summer,
Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford said. ``We have not been this
desperate in Florida in 50 years.'' (Date, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCEONE _ DAYTON, Ohio _ A woman spoke quietly, almost
reverently to her female companion. ``If the insides of this plane
could only talk. My goodness, the stories we would hear.'' The two
were among about 900 who visited the U.S. Air Force Museum to tour
the original Air Force One and to take a personal look at the plane
that winged presidents around the world. (Huffman, Dayton Daily
News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
