<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-HNS &LR;      06-23 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHER EXCELS IN `ELEVENTH COMMANDMENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
 _____  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Eleventh Commandment.'' By Jeffrey Archer. HarperCollins.
$26. 359 pages.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Jeffrey Archer delivers a first-rate, well-crafted and
very readable international thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Connor Fitzgerald is almost too good to be true _ college
football star, Congressional Medal of Honor winner in Vietnam,
devoted father and husband, and a negotiator for an insurance
company specializing in international kidnappings and ransoms. And
for the last 25 years, Fitzgerald has been the CIA's top assassin
and followed the Eleventh Commandment: Thou shalt not get caught.
But if you are, deny absolutely that you have anything to do with
the CIA. Don't worry _ the Company will always take care of you.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly he is being forced into retirement by his boss, CIA
Director Helen Dexter, who will do anything to keep her job. The
president wants her out, so she sets up Fitzgerald, who believes
the president himself has asked him to go to Russia and take out
one of the leading presidential candidates. Fitzgerald, of course,
is caught before he can carry out the assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Archer is a master at building political intrigue and crafting
interesting and multilayered characters. His plot rings true and
moves along at a satisfying pace. And best of all, he doesn't give
away the ending.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Icefire.'' By Judith &AMP; Garfield Reeves-Stevens. Pocket Books.
</P>
<P>
   The authors get so involved in the techno jargon that what
should have been a truly entertaining thriller gets buried.
</P>
<P>
   On Thanksgiving Day, terrorists explode six nuclear bombs
beneath Antarctica's Ross Ice Shelf, causing the shelf to break up.
Instantly, a 400-mph soliton wave begins to move across the
Pacific, wiping out everything in its path _ first the HMS
Intrepid, most of New Zealand, parts of Australia, the Solomons,
Hawaii and on toward the West Coast of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Two people survive the blasts in Antarctica _ Navy Seal Mitch
Webber and oceanographer-environmentalist Corazon Ray. They
helicopter to the Intrepid, tell them about the soliton so the crew
can send out a disaster warning, refuel and get airborne before the
wave hits. Somehow, they must get to the man who originated the
Icefire plan, find out if the wave can be stopped, convince the
U.S. military to act and find the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   The plot might not be believable, but a good yarn is a good
yarn. If it weren't for the recurring technobabble, this could have
been a winner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Tin Man.'' By Dale Brown. Bantam Books. $24.95. 367 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Read somewhere that ``The Tin Man'' was one of the summer's hot
books. To say I was disappointed is an understatement. This book is
a mess.
</P>
<P>
   Former U.S. Gen. Patrick McLanahan is the director of scientific
development for a San Diego firm specializing in creating
technologies for the military. He and his very pregnant wife fly to
Sacramento for his brother Paul's graduation from the police
academy. On his first night on the force, terrorists hit the money
room of a huge complex, kill several police officers and seriously
wound Paul.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick decides to track down the killers. He dons a ``carbon
filament bodysuit that can instantly harden into
stronger-than-steel protective armor,'' making the wearer almost
invincible. The suit cannot be pierced by bullets, bombs, etc. But
it can be pierced by a knife. And every time Patrick puts it on, he
goes a little insane, hurting even some of his colleagues. Go
figure this logic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the terrorists offer the biker gangs (who are drug
dealers) a deal they can't refuse. The terrorists, calling
themselves the Aryan Brigade, will supply the gangs with new
cookers and supplies for making illegal drugs. All are delivered on
the same night, all blow up and most of the gang members of
Northern California are wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   About the only character in this book that's believable is the
wounded Paul, who reacts to his plight like a normal human being.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aryan Brigade's ultimate goal is about as far-fetched as
you can get in one book. This tale just doesn't make sense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
