<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2307 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-23 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY'S NOOSE AROUND LOTT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- The last time Senator Edward M. Kennedy did what
he is about to try to do, he drove Bob Dole batty.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling toward the Republican presidential nomination two
years ago, Dole wanted to save money and strut his stuff as Senate
majority leader one last time. In his way was Kennedy, cheerfully
and relentlessly pushing for votes on a higher minimum wage and
health insurance reform.
</P>
<P>
   So relentless was Kennedy that Dole quit the Senate early, and
the proposals became law. Two years later, under probably more
difficult circumstances, Dole's successor, Trent Lott, is about to
get the same treatment, only with three twists.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he will have to block votes on three worthy and
popular measures: the procedurally blocked tobacco legislation,
reform of literally predatory health maintenance organizations, and
a substantively unassailable followup increase in the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Lott's lot has company in Newt Gingrich's
dysfunctional House of Representatives, where Democratic leader
Dick Gephardt is planning maneuvers to free similarly blocked
proposals for voting consideration on the floor. And for another,
the battling over these policy issues will not obscure a fourth,
also blocked initiative to change the scandalous campaign finance
system.
</P>
<P>
   What Kennedy is planning, thanks to the Senate's tradition of
almost anything goes, is to keep offering the blocked proposals as
amendments to whatever is the official business on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   What Lott then has to do is muster either a majority to set
Kennedy's initiatives aside each time or a minority of at least 40
to block a vote on the merits. More often than not _ for sure on
tobacco and possibly on the others _ it will have to be a minority
of almost entirely very conservative Republicans. That is because
tobacco, HMOs, and the minimum wage all have one important,
political thing in common _ moderate Republicans, some of them
facing the voters this fall, who favor action.
</P>
<P>
   Having done his homework, Kennedy has already made sure his own
party is solidly aboard. This means that he is pushing proposals
for which a Senate majority already exists. In the case of tobacco,
for example, the comprehensive measure drafted by Commerce
Committee chairman John McCain of Arizona had 57 senators
officially ready to vote on it.
</P>
<P>
   The result was absurd _ a steady stream of Republican amendments
to the McCain bill, followed by their leadership's claim that it
had become too unwieldy to be voted on because it had too many
amendments attached.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of HMOs and the minimum wage, the Lott tactic for
the moment is to keep both proposals off the Senate's official
radar screen. And for that reason, it becomes the Kennedy tactic to
keep bringing them up, on the theory that it becomes harder to take
the difficult votes to block them as Election Day gets closer.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair to the conservatives, there is ideology behind the
opposition and not merely PAC money. They see taxes or big
government or both involved, and they see red.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair as well to Lott, there is nothing un-American about
using tactics to block votes in the Senate on measures one opposes
strongly. Liberals, Kennedy included, have done it countless times.
The political difficulty comes in when the measures one is blocking
are clearly popular and would become law if senators could vote on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy is forcing his opponents to vote affirmatively to not
vote. Over time, that position can become increasingly difficult to
sustain, as Dole discovered. That is why there is talk (but so far
no action) in the GOP leadership in both houses about offering
greatly slimmed down versions of the blocked measures, targeting
but not hitting young smokers and HMOs. The political problem,
however, is that it is even harder to offer a pale palliative while
refusing to consider the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Kennedy says, pushing the palliatives is an attempt to
save politically fearful senators while doing nothing to help
people. For $1.10 per pack of cigarettes and the first real
regulation of the tobacco racket, a lot of young people won't start
smoking and a lot more will have health insurance and day-care
slots. For a simple chance for senators to vote, the insurance
monsters will have to concede patients some basic rights. And for
the same chance, wages at the bottom can rise again in the middle
of the best economy in a generation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
