<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-23 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNICLE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUTHS LEARNED ON THE STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE BARNICLE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ I am sitting on a bench in Stephen's Green, listening
as one of my sons describes the look and feel of a museum exhibit
where he had just seen the uniform worn by Michael Collins the day
he was ambushed decades ago, shot to death by his own people. Irony
prevails. It is an odd feeling: Cleared of a crime you didn't
commit. It's like responding to the unanswerable accusation, ``When
did you stop beating your wife?'' Indicted. Investigated. And
declared not guilty. Yet why do I still not feel in tip-top shape?
</P>
<P>
   I sit thousands of miles from a genuine human tragedy. This was
not some industrial accident. A woman's life has been shattered.
Her career destroyed. Her dream momentarily dead. Yet that seems
not to satisfy the predators within the press corps who then
decided to take 25 years worth of my work and use it as target
practice.
</P>
<P>
   In order to balance its uncomfortable decision, the Globe chose
to put me on the rack to appear even-handed within the politically
correct, agenda-driven journalism of the age. No double standards
here!
</P>
<P>
   And who better to incite the trial than the noted ethicist,
Inspector Dershowitz, champion of the underdog, especially when
cameras are around. The self-promoting professor thinks O.J.
Simpson is innocent, Louise Woodward is a terrific baby sitter, and
that I am a bad guy. I can live with his contempt.
</P>
<P>
   For few have been allowed my privilege: To record stories of our
time, thrice a week for over a quarter of a century. To take note
of the pain, the humor, the daily drama far from bright lights and
front pages. To offer a portrait _ a snapshot if you will _ of
those moments in tenement halls, firehouses, police stations,
courtrooms, classrooms, dark corridors and sidewalks cluttered with
the chaos, humanity, the good, the evil and the inexplicable that
shape how we live and who we are. To witness that. To have people
share their grief or their delight with you is a humbling thing.
</P>
<P>
   And these people, many falling below the media's radar screen,
are real. Their tales are told without deception or the arrogant
delusion that I am always right, never mistaken, totally
infallible. Because I _ like you, the customer, the state employee,
the nurse, the bus driver, the hospital orderly, the teacher, the
detective, parish priest or rabbi, neighborhood nun or social
worker, like even the bums, content in their own integrity _ am
indeed human.
</P>
<P>
   This is no trick. It is simply one aspect of being a part of a
magnificent business at a tremendous time when people of honor like
Davis, John I. and Bill Taylor along with Tom Winship, Bob Healy,
Jack Driscoll and Ed Doherty taught me to report the truth, to be
unafraid of controversy, and to avoid writing for the approval of
colleagues or to satisfy ``uptown'' encampments.
</P>
<P>
   Today, we talk endlessly about codes of ethics. But they are
useless if they have to be drawn up by study groups of editors on
retreat because the ultimate code is character.
</P>
<P>
   As this is whirring through my head, a brilliant rainbow
suddenly appeared over Phoenix Park and at the end of it I could
actually see the vision of ``Juicy'' Johnson, dead on the ground,
in an alley between three-deckers in Dorchester, one of the first
victims of the ``crack wars'' that claimed so many a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's body, looking as if it had been shot with a sewing
machine, was on the pavement that night when a woman came to stand
on the porch. I asked if she'd heard the gunfire. When she
indicated she had, I wanted to know what she did next, and she
looked at me and said: ``I called Radio-59 for the $50 news tip,''
talking about the old WEEI in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Three policemen stood alongside: Bo Mullane, Danny Downey and
Bob Faherty. Mullane turned and said with a grin on his face: ``You
put that in the paper and they'll think you made it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, years later, it is still astounding to me how much daily
drama happens out of the headlines. And it is amazing as well as
sad that when the concerns, the problems or some of the issues that
affect the consistently normal are chronicled, their stories _ even
their lives _ are thought to be fiction by the isolated or the
affluent. I am proud of what I do, yet, believe me, no paycheck is
worth a reputation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Barnicle is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
