<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIPS-MOTHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW AN HONOR ROLL SON BECAME ENSNARLED IN GANG VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RIC KAHN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Holly Charles always thought that her son, Dwayne
Johnson, had it all going for him: handsome, athletic, smart.
School officials pushed him to achieve. She sustained him.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson also wore a blue bandanna, an emblem of his reputed
allegiance to the Crips gang.
</P>
<P>
   Charles found it one day, tucked among her son's underwear and
T-shirts in a bedroom dresser, below a poster of pro football star
Natrone Means.
</P>
<P>
   Charles knew what the blue bandanna meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, Ma,'' he told her. ``I just wear it for style.''
</P>
<P>
   She pulled out a lighter and torched the bandanna, hoping to
make an impression. But, it turned out, she couldn't stop her son
from playing with fire.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two years later, at 16, Dwayne Johnson is a reputed Crip
leader, languishing in a 5-by-12 cell in the Plymouth County
Correctional Facility. He's awaiting trial for allegedly trying to
murder an associate of the Bloods _ a rival gang whose members
pledge fealty to the color red.
</P>
<P>
   A son's descent is a mother's grief. Holly Charles's story _ a
mother's tale _ could be the lament of as many as 500 women who,
police sources say, may be losing their sons to the Crips and the
Bloods, Los Angeles-inspired gangs gaining a foothold in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Charles feels she did all a mother could. She said she told
Johnson she loved him every day. When tender talk didn't work, she
laid down a curfew. Then she asked the courts to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried my best. ... I didn't just sit back and let it
happen,'' Charles, 34, said in a recent interview. ``Whatever they
were telling him is more powerful than me.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials remember Johnson as clean-cut, confident,
talented, an honor roll student who was respectful to authorities
and respected by his peers.
</P>
<P>
   If he had kept out of trouble, they say, his future would have
been bright. They envisioned him as a class president and college
graduate, someday working in business or government.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Johnson's success story is a cautionary tale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had natural ability far above most of the average kids in
the Boston public schools,'' said Lieutenant Michael Hennessey of
the Boston School Police, who spent hours trying to set Johnson
straight. ``Now, he's a poster boy for what can happen when you get
caught up in the insidiousness of gang culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on her living room couch at the Faneuil housing project,
insulated from Crip graffiti that scars the common corridor,
Charles &UR;  &LR; buries her face in the crook of her arm. Her doe eyes
begin to fill with tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how much I can take,'' she said. ``There's so
much tragedy in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles, a store clerk, quit high school when she had Dwayne,
her oldest child. Together with her mother, she raised him at the
South Street projects.
</P>
<P>
   She described him as a sweet child who walked away from fights.
He carried a football everywhere he went and told her he was going
to make it to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Although he denied it, his mother knew Dwayne missed having
his father around full time. His 25-year-old uncle was shot down in
the projects, allegedly over a drug theft. Dwayne was 9. Surrounded
by bad memories, the family moved to the Old Colony development in
South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But the bullets followed them. One day about a year later, an
older white boy spit at Dwayne and used a racial slur. After she
confronted the boy, Charles said, someone shot at Dwayne's
stepfather, Max Charles, as he sat in his car, and strafed their
living room with gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Again Charles sought refuge for her family, this time at the
Faneuil projects. But in the mid '90s, Boston's Allston-Brighton
section was the breeding ground for Crips and Bloods in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And by 1995, school police who tracked gangs reported that
Dwayne Johnson _ then a 13-year-old in Taft Middle School _ had
quietly emerged as the neighborhood leader of the Crips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Appearances are deceiving,'' said Irene McCarthy, principal at
the Taft. ``He was a bright child _ all the leaders of gangs are
bright people. They don't apply their thinking skills to everyday
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles's maternal instints detected danger signs.
</P>
<P>
   She bought him a red shirt. He refused to wear it.
</P>
<P>
   She asked about his cryptic blue tattoo. He denied it was a gang
symbol.
</P>
<P>
   She asked him hard questions, but got soft answers.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled a typical exchange:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(begin itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, Dwayne. Do you think I don't love you? Are you all
right?'' she asked. ``Is it that you can't get out?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't understand, Ma,'' he answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me understand so I can help you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't in no gang, Ma.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson had already been initiated into the gang the usual
way _ by being beaten _ when he was a fifth-grader, school police
say he told them. Gang members in a nearby city taught him the Crip
hand signals, colors, and code. He allegedly said he enjoyed being
part of a group willing to die for one another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blue for life,'' Johnson reputedly bragged.
</P>
<P>
   In school and at home, Johnson remained soft-spoken and polite.
He exchanged pleasantries with the older women in the neighborhood,
even carried their groceries.
</P>
<P>
   But on the streets of Allston-Brighton, police say, Johnson and
his fellow Crips faced down the Bloods, each side wielding bats or
bike chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was with his peers he was a totally different
individual,'' said Chris Rogers, youth service police officer in
Allston-Brighton, who had encouraged Johnson to become a
trophy-winning soccer player in the Police Activities League only
to see him turn into a bike-stealing bully. ``He had to be the
tough guy, the leader of the gang.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Johnson, Hennessey saw a charismatic person with great
promise. The veteran officer warned the boy of what lay ahead in
the gang life: addiction, jail, even death. If he went straight,
Hennessey promised, he'd get Johnson an after-school job at John
Hancock. Johnson said OK.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he spiraled further into the gang realm. He started
skipping classes, officials say, and allegedly immersed himself in
the Book of Knowledge _ the Crips bible, which tells the secrets of
the national gang.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, sources said, he was arrested for an armed carjacking
in Waltham. A year later, he was jumped by neighborhood Bloods as
he went to school at English High, his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was obsessed with Crippin','' said Hennessey.
</P>
<P>
   Charles tried to win back her son. Hearing that he was under the
influence of a Crip ``recruiter'' originally from Los Angeles,
Charles tracked the man down and got in his face, warning him to
stay away from her son.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to follow all the rules for at-risk children: She made
sure someone was there when her son came home. She preached the
value of education. She punished him when he broke curfew.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  At wit's end, Charles said, she petitioned juvenile court to
monitor her son's school attendance and curfew, but he fell through
those cracks, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have been there every minute,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On March 4, Johnson told his mother he was going to play
basketball. He never came home. Dressed in blue, he ended up in
handcuffs, charged with a gang attack in Allston. Police say
Johnson and a group of Crips cornered a 17-year-old, bashed his
head with a hammer, and cut his face with a meat cleaver. Some
believe it was payback for Johnson's beating.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Charles pulls out a picture of Johnson as an early
adolescent, smiling and wearing red pants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dwayne is a sweet kid deep down inside,'' she said, still
searching for answers, and beating herself up when none are found.
``I don't know if he's trying to prove something to the people he
hangs with. ... Maybe he needed a brother. I wish I could have done
more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-HENLSY-BOS &LR;      06-23 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-HENLSY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOKING DAPPER FOR THE RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a sporting event so stiff and formal that male
spectators, the poor dears, need permission to take off their
jackets, no matter how hot and humid it gets. And women? They're
turned away at the door if their skirt or dress doesn't completely
cover their knees.
</P>
<P>
   It would probably prompt a lawsuit in Boston. But in England,
strict dress codes like these are ancient tradition at the annual
Henley Royal Regatta rowing race for anyone sitting in the best
seats in a private area near the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   And since Harvard University has decided to compete there next
month, many of the friends and family of the school's heavy-weight
rowing crew (whose oarsmen must weigh 185 to 220 pounds each) are
grappling with what to pack for the hoity-toity event, which runs
July 1-5.
</P>
<P>
   After all, spectators at Harvard's races typically wear jeans
and sneakers. But Henley's rules clearly state that men must wear
suits and ties or blazers with flannel pants. Women must wear
dresses or suits that cover their knees. Culottes, trousers,
shorts, and jeans just aren't an option.
</P>
<P>
   As if that's not bad enough, British women take it to the
extreme, stepping out in dresses fit for a wedding reception, high
heels, and fancy hats adorned with feathers and scarves that match
their school's colors. Even gloves and parasols are part of this
social scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to buy a lot of fancy clothes just for this,''
says Joanne Moser of Moultonborough, N.H., whose son Wolfgang will
compete.
</P>
<P>
   Skirts and high heels indeed. If it rains, the grass alongside
the Thames River will turn into mud, she says, adding ``I should
bring my New Hampshire mud boots. These rules are from an era when
people had servants who looked after them. They haven't kept pace
with the times too well.''
</P>
<P>
   British men put on the ritz as well. The typical outfit is white
flannel trousers, school blazers striped in their former school's
colors and straw boater hats with coordinated ribbons. ``I don't
think there's a shop on this side of the Atlantic that sells white
flannels,'' says Peter Ellis of Cambridge, Mass., whose son David
is on the Harvard team. ``I'm wearing a blue blazer and
summer-weight gray flannels.''
</P>
<P>
   Like it or not, the Yankees are going to have to submit to the
British on this one. The rules, which date to the first races in
1839, clearly state that spectators in the Stewards' Enclosure are
required to ``dress in accordance with long-established
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep on their jeans, the Americans could stand upstream away
from the finish line and wear whatever they want. But it's
considered an honor to be invited to the Stewards' Enclosure, which
only allows a few competitors' families in. There, sitting in
canvas deck chairs and grandstands, they can see the finish line,
sip champagne, and eat strawberries with whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard doesn't compete every year, either. The heavy-weight
crew hasn't been to Henley since 1993 (the light-weight crew
competed in 1995).
</P>
<P>
   ``The dress for Henley has always been very smart,'' says Sarah
Moody, a Henley spokeswoman. ``We've had this tradition since
Henley began. You can compare it to going to a wedding as a guest.
It's a very important social occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Sahs of Southborough, Mass., who's been to Henley twice
and whose son Geoffrey is rowing this year, says, ``Picture being
invited to a Great Gatsby party. It's absolutely the most fun
parade. You stroll around while a big band plays in the pavilion.
Some women have parasols, and the men are just as decked out as the
women are. It's quite a show.''
</P>
<P>
   Cristie Ellis, 20, Peter Ellis's daughter who also lives in
Cambridge, says she's looking forward to the event and to seeing
her brother compete. A rower herself at Williams College, she says,
``This is probably the only time in my life I'll travel with a hat
box. It'll be sort of surreal standing on the shore with my
champagne glass, watching my brother sweat it out. I know how
agonizing it really is. It's sort of weird how refined (the event)
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Because royalty could very well show up, the Americans need to
be aware of the unwritten rules of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   Rule No.1? In British culture, there's absolutely no screaming
and yelling during the races. Pleeeease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is very dignified,'' says Sahs, ``You can always tell
who the Americans are. We're much more boisterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, wearing the same dress every day might raise a few
eyebrows. ``My daughter needs four dresses. Obviously, she can't be
seen in the same dress twice,'' Peter Ellis concedes. ``I'm not
sure if cotton is acceptable or if it has to be a silk blend.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtsying or bowing if you cross paths with royalty isn't likely
to come up. ``When (the royals) come, it's an organized visit, and
they're usually surrounded by security,'' says Moody, the Henley
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, hot as they may get in their jackets and ties, the men
must keep stiff upper lips and not take off their coats unless an
announcement is made over the loudspeaker that, indeed, it's too
hot to bear. Unfortunately for the men, that kind of announcement
is rare. Says Moody, ``The last one was in 1976.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long list of rules (some are published on the
Internet and others are passed along through friends), Sahs says
she's ready to embrace British ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Americans should go over there with an
attitude.'' she says. ``It's a very different culture, and it
sounds very contrived. But let me tell you, it's fun. I consider it
a huge treat to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
