<HEADLINE>
ARTS AND IDEAS GALORE AT NEW HAVEN FEST 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The third annual International Festival of Arts and Ideas will
be held in New Haven June 24-28.
</P>
<P>
   The festival features a broad range of world and American arts,
and many events will be free.
</P>
<P>
   Performances will be given by the Royal National Theatre of
London; Cirque Baroque, an international circus group; Little
Richard; the Preservation Hall Jazz Band; and the Four Nations
Ensemble, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   Originally founded to stimulate economic development, social
cohesion, and to make Connecticut and New Haven a major tourist
destination, the festival has more than succeeded in these areas.
Last year, more than 50,000 people attended.
</P>
<P>
   This year's festival features Concerts on the New Haven Green
with top names in the music world; Heart of the Matter, an
interactive, mind-expanding art and science event; International
Theater at Long Wharf Theatre, featuring an American premiere;
popular music performances at Shubert Performing Arts Center; and
stimulating talks and discussions by cultural and artistic leaders
as well as entertainment, crafts, and activities throughout
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the festival, call 203-498-1212. For concert
locations and tickets, call 888--ART-IDEA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Parks help
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's national parks are one of the greatest assets of the
land. The parks are also some of the most popular vacation places
throughout the year. With more than 300 million visitors a year,
the national parks could easily be endangered. The National Parks
and Conservation Association says that the best visitors are those
who know the regulations and leave only footprints. To help ensure
the fullest enjoyment of the parks and to protect their fragile
ecosystems, the association has published ``National Park Discover
Guides.'' The guides cover the nation's entire park system in eight
regional manuals: Alaska, Heartland, Northeast, Pacific, Pacific
Northwest, Rocky Mountain, Southeast, and Southwest. Each guide
($8.95 plus $2.85 postage) provides information on regulations,
resources, programs, plants and animals, maps, events, and points
of interest nearby. For any guide, call 800-395-PARK.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tied to earth
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for high adventure without losing contact with the
earth? The Great Balloon Experience at Fantasy of Flight in Polk
City, Fla., can do just that. It's the first tethered balloon ride
of its kind in North America. The adventure provides all the
excitement of a balloon flight without the uncertainty of knowing
when or how the gas-filled vehicle will descend. The 115-foot
Fantasy of Flight balloon can rise 500 feet, yet is securely
anchored at 16 points to the ground. Drivers on Interstate 4
between Orlando and Tampa can easily see the balloon from the
roadway. Similar balloon rides in Sweden and Germany have had a
perfect safety record, according to the operators. The attraction
is about 20 minutes west of Disney World. For information, call
941-984-3500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Shopping ideas
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Art and antiques shoppers have a unique experience available in
October. A Tale of Two Cities is a shopping tour that ranges from
the shops of London to those of Paris. Maureen Reddy Sullivan of
the DaVinci Designer Gallery in Winthrop is organizing the tour and
will use her European contacts to find collectibles. Special
courier and shipping services will be available to tour
participants. Accommodations, meals, and special events are
included in the package. The tour is set for Oct. 7-15. For
information, call 617-539-0241.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Riches of France, a Shopping and Touring Guide to the
French Provinces'' (St. Martin's Griffin, $19.95) by Maribeth
Clemente is not, as the title may imply, just a shopping guide to
France. The book reflects Clemente's ``crazy love affair with
France.'' She adds, ``I did not shop my way through the country,
rather, one could say, I chatted my way through, talking with
glassblowers, cheesemakers, potters, and many more wonderful
artisans and boutique owners, in order to learn about what they
loved to do most.'' The book reveals France through the rich
history of many of its products. Clemente also includes museums and
other places of interest, and favorite places to stay and dine.
Clemente adds the book will not go out of date because many of the
places she writes abut have been in business for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   If a book or a tour won't satisfy your French shopping desires,
then perhaps the Web will. All Things French is the first on-line
French market (www.allthingsfrench.com or www.toutestfrancais.com),
and it features more than 100 product offerings with many unique
items made not just in France but in French-speaking countries
around the globe, including the Cajun culture in the United States.
The service is bilingual and provides a way to brush up on your
French. Through June 30, visitors to the site have the opportunity
to win a trip to the south of France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Super Korea 200 is a tour package available to those flying to
Korea on Korean Air or Asiana Airlines between July 1 and Aug. 30.
The tour includes two nights' accommodation in Seoul, a city tour,
and transportation to and from the airport for $200 for one, $300
for two. Discounted air fare may also be available, except July
25-Aug. 10. For information, call Korean Air at 800-438-5000 or
Asiana Airlines at 800-227-4262.
</P>
<P>
   Comfort, Quality, Sleep Inn, and Clarion hotels are offering a
$1,000 coupon book to guests good for discounted services to
attractions ranging from Sea World and Universal Studios to the
Hard Rock Cafe and Pizza Hut.
</P>
