<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-U.S.-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH FINALLY CONCEDE AMERICA CREATES REAL JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France's Socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin visited
the United States last week to examine how its economy has created
millions of jobs during a time when his country and most of Europe
are suffering from heavy unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's trip punctured a cherished French myth. The French have
consistently argued that the vast increase in U.S. jobs since the
early 1990s was overwhelmingly due to hamburger-flipper-type work,
badly paid and without prospects of advancement.
</P>
<P>
   French officials and much of the docile media here sought to
console the more than 12 percent of their compatriots who have been
unable to get work by contending that they receive a better deal
under the protection of generous state unemployment benefits than
the mass of unskilled workers in America do from their low-level
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But Jospin, in many ways a refreshingly fair-minded politician,
decided it was time to dispel this bunkum although, as he
confessed, he had regarded it as an article of faith for years.
</P>
<P>
   He grasped that the dynamic growth of the U.S. economy, now
recognized throughout the world, made it impossible to continue
denying the fact that many good jobs were being created.
</P>
<P>
   Won over by America's unmatched prosperity, he declared that
``the first lesson to be drawn from America's economic development
and the steep drop in its unemployment, contrary to what we've long
claimed and even believed during a long period, is that the
creation of jobs in the United States is not solely or even in a
majority of cases based on low-paid, unskilled work.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that much of the 2-million-jobs-a-year increase since
1993 was in high technology and at salaries superior to the
national average. It's a record that no other country has come
close to, he added.
</P>
<P>
   A French government spokesman later explained that, with the
American model before him, the prime minister now wanted ``to give
greater weight to the spirit of enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Jospin's verdict is all the more noteworthy since, unlike
Britain's Prime Minister Tony Blair, he isn't a capitalist in
socialist clothing.
</P>
<P>
   At 65, he remains a convinced leftist who insists social justice
must have priority over the market place. The most important steps
he has taken in the year he has been prime minister have been to
introduce a mandatory 35-hour work week in an effort to persuade
employers to take on more people and to beef up the state payroll
by 750,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists are convinced that the 35-hour week will worsen
unemployment rather than cut it and that the additional state jobs,
mostly make-work schemes, will do little or nothing for the
economy. But old-line socialist dogma compelled Jospin to take
these measures against common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a trip to the United States opened his eyes. Too bad he
didn't stay there more than a few days. A longer visit might have
sent him home with some concrete ideas about how to get France back
to work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
