<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO LITTLE, TOO LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching state insurance regulators in action Monday was almost
enough to give you a fuzzy feeling about the banks, for heaven's
sake. There they were at the Marriott Copley Place in Boston, 20
regulators and aides from various states gathered around a table,
now nearly a year into their debate over the merits of the
controversial concept of mutual insurance holding companies. The
discussion was ``perfect timing,'' said Jack Ehnes, Colorado's
insurance commissioner and the chairman of the National Association
of Insurance Commissioner's working group, given that the
Massachusetts Legislature was rumored to be taking up its own
holding company bill that very day.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect timing? The debate over how the nation's mutual insurers
are going to raise billions in new capital to compete with banks
and mutual fund companies is almost over, and state insurance
regulators across the country are still trying to decide whether
the introduction of article B, section II of their ``White Paper''
should be one paragraph or four?
</P>
<P>
   No, these mostly well-meaning, underpaid regulators have lost
their chance to play a real role in one of the most critical turns
in the history of the mutual insurance industry _ and, just as
importantly, in how millions of policyholders will, or will not, be
compensated for surrendering their ownership stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the only real debate (and in some states there has been
no debate at all) has come in the legislatures, where threats by
insurance companies to move jobs to Oshkosh and campaign donations
carry a lot more weight than technical discussions about closed
blocks and dividend scales.
</P>
<P>
   In the past couple of years about 20 states have passed
holding-company laws, which would allow policyholder-owned mutual
companies to raise capital by selling up to a 49 percent interest
to investors in a stock-owned insurance subsidiary. Policyholders
would retain a stake in the holding company.
</P>
<P>
   After a year of on-again, off-again debate a holding company
bill is near final approval by the Massachusetts Legislature; it
didn't come up Monday, as Ehnes suggested but it could later in the
week, as soon as the House finishes considering the assault weapon
ban.
</P>
<P>
   The state's two largest insurers, John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. and Massachusetts Mutual Life Insurance Co., had
pushed legislators hard for this bill. But then John Hancock
dropped out, opting instead for a plan to go public through a
traditional demutualization, in which its policyholders will be
paid for their ownership interests.
</P>
<P>
   All this is the kind of stuff only an actuary could love. But
here, in short, is about all any real human being needs to know:
Under Hancock's demutualization plan, policyholders would get, on
average, maybe $2,000 in stock, cash, or policy enhancements;
should Mass. Mutual pursue a mutual holding company, its
policyholders would get zero _ that's zero as in no stock, no cash,
no policy enhancements.
</P>
<P>
   Mass. Mutual says it wants the holding company bill only as
another ``option.'' But it is the one staking out legislators in
the hallways on Beacon Hill. And its general counsel, William
Fisher, was at the microphone at the NAIC meeting repeatedly
Monday, carrying the industry argument against consumer advocates
who oppose the mutual holding company approach. David Schiff,
editor of Schiff's Insurance Observer, dogged Fisher and the state
commissioners throughout with his video camera. ``The eye of
truth,'' as Schiff called it.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday night in New York, the campaign by Governor George
Pataki and that state's biggest insurers to push through a
last-minute holding company bill collapsed. The failure came
despite personal lobbying at the State House by the chairmen of
Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. and New York Life. And it came
despite a series of 11th-hour concessions by insurers that would
have provided compensation to policyholders for their ownership
stake and linked future shareholder dividends with those of
policyholders.
</P>
<P>
   Now Massachusetts legislators are being asked to approve a bill
that consumer activists say has none of those same concessions
insurers were willing to make in New York. Monday, Fisher, Mass.
Mutual's general counsel, seemed pretty confident his company could
get it done.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
