<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CRUISING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELATED OVER THE ELATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the newest cruise ships afloat gives a new reason to sail
the West Coast. Carnival Cruises' Elation is now the largest ship
to cruise from Los Angeles to the Mexican coast.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,040-passenger vessel cruises from Los Angeles on Sundays,
calling on Puerto Vallarta, Mazatlan, and Cabo San Lucas in Mexico.
The ship allows for three ``fun'' days at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Carnival is the largest cruise line around, and each
week sails almost always full, many people have said that if
they're going to cruise, Carnival isn't for them. Too much neon,
too glitzy, it's Las Vegas at sea, they say, adding that they don't
think the food is up to their standards. My wife was one of those
critics until I persuaded her it was time to try Carnival.
</P>
<P>
   Our brief cruise aboard the Elation changed her mind. One reason
was that Joe Farcus was aboard. Farcus has been designing the
interiors of Carnival ships for 21 years. He likes innovation and
he likes people to know they're not at home but on an adventure. He
believes in designing up, not down, for people, and that the design
affects the experience of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation offers a new experience and one that should appeal
to a broader market. My wife liked what he had to say, and
appreciated his art all the more, especially after Farcus explained
details that we might have missed.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation's interior design is fun. The Jekyll and Hyde Dance
Club has eight-foot-tall sculptures with faces split to convey both
benevolence and menace, eyes glowing as their heads swivel right
and left to the music's tempo, and occasionally blowing puffs of
smoke. In Duke's, the piano lounge named for Duke Ellington,
there's a New York motif with scale models of the city's famed
buildings, even a detailed model of the Brooklyn Bridge. There's
even a zeppelin floating in the sky, and tiny zeppelins embedded in
the rug design. Fun rooms.
</P>
<P>
   The quality of materials and features throughout the ship are
superior to that found in most hotels or resorts.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has its quiet areas, like the Mark Twain Library, done
in the style of a river steamboat. As Dorothy might say, ``We're
not in Kansas anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The ship is designed to be enjoyed. Maybe it's not for everyone,
but it made my wife happy. She was impressed with the quality of
the food, the facilities on board, the size of the cabins, and even
the baths, which were more spacious than on some ships we've
sailed.
</P>
<P>
   The ship dazzles with its shows, casino, and lounges. There's
even a wonderful children's area, with everything from a play area
to computers to learn on. There's even a conference center. And a
grand fitness center overlooks the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation has an innovative propulsion system that pulls
rather than pushes the ship through the water. The engine is
quieter, less thirsty, and makes the vessel easier to maneuver.
Passengers will notice none of this, but it's nice to know it's
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Elation is the seventh ship in Carnival's Fantasy class of
70,000-ton vessels. The final edition will be the Paradise, billed
as the world's first smoke-free cruise ship. The Paradise begins
Sunday cruising on Dec. 6 from Miami with seven-day cruises
alternating between the eastern and western Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is sure: Even though there will be eight ships in the
Fantasy class, and even though they have many similarities as to
location of public rooms, each is distinct and fun.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival recently completed the acquisition of the Cunard Line
and is already beginning to create new life for the venerable line.
Larry Pimentel, Cunard's new president, announced that the line
will build a ``stately superliner that will evoke the spirit of a
bygone era of seagoing luxury. Our goal is nothing less than to
create a new golden age of sea travel for those who missed the
first.''
</P>
<P>
   No further information was given on the plans other then to note
the ship will not replace the QE2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cruise happenings
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seabourn Cruise Line will hold a Twentieth Century Fox Film
Retrospective cruise with guest lecturers and films from the golden
years of Hollywood. The 12-day cruise on the Seabourn Pride will
sail from New York on Oct. 20. Movie stars June Haver and Donald
O'Conner will be aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Aloha Festivals/Hawaiian Heritage theme cruises will be held on
American Hawaii Cruise Independence on Sept. 12, 19, and 26 and
Oct. 3. The weeklong cruises that visit the Hawaiian islands will
feature onboard activities on music, history, dance, and the arts
of the islands.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone wants to fly to take a cruise. Uncommon Journeys
(309 Lennon Lane, Suite 101, Walnut Creek, CA 94598; telephone
800-323-5893) features rail-to-ship trips. Among offerings are A
Journey to Quebec by streamliner train to the Queen Elizabeth 2,
Oct. 5-15. Travelers will depart New York City to Quebec City for
the voyage.
</P>
<P>
   United and Northwest Airlines will award members of their
frequent-flier programs 20,000-30,000 bonus miles per stateroom on
23 voyages of Radisson Seven Seas Cruises 180-passenger Song of
Flower in Arabia and Asia from October 1998 through December 1999
if the trip is booked by Aug. 1, 1998. The voyages range from eight
to 14 nights in length.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Olson Cruise Lines is offering a 25 percent discount and
free air fare on fall cruises from Barbados. The cruises are aboard
the Black Watch (formerly the Royal Viking Star). The 12-day
cruises begin at $2,016 a person. For information, call EuroCruises
at 800-661-1119.
</P>
<P>
   Where will you be on Dec. 31, 1999? If you cruise on Holland
America Line, you could have the opportunity to celebrate the turn
of the century twice, toasting it in Hawaii or on a Panama Canal
cruise. Bookings for the millennium cruises have just opened, and
travelers wishing to lock in their cruise are asked for a $500
deposit on seven-day cruises or $1,000 a person on cruises of 10
days or longer. Early booking discounts will be available. To
celebrate the new century, the Nieuw Amsterdam on its Australia/New
Zealand cruise will sail east across the International Dateline
into ``yesterday'' so they can celebrate all over again.
</P>
<P>
   This being honeymoon season, many who are about to be married
may want to know about honeymoon cruises. The Cruise Line, which
offers savings of $300 to $2,000 on cruises it sells, has a free
32-page Guide to Cruise Ship Honeymoons &AMP; Weddings. For a guide,
call 800-777-0707.
</P>
<P>
   Ivaran Lines, which operates the luxury passenger freighter
American, is now including gratuities for onboard staff in its
pricing for 1999. The cruises from Houston to South American ports
begin at $4,458 for an inside single. Special cruises, booked by
Nov. 19, come with a savings of up to 20 percent off '99 rates.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing you'd think cruise passengers would want to be
reminded of is a seagoing tragedy. But when it involves the
Titanic, anything goes. The film ``Titanic'' is being credited with
a new interest in cruising. And this summer, guests on Holland
America Line's Veendam cruises to New England and Canada will call
on Halifax, Nova Scotia, where they will explore sites and
memorabillia associated with the sinking. Haligonians were
commended at the time for their response and compassion during the
relief effort in 1912.
</P>
<P>
   Most people who take a cruise like to know where they are going.
However, those booking a cruise on the Delta Queen Aug. 25 will
only know where they are leaving from (Little Rock) and where they
will disembark (Cincinnati). Captain Gabe Chengery of the historic
paddlewheeler says, ``Nothing is definite, except that I guarantee
an adventure _ just like traveling aboard steamers a century ago.''
The captain plans to ``tie up'' wherever the whim arises. If you
choose to wait till next year to take a ``tramping'' (stopping
wherever and whenever) cruise, free air fare is being offered. Call
800-543-1949 for details. Fares for the eight-day '98 cruise begin
at $1,350 a person; in '99, a seven-day version begins at $1,050.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barging in America
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   America's great rivers _ the Mississippi and Ohio among them _
have been known for two means of transportation, steamboats, and
barges. Travelers will now be able to cruise these and other
waterways on a luxury barge. RiverBarge Excursion Lines offers a
different way of looking at the rivers.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, the river barge has evolved into a luxury means of
transportation; now the same will be true in America. The River
Explorer is the first American-built first-class hotel barge and
will offer four- to 10- day excursions throughout America's
heartland rivers and the Gulf Intra Coastal Waterway.
</P>
<P>
   The River Explorer is actually two 295-foot-long barges that are
connected together. The aft barge contains 100 spacious staterooms
that give the barge a 200-passenger capacity. All staterooms
feature large picture windows, a choice of twin- or queen-size
beds, a television with a VCR, phones, mini-refrigerators,
coffeemakers, irons, and a bathroom with a tub. The forward barge
contains public rooms, including a single and open-seating dining
room, a show lounge, a bar, a gift shop, a library, a game room,
and a Pilot House, a re-creation of a working pilot house with
radios, radar, maps, and a large window over the bow for viewing
the river.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises begin at $750 a person for a four-day excursion and
include tips, taxes, port charges, and scheduled shore excursions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We designed the River Explorer so it will offer a wide range
of comforts, options, and amenities, which we think our guests will
find desirable,'' said Jeff Krida, RiverBarge Excursion Lines
president. ``And, apart from a wonderful vessel, we also will be
offering our guests the opportunity to partake in the customs and
traditions of the folks who live along the waterways we'll visit.''
Krida, who once headed the Delta Queen Steamboat Co., added, ``The
barge platform has given us a dependable and proven base to build a
wonderful floating hotel/resort, and we're doing just that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
