<HEADLINE>
FUN AT THE AIRPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hanging around airports can be B-O-R-I-N-G, especially when your
flight has been delayed. But maybe you'll be lucky and find
yourself in one of these airports that, according to Travel
Holiday, feature unique diversions.
</P>
<P>
   _Schiphol in Amsterdam. There is a casino where you can play
roulette, blackjack, or slots and where 16 kinds of currency are
accepted. (The casino is between the west wing and the central
terminal, beyond Customs.)
</P>
<P>
   _Miami International. At the Airport Hotel, you can swim in an
outdoor pool, get some sun, take a sauna, or jog on a track for a
mere $8. Locker rooms and showers are available, too. (Head for
Concourse E, second floor.)
</P>
<P>
   _Milwaukee Airport. The Renaissance Bookshop sells used
paperbacks, vintage Life magazines, even gems like a Steinbeck
first edition for $35. (The shop is in the main terminal.)
</P>
<P>
   _Orlando International. The world's first airport microbrewery
offers five beers, darts, and a tour of the facility. And if you
have enough brews, you won't care how late your plane is. (The
microbrewery is in the main terminal's central corridor. A second
pub is near gates 60-99.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  An American and an Irishman bump into each other.
``Sorry,'' says one. ``I wasn't looking where I was going.''
``Excuse me,'' says the other. ``Neither was I.'' Which is the
American? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; And speaking of Irish things: &LR;  We recently mentioned that an old
Irish nickname for a pint of Guinness is a ``parish priest.''
Edward J. Flynn of Peabody writes that another nickname for
Guinness, with its dark body and white foamy top, is ``the blond in
the black dress.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable: &LR;  ``I haven't been Everywhere, but it's on my list.'' _
Susan Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  Viagra is not yet legal in Canada. But so many Canadian
men have been crossing the border to fill prescriptions of the
impotence drug that ``The Honeymoon Capital of the World'' has
gained another nickname: Viagra Falls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  The Hotel Inter-Continental in
Tashkent, Uzbekistan, has an order form for room-service breakfast
that instructs the guest to ``please hang the completed doorknob
outside your room before retiring.'' (With thanks to Elia L. Puffer
of Winchester.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Seen in the sky:  &LR; Apparently the airlines consider ``One Fine Day''
to be one fine movie: It was selected by the greatest number of
airlines worldwide for in-flight vieiwng during 1997. Here,
according to the World Airline Entertainment Association, are the
rest of the top five: ``Jerry McGuire,'' ``The First Wives Club,''
``101 Dalmations,'' and ``The Saint.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; It's contest time:  &LR; You're driving along and suddenly a tune enters
your head _ and you can't stop singing it! Don't fret: It might
give you fame of sorts. Just sing your favorite song into a tape
recorder. Then write in 50 words or fewer why the song is your
favorite to sing while traveling. Then submit tape and essay to
Dramamine Drives, c/o CGI Group, PO Box 3842, Grand Central
Station, New York, NY 10163. The grand prize winner gets to sing at
a professional venue in his or her hometown. Entries must be
postmarked by June 30, and tapes and essays will not be returned _
as if you really wanted them back.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Tired travel joke:  &LR; A man checks in at an airport counter. He says,
``I've got three suitcases. I want you to send one to New York, one
to Chicago, and one to L.A. ``I'm sorry,'' the attendant replies,
``we can't do that.'' ``Really?'' the customer says. ``You did last
week!'' (With thanks to Josef Orosz of Cyberspace.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  The American is the one who said ``Excuse me.''
``Sorry'' is the more common expression in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
