<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FIRING OF AL DUNLAP, FROM THE PEN OF FRANZ KAFKA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Al Dunlap awoke one morning from a troubled dream, he found
himself changed in his bed into a monstrous insect. He lay on his
back, which was as hard as armor plate, and, raising his head a
little, he could see the arch of his great brown belly, divided by
bowed corrugations. The pattern of his stomach faintly reminded him
of a Grillmaster grill.
</P>
<P>
   Al was chief executive of Sunbeam Corp., and his products _
barbecue grills, coffee makers, smoke detectors, electric blankets
_ were never far from his thoughts. He heard a soft gurgle from his
bureau and was cheered by the thought that his Mr. Coffee had
completed its automatic brewing. He shifted his buglike eyes to a
tiny, red light overhead _ it was his First Alert smoke detector.
His Sunbeam electric blanket slipped off his belly, and Al's legs,
pitiably thin compared with their former size, fluttered helplessly
before his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has happened to me?'' he thought.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed what had happened? Here was the high-flying chief
executive _ so ruthless and unforgiving he was known as ``Chain Saw
Al'' and ``Rambo in Pinstripes'' _ now reduced to a quivering
insect. Al was the turnaround magician who had waved his chain saw
at Scott Paper Co., hacked off 11,000 jobs, saved the company, and
walked away with his reward of $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sunbeam had been so impressed _ and so financially distressed _
it booked the rescue artist for an encore performance in corporate
triage. Again Al whipped out his enchanted chain saw and sheared
away 6,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Things couldn't have looked better. When Superman Al first flew
in through the window at Sunbeam, the stock price leaped 49 percent
in a single bound. Soon he was boasting of a swift and efficient
turnaround. But lately, the magician had been revealed for a
curious sleight of hand. Last year, earnings had been artificially
inflated by an accounting gimmick, it was disclosed, and Sunbeam's
stock had plunged back to earth, losing half its value in three
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I will fix everything,'' thought Al. ``If I can just get
myself out of this bed.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a cautious tap at his locked door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert,'' said a voice _ it was his wife. ``It's a quarter to
seven. Didn't you want to fire more people today?''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, of course, that was his only solution. He had to cut costs
still further by hurling hundreds more employees out into the
streets. He lay on his hard-shell back and, rubbing his scrawny
feet together, muttered diabolically: ``I'll crush them like
insects.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought momentarily lifted his spirits. And he started
rocking his body, with the idea of swinging himself onto the floor.
When at last he was half out of bed, there came a second knock at
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert,'' his wife whispered. ``Mr. Price and Mr. Perelman are
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors Michael Price and Ronald Perelman were the biggest
shareholders in Sunbeam. They had been bitterly disappointed over
the past several months as the value of their holdings had
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on in there?'' Price demanded. ``Open the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Chain Saw Al was uncharacteristically silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't seem your old self, Al,'' Perelman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A slight illness, an attack of giddiness,'' replied Al. His
voice had a horrible twittering squeak.
</P>
<P>
   Price came right to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've wrecked everything, Al,'' he said. ``You're not what
you appear to be. You leave us no choice. Open the door, Al. One
way or another we're coming in there and we're going to crush you
like a bug!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(AT)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
