<SLUG> BC-GLF-OPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE OLYMPIC, A GOLD MEDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Early in Sunday's final round, when the
ne'er-do-wells and also-rans and never-rans were teeing it up in
the US Open, the volunteers manning the leaderboards needed
something to do to pass the long hours until the leaders teed off.
</P>
<P>
   They posted scores.
</P>
<P>
   Many of which were all in red.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Azinger's was the most brilliant red of all, a 5-under-par
round of 65. The red numbers, for sub-par scores, also were posted
beside the names of Mark O'Meara, Jeff Sluman, and Colin ``Jousting
With The Galleries'' Montgomerie. Why not? All were far back, none
of them felt any pressure, and they could whale away at the Olympic
Club at will.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And then came green number after green number, ugly green
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   For the longest part of the afternoon, when the Olympic Club
leveled the world's best golfers, there were no red numbers on the
leaderboard after the names of the top 10. Instead there were only
those green numbers _ for par or over-par golf _ until a solitary
red number went up by the name of David Duval, who broke par by a
single stroke, and then by the name of eventual winner Lee Janzen,
who finished 2 under for the day.
</P>
<P>
   But, for overall scores for four days of trying to survive
Olympic, there was not a single red number. Janzen's final number _
a ``0'' for level par _ also was in ugly green.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympic Club had won the Open. Janzen had survived and taken
home the $535,000 winner's check because some golfer must be
declared the winner, but it was the golf course itself that had
won. As is usually the case with the United States Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Olympic Club really won, because there was only
one person even par for the tournament,'' said Payne Stewart, who
once led by five strokes but succumbed to Olympic and the Open
pressure to blow the largest Sunday lead since Tony Jacklin had a
four-stroke lead in 1970. ``I think this golf course stood up to
the test of being an Open Championship course.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the furor over the impossible pin placement on a top
slope of the 18th green Friday, for which the US Golf Association
apologized, Stewart conceded that the course was ``fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course was every bit championship-caliber,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The USGA takes untold abuse year after year for making its Open
courses as difficult as possible. The best golfers in the world,
believing that the minus-16 scores posted at Pleasant Valley or
Hartford or Memphis are their birthright, moan and then moan some
more. Jack Nicklaus call these golfers ``whiners,'' and whiners
they are.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of this Open, golfer after golfer had stopped
moaning and was complimenting Olympic and, by entension, the USGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the USGA ever decided to go on rotation, Olympic should
definitely be in the rotation,'' said Azinger. ``I think the
golfers, for the most part, all love this course.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, if the powers that be wish to give the United States a
home-course advantage for the Ryder Cup at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass. next year, they might copy what the USGA does at
its Open courses _ let the rough grow. Specifically, let the rough
grow around the greens, that high rough only a few feet from the
greens that bedeviled golfer after golfer, particularly the
Europeans. Lee Westwood (tied for seventh) and Nick Price (fourth)
were the only foreigners to finish among the top 14.
</P>
<P>
   Even Montgomerie, the Scot whose 69 Sunday brought a horrible
performance back to respectability _ he finished 18th _ praised
Olympic despite enduring more than a few catcalls from the gallery.
Several fans jeered Montgomerie, doubtlessly engendering more
anti-US fervor in the London tabloids ``and it all had to do with
the Ryder Cup,'' he said. ``I was seemed to be blamed for (Europe)
winning the Ryder Cup. But it's always the minority more vocal than
the majority, unfortunately.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the course itself, ``I think they set this course up
fantastic,'' said Montgomerie. ``It's a real mental battle, and you
get rewarded for good shots and you definitely get penalized for
bad ones. I'm a great fan of that and always will be, and I think
(the USGA) has done a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   This Open at Olympic will be remembered for much: for Tiger
Woods officially stepping down from Olympus and becoming just
another good golfer; for Casey Martin proving he is an exceptional
golfer and more than just a man who needs a golf cart to get
around; and for the fresh face and fresher smile of amateur Matt
Kuchar lighting up the Open just as they had lit up the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Olympic itself that will be most remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard out there,'' said Duval. ``It was hard Saturday
and hard the day before that. You can't define it. I mean, it's so
subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said this was the hardest course he has played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had to carve a golf shot on every hole as I had to
carve a golf shot here,'' he said. ``You had to slam it against a
slope or else you go into rough. Then ... it's tough to make a
15-foot putt here.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly as the test to find the national champion should be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
