<HEADLINE>
`MONK AND MINGUS' MAKE BEAUTIFUL MUSIC TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHILIP ELWOOD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Monk and Mingus'' _ a conveniently alliterative
matching of jazz pantheon members' names _ was the only title that
the JVC Jazz Festival's Symphony Space marquee needed to lure 1,000
jazz fans, young and old, to the nicely renovated old theater.
</P>
<P>
   As structured by drummer-leader T.S. Monk Jr., the musical
portions of his tentet's ``Monk on Monk Tribute,'' are presumably
held together by his rambling reminiscences and anecdotes about his
famous pianist-composer father.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his remarks (often frivolous and apocryphal) bog down
his set's musical momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Monk composed at the piano, worked regularly as a
quartet leader and was never successful in the role of a big-band
leader at the keyboard. His son, wisely making use of a midsized
piano, bass, four-sax, three brass and drums complement _ and
employing lead trumpeter Don Sickler's brilliant arrangements _ has
come up with a marvelous book of Monk music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Epistrophy,'' loaded with cascading, dissonant runs undercut
by Howard Johnson's surging baritone sax, proved a perfect
overture, leading into ``Bye-Ya,'' which was followed (after T.S.'s
first stand-up monologue) by a magnificent rendition of
``Evidence,'' featuring Jeff Stockham's French horn solo and a
couple of passages by an unusual baritone sax-clarinet-alto
sax-soprano sax quartet, which spun off into individual solos.
Pianist Ronnie Matthews, masterful in his Monkish chording, seldom
uses Monk's jagged rhythms and broken meters _ on ``Evidence,''
however, he inserted a chorus of ``Thelonious,'' much to my
delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I Mean You,'' a wonderful Sickler orchestration with John
Gordon on Bird-like alto, is a lusty romp, and Nneenna Frelon's
vocals on ``Ruby, My Dear'' and ``In Walked Bud'' fitted into the
performance nicely. Outstanding tenor sax work by Johnson and Dave
Schumacher and trombone by Eddie Bert were highlights.
</P>
<P>
   By midconcert, T.S.'s ever-longer commentary was backed lightly
by pianist Matthews and bassist Gary Wang. ``Four in One,'' an
expanded version of one of Monk's more complex compositions, was a
fitting conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Monk mavens might note that Monk's wife (T.S.'s mother),
``Nellie'' (as in Monk's tune ``Crepescule for Nellie''), was
sitting behind me, having a grand time and looking great.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing the evening's bill with T.S. Monk was the Mingus Big
Band, playing its familiar Mingus stuff like ``Moanin'' and ``Love
Chant,'' as well as ``Sweet Supper Dance,'' the multipart
``Kuumbwa'' and a sensational arrangement of ``Isabel's Table
Dance'' (from Mingus' famed ``Tijuana Moods'' recording), complete
with a castanet-clicking, lady-in-red, Spanish dancer.
</P>
<P>
   She danced on stage, not on a table.
</P>
<P>
   Though the New York-based Mingus Band's complement of 14 to 15
is in a constant state of flux, it draws from a pool of 40 to 50
musicians, all of whom share an enthusiasm for the free-spirited,
go-for-it, Mingus musical mode. Outstanding at the Symphony Space
concert on Friday were Andy McKee (emerging as a great
band-bassist), Ronnie Cuber (baritone saxist and Mingus Band
concertmaster), alto saxist Vincent Herring, trombonist Britt
Woodman (there's a legendary name) and pianist Dave Kitakovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Mingus' concept of composition and orchestration was founded on
his role as bassist and pianist _ bassists are part of both the
rhythm and harmony segments of a band; pianists, in modern jazz
groups, eschew melody, suggest harmonies and expand melodic lines.
While listening to the Mingus Big Band, one feels the spirit, the
freedom, the expansiveness (melody, harmony, rhythm) that Mingus
pursued in his music _ and in his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
