<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2367 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPES-COBBLER2     06-23 2398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES-COBBLER24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cobbler recipes are simple and follow basic rules
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's hardly a better way to enjoy summer fruits than cobbled
with biscuit topping and crowned with pure vanilla ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Cobblers and crisps (and crumbles and slumps and grunts) are
truly folk food, as Richard Sax explains in his book, ``Classic
Home Desserts'' (Chapters, $29.95). And he came up with no less
than 18 different recipes.
</P>
<P>
   But all of them break down to the essentials: fruit and dough,
or some crumbly-sweet topping. And there are some basic rules. It's
best to use the ripest fruits possible, because they will provide
more juices. And don't be afraid to play with the amount of sugar
in a recipe. Adjust to your taste and to the sweetness of the
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Don't overmix or stir. That's especially true, Sax wrote, to get
a light biscuit topping. We'd also recommend paying careful
attention to the kind of flour a recipe calls for. The simplest
recipes will call for self-rising flour.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, your imagination is the limit. To get started, try
some of these ideas.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Gingersnap Rhubarb Crisp
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This recipe comes from Marcia Adams' ``New Recipes From Quilt
Country'' (Clarkson Potter, $30) and is a tradition on ``work
days,'' or days when Amish women gather to do canning, special
heavy cleaning and other chores.
</P>
<P>
   1cup gingersnap crumbs (about 20 cookies), homemade or bought
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup quick-cooking oats (not instant)
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   2pounds fresh rhubarb, cut into 1/2-inch pieces (about 6 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup light brown sugar, firmly packed
</P>
<P>
   Red food coloring (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. In a small bowl, combine the
gingersnap crumbs, oats and nutmeg. In a large bowl, combine the
rhubarb, granulated sugar and brown sugar. Add a few drops of red
food coloring to tint the mixture light pink, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Grease a 2-quart flat casserole and sprinkle 1/4 cup of the
crumb mixture on the bottom. Add half the rhubarb and top with 1/2
cup of the crumb mixture. Add the rest of the rhubarb and top with
the remaining crumbs. Dot mixture with butter and bake for 35 to 40
minutes, or until the top of the crisp is browned and bubbling up
in the center. Serve warm with cream or a scoop of ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 429 calories, 5 grams protein, 9 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 19), 85 grams carbohydrates, 15 milligrams
cholesterol, 223 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Peach Blueberry Cobbler
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Peach Blueberry Cobbler
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The combination of peaches and blueberries not only tastes
sensational, but it looks sensational, too. This recipe provides
ample, biscuitlike crust. It comes from April Moon's ``The Flying
Biscuit Cookbook: Breakfast and Beyond'' (Longstreet Press, $14).
</P>
<P>
   2cups fresh blueberries, washed and dried
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2pounds fresh peaches, peeled and thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2cups plus 1/4 cup all-purpose flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup plus 3 tablespoons granulated sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   TOPPING:
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon plus 1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   4tablespoons unsalted butter, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons raw sugar for sprinkling over the top
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a large bowl mix blueberries,
peaches, 1/4 cup flour, 2/3 cup sugar and nutmeg. Turn fruit into a
2-quart baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Topping: Place 2 cups flour, baking powder, salt and 3
tablespoons sugar in a mixing bowl. Cut butter into 1/2
tablespoon-size pieces and work into the flour with your fingertips
or a pastry cutter until mixture resembles coarse meal. With a
wooden spoon, stir in cream and mix until just combined.
</P>
<P>
   Using a tablespoon, drop batter over the top of fruit until
entire surface is covered. Sprinkle with 2 tablespoons raw sugar.
Bake cobbler for 40 to 50 minutes. The top will be golden and the
center bubbling when done. Serve warm, with a scoop of vanilla bean
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 440 calories, 5 grams protein, 17 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 36), 69 grams carbohydrates, 57
milligrams cholesterol, 498 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Wild Blackberry Cobbler
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   June means it's blackberry-picking time, and novelist and food
writer Jack Butler suggests there's no better way to enjoy the
jewels than in this cobbler. We tried his recipe from ``Jack's
Skillet: Plain Talk and Some Recipes From a Guy in the Kitchen''
(Algonquin Books, $19.95) and have to agree.
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unbleached all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1Universal Black Iron Skillet Pie Crust (see recipe above)
</P>
<P>
   6cups fresh or frozen blackberries
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a mixing bowl, cut butter or
margarine into flour until mix is consistency of cornmeal. Then
thoroughly mix in 1/4 cup to 1/2 cup of the sugar, according to
taste. Layer the prepared crust with about a third of the berries.
Sprinkle this layer liberally with about a third of the remaining
sugar, then sprinkle it with a third of the butter-flour-sugar mix.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out dough scraps as thin as you can make them and top the
layer of berries. (You don't have to cover the berries completely,
as this layer of dough serves to create dumplings.) Repeat this
process twice more, so that you have 3 layers of berries and your
skillet is full. For the final layer of berries, you may wish to
cut your dough into strips for a latticework top crust or into
other decorative shapes. Sprinkle the top crust lightly with sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Put cobbler in oven. Check it after 40 minutes, although it may
need another 10 minutes or so. It is done when the crust is
browning lightly and the dark juices are bubbling up through the
top crust.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 436 calories, 5 grams protein, 18 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 37), 67 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 257 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Universal Black Iron Skillet
</P>
<P>
   Pie Crust
</P>
<P>
   Makes one 10-inch pie crust plus dumplings or two 9-inch pie
crusts
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 40-50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2cups unbleached white flour
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup ice water
</P>
<P>
   Mix flour and salt in a bowl. Cut in margarine or butter with a
table knife or rubber spatula until mix has the consistency of
cornmeal. Trickle in ice water gradually, mixing with spatula until
dough balls up. You probably won't need all the water. Do not knead
the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Roll dough out on floured board, dusting both sides as needed to
keep it from sticking to the board or the rolling pin. Roll out to
desired thiness (for a truly flaky rather than stout crust, usually
1/16 inch or less). Roll out evenly in all directions, forming a
rough circle. When the circle is 3 or 4 inches wider in diameter
than necessary to fill a 2 inch-deep, 10 1/4-inch black iron
skillt, it is about the right thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Lift the crust and fit into the skillet, then trim the edges
with a knife. (The crust may tear as you lift it into the skillet.
No problem. It tears because it is fragile, which means it will be
truly crisp and delicate in texture. Make patches from the remnant
dough, moisten the edges with ice water and press the patches into
place in the skillet.)
</P>
<P>
   Press a dinner fork around the edges of the crust to provide a
decorative crenelation. Depending on the filling, the leftover
dough may be used for stripping for the top, as with a cobbler, or
as dumplings for the interior.
</P>
<P>
   Bake as needed for the particular filling. With any given dish,
you generally don't want the crust to bake more than 40 to 50
minutes. If the filling is cooked ahead of time and requires less
baking time, brown the crust at 375 for 10 minutes before adding
the filling.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (8 servings): 243 calories, 3 grams protein, 16
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 22), 66 grams carbohydrates,
no cholesterol, 238 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Plum Oatmeal Crisp
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the easiest ways to gussy up plums, and the oats
make a classic crisp topping.
</P>
<P>
   3plums ( 1/2 pound), pitted and chopped (about 1 3/4 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup firmly packed light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup old-fashioned rolled oats
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup finely chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons cold unsalted butter, cut into bits
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla ice cream as accompaniment, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. In a bowl stir together the plums,
lemon juice and granulated sugar; spread the mixture evenly in the
bottom of a buttered 8-inch-square pan. In another bowl blend the
brown sugar, flour, oats, salt, cinnamon, ginger, walnuts and
butter until the mixture resembles coarse meal. Sprinkle the brown
sugar mixture evenly over the plum mixture and bake the dessert in
the middle of oven for 30 to 35 minutes, or until it is crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Serve while warm with vanilla ice cream. -- Gourmet magazine,
September 1990
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 379 calories, 7 grams protein, 15 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 35), 58 grams carbohydrates, 23
milligrams cholesterol, 67 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Mango Cobbler
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This is Dana Phelps-Marschalk's recipe adapted for mangoes. But
if you want to try other fruits, sprinkle with up to 1/2 cup sugar
and allow to sit at room temperature for an hour. You can also
increase the sugar in the dough up to 1 cup. It's all a matter of
what your sweet tooth desires.
</P>
<P>
   2cups sliced mangoes, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1cup self-rising flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   Dash salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Allow mangoes to sit at room
temperature for one hour. Melt the butter in an 8-by-8-inch baking
pan. Combine the flour, sugar, salt and milk. Drop spoonfuls of the
flour mixture into the melted butter. Do not mix or stir. Then drop
the fruit on top of the butter and around the batter. Again, do not
mix or stir. Bake for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 321 calories, 3 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 46), 42 grams carbohydrates, 43
milligrams cholesterol, 312 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Blackberry and Blueberry Slump (Grunt)
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   A slump or grunt is so named because of the sound the berries
make while boiling. This recipe comes from Richard Sax's ``Classic
Home Desserts'' (Chapters, $29.95), which is loaded with
fruit-dessert recipes.
</P>
<P>
   1generous pint fresh blueberries (or 2 cups frozen)
</P>
<P>
   1generous pint blackberries (or 2 cups frozen)
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup plus 2 tablespoons granulated sugar (or more to taste),
divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup water
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Pinch each of ground cinnamon and freshly ground pepper
(optional)
</P>
<P>
   1cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/8teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons unsalted butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup buttermilk (or a mixture of plain yogurt and skim milk
and water) plus more if needed
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons cinnamon-sugar, for topping
</P>
<P>
   Heavy cream or ice cream for serving, if desired
</P>
<P>
   Place the berries in an 8-inch cast-iron skillet or shallow
heatproof casserole and add 3/4 cup sugar (or more to taste),
water, lemon juice and the optional cinnamon and pepper, if
preferred. Toss gently to combine and set aside. In a mixing bowl,
stir together the flour, 2 tablespoons sugar, baking powder, baking
soda and salt. Stir in the melted butter. Add enough of the
buttermilk to form a soft, sticky dough that is slightly wetter
than biscuit dough.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the skillet with the berries in it and bring to a boil.
Lower the heat to a steady simmer, uncover and spoon the dough over
the fruit, forming small dumplings with a soup spoon. Sprinkle
dumplings with cinnamon-sugar. Tightly cover the skillet with the
lid or a sheet of foil and steam the mixture over medium-low heat
until the dumplings set and their surface is dry when touched,
usually about 15 minutes. Spoon the slump into serving bowls, and
top with heavy cream or ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 291 calories, 3 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 14), 61 grams carbohydrates, 11 milligrams
cholesterol, 245 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Apricot Cherry Cobbler
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   It's worth seeking out fresh cherries at the farmers market to
make this cobbler because they taste so good with the apricots.
Pulling the cobbler together is an unusual cornmeal topping.
</P>
<P>
   8fresh apricots, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup plus 1 1/2 tablespoons plus 1 teaspoon granulated sugar,
divided
</P>
<P>
   2cups pitted fresh cherries
</P>
<P>
   1cup plus 1 tablespoon all-purpose flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon grated orange peel
</P>
<P>
   5tablespoons unsalted butter, chilled
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 375 degrees. Combine apricots and 1/3 cup sugar and
set aside. Combine cherries and 1 tablespoon flour and set aside.
Combine the 1 cup flour, cornmeal, salt, 1 1/2 tablespoons sugar
and baking powder. Stir in orange peel. Cut in butter until mixture
resembles coarse meal. Add milk; stir just to moisten dry
ingredients. Combine fruit in buttered 1 1/2-quart baking dish.
Spoon batter over top. Sprinkle with remaining 1 teaspoon sugar.
Bake 25-30 minutes or until golden brown. Cool slightly and serve.
-- California Apricot Advisory Board
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 324 calories, 5 grams protein, 11 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 31), 53 grams carbohydrates, 27
milligrams cholesterol, 340 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
