<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-US-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US DOWN TO LAST STRIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LYON, France _ They are among the World Cup zombies now,
wandering around the countryside with the Japanese and the Saudis
and the Jamaicans and the rest of the walking dead.
</P>
<P>
   The US men's soccer team, eliminated from the tournament by its
2-1 loss to Iran here Sunday night, still has to play Yugoslavia in
its group finale Thursday night. So the players arose stiff-legged
and glassy-eyed Monday, slipped into their team blazers, caught a
flight to Nantes, and went back out on the practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Dead or not, the Yanks still have something to prove to the
world: that they can match up with the best sides on the planet and
play entertaining soccer doing it. And if they play like zombies in
Nantes, they'll be soundly hammered by the Yugoslavs, who can still
be eliminated even though they're undefeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play to win,'' vowed US coach Steve Sampson,
who could be out of a job if his squad does not. ``We're going to
play to get a result. The objective in the third match has not
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the stakes have, dramatically. Ever since last December's
draw, the US had assumed that it would still be alive and kicking
coming into the Yugoslavia match.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept was to get a tie against Germany and get a win
against Iran,'' Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after losing, 2-0, to the Germans, the Americans would have
advanced to the second round _ their announced goal _ by winning
their other two matches. That was why Sampson shook up his lineup
against the Iranians and loaded it with attacking players, to go
for the knockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we took the risk of sending so many people
forward,'' he said. ``Because we needed the 3 points.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans created dozens of scoring chances. They took 27
shots, whacking balls off both posts and the crossbar. Even after
Iran burned them twice for goals on counterattacks, the Americans
kept risking, pushing, shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We scored another goal and you didn't,'' Iranian coach Jalal
Talebi told Sampson afterward. ``That is the only reason why you
didn't win in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   For all that, the Yanks still went two-and-out, walking off the
pitch at Stade Gerland depleted and deflated as Iranian drums
pounded a victory beat all around them. ``Fin Des Illusions
Americaines,'' L'Equipe, the French sporting daily, proclaimed
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had no illusions about winning the Cup. Their
admittedly bold master plan/pipedream doesn't have them doing that
until 2010. They knew, in their heart of hearts, that it would be a
coup even to survive their group.
</P>
<P>
   What they wanted to show here was that 1994 had not been an
illusion, that their results since then _ victories over Mexico and
Nigeria and Argentina and Brazil and Austria _ showed that the US
had evolved from the college all-star side that got a harsh lesson
in the global grad school eight years ago. That they had developed
a tactical sophistication, that they had learned how to impose
their game on a rival, that they knew how to get whatever result
they needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show that we'd improved,'' said Ramos, who was
playing in his third Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans did not show that against the Germans, when they
came out on tentative tiptoes and were knocked back on their heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed them too much respect in the first half,'' Sampson
said. ``The Germans were ripe for the taking.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Americans imposed themselves on the Iranians from the
first minute, and got everything but the result.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans had bad luck,'' said Miljan Miljanic, president
of the Yugoslav football federation.Monday ``They should have won
the match.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the should-have/could-haves were done, what the world
saw was that the Americans had lost to a team that hadn't been to
the dance in 20 years, had never won a Cup match, and needed a
miracle to get here. Unless you can win matches when the world is
watching, the world doesn't want to hear about your improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to leave here at least winning one game,'' said
Ramos, who is 1-7-1 in his Cup career. ``But it's going to be
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs, who were banned from the last tournament, are
very much alive and need at least a draw to advance. And they've
seen enough American horror flicks to know that you must kill a
zombie twice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
