<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2373 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-SAVARESE-BOS &LR;      06-23 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-SAVARESE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVARESE GETS A RUNNING START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While preparing for Thursday night's showdown with former
heavyweight champion Buster Douglas, Lou Savarese decided that in
the long run it was best to go for a short run.
</P>
<P>
   On the run is not exactly where you'd expect to find a
power-punching knockout artist from Long Island, but after two
straight defeats, Savarese understood he needed to do something to
energize his suddenly flagging career. Before he would visit
Douglas, he decided, he would visit Tim Hallmark, the fitness
fanatic who helped redirect the fortunes of the most successful
heavyweight of this era, Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   What came from that was a new approach to an old boxing wives'
tale. At Hallmark's insistence, Savarese went for a run, but not
the kind you see in the movies. No hooded sweatshirt pulled over
his head, no neck bowed against the chilly morning air, no feet
shuffling along a country road for miles as his trainer rides
alongside in a slow-moving Caddy with a cigar clamped in his cheek.
</P>
<P>
   These are high-speed, high-tech times, so Savarese has taken a
high-speed, high-tech approach to perhaps the oldest sport known to
man. To fight for long, it was decided, first you had to run short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to run a lot, at least 6 miles a day, five days a
week,'' Savarese recalled after finishing a recent day of sparring
and sprinting in Houston. ``But Tim's not big on long runs. Now I
only run three times a week, with the longest run maybe 3 miles.
There's a lot less long running and more sprint work. It's called
peak-and-valley training. It's designed to get your heartbeat up.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it will be up Thursday night in the Bingo Hall at
Foxwoods, where Savarese and Douglas will fight for a minor title
and their futures. The winner will leave with the little-known
International Boxing Association heavyweight championship, a title
that is vacant for a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   It is vacant for lack of interest, a trend that is very likely
to continue once it's occupied.
</P>
<P>
   So the title itself is not the aim for Savarese, just as a short
sprint championship is not the aim of his form of training. Both
are designed to serve a larger purpose. They are to be used to
resurrect a once-burgeoning career that came to a halt the night it
ran up against George Foreman.
</P>
<P>
   That has happened to a lot of fighters, so this is nothing new.
But what followed their meeting last April _ a disappointing
split-decision defeat for the previously unbeaten Savarese (with
judges' cards that ranged from Savarese winning, 114-113, to
Foreman winning, 122-115 _ was a stunning fifth-round stoppage five
months later that no one could have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   That night, unheralded David Izon (20-2) blasted out Savarese in
a fashion that cried out for change and hinted at Post-Traumatic
George Disorder. It was the kind of shock that either ends your
career or alters it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it was a lucky punch, but he beat me and that's
it,'' said Savarese (36-2, 20 KOs). ``I was coming off the Foreman
fight, and looking back I could see I should have been busier in
the last rounds in that fight, but mentally and physically I got
dejected after they took a point away from me late. That was my
only regret in that fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``After it, I thought I was going to fight Shannon Briggs, and
when they changed to Izon at the last minute, I was mentally let
down again. I thought I'd just knock Izon out.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not a totally unreasonable assumption, but assumptions
can get you in trouble in boxing, and so can big guys like Izon if
they hit you right. He did, which led Savarese to Hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen for a reason,'' Savarese said. ``I don't get
Buster if I won those fights. This is a great opportunity I don't
get if I'm 38-0 with a win over George.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what this fight is for me. It's everything. I don't
want to be a journeyman. It's not like the old days when guys were
fighting all the time. Now there's such a stigma to not being
undefeated, but what are you gonna do? It's why so many guys are
hand-picked (opponents).
</P>
<P>
   ``But after a loss you can do three things. You can quit. You
can do the same things. Or you can correct your mistakes. After I
lost to Izon, I hired Tim.''
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark changed Savarese's diet, actually adding food to it,
and changed his running approach. The result is an additional 8
pounds with a reduction in body fat to about 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for me,'' Savarese said. ``I've
watched the Douglas-(Mike) Tyson fight a dozen times. I've watched
some of his later fights, too, and he still puts his punches
together great. If he dictates the pace, he's great because of that
jab and what he can throw behind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have to go after this guy. You can't stay at the end
of his jab. You gotta beat his jab. He sets everything up with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Savarese will thus take a run at Douglas the same way he trained
for him. He'll come out hard and fast, fighting in spurts.
Sprinting, not jogging, to get back into the pack of heavyweights
pursuing Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``The running I've been doing is sport-specific for the first
time and it's really helped my conditioning,'' Savarese said. ``It
makes sense. How often do you go at the same heart rate for a
half-hour in boxing? A guy's not going to let you just plod along
like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Savarese doesn't intend to allow Douglas to plod
along. His plan is to run for it, something he's been doing for
seven long weeks in the Texas heat. In the long run, Savarese is
hoping that route will be a short cut to a title nobody wants and
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight will be decided by conditioning,'' Savarese
postulated. ``I'm in the best condition of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to say anything more to make his point. In his
mind, he's on the move again. Off and running.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how the heavyweight division is today,'' he said. ``A
day is a year in this division. You win a fight like this, you're
right back in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on the short list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1412EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
