<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2395 &Cx1f; tth-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SP     06-23 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVING-COLUMN-HAHN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBER BARBECUE BROUGHT 30 YEARS OF SEAR PLEASURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boy, they just don't build 'em like they used to. After just a
tad over 30 years, our Weber barbecue grill died.
</P>
<P>
   Basic black, charcoal-fired, grease-encrusted, patched-together,
jury-rigged backyard grill just bit the dust during this past
weekend's Father's Day cookout. Like many of us old-timers, its
legs gave out . . . separated from the body just as I was loading
it with some ribs and chicken.
</P>
<P>
   We managed to cook without spilling the meal _ not that we
haven't had to brush off some grass clippings, mulch, dirt and a
little gravel from previously spilled barbecues _ and left it
there, a burned-out hulk.
</P>
<P>
   There should be some sort of ceremony, some honor attaching to a
consumer product having lasted that long in this era of disposable
goods. We held onto it partly because we are from a time when
parents and grandparents recited: Use it up; wear it out. Make it
do or do without. And the Weber lasted a whole lot longer than my
'51 Chevy or '72 Olds, which we kept going out of sheer necessity.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three decades, we've burned everything from hot dogs
to turkeys and rib roasts on that Weber grill. We resisted the urge
to get a fancy-shmancy, gas-fired, cast-iron grill, opting instead
to ingest a goodly amount of hydrocarbons from charcoal and starter
liquid as we did our part to augment global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Our family has barbecued out in the yard since just after ``the
War,'' sometimes called ``The Big One,'' when Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co.
sold some folding-leg, thin-gauge grills that looked like cheap
suitcases and lasted about two or three seasons. Barbecuing was
convenient because Dad always had a ready supply of what we called
``real'' charcoal that tin-benders used to heat their soldering
irons.
</P>
<P>
   I inherited our father's uniquely blue-collar method of starting
the backyard grill: a cup of gasoline torched with a well-aimed
lighted match. This has accounted, over the years, for those times
when I came to work on Monday mornings without eyebrows or with
drastically shortened mustache and beard.
</P>
<P>
   The Weber was a gift from a friend back in Illinois when we
lived not far from where Webers are made. Initially, like old
Fords, they came only in basic black, and two or three sizes. But
they were considered the Cadillac of backyard grills, and we
certainly put the miles on ours.
</P>
<P>
   We did burnt bratwurst offerings to the gods of summer and we
did a few overly ambitious turkeys and rib roasts . . . just to say
that we did it. But my all-time favorite has been the Father's Day
rib barbecue. Tradition held that the man of the house was allowed
to spend the entire day barbecuing pork spareribs.
</P>
<P>
   To do this properly, coals were banked to one side with the help
of a Weber coal rail, and one rack of ribs was cooked while the
others were heaped off to one side, absorbing the sweet smoke.
Depending on the trendiness of the market choice, chips of
mesquite, alder, cherry or other woods _ some soaked overnight in a
water bucket _ were added to the coals.
</P>
<P>
   It took all day and a dozen or so bottles of beer to cook the
Father's Day meal, by the completion of which the ribs looked like
what was left of a herd of cloven-hoof animals hit by an asteroid,
and the cook looked well-done. And last weekend's was no exception,
except the cook was sober.
</P>
<P>
   There were harsh winter days back in northern Illinois when I
wanted to prove that backyard cooking was not a summer phenomenon,
and so I fired up the ol' Weber in some gawdawful weather and near
'bout froze my buns off. It was so cold during some of those
cookouts that the main dish was cold by the time I'd rushed it back
into the kitchen to something less than rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   The aftermath of these cookouts was not a pretty sight. And
cleaning the grill became a chore to be avoided, so it was easier
to buy a new grill top every year. The buildup of grease and ash
and sauce was occasionally scraped off the bottom half of the Weber
globe.
</P>
<P>
   As the years passed, I replaced the original set of plastic
grill wheels with some slightly larger plastic lawnmower wheels.
The handles began to fall off. It was well beyond garage-sale
material; it was the Old Family Retainer, kept on for having served
so well for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   The old grill will go to the county transfer station. After an
appropriate period of mourning, we may look for another, no doubt
slimmer and younger, model. But it won't be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Hahn is a staff columnist for the P-I. He can be reached at
206-448-8317 or e-mail him at jonhahn(at0seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
