</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEI-JINGSHENG-PROFILE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN AMERICA, CHINA'S WEI JINGSHENG HAS A TOUGH AGENDA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By PHILIP CAPUTO  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    He sniffs the cigarettes first, draws them lengthwise under his
nose and then lights them one after the other, the smoke curling in
the soft bronze light that flows through his west window.
 &HT;    ``River light,'' the novelist John Cheever called that
luminescence peculiar to New York City mornings.
 &HT;    It does seem to rise off the Hudson before it enters the room
where Wei Jingsheng sits and talks about the regime that imprisoned
him for all but a few months of the last 18 years, before releasing
him into exile in November.
 &HT;    ``The Chinese Communist Party is indeed the evil empire,'' he
says, echoing President Reagan. ``If the Soviet Union was the evil
empire, then the Chinese Communist regime is an even greater one _
or at least a slyer one.''
 &HT;    That's a reference to the recent scandals involving the
satellite industry and campaign contributions by Chinese nationals
to the Democratic Party.
 &HT;    ``The Chinese government is continuously trying to spread its
influence and build its strength,'' he says. ''The Chinese
Communists have always used these methods. Perhaps only now with
this evidence will more Americans pay more attention to it, and to
their schemes. It should serve as a very clear warning.''
 &HT;    Under the circumstances, Wei says, President Clinton clearly
should have canceled his trip to China.
 &HT;    ``I believe Clinton, under these conditions, should not go.
Clinton has not said what he plans to say or do, so I feel that he
won't stray from the path of the wishes of the Chinese Communists.
If he doesn't say clearly what he will do, then I believe it is a
mistake to go under these conditions.
 &HT;    ``If he does finally appear at Tiananmen Square _ although I
think that would be a major political mistake _ then he should
state clearly his support for the struggle, his sympathy for those
who were killed and injured and his commitment to pressing for the
release of the democracy activists still in prison. If he doesn't
do these things, then his appearance may damage his standing in the
eyes of every single Chinese. He should not adhere to the
conditions attached by the Communists.''
 &HT;    The president's trip is a kind of benchmark for Wei, who, with
Wang Dan, a leading figure in the 1989 Tiananmen Square uprising,
shares billing as China's most famous dissident. Clinton's presence
in China, surrounded by his beaming hosts, provides a platform that
has been largely missing in Wei's seven months of exile. The
attention could help him press his campaign against Clinton's
policy of ``engagement'' and cement his position as the primary
spokesman for the dissidents. But it could just as easily backfire,
if his ideas are brushed aside or, as Beijing so fervently hopes,
dismissed as irrelevant.
 &HT;    Certainly, Wei is not silent; his recorded message to a crowd of
thousands in Hong Kong in early June _ commemorating the ninth
anniversary of the Tiananmen Square massacre _ made headlines
around the world. But the questions linger: How many are listening?
Whom does he speak for? And not just in the West, but in China as
well. More immediately, did Wei make the right decision when he
relented and accepted Beijing's offer of exile?
 &HT;    To most people, there would have been no choice whatsoever:
whether to remain in prison or to accept an offer of medical parole
and exile. But Wei is not like most people.
 &HT;    If he were, he never would have been imprisoned in the first
place, for the crime of speaking his mind. He never would have
endured, merely for refusing to recant his belief in democracy,
solitary confinement in a cell where a bright light burned 24 hours
a day, frequent beatings from other inmates and conditions so
abysmal that he lost a dozen teeth and contracted high blood
pressure, heart disease, arthritis and hepatitis during his two
separate incarcerations.
 &HT;    In 1995, at the beginning of his second prison term, he was made
an offer that few thought he could refuse: He would be freed if he
accepted exile in the United States. He had become an international
cause celebre and the regime of President Jiang Zemin wanted to be
rid of him.
 &HT;    He had written, besides his incendiary public essays,
impertinent (and often humorous) letters to Deng Xiaoping, China's
late paramount leader, and was now making Jiang his new pen pal.
 &HT;    Execution was one option, but Wei was too famous to be dealt
with so crudely. China wanted trade with the West, and
international respectability. Clearly, the only thing to do with
Wei was to export him. But he declined the offer, not once but
twice.
 &HT;    ``Wei didn't want to leave China because by being there, he
would be a player,'' explains Philip Cunningham, a journalist and
China scholar who edited a collection of Wei's prison letters to
Deng and Jiang. ``He wanted to be there even in jail rather than
free in exile because the danger of exile is that you become
irrelevant.''
 &HT;    But last fall, Wei finally accepted banishment. On Nov. 16,
1997, he was released from prison, taken to a Northwest Airlines
plane in Beijing and flown to the United States.
 &HT;    What made him change his stand? We are in the small but
comfortable apartment he occupies at Columbia University, where he
is a visiting scholar. He is a stocky man of about 5 feet 8 or 9
inches, 48 years old, with a full head of black hair. There is no
hint of gray. His youthful, robust appearance is miraculous,
considering what he has been through.
 &HT;    ``Two reasons,'' he answers through an interpreter. ``My health
was quickly deteriorating. So I had two choices. One was to leave
the country, the other to die in prison. I felt there was no reason
for me to die in prison for no worthy cause.''
 &HT;    Wei slips another Marlboro out of the pack and lights up. ``The
second, which is more important, is that in recent years, the
position of the Western countries toward the Chinese Communist
Party has been softening, which has dealt a blow to the confidence
of the Chinese people. It is important for me to come out and tell
Western governments the real situation, the realities in China and
what effective roles they can play, and also to convey what the
Chinese people would really like to say to the people of the
Western countries.''
 &HT;    That ought to be enough to keep 10 men busy. But after some
thought, Wei gives me a third reason: He hopes to coordinate the
activities of pro-democracy dissidents abroad.
 &HT;    In effect, he would become the leader of the dissident movement,
which could be far more difficult than persuading Western
governments to amend their China policies. The 500 or so active
dissidents in this country are hopelessly fragmented by petty
squabbles, jealousies and differences in opinion about how best to
deal with Beijing.
 &HT;    It's a difficult agenda for a man who has little support other
than his name and the enormous respect and good will it commands.
Columbia provides Wei with an office and clerical assistance, but
he does not teach or lecture on a regular basis. Rising at 9 a.m.,
he usually works late into the night, conferring with other
dissidents.
 &HT;    Wei is determined not to retire to the scholar's cloister, as
many other exiled dissidents have done. And yet, looking at him,
dressed in slippers, a beige cotton shirt and gray trousers held up
by black suspenders, his legs folded on a threadbare couch as he
sips tea and smokes and smokes, it is hard to picture him
maneuvering in the corridors of power.
 &HT;    He has tried, but to little effect. This winter, he traveled to
London, Paris and Brussels, where he lobbied the European Union to
ratify a U.N. resolution condemning China's human-rights record. In
the spring, after the 15-nation European Union voted not even to
introduce the resolution, much less to pass it, Wei embarked on a
12-nation, seven-week tour of European capitals, calling on foreign
secretaries and members of parliament to explain their decision.
 &HT;    He fared no better with the Clinton administration, which in a
reversal of longstanding policy, also withdrew support for the
resolution this year. And now, in a further disappointment, Clinton
is visiting China.
 &HT;    To Wei, there is no compromise with Beijing, no engagement and
no partnership.
 &HT;    ``Clinton has an opportunity. I want him to make his support for
human rights and democracy clear. If he does not do this, then he
will not help the movement and he will not help the standing of
himself and the United States in the eyes of the Chinese people. I
think that Clinton's use of the word `partnership' is completely
wrong, since the Chinese Communists use the word `enemy' in
describing the United States. I don't think the American people
want a partner like the Chinese Communists.''
 &HT;    When Wei speaks, his baritone barely changes inflection and,
whatever may be going on inside him, he gives an outward impression
of serenity. Yet the position he has staked out for himself is
nearly impossible. Here is a man without a political party or power
of any kind beyond the moral authority vouchsafed by his
sufferings, appointing himself roving ambassador for one-fifth of
the world's population, trying to shape American foreign policy. I
wonder if I'm in the presence of a Chinese Don Quixote, or a man
who could become to China what Vaclav Havel is to the Czech
Republic or Nelson Mandela is to South Africa.
 &HT;    There is a certain purity about Wei, but it's hard to tell
sometimes if it is the purity of an egomaniac or a saint. Others
have commented on Wei's saintly qualities: his lack of bitterness,
his heroic readiness to sacrifice himself on the altar of
principle, his unflagging composure.
 &HT;    But in time, I realize that Wei is neither saint nor egomaniac.
He is a man of integrity _ integrity in its fundamental meaning: He
is united within himself. God knows, he had plenty of time, in the
isolation of his cell, to think things through. He has emerged as a
man with a seamless confidence in himself and in the truth of his
ideas.
 &HT;    Wei has hundreds, if not thousands, of admirers and supporters
in the West. Among many Chinese dissidents, he is an icon. Even
those who disagree with his views on China are in awe of his
courage and his ability to write and argue in clear, direct,
forceful language.
 &HT;    But will that be enough? Now that Wei is out of prison and no
longer a myth, there are dissidents as well as Western diplomats
and scholars who think that his ideas are outdated and that Wei
himself, though unquestionably a hero, is a hero from a bygone era.
They question whether he is the right candidate to lead the
dissident movement and to convey realities in China to Western
leaders.
 &HT;    They say that Wei, having been isolated for so long, clings to
views and rhetoric frozen in the amber of the Cold War.
 &HT;    ``The more Wei speaks out, the more he reveals that he doesn't
know the current situation,'' says Merle Goldman, a professor of
Chinese history at Boston University and an expert on the dissident
movement. ``Through no fault of his own _ he was in prison for all
but a few months of the last 18 years _ he has no clear idea what
is going on in China or abroad.''
 &HT;    The China of the 1990s is not the China of the 1970s under Mao,
she notes. A rudimentary democracy has taken hold at the village
level, where elections have been held this year. Although open
dissent is still prohibited, citizens privately criticize the
government in ways that would have been unthinkable 25 years ago.
It is a much more prosperous and at least somewhat freer country.
 &HT;    When I mention to her that Wei has said that ``millions of
workers and peasants in China are truly starving,'' she exclaims,
``That's not true!'' and adds that Wei's penchant for injudicious
comments like that could undermine his credibility.
 &HT;    Wei's defenders say it's too early to judge him, after only a
little more than seven months in exile.
 &HT;    ``We're honoring him for his courage, not necessarily because
he's an astute politician,'' says Robert Bernstein, the founding
chairman of Human Rights Watch. ``We don't know about that yet. Wei
has sacrificed for his ideas and deserves a chance. Besides, it
never hurts to put pressure on the regime.''
 &HT;    Chen Xiaoping, a 36-year-old former journalist and law professor
now studying at Harvard, was forced to leave China because of his
pro-democracy activities. He says the youngest dissidents _ of whom
Wang Dan is the most prominent _ almost literally don't understand
the language that Wei speaks.
 &HT;    When Wei gave a talk at Harvard, Chen says, ``Some students
asked him: `Where are you coming from? This is traditional, not
modern discourse.' He was talking like somebody from the Cultural
Revolution.
 &HT;    ``Wei is too old,'' Chen adds flatly. ``In jail for 18 years,
and because he was in prison for such a long time, he cannot
understand the modern China.''
 &HT;    The obvious implication is that the 29-year-old Wang, who was
serving an 11-year sentence when released to American doctors this
spring, understands China better _ the China, that is, of young
entrepreneurs bearing cell phones instead of Mao's little red book.
Wang's opinion on Clinton's visit does seem to be more nuanced than
Wei's.
 &HT;    ``I feel extremely uncomfortable when I think about President
Clinton walking on Tiananmen Square,'' Wang says. ``But I
understand that United States policy toward China should represent
the interests of the American people. I just hope it also
represents the moral standards of the American people.''
 &HT;    Aware of the force his words carry in the dissident community,
Wang, who is spending the summer at Harvard, adds diplomatically:
``Both Mr. Wei Jingsheng and I believe that to promote a peaceful
transformation toward democracy in China, international influence
is crucial.''
 &HT;    Almost no one disagrees with Wei's objectives: building a China
where people aren't arrested without charges and tortured in
prison, where workers trying to organize independent labor unions
aren't crushed and freedom of speech and expression are not
repressed.
 &HT;    Besides, as Bernstein points out, it's not as though the younger
dissidents are accomplishing any more than Wei.
 &HT;    ``They aren't getting results either,'' he says. ``Of course
there's more economic freedom. Of course the party is giving ground
politically _ it has no choice.''
 &HT;    The difference between Wei and his loyal critics is in figuring
out how to get there from here. For Wei, the correct approach _ the
only approach _ is to get tough. But this does not mean the
complete suspension of relations, says Xiao Qiang of the
organization Human Rights in China.
 &HT;    ``We don't want to fall into the trap of isolation versus
engagement,'' he says. ``We want a strong and effective
human-rights policy, on an equal footing with trade and security
policy.''
 &HT;    Wei puts it more succinctly. Dealing with China, he says, is
like dealing with a ``scoundrel on the street'': the nicer you are,
the more likely you are to get mugged.
 &HT;    But he will lose credibility if he doesn't catch up on all that
happened in the world while he was in prison. In the words of
Cunningham, Wei's editor, Wei may not be a ``first-class
intellectual,'' but of all the prominent dissidents, he has ``the
appeal and spirit, the personality and the charisma, all the
credentials to unify that fractious movement.''
 &HT;    It does neither himself nor his cause any good to paint Jiang's
China in the chiaroscuro pigments of Mao's China, where people,
literally, were forced to devour their children.
 &HT;     c.1998 Philip Caputo  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Philip Caputo is author, most recently, of ``Exiles,'' a
collection of novellas, and of ``A Rumor of War,'' a Vietnam
memoir.) &LR;
</P>
