<HEADER>
A2410 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROWNING-SEASON-HNS &LR;      06-23 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROWNING-SEASON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA OFFICIALS URGE CAUTION AMID SURGE OF DROWNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Summer is here and officials are reminding
people who want to cool off that a serene swim at the beach can
turn to terror in an instant.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, six people died in three separate drowning
incidents in the San Francisco area.
</P>
<P>
   Lifeguards are rare despite a massive, El Nino-bred snowmelt
that has turned creeks and rivers into turbulent highways of death.
Ocean beaches _ with few exceptions _ are made hazardous by
pernicious rip currents that can suck a swimmer or a wader into
deep, cold water far from shore.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, two women and a 13-year-old boy were swept to
their deaths at Ocean Beach in San Francisco. The women, believed
to be in their early 30s, were apparently wading when they were
pulled away from shore by an unusually potent riptide.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was knocked over by a wave later that day. He
disappeared into the water.
</P>
<P>
   Two men, said to be good swimmers, disappeared into the Napa
River after a speedboat in which they were passengers was struck by
a wave and overturned. The search for David Snowden and Jeff
Emerson, in their early 20s, was abandoned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Four teen-age girls wading in Niles Creek near Pleasanton were
caught in a perilous undertow. Three escaped, but the fourth,
17-year-old Stacey Feuychieng Saechin of Richmond, drowned.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, three rafters drowned Monday in the Cosumnes River,
where the rapids were so intense they ripped the victims' clothing
off.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine people have died in rafting accidents in Northern
California since last week. Investigators attribute the accidents
to cold, fast water and debris-filled rivers _ the result of runoff
from the Sierra Nevada snowpack.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 and 1997, five people were killed on noncommercial
rafting trips, said David Johnson of the state Department of
Boating and Waterways.
</P>
<P>
   The record for such fatalities was in 1993, when 12 people died,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are approaching those numbers very quickly, and the season
has just started,'' he said. ``It's pretty scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The rivers will subside when the snowpack disappears later this
summer. But beaches will always be treacherous, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only place we actually encourage people to swim is Stinson
Beach (in Marin County), and we encourage that only when lifeguards
are present,'' said Tracy Fortmann of the Golden Gate National
Recreation District, which manages many beaches _ including Ocean
Beach _ in San Francisco and Marin.
</P>
<P>
   She said 10 people drowned at Ocean Beach in the past 10 years,
although in some stretches of one to four years no drownings were
recorded there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ocean Beach is one of the most notorious beaches in California
because of the fact that large volumes of water from the northwest
that are generated by wind swells and storms hit Ocean Beach,''
said Matt Ehmann, a Park Service ranger. ``And they are unabated by
any land masses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
