<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2449 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUITAR-FACTORY-SPI &LR;      06-23 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUITAR-FACTORY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRINGS OF DESIRE: TACOMA GUITARS INSTRUMENTS ARE IN DEMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Photo available through Wieck Photo Database)  
 By KRUTI TRIVEDI  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gary Weyand, president of Pacific Music in Redmond, Wash., must
answer the same question day after day.
</P>
<P>
   Customers enter his guitar store. They look around, imagine
themselves on the next cover of Rolling Stone and pick up one of
the more than 200 guitars in the shop.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, they stumble over to what Weyand says is his
best-selling brand _ Tacoma Guitars.
</P>
<P>
   And then they ask the question: ``Tacoma Guitars _ is it really
in Tacoma?''
</P>
<P>
   One of the top four makers of acoustic guitars in the United
States, Tacoma Guitars is tucked into the side of the road a little
past a Boeing plant, but the 60,000-square-foot facility is
officially in Tacoma, south of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18 months since its inception, the subsidiary of Korean
piano maker Young Chang has broken into an industry dominated by
longtime giants.
</P>
<P>
   It started making a profit when it celebrated its first birthday
six months ago. Revenue for this year is expected to be about $4
million to $5 million, according to John Hawkins, director of
company sales and worldwide marketing.
</P>
<P>
   This month's issue of Music &AMP; Sound Retailer rates three models
of Tacoma Guitars among the best 10 acoustic guitars sold for more
than $700.
</P>
<P>
   No other guitar manufacturer has as many on the list, and two of
the three Tacoma Guitars models are the least expensive of those
listed.
</P>
<P>
   Local retailers say Tacoma Guitars are in high demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Tacomas go, they come in and they go out as quickly
as I can get them,'' Weyand said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sold them to all walks of life,'' said Jimmy Thomas,
manager of American Music in Fremont. ``I have guys who work at
Microsoft who have them in their office because it's a good way to
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Tacomas cost $479 to $2,200. It may seem pricey, but it's still
less than most custom guitars, which, according to Ron Reed, sales
manager at Dusty Springs in Seattle's Fremont neighborhood, can
cost as much as $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like buying a tailor-made suit as opposed to an
off-the-shelf suit,'' said Stephen Davies, president of Stephen's
Stringed Instruments in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Off the shelf seems to be working just fine for Tacoma Guitars'
customers. The company is planning to manufacture between 11,000
and 12,000 units this year, and usually has about 2,000 guitars on
back order. Hawkins just hired a second shift of workers to keep up
with the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma Guitars' mass production techniques turn out a guitar far
quicker than the weeks to years it takes to make a custom guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a very high-tech company in a very low-tech business. It
allows us to sell guitars at a much better value,'' Hawkins said.
</P>
<P>
   While the company employs 85 people, it relies on computers for
many tasks. For example, a machine cuts the wood used in the
guitar. Many custom guitar makers cut the wood themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma Guitars also uses a machine to suck out the excess glue.
Custom makers often remove the glue by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Mass production does have its disadvantages, according to custom
guitar makers. Davies _ whose company makes electric guitars, not
acoustics _ says mass production has some shortcomings regardless
of the type of guitar being made.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to, no matter what, put out cookie-cutter
instruments,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can have two pieces of wood from the same tree, but they
can be different'' in sound, Reed said. By inspecting each piece of
wood, he said custom makers optimize sound quality.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins emphasizes that his guitars are the best quality guitars
produced at a specific, midlevel price range.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more than machinery to their success, said George
Gruhn, owner of Gruhn's Guitars in Nashville, Tenn., who has been
involved with the company from the time it was formed.
</P>
<P>
   And the beginning was all-important.
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma Guitars already had a facility for making guitars and
easy access to much of the wood it would need for those
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Young Chang America Timber, whose parent company is the piano
maker Young Chang Korea, was located in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, it opened a facility next to the timber company,
where it started making guitars for other guitar companies.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, President J.C. Kim decided it made sense
for the facility to start making its own brand-name guitars.
</P>
<P>
   He hired John Hawkins to be its director of sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins, who had been in the music industry for more than 20
years, left Tacoma's Illinois-based competitor Washburn Guitars.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins linked up with Gruhn, one of the world's authorities on
vintage guitars. Gruhn already was well known for selling guitars _
his own shop has more than 700 guitars on the floor _ but he wanted
to try something new.
</P>
<P>
   Gruhn wanted a guitar that used a different design. Hawkins was
looking for just that.
</P>
<P>
   A unique design, he reasoned, would help the company break into
the guitar business and compete with other manufacturers that had
decades of experience.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they produced a small guitar, the Papoose, tuned at
the higher note A instead of E, at which most guitars are tuned.
</P>
<P>
   The Papoose, like its successors, uses voiced support bracing, a
special bracing system that Hawkins says improves sound quality.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a comma-shaped sound hole in the upper right hand
side of the body instead of a round sound hole in the middle of the
guitar body.
</P>
<P>
   But the differences didn't stop with design.
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma Guitars didn't send its new product to stores and then
pore over the sales results. Instead, Gruhn was given about 50
Papoose guitars in November 1996. He handed them out to musicians
he knew, entertainers such as Ricky Skaggs and Bela Fleck. Soon
enough, Hawkins said he had proof his idea was a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artists all pretty much gravitated toward it,'' Hawkins
said. ``The word we got back was, `This is great. Do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The move was a smart one. Gruhn said new companies often find it
difficult to get recognition from customers and dealers. By giving
guitars to musicians, Tacoma Guitars targeted a younger audience
that was used to buying guitars based on name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tend to go for whatever their idol is playing,'' Gruhn
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to continue expanding. Six more models will
debut next month, bringing the company's count to 23.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe Weyand will stop having to answer the same question
every day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
