<HEADER>
A2487 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-CLINTON-0624     06-23 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-CLINTON-0624-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON'S CHINA TRIP RIVALS WOODROW WILSON'S IN LENGTH, IF NOT
POLITICAL RISK
 &HT;    With CHINA-DIG-$ADV24; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV24
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIAN, China _ President Bill Clinton arrives here Thursday to
kick off the longest presidential visit to any country in 79 years,
a voyage overshadowed by controversy and underscored by limited
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Since President Woodrow Wilson steamed to Paris in 1919 to
midwife the creation of the ill-fated League of Nations, no
American president has made such a long and extensive tour of a
single foreign country.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is sure to be trailed by Congressional criticism of his
policies, from human rights to technology transfers. But his
nine-day trip carries limited stated ambitions and is not likely to
put him at the same risk that Wilson took -- and lost.
</P>
<P>
   The idealistic Wilson spent more than two months negotiating in
France, then for his trouble got a congressional thumbs down on
American membership in the new international assembly he was
convinced could insure world peace.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other lengthiest presidential sojourns also were to
China. President Richard Nixon ended a quarter century of hostility
with the Chinese during his seven-day visit in 1972, and President
Ronald Reagan made a six-day trip in 1984 that was perceived as
mainly symbolic. However, it led to an unprecedented era of warming
in the two nations' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's trip is caught in a cross-current of pressures.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, China's Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan called on
Clinton to end U.S. sanctions that were imposed after the Chinese
army violently suppressed the 1989 Tiananmen Square democracy
movement.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, new measures were introduced in Congress to put
more punitive measures on China, including prohibiting U.S. visas
to any Chinese official who engaged in human rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   This ancient capital of imperial China is an ideal place for
Clinton to open his nine-day tour at 7:30 p.m. China time (7:30
a.m. EDT) on Thursday. During the Tang Dynasty in 900 AD, Xian
(pronounced Shee-an) welcomed foreign dignitaries with the same
pomp and color that will greet the First Family Thursday when
drummers, pipers and lavishly-costumed dancers perform before the
romantic backdrop of the walled old city's south gate.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, Xian is not the focus of a single Congressional
gripe over administration policy. Nor has it been the seat of
government for the last 1,100 years, so the President can put off
for a couple days the talks with China's steel-willed leaders that
isn't expected to produce much substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least there's a ceremonial significance,'' said Charles Wu,
the general manager of IBM China Co., Inc., speaking about the
potential impact of Clinton's trip. ``It may even surpass the
results the Reagan visit was able to generate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wu said he would be surprised at any big immediate
breakthroughs, such as clinching an agreement that would allow
China to enter the World Trade Organization (WTO). That has been
one of China's major goals of the visit, and negotiators from the
two sides were still plugging away at it this week.
</P>
<P>
   He would be happy, Wu said, if Clinton's tour creates sufficient
good feelings for the Chinese to ``shorten the cycle times'' for
U.S. companies to get approvals to conduct and expand operations
here.
</P>
<P>
   On the Chinese side, weapons expert Shen Dingli, director of
international programs at Shanghai's Fudan University, said he
believes the Americans also will be denied a priority item on their
wish-list -- China's signature on the Missile Technology Control
Regime (MTCR).
</P>
<P>
   China had provisionally accepted the missile regime when it
prohibited transfer or sale to another country of missiles with a
range more than 300 kilometers (180 miles) and capability to carry
weapons of mass destruction. The updated protocol applies to
missiles of any range, which China has resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A missile can deliver warheads, conventional or
nuclear-tipped. A jet can also deliver bombs. So why only restrain
missiles and not other types of delivery techniques?'' he asked,
referring specifically to the U.S. F-16 fighter jets that America
sometimes sells abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``You (Americans) can afford not to export missiles because you
can export warplanes, even to a part of China,'' said Shen, raising
another, and probably the primary, reason the Chinese are unwilling
to join the MTCR. Refusal is a bargaining tool to get the Americans
to stop selling F-16s to Taiwan, the island province that broke
away from China after the communist revolution.
</P>
<P>
   One potential agreement Shen cited is the addition of a
verification article to the protocol on biological weapons control.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington talk also has focused on the likelihood of both
sides agreeing to de-target nuclear missiles aimed at the other.
</P>
<P>
   And in Beijing a proposal is circulating for stabilizing the
precarious nuclear arms situation in the Indian subcontinent after
both India and Pakistan exploded nuclear weapons last month.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would end sanctions against Pakistan -- a friend of
China -- and give the country incentives to sign the nuclear
non-proliferation treaty. The assumption is that helping Pakistan
upgrade its conventional weapons capability would convince it to
freeze its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   Whether deals are struck or not, one clear aim of the White
House is sending Americans a new view of fast-changing life in
China, which the administration hopes would dilute criticism of
Clinton's policy of engaging with China despite its continuing poor
record on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   From here Clinton heads to Beijing for three days, with official
talks only scheduled for a few hours Saturday. There's free time to
extend discussions, when Clinton isn't climbing the Great Wall or
giving speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night the presidential entourage departs for Shanghai,
then spends the day Thursday in the misty mountain splendor of
Guilin before heading on to Hong Kong that night. He departs China
on Friday night in time to be on American soil on the Fourth of
July.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
