<HEADER>
A2489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-CHINA-DIG-$ADV24-C     06-23 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-CHINA-DIG-$ADV24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DUE TO MEET WELL-DIGGER WHO DISCOVERED TERRA COTTA ARMY
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON-0624; CHINA-HISTBOX-$ADV24.
 &HT;    With photo to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server available from the New York Times News Service.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIYANG, China _ This village was aghast in 1974 when farmer Yang
Zhifa accidentally dug into the vaults of terra cotta warriors, the
2,200-year-old Chinese time capsule that some call ``The Eighth
Wonder of the World.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents scolded me, my wife also scolded me,'' Yang
recalled Tuesday. ``They said that I had broken a statue of a
god.''
</P>
<P>
   People around here have long since forgiven this 61-year-old
peasant with age-worn cheeks and tobacco-colored teeth.
</P>
<P>
   He's become a tourist attraction for visitors to the nearby city
of Xian, and he sits for hours at a local artifacts shop here
signing autographs for lines of tourists.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Yang's fame is likely to go global. Yang disclosed
that he has been invited to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton and
tell him about how his trusty shovel helped open an archaeological
attraction that rivals the Greek Parthenon and Egypt's Valley of
The Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the terra cotta warriors museum, Wu Yonqi,
confirmed that Yang is likely to meet Clinton. ``Many visitors like
to meet the discoverer,'' Wu said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum director also disclosed that China is preparing a
special honor for the president.
</P>
<P>
   Wu said the museum staff has erected a red carpeted staircase
that will allow the Clintons to become the first foreign visitors
since 1993 to descend into the 700-foot-long underground ``Pit No.
1'' that contains the most perfectly preserved of the 7,500 terra
cotta warriors.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Elizabeth and President Ronald Reagan were granted access
to the same pit floor in the 1980s. But then in 1993, the pit where
the warriors stand was closed to all outsiders to avoid the risk of
damaging the artifacts, Wu said. Recent tourists and state visitors
have viewed the warriors only from an elevated platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``After careful consideration, we've decided to make an
exception for President Clinton,'' said Wu. ``The special staircase
(into the pit) will be removed immediately after his visit.''
</P>
<P>
   What Yang the Discoverer is preparing to tell Clinton is a
modern legend -- one that has been confirmed by Chinese
archaeologists as being authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1974, Yang was one of 400 members of the Xiyang
``production team,'' as villages were then called. Conditions on
their farm commune were grim because of a four-year dry spell, Yang
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They needed someone to drill a well because the wheat needed
water very much, so they asked me and another man,'' Yang recalled.
They struck water on their first try and were told to drill a
second well.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sunny day in March when Yang and his partner noticed
something odd. After digging for two days, they struck a layer of
red dirt they thought looked baked. ``I was confused,'' he said.
``Here, the earth is yellow.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, around midday, ``my shovel hit something,'' Yang
remembered. ``We thought it was a piece of pottery because it was
open at the top, like a vase.''
</P>
<P>
   They had dug through the top of an earth-and-wood structure
built by China's first emperor, the ruthless visionary Qin
Shihuang, who conquered eastern China's warring states in hopes of
building an empire that his descendants would rule for 10,000
years.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to achieve eternal life in an underworld of his own
creation, Qin has long been portrayed by historians as dragooned
tens of thousands of artisans to craft an underground city as his
tomb. Some chroniclers claimed it was complete with a bronze floor
and with rivers made of flowing mercury. Hundreds of workmen were
allegedly murdered later to keep the secret of what was inside.
</P>
<P>
   Though Qin's fabled city of the afterlife hasn't been fully
excavated, Yang stumbled on something in 1974 that will be hard for
any later discoverer to match.
</P>
<P>
   It was the buried war machine that Qin planned to command in his
next life: an army of bigger-than-life-sized terra cotta figures,
complete with chariots and swords and bronze arrows tipped with
lead poison.
</P>
<P>
   Yang foresaw none of this when his shovel hit the first
warrior's neck. All he could tell was that this was a very
strange-looking pot.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started digging from the neck to the shoulders, the
earth became very soft, easier to dig.''
</P>
<P>
   Digging quickly, they soon uncovered an almost-intact terra
cotta warrior. They accidentally broke the left leg during the
digging, but they did manage to uncover the head that had gotten
separated from the neck. They also found a buried trove of ancient
bows and bronze arrows.
</P>
<P>
   The village was just 200 meters away, and word began to spread
when the two peasants walked home to eat lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Around the middle of that first day Yang and his partner decided
it would be best to lift the statue out of the hole so they could
go on with their task of well-digging.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't lift it. (The warriors weigh from 240 to 660
pounds each.)
</P>
<P>
   Yang and his partner decided to hack the terra-cotta statue into
pieces with their shovels. ``We had to break it into parts, so we
could lift it onto the surface,'' he said. ``Then we went on with
our digging.''
</P>
<P>
   After lunch, villagers slipped away from the fields to gawk. It
wasn't long before someone talked with an elderly woman neighbor
who believed in Buddhism. She immediately warned that this was
probably a buried figure of Buddha.
</P>
<P>
   That's when village opinion turned against Yang and his partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was not good to break a god,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Yang's boss at the ``production team'' intervened.
He reported the strange discovery to cultural officials in Lintong
County, who ordered Yang to send in the statue fragments for
analysis. The pieces filled three big wheelbarrows.
</P>
<P>
   The well hole was turned over to the archaeologists, who were
given urgent orders to excavate the site without delay. Yang was
told to dig a third well 150 feet away, and this time he struck
water.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the discovery of the first warrior, the Chinese
public was allowed into a big hangar-like museum structure that by
now holds hundreds of terra cotta warriors, lined up in solemn rows
to battle on behalf of the spirit of Emperor Qin.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
