<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LONGEST U.S. PRESIDENTIAL VISITS TO A SINGLE COUNTRY
 &HT;    With CHINA-CLINTON; CHINA-DIG-$ADV24.
 &HT;    For Use Wednesday, June 24 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SAMAR ABULHASSAN 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Bill Clinton's nine-day trip that he
embarks on today to the People's Republic of China -- and returns
on July 3 _ is one of the longest single-country trips ever taken
by a modern-day American president.
</P>
<P>
   It is exceedingly rare for a president to spend so much time in
one country when there are no across-the-table negotiations,''
Henry Graff, a presidential historian at Columbia University said.
Historically, he said, such lengthy trips are limited to
``specific'' major policy dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The following are some of the longest single-country trips ever
taken by U.S. presidents:
</P>
<P>
   _ President Woodrow Wilson's trip to France from March 14 to
June 18 in 1919; where World War I ended with a peace treaty signed
at Versailles.
</P>
<P>
   _ President Richard M. Nixon's trip to China lasted seven days,
from Feb. 21-28, 1972 to establish relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   _ President Harry S Truman's trip to Potsdam, Germany from July
16 to Aug. 2, 1945 -- following the surrender of Germany in World
War II -- to decide the fate of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   _ President Franklin D. Roosevelt's trip to Yalta, Ukraine from
Feb. 4 to Feb. 11, 1945 for the Yalta Conference among the ``Big
Three'' -- Roosevelt, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill and
Soviet Premier Joseph Stalin -- which positioned the allies against
Germany and later divided Germany into zones of occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Source:(at) White House Press Office.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
