<HEADER>
A2506 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APARTMENT-PETS-HNS &LR;      06-23 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APARTMENT-PETS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDLORDS MISS A CHANCE TO CASH IN ON MAN'S BEST FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CORRIE M. ANDERS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ OK, so you're a landlord with a vacant
apartment, and a potential renter knocks on your door, holding the
leash on a massive Great Dane. You immediately envision a 150-pound
Godzilla wreaking havoc in your nice apartment.
</P>
<P>
   You don't much care for dogs in your building in the first
place, but you might have been swayed if it had been a Pekingese,
Chihuahua or some other little pooch. But no way this prospect at
the front door is getting the apartment, even if the dog is as
sweet as Marmaduke.
</P>
<P>
   That bias against large dogs is the prevailing attitude among
landlords around the country. Because of it, many owners are
missing an excellent chance to get premium rents while endearing
themselves to a largely untapped market of dog lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Apartment owners who do accept dogs often have weight
limitations _ usually 20 pounds or less. That limit eliminates many
favorite breeds even though the rationale for the pet policy may
not have merit, according to Rob Foellinger, an apartment
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one could explain to me where we got the idea we should
accept or reject pets based on weight. Why not do height? Let's do
color of eyes. It doesn't make any sense,'' said Foellinger,
president of MarkeTactics Consulting Group in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Foellinger surveyed 1,200 veterinarians, animal
trainers and humane societies to get a feeling for which canines
were most likely to cause damage in an apartment and which were
most likely to do well in an apartment. The response from 400 pet
professionals showed many landlords were barking up the wrong
breed.
</P>
<P>
   The best breeds for apartments were fairly large animals such as
retrievers, Dalmatians and collies, and only one on the top 10 list
was under 20 pounds. Small dogs dominated the worst 10 list,
including terriers, Pekingese, Chihuahuas and miniature poodles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about temperament,'' said Foellinger, who has a
Dalmatian, ``but a lot of small dogs we welcome with open arms
suffer from separation anxiety, they bark all day, they're very
territorial and are more apt to bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big dogs will drive you nuts, too,'' Foellinger said, ``but
try to get a golden retriever to bite anyone. His idea of a good
time is to lick five burglars at once.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ``no dog'' signs are as prevalent in cities as in the
suburbs, Amanda Kennedy considered herself super fortunate to find
an apartment in San Francisco, where there are so few rentals
available that landlords have carte blanche over whom they choose.
</P>
<P>
   It took only 45 days before Kennedy found an owner that would
accept her and Levi, her nearly 100-pound black Labrador. ``He's a
couch retriever. He's very calm and laid back,'' said Kennedy, an
art director. ``Unfortunately, landlords don't ask for pet
resumes.''
</P>
<P>
   They should. Apartment operators who cater to residents with big
dog outperform their competitors. Their apartments rent quicker,
they have fewer vacancies and they can charge higher rents,
according to apartment operators.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Greenhill Village apartments in Columbus, Ohio, which
runs huge ads that announce: ``We accept large dogs with good
credit; owners also welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 90 percent of the 228 units are rented by pet
lovers who pay $25 a month extra for their animals, which include
Great Danes, Labs and German shepherds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a difference in what a large dog or a small
dog does regarding damage,'' said Ana Morera, manager of the
apartment complex. ``All dogs scratch things up, but we don't have
that many problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalon-Bay Apartment communities, a national real estate company
that operates more than 35,000 luxury apartments on both coasts, is
taking an experimental look at studies showing large dogs may make
good house pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're testing that right now in five buildings,'' said John
Pringle, a company executive. ``If it's true, we'll probably modify
some of our pet policies to allow them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most landlords, however, remain skeptical. Dogs can appear
intimidating, assault the olfactory and auditory senses and even
drive away potential renters.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Carrico, a San Francisco apartment investor and property
manager for landlords on both sides of the doggy fence, said he
encourages a cats-only pet policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not worth it,'' he said. ``It's just amazing how
much trouble there is'' with dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Barking, for one, which can be especially odious when owners are
away. Carrico tells the story of a vacant apartment he tried to
rent in a four-unit building where the three other tenants owned
dogs. ``Every time a (potential) renter would go in the building,
it sounded like they were walking into a kennel. It took quite a
while to rent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some animals left unattended for too long chew on doors or use
the carpet as their faux fire hydrant.
</P>
<P>
   That problem also makes landlords reticent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get that smell in your carpet, it seeps from the
carpet into the concrete slab,'' said Steve Epcar, a principal of
Ventana, a property management firm in San Mateo, Calif. ``It's a
smell that _ short of a fire _ you'd never get out of the unit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outdoors can be problematic as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Labrador lays a big bomb and a Chihuahua doesn't,'' said
Mark Abrahams, regional property manager in Sacramento, Calif., for
FPI Management. ``If everyone were more conscientious and picked up
after themselves, I think owners might be a little more likely to
increase the size limit,'' said Abrahams, who handles 1,000
apartments in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   If an owner allows pets, Carrico said his firm screens both the
applicant and the animal. ``We ask to meet the dog. That puts the
person on notice that we really care,'' Carrico said, ``but the dog
can't tell us if the owner cleans up behind them.''
</P>
<P>
   When she applied for a small, Victorian apartment two years ago,
Kasie Maxwell said, her San Francisco landlord met not only
Gabriel, her 140-pound Great Dane; but also her two cats, two
turtles and four birds.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell was well prepared for her move from Oregon. She had
letters of praise about her menagerie from previous landlords, two
in-house pet sitters and her veterinarians. These references and
luck, she said, helped her get the apartment two days after her
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel died of cancer last year, so the 500-square-foot
apartment seems larger, but there's no chance she'll settle for one
of those little tykes as a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small dogs are really annoying,'' she said. ``I had a neighbor
in the building who had small dogs and they were yapping all day. I
couldn't wait till she moved out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
