<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, June 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIRCOSOFT &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Washington) _ An appeals court lifts the
preliminary injunction against Microsoft, meaning that the company
is again free to market its Internet Explorer browser with Windows
95. The court also dismisses from the antitrust case the special
master, Michael Lessig of Harvard, who had been accused by
Microsoft of being biased against the company. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-WINDOWS (Undated) _ What today's ruling means for this
week's release of Windows 98. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; China &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PIRACY (Shanghai) _ The authorities have begun a crackdown
on many of the illegal activities that are ordinarily tolerated
these days, like the sale of pirated video and music compact disks.
The fight against piracy of software, music and movies, an issue
that loomed large in China-U.S. relations a few years ago, has been
pushed in the background and is unlikely to be raised seriously
during President Clinton's visit, even though it remains as rampant
a problem as ever. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MISSILES (Washington) _ As Clinton prepares to leave for
China, Senate votes on a measure to shift satellite licensing
authority back to the State Department from the Commerce
Department; a House hearing into sensitive technology transfers to
China continues; and several Capitol Hill news conferences are held
criticizing China's record on human rights and other issues. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-VISAS (Washington) _ China cancels visas of three
reporters from Radio Free Asia, upsetting the administration and
Congress. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PEONY (Shanghai) _ The latest developments in the ``Peony
Pavilion'' contretemps, with a Chinese dance company's plans for a
U.S. and world tour blocked. By Seth Faison.
</P>
<P>
   We are also considering stories on Clinton's press treatment in
China and a look at changes in the Chinese media.
</P>
<P>
   And for a look ahead at N.Y. Times coverage during Clinton's
trip, look for BC-CHINA-ADVISORY, which will move late this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ President Yeltsin demands that parliament
pass his ``anti-crisis'' package of economic measures to satisfy
the IMF, setting stage for new political confrontation. By Michael
R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-SUBMARINE (Tokyo) _ South Korea protests the incursion of
a North Korean submarine into its waters as a violation of the
armistice that ended the Korean War, but it loses control of the
submarine when a tow cable breaks and the boat sinks to the sea
bottom. By Nicholas D. Kristoff.
</P>
<P>
   WORLDCUP-VIOLENCE (Dresden, Germany) _ Riots by German World Cup
soccer hooligans in France last Sunday leave a French policeman
fighting for his life. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN-BASQUES (Madrid) _ Former Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez
testifies that he never ordered his Socialist government in the
1980s to conduct illegal counterterrorism against armed Basque
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AIDS-REPORT (Geneva) _ U.N. officials on Tuesday painted one
of the gloomiest pictures of the HIV epidemic since it was first
recognized in 1981. In its first country-by-country analysis,
released on the eve of the 12th international AIDS conference, they
said that 30 million people were now infected with HIV, the AIDS
virus, and that the majority were doomed to die because they live
in countries that cannot provide adequate health care. HIV now
infects one in four adults in two African countries, Botswana and
Zimbabwe. HIV-infection rates exceed one-third of the adults in
some major African cities and reach 70 percent of women tested in
pre-natal clinics. By Lawrence K. Altman.
