<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR &LR;      06-23 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO SHOWALTER FEUD WITH BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas - A seemingly out of place, throwaway line in a
nationally syndicated baseball column by Peter Gammons has set off
alarms throughout the country that trouble is brewing between
Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo and Manager
Buck Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Before the rumor continues blazing across the nation, let's get
one thing straight: There is absolutely no rift between Colangelo
and Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   None.
</P>
<P>
   Zip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anyone I respect, trust or feel closer
to than Jerry Colangelo,'' Showalter said. ``To even respond to
this is ridiculous, because it almost gives it credence. It's so
far from the truth, it's not even worthy of a response.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst part of this sordid tale is that national radio
personality Jim Rome, who has quite a cult following, mentioned the
alleged problems on his show, further spreading the false talk.
</P>
<P>
   The item on the Diamondbacks was sandwiched between a Chicago
White Sox note and another about Jim Leyritz, deep in Gammons'
weekly notes column. This is how it appeared in Sunday's ``Boston
Globe'':
</P>
<P>
   `` There is constant speculation about the White Sox front
office, much of it fueled by Kenny Williams's self-promotion. And
you may not want to invite Jerry Colangelo and Buck Showalter to th
e same cocktail party. Tricks of the trade: Granted, Jim Leyritz is
a good hitter ''.
</P>
<P>
   Gammons, reached Monday night at his Massachusetts home, said
the short item was intended as a joke and that his newspaper, the
highly respected ``Boston Globe,'' edited out the second half of
his statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a joke about when things go wrong,'' Gammons said.
``That's why I picked a cocktail party. Neither would go to a
cocktail party because they'd never leave their job; they're so
obsessed with what they have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in baseball have been taking so many shots at these
guys (Colangelo and Showalter). It was a joke and the rest of the
item got cut.''
</P>
<P>
   At first it seemed like such an insignificant note that it would
not merit a response from the Diamondbacks. But with the
speculation running rampant, it's time to cut this nonsense off
before it becomes a wild fire and some people have Showalter on the
street, suitcase in hand.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Showalter may be one of the most solidly
entrenched managers in the game today. He is arguably the most
powerful manager, with as much say over personnel decisions as
top-ranking managers such as Atlanta's Bobby Cox or St. Louis' Tony
La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo handpicked the meticulous Showalter from a pool of
potential candidates who would have lined up at any corner for a
chance to manage Arizona's expansion entry.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in baseball knew the Diamondbacks were not going to
cower and play the small-market role; that this was a club that was
going to shoot out of the gate, guns ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   This was a club that said it was going to be a big-time player
and immediately followed their big talk by signing Jay Bell, Andy
Benes, Willie Blair and Matt Williams for a combined salary of
$111.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   They were also going to be able to back up the big salaries with
what amounts to a river of revenue. What manager wouldn't want an
opportunity to have a big payroll to play with?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the false innuendo stung a bit, especially with all the
other potshots the Diamondbacks have had to put up with since
before the expansion draft, even if some of them were
self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Gammons item appeared, Diamondbacks General Manager Joe
Garagiola Jr., made a point of calling Colangelo, who has been
vacationing in Europe and is set to return to Phoenix tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He laughed when I read him the line,'' Garagiola said. ``He
asked, `Where do people get this stuff from?' It was the only
appropriate reaction. The unfortunate part is that it's like trying
to un-ring a bell. There's absolutely zero to this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
