<P>
   Food and dining stories in sight at this hour from The N.Y.
Times News Service for Wednesday, June 24:
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (212)
556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and
Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-SCHOOLS (New York) _ A pile of carrots, turnips, onions,
shallots, lettuce leaves and potatoes lay on a stainless-steel
table at the French Culinary Institute's teaching kitchen. My
mission, on this first day of La Technique, the institute's basic
course for amateur chefs, was to turn those vegetables into
textbook examples of the basic French cuts. My goal was to test the
basic-skill courses offered by New York's top cooking schools: the
French Culinary Institute, Peter Kump's School of Culinary Arts and
the culinary arts division of the New School. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-CIA (New York) _ It used to be that if you wanted to
become a chef, you were expected to go to cooking school in Paris.
There you learned classic technique, the organization of the French
kitchen, and discipline under the critical eye of French
instructors. And when you returned to America, you were practically
guaranteed to land a job at a top restaurant. But over the last
decade, the culinary world changed. Cuisines fused, and American
kitchens were transformed from French food factories into dens of
creativity. Nowhere is the break with the past clearer than in a
comparison of the most influential school in the United States, the
Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, N.Y., with its
counterpart in France, Le Cordon Bleu in Paris. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING-GRADS (New York) _ By the time Matthew Laux completed a
two-year program last March at the New England Culinary Institute _
after paying nearly $40,000 for an education that encompasses all
aspects of the food service industry _ he had earned his reward: a
job at Trois Jean, a New York bistro, where he peeled and chopped
vegetables 12 hours a day, six days a week. For this, he received
the munificent sum of $65 a shift. The food service industry is
booming nationally, and students who complete a culinary school
education will almost certainly have a career ahead of them. But
they may not have a life. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CIPRIANI (New York) _ To most New Yorkers, the name Cipriani
means just the boutique restaurant in the Sherry-Netherland that
his father, Arrigo, opened in 1985 and where they serve the Bellini
cocktails invented at Harry's Bar in Venice (started by Giuseppi
Cipriani's grandfather in 1931). But that profile is about to get a
lot higher. By Florence Fabricanbt.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   WINE-OPERA (Undated) _ Using wine labels, the sommelier at
Harry's Bar in London makes collages that depict opera scenes
involving wine. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   HANMADE-MOZZARELLA (New York) _ Mezzogiorno, Tribeca Grill and
Bice are among the restaurants that want handmade, tender
mozzarella that tastes and smells as pure as it looks. They all
rely on the early morning visits of Giuseppe Cuomo, a traveling
mozzarella maker. His family has done the same for three
generations in southern Italy, and Cuomo, 52, continued the
tradition after he moved here 20 years ago. By Suzanne Hamlin.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC-BROTH (Undated) _ In this season of good vegetables and
good garlic, soups based on a meatless garlic broth are a pleasure.
By Barbara Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 recipes.
</P>
