<P>
   CHINA-SCANDALS (Washington) _ As if controversy over his
scheduled visit to Tiananmen Square isn't enough, President Clinton
has two other major clouds hanging over his trip to China: the
domestic controversies over alleged Chinese contributions to the
Democrats and questions about the sale of missile technology to the
Chinese. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ Trade experts and diplomatic sources
warn that any disruption in U.S.-China trade at this time could
send China into a recession, force the country to devalue its
currency and send economies from Bangkok to Tokyo spinning out of
control. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ As President Clinton prepares to
leave on his historic trip to China, critics of the
administration's China policy blast his decision to go but urge him
to be tough with Chinese leaders on such issues as human rights,
religious freedom, interference in U.S. politics, trade
restrictions and weapons proliferation. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-DIABETES (Washington) _ A national campaign to make
Hispanics more aware of the dangers of diabetes is launched by
specialists, who say that Latinos and other minorities have a
higher rate of the disease and its complications than Anglos. By
NICOLE TSONG.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-ATTACK (Jasper, Texas) _ Shortly after James Byrd Jr. was
beaten, one of the three suspects in the fatal attack spray-painted
the victim's face with black paint, one of the accused men has told
the police. Also, local officials are urging the Ku Klux Klan not
to hold a march here Saturday. By RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NASA-TECHNOLOGY (Houston) _ NASA and the University of Houston
have formed an organization to develop technology for consumer and
industrial use and to help technology companies develop their
products. One item being considered is a water filtration system
using ultraviolet radiation instead of chlorine. By KAREN SANTOS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ When Money magazine chose the
nation's capital this month as the ``best place to live'' in the
Northeast, eyes rolled. Imagine that a political city with what
President Clinton once called an ``abnormal'' atmosphere could be
considered desirable! But this city has always been better than New
York. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-U.S.-JOBS (Paris) _ already filed _ The trip of France's
Socialist Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to the United States last
week punctured a cherished French myth _ that the vast increase in
American jobs since 1993 was mainly due to hamburger-flipper-type
work. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN.
</P>
