<HEADLINE>
SPACE ... THE BUSINESS FRONTIER: NASA, UH FORM TEAM ON SPINOFFS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KAREN SANTOS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Tang and Velcro are probably two of the most
well-known spinoffs of the U.S. space program.
</P>
<P>
   In the more than 25 years that NASA has commercialized
innovations designed for the special rigors of space, most were
licensed directly to various existing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hoping its innovations can give birth to and support entire
companies, NASA and the University of Houston recently formed a
business incubator.
</P>
<P>
   The incubator will help create business strategies and find
funding for new businesses based on NASA spinoffs, as well as other
innovations brought to it by individuals and companies.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the UH-NASA Technology Commercialization Incubator has
focused on 15 innovations, said Judy Johncox, director of
technology management at UH and temporary director of the
incubator.
</P>
<P>
   Here are just a few:
</P>
<P>
   _ A water filtration system using ultraviolet radiation instead
of chlorine. It could be used in sewage treatment plants or in home
purification systems. It is advantageous because ultraviolet rays
do not leave residue, while chlorine does. Over time, chlorine
exposure can lead to cancer.
</P>
<P>
   _ A testing procedure for herpes that will detect the disease
sooner than other methods. The test uses a modified chemical
reaction process that needs only a small amount of genetic material
to make many copies. That, in turn, allows for an easier and
quicker diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   The test is projected to detect the disease within a few hours
instead of the usual two to three days at present.
</P>
<P>
   _ A method that would allow blood to be stored in a refrigerator
for up to 72 hours before it is processed or analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   This will be useful to small medical labs and remote medical
facilities, which often do not have the tools for proper analysis
of blood.
</P>
<P>
   _ A pressure sensor that is only two inches square. Such a
device might help in deploying air bags during an auto collision.
</P>
<P>
   Current air bag systems can only detect front-end collisions,
and the sensors in these systems are expensive. New air bag systems
may be equipped with side-impact bags, which would require more
sensors, and the patented pressure sensor being developed for
market by the incubator might help reduce the cost of the systems.
</P>
<P>
   There is no set time frame for the release of these products,
Johncox said. Many are still in development and could be released
six months to a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen of the 15 products under consideration have patents or
have patents pending.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently no businesses within the incubator. However,
both Johncox and Arthur Vailas, vice president for research at UH,
said they would begin searching for companies for the incubator in
the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good thing for Earth-based spinoffs of NASA
research,'' Vailas said. ``The university has a good view for
evaluating technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The university will draw upon students in its graduate business
program and the resources of its small business development office
to help show future businessmen what is vital to the birth and
development of their company.
</P>
<P>
   Vailas said the university also will draw upon the knowledge of
faculty at other colleges with which it is affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has a history of spinning off products.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Velcro and Tang, the technology used to shield
the space shuttle from the sun's heat is used to keep race car
drivers cool inside their cars.
</P>
<P>
   The liquid cooling garment worn by astronauts has been adapted
to help people born without sweat glands to eliminate excessive
body heat. Also, some people with multiple sclerosis, for example,
have found that the suit relieves their symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   NASA also developed the bioreactor, which keeps human and other
cells alive during space experiments. It's now being used in cancer
research in studies of tumor growth.
</P>
<P>
   The technology transfer department at Johnson Space Center in
Houston licenses products to be developed for consumers, said James
Cameron, who works for the NASA department.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Cameron's department helps evaluate the technology,
its commercial potential and its patentability.
</P>
<P>
   After a product is identified as a potential consumer item, and
a patent application has been filed, the product is shown to
potential licensees.
</P>
<P>
   An upfront fee of up to $10,000 as well as royalties are
charged. If a product makes a few million dollars, royalties are no
longer collected. Cameron said a large majority of the profit,
about 97 percent, usually is kept by the licensee.
</P>
<P>
   The incubator is different in that it will spin off new
businesses from NASA technology, and allow inventors to develop
their ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``You usually have someone technical who wants to develop
technology, who doesn't want a business plan,'' a common mistake
among technology start-ups, Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big difference is that UH is a class act; it has all the
resources,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UH had formed an alliance with NASA in 1986, to develop a
process that used molecular beams to put a layer of chemicals just
a few atoms thick onto silicon and other crystals used in producing
microchips.
</P>
<P>
   Johncox said development of certain technologies will be
assigned to faculty members whose research complements the function
of the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Johncox said she hopes that ``we will be a vehicle ... to
commercialization'' for many innovations. ``This is not just a NASA
vehicle, or a University of Houston vehicle, it's also important to
the city and the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The incubator will be funded for three years by a $1.2 million
grant from NASA. UH is currently looking for other sources of
funding so it can continue its research after three years. Johncox
said it probably will seek funding from the National Science
Foundation, a government agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be a model which spreads across the country,'' Vailas
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
