<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Wednesday, June 24. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (212-556-1927).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Beijing) _ At home, President Clinton's fortunes
may wax and wane, but here, on the eve of his first state visit to
China, he is already a star. Not only in the official press but
also among elements of the intelligentsia, he is being lionized as
a great statesman who had the wisdom to change his mind about China
_ turning from his early attack stance to his current policy of
engagement. Clinton's great global vision, it seems, ranks him
right up there with that all-time great strategist, Richard Nixon,
who will ever be revered here for reviving ties between the United
States and China. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ALBANIANS (Klina, Serbia) _ The gong of church bells
summoned the Serbs up to the weed-choked cemetery with its ancient
stone crosses, marble tombs etched with the faces of the departed,
crooked iron gates and gnarled trees. During the tolling, the open
coffin of Oliver Zaic, 17, his face waxy with the pallor of death,
was carried through the dusty streets, lifted through a hole in the
cemetery fence and borne up the steep hill. He was killed in his
garden, his family said, as he tried to protect his widowed mother
and 10-year-old sister Marica from ethnic Albanian rebels who in
recent days have begun to attack and kidnap Serbian civilians in an
apparent effort to drive them out of their villages in the
overwhelmingly Albanian province of Kosovo. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-REPORT (Geneva) _ AIDS is hitting Africa so fiercely that
it now rivals history's greatest and deadliest epidemics _ plague
in the Middle Ages and influenza in 1918-1919, United Nations
officials said here today. They also said the AIDS epidemic will
worsen before it improves. The overwhelming majority of the 30
million people infected with HIV, the AIDS virus, are doomed to die
because they live in countries that cannot provide adequate health
care. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ President Boris Yeltsin summoned Russian
legislators to a public meeting on Tuesday and demanded that they
adopt a rash of new measures to restore the confidence of foreign
investors. The extraordinary session was intended to impress the
International Monetary Fund, which is beginning new negotiations
over billions of dollars in additional financing. But Yeltsin also
warned the Communist-dominated parliament: ``If the package of
bills in the government is not approved, other measures will be
taken.'' By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PEONY (Shanghai) _ After a day of last-minute efforts to
negotiate a compromise that would permit a local opera company to
travel to New York City to perform a classic Chinese opera, ``The
Peony Pavilion,'' as a centerpiece of the Lincoln Center Festival
next month, cultural officials here continue to block the project.
The director of the Shanghai Bureau of Culture instead insisted
that the company's modern staging of the work was inappropriate for
foreign viewers and would not be permitted to travel. Coming just
days before the arrival of President Clinton, who is scheduled to
land in China on Thursday evening, the artistic controversy now
threatens to sour an otherwise optimistic atmosphere that has been
carefully planned by Chinese and American officials for the visit,
which includes three days in Shanghai beginning June 29. By Seth
Faison.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-IRS (Washington) _ Republican leaders appeared likely
to cut the holding period for investors to get favorable capital
gains tax rates by pushing the measure onto a bipartisan bill
overhauling the Internal Revenue Service. The move was an effort by
Republicans to take advantage of the White House's apparent
reluctance to get into a partisan fight over the IRS bill, which
passed both the House and Senate by overwhelming margins and is one
of the few major pieces of legislation likely to come out of
Congress and be signed by President Clinton this year. By Richard
W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Setting Congress on a collision
course with President Clinton, a House panel proposed slashing the
President's education initiatives as well as the annual financing
for home-heating oil for the poor. The proposal provides
substantial increases for the National Institutes of Health and the
Centers for Disease Control. At the same time, it takes a
$2.6-billion bite out of Administration priorities, cutting
education spending and eliminating programs that provided summer
jobs, helped pay heating bills and provided tutors for low-income
families. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Nothing at this hour.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-SUIT (Washington) _ In a victory for the Microsoft
Corp., a federal appeals court struck down two previous decisions
against the company by the judge who is overseeing the government's
current Microsoft antitrust case. Although Tuesday's appellate
decision involved a separate Microsoft case, the ruling throws into
question a significant portion of the Justice Department's pending
suit against the company, which is scheduled for trial this fall
under U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Jackson. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
