<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-SLIPPING-FORTU     06-23 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-SLIPPING-FORTUNE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S DECLINING FORTUNE IS ZEDILLO'S NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JORGE G. CASTANEDA &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   As little as a year ago fortune finally seemed to be smiling
upon Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The economy was vigorously recovering from the deep recession of
1995-96, and was on the way to its highest yearly expansion since
1981. Employment was up; even wages had stopped falling and were
beginning to rise.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the mid-term congressional and gubernatorial
elections had placed Mexico firmly on the road to democratization.
The results were not contested, and the ruling PRI lost its
absolute majority in the lower house, while the opposition picked
up several victories in state races.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the win in Mexico City saw Cuauhtimoc Cardenas, the
symbol of resistance to the prior government of Carlos Salinas de
Gortari, elected mayor by a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Disquieting trends persisted: In Chiapas, peace negotiations
remained stagnant; in Guerrero, new guerrilla groups surfaced; in
the cities, a crime wave was met by a collapse in law enforcement;
and in government, President Ernesto Zedillo, surrounded by a
remarkably mediocre team, seemed out of touch with Mexico's new
balance of forces.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there were stronger grounds for optimism than in many
years and skeptics, such as this writer, seemed increasingly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Today, even the naysayers seem to have fallen short in their
pessimism. Although foreign perceptions remain upbeat _ fortunately
and blindly _ in Mexico there is a widespread sense that the
country is adrift. Economic, social, political and psychological
trends add up to an unease and foreboding uncommon even by
traditional Mexican standards. Just about the only note of optimism
stems from the national soccer team's exceptional performance in
the World Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo wanted at all costs to avoid the sixth-year, end-of-term
jinx that has befallen every Mexican president since Luis
Echeverrmi in 1976. In fact, he is on the verge of succumbing to a
last-year-in-office crisis two and a half years before his
administration ends.
</P>
<P>
   The ominous signs are everywhere. On the economic front, the
plunge in oil prices is wreaking havoc with Mexican public
finances. Oil still accounts for nearly 40 percent of government
revenues. The president was forced to acknowledge that a third,
hefty cut in domestic spending is probably inevitable, given the
current glut in world oil markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican stock exchange index has fallen almost 20 percent in
five weeks in peso terms, and an additional 5 percent in dollars;
the currency dropped below the nine-peso-to-the-dollar barrier and
shows no sign of strengthening.
</P>
<P>
   Part of this dismal showing is inspired by international trends
_ the Asian crisis, the current squabble with Washington over
Operation Casablanca and the United States' unabashed and
unannounced intrusion into Mexican territory to carry out a
money-laundering sting. Local factors are also at play _ for
example, the banking crisis and the government's failure to
convince the Congress to pass the $65 billion bailout bill over to
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, opposition congressmen are reluctant to do
Zedillo's bidding, in this regard, and even PRI legislators are
wary of backing their president. The reason is obvious. The
government claims it had no choice but to buy off the newly
privatized banks' bad loans.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the Congress never formally authorized the
bailout; meanwhile, the evidence of corruption, insider trading,
crony-capitalism and self-lending by the ``new bankers'' is
mounting. Pressure from abroad for transparency and disclosure in
national accounts grows by the day, but Zedillo cannot deliver. The
Congress will not bail him out on the bail out, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for nervousness and dismay is bloodier, and far
more disturbing to Mexico as a nation. In one week, incidents in
Guerrero and Chiapas showed how precarious the situations are
there, and how unprepared the Mexican security and armed forces are
for the type of policy the government is intent on pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   On a Monday, in the small Guerrero town of Ayutla, the army
surrounded a small schoolhouse where a dozen guerrillas were
spending the night. They opened fire, with scant or no warning,
killing 12 Mixteco ``presumed combatants.'' The army suffered no
casualties. There was little evidence of the guerrillas returning
fire and soon, the Mexican press began to point to a cold-blooded
execution, rather than a firefight.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, in the Chiapas village of El Bosque, local
police forces backed by the army moved in on one of the 40 or so
``autonomous townships'' set up by the Zapatista rebels. The
ostensible purpose of the 1,000-troop assault was to ``reestablish
the rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Villagers apparently defended themselves with shotguns, hunting
weapons and sticks and stones. Government forces replied with
mortar and automatic-weapons fire. Eight villagers were killed; the
army suffered one dead and several wounded. Reports began to
surface that the eight dead had been executed after the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential elections are still two years away, and Zedillo's
term concludes on Dec. 1, 2000. The question is whether the current
storm clouds herald the beginning of the traditional last-year
crisis _ or are the country's present travails merely a pebble in
the road to be quickly left behind? One can hope for the latter,
but should expect the former.
</P>
<P>
   Although previous experience and Zedillo's obsession with
preventing a debacle should suffice to avoid a full-fledged
economic meltdown, a combination of recession, gridlock, violence
and political turmoil is more likely.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a classical, big-bang type of crisis similar to those
in 1976, 1982, 1987-88 and 1994-95, Mexico may be entering a new,
prolonged period of political instability and economic fragility.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a case of fortune smiling on anyone.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jorge G. Castaneda, Latin America's leading political
scientist, is the author of the best-selling ``Companero: The Life
and Death of Che Guevara.'' Castaneda lives in New York and Mexico
City and teaches at New York University.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
