<HEADER>
A2792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SCANDALS-HNS &LR;      06-23 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SCANDALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY QUESTIONS HANG OVER CLINTON TRIP TO CHINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Among the many clouds hanging over President
Clinton's historic visit to China this week, one in particular may,
for many Americans, be the darkest of all.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Clinton administration, swayed by the Democratic Party's
largest donor, change export policy and aid a U.S. satellite firm
that may have helped China improve its nuclear missiles? And, did
China actively try to influence the 1996 U.S. elections with
illegal campaign donations?
</P>
<P>
   The questions bring curt denials from administration officials,
but Republicans on Capitol Hill spent much of last week trying to
keep the public's attention focused on those issues as Clinton
prepared to travel to the Asian giant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly would not be involved in any kind of sale that in
any way jeopardized our national interests,'' said Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in appearances before House and Senate
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have accused the administration of twisting export
policy to favor a campaign donor whose company was under
investigation for providing China with information that could have
improved its Long March missiles. And, they repeatedly accused
China of conspiring with Democrats to funnel money into campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of both issues is the China Aerospace Corp., a
state-owned offspring of the Red Army.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1970s, China Aerospace has operated a commercial
venture using its Long March rockets to boost into orbit satellites
owned by international customers.
</P>
<P>
   But a series of mishaps, five in four years, prompted increasing
international pressure in 1996 for the firm to improve the
reliability of its rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are now looking at two decisions President Clinton
made. In March 1996, Clinton moved the authority over satellite
export control from the State Department to the Commerce
Department, which regulates so-called ``dual-use technology.''
</P>
<P>
   This February, Clinton also granted, despite objections from the
Justice Department, a waiver of a satellite launch ban to Hughes
Electronics and Loral Space &AMP; Communications Ltd., allowing them to
use China Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, at the time, was investigating whether
Loral illegally provided missile technology to China Aerospace
following the 1996 explosion of a Long March rocket carrying a
Loral satellite. Justice objected to the February waiver,
contending it could undermine any case against Loral.
</P>
<P>
   Administration critics argue the information provided by Loral
could have been used by China Aerospace to improve the guidance
systems of not only the Long March rockets, but other missiles
armed with nuclear warheads pointed at the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we export a satellite to China and pay the Chinese
government to launch it, we are directly or indirectly enhancing
the ability to improve its space and military launch capability,''
said Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Loral is owned by Bernard Schwartz, a major Democratic
contributor who was the party's largest donor at $1.3 million since
1995. Schwartz has denied any attempt to influence the waiver
decision with campaign donations.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials note that President Bush granted nine
launch waivers while in office to President Clinton's 11. And, they
point to a 1993 letter signed by 30 California House members, 16 of
them Republicans, protesting the launch ban, noting the satellites
are guarded and no transfer of technology is possible.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., called on Clinton to delay
his trip until the questions about the Loral waiver and the
decision to move satellite export control to the Commerce
Department were answered.
</P>
<P>
   Congress' investigation into China's alleged attempt to
influence U.S. election in 1996 was rejuvenated last month when a
central figure changed his story and told of receiving money from a
former Red Army officer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Chung, a California businessman who pleaded guilty to
making illegal campaign contributions, told Justice investigators
that in August 1996 he received $300,000 from Liu Chaoying, a top
executive at China Aerospace International Holdings, a China
Aerospace subsidiary, and gave at least $35,000 of it to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Chung provided the first piece of evidence connecting the
Chinese government to illegal contributions. He previously denied
any such connections, but the businessman had likened the White
House to a subway where tokens were needed to get inside. Chung
visited the White House more than three dozen times despite
warnings from national security officials who labeled him a
``hustler.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, there were reports that Chung told investigators that
Democratic Party officials asked him to solicit illegal foreign
donations.
</P>
<P>
   China President Jiang Zemin repeatedly has denied any attempt to
divert funds to U.S. candidates. China Aerospace officials first
suggested Liu spent her own money but later denied that she had
given Chung any funds. Last week, another China Aerospace official
said the $300,000 came from a Hong Kong businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Chung's indictment was one of three secured by a special Justice
Department task force investigating the campaign irregularities for
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Also under indictment are Maria Hsia, accused of money
laundering in connection with a Buddhist Temple fund-raiser
attended by Vice President Al Gore, and Yah Lin ``Charlie'' Trie,
the former Little Rock, Ark., friend of the president's. Trie and a
friend are charged with 15 counts in a scheme to divert foreign
money to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of others also are under investigation, including John
Huang, a former Democratic Party fund-raiser who raised $3 million
in 1996 from the Asian community. The party returned $1.6 million
raised by Huang because it could not determine the money source.
Huang, a Chinese-born American citizen, previously worked for the
Riady family's Lippo Group based in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
