<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2804 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANTHERS-VANBIE24-COX     06-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANTHERS-VANBIE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vanbiesbrouck back in Panthers' picture
 &HT;    By Brian Biggane
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If new coach Terry Murray gets his way, the Florida Panthers'
search for a goaltender could end where it began _ with John
Vanbiesbrouck.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, who praised Vanbiesbrouck Sunday during the news
conference to name him coach, apparently has encouraged his
brother, General Manager Bryan Murray, to renew efforts to work out
a deal with Lloyd Friedland, Vanbiesbrouck's agent.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides spoke for the first time in months late last week,
according to an NHL source. The meeting was apparently at Terry
Murray's urging. Bryan Murray said no negotiations were conducted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry thinks John is a good goaltender,'' Bryan Murray said
Monday. ``He said it (Sunday) and again today _ he feels you have
to have a good goaltender to win in this league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that strengthens John's position (to sign with
Florida) or not, but it does confirm that he likes him.''
</P>
<P>
   The departure of Vanbiesbrouck, who can become an unrestricted
free agent July 1 if he's not signed, has been anticipated for
months, since negotiations stalled with the two sides about $1
million apart per season.
</P>
<P>
   Vanbiesbrouck is asking for$4.5 million per season, while the
Panthers are offering $3.5 million. The top two goaltenders in the
free-agent market, Curtis Joseph of Edmonton and Mike Richter of
the New York Rangers, are both seeking about $7 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's plan has been to protect Kevin Weekes in Friday's
expansion draft and hope to pick up another up-and-coming
goaltender in a trade with Nashville, which can select up to five
goaltenders.
</P>
<P>
   But the protected lists released Monday revealed that four teams
_ Los Angeles, San Jose, Boston and Anaheim _ protected two
goaltenders apiece, thus shortening the list.
</P>
<P>
   Among those protected were the Sharks' Steve Shields and Kings'
Jamie Storr, both of whom Murray had considered.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of unprotected goalies were backups Jamie
McLennan of St. Louis, Craig Billington of Colorado, Kevin Hodson
of Detroit and Mike Dunham of New Jersey. None has ever spent a
full season as a No. 1 NHL goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Murray said Sunday that the decision on keeping
Vanbiesbrouck would ultimately fall to Bryan Murray, President Bill
Torrey and owner Wayne Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he had clear memories of Vanbiesbrouck's
spectacular playoff run two years ago. One of the teams Florida
beat during that run was the Philadelphia team coached by Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know how he played,'' Murray said. ``(The Panthers)
beat the Flyers, and I think he was the reason why.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the goaltending situation Sunday, Bryan Murray said,
``The three of us (the two Murrays and Torrey) have to sit down and
talk about that. We have to find out if Terry's satisfied and go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, he added, ``All along our interest in John was very
clear, given the right opportunity, the right contract.''
</P>
<P>
   If Vanbiesbrouck goes to free agency, the Panthers' biggest
competition for his services could be the New York Islanders, who
traded backup Eric Fichaud over the weekend, leaving them with only
Tommy Salo and 19-year-old prospect Roberto Luongo.
</P>
<P>
   Vanbiesbrouck made $2.2 million last season in the final year of
a three-year contract. As has generally been the case when he was
up for a new contract, he had a subpar year, finishing 29th in the
league with a 2.87 goals-against average and an 18-29-11 record.
</P>
<P>
   The first player selected by Florida in the 1993 entry draft,
Vanbiesbrouck is one of only six remaining original Panthers. He
will turn 35 in September. Friedland is seeking a three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   Vanbiesbrouck was left unprotected in the expansion draft, as
were Joseph, Richter and Philadelphia's Sean Burke. But since all
will be free to sign with any team after July 1, there's only one
reason Nashville would select any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Since a team that loses a goaltender this year doesn't have to
expose one in next year's expansion draft, a team like New York
could persuade the Predators to take Richter, then compensate them
for the trouble, re-sign him and not have to risk losing him next
year.
</P>
<P>
   (endit)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-23-98 0139E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
