r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STODA-COLUMN24-COX     06-23 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STODA-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Jordan, that was Zen, and this is now
 &HT;    By Greg Stoda
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Phil Jackson jumps on a motorcycle signed by Chicago Bulls one
and all, drives away from the team's practice facility in Zen
farewell and everyone assumes an NBA dynasty now lies in ruins?
</P>
<P>
   Please.
</P>
<P>
   Spare me.
</P>
<P>
   The kingdom and glory of professional basketball in Chicago will
collapse only when a team dethrones the Bulls by beating them on
the court, or when Michael Jordan retires again (see as source:
Heat coach Pat Riley, who has insisted as much for many, many
years).
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Jackson was anything other than an
excellent coach and master motivator while directing his team to
six titles in matching sets of three during the 1990s, but the
Bulls' future will be in good and secure hands with George Karl or
Roy Williams or Dean Smith or some other Carolina Blueblood running
things... as long as Jordan is around.
</P>
<P>
   The rumor mill is spinning out of control in Michaeltown these
days, and the best guesses on Jordan's considerations concerning
his future are exactly that _ guesses.
</P>
<P>
   The aforementioned Carolina Blueblood item, for example, is
rooted in the notion that Jordan, who, of course, is out of the
Carolina Bluebloodline himself, will continue to wear Tar Heel
practice shorts under his Chicago game trunks only if he is allowed
to name Jackson's successor.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of all this BS (Bull Speculation), there
existed five possibilities; 1) Jordan would play for Jackson in
Chicago; 2) Jordan would play for someone else in Chicago; 3)
Jordan would play for Jackson somewhere else; 4) Jordan would play
for someone else somewhere else; 5) Jordan would quit.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has removed the ``both-in-Chicago'' scenario from the
list, and does not seem inclined at this time to pursue another
coaching job. What that means is Jordan's pie chart of
possibilities now includes only three slices, and playing somewhere
else for someone other than Jackson seems remote. Let's put that
one at 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   So, does Jordan stay in Chicago with a new head coach?
</P>
<P>
   Or does he quit?
</P>
<P>
   Says here it's 60-30 favoring Jordan's return to his very own
Sweet Sixteam in pursuit of a seventh championship, and a first one
without Jackson. And maybe without superstar sidekick Scottie
Pippen, too, and a whole bunch of other free-agent Bulls as well.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   For the simple reason that Jordan craves a challenge. If one
isn't handy, he'll create something. He wants the chance to again
defend a championship, and might even enjoy having a new cast of
compatriots with whom to undertake the effort.
</P>
<P>
   What if, for the sake of argument, the Bulls were able to shed
themselves of enough salary _ see ya' Scottie, see ya' Dennis
Oddman, see ya', see ya', see ya' all other dollar drainers not
named Jordan _ and land New Jersey's Jayson Williams and Detroit's
Jerry Stackhouse while keeping Toni Kukoc and Ron Harper?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan and those four guys would form a nice starting lineup,
huh?
</P>
<P>
   Oh, he should quit. He should walk away and stay away and not
worry about how the NBA learns to breathe without Air. He should
leave in concert with Jackson and in ultimate demonstration of
their mutual allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   But can he satisfy himself, as he insists he can, with what has
already been accomplished?
</P>
<P>
   Or, as usual, does Jordan see another summit?
</P>
<P>
   He knows he can't spell zenith without Z-E-N, but would love to
prove he can get there without it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
