</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money talk: Whatever you do about stocks, don't panic
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- Most experts agree on how to deal with a stock market
as high and as tippy as this one. Don't do anything, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Their rationale is a sound one: Nobody knows when the market
will decline. Nobody knows how low it will go or how long it will
stay down in the horse latitudes. But everyone knows it will come
back, and eventually the advance will continue.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of studies back this up. One, published by Van Kampen
American Capital, showed the average bear market lasts eight
months. The average recovery lasts a bit more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody questions the Ibbotson Associates' studies, now
covering more than 71 years, which demonstrate investors get much
higher returns from stocks than from other forms of investment. The
most recent figures, through the end of May, gave big-company
stocks a score of 11.1 percent, compared with 5.8 percent for
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Less publicized studies, such as those cited in the
illustration, demonstrate the damage you can do to yourself by
hopping in and out of the stock market. If you try to dodge the bad
days, you'll probably miss a bunch of the good days, too.
</P>
<P>
   With that said, there are plenty of investors who worry about
getting creamed in the stock market. Even if they're saving for
retirement 20 years from now, they fear they're going to get hurt
by the bears right now.
</P>
<P>
   That worry can be more compelling than all the statistics on
Wall Street. Indeed, one of the risks in investing is fear. What
happens if the market goes down and you can't stand the pain? Are
you going to sell out, hoping to cut your losses even as you make
them real?
</P>
<P>
   If you are profoundly worried, there are a couple of things you
can and should do. The first is to examine carefully how much pain,
and how much uncertainty, you can bear. The second is to act on
what you discover, preferably slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Step one is what insiders refer to as establishing your risk
tolerance. It's a parallel to the first law of hang gliding: Never
fly higher than you're willing to fall.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy, mainly because risk aversion is an individual
thing and a subjective one. For married couples, it's a much more
complicated, two-individual thing. It's the eternal balancing act
for investors: how much return you want or need vs. how much
uncertainty you're willing to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   One approach is a bit of mind-gaming. It goes like this: Think
about the retirement savings you have invested in stocks. Suppose
today is the day the stock market drops 20 percent. Subtract 20
percent from your family's savings. Are your hands shaking? Are you
willing to wait for a better day tomorrow? Or do you want to sell
those faithless stocks and hole up in CDs forever?
</P>
<P>
   For an insight just a shade more informative, you can go on the
Internet and search out a number of risk tolerance quizzes. The
results are at best rough ideas, but they can help stimulate your
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I would avoid the ones that require you to submit
your answers and wait for a scoring from the company. Sounds too
much like a sales call to me. You can find reasonably good ones at
http://www.mcdonaldfunds.com
</P>
<P>
   /risk.htm and http://www
</P>
<P>
   .strong-funds.com/aci/planner
</P>
<P>
   .cgi?planasset.
</P>
<P>
   Other alternatives involve more systematic efforts at education.
If you have a 401(k) or other retirement plan at work, the office
that manages your plan may well have informative booklets on
dealing with stock market volatility. If you use a stockbroker or
mutual fund manager, that agency may offer free literature. If you
have a decent library, look for the books numbered 332, check in
the indexes under ``risk,'' and read what you need.
</P>
<P>
   Step two may be a timely one, even if you haven't discovered new
depths of stock fright. This is the action step, referred to by
pros as rebalancing your account.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you put half of your 401(k) contributions into a stock
fund, a fourth of it into a bond fund and a fourth into a money
market fund. But you've decided that's too risky. You would rather
rebalance, cutting stocks back to 40 percent and boosting bonds to
35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Or suppose you want to maintain 50 percent in stocks, but the
booming market has outrun your bonds and money market fund. Stocks
now make up, say, 65 percent of your account, and you find that too
risky.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, you can decide whether to do it all at once or
gradually -- the approach favored by most experts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advise clients to take their future contributions and put
them in the sector that they want to add to,'' said Mike Gerken,
senior vice president of investment manager Waddell &AMP; Reed. ``You
make it a process, rather than making it an event. You can't time
the market.''
</P>
<P>
   That slow-and-easy approach avoids any sales charges, as well as
lowering the chances of selling a big block of stock on a bad day
in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, don't panic. The point of this whole exercise is to
reduce your exposure not to stocks but to panic. ``There's no
reason for it,'' said Gerken.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he suggests declines could be a good thing for steady
investors. ``If an investment made sense for you yesterday and
prices go down today, it makes even more sense to invest some more
today,'' Gerken said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-06-19-98 2317E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
