r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RACING-PINCAY24-COX     06-23 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-PINCAY24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pincay's skills have eroded, but his chase of Shoemaker goes on
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ During a week in June, jockey Laffit Pincay rode in
promotions at tracks in Kentucky, Iowa and Texas, but did not win
in 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   But he raced three days that week at his home track, Hollywood
Park, and won three times. That made it a good week.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay is the most honored rider in the history of horse racing,
the only person (owner, trainer or jockey) ever to win five Eclipse
Awards.
</P>
<P>
   But winning three times in a week isn't a regular occurrence
anymore for Pincay.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, he won 380 times, more than any rider in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he won just 75 races.
</P>
<P>
   At 51, Pincay is fighting the record book and the calendar
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to become the all-time winningest jockey, but he is
running out of time. Every day, the owners and trainers of the best
horses in California tell Pincay that his hour is past. They tell
him by not letting him ride their horses any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wasn't great, he would be gone,'' said trainer Richard
Mandella.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Pincay goes on.
</P>
<P>
   He travels across the country, to Iowa, Texas and Kentucky,
chasing Willie Shoemaker's record of 8,833.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay is 210 short of that.
</P>
<P>
   At the present rate, he won't catch Shoemaker this century.
</P>
<P>
   Was Ahab more obsessed?
</P>
<P>
   ``You need goals in your life, no matter what age you are,''
Pincay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got plenty of time. As good as I feel, I can ride until
I'm 60.''
</P>
<P>
   But at 60, who will give him horses to ride?
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker, who retired in 1990, rode until he was 58. But after
50, his phone stopped ringing. ``The trainers want the young
bulls,'' Shoemaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay's primary workplace is Southern California, one of the
most competitive areas in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Riders from the top of the national money list, like Gary
Stevens, Kent Desormeaux and Alex Solis, get the best California
mounts. Pincay gets the dregs. It is rare for him to be offered
work in a stakes race any more.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay could get better horses at a smaller track. But he will
not uproot his family. Pincay and his wife, Jeanine, have a
4-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of competing in eight races a day, as he did when he led
the nation in earnings seven times, Pincay has a busy afternoon if
he gets three mounts. And the horses he rides are seldom favorites.
</P>
<P>
   He finished last on a 34-1 shot in Kentucky last week. You won't
catch Gary Stevens or Jerry Bailey on a 34-1 shot.
</P>
<P>
   Pincay has 19 Kentucky Derby starts, but none since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   When Pincay was voted into the Racing Hall of Fame in 1975,
Desormeaux, the 1998 Kentucky Derby winner, was 5 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Pincay is not at the track because he needs the money.
His total purses won are close to $200 million. His share is 10 per
cent.
</P>
<P>
   But Pincay has paid his dues. He has broken his collarbone 11
times. He sustained three cracked ribs and a fractured pelvis in a
fall last year.
</P>
<P>
   The concern about injury is a constant for Pincay's wife. ``I
come home, I hold my breath while I listen to the messages on the
answering machine, until I find out nothing has happened at the
track,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At 46, Eddie Delahoussaye is one of Pincay's oldest California
competitors. ``The only way he is going to retire,'' said
Delahoussaye, ``is if he gets hurt or sick. Or if people just stop
riding him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
