<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK: BENZIGER SYRAH 1995, CALIFORNIA CENTRAL COAST.
ABOUT $16. 
(JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are fanatics who say California, given its predominately
warm climates, should forget about cabernet sauvignon and merlot
and concentrate on hot-climate grapes like syrah, grenache and
mourvedre. That's never going to happen, but if it were to, we
could make do quite nicely with wines like this one.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Bien Nacido Vineyard in Santa Maria, where much of the
fruit in this wine originated, is in a relatively cool climate; the
Shell Creek vineyard, which provided the rest of the grapes, is in
a hot climate. The combination makes for a complex, intriguing
blend. The wine, which includes 4 percent petite sirah _ an
entirely different grape from syrah _ spent 16 months in oak. It
should improve with another year or two in the bottle and last, oh,
maybe a decade after that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
