</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDMADE-MOZZARELLA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOZZARELLA TOO DELICATE TO TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 By SUZANNE HAMLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent sunny morning, Giuseppe Cuomo arrived at
Mezzogiorno restaurant in SoHo a little before 9 o'clock. From his
van, he unloaded a 30-pound pillow of cow's milk curd, toted it
into the restaurant, nodded to the kitchen staff and started to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Changing into chef's whites, he scrubbed his hands and forearms
like a surgeon. Then, with a few deft stokes of a chef's knife, he
cut the big mound of white curd into chunks and pushed them through
a chitarra, a stainless steel device that cuts the curd into small
pieces. The pieces dropped into a huge stainless steel bowl, and
Cuomo covered them with hot water, forcing the curd to release its
whey.
</P>
<P>
   Using his hands and a wooden paddle, Cuomo worked the whey: He
pushed it, pulled it, salted it and kneaded it until it became a
stretchy, satiny blob _ a blob that he was turning into mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   Mezzogiorno, Tribeca Grill, Bice and Naples 45 are among the
restaurants that want handmade fresh, moist, tender mozzarella that
tastes and smells as pure as it looks. They all rely on the
early-morning visits of Cuomo, a traveling mozzarella maker. His
family has practiced this craft for three generations in southern
Italy, and Cuomo, 52, continued the tradition after he moved here
20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mozzarella, it needs to be fresh,'' he said, defining fresh as
a maximum of two days old. Yes, he could make mozzarella in large
batches at his home in New Jersey and truck it into the city, but
that would be a loss for both the diner and the cheese, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On and off trucks, lost time, changes in temperature.'' He
rolled his eyes as he considered the potential for culinary
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   He continued to work the whey. ``The trick is to keep it pliable
and smooth,'' he said. ``If it's in water too long, the cheese
loses too much of its butterfat and gets rubbery.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment of readiness _ a precise moment perceptible to
Cuomo _ he pulled it from the water and, with the help of a kitchen
assistant, stretched it into a long braid, squeezing out the water.
Pulling off handfuls (the word mozzarella is from mozzare, meaning
``to tear''), he fitted some into molds that looked like shallow
bread pans, and shaped others into balls, knots and braids _ and
several beguiling little birds. In all, he makes about 300 pounds
of mozzarella a week for each of six restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two decades, mozzarella has become one of America's
favorite cheeses, second only to cheddar. But most mozzarella made
in this country is processed in blocks that are sealed in plastic
and sold in supermarkets. For connoisseurs, there are alternatives
provided by artisans, many of them Italian, who like Cuomo supply
restaurants, Italian delis and specialty food shops like Fairway,
Todaro Brothers and Balducci's in New York.
</P>
<P>
   They usually make fior di latte, cow's milk mozzarella, though
their colleagues in southern Italy also make fior di bufala, from
the milk of water buffaloes. The more delicate fior di bufala is
about twice the price, and many swear it is the finer of the two.
Cuomo prefers cow's milk mozzarella, though his family is from a
small town near Salerno, in the heart of buffalo mozzarella
country.
</P>
<P>
   Besides salads and pizza, fresh mozzarella cut in small pieces
can be added to pastas _ tossed in at the very end so it just
starts to melt but does not become stringy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking fresh mozzarella would be a travesty,'' said John
Taylor Martin, a food writer who lived in Liguria for two years.
``My Italian friends ate mozzarella almost every day in the summer
but only two ways _ tossed with hot pasta at the last minute, or in
insalata caprese.''
</P>
<P>
   Insalata Caprese, or salad of Capri, is the familiar combination
of tomato slices, mozzarella and fresh basil, lightly dressed with
olive oil, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   It is a fairly recent invention, created in the early 1950s at
the Trattoria da Vincenzo in Capri. It was made then, as it is now,
with fior di latte, ripe tomatoes and two local products: wild
arugula and a pinch of dried wild oregano. Vinegar, which would
overwhelm the flavor of delicate, fresh mozzarella, is never used.
</P>
<P>
   For those who happen to catch the ingredients together at their
peak of freshness, life is good. ``Yellow, rubbery processed
mozzarella and hothouse tomatoes are unacceptable,'' Faith
Willinger, a food writer who has lived in Italy for 23 years, wrote
in ``Red, White and Greens'' (HarperCollins, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   With some crusty bread, insalata Caprese can be an appetizer, a
singularly satisfying lunch or, on a sweltering summer night, an
instant, reviving supper.
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO AND MOZZARELLA SALAD FROM CAPRI
</P>
<P>
   From ``Red, White and Greens,'' by Faith Willinger
(HarperCollins, 1996)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   \ cup loosely packed fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   \ cup loosely packed arugula (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds ripe tomatoes, sliced 1/2-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 pound fresh mozzarella, sliced 1/4-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1 pinch first-rate dried oregano (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Tear the basil and optional arugula into bite-sized pieces.
Alternate slices of tomato, mozzarella and basil leaves on a
serving platter. Scatter arugula and oregano on top. Drizzle salad
with extra virgin olive oil. Season with salt and pepper and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 appetizer servings or 4 main course servings.
</P>
<P>
   For mozzarella and roasted red pepper salad: Substitute one 8
oz. jar marinated roasted peppers or two home-roasted red peppers
for the 2 pounds of tomatoes. Sprinkle with capers and olives, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   Mozzarella and sun-dried tomato salad: Substitute 2/3 cup
sun-dried tomatoes packed in olive oil for the two pounds of
tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Mozzarella and caponata: On individual plates, arrange slices of
mozzarella around a large spoonful of caponata.
</P>
<P>
   Antipasto: Fan out slices of mozzarella, prosciutto and salami
on a platter. Center with a mound of oil-cured olives.
</P>
<P>
   Mozzarella and prosciutto: Alternate thin slices of mozzarella
and slices of prosciutto on a platter; sprinkle with capers and
just a bit of olive oil. Or, for savory finger food, wrap small
pieces of prosciutto around small cubes or balls of mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER PASTA
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The New Southern Cook'' by John Taylor Martin
(Bantam Books, 1995)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound high-quality dried fettuccine or other pasta
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 cloves of peeled garlic
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe tomatoes, cored, peeled if desired and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup firmly packed basil leaves, slivered
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup grated fresh mozzarella.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large pot of boiling salted water, cook pasta until it
is al dente, 8 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. While pasta is cooking, combine olive oil and garlic cloves
in a small pan. Heat until oil is very hot and garlic has released
its aroma, without letting the garlic brown.
</P>
<P>
   3. As soon as pasta is cooked, drain it and transfer to a large,
shallow bowl. Immediately strain hot oil over it. Discard garlic
cloves and toss the pasta. Add diced tomatoes, basil and grated
mozzarella and toss again to combine well.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
