<HEADER>
A2863 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRULY-COLUMN-TEX     06-23 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRULY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN CASH, CURBING COUNSELS AND GOOD GOVERNMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAT TRULY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few parting thoughts while tip-toeing toward the exit:
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance _ Folks, the republic is in trouble because the
moneychangers have occupied the temple. Remember the bankruptcy
legislation that just passed in the House? Those in the consumer
credit business, especially companies promoting credit cards, gave
$6.7 million to politicians in the last year, knowing they would
seek legislative help.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco companies, knowing Congress would become involved in
anti-smoking legislation, gave $4 million to Republicans and $1
million to Democrats since January 1997 (that's just nationally;
they gave more at the state level). On the other side, health
groups divided $1.367 million between the two parties, and trial
lawyers gave $774,000. The parties' congressional committees have
raised $60-odd million for 1998 ($42 mil for the GOP alone). And
that is on top of the six- and seven-figure war chests of
individual incumbents. All of it derived from public-spirited and
disinterested sources, of course. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   You _ Mr. and Ms. American _ have a stake in every issue before
Congress. Were you able to give millions? Was your voice heard as
loudly? Is a Congress that receives this much money actually likely
to do anything about soft money political contributions? Can you
spell d-a-m-n-t-h-e-p-u-b-l-i-c?
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsels _ There will be rare instances when they
are needed, and at those times they will need a high degree of
independence, but the law has to be changed to limit the range of
accusations referred to an independent counsel. Does anyone
remember what rationalization was used to begin a counsel
investigation of Whitewater? A device originally seen as a way to
avoid political influence in important investigations has been
reduced to the status of a political tool employed unnecessarily
for partisan reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Language _ The bilingual education fracas somewhat obscures the
real point, which should be that however it is achieved, every
citizen of this country should be functional in English.
</P>
<P>
   A bilingual education proposal working its way through Congress
(it recommends immersion programs) was amended the other day. It
had said that it is ``imperative'' that every person in the United
States know English. Now it says every person ``should have a
command of English.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the other day I was at a fast-food joint when two city
employees came in. One guy ordered breakfast for himself and then
ordered for his companion, who spoke Spanish but not English. I've
seen that happen all too often. Perhaps the standard should be that
everyone in the United States should attain a sufficient
``command'' of English to be able to order his or her own breakfast
at Jack-in-the-Box. Is that too much to ask?
</P>
<P>
   Guv'mint _ As much as we might wish otherwise, we have to have
it. The idea should not be to starve it to death but to make it
work efficiently and frugally. Nor should it be confused with
business, as in campaign flapdoodle such as, ``I promise to run
government like a business.'' Business and government have
different roles. The only real difference between Democrats and
Republicans is about the purpose of government beyond defending our
shores and building roads (both of which they pretty much agree
about). Democrats seem to think government is there to protect the
masses from everyone else. Republicans seem to think it is there to
protect everyone else from the masses.
</P>
<P>
   And finally _ As might be expected with a populace so
independent-minded, there always has been an American tendency to
pull apart (New England almost seceded from the union in 1814,
years before the Suthrun Confederacy). As a people, we seem to need
an external challenge to bring Americans together.
</P>
<P>
   We need an enemy _ a believable threat from outside _ to give us
common purpose. We had it in World War II. Then the Soviet Union
provided this for 40-something years. No current bad guys really
fill the bill.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, as we tend to do after dealing with an emergency,
we look for enemies at home. Looking, we discover them all around
us. Some of them (modernism, for instance; immigrants, for
instance) always were there but were overshadowed by Russian
rockets aimed at Fargo, N.D., and San Angelo, Texas. Others we have
had to invent to replace political labels like ``soft on
communism.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why we are where we are at the end of the 20th
century: We're so strong, economically and otherwise, that we have
no immediate, credible external threat to our existence. So we must
invent our own.
</P>
<P>
   My advice: Stay the course. Keep this nation's fundamental,
long-term human mission in mind. And this, too, shall pass. Of
course, it would pass faster if Uruguay or Liechtenstein would just
threaten us with destruction.
</P>
<P>
   (Pat Truly is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram who plans to retire this month. You can call
him at (817) 390-7751. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
