<HEADER>
A2866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RICE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-23 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RICE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY THE BOOK: `EVERY GRAIN OF RICE'  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUZANNE HAMLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the photograph on the jacket of ``Every Grain of Rice''
(Clarkson Potter, $25), Annabel Low and Ellen Blonder resemble the
striking daughters in ``Eat, Drink, Man, Woman,'' Ang Lee's film
about the supreme relevance of food in Chinese life. Their new
book, a family memoir and cookbook, makes the comparison even
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   The authors were raised as sisters, although they are aunt (Ms.
Low) and niece (Ms. Blonder), born 16 days apart. The children of
Chinese parents, they grew up in California, where they still live,
as close now as when an extended immigrant family shepherded them
into a new, American life.
</P>
<P>
   But the girls were never allowed to forget their Chineseness.
Legends, superstitions and wisdom were fed to them in generous
amounts. What must have been tremendous hardship is glossed over in
the book; what remains are memories of a happy family life, filled
with nourishment.
</P>
<P>
   The women, now 48, have families and careers: Ms. Low is the
benefits manager of a major corporation, Ms. Blonder a designer and
illustrator, whose enchanting watercolors are among the book's
pleasures. But something got lost along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the time we spent helping in the kitchen while we were
growing up, we missed that next step of mastering the recipes on
our own,'' Ms. Blonder writes. ``We can teach our daughters how to
deal with corporations, but we couldn't pass down the simplest
technique for dealing with a taro root.''
</P>
<P>
   So the women consulted their relatives, cooked with them and
gathered 120 recipes, for both everyday and festive dishes. Rice,
of course, is given its full due. As children, the authors were
told to eat every grain of rice and that any grain left over would
reappear as a freckle on the faces of their future husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The family celebrated Chinese and American holidays with
pan-fried prawns in ketchup sauce, turkey jook, steamed eggs with
clams, sesame spinach, long-life noodle soup and fried rice
country-style, made with pungent shrimp sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Are all Chinese families so adept in the kitchen? I suspect not.
The recipes have too many subtle tricks that make a world of
difference. And they are meticulously written, perhaps because the
authors had to learn the dishes from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Following their directions for simple steamed fish, for example,
was a humbling lesson. Caught up in the grilling decade, I had
almost forgotten how delicate and sweet, how perfect, a freshly
caught steamed fish can be. And stir-fried flank steak with green
tomatoes is as clever and good as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   These dishes are a joy to cook, not only for their ultimate
goodness but also because the authors and their families are so
much a part of each dish. I plan to join them, via their recipes,
for at least part of the Fourth of July weekend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIMPLE STEAMED FISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; From ``Every Grain of Rice'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 30 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1{ or 2 pounds whole, scaled fish like red snapper, rock cod,
large flounder or black bass; or a thick chunk of striped or black
bass
</P>
<P>
   1 1{-inch piece of ginger, peeled and cut in fine slivers
</P>
<P>
   1 scallion, trimmed and sliced in thin strands lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2 cilantro sprigs, leaves only (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   4{ teaspoons soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   1. Rinse the fish. Pat dry, then place in a heat-proof dish.
</P>
<P>
   2. Set a rack in a pot and add water to a depth of 1{ to 2
inches. (If you use a steamer, fill half the lower tier with
water.) Bring to a boil. Set dish on rack (or on upper tier of
steamer) and steam over high heat for 15 to 20 minutes, depending
on the thickness of the fish.
</P>
<P>
   3. Test for doneness by poking a chopstick or sharp knife
through the thickest part of the fish. It should flake easily and
look opaque all the way to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   4. When fish is done, use a turkey baster or spoon to discard
any accumulated liquid.
</P>
<P>
   5. Sprinkle ginger, scallion and optional cilantro over fish.
Heat oil in a small skillet. Add soy sauce and heat for a few
seconds. Pour mixture over fish. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
