<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2871 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-SURO-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      06-23 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SURO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRANGERS' ASSESSES IMPACT OF LATINO IMMIGRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GRACIELA SEVILLA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ In churches, on playgrounds and in supermarkets
across the country, the growing presence of immigrant and
American-born Latinos is altering our society.
</P>
<P>
   Booming end-of-the-century immigration has fueled the Latino
population rise and ignited a national debate stoked by cliches and
misguided fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strangers Among Us: How Latino Immigration is Transforming
America,'' a new book by Washington Post immigration reporter
Roberto Suro, reaches beyond the overheated rhetoric to examine and
explain this controversial phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Supported by excellent reporting, shrewd analysis and compelling
human stories, Suro unravels the why's and how's of Latino
migration to the United States. He sorts out the history of this
shift and the changes and challenges it brings to our country.
</P>
<P>
   In his reporting, Suro interviewed countless immigrants,
policymakers, academics and opinion leaders around the United
States to present a thorough and balanced examination of
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   As the American-born son of a Puerto Rican father and an
Ecuadorean mother, Suro treats the subjects of his stories
humanely.
</P>
<P>
   But his background doesn't stop him from presenting the harsh
realities and warning of potentially dire consequences facing U.S.
society if serious steps aren't taken to manage immigration and
integrate those already here so they do not become a permanent
underclass of working poor.
</P>
<P>
   Suro notes that Latino immigration to the United States exploded
in the 1980s fueled by civil wars in Central America, an economic
crisis in Mexico and a growing American demand for cheap labor.
</P>
<P>
   He persuasively argues that illegal immigration spiraled
relatively uncontrolled over the last 30 years because U.S.
officials consistently adopted convoluted, weak compromises rather
than risk the fallout of establishing effective controls.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration control laws, he writes, have failed. ``No effective
or lasting agreements have been reached when it comes to spending
government money, risking economic disorder or taking political
heat in order to control the flow.''
</P>
<P>
   But Suro's book isn't filled with dry analysis. Powerfully
detailed portraits emerge of the many enclaves and distinct peoples
making up this new America.
</P>
<P>
   From Cuban Miami, ``the only barrio with a country club,'' to
the middle-class Mexican suburbs of Los Angeles, to the decaying
New York ghettos of Puerto Ricans and Dominicans, to the tightly
woven network of Guatemalans in Houston, he presents a fascinating
tapestry of divergent and separate Latino-American worlds.
</P>
<P>
   Suro makes the point that the experience of Latino America is
far from the ``melting pot'' that absorbed Europeans and the Irish
into the American mainstream after the waves of immigrants landed
on Ellis Island.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos are not a single, cohesive people that can be classified
easily by race, he emphasizes.
</P>
<P>
   Latinos include native-born citizens and immigrants from more
than a dozen nations. Even among compatriots, they differ from one
another by skin color, economic class, immigration status and their
ability or inability to speak English. These factors and more
create a pecking order among Latinos that separates one group from
another.
</P>
<P>
   Suro's tours of the various barrios illustrate this
fragmentation and help to explain why some immigrants succeed
against the odds and others remain in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Among the challenges that cannot go unmet without severe social
repercussions is the growing competition and tension between
African-Americans and Latinos, Suro writes. The two groups are now
vying for ``jobs, neighborhoods and political clout'' in many
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a struggle between those already left behind by society
and newcomers who arrive with many disadvantages,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Suro is also concerned about the decay of the barrios and the
future of the enormous population of first-generation
Latino-Americans born of immigrant parents.
</P>
<P>
   He writes: ``Poor and low-skilled immigrants come to the United
States expecting to live at the bottom of the economic ladder, but
their children need patience, tolerance and investments to ensure
they have access to economic mobility.''
</P>
<P>
   For the barrios on the fringe, Suro advocates ``more bank
lending, small-business programs, public transportation and, of
course, better schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He decries the current anti-immigrant backlash that portrays
immigrants as a drain on taxpayers who must be stopped from
accessing public resources as the real threat to the country's
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exclusion will create a new kind of underclass of people who
live and work here and pay taxes but who are cut off from the
institutions and programs designed to give poor people a minimal
sense of security and to guarantee that there is a limit to misery
in America,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   But while Suro believes access and opportunities should be made
available to those already here, he takes a hard line on illegal
immigration.
</P>
<P>
   He favors imposing strict controls on the borders, penalties
that bar arrested undocumented crossers from future entry and
subjecting sending countries to a certification test that renews
economic aid based on cooperation to stop illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Suro concludes that the future of American society
will be determined in good part by how it copes with Latino
immigration. The outcome is yet to be defined, but Suro is
confident of this: ``At this point, we can be certain that more
Latinos will head north, that the United States will change them,
and that they will change the United States.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
