<HEADER>
A2874 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      06-23 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SUNSET LIMITED &QL; 
 &UR; James Lee Burke (Doubleday, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   What can you say about Burke? That he sometimes overwrites but
does it with such flair that you not only forgive him, but enjoy
yourself in the process? That his descriptions are rich and his
characters authentic? That he's one of a handful of writers who
give the detective novel a good name? In his new book, Cajun
detective Dave Robicheaux _ Burke's alter ego _ investigates a
series of events that include a rape, an apparent suicide, several
murders and the ugly racial history of the deep South. Through all
of it, Burke weaves the mystery of the 1956 crucifixion of a labor
organizer named Jack Flynn, whose grown children have returned to
New Iberia, La., bringing their father's memory with them. The
twists are novel, the connections complex. It's all rooted in the
violent past, which is never really dead, Robicheaux knows, if you
choose to deny its existence. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GARY COOPER: AMERICAN HERO &QL; 
 &UR; Jeffrey Meyers (Morrow, $26)
</P>
<P>
   He was, in the beginning, just a handsome cowboy from Montana.
That changed when he got to Hollywood. Cooper was shy, but as his
friend Richard Widmark noted, he also was ``catnip to the ladies.''
Other people put it more crudely (we really, really wish we could
tell you Clara Bow's exact words on the subject), but the bottom
line is that he got around and had a good time. His long series of
mistresses included the ribald Bow, Marlene Dietrich (she baked
cakes for him), Carole Lombard, Tallulah Bankhead, Patricia Neal,
Grace Kelly (``Listen,'' Neal said of Kelly, ``she slept with them
all.'') and Ingrid Bergman. Between conquests, he made movies, got
married, had a much-loved daughter, converted to Catholicism and
became friends with the likes of Ernest Hemingway. Read about it in
this amiable, if not terribly deep, biography. Cooper became ``the
icon of our longing for lost purity and innocence,'' Meyers says.
``His visual and spiritual force defined the classic American
hero.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE PROUD HIGHWAY &QL; 
 &UR; Hunter S. Thompson (Ballantine, $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   New in paperback is this collection of letters written by
Thompson from 1955 to 1967. That's right. The book is nearly 700
pages long (and pricey), and he's not finished yet. Thompson wrote
great, entertaining letters, even when he was apologizing for his
notoriously skewed behavior or haggling with editors over money.
Here is a partial list of his correspondents: Joan Baez, Tom Wolfe,
Lyndon Johnson (whom he scolded for the Vietnam War), Allen
Ginsberg, Norman Mailer, Charles Kuralt, Herb Caen and Ken Kesey.
The secret of this book, however, is not just that he wrote letters
but that he was deeply aware of their pending importance. He knew
that someday you might want to read the odd jottings of his early
life, so he made carbon copies of each letter, 20,000 in all (for
every one included here, editor Douglas Brinkley says, 15 were
cut). They are an offbeat record of a decade of American life by
one of the most entertaining bad boys of them all. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; BITING THE DUST &QL; 
 &UR; Margaret Horsfield (St. Martin's, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   Are you among those people who throw body blocks at their front
doors rather than allow unexpected visitors to see into the debacle
beyond? Well, come sit here by Horsfield, because she'd like to
hear what you have to say. Her subject is housecleaning _ why we do
it, how we do it and how we feel about it. This is a book about our
attitudes toward dirt. Included are chapters on how our mothers
influence the way we clean (or don't), the history of cleaning
(squalor goes back a long way), germs, appliances and the high
standards they forced on us, domestic consumerism and the effects
of advertising on it, bugs and other vermin (and the cleaning
frenzy they set us to), ``clean freaks'' and professional cleaners.
And, oh yes, men _ there's a short chapter on them near the end, in
which Horsfield concedes that there might be a ``Mr. Clean''
somewhere in the world, but she hasn't met him yet. If you finish
her book and want more, there's ``Other People's Dirt'' by Louise
Rafkin (Algonquin, $17.95), about Rafkin's adventures in the
housecleaning trade. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; READING PEOPLE &QL; 
 &UR; Jo-Ellan Dimitrius (Random House, $23.95)
</P>
<P>
   She helped pick the jury that acquitted the police officers
accused of beating Rodney King. She helped pick the jury that
acquitted O.J. Simpson. With all due respect to her track record,
we were not far into this book before we could not bear to read
another sentence of it. Dimitrius has written nearly 300 pages of
tips on how to ``read people,'' how to take in ``the hundreds of
bits of information available to you,'' process them and (begin
itals) enlarge (end itals) (italics hers) those few traits that are
most important, separating good information from silly details. We
have seen her on television talk shows and found her charming and
interesting. Some things, it seems, are just better in sound
bites. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CIPRIANI-NYT &LR;      06-23 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CIPRIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENETIAN RESTAURATEURS TO RAISE PROFILE AT LANDMARK RAINBOW ROOM
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was about 4 p.m. Giuseppe Cipriani had been on the
go since midmorning and had not eaten any lunch. When he spied a
plate of bread and salami in a kitchen at 55 Wall St., a landmark
building his company is converting into a hotel, he asked for it to
be sent to his office. He munched eagerly, gulping cups of dense
espresso, and asked for another serving.
</P>
<P>
   Late evenings often find him sharing a table with friends at
Downtown, the restaurant he opened two years ago in SoHo, but there
he typically jumps up from his plate of risotto every few minutes
to greet someone with kisses on both cheeks or to consult with the
staff. No wonder he's as slim as a breadstick.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cipriani, 34, heads an international company with 1,200
employees, his business style _ zipping between midtown and Wall
Street in a private car _ is as whirlwind and off-the-cuff as the
scavenged lunch or casual supper.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the name Harry Cipriani usually means the boutique
restaurant in the Sherry-Netherland that his father, Arrigo, opened
in 1985 and where they serve the Bellini, the white peach juice and
sparkling wine cocktail invented at Harry's Bar in Venice (started
by Cipriani's grandfather in 1931).
</P>
<P>
   But that profile is about to get a lot higher.
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani International has just succeeded in beating out some
extremely heavy-duty competition for a $4 million-a-year lease on
the Rainbow Room, to start in January.
</P>
<P>
   The soaring, domed Great Hall at 55 Wall St., one of the
grandest banquet settings in the city, has been booked since
February. A Harry Cipriani restaurant is to open there in August,
with outdoor terrace seating overlooking Wall Street. The 140-room
Cipriani Wall Street Hotel is to follow on the upper floors in
early 1999. Cipriani has also signed leases in the restored Grand
Central Terminal for two restaurants, one to be called Midtown, and
a private dining room. The are also restaurants in Buenos Aires and
Venice, and a line of food products, soon to include a
single-serving Bellini.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose you could call me the CEO of the company,'' he said
with a warm smile. ``When you go to big corporations and ask them
for money they want you to have a title,'' he added in his ever so
slightly hesitant English that has a soft, Venetian accent.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is the Cipriani stamp that New Yorkers are about to
see more of? Their restaurants are known for a certain clubby
quality _ for young, beautiful people in SoHo, for older, more
affluent beautiful people uptown. Regular customers bask in the
warmth of an attentive staff that some first-time visitors might
not find welcoming enough. The food, including the famous
carpaccio, tends to be refined and pricey, a style of Italian
cooking that Cipriani admits has ``always had the worst reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Ciprianis seem genetically programmed to
attract the right clients, who then become friends and business
associates. That, in a nutshell, is how Harry's Bar in Venice got
started and achieved its worldwide renown. And it's a technique
that continues to open doors and bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, when Cipriani learned that 55 Wall Street, the grand
limestone building that was built in 1842 as the Merchants Exchange
(and later expanded by McKim, Mead &AMP; White), was available, he
approached Sidney Kimmel, the chairman of the Jones Apparel Group
and a frequent customer at Harry Cipriani, to help him finance it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Seppi told me about the Wall Street property,'' Kimmel
said, ``I agreed to meet him at 9 the next morning, and by 3
o'clock we had a deal. I did no due diligence, but I loved the
idea.'' Kimmel is now a partner in Cipriani International.
</P>
<P>
   Cipriani said that when his 15-year Rainbow Room lease begins,
on Jan. 1, he planned to close the main room for one month, then
open it to the public only on Friday nights, for Sunday brunch and
one Saturday night a month with guest chefs. The rest of the time
it will be booked for private functions. (It's used that way much
of the time now.) At lunch time, it will remain a private club.
Giuseppe Marangi, who has been at Harry Cipriani, is to oversee the
food. The floor below will continue to be used for parties.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow and Stars cabaret will disappear. The room is to
become an elegant restaurant, which Cipriani would like to turn
over to another operator to manage and lure a chef of the stature
of Alain Ducasse and Nobu Matsuhisa. Other plans (perhaps a cabaret
or night club) are still being hatched for other parts of the
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Zagat, the publisher of the Zagat surveys, who calls the
Rainbow Room ``New York's crown jewel,'' was critical of the
Ciprianis taking over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it,'' he said. ``You need someone very theatrical,
and they basically just run restaurants.''
</P>
<P>
   And in New York, loyalty to Joseph Baum, who revived the Rainbow
Room 10 years ago and whose lease is expiring, runs high.
</P>
<P>
   The Cipriani approach appealed to Jerry Speyer, the president of
Tishman-Speyer, co-owners and the operators of Rockefeller Center.
Speyer wants to make Rockefeller Center _ and the Rainbow Room _
places that will attract New Yorkers, not just tourists. ``A small
restaurant for dining and a large space for catering is what New
Yorkers want today,'' Speyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it's a little tired,'' Cipriani said of the Rainbow
Room. ``The service is a disaster. But it's an American institution
that has to be treated with respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``These places, 55 Wall Street, the Rainbow Room and Grand
Central station, are historically beautiful properties,'' he
continued. ``Maybe I'm attracted to them because I grew up in
Venice, where everything is historic and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   And being a Venetian, he keeps a boat moored at 23rd Street in
the East River. He tries to find time to use it on weekends,
especially when his two children, 8, and 10, are visiting from
Milan (where they live with his former wife).
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is not used to its water,'' he said. ``I would love
to see Canal Street a canal again so you could get across town in a
boat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
