<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2886 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARLIC-BROTH-NYT &LR;      06-23 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARLIC-BROTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARLIC IN ANOTHER GUISE: AS A BASE FOR SOUPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA KAFKA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Garlic bulbs are at their juiciest, least sharp and least bitter
at this time of year. When long-cooked, garlic is mild and sweet,
not aggressive; even those who are put off by raw garlic's strong
taste will find this broth deliciously smooth.
</P>
<P>
   It is versatile, too, because it can be eaten on its own with
the addition of just a few ad-hoc ingredients. Consider some
jalapeno pepper, cilantro and lime juice; diced tomato, chopped
parsley, matchsticks of zucchini and thinly sliced basil; cooked
peas and small leaves of spinach; lemon grass, curry leaves and
lime juice, or anything else that appeals to you. Traditional
additions, in quantities determined by the cook's imagination, are
poached eggs with croutons, or egg drops (for stracciatella) and
thin slivers of Serrano ham, or tomatoes and stale bread, or
broccoli rape.
</P>
<P>
   As for soups that one can create using the broth as a base, here
are three that will please vegetarians and meat-eaters alike:
</P>
<P>
   The first takes advantage of vegetables in season now: peas and
asparagus (or fiddlehead ferns). They shine in all their freshness
with little competition from the other ingredients. This soup is
pretty, with its dots of white and green. And what is amazing is
that the garlic does not overpower these seemingly delicate
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   I always make at least double the amount called for in the
curry-tomato soup recipe. It can be served hot before a big-salad
lunch, or cold before a summer dinner of grilled fish or roast
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients in the mixed vegetable potage can vary as summer
progresses, and leftovers are just fine. I usually scan the
refrigerator to see what I have on hand before I go shopping. It is
amazing what can happen to a slightly wilted bunch of watercress or
some cooked carrots from last night's dinner.
</P>
<P>
   This is the comforting soup that Europeans _ particularly the
French _ have lived on from about the 15th century to our own
times. I like to make it in large quantities because it freezes and
reheats well. For added richness, stir in some butter just before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   GARLIC BROTH
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 small heads garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste, optional
if the broth is served as a soup on its own.
</P>
<P>
   1. Smash the garlic heads, separating the cloves. Smash and peel
the cloves, and cut in half lengthwise. If necessary, remove the
green germ that grows through the center.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium saucepan, warm the oil over low heat. Stir in the
garlic, and cook, stirring often, for about 20 minutes or until the
outside is translucent and the garlic is soft. Do not let the
garlic brown.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add 9 cups of water, and bring to a boil. Lower the heat, and
simmer, uncovered, for 40 minutes. The garlic will be very tender.
If using the broth on its own, season to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 cups.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT SOUP WITH PEAS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   5 cups garlic broth (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup long-grain white rice
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds peas in the pod, shelled (2 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Tip from 1-pound bunch of medium asparagus, reserving the stems
for another use (or 1/4 pound fiddlehead ferns, well washed).
</P>
<P>
   1. In a small saucepan, bring 1 cup of the broth to a boil with
the rice. Cover, lower the heat, and simmer for 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a medium saucepan, add half of the peas to the remaining
broth, and bring to a boil. Lower the heat, and simmer for 5
minutes. Strain, reserving the liquid.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a blender, puree peas with a little reserved liquid. Whisk
together remaining liquid and the puree. Season with salt and
pepper. The soup can be made ahead up to this point and
refrigerated for up to 2 days.
</P>
<P>
   4. Return the soup to the stove, and bring to a boil. Stir in
the remaining peas (and the fiddleheads, if using). Return to a
boil, lower the heat, and simmer for 3 minutes. Add the rice, and
simmer for 2 minutes longer. If using the asparagus instead of the
ferns, add them and the rice after the peas have simmered for 3
minutes. Simmer for 2 minutes longer. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CURRY-TOMATO SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sweet paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups canned Italian plum tomatoes, pureed with their juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups garlic broth (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons plain yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a medium saucepan, melt the butter over low heat. Stir in
the onion, and cook until the onion is limp and completely
translucent, about 10 minutes. Stir in the curry powder and the
paprika, and cook, stirring constantly, for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Stir in the tomato sauce and broth. Bring to a boil. Lower
the heat, and simmer for 5 minutes. Stir in the salt. The soup can
be made ahead up to this point. Refrigerate for 2 hours or
overnight if serving cold, or reheat.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir in lemon juice and pepper. Top each serving with 2
tablespoons of the yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   MIXED VEGETABLE POTAGE
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 pounds spinach, stemmed and washed well
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds mashing potatoes, peeled, halved lengthwise and cut
crosswise into 1/4-inch-thick slices
</P>
<P>
   12 medium carrots, peeled and cut crosswise into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, cut into chunks
</P>
<P>
   10 cups garlic broth (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, smashed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   9 teaspoons butter (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1. In a tall stockpot, bring all the ingredients, except the
salt, pepper and butter, to a boil. Lower the heat, and simmer for
30 minutes, or until each of the vegetables is easily pierced with
the tip of a knife.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pass the soup through the medium disk of a food mill, or skim
the vegetables out of the liquid, and pulse them to a coarse puree
in a food processor. If using a food processor, recombine the
vegetables and the liquid. Season with salt and pepper. The soup
may be refrigerated for up to 3 days or frozen for up to 2 months.
</P>
<P>
   3. Bring to a simmer. If desired, stir a heaping 1/2 teaspoon of
the butter into every portion just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 4 quarts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
