<HEADER>
A2889 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-TEEN-TIME-0623-COX     06-23 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-TEEN-TIME-0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEGISLATION AIMS TO PUT HIGH SCHOOLS ON TEEN TIME
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a move sure to wake up the youth vote, a
California congresswoman plans to introduce legislation Wednesday
encouraging high schools to start later in the morning so teenagers
can sleep in longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for high schools to sychronize their clocks with
their students' body clocks so that teens are in school during
their most alert hours and can achieve their full academic
potential,'' said Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren, a mother and education advocate, will unveil her ``Zs
to As'' bill at a Capitol Hill press conference where she will be
joined by several sleep researchers who support putting high
schools on teen time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Puberty changes the body's sleep cycle in such a way that
teenagers stay alert later at night and are sleepier in the
morning,'' said William Dement, a Stanford University professor and
chairman of the National Sleep Foundation's Government Affairs
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shift in their biological clocks makes it difficult for
them to fall asleep early enough at night to get all the sleep they
need for an early class,'' Dement said in a prepared statement.
``As a consequence, many adolescents are severely sleep-deprived,
which often leads to serious academic, behavioral and psychological
problems as well as a greatly increased risk for accidents and
injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Research also shows a direct correlation between a good night's
sleep (about eight and a half hours for teens) and good grades.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, local school districts _ not Congress _ set school
hours. However, Lofgren's legislation would encourage high schools
to start later by providing a federal grant of up to $25,000 to
cover administrative and operating costs resulting from the change.
</P>
<P>
   The National Sleep Foundation, an independent, nonprofit
organization that promotes public understanding of sleep and sleep
disorders, recommends that high schools start classes at 9 a.m. or
later.
</P>
<P>
   Lofgren said that additional social problems would be addressed
by changing a typical 7:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. schoolday to 9 a.m. to
4 p.m. That would reduce the hours that children are without
parental supervision after school. FBI statistics show that about
half of all violent juvenile crime occurs between 2 p.m. and 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Many school administrators have argued that the later hours
reduce the time for after-school activities such as sports, band
and academic clubs.
</P>
<P>
   However, researchers say theres a biological basis for all those
teenagers stubbornly clinging to their pillows while exasperated
parents pull them from bed to get to school by 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids are waking up and going to school at a time when their
brains are still in the nighttime mode,'' said Mary Carskandon, a
sleep researcher at the Brown University School of Medicine. ``Even
in second period, they are not ready to learn, not ready to be
engaged in education.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1740EDT &QL; 
