<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-N     06-23 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDAY-EARLY-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, June 28,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (`e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIX-OPERA-FESTIVAL (Aix-En-Provence, France) _ Amid Europe's
ever more crowded calendar of summer musical happenings, the slow
demise of the opera festival in this bucolic southern French city
went largely unnoticed. In its heyday, in the 1950s and 60s, when
it reintroduced Mozart to France, le tout Paris would flock here
every July. But in recent years, even for dedicated opera lovers,
Aix was increasingly overshadowed by Salzburg, Bayreuth,
Glyndebourne and other festivals more offbeat, glitzy or
crowd-pleasing. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   KAUFFMANN-FILM-CRITIC (Undated) _ Sixteen years into his
marathon run as the film critic for The New Republic, Stanley
Kauffmann sat down in 1974 to write an essay to answer the two
questions he was most often asked: How many films do you see in a
week? And don't you get bored? Zero to 12 and no, Kauffmann
answered in that essay, ``Why I'm Not Bored.'' A film may be
boring, but the idea of going never is. Boredom is incompatible
with hope, Kauffmann wrote, and hope is more of a constant in film
than in virtually any other art in America. By Janny Scott.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   X-FILES-FILM (Undated) _ The ``X-Files'' film has brought us two
things that the television show had not: the Barbie-as-Scully and
Ken-as-Mulder collectible dolls, each with its own little FBI
badge. Merchandising has nothing to do with the film's many
convoluted plots, but money has everything to do with what happened
to ``The X-Files'' in its leap from television to the movies. By
Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   GONE-WITH-THE-WIND (Undated) _ ``Gone With the Wind'' is still
generally accepted as the most widely seen motion picture ever to
come out of Hollywood. When its estimated income is adjusted to
reflect the increase in ticket prices over 59 years, it is still
one of the biggest-grossing movies in history, topped only by a
handful of others, including the newest champion of champions,
``Titanic.'' By Vincent Canby.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL-SWEDISH-BALLET (Undated) _ The Royal Swedish Ballet,
celebrating its founding in 1773, held a highly successful 225th
anniversary festival this month. This showcase of performances in
Stockholm, was enhanced by an international lecture series. By Anna
Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL (Undated) _ The Tanglewood Music Center in
Lenox, Mass., the most prestigious summer training institute for
young musicians in the United States, has just begun its 49th
season, and much attention will be focused on Seiji Ozawa, who, as
music director of the Boston Symphony Orchestra, oversees artistic
matters at the center. Over the last two summers, Ozawa fomented a
shakeup, which provoked angry, noisy resignations from respected
leaders of the center: the pianist and conductor Leon Fleisher, who
had been artistic director for 12 years, and the pianist Gilbert
Kalish, who had served on the faculty for nearly 30 years, the last
12 as chairman. By Anthony Tommasini.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-CONCERT-MUSIC (Undated) _ A venerable article of faith
holds that American concert music ``came of age'' after World War
I. Previous American composers, we are told, were second-rate
clones of German teachers. Virgil Thomson called the music of
George Chadwick, Edward MacDowell, John Knowles Paine, Amy Beach
and other prominent turn-of-the-century Americans ``a pale copy''
of ``Continental models'' and reckoned their scale of achievement
``a sort of adolescence.'' By Joseph Horowitz.
</P>
<P>
   OPERAS-80s (Undated) _ The scarcity of good new operas in the
present decade _ unless something remarkable happens more than once
during the next year and a half _ makes all the more striking how
much was achieved in the 80s. By Paul Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BRANDY-MUSIC (Undated) _ The appeal of ``Never Say Never,'' the
second album by the teen-age rhythm-and-blues singer Brandy, lies
not in her inventing anything new but in her delivering familiar
pleasures with all the accessories. And she can really sing. For a
performer who just turned 19, Brandy seems to have a grown-up
control freak's attention to detail, and it has served her career
well. By Dimitri Ehrlich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM-CONGDON-ART (Milan, Italy) _ Taking the measure of
William Congdon, who died April 15 on his 86th birthday, proves
tricky. As a painter associated with the New York School, the
cluster of Abstract Expressionists who shook up the art world in
the late 1940s and 50s, Congdon distinguished himself with his
spirited cityscapes of New York and Venice, often rendered in thick
strokes of black and gold. By Christopher Reardon.
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE-ART-MUSEUMS (Undated) _ For some, the ``culture
wars'' between liberals and conservatives have been at best a
sideshow. The main event (it's been going on since the Renaissance)
has been the struggle between artists and politicians. Artists
understand that creativity invites destruction. Politicians prefer
to snack on sweetness and light. Victoria Newhouse's new book,
``Toward the New Museum'' (The Monacelli Press), offers a shrewd,
biting account of one of the most conspicuous fields in which this
struggle has been joined in recent decades: the architecture of art
museums. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-PHILADELPHIA (Undated) _ For the Liberty Bell, a move
with a view. By Michael Janofsky. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-TRAVELER (Undated) _ Walking tours run out fast. By
Betsy Wade. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Travel notes and news: Tours to
Indonesia postponed for many; Bag-tracking by phone or Web;
Ruminate on tomorrow at Disneyland; An alternative to leaping tall
buildings; Rail passes for Greece and Eastern Europe. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Barcelona Festival; Pearl Harbor tours;
Tuscany cooking schools. By Suzanne MacNeille. (Moved).
</P>
