<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, June 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mercury rose to 102 degrees in Tallahassee, Fla., on Monday,
bringing the number of days that the city has reached or exceed 100
degrees this month to nine. The extreme heat will continue
Wednesday across the Southeast and southern plains as burly high
pressure remains steadfast. Temperatures will climb to 100 degrees
in many areas from South Carolina to Texas. Spotty thunder will
bring relief to parts of the Florida peninsula and Gulf Coast as
inland-penetrating sea breezes lift the torrid air into towering
cumulus clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will also form from eastern Pennsylvania to
Virginia as a disturbance trudges through the region. With winds
aloft weak, slow-moving thunderstorms will produce localized
flooding. An onshore flow of cool, moist air will promote coastal
low clouds from Maine to Virginia while morning clouds will yield
to afternoon showers in interior New England. Western New York will
turn sunny and less humid.
</P>
<P>
   Strong thunderstorms will develop from North Dakota to Michigan
as a flow of warm, muggy air aloft overruns cooler air at the
surface. Changing wind directions with height will impart rotation
to some of the storms, increasing the risk for hail and isolated
tornadoes. Spotty thunder will also erupt in the late afternoon
heat from Iowa to western Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a cold front will invade the Pacific Northwest and
northern Rockies, accompanied by showers and chilly air. The
Southwest will be sunny and seasonably warm, though coastal clouds
will plague California.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Double Record
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Melbourne, Fla., registered a record morning low of
68 degrees, which was followed by a record afternoon high of 97.
Both records are attributed to a strong high pressure zone over
Florida. High pressure systems produce currents of sinking air,
which dry upon descent through the atmosphere. The resulting ample
sunshine causes the heating of the ground by the sun, and the
consequent heating of the air by the ground, to be maximized. At
night, the absence of clouds and significant water vapor allows for
the day's warmth to escape readily into space.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
