<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING OLDER WITH CONRAD IS A WONDERFUL THING TO DO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the initiation eight years ago of these weekly literary
sermons, my reading has been given more to old stuff than to new.
It seems harder nowadays to manage time for reading; but when I do
manage, my greater inclination is to seek out a classic title. It
may be a work I failed to read despite earnest intention, or it may
be a book I read when I was much younger, and now find to be a
quite different book because I am a quite different person.
</P>
<P>
   I know I once inhaled youthful pride in being a precocious
reader, but reading prematurely is not always a good thing. In my
teen years, not yet savvy for reading between the lines, I
certainly wasn't ready for Joseph Conrad. I tried, though. I went
the full distance with ``Lord Jim'' and ``Victory'' and started but
couldn't get into ``The Nigger of the Narcissus.''
</P>
<P>
   An English major in college could not avoid Conrad, but I faked
the issue, reading mostly ``about'' his novels and passing on other
people's critical opinions as my own. I left Conrad alone until the
1979 movie ``Apocalypse Now'' prodded my belated reading of ``Heart
of Darkness,'' the great novella it paraphrases. That led in turn
to an investigation of Conrad's short stories, most of them
masterful _ ``The Secret Sharer'' perhaps above all.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after commencing this series, I felt obligated to write
about Conrad. I hoped to articulate my mixed feelings about his
work. For preparation, I reread ``Victory'' with heightened
understanding and appreciation; read again and this time finished
``The Nigger of the Narcissus''; read ``Nostromo'' for the first
time; and although I now warmed to Conrad, I resisted for a while
another look into ``Lord Jim.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1960s Richard Brooks' film of ``Lord Jim'' with Peter
O'Toole and James Mason was a consensus flop and, I thought, a
failure on all counts. The movie persuaded me (wrongly) that ``Lord
Jim'' is Conrad's most famous work for being the most
philosophically pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   However, prose style is unphotogenic, rendering it almost
impossible to capture the essence of Joseph Conrad on film. He has
to be read, and finally I was cajoled by a Conrad admirer into
giving ``Lord Jim'' another chance. Reread I did; and now I'm in
camp with those who rate it a great novel.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it great? Let me count the ways. It involves the reader
into the heart and mind and soul of the tormented protagonist. The
narrative detailing a young man's desperate quest for spiritual
peace has pulsating vitality. Jim's obsession is to atone for an
act of instinctive cowardice that will haunt the rest of his life;
and Conrad's stylistic grace is so appropriate for a tale that
suggests a biblical parable.
</P>
<P>
   A remarkable man was the Polish-born Teodor Josef Konrad
Korzenowski. He was a 21-year-old sailor on a British merchant ship
when he first made acquaintance with the English language he was
destined to glorify. In 1886, he became a naturalized British
subject as Joseph Conrad. With the publication of ``Almayer's
Folly'' in 1895, Conrad was a first novelist at age 38; and when he
died in 1924, he was the author of 18 books, had also co-written
two novels with Ford Madox Ford, and had secure reputation as one
of the world's great authors.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad has literary kinship with Herman Melville and Jack
London. Like them, he is often characterized as a man's writer.
Strong is his appeal for readers who crave adventure. Also like
Melville and London, Conrad is concerned with moral dilemmas. His
protagonists almost invariably are men being tested _ by God and
conscience _ in circumstances of great peril.
</P>
<P>
   And still I'm faking it, having not read nearly enough of Joseph
Conrad. In those sedentary years ahead, I hope to read ``Almayer's
Folly'' and its sequel, ``An Outcast of the Islands.'' And ``The
Secret Agent.'' And ``The Shadow Line.'' And ``The Rescue'' ...
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Call him at (817) 390-7731, or e-mail:
lswindell(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
