<HEADLINE>
WOMEN AT WORK: HERE'S A WAY TO TAKE THAT CLASS AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILIAN MINCER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps you've always wanted to learn more about investing or
launching a business. Maybe you've wanted to meet other women in
management but never thought you had time because of work, family
and other responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that class you've been postponing is only a phone call
away. In May, Elyse Killoran launched Women's University. Also
known as Women's U., it is thought to be the first virtual
educational community exclusively for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm creating a sandbox where other people come to
play,'' said Killoran, a Long Island mother and former teacher.
`It's one way to move beyond where we are and do it in a supportive
community.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of colleges are offering on-line classes.
Women's U. is different in that its courses are not for credit or
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, someone signs up for a course, most of which are one to
four sessions and cost under $45. Participants join the class by
dialing a phone number at a designated time to connect with the
teleclass leader and classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way for women to bring other women into their
homes,'' Killoran said. ``Not only is it extremely convenient,
there's a real ability to talk because you are not distracted.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Reynolds, an instructor from Phoenix who does corporate
training, said people often sign up for courses at work but don't
attend because they can't take time from their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Women's U. they can do it...on their own phone, even if
they travel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She was initially concerned about the Women's U. format but
found that people were more willing to open up and take risks
because they were talking with people they didn't know well.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hope the courses will not only be informative but
will give women the opportunity in our fast-paced, technologically
driven world to connect with other women. In a sense, they want it
to become the coffee klatsch of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to tap into women's desire to connect, but
it will keep it convenient by tapping into the telephone,'' said
Carol Gerrish, one of the instructors, who has her own consulting
business. ``It is lonely and exhausting to be one of the few women
in the corporate boardroom, and it is lonely and exhausting to be
one of many women in front of the computer terminals. Working women
are looking for balance. They are looking for reward that goes
beyond the monetary.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information about Women's U., call (516) 851-1192 or
take a look at {www.womensu.com}.
</P>
<P>
   /{Women at Work is published on Mondays. Write to Jilian Mincer
at the business desk,/} The Kansas City Star, /{1729 Grand Blvd.,
Kansas City, MO 64108. Send e-mail messages to/}
{jmincer &LR; kcstar.com}.
</P>
</TEXT>
