<SLUG> BC-NY-WINE-OPERA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMBINING PASSIONS, SOMMELIER USES WINE LABELS TO DEPICT OPERA
SCENES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wine has always been the first love of Valentino Monticello, a
sommelier at Harry's Bar in London for 18 years. But art and music
follow soon after, and Monticello has found a way to combine these
passions. Using wine labels, he makes collages that depict opera
scenes involving wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``In opera,'' he said, ``you have many, many songs about people
drinking wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Choosing labels from the region or country in which the scene
takes place, he cuts the labels to form figures, props and scenery.
For instance, in a scene from La Boheme, a woman's skirt is made
from a 1970 Petrus label, the stage curtains from Veuve Clicquot.
</P>
<P>
   Each collage takes Monticello several months to complete and
incorporates as many as 800 labels. There is no drawing; every last
detail is cut from labels.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, I bought a lot of wine because of the
label,'' said Monticello, 65. ``But now, because many producers
know what I'm doing, they send me labels.''
</P>
<P>
   Monticello, who has no formal art education, plans to make
collages for many of the winemaking regions or countries in the
world. He has chosen 64, and said he is almost halfway through. He
expects to complete the project in two years.
</P>
<P>
   He does not sell or display his work, which has received some
notice in European magazines. He stores them all at his home in
London, saving them to be photographed and, he hopes, to be
published as a collection when he is finished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1804EDT &QL; 
