</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S OUR LEGAL RIGHT TO BE BOUGHT, SOLD 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The card came in the mail, giving a telephone number I should
call immediately for important information about my car. The make
and year of the vehicle were printed on the card.
</P>
<P>
   It had an official look, so I laid it aside _ but then promptly
forgot it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, the second card came.
</P>
<P>
   ``REMINDER,'' it said in large type. ``Please call at your
earliest convenience...Have this card and your manufacturer's
warranty booklet in hand when calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there was a problem. Perhaps the automaker had
discovered a defect that would cause the machine to self-destruct
at a speed over 45 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   I rang the number on the card, and a woman answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you today Mister Goose... Goose...?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Never mind,'' I told her. ``What are you selling?''
</P>
<P>
   When they start out by asking how you are, you know there's a
pitch coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to talk with you about our extended warranty plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have a warranty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh.'' She sounded crushed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where did you get my name?'' I asked her.
</P>
<P>
   ``From your state motor vehicle bureau. We bought it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's crazy,'' I said. ``I can't believe my own state is
selling me.''
</P>
<P>
   I hung up, then, and telephoned the license bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not true,'' said the woman there. ``Absolutely not!
Nobody can get your name without a special code. It would cost them
thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   So I called the first people back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The motor vehicle bureau says you're nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you talk to my supervisor.''
</P>
<P>
   The supervisor came on the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state says they didn't sell me,'' I told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, they did. All but eight or 10 states do it. We're
entitled to your name under the Freedom of Information Act.''
</P>
<P>
   I called the state capital for the motor vehicle bureau again,
and this time I got someone who actually knew something.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wrong about the Freedom of Information Act,'' she said.
``It's the state Sunshine Law. The records are public.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if some direct mail or phone marketing outfit
comes around wanting the dope on you, it's illegal for the state to
say no.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's more,'' said the lady, ``we can't keep them from
/{reselling/} you. And we know some of them do. The only way to
prevent it is when you buy or renew your plates.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I do that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It tells on the license form.''
</P>
<P>
   I dug my pink copy of the renewal application out of an
envelope. And sure enough, there were the instructions on the back
of the application. Not very prominently displayed, mind you, but
they were there.
</P>
<P>
   Release of your motor vehicle records for commercial use can be
restricted, the instructions said, by completing form DOR-4673.
</P>
<P>
   Provided you happened to notice that paragraph in small type.
</P>
<P>
   And just by chance have a DOR-4673 lying around handy.
</P>
<P>
   Or know offhand where to get one.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, you may as well be advised that the state
legislature, in its infinite wisdom, has written a law that allows
you, me _ everyone _ to be bought, sold or traded like pork bellies
or any other commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that government for you, working night and day on behalf
of us all?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
