<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUNK FOOD': SEAMY LOWLIFE IN ORDERLY TOKYO 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes at end of review)  
 (JT)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not just true of New York, Los Angeles or Miami. Every
naked city has a million squalid stories hatching under its smog.
``Junk Food,'' Masashi Yamamoto's collage of urban vignettes
unfolding simultaneously over a single day insists that even nice,
orderly Tokyo has a fetidly seamy lowlife.
</P>
<P>
   This icy little movie has the exploitative feel of a
can-you-top-this sampler of urban maladies, all viewed with an
unnerving detachment. Some of its scenes are little more than
snapshots of dramas whose backgrounds and details remain
unexplained. Others are fuller portraits of people in serious
trouble who lash out with a lethal fury that seems totally out of
proportion to what sets them off.
</P>
<P>
   The film's attitude of studied nonchalance is established in the
opening scene (shot in video), in which a blind elderly woman (the
director's mother, Shizuko Yamamoto) is awakened by a clock radio
and methodically begins her day with a Buddhist prayer, then slowly
ambles to a convenience store to shop for groceries. Little does
she know of the sordidness surrounding her.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the movie switches from video to film, and we've
entered the desperate world of Miyuki (Miyuki Ijima), a heroin
addict and possible prostitute waking up with a male companion (who
may or may not be a client) whom she cajoles into letting her tie
him up. Once he is tethered, she strangles him to death with a
cord, then flees the murder scene. Who he is and why she kills him
are questions that are never addressed.
</P>
<P>
   For much the rest of her part of the film, Miyuki, who turns out
to be married with a day job in an office, frantically scours the
city for drugs, getting into one humiliating scrape after another.
In the movie's ugliest scene, she is viciously beaten by a paranoid
drug dealer who then takes pity on her, injects her with heroin,
and makes love to her.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that distinguishes ``Junk Food'' from other
contemplations of urban sleaze is the absolute out-of-the-blue
savagery exhibited by its characters and the way sex often triggers
the violence. The most coldblooded among the movie's nasty people
is a shady Pakistani businessman named Cawl (Ali Ahmed), who slits
the throat of his Japanese girlfriend when she contemptuously
refuses to marry him, then meets with the Pakistani friend who
helped subsidize whatever business he's in and shoots him in an
argument over money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junk Food'' contrives some pungently seedy settings for its
characters to writhe around in. The rooms in which Miyuki arranges
her date's unexpected rendezvous with death suggests a dripping
subterranean plumbing facility with a bed plunked in the middle.
The movie tries so aggressively to evoke urban seediness that it
ends up feeling surreal. ``Junk Food'' is not a film to be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   JUNK FOOD
</P>
<P>
   Written (in Japanese, with English subtitles) and directed by
Masashi Yamamoto; director of photography, Hiroshi Ito; edited by
Syuichi Kakesu; music by DJ Krush and Ko Machida; produced by
Toshihiro Isomi; released by Junk Food Connection for Stance
Company. Running time: 84 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Act 1 and Act 4: Shizuko Yamamoto (Blind Woman). Act 2:
Miyuki Ijima (Miyuki), Akifumi Yamaguchi (Boss), Keigo Naruse
(Murdered Man) and Yoichi Okamura (Miyuki's Husband). Act 3:
Yoshiyuki (Hide), Onimaru (Ryo), Mia (Myan), Ali Ahmed (Cawl) and
Esther Moreno (Mariarna).
</P>
</TEXT>
