<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-SEABOARD, </SLUG>
 2ND TAKE-KAN  
 Seaboard aims at hogging pork market  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICH PALMER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seaboard opened its plant in December 1995. The plant reached
double-shift capacity in mid-1997, just in time to see its
increased capacity feed into a mountain of domestic meat hitting
the market. At the same time, Asian economies were spinning out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an 8 percent increase in slaughter last year,'' said
Steve Meyer, director of economics for the National Pork Producers
Council. ``That is a huge increase in pork production.''
</P>
<P>
   Pork producers such as Seaboard were encouraged to expand, Meyer
said, because wholesale prices were up in 1996 and 1997, grain
prices were down and retail pork prices were at record levels. Pork
sales of $13.2 billion last year at the farm level were a record.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expansion was coming from a lot of places, not just from
Seaboard,'' Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, with the plant hitting full capacity, Seaboard's
income from pork reached $54.3 million, up $51.2 million from 1996.
This year will be more challenging.
</P>
<P>
   According to Seaboard's financial report for the quarter that
ended March 31, its pork sales increased by $16.8 million in the
first quarter compared with the first quarter of 1997, reaching
$121.7 million. But increased sales did not translate into greater
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gross income'' for the pork operations was $1.5 million, a $9
million free fall from $10.5 million it reported in the same
quarter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman declined to comment beyond the company's financial
statement.
</P>
<P>
   McGlone, at Texas Tech, is impressed with how quickly Seaboard
has grown but is unimpressed with its skill of operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are known to have some production challenges, to be
kind,'' McGlone said. ``You probably have to chalk that up to
growing too fast. They have had more environmental challenges than
others in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaboard settled a complaint in Oklahoma in February by agreeing
to pay an $88,200 fine and improve its disposal of dead hogs. The
Oklahoma Department of Agriculture had proposed a $102,000 fine
after inspections at 44 Seaboard hog farms in November found dead
hogs on the ground or spilling out of trash bins.
</P>
<P>
   A release from the company and the state said, ``While Seaboard
Farms believes the fine is disproportionate with the alleged
violations and that there was no threat to the environment or
public health, it elected to resolve the matter so it could
continue building a positive working relationship with the
Department.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman is loath to talk about the fine. The state and the
company agreed the release would be all that would be said. He
explained that the company's written plan always had been to take
dead hogs to a rendering plant within 24 hours of dumping them.
Sometimes the rendering plant is down or a truck is out of
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals die,'' Hoffman said. ``We have 30,000 animals die a
month. A system of 24-hour delivery to a rendering plant is unheard
of in this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The publicity from the complaint provided political momentum for
those who wanted Oklahoma to tighten controls on corporate hog
farms. The state last month passed new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Seaboard's plan to expand in Kansas also resulted in the Kansas
Legislature writing into law regulations specifically governing hog
farms. The meat of the law contains environmental regulations, such
as required distances between pig farms, homes and wildlife
refuges.
</P>
<P>
   It also requires the state departments of Agriculture and Health
and Environment to create plans for things such as odor control,
dead animal disposal and waste disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman said Seaboard could live with the new regulations. While
there has been opposition to its plans for its new plant, there has
been support from people who realize the company is bringing new
vitality to the areas it invests in, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This growth has been unprecedented by our company, but we have
done well,'' Hoffman said. ``Our company recognized this was an
area attractive for animal processing. We have taken a bold step
away from what this market has done before. We think the future for
pork is great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
