<HEADER>
A2959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATGREEN-TEX     06-23 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATGREEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMER PAT GREEN HARKS BACK TO WAYLON, WILLIE AND THE BOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Pat Green isn't in any hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Not to become a big-deal country singer like his heroes Jerry
Jeff Walker, Willie Nelson and Merle Haggard.
</P>
<P>
   Not to move from Waco, where he grew up, to Austin or some other
Lone Star music hub.
</P>
<P>
   Not even to finish lunch at George's, Waco's long-standing
home-cooking mecca where, on a recent weekday, he sat in a booth
and talked leisurely about his career, which so far has included
two CDs and a growing rep as a young country singer to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like congestion,'' says Green, a 26-year-old San
Antonio native who has become a solid draw in clubs from Texas A&AMP;M
University to Texas Tech University to Texas Christian University.
``I'm small-town, no doubt about it. You can go to Austin and hit
traffic at 9 p.m. on a Sunday night. I don't need that.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's easygoing manner is borne out by his music, hard country
that bears much resemblance to the ``outlaw'' movement wherein
Nelson, Walker and Waylon Jennings found their greatest success.
Green sings about his craft, about his love of good friends and
small towns, in music that is heavy on fiddle, mandolin and pedal
steel guitars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like positive songs,'' he says. ``The song's the important
thing _ not who's good-lookin' or has a full-size cutout of them
with a Miller Lite in their hand in the record store. I'd like to
see a re-emergence of the Willie and Waylon days, when everything
coming off the radio didn't sound the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all of the Texas country heroes of the '70s, Green sounds
most like Walker _ which is understandable because it was Walker's
classic 1973 ``Viva Terlingua!'' album that made him want to play
guitar.
</P>
<P>
   Green first heard Walker in high school; he loved the earthy
quality of the music and the songs, and he was hooked. By the time
he left Waco to attend Texas Tech in the fall of 1990, he had a
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only goal I ever had that came to fruition was that I told
myself I would learn to play guitar when I went to college _ and I
did,'' he says. ``I annoyed the hell out of my roommates. I never
had one lesson. I bought a James
</P>
<P>
   Taylor songbook and learned _ his chords force your hands to do
things they're not used to doing, and I loved his finger-picking.''
</P>
<P>
   That led to Wednesday-night get-togethers, which led to playing
a campus club, Dash Riprock's, and writing songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had written one song, `Family Man,' and then it was a
flood,'' he says. ``I was writing every day. I had 21 years of
experience I wanted to capture.''
</P>
<P>
   By April 1994, Green had formed a band that played a lot of
Walker, Haggard and Robert Earl Keen _ and was hitting the clubs.
Hearing all the instruments, he says, made it easier to write
songs.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1995, he released his first CD, ``Dancehall Dreamer,''
and was becoming a serious draw. The same young country fans who
liked Keen, Jack Ingram and Charlie Robison liked him, and he found
himself opening for Nelson and Chris LeDoux, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``People indoctrinate their families to this music,'' he says.
``Their dad loved Willie 20 years ago and now they love him, too.
We all have our own styles _ our own experiences and way of telling
a story _ but I don't think Texas guys get as wrapped up in stardom
as Nashville people. We don't go hide on our bus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``George's Bar'' was recorded in April 1996, a month after Green
moved back home to Waco. These days, after years spent as a
bartender or waiter, he's performing full time; this August, he
will have his first headlining show at Billy Bob's Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, he'll release his third CD, a live recording
drawn from shows this spring in College Station and Gruene. The CD
features older songs and three new ones, including a cover of Joe
Ely's ``Me &AMP; Billy the Kid.''
</P>
<P>
   And from there, he says, there are plans for more shows, more
songs and plenty of time to relax and enjoy life. Green never
figured he would become a big deal _ which he may, and soon _
because he really doesn't see himself as a big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get past all the `Hey, this guy's a star' stuff, it
boils down to, `We're regular people,' '' he says. ``I go to the
Gap and buy my blue jeans and put 'em on one leg at a time like
anybody else. What I do isn't any more amazing than the guy that
works at the grocery store. We're just folks.''
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman writes on popular music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
