<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOD NOTES: MEDITERRANEAN ACCENT ON WALL STREET; BAGGING IT ON THE
TRAIL; WELL-TRAVELED WATER; WINE IN THE EMPIRE STATE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hungry hordes that spill onto Wall Street at
lunch time have a new option. Mangia's fourth cafe in Manhattan has
just opened at 40 Wall St. Hot sandwiches, like soft-shell crab,
and entree salads topped with beef or seafood have been added to
Mangia's bright Mediterranean-accented menu.
</P>
<P>
   In about a month, beyond the cafe area's booths and tables, the
rest of the space will open, with Mangia's popular antipasto buffet
expanded to include more than 75 items. There will also be hot food
and pizzas, all in a setting of inlaid marble floors, polished wood
and even a waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   Backpacker's Boon
</P>
<P>
   Planning a hiking or camping trip this summer? Reynolds Metals,
which makes Reynolds Wrap, has introduced Hot Bags, heavy-duty foil
cooking pouches that can be filled with food and go directly on a
grill. Though they are mainly for backyard grills and oven use,
they are convenient for backpackers. Fish, chicken, corn and spare
ribs can be cooked in them, but without much liquid, as they are
not leakproof. A package of three is around $3.25.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji Islands in a Bottle
</P>
<P>
   With all the bottled waters on supermarket and deli shelves, why
would anyone bother selling water transported all the way from the
Fiji Islands in the South Pacific?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is the taste. Fiji Natural Artesian Water, a newcomer
in a decorative square plastic bottle, is a soft, delicious,
smooth-tasting water that comes from a tropical aquifer fed by
rainfall on the main island of Viti Levu. It makes excellent coffee
and tea.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long voyage, a 1.5-liter bottle costs about the same
as other imported waters, less than $2 in supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   A Wineries Baedeker
</P>
<P>
   The new edition of ``Wine Country Passport,'' a booklet-size
guide to New York state wineries, has just been published, and it's
bigger than ever, with 125 wineries listed by region, along with
hours, events, maps, an explanation of types of grapes and tips on
wine storage and wine appreciation for beginners. It is $1 from
``Wine Country Passport,'' New York Wine Grape Foundation, 350 Elm
St., Penn Yan, N.Y. 14527.
</P>
<P>
   New on Columbus Avenue
</P>
<P>
   Avenue, 520 Columbus Ave., a restaurant that Scott Campbell
opened a week ago, offers more than just French-style country food
for breakfast, lunch and dinner. It has prepared foods to go,
including well-made baked goods like small quiches, rustic apple
tarts, buttery fruit tarts and pain au chocolat stuffed with
Valrhona chocolate. The breads and tender doughnuts have a homemade
quality.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
