<HEADER>
A2985 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      06-23 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA TRIES TO TAME AN ITALIAN GRAPE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL  
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   European winemakers like to say that grape vines must suffer to
make good wine. Which may explain why, in northern Italy, the best
sangiovese grapes are the result of a protracted struggle between
the vines and the hardscrabble Tuscan hills.
</P>
<P>
   Transplanted to the lushness of California, the same vines burst
forth like prisoners suddenly released from the meanest of jails,
growing in an unwanted profusion of fruit and leaves. Well-tended
cabernet vines may produce two tons of grapes an acre in
California; uninhibited sangiovese can push out 12 tons or more.
Sadly, the wine pressed from these ebullient vines is usually poor
stuff _thin, watery and acidic.
</P>
<P>
   This has not stopped California's incurably optimistic vintners.
``We tame the vines,'' Glen Salva of Atlas Peak Vineyards, in the
Napa Valley, said the other day. ``We cut them back 40, 50, even 60
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   As winemakers and grape growers have come to understand the
grape, the market for sangiovese has begun to grow. As late as the
1970's, there were not even a dozen California sangioveses on the
market. Today there are more than 50, as well as a hundred or more
growers who find wineries eager to buy their sangiovese grapes.
Ferrari-Carano, Mondavi, Flora Springs, Coturri, Silverado,
Lockwood, Renwood, Swanson, Shafer, Staglin, Sterling, Atlas Peak
and Altamura are some better-known California wineries producing
sangiovese. Leonetti Cellars in Washington State also makes it.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, California sangioveses resemble other
California wines more than they do Italian wines made from the same
grape. They are fuller-bodied, softer and richer, yet keep the
distinctive sangiovese taste. The best are truly attractive wines.
They are just very different in style. Perhaps easygoing is a way
to describe them.
</P>
<P>
   To an Italian winemaker, the name sangiovese is not enough to
identify a wine. Which sangiovese, he wants to know. The grape
reaches its apogee in Tuscany, where it plays a starring role in
Chianti; in Montalcino, where it's called brunello, and in nearby
Montepulciano, where, as either sangiovese or prugnolo, it produces
Vino Nobile di Montepulciano. Sangiovese's different names are more
than marketing ploys. They signify different clones of the grape,
clones that can produce very different wines. One variant,
sangioveto, is hailed by some winemakers as being far superior to
sangiovese itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sangiovese is hardly limited to Tuscany. Around Bologna, it is
known as sangionvese di Romagna; in Umbria, it shows up in the wine
known as Torgiano; in Emilia-Romagna and on the plains south of
Rome, it produces millions of gallons of nondescript wine for quick
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, at a conference on sangiovese at San Felice,
near Siena, I watched Tuscan winemakers sample California versions
of their wine. Their praise was guarded. They didn't know what to
make of the Californian approach.
</P>
<P>
   Italians and Californians may not agree on style but they do
share one thing: a fondness for blending sangiovese with cabernet
sauvignon and, on occasion, merlot. Chianti has always been a
blend: about 80 percent sangiovese, plus canaiolo, a red grape, and
trebbiano, a white. About 20 years ago, some producers began to
blend in cabernet sauvignon, even when the authorities refused to
allow the resulting wine to be called Chianti. Some winemakers went
overboard, making all-cabernet wines and predicting that
traditional varieties like sangiovese were obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Tuscany continues to produce excellent cabernet and merlot but
the Tuscans also have been rediscovering their traditional
varieties, sometimes producing superb single-grape wines from
sangiovese or sangioveto, sometimes enhancing them with cabernet.
Antinori's Tignanello is a blend of mostly sangiovese with some
cabernet sauvignon. Badia a Coltibuono's Sangioveto de Coltibuono
is, as the name implies, made entirely from the sangioveto grape.
</P>
<P>
   California winemakers operate in much the same way. Some produce
single-grape wines. Others blend because even after severe crop
thinning, sangiovese can produce a light wine and the cabernet can
give it more body and color. Staglin Vineyards' elegant Stagliano,
which is 100 percent sangiovese, can match the best of the Tuscans.
So can Shafer Vineyards Firebreak, a sangiovese-cabernet sauvignon
blend.
</P>
<P>
   Chianti remains one of the best wine buys, with many Chianti
classicos at $20 or less. Ruffino's Chianti Classico Aziano 1996 is
about $9; Castellare di Castellina's Chianti Classico, $13.
California sangioveses generally cost 30 percent more than their
Italian counterparts. Three reasonably priced examples, by
California standards, are Swanson Winery's 1995 at about $24,
Silverado Vineyards 1995, $20, and Flora Springs 1996, $16.
</P>
<P>
   There is every reason to assume that California sangioveses will
continue to improve. But except for the few mentioned here, most
are indifferent wines when compared with other California and
Tuscan red wines. Unless you are a California fanatic, there is no
reason to drink so-so sangioveses when there are dozens of
excellent little Chiantis out there for less than $10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
