<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-SOC-WORLDCUP-CHILE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILE ADVANCES TO SECOND ROUND AFTER 1-1 DRAW WITH CAMEROON  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
 
(Repeating; adds information in 2nd graf about suspended Chilean
players)   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ When Chile had survived a contentious 1-1 draw
with Cameroon Tuesday and advanced to the second round of the World
Cup, its players removed their jerseys and tossed them into the
crowd, shedding their shirts and 36 years of frustration and
humiliation in soccer's world championship.
</P>
<P>
   After a frustrating wait of nearly four decades, however,
Chile's promotion may be a meager reward. Its next opponent, on
Saturday, happens to be Brazil, the defending champion and the same
team that eliminated Chile when it last advanced in the World Cup
in 1962. In addition, Chile will play without three starters _
Francisco Rojas, Moises Villarroel and Nelson Parraguez _ who
accumulated two yellow cards during the first round.
</P>
<P>
   (Pickup 3rd graf, `In fact, etc.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
