<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2992 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBQ-SMOKER-COX     06-23 1632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBQ-SMOKER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flavor-infusing water smoker is one hot item
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of the 77 million Americans who own a grill, not everyone just
puts on a funny hat and burns hot dogs over an open flame. A full
10 percent of grill owners _ nearly 8 million people _ have decided
to invest in a second piece of outdoor cooking equipment: a water
smoker.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the country, smoke cooking is catching on like never
before. ``Smoking is definitely a trend,'' says Donna Myers, a
spokeswoman for the Barbecue Industry Association. ``Sales of wood
chips and chunks have far more than doubled in a 10-year period.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that all this wood is going into smokers. Backyard chefs
throw wood into charcoal grills to give extra flavor to steaks and
chops. They also risk setting off alarms by smoking foods in
covered pots on the stove.
</P>
<P>
   But water smokers are a hot-ticket item around the country, with
annual sales of 2 million units. Water smokers look like a covered
canister, with a heat source (either charcoal or electric) in the
bottom, a water pan in the middle and a rack or two for cooking
meats on the top. You place the wood chunks near the heat source,
and the smoke filters up, mingling with the steam that cooks the
meat. Unlike dry smokers, where the wood burns in a separate
tinderbox, water smokers are relatively small and inexpensive.
``Somebody who has never smoked can go out and get a water smoker
from $40,'' says Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Jamison, author with wife Cheryl Alters Jamison of ``Born
to Grill'' (Harvard Common Press, $27.95), recommends getting an
entry-level electric model. ``They cost a little over $50, but are
better and cheaper in the long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Bishop, writing up a comparative testing of water smokers
in the food magazine ``Cook's Illustrated,'' came to the same
conclusion; the variations of charcoal heat make for longer cooking
times, and there's more chance the fire will burn out if you forget
to add charcoal or burn the food if it gets too hot.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop tested several makes and models and gave his top score to
the Meco Water Smoker 5030 XElectric Combo, a fairly inexpensive
($80) model with a door for adding more wood during cooking and an
adjustable heat gauge.
</P>
<P>
   I, on the other hand, bought the first electric smoker I laid
eyes on: the Brinkmann Gourmet Electric Water Smoker, which cost
$59.85 at Home Depot. (By the way, a source at Home Depot's
corporate office said that sales of water smokers in Atlanta remain
good but are not higher than in recent years. In the South, we've
apparently reached smoke saturation.)
</P>
<P>
   I love my new smoker. The first batches of both pork shoulder
and baby back ribs were successful. The rack of ribs _ seasoned
with a basic spice rub and painted with a sweet bottled barbecue
sauce _ disappeared in a family feeding frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   I've been playing around with the water smoker enough to offer
some tips, techniques and guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   -- The wood: Use chunks of aged hardwood (hickory and mesquite
are the most common packaged varieties), soaked for at least 20
minutes in water. Place four fist-size chunks near the heating
element. Some people recommend replenishing the wood partway
through, but I thought one dose added all the smoke flavor I
wanted. Also, some sources say you can wrap the dry wood chunks in
foil with holes poked in it instead of soaking it. That sure didn't
work for me.
</P>
<P>
   -- The water pan: The manufacturer claims that the water pan
should be replenished every two or three hours. I found that the
water easily lasts six hours, so you can cook ribs or a pork picnic
shoulder without any sloshy fuss.
</P>
<P>
   -- The rub: Stick to a good, basic rub. Just for the heck of it,
I tried cooking ribs seasoned with every kind of spice mixture,
from Moroccan ras-el-hanout to Indian tandoori masala, and I can
tell you there's a reason beyond religious injunction that Indians
don't make tandoori pork: It tastes awful.
</P>
<P>
   -- The sauce: A good homemade barbecue sauce in the fridge is
all the incentive you need to fire up the smoker. But bottled
sauces are easy enough to doctor up. Just be wary of ``hickory''
flavored sauces, which usually have a nasty bite from liquid smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Most bottled sauces contain a hefty component of high-fructose
corn syrup, which is not necessarily a bad thing, according to
Atlanta food scientist Shirley O. Corriher, author of ``Cookwise''
(Morrow, $28.50). Corn syrup is what she calls a ``reducing sugar''
that helps meat brown more delectably at a lower temperature. She
recommends adding a shot of Karo syrup to your favorite homemade
barbecue sauce recipe. She also suggests adding a whole, finely
cut-up lemon to sauce as it's cooking. Any scientific reason? ``No,
it just tastes good. And my momma made her barbecue sauce like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Time and temperature: If you can adjust the temperature of
your smoker, you should barbecue pork at 225-250 degrees. At that
temperature, ribs take four to five hours and a pork picnic
shoulder takes six to seven. If the cooker runs hotter, you can
still make good barbecue. Pork is ready when it reaches an internal
temperature of 160 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   -- Water-smoking a pork shoulder: A whole pork shoulder,
weighing 18-22 pounds, is the cut that championship barbecue teams
prepare during contests. For the home market, the shoulder is cut
into two pieces: The piece around the shoulder blade is called the
``Boston butt''; the shank end is called the ``picnic shoulder.''
The butt is fattier, and therefore juicier, while the picnic is
more attractive and easier to cut. I'd go with the picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the layer of skin and fat, except for the portion around
the shank, and coat the meat liberally with a rub or spice paste.
If you want the meat tender enough to pull, that requres some work.
Jay Duke of the Grillmasters, a championship pork barbecue team
from Americus, says you need to tend to it every hour during the
smoking. ``We recommend mopping it or basting it with lemon juice
or salt water to add the flavor to the meat. Every time you open
the grill to look and see how things are going, you always want to
add something to the meat to keep it from drying out. We also take
a sterile cloth and lay it on the meat.'' The sign of good pork
shoulder, says Duke, is the ``bark'' of seasoning and browned meat
that forms on the surface. The ``smoke ring'' is the layer of meat
under the bark that turns pink from smoke penetration.
</P>
<P>
   If that's too much work, simply let the meat smoke until the
internal temperature registers about 165 degrees. Let it rest for a
few minutes at room temperature when it comes out of the smoker,
then slice it thinly against the grain. Remember, the easiest way
to break down tough meat fibers is to slice through them properly.
</P>
<P>
   -- Water-smoking pork ribs: Whether you're cooking baby back
ribs or spareribs, you need to remove the membrane along the back
by loosening it with a knife, then pulling it off with your
fingers. Also, trim off any excess fat or filaments. Cut the ribs
into half racks. Sprinkle the convex surface of the ribs liberally
with rub, but contrary to the name, don't rub it in.
</P>
<P>
   Place the ribs on the smoker racks and smoke for about 3 hours,
until the meat begins to pull away from the bones. Remove the ribs
and place them on individual pieces of foil, and sprinkle a mild
vinegar (cider or Japanese rice wine) over the top. Wrap them fully
and return to the smoker to finish cooking, about another 1 1/2
hours. At the end unwrap them and paint them with sauce. You can
either serve them immediately or return them to the smoker for a
few minutes to encourage the sauce to crust.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Grillmasters
</P>
<P>
   Barbecue Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 1/2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 45 minutes
</P>
<P>
   11-pound box light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2cups ketchup
</P>
<P>
   1cup Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup honey
</P>
<P>
   1cup cider or distilled vinegar
</P>
<P>
   6green onions, trimmed and minced
</P>
<P>
   3cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   16whole cloves
</P>
<P>
   1bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon crumbled dry rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon ground oregano
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon ground red pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup white zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup ( 1/2 stick) butter
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   In a large saucepan, combine all ingredients except butter and
lemon juice and simmer over medium-low heat 30-45 minutes. Reduce
heat to low, add butter and lemon juice and simmer 5 minutes
longer. Strain; discard solids. Serve warm. You can refrigerate
unused sauce for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Uses: As a finishing sauce on ribs and pork barbecue. Also good
on chicken and hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1 tablespoon: 37 calories, trace protein, 1 gram fat
(percent calories from fat, 12), 9 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 88 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   SEASONING
</P>
<P>
   Willingham's
</P>
<P>
   Mild Seasoning Mix
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1/4 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon lemon pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dry mustard
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon dark or light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of Accent or other flavor enhancer (optional)
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl or glass jar with a lid, combine all
ingredients. Stir or shake to mix. Use immediately or store in a
cool, dark place for several months. _ From ``John Willingham's
World Champion Bar-B-Q'' (Morrow, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Per 1 tablespoon: 13 calories, 1 gram protein, no fat, 2 grams
carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 3,580 milligrams sodium.
</P>
