A2994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN24-COX     06-23 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Caring friends at hospital fix the highway to my heart
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So one night, lacking anything more exciting to do, I had a
heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   And then, asked the cardiologist, what did you do?
</P>
<P>
   ``Finished reading `Angela's Ashes,''' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a miserable book,'' said the cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   So we talked about that and other books for a while, and he
explained that he was going to run a wire up an artery to my heart
and find out what was what. Easy, painless and I could go back to
work in four hours, unless ... unless something was blocking the
blood to my heart, and it turned out something was.
</P>
<P>
   A covey of young people, nurses and technicians, were making me
welcome, enveloping me in a warm blanket, giving me coffee, my
first of the day, and making little jokes about why they couldn't
find a vein in my arm that would do for drawing blood. (Finally a
young man named Greg did find one, and we cheered and called him
Dr. Vein.)
</P>
<P>
   The day wore on, and I was having a pleasant time in the J.B.
Fuqua Heart Center at Piedmont Hospital in Atlanta, reminiscing a
little about the days when Mr. Fuqua served in the Georgia
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Come midafternoon, they stuck a balloon in that highway to the
heart to nudge the roadblock aside, and the operation was over. The
artery they used runs from a thigh, and that leg got awfully tired
of being immobilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm tired,'' I explained to a nurse. ``My back hurts.
I've got to move.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You move that leg,'' said a fierce little woman, ``you'll
bleed to death, and I'll get fired!''
</P>
<P>
   I lay still and brooded over which would be worse.
</P>
<P>
   She and her colleague pounded on my leg to get it back together,
I suppose, and I whined that my back hurt and finally they gave me
a shot.
</P>
<P>
   When I awakened, the sun was shining and I could put on my
clothes and go home. I hesitated to take my old body away from
them. My doctor and his young assistants had taken such an interest
in it.
</P>
<P>
   But all good things come to an end and they have plenty of other
bodies with similar problems.
</P>
<P>
   While I chatted and made jokes with his staff, the doctor
performed four similar operations, and for all I know he kept doing
them into the night. It seems there are a lot of us with chunks of
cholesterol lodged in that road to the heart, and taking care of it
is no more trouble than sweeping floors or scrubbing pots. (Your
back gets tired doing those things, too.)
</P>
<P>
   It's funny it never occurred to me that I would have any trouble
with my heart. It has performed reliably all these years, but you
never know, and there certainly seems to be a high incidence of
heart trouble out there.
</P>
<P>
   I walked down the hall at Piedmont Hospital reading the names of
doctors who specialize in the heart. There must be hundreds of
them.
</P>
<P>
   This particular operation, a balloon angioplasty, had not been
developed when my mother died in 1976. I wonder if it would have
saved her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``That pain,'' she told me over the phone, ``is back.'' Not
wanting to go back to the hospital, she got back in her bed and
willed herself to die. I wish she could have known my warm and
caring friends at Piedmont Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley is recuperating at home; her column will resume
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
