<HEADER>
A2996 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-BBQ-COX     06-23 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-BBQ-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Now that it's hot outside, start your summer feast inside and
work your way to the back yard
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My Weber Barbecue Kettle hasn't been looking so good lately. The
rubber stopper that holds one of the wheels in place is long gone,
so I have to be careful when moving it. Likewise, the side supports
are warped beyond usefulness, and only a taut band of packing tape
keeps the spindly legs from collapsing. When guests come over for a
back-porch cookout, they eye the bandaged, tippy, smoldering kettle
nervously, as if at any moment they may need to fling down their
paper plates and wineglasses and go running for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't yet burned down the balcony, so I remain loyal to my
10-year-old Weber. Up to now, I've used it primarily as a high-heat
grill _ a device for crusting salmon fillets and butterflied legs
of lamb over a direct, sizzling flame.
</P>
<P>
   But what about barbecue? What about indirect heat, ambient wood
smoke and the low-and-slow cooking necessary for ribs and pork
shoulders? What about everything the manufacturer claims you can
accomplish with a kettle?
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. With barbecue I've had less luck, or perhaps less
inclination. Following the game plan, I'm supposed to set up a
small pile of charcoal on one side, place the meat on the other
side, and then work hard for my meal tending the coals and
adjusting the air vents over the course of six hours. All this work
for at most two racks of ribs.
</P>
<P>
   Surely there must be a way to start ribs cooking indoors, then
transfer them to the grill for a final application of char.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Alters Jamison and Bill Jamison, authors of the newly
released ``Born to Grill'' (Harvard Common Press, $27.95), know the
smoky pleasure of honest barbecue as well as anyone but also know
the myriad tricks people try to pseudo-barbecue ribs at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked to people who boiled them and microwaved them and
did all this stuff,'' says Cheryl over the phone from her home in
Santa Fe, N.M. ``But we felt like it took a lot of flavor away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jamisons found they could conjure up a good facsimile of
barbecued baby backs by wrapping them in foil, roasting them in a
medium oven, refrigerating them thoroughly and reheating them over
a hot grill. Unlike recipes for braised or boiled ribs, these cook
as they should, in constant contact with a spice rub, so, as Cheryl
notes, ``you get more of that flavor soaked into the meat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' she adds, ``you get that official thing called the
Maillard reaction.'' She is referring to the browning of the ribs,
first in the oven, and then on the grill. The chemical reactions
that make meat brown (collectively called the Maillard reactions
for the French chemist who first documented them) yield a
particularly complex and delectable array of flavors when the meat
starts cooking at a low temperature and in contact with sugar, such
as the little bit the Jamisons put in their barbecue rub. The
flavors of slowly browned meat are half of what we crave in
barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the other half is the flavor of smoke. Since the
ribs won't spend long enough on the grill to get a major shot of
smoke flavor, the Jamisons introduce it via chipotle (smoked ripe
jalapenos) that they put in their barbecue sauce as well as their
spice rub.
</P>
<P>
   I love their technique. And I love the possibilities. With ribs
cooking for several hours in the oven, why not throw in a pot of
old-fashioned baked beans as well? And while I'm at it, a batch of
homemade Parker House rolls is easy enough to assemble, and so much
better than the cottony white bread everyone expects with barbecue.
As long as I'm not an all-day slave to the grill, I can cook up a
storm in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   While Cheryl Jamison and I discuss the possibilities of indoor/
</P>
<P>
   outdoor barbecue on the phone, Bill Jamison listens in, not
adding much to the conversation until I ask if their technique
would work on a pork shoulder as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we call a compromise,'' he said matter-of-factly.
``But, you know, if you really want to barbecue _ really barbecue _
you can get one of those little water smokers for $30 to $40.
People use 'em all the time. They're great.''
</P>
<P>
   They are?
</P>
<P>
   With a sinking feeling, I knew that I was about to enter the
second phase of my career as a backyard barbecuer. Move over,
Weber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
