<SLUG> BC-FOOD-INSEASON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cherries are at their sweet peak
 &HT;    FREELANCE STORY. TO BE USED BY COX PAPERS ONLY. NOT TO BE USED
BY NY TIMES WIRE.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Cynthia Hizer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the early cherry crop coming from rainy California has
been a bust this year, Northwest growers are looking at a promising
season. Look for the peak season to start now for sweet cherries _
Lamberts and, later, the Bing _ and to continue through late July.
The demand for cherries is exceeding the supply right now, with
Japan sweeping up most of the supply at prices that most Americans
wouldn't consider paying.
</P>
<P>
   Cherry season is short and commands plenty of promotions. Bings
carry the show and sell the most. The round Bings are
mahogany-colored at the peak of ripeness, while the smaller and
heart-shaped Lamberts are a crimson red.
</P>
<P>
   Sour cherries, those prized for pies, mostly come from Michigan
rather than the Northwest. And few of them make it to Georgia as
fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Most stores still sell cherries in bulk, and most customers
still like to pick out their own fruit, hunting for the darkest and
prettiest cherries. Other stores are experimenting with prepackaged
fruit, but it adds to the already high cost of the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Also, cherries don't lend themselves to store sampling. The
reason is the pits _ literally. People spit them out or drop them
on the floor, creating a dangerous situation.
</P>
<P>
   Other produce
</P>
<P>
   -- What's new: The heat is causing problems for cucumbers and
beans, and many supplies that get to the stores will show decay.
</P>
<P>
   -- Best buys of the week: Commercial Georgia sweet corn
(supersweet), Georgia peaches.
</P>
<P>
   -- Peak season: Local squash, and most of the Southern peas are
in (zipper, pink, black-eyed, purple hull), especially at the State
Farmers Market. Also California Long White potatoes, Vidalia
onions, squash, zucchini, bell peppers, banana peppers (hot only),
okra, Florida okra, turnip greens, cabbage, grapes, California
melons, strawberries, watermelon.
</P>
<P>
   -- Iffy: Spinach, cucumbers, pole and snap beans.
</P>
<P>
   -- Expensive: Beans, cucumbers, snap beans, pole beans,
specialty melons, raspberries and blackberries.
</P>
<P>
   -- Going, going, gone: Florida citrus.
</P>
<P>
   -- At farmers markets: Sweet onions, garlic, green tomatoes,
greens (lamb's quarters, spinach, collard greens, rapini, kale),
cocozelle zucchini, pickling cucumbers, commercial and organic
sweet corn, organic blueberries, wild blackberries, herbs, honey,
farm eggs.
</P>
<P>
   -- Meat, poultry, seafood: Boneless, skinless chicken breasts,
sirloin tip roast, Alaskan salmon, catfish fillets.
</P>
<P>
   Two quick cherry ideas
</P>
<P>
   During their fleeting season, it's hard to beat fresh cherries
eaten right off the stem. But for a little variety, here are a
couple of other fast ideas to try:
</P>
<P>
   -- Frozen cherry treats: Freeze pitted sweet cherries on cookie
sheets. When frozen, pack in freezer bags. Eat out of hand as a
quick sweet snack or drop into iced tea, lemonade, seltzer or white
wine.
</P>
<P>
   -- Cherry-peach compote: In a skillet over medium-high heat,
melt 1 tablespoon butter; add 6 peeled and sliced peaches and 1/4
cup pitted cherries. Cook, shaking pan often, 2-3 minutes. Sprinkle
with 1 or 2 tablespoons brown sugar and 1 teaspoon vanilla. Remove
from heat and serve over vanilla ice cream. Makes 4-6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   CHERRIES
</P>
<P>
   -- Price: Prices shouldn't top $3.49 a pound for premium
cherries, with some store specials a little less for smaller sizes.
</P>
<P>
   -- Nutrition: A 3 1/2-ounce portion has 70 calories and little
fat. Cherries are a good source of fiber and potassium as well as
vitamins C and B complex.
</P>
<P>
   -- Selection: Look for bright or dark red cherries that are
shiny and plump, with firm stems. Lighter fruits are more tart.
Avoid fruit that is shriveled or has soft or brown spots.
</P>
<P>
   -- Storage: Loosely wrap cherries in paper towels and place in a
plastic bag, unwashed. Refrigerate up to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   -- Uses: One pound of unpitted cherries makes about 2 cups
pitted. Use fresh for out-of-hand eating or use in pies, cobblers,
cakes, relishes, meat sauces or salads.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
