<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN:`A family tradition' with all the furnishings
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blue Ridge, Ga.-- It was a classic Saturday lunch: fried fish
(bluegills), jalapeno hush puppies, potato pancakes and coleslaw.
Charles Abernathy, the orchestrator and chef for this feast, had
gathered his family _ and invited mine.
</P>
<P>
   After lots of fun chat, we sat at the two tables covered with
red and white checkered oilcloth and fell onto our plates and into
semi-silence _ savoring some of the best food you'll find in any
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not a restaurant; it was a furniture store _ the
52-year-old family business, Charles' Home Furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   By the time we'd enjoyed this meal recently, we were familiar
with the Abernathys' graciousness: Stop by around 11:30 and maybe
get offered lunch or a snack between conversations about
handcrafted wood furniture made at the shop in back of the
building.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Charles proved to be not only a wood man,
but a food man, too. He enjoys people enjoying food: ``It's a
family tradition.'' He hands out candy to fellow worshippers at
First Baptist Church in nearby Epworth because ``it makes people
smile.''
</P>
<P>
   And, after Lyn and I had visited the store a few times, he
surprised us by offering stalks of celery for the road, asserting
that, in addition to being a good healthy snack, celery causes you
to use more calories digesting it than it puts into your body.
That'll work, I said to myself. Eat enough celery, and you can do
serious damage to other foods.
</P>
<P>
   We'd have to eat a whole lot of celery to compensate for the
calories consumed on the day of Charles' special feast (prepared at
the nearby family home). We had planned the fish fry one day when
we were sitting around talking about food and how much Charles
loves to cook. This meal, it turned out, was one of his favorites.
</P>
<P>
   One taste told us why. The Abernathys _ Charles' wife,
Marguerite (a painter and calligrapher, she expresses her artistry
on paper and canvas rather than in the kitchen), sons Allan (a
local radio personality) and James and James' wife and son, Sandy
and Justin _ knew the meal well and could practice moderation. But
Lyn and I, along with our daughters, Leslie and Petria, threw
moderation off the mountain. OK, I can only speak for myself, as my
plate was the only thing I saw for almost an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The bluegills were fried the way I remember them at family
gatherings in Meridian, Miss., where we used to catch them _ as
Charles does today. Just hard enough to give you a golden crunch on
the outside and a succulent white moistness on the inside.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the hush puppies were browned and crispy outside,
perfectly mealy and moist within. You chew on one, and just as you
savor the flavor of onion, the jalapeno kicks in. Hot puppies.
Thankfully, Charles eschews added sugar, a bad practice embraced by
too many restaurant cooks.
</P>
<P>
   The potato pancakes added a culinary touch familiar to many
families; my mother used to fry the leftover mashed potatoes for a
side dish _ or a main dish during the many hard times we went
through.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, times were good. They rolled on to dessert,
Marguerite's icebox lemon pie with Graham cracker crust. ``I
suppose you want a small piece,'' she said teasingly to Allan.
</P>
<P>
   Deadpan, he shot back: ``Some things we don't joke about.''
</P>
<P>
   First time I'd ever been too full to laugh after a big meal at
the furniture store.
</P>
<P>
   -- E-mail: leemay(at)bellsouth.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
