<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mixing flours gives rise to wheat biscuits
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many home cooks looking for a healthier breakfast treat or who
simply love the taste of whole wheat have experimented with whole
wheat biscuits, only to discover that simply replacing regular
flour usually won't do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   Whole wheat flour has a different texture and consistency. So
making a whole wheat biscuit can be tricky. Mildred Lynch of
Smyrna, Ga. wanted a recipe that was tried and true. Stella Jones
of Ellenwood, Ga. came through. Jones said she's tried several
recipes but likes this one best. It uses a mixture of regular and
whole wheat for a light texture.
</P>
<P>
   Whole Wheat Biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 2 1/2-inch biscuits
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1cup whole-wheat flour
</P>
<P>
   7/8cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3/4teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/3cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   3/4cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 450 degrees. In a medium bowl, combine flours,
baking powder and salt. Mix well. Cut in shortening. Add milk to
make soft dough. Place on floured board and roll out. Dust surface
of dough with flour if too sticky. Cut biscuits with cookie cutter
or mouth of a glass. Place on ungreased baking sheet. Bake about 5
minutes or until bottoms are browned. Put under broiler briefly to
brown tops. Cool.
</P>
<P>
   Per biscuit: 74 calories, 2 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 48), 8 grams carbohydrates, 1 milligram
cholesterol, 194 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Barbara Chamberlain of Lawrenceville is looking for a brownie
recipe that calls for a whole can of Hershey's Chocolate Syrup.
</P>
<P>
   -- Marilynn C. Hinton of Stone Mountain is looking for a recipe
for Greek salad with dressing.
</P>
<P>
   -- Caryn Hanrahan (e-mail) is looking for a cold black-eyed pea
salad with pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   _Reagan Walker
</P>
<P>
   Where to write: Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA
30302. Include a daytime telephone number. E-mail:
rwalker(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
