<HEADER>
A3002 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     06-23 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOISTURE ASIDE, MATCHES GO ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Did Dick Williams moan, ``Water, water everywhere and
what a place to sink!'' as he dived from the Titanic on that
abysmal April night in 1912?
</P>
<P>
   We shall never know, only that Williams astoundingly didn't
sink. Keeping his head above water, a neat trick for a Harvard man,
he actually outfloated Leonardo DiCaprio, star of the wettest movie
since ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' and went on to win a Wimbledon title
in doubles eight years later. Not to mention the US singles titles
of 1914 and 1916.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture is ever the topic at Wimbledon, where an inordinate
amount of it frequently appears during the last week of June and
the first of July when a lot of people are trying to win a tennis
tournament. Since this tournament is played on an archaic substance
called grass _ a mystery to most of those involved _ the tendency
of the host All England Lawn Tennis &AMP; Croquet Club to masquerade as
a Brazilian rain forest at the whim of every passing cloud makes
tennis a pastime somewhere between treacherous and impossible.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the liquid intake of the tourney, approaching that
of Nicolas Cage in ``Leaving Las Vegas,'' nearly caused Wimbledon
to join the Titanic. Memories of 1997 were rife Tuesday as the
tournament was subdued by patches of mad and frantic drizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Meanderers in the mist managed to complete a few matches, such
as Martina Hingis beginning the defense of her crown, 7-5, 6-3,
over Lisa Raymond. And another winner, the almost forgotten US Open
champ Patrick Rafter, who says at last he's got the message.
</P>
<P>
   Since beating Greg Rusedski to rule Flushing Meadow nine months
ago, Rafter has herniated. What else would you expect for a young
fellow suddenly lugging a continent _ Australia _ around on his
shoulders? That's the burden he won by reviving the hopes of the
ex-world conquerors, the Down Under-takers. Last of that tribe to
perform what had become an annual ritual _ plundering America _ was
John Newcombe back in the year of OPEC tyranny and gasoline-pump
lineups, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Many very wet evenings have been spent on that far-off island
toasting ``Our Pat,'' and hailing his restoration of the Aussie
style: full-speed ahead serve-and-volleying in an era of baseline
topspinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of expectations after the Open,'' Rafter
says. ``I couldn't relax out there, and I started losing.''
</P>
<P>
   His win over a Swiss qualifier, No. 146-ranked Ivo Heuberger,
6-1, 6-2, 4-6, 6-1, is hardly cause for nonstop waltzing to
``Waltzing Matilda'' back home in Queensland. But when he says,
``I've got my happiness back,'' the tribe is encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Happiness Tuesday was Rafter in full volleying, smashing cry,
and it overflowed the celebrated graveyard, Court 2, where,
regardless of stature or name, a honcho is always at risk from a
long-shotter. Didn't No. 281 Doug Flach inter No. 3 Andre Agassi
there two years ago, and No. 98 Nicolas Kiefer likewise undo No. 3
Yevgeny Kafelnikov last year? Heuberger had his chance to make the
embalming honor roll.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 33,688 crowding the grounds, 2,300 packed 2, an overgrown
closet, to scream for Rafter and keep him going when he lost the
third set.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, who rose to No. 2 after starting 1997 at No. 62, has
receded to No. 6, barely playing above .500 after Flushing. But
he's on a six-match streak, his hottest trot since the Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure after the US Open was tremendous, a lot of it
self-inflicted,'' Rafter says. ``But I think I started to turn it
around last week when I beat Andrei Medvedev at Rosmalen'' (a
grass-court tuneup in the Netherlands) ``and went on to win the
tournament. That was important coming in here, to know I could win
a tournament again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began to relax. I realized that just because I won the US
Open I couldn't expect to win everything, and I think the people at
home realized it, too. I got the message at Rosmalen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a tangible message, a tough fax from his Aussie
predecessor as US champ, Newcombe, now the Australian Davis Cup
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it said is between me and Newc,'' says Rafter, ``but it
was a kick in the bum. There was a fine line. I could've snapped
and thrown it in the bin, or taken it aboard. They were facts, and
I took them. Things I needed to do. I'm glad he sent it. It helped
me relax. I don't feel like I'm carrying Australia any more.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rafter, one of the few who understands grass, can make a
genuine stab at the title, will we learn Newcombe's settling words?
Were they: ``Don't spill the beer, Patrick. We don't need another
flood''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
