A3001 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-VEGETARIAN25-COX     06-23 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-VEGETARIAN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's official: Plant-based diet smart
 &HT;    FREELANCE STORY. TO BE USED BY COX PAPERS ONLY. NOT TO BE USED
BY NY TIMES WIRE.
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL JUNE 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Cynthia Hizer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American Dietetic Association is considered the official
word on nutrition in America. It wasn't very long ago that it
didn't think much of vegetarian diets and was positively thumbs
down on vegan diets. The four food groups might have been updated,
but meat and dairy were still the foundation of a healthy diet.
</P>
<P>
   It was groundbreaking news in 1993, then, when the association
presented an official position paper on vegetarian diets. While it
stopped short of a full-fledged endorsement, at least it said that
vegetarian diets were healthful and nutritionally adequate when
properly planned.
</P>
<P>
   Now the association has revised that position with an even
stronger, more positive message, noting that: ``vegetarian diets
are nutritionally adequate and provide health benefits in the
prevention and treatment of certain diseases.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the ADA:
</P>
<P>
   -- Vegetarian diets offer disease-protection benefits because of
their lower saturated-fat, cholesterol and animal-protein content
and, often, higher folate concentrations (which reduce serum
homocysteine levels), antioxidants such as vitamins C and E,
carotenoids and phytochemicals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Not only is mortality from coronary artery disease lower in
vegetarians than in nonvegetarians, but vegetarian diets have also
been successful in arresting coronary artery disease. Total serum
cholesterol and low-density lipoprotein cholesterol levels are
usually lower in vegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   -- Vegetarians tend to have a lower incidence of hypertension
than nonvegetarians.
</P>
<P>
   -- Type 2 diabetes mellitus is much less likely to be a cause of
death in vegetarians, perhaps because of their higher intake of
complex carbohydrates and a lower body mass index.
</P>
<P>
   -- Vegetarians have lower incidences of lung, colorectal and
colon cancers.
</P>
<P>
   The position paper offers much more, and you can read the entire
piece at www.eatright.org.
</P>
<P>
   Above is a vegetarian recipe that wins high marks for nutrition
and taste.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Vegetable Pizzas
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Cooking time: 45
minutes
</P>
<P>
   As the vegetables cook, they turn into a juicy melange, perfect
for spreading on a pizza. Japanese eggplant has a thin skin and
doesn't need to be peeled, so it's a good choice for this easy
pizza.
</P>
<P>
   2Japanese eggplants, cut into 1/4-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2yellow onions, cut in wedges
</P>
<P>
   2red bell peppers, diced
</P>
<P>
   3cups mushrooms, thickly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4teaspoons dried basil (8 teaspoons fresh)
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon coriander
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1cup roasted red peppers, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1cup chopped tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4garlic cloves, crushed
</P>
<P>
   6whole-wheat pitas
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 450 degrees. Place eggplants, onions, bell
peppers and mushrooms in a single layer in one or two large baking
dishes. Toss with 3 teaspoons of the basil and the cinnamon,
coriander and salt. Bake until eggplant is fork-tender, about 30
minutes. Reduce oven temperature to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the roasted red peppers with the tomatoes, garlic and
remaining teaspoon basil.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble the pizzas, spread a layer of the pepper-tomato
mixture on a pita. Top with a generous layer of the roasted
vegetables. Place on a baking sheet. Repeat with the remaining
pitas. Bake for 15 minutes. _ From ``Garden Cuisine'' by Paul
Wenner (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $14)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 215 calories, 8 grams protein, 2 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 9), 45 grams carbohydrates, no cholesterol, 544
milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
