<HEADER>
A3003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEORGECLOONEY-COX     06-23 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGECLOONEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fame, by George
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Get past the looks of George Clooney. Past those eyelashes over
the dark eyes, and the jutting jaw, and that fraction of an inch of
perfectly even beard stubble that would look slovenly on most guys
but on him just looks great; get past all that and there is the
ambivalence of George Clooney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's weird,'' he says, ``the work you have to do to stay
somewhat normal.''
</P>
<P>
   He has one more season to go as Dr. Doug Ross on ``ER,'' the
most popular series on TV. He has a new movie opening Friday, ``Out
of Sight,'' based on an Elmore Leonard novel. He has an essay in
the premiere issue of Brill's Content, the new media watchdog
magazine, in which he takes on the press for succumbing to the
taint of the tabloids. The star of the fourth ``Batman'' movie is
no longer caped, but still a crusader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a day goes by, literally not a day, that there isn't some
story about me in some newspaper that's completely wrong. I read I
was at Cindy Crawford's wedding, sitting on the beach talking to
Richard Gere. I'm reading this in New York, thinking, 'Wow! Was I
there?'''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney loves to talk, and he can be serious and analytical one
moment, charmingly self-deprecating the next, as he circles the
strange notion of celebrity in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like actors complaining how miserable their life is,''
he says. ``I'm very well paid and I love what I do. But if you
spend a day walking around with me, you'd rethink whether you want
to be me. You can be walking through an airport and here comes some
17-year-old with a video camera, and he starts making fun of your
female assistant to get a response. He wants me to go, 'Screw you,'
and shove him, and that's the clip they'll play over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that it's cool to be in what he calls the
famous club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kind of society of people you become friends with.
There's something fun about walking down the aisle at an awards
show and you see James Woods. You're part of the famous club. You
automatically know each other 'cause you're famous: 'Hey James, how
ya doin'?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Those types of things really crack me up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' is Clooney's fifth film, and his fifth attempt
to establish himself as a box-office heavyweight movie star as
distinct from a TV star. ``From Dusk Till Dawn'' didn't do it, nor
did ``The Peacemaker'' or ``One Fine Day'' and certainly not
``Batman &AMP; Robin,'' which he laughs about now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I buried the franchise,'' he says, grinning, eyes
flashing. ``This time I'm not wearing any rubber (suit), which I
think will be the key,'' he says of ``Out of Sight.'' In the movie,
Clooney plays a career bank robber, a charming loser who has a
problematic romance with a U.S. marshal, played by Jennifer Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to happen,'' says Steve Soderbergh, Clooney's
director in ``Out of Sight.'' ``He just hasn't gotten the right
part yet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on that list where about four or five people have to go,
'Nah, I'm too busy.' Then I get it,'' Clooney says, referring to
the path of scripts that determines the pecking order in the club.
</P>
<P>
   Until he gets the right part, Clooney will continue with the
show that got him into the club, ``ER.'' Clooney knocked around
forgettably in TV shows for years, playing Roseanne's boss in that
sitcom's first season (shaggy haired, he made little impression), a
neighbor on ``The Facts of Life'' and a tough on an old sitcom
named ``E/R.''
</P>
<P>
   He insists his departure from ``ER'' after next season is not
ingratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm honoring a contract that was for five years.
It's better for a show like that to rejuvenate itself regularly,
get in some fresh blood.'' He says it's unlikely Doug Ross will
die, because he's told the producers he'd willingly come back for
occasional guest shots.
</P>
<P>
   His schedule for the past two years, making movies and ``ER''
simultaneously, has been a killer, seven days a week almost every
week. For ``Out of Sight,'' filmed in Florida and Detroit, he would
film for four to five days, fly back to Los Angeles to do his
``ER'' scenes, then fly back to the movie set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this year Doug probably had more stories and time than
in any other season,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney is well-known as a prankster on the ``ER'' set, dropping
prop baby dolls and pretending they're real, smearing a goo called
SurgiLube on phones that cast members are about to answer. On the
set of ``Out of Sight,'' Albert Brooks, who plays a millionaire
robbery target of Clooney's character, was his mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's notorious,'' says Anthony Edwards, who plays Dr. Mark
Greene, Ross' best friend, on the series. ``When George is in the
next scene, he'll keep everybody laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   There will come a day, Clooney notes with what borders on glee,
when his membership in the famous club will be revoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to see me on TV or in a movie, you do that. And
when you don't, I will go away. Which I will eventually. There are
very few Paul Newmans in the world. I'm doing dinner theater in
about 10 years. In the end, I'm gonna end up on 'Hollywood
Squares.'''
</P>
<P>
   If he never plays Batman again, and it's doubtful he will, maybe
he could play the Joker. If he could get past his looks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
