<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sights, sounds of Appalachian fest entice mountain region
 &HT;    By Alan Patureau
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hills around Boone, N.C., will be enlivened July 5-Aug. 1
with the sounds of the Appalachian Summer Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Spread over the woodsy campus of Appalachian State University,
this 14th annual celebration of music, dance, theater and art will
point toward a climactic concert by country superstar Willie Nelson
at 7:30 p.m. Aug. 1 in Kidd-Brewer Stadium (adults $25, children
$5). Festival-goers can make a night of it, picnicking at the
stadium and staying for fireworks billed as the biggest display in
the Blue Ridge High Country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of summer festivals, but ours is the one with
the beautiful mountain setting and the world-class artistic
program,'' boasts organizer Denise Ringler, the Appalachian State
cultural affairs officer.
</P>
<P>
   Another musical highlight, at Farthing Auditorium on campus,
will be a recital by classical pianist Andre Watts at 8 p.m. July
25 (adults $20, students $10). Other 8 p.m. performances at
Farthing Auditorium include the Preservation Hall Jazz Band on July
16, the Jimmy Dorsey Big Band Spectacular on July 11, the Salt Lake
City-based Ballet West on July 18, the North Carolina Symphony Pops
on July 5, and two classical concerts by the North Carolina
Symphony, on July 22 featuring cellist Zuill Bailey and July 29
featuring violinist Stephanie Chase. Tickets are $16 for adults, $9
for students and $2 for children. Call 1-800-841-2787.
</P>
<P>
   A visual arts highlight will be the 12th Rosen Outdoor Sculpture
Exhibition, a national juried competition in outdoor sculpture, and
an indoor exhibit, ``Post-Modern Potluck,'' featuring the colorful
quilts of Betty Bivins Edwards. Theater offerings will include
staged readings of ``A Night at the Algonquin'' and ``The Inferno
of Dante.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the festival is offering a ``Family Series''
with weekend matinee performances and workshops. Performances
include stories and songs by David Holt, Ballet West, singer John
McCutcheon, the Broyhill Chamber Ensemble and the North Carolina
Symphony's Young Peoples Concert. Prices are $12 for adults, $5 for
students and $2 for children under 12.
</P>
<P>
   A children's visual arts workshop July 13-17 will focus on
making puppets and nested figures and a creative writing workshop
July 20-24 will feature ``fantasy writing''; fee is $10.
</P>
<P>
   -- Deals and meals: Mountain Getaway packages for two include
lodging at Broyhill Inn &AMP; Conference Center on campus: one night,
two meals and one show, $180; two nights, three meals and two
shows, $280. Call 1-800-951-6048. Try the duck or mountain trout at
the Broyhill's Commons Dining Room, or head for Dan'l Boone Inn,
130 Hardin St., for family atmosphere and fried chicken.
</P>
<P>
   -- Mountain lures: Nearby are attractions such as Grandfather
Mountain, the Blue Ridge Parkway, Watauga River white-water rafting
and Blowing Rock, where playful winds might return a hat tossed
from the 4,000-foot precipice.
</P>
<P>
   -- Getting there: From Asheville, N.C., go east on U.S. 25 and
I-26, then northeast on I-40, U.S. 221 and N.C. 105 to Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
