<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS &LR;      06-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS URGE CLINTON TO ADDRESS TOUGH ISSUES IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of President Clinton's trip to China, a
bipartisan group of lawmakers urged him Tuesday to speak out
against human rights abuses and religious persecution, warning that
he will end up ``on the wrong side of history'' if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., one of the harshest critics of
Clinton's China policy, warned that the president's planned visit
to the site of a bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators in
1989 will ``remove the shadow of Tiananmen Square from the
regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi held up a white two-foot statue of the ``Goddess of
Democracy,'' a replica of the statue that was torn down during the
Tiananmen Square massacre that left hundreds dead. She called on
the president to meet with political dissidents and families of
victims of the crackdown during his 10-day visit so he won't signal
his approval of the crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi claimed that Clinton is allowing the Chinese government
to control his visit and, as a result, ``he will miss his
opportunity to stand with the Chinese people in their fight for
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If this pattern continues throughout the president's trip, he
will be remembered for standing with China's authoritarian regime _
and will, indeed, find himself on the wrong side of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi and other critics of the administration's policy of
reaching out to China spoke at a news conference in an U.S. Senate
office building. The president departs Wednesday and returns to
Washington on July 3 after visiting five Chinese cities. On
Saturday, the president will participate in a welcoming ceremony on
the edge of Tiananmen Square in Beijing, the second Chinese city on
his itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., decried a decision by the Chinese
government to revoke the visas of three U.S. reporters who work for
Radio Free Asia who had planned to travel with Clinton this week.
Radio Free Asia, which is funded by the U.S. government, broadcasts
to China and has often outraged Beijing by reporting on human
rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson has proposed legislation that would deny travel visas
to Chinese officials involved in any religious persecution or
forced-abortion policies, end U.S.-backed loans to China and modify
U.S. policy on satellite exports.
</P>
<P>
   However, Senate leaders agreed to postpone consideration of any
legislation hostile to China until after Clinton's returns home.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., who said his own father fled
persecution from Russia, urged Clinton to call for the release of
people imprisoned because of religious practices.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone added: ``I am very worried that the symbolism of the
visit to Tiananmen Square will be so powerful it will validate the
government's efforts to suppress human rights there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J., told Clinton as he extends
the ``hand of friendship,'' to remember that ``friends don't let
friends murder and torture and imprison innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Clinton should speak ``forcefully and openly about
forced abortion and sterilization, organ harvesting from executed
prisoners, religious persecution, forced labor camps, and the
denial of freedom of speech, association and the press.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer, president of the conservative Family Research
Council, said in an interview that Clinton's visit ``will be
incredibly demoralizing to those people in China who have resisted
the attempts of the Chinese government to stamp out political and
religious liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Chinese political prisoner Harry Wu said Clinton's China
policy ``is based on commercial interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Wu said in an interview that pictures of Clinton at Tiananmen
Square will be interpreted by the Chinese as sending the message
that ``we are stable, we are in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Drew Liu, executive director of the China Strategic Institute, a
Washington think tank, said in an interview that the Chinese will
watch television broadcasts of Clinton's trip to read whether he
``cares for money, trade or for something else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be able to read very subtle messages as to whether
Clinton is showing whether he submits to the Chinese will,'' he
said, adding that the Chinese press has communicated that
``Americans care for money, not democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
