A3012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-23 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE MINISTER TRIES TO REASSURE MARKETS, BANK INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By SHERYL WuDUNN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's finance minister tried to calm the financial
markets Tuesday and avert a further selloff in the shares of a
large bank, as the government moved a step closer toward
establishing a system to help restructure failed banks.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's leaders are working out the details of what they're
calling the Total Plan to tackle $600 billion in bad and doubtful
loans infecting the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has taken on a special urgency because of reports that
Long-Term Credit Bank, one of Japan's biggest financial
institutions, is in trouble. The market has driven down its stock
down by more than 60 percent in the last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Credit is reportedly seeking a rescue merger to help
stabilize its business. The bank has denied the reports, as well as
accounts of merger discussions, but said Tuesday that it was
working on a restructuring plan.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's anemic banking system is considered an underlying cause
of the malaise that has afflicted the world's second-largest
economy, severely weakened the yen and stock market, and played a
role in the broader economic problems confronting much of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. delegation visited Tokyo last week to discuss Japan's
predicament after both countries took the unusual step of buying
yen and selling dollars to strengthen the Japanese currency. But
the yen has started to weaken again, and Tuesday the stock market
fell 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Government leaders, one after another, expressed assurances
Tuesday that Long-Term Credit's depositors, lenders and
counterparties in financial transactions would not suffer losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope depositors and investors feel assured about their
assets,'' said Finance Minister Hikaru Matsunaga.
</P>
<P>
   Long-Term Credit's stock price fell to a record low of 62 yen
Monday, from more than 200 just a couple of weeks ago. Tuesday, it
was the most heavily traded stock, closing at 71 yen, up 9 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto also tried to reassure
depositors and investors Tuesday that the government would maintain
financial stability. He said the government would take ``drastic
measures to resolve the bad loan problem and will completely
protect sound borrowers.''
</P>
<P>
   A high-level group of ministers and members of the dominant
Liberal Democratic Party on Tuesday approved an overall proposal
for the Total Plan, which will be submitted to a special
parliamentary session shortly after Upper House elections July 12.
The group also endorsed the idea of establishing a ``bridge bank,''
and will work out the details by July 2.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge bank would take over the assets and liabilities of
banks facing bankruptcy and have the ability to lend money, so that
the borrowers of failed banks would not be hurt. Critics say unless
the plan is properly structured, the bank could just keep expanding
if the number of bankrupt banks increased. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1839EDT &QL; 
