<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BC-MICROSOFT-0623-COX     06-23 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BC-MICROSOFT-0623-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT WINS COURT VICTORY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft Corp. scored gains Tuesday on both the
legal and legislative fronts, sending its stock to a record high.
</P>
<P>
   Even as a panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals here quashed an
injunction that barred Microsoft from forcing computer makers to
bundle its Internet browser with the Windows 95 operating system,
the software giant's allies on Capitol Hill launched a drive to
derail a broader Justice Department antitrust suit by denying it
extra funding.
</P>
<P>
   In a 2-1 decision, the appellate court found that U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson had ``erred procedurally'' last
December ``in entering a preliminary injunction without notice to
Microsoft and (had erred) substantively in its implicit
construction of the consent decree on which the preliminary
injunction rested.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also effectively fired Harvard University law
professor Lawrence Lessig, whom Jackson had brought in as a
``special master'' in the case to weigh technical issues. Microsoft
had claimed Lessig was biased and that he had been granted too much
power.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court said the appointment was ``either a clear
abuse of discretion or an exercise of wholly nonexistent
discretion.'' But it did not find Lessig to be biased.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Justice Department joined 20 state attorneys general
in mounting a much broader antitrust case against Microsoft, one
that charged the firm with abusing its near-monopoly power over
operating systems for personal computers to seek control of the
Internet and other markets.
</P>
<P>
   With that wider case set for trial Sept. 8, the judges wrote
that the government ``may well regard further pursuit of this case
as unpromising, especially given the alternative avenues developing
in its recently launched separate attacks on Microsoft's
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   In light of that admonition, the government must now decide
whether to appeal to the full appellate bench or directly to the
U.S. Supreme Court. ``We are disappointed with the Court of
Appeals' decision in the consent decree case,'' the department said
in a statement. ``We're reviewing the opinion to assess our
options.''
</P>
<P>
   At corporate headquartes in Redmond, Wash., Microsoft spokesman
Greg Shaw termed the judicial decision ``a great day for
consumers.'' He said it ``affirms the central principal Microsoft
has been defending, that every company should have the freedom to
improve its products and integrate new features on behalf of
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock surged on the good news, rising to a new record
level of $100.75 a share, thereby raising the value of co-founder
Bill Gates's holdings in the company to some $57 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft's friends in the Senate moved to deny the
antitrust division additional funds it had sought for its growing
case load.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., and Lauch Faircloth, R-N.C.,
succeeded Tuesday in getting a Senate appropriations subcommittee
to yank $9 million that had been requested by Justice Department
Antitrust Division chief Joel Klein _ on top of the $98.3 million
in the original Clinton administration budget.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, however, declined to include a Microsoft-backed rider
that urged Klein's staff ``to take special care to not make public
statements or release any evidence in its possession'' because such
``practices have the explicit effect of creating prejudicial
pretrial publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   Deletion of the funds will be tested again on Thursday when the
full Approprications Committee meets to consider the request.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the day that Microsoft will release Windows 98 for
general sale. As the successor operating system to Windows 95, the
new software integrates the browser even more deeply than the code
to which the government already objects.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
