<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: CELEBRATING BROOKLYN; HIGH CULTURE MEETS HARLEY
CULTURE; 35 MILLION TICKETS LATER; HONORING SHELLEY WINTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Music, dance, the spoken word and film are on the
menu as the performing arts festival called ``Celebrate Brooklyn!''
begins at 7:30 p.m. Thursday with a performance by the Cajun dance
band Beausoleil Avec Michael Doucet at the new Prospect Park Band
Shell, at Ninth Street and Prospect Park West. The 20th anniversary
season of ``Celebrate Brooklyn!'' which runs through Aug. 22,
continues on Friday with an evening of Eric Bogosian's monologues,
and on Saturday with the salsa of El Gran Combo de Puerto Rico.
Admission is free, although a $3 contribution is suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Vroom Service
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all who thrill at the look and lore of the
motorcycle, the place to be starting Friday is the Solomon
Guggenheim Museum on Fifth Avenue at 89th Street, where a new
exhibition called ``The Art of the Motorcycle'' opens for a run
through Sept. 20. During that time, in an installation designed by
the architect Frank Gehry, more than 100 motorcycles will be on
display in the Rotunda and Tower Galleries.
</P>
<P>
   The show, organized by Thomas Krens, director of the Guggenheim
Foundation, chronicles the evolution of motorcycle technology and
design and puts the motorcycle in a cultural and historical
context. The display ranges from the German-made Hildebrand &AMP;
Wolfmuller of 1894 to the high-concept motorcycles of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Square Deal
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Time doesn't always fly when you're waiting in line,
but it hardly seems that 25 years have passed since TKTS, the
Theater Development Fund's discount ticket booth, opened. Although
the booth in Duffy Square on Broadway at 47th Street began its
365-day-a-year operation on June 25, 1973, the anniversary party
has been scheduled not for Thursday but for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   John Lindsay was mayor when TKTS began, and after the sale of
nearly 35 million discounted tickets with revenue of $670 million
for thousands of Broadway and Off Broadway shows, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has proclaimed Saturday TKTS Day. For those in the ticket
line from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m., the celebration will feature
performers from shows like ``Chicago,'' ``Titanic'' and ``Forever
Tango,'' as well as a live band playing tunes from musicals and a
raffle of 250 free tickets.
</P>
<P>
   In Tribute
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shelley Winters will be honored for half a century on
screen when the Hollywood Film Festival gives her its Lifetime
Achievement Award on Aug. 10. Ms. Winters, who was strangled by
Ronald Colman in ``A Double Life'' (1948) and seduced by Montgomery
Clift in ``A Place in the Sun'' (1951), won Oscars for her
performances in supporting roles in ``The Diary of Anne Frank''
(1959) and ``A Patch of Blue'' (1965).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
