<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CHINA, CLINTON IS LIONIZED AS A GLOBAL VISIONARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., see related CHINA-PIRACY, CHINA-VISAS, CHINA-MEDIA,
CHINA-U.S.-ECON, CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-MISSILES.) 
(ps) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ At home, President Clinton's fortunes may wax and
wane, but here, on the eve of his first state visit to China, he is
being lionized as a great statesman who had the wisdom to change
his mind about China _ turning from his early attack stance to his
current policy of engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's great global vision, it seems, ranks him right up
there with that all-time great strategist, Richard Nixon, who will
ever be revered here for reviving ties between the United States
and China.
</P>
<P>
   The adulation of Clinton was evident on Tuesday afternoon at the
monthly salon of the XSH Book Club, in its headquarters in the
middle of a park in northwest Beijing. The directors of the club _
which markets books at a discount to its thousands of members
through catalogues and seminars like the one on Tuesday _ assembled
foreign policy experts and a few dozen Chinese journalists and book
lovers to discuss three major American titles recently published in
Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   The first was Clinton's ``Between Hope and History: Meeting
America's Challenges for the 21st Century'' (Random House, 1996), a
summary of his political philosophy written with William Nothdurft.
This month, the book went into its second printing in China after
the first several tens of thousands sold out. (``Not quite a
`Titanic','' said the book club editor, Xi Hong, ``but a consistent
top-seller over the last year.'')
</P>
<P>
   The second featured title, just published here this week after a
rush translation job, was Monica Crowley's new memoir, ``Nixon in
Winter'' (Random House, 1998). The third was Henry Kissinger's 1994
tome ``Diplomacy'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster), which appeared in Chinese
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever American critics may have made of the Clinton book and
Ms. Crowley's obsequious memoir of the former president who took
her under his wing in his final years, the assembled professors
here treated these works seriously, as offering insight into the
men who made today's emerging Chinese-American partnership
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Qian Wenrong, deputy director of the New China World Issues
Research Institute, noted that by the time Clinton published his
book, he had already made his momentous shift in China policy, and
recognized the leading role China will play in world affairs in the
next century. Back in the 1970s, Qian said, Nixon had presciently
seen how the world system was changing and China's inevitable rise.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Yizhou of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences called the
Nixon book excellent, a reminder of how far-sighted the man was.
Kissinger's book he declared a classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kissinger book is very deep,'' he said, ``but I like the
Clinton book better.''
</P>
<P>
   Jia Qingguo, a political scientist at Beijing University who
spent several years in the United States, was less taken with the
books per se, but noted that through Clinton's book, and his rags
to riches story, Chinese could better understand the American
Dream.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth scholar, Huang Annian, a historian at Beijing Normal
University, listed the three most important American presidents
from China's perspective. The first was Franklin Roosevelt, leader
during World War II, ``the most glorious period in Chinese-U.S.
relations'' as the countries fought together against fascism and
Japanese aggression.
</P>
<P>
   The second was Nixon, who set the process in motion that led to
normalized relations. And third was Clinton, who despite human
rights and other concerns has realized that the isolation of China
does not serve America's interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``These three men _ they all have strategic vision,'' Huang
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even greater praise has appeared in the official media.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton gave an interview to visiting Chinese journalists
last week, an article in the Economic Daily here said: ``The
40-minute interview was unforgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ``foresight, courage and insight deeply impressed the
Chinese correspondents,'' the article said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
