<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL:  
 AMEX MAY ADD TO AIRLINE-SEAT BULK PURCHASES  
 MORE MARKETS, FEWER CUSTOMERS  
 FLYING TO KUALA LUMPUR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Pa., Malaysia)   (Duplication warning: Also being filed in `t' category)  
(mk) 
 By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The planned bulk purchase of airline seats between the United
States and London may be only the first in a series of such deals
by American Express.
</P>
<P>
   The company is buying seats on Virgin Group's Virgin Atlantic
Airways flights from Continental Airlines, Virgin's partner, on
routes between London and New York, Los Angeles, Washington, San
Francisco and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Other similar arrangements are possible, ``with Continental and
with other airlines, as well as hotel companies,'' according to
Melissa Abernathy, a spokeswoman for American Express.
</P>
<P>
   No company the size of American Express has previously bought
tickets this way for resale to corporate customers, according to
Norman Sherlock, executive director of the National Business Travel
Association. He said he expected to see similar deals in the
future, adding, ``The problem is how much cash people have to do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all large corporate travel companies are rushing to jump on
the bandwagon. Travis Tanner, chief executive of the Carlson
Wagonlit travel agency chain based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., was
skeptical about bulk buying of airline seats. ``We haven't seen yet
where that creates any greater value,'' he said. Carlson Wagonlit
has so far preferred to contract for volume discounts without
purchasing the seats outright, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenbluth International, the corporate travel agency based in
Philadelphia, has been negotiating bulk purchases for clients for
about three years, with the clients putting up the money. However,
it turned down a bulk-purchase deal with Continental similar to
American Express', according to Patty McMenamin, a spokeswoman, who
said the company would be open to other offers.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party to the transaction between American Express and
Continental would disclose the number of seats or the amount of
money involved, though both said it was a multimillion-dollar deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Abernathy said the discount on the fares, estimated at 25 to
30 percent, was greater than what most of American Express'
corporate clients would be able to negotiate on their own.
</P>
<P>
   The seats, in both first class and coach, will be sold mostly as
fully refundable unrestricted tickets to American Express'
corporate clients, according to Ms. Abernathy, although she said
some might be made available to the company's retail travel agency
network for sale to individuals. The seats will be on flights over
the next year that match the preferences of the company's corporate
customers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked which airline might be a candidate for similar deals in
the future, Ms. Abernathy said, ``Any time an airline gets into a
new market or expands in a market, they have to put a lot of
resources into building their presence. That would be one place to
look for another opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case with Continental, which began code-sharing
with Virgin Atlantic in February and has been ``looking to broaden
awareness and availability of our new seats,'' said Dave Messing, a
Continental spokesman. The agreement between Continental and Virgin
Atlantic called for the airlines to buy seats on one another's
planes.
</P>
<P>
   Competition Report
</P>
<P>
   Though low-fare airlines served more markets around the country
last year than in 1996, fewer people had access to them, according
to a new study by the Department of Transportation. In 1997, 1,115
city pairs had ``competitive service'' _ defined as at least 10
percent of market share _ by carriers such as Southwest Airlines,
Tower Air, Vanguard Airlines and Airtran Airlines; in 1996 there
were 984. Yet the total number of passengers on those routes last
year was 120 million, down from 122.9 million in 1996. The reason
is that the low-fare carriers have been entering markets that are
traveled by 50 or fewer passengers a day, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, fares were lower in city pairs that had
competitive low-fare service, the department said. The differential
was greatest in short-haul markets. For example, average fares for
city pairs of between 251 and 500 miles without low-fare
competition were 121 percent higher than for those that did have
such competition. The study was part of the department's quarterly
report on domestic airline fares, covering the fourth quarter of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Another New Airport in Asia
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's new airport at Chek Lap Kok, set to open July 6, may
be getting all the attention, but Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, is also
getting a new international airport, scheduled to begin operating
June 30. It is situated near Sepang, about 35 miles south of the
city, on a 39-square-mile site that allows for future expansion. In
the first phase, the airport will be able to handle 25 million
passengers a year.
</P>
<P>
   The main terminal, measuring 2.6 million square feet, will be
connected by an automated shuttle train to a satellite building for
international passengers. Express rail service from the city is
expected to begin in late 1999 or early 2000. Taxi fare is about
$18 and travel time about 45 minutes, depending on traffic.
</P>
<P>
   A new Pan Pacific Hotel is set to open Thursday at the airport.
It is linked to the main terminal by a walkway. The 450 guest rooms
will have fax machines, modem jacks and two phone lines. An
auditorium will seat 200; a ballroom will seat up to 1,000, and 10
meeting rooms can accommodate up to 360. The hotel will also have a
business center, video teleconferencing facilities, a health club
and pool. Regular rates start at around $110 a night, but the hotel
is planning to offer a 50 percent discount for the first three
months.
</P>
</TEXT>
