<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Wednesday, June 24 and thereafter. If you have any questions,
please call Tina May at (206) 448-8355.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-RULING (Undated) A three-judge federal appeals court
ruled in favor of Microsoft Tuesday, throwing out a December
judge's order that barred the company from including its Internet
Explorer browser in Windows 95. The decision could make it harder
for the Justice Department and 20 states to win new, more sweeping
lawsuits filed in May. Those suits seek to force Microsoft to
remove its browsers from its new Windows 98 operating system
software, or offer a competing browser, such as Netscape
Communication Corp.'s Navigator. The 39-page appeals court decision
said Jackson exceeded his authority in issuing an injunction
against Microsoft. Microsoft stock shot up to nearly $100 a share.
</P>
<P>
   By Warren Wilson. (story will move in the ``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SURGERY-BLOODLESS (Seattle) Scientists at the University of
Washington and elsewhere are perfecting techniques that could one
day make bloodless``surgery'' possible using ultrasound waves,
without ever opening the body. Within a few years, doctors may be
able to use the technology to stop internal bleeding for patients
in remote locations, such as the mountains, or on the battlefield.
The ultrasound passes through the skin and other organs without
damaging them until it gets to the ``focal site'' where it heats
the tissue, cauterizing it. The technique is also already being
used in clinical trials to destroy tumors in the body without doing
incisions. The technology was the subject of talks here Tuesday at
the Acoustical Society of America Meeting, which has drawn
scientists from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (story will move in the ``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) Mariners vs. San Diego Padres at
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   By Jim Street. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-NBADRAFT (Undated) The NBA draft has only modest talent
available but the Sonics figure to take it more seriously than they
have in the past. They have three picks in the late first and early
second rounds.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-TECHNOLOGY (Undated) Are technology and equipment changing
golf? Many of the game's top stars, including legend Jack Nicklaus,
are concerned with the evolution of metal alloys, aerodynamic
designs and space-age technology in the equipment to the mechanics
of the swing itself. Nicklaus believes that ball development has
gone too far and should be restricted.
</P>
<P>
   By Angelo Bruscas. (story will move in the ``s'' category)
</P>
</TEXT>
