<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-AGENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIS REGISTERS AS PAKISTANI AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lanny Davis, the former White House special counsel
and presidential spokesman on campaign-finance matters, this week
registered as a foreign agent for the government of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   As reported by The Boston Globe last week, Davis began his work
for the Islamabad government shortly after leaving his White House
post in February. Davis, however, said he was not required to
register immediately as a foreign agent. Davis registered Monday
and distributed a copy of the registration to the news media
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Davis's work comes at a time when White House officials are
making decisions about the relationship between the United States
and Pakistan. Pakistan and India recently conducted nuclear tests,
much to the dismay of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials who earn more than $110,000 a year are
prohibited after leaving from engaging immediately in lobbying
activities. Davis said he earned $100,000. He is now employed by
the Washington law firm of Patton Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has said he was not trading on his work at the White
House, which mostly involved responding to allegations that Clinton
had evaded campaign-inance laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
