<SLUG> BC-HISPANICS-DIABETES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIABETES ADS AIMED AT HISPANICS, OTHER MINORITIES, ARE LAUNCHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two U.S. health agencies launched a nationwide
campaign Tuesday alerting the 16 million Americans with diabetes,
including 1.2 million Hispanics, to the dangers of the disease,
which can lead to blindness, amputations, kidney failure, heart
trouble and death.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institutes of Health (NIH) and the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), in announcing their National
Diabetes Education Program, urged all Americans with the disease to
control their blood-sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics and African Americans ``are on average almost twice as
likely to have diabetes as non-Hispanic whites of similar age,''
said Dr. Richard Eastman, director of the Division of Diabetes,
Endocrinology and Metabolic Diseases at NIH.
</P>
<P>
   In a videotaped statement, U.S. Surgeon General David Satcher
said that minorities ``experience higher rates of eye disease,
kidney disease, amputations and premature deaths'' because their
ailments often are untreated or inadequately treated.
</P>
<P>
   NIH and CDC released two public service ads Tuesday, one in
Spanish and English and one in English alone, that are being
broadcast on TV and radio and run in print media around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The ad aimed at Latinos shows an elderly Hispanic man who says,
``There are good days and bad days, but that's life. Having
diabetes has made me appreciate all of them. I realize the way I
feel depends entirely on the way I treat myself. There are many
things in life that can't be controlled. Fortunately, diabetes
isn't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad in English alone shows people of many ethnic backgrounds
with diabetes. One says, ``I know it can lead to more serious
health problems.'' Another says, ``I know my blood-sugar numbers.''
A third says, ``I'm in charge of what I eat.'' And a fourth says,
``I get regular exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Ads aimed at minorities other than Hispanics will be released
over the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   Satcher said the campaign is a part of President Clinton's
initiative on race and is designed to ``eventually eliminate
disparities'' in the rates that different ethnic groups contract
the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes is a disorder in which the body is unable to properly
process sugar. It is usually caused by a defective pancreas, which
is unable to produce the right amount of insulin, a hormone that
metabolizes sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Rowley, associate director for science at the CDC, said,
``Diabetes is serious, it's common, it's costly and it's
controllable.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's campaign seeks to reach undiagnosed diabetics
through the ads as well as information provided to physicians
around the country, said an official of the diabetes education
program.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Elizabeth Furse, D-Ore., co-chair of the Congressional
Diabetes Caucus said federal funding for diabetes should be
increased. She noted that the proposed budget for the disease for
fiscal 1999, which begins Oct. 1, is $415 million, up from the
current $373 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
