</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN TELLS PARLIAMENT TO APPROVE `ANTI-CRISIS' PLAN OR ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin on Tuesday summoned Russian
legislators to an unusual public meeting and demanded that they
enact a rash of measures to restore the confidence of foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary session was intended to impress the
International Monetary Fund, which is beginning negotiations over
billions of dollars in additional financing.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not just a matter of political theater. Yeltsin
presented an ``anti-crisis'' plan to overhaul the tax system,
lay-off civil servants and slash government spending.
</P>
<P>
   Raising the specter of a fresh confrontation, Yeltsin insisted
that the Legislature approve the plan before it breaks for its
summer recess on July 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the package of bills in the government is not approved,''
Yeltsin warned ominously ``other measures will be taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's threat to impose the measures by decree drew protests
from the Communist-opposition in the parliament, or Duma, as it is
called here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin performed his usual repertoire,'' said Gennady
Zyuganov, the Communist leader. ``He opened the meeting, started
threatening the Duma, was rude, insulted us and then left.''
</P>
<P>
   The steps proposed Tuesday were designed to placate the IMF,
which has demanded that the Kremlin meet a series of tough demands
to qualify for billions of dollars in additional loans.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley Fischer, deputy chairman of the IMF, has come to Moscow
for talks with top Russian officials, along with other Fund
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's plan addressed two of the IMF's concerns _ reforming
Russia's antiquated tax code and slashing its budget deficit. But
it was silent on the IMF's insistence that the government break up
Gazprom, the huge natural gas monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Chubais, who is representing the Russians in talks with
the IMF, said he expected the negotiations to take one or two
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall amount of the package should be in the range of
$10 billion to $15 billion,'' Chubais reiterated Tuesday. ``It is
too early to say what the share of the IMF will be in this.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's meeting took place in the White House, a mammoth
marble structure. Yeltsin ordered Russian tanks to pound the
building in 1993 when it was occupied by rebellious members of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But these days the White House is the administrative center for
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko and other top Yeltsin aides.
</P>
<P>
   Angry coal miners have set up a small squatters' camp outside to
protest months of waiting for their wages. They demonstrated as
black Mercedes, BMWs and Volga sedans with flashing blue lights
ferried legislators and Kremlin aides to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the well-appointed hall, the meeting was dominated by
Kiriyenko, who provided a catalog of the economy's ills. Reporters
watched from the balcony and Russian television broadcast
highlights of the session.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko noted that the flight of investors from emerging
markets and the decline in world oil prices had taken a heavy toll.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of putting all the blame on external factors or
nameless speculators, he acknowledged that the failure to impose
budget discipline and follow through on reform had made Russia
especially vulnerable to the global economic turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko described an economy that is groaning under a mountain
of short-term debt. Russia has been forced to sell treasury bills
at high interest rates to finance its budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's short-term debt is being redeemed at a rate of 31
billion rubles ($5 billion) a month, 1.4 times the federal
government's monthly revenue, Kiriyenko explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means that we are forced to borrow again in order to pay
back old debts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding more like a conservative American Republican than a
former member of the Communist youth league, Kiriyenko called for
easing corporate taxes and introducing a flat tax on income.
</P>
<P>
   To cope with the deficit, the government has already called for
spending cuts totaling 42 billion rubles, or $6.8 billion. To
encourage investment in Russian enterprises, the government is
trying to drive down interest rates substantially, to about 20
percent to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Much will depend on the parliament, which has been suspicious of
the IMF and shown little understanding of monetary policy. But
there is a palpable sense that Russia is in the midst of a genuine
crisis. That may help the Kremlin and the Legislature transcend
partisan posturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we are confronted with the result of our indecisiveness
in carrying out reforms,'' Kiriyenko said. ``Russia's problems lie
not in Asia, but in Russia itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
