<HEADER>
A3088 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-BOOKS-ANTIQUES     06-23 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-BOOKS-ANTIQUES-ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CENTURIES, THE GARDEN PATH HAS LED TO ADVENTURE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In addition to providing intellectual and visual
pleasure, art exhibitions can engage the imagination the way
adventures do. ``Verdant Riches Revealed: A Selection From the
Treasures of the LuEsther T. Mertz Library at the New York
Botanical Garden,'' offers a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the 80 illustrated books, neatly arranged in
showcases at the Grolier Club in Manhattan, are a fine collection,
featuring botanical prints and early garden designs. But to proceed
along the exhibits slowly, reading the informative captions, is
like traveling, first to a medical school in Salerno in 1190, on to
the cargo hold of Captain Bligh's Bounty in 1792 and, eventually,
to the landscape at the Royal Pavilion at Brighton in 1808.
</P>
<P>
   The fascinating story of plants and their uses is marked by
scientific discoveries, sea voyages to explore distant countries,
commercial development, preservation in botanical gardens, and
finally the great wealth and intrigue that surrounded the
establishment of princely gardens. Rarely have plants appeared so
interesting as they do in this selection from the 250,000 volumes
in the New York Botanical Garden's Library, one of the premier
collections of books on botany, horticulture and garden design in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   This exhibit, which runs through July 31, is occasioned by the
recent gift to the botanical garden of 400 rare books and prints on
the history of garden design donated by Elizabeth K. Reilley, a
90-year-old Long Island librarian and book collector.
</P>
<P>
   The show has also been arranged in part to celebrate the new
library building, now under construction, supported by a $6 million
grant from the LuEsther T. Mertz Charitable Trust. Although Mrs.
Mertz was a generous cultural benefactor of New York City (notably
the New York Shakespeare Festival), it is not generally known that
she was a trained librarian, and passionate about her own garden
and botanical science.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition turns on an important art historical footnote. It
was the introduction of the woodblock print in the 15th century
that made possible the use of illustrations to disseminate
scientific information. Previously, books were illustrated by hand
illumination with idealized versions of flowers and leaves; a 1483
edition of Pliny the Elder's ``History of Nature'' is an example on
view.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit also demonstrates that botanical researchers
centuries ago were exploring the same questions that their
counterparts are today: the medicinal uses of plants, for example.
Matthaeus Palterius, the physician who taught at Salerno, kept his
list of plant nomenclature by hand, while Konrad von Megenberg's
``Book of Nature,'' printed in Augsburg in 1475, is credited with
publishing the first botanical prints for scientific rather than
ornamental purposes.
</P>
<P>
   As artists drew plants in increasingly realistic detail, books
about them, called herbals, became more authoritative, and
researchers' lists of plant terminology turned into early systems
of codification. Carolus Linnaeus' ``Species Plantarum,'' a
classification of 8,000 plants published in Stockholm in 1753, was
the culmination of those efforts and is a high point of the show.
</P>
<P>
   While the Linnaean system remains the most prevalent method of
categorizing plants, scientists are now developing a new
classification based on DNA studies. The computer printouts it
yields will never, however, compete with the sumptuous botanical
prints on view.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the 16th century, explorers took to the seas to
gather plant specimens from around the world. The French friar
Charles Plumier produced 6,000 botanical drawings, like the passion
flower in the show, from his travels to the Caribbean; Linnaeus
later used them in his work. The Englishman William Bartram's
exploratory visit to the American South is represented by his
illustration of a Seminole chief who was his protector during a
sojourn in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Plants from distant lands were also being exploited for
commercial purposes, like the breadfruit seedlings that were
shipped from Tahiti to Jamaica to feed the slaves. One drawing
shows how the Bounty was outfitted with brackets for a thousand
potted plants. The ill-fated voyage ended with the breadfruit being
dumped overboard during the mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The show also chronicles the evolution of garden design. ``The
Profitable Arte of Gardening,'' by Thomas Hill, from 1593,
contained the first woodcut of a garden published in England. A
trellised fence encloses patterned beds, and water was supplied by
a well on the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   Such simplified drawings were later replaced by detailed
depictions of gardens, complete with strolling courtiers, by
artists like Israel Silvestre at Versailles. (Elizabeth S. Eustis,
one of the show's curators, noted that Louis XIV's chief minister,
Jean Baptiste Colbert, regarded garden prints as a way to spread
the king's influence throughout Europe.)
</P>
<P>
   A print of a design for a cascade, with 600 levels, near Kassel,
Germany, is an example of extravagant garden style. The nobleman
Karl of Hesse began the project around 1700 but never completed it.
</P>
<P>
   The word horticulture, one learns, was first used in 1632 as the
title of a book by a German professor, Peter Lauremberg, who
presented etched designs for topiary shapes. And the magnolia,
illustrated in the show by one drawn in the Chelsea Physic Garden
in London in 1743, was named for the French botanist Pierre Magnol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
