<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-WORLD-ITALY-BOS &LR;      06-23 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLD-ITALY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY, UNDER MALDINI'S INSTINCTS, CONQUERS AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAINT-DENIS, France _ ``Caesar, reconquer Gaul,'' the
hand-painted sign said in Italian in the upper decks of the Stade
de France, an ultra-modern Caesar's Palace, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cesare Maldini moved a step closer to capturing France '98 by
guiding Italy to a 2-1 victory over Austria. At least, Maldini has
reconquered the hearts of Italians, deluded after six years of the
reign of Arrigo Sacchi, who many considered too arrogant to deserve
their approval.
</P>
<P>
   Maldini apparently has what might be luck, or just good coaching
instincts, and certainly a comfortable rapport with the fans,
media, and players.
</P>
<P>
   He has had the good sense to integrate the fantasy of both
Roberto Baggio and Alessandro Del Piero, to rejuvenate the team
with exciting performers such as Luigi Di Biagio and Francesco
Moriero, and the self-assurance to recall Giuseppe Bergomi.
</P>
<P>
   Each of those players had a major role in the victory which
clinched first place in Group B and set up a second-round meeting
with Norway in Marseille Saturday. Del Piero's free kick was headed
in by Christian Vieri four minutes into the second half, and Baggio
combined with Filippo Inzaghi for a 2-0 lead in the 89th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas Herzog, a reserve who is considered Austria's best
player, scored a 92d-minute penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to talk about one player,'' Maldini said.
``When you have good players, they have to play. And when you have
good players, you can win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maldini has been wise enough to find the right combination
of players. He appeared to have an unreasonable predilection for
Vieri in qualifying, but his faith has paid off as Vieri has scored
four goals, tied for the tournament lead with Gabriel Batistuta of
Argentina. And Maldini has complemented Vieri's strength with the
creative subtlety of Baggio and Del Piero.
</P>
<P>
   Del Piero, making his first World Cup start, displayed flashes
of brilliance in the first half but was treated roughly by the
Austrians. The Austrians required a victory to advance, but seldom
seemed threatening in attack.
</P>
<P>
   Italy played conservatively, yet still had more quality
opportunities as Del Piero constantly threatened. Vieri finally
scored with a header as Bergomi moved into the goal area and
goalkeeper Michael Konsel collided with Anton Polster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I've surprised anyone,'' Vieri said. ``I'm a
forward and I am supposed to score goals. I'm happy with the four
goals I have scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Inzaghi replaced Vieri early in the second half and Baggio
entered for Del Piero midway through. They combined with Moriero on
effective counterattacks, and Baggio dribbled past three defenders
and Konsel to nearly score a third goal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Austria seemed in as much disarray as it was in 1990,
when it was eliminated in the first round, then lost to the Faroe
Islands in European Championships qualifying. Polster, the
Austrians' leading scorer, departed in the 62d minute and headed
straight past coach Herbert Prohaska to the lockerroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed the coach took me out, I don't understand
the decision,'' Polster said.
</P>
<P>
   Maldini, though, seems in command of the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sacchi, Maldini has the lasting respect of both players
and TIFOSI because he was a highly-regarded player in the 1960s. He
also has an empathetic feel for the current national team members
because he coached some of them on the junior level, and through
his son, Paolo, who is the team captain.
</P>
<P>
   His master stroke might have been to bring back Bergomi, the
34-year-old defender nicknamed ``Zio'' (``The Uncle'') who played
in Spain in 1982, the last time Italy won the World Cup. Bergomi
replaced Alessandro Nesta, who departed with tournament-ending knee
injury in the fourth minute, and performed more like a lively young
``Nipote'' (``Nephew'').
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't words to describe a player like Zio,'' Paolo
Maldini said. ``He is incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
