<HEADLINE>
MOCK DRAFT 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. LA Clippers: Michael Olowokandi, C, Pacific. Too valuable to
pass up.
</P>
<P>
   2. Vancouver: Paul Pierce, G-F, Kansas. Solves one glaring need.
</P>
<P>
   3. Denver: Mike Bibby, G, Arizona. Best point guard in the
draft.
</P>
<P>
   4. Toronto: Raef LaFrentz, Kansas. Solid player for a team in
need of solid players.
</P>
<P>
   5. Golden State: Antawn Jamison, F, North Carolina. Dynamic
player and even better person for team needing both.
</P>
<P>
   6. Dallas: Larry Hughes, G, St. Louis. Backcourt scorer to go
with Michael Finley.
</P>
<P>
   7. Sacramento: Vince Carter, G, North Carolina. Kings jump at
this guy as the heir apparent to Mitch Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   8. Philadelphia: Robert Traylor, F, Michigan. Derrick Coleman
wants to stay, knowing he has an eating companion.
</P>
<P>
   9. Milwaukee: Michael Doleac, C, Utah. Bucks need size in the
middle. He's the best center on the board.
</P>
<P>
   10. Boston: Pat Garrity, F, Notre Dame. OK, he's not Michael
Johnson. But Rick Pitino wants character and scoring, and Garrity
has both.
</P>
<P>
   11. Detroit: Nazr Mohammed, F-C, Kentucky. He can block shots
and play the post, two rarities in Motown.
</P>
<P>
   12. Orlando: Dirk Nowitzki, F-C, DJK Wurzberg. A possible steal
if Magic can get him to forsake Italy. Could also go to Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   13. Orlando: Jason Williams, G, Florida. Talented point guard
with a blemished record.
</P>
<P>
   14. Houston: Michael Dickerson, G, Arizona. The rebuilding
starts here and now.
</P>
<P>
   15. Orlando: Bonzi Wells, G, Ball State. Best shooting guard on
the board.
</P>
<P>
   16. Houston: Radoslav Nesterovic, C, Kinder Bologna. Hakeem
isn't getting any younger.
</P>
<P>
   17. Minnesota: Keon Clark, C-F, UNLV. The latest in a long line
of All-Star Timberwolves centers.
</P>
<P>
   18. Houston: Rashard Lewis, F, Alief Elsik High, Texas. Local
prospect groomed by Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   19. Milwaukee: Bryce Drew, G, Valparaiso. Good shooter and
Terrell Brandon insurance.
</P>
<P>
   20. Atlanta: Ruben Patterson, F, Cincinnati. Best available
Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   21. Charlotte: Casey Shaw, C, Toledo. Best American center
available, such as it is.
</P>
<P>
   22. LA Clippers: Al Harrington, St. Patrick's (N.J.) High. Why
not? He can be the Clips' Kobe.
</P>
<P>
   23. Denver: Tyronn Lue, G, Nebraska. Best point guard available
on a team that needs everything.
</P>
<P>
   24. San Antonio: Matt Harpring, F, Georgia Tech. Could help
Spurs' anemic outside game.
</P>
<P>
   25. Indiana: Corey Benjamin, G, Oregon State. It's all about the
Benjamins at this point.
</P>
<P>
   26. LA Lakers: Brian Skinner, F, Baylor. Jerry West hopes he has
another late bloomer.
</P>
<P>
   27. Seattle: Ricky Davis, G, Iowa. Young, spirited talent who
fits in well with Sonics' style.
</P>
<P>
   28. Chicago: Simon Dwight, F, Australia. Another Jerry Krause
specialty.
</P>
<P>
   29. Utah: Mirsad Turkcan, F, Efies Pilsen (Turkey). Good choice
here for a team that looks to remain intact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
