<HEADER>
A3109 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAIRY-COMPACT-BOS &LR;      06-23 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAIRY-COMPACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWEST CHALLENGE TO DAIRY COMPACT FAILS IN HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS BLACK  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The dairy compact that sets milk prices in New
England withstood a House challenge Tuesday from Midwest dairy
interests.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture appropriations bill being considered by the
House contains a provision that would extend for six months the
Northeast Interstate Dairy Compact, which is scheduled to expire
April 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The extension would keep the compact through Sept. 30 next year,
the end of the fiscal year and the deadline for introduction of a
new federal milk pricing system.
</P>
<P>
   Two Wisconsin lawmakers, Representative Tom Petri, a Republican,
and David Obey, a Democrat, attempted to eliminate the extension
with separate amendments. Petri's amendment was struck down on a
parliamentary motion, and Obey's was defeated by voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am delighted we were able to defeat this effort,'' said
Representative Bernard Sanders, a Vermont independent. ``It is a
sad state of affairs that we are fighting each other when we should
be working together. ... There should be a commitment to preserving
family farms all across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The extension measure stirred regional rivalries, with New
Englanders rallying behind the plan and Midwesterners lining up
against it, regardless of party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat, broke the
regional unity to oppose the compact, which he said violates
free-market principles. During Tuesday's debate, he said Sanders,
the former Socialist mayor of Burlington, was being consistent with
his position, but Republican supporters were at odds with the GOP's
traditional support for unregulated markets.
</P>
<P>
   The compact sets milk prices in the six-state region at a level
slightly higher than the rate set by the federal government.
Supporters of the compact say it helps to preserve regional dairy
farmers, open space and fresher milk for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say it hurts consumers in New England by raising the
price of milk and dairy interests in other parts of the country by
blocking them from the market. National dairy firms have been
financing a lobbying campaign to block regional cartels that could
undermine national pricing policies. Southern states are
considering establishing a similar compact.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department regulates the price of milk for
different sections of the country. Under the current system, the
price of milk in the Midwest, a major dairy area, is the nation's
lowest, a sore point for Midwestern dairy interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
