<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.H. COURT DECLARES SCHOOL FUNDING PLAN UNCONSTITUTIONAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ The New Hampshire Supreme Court Tuesday
unanimously ruled that Governor Jeanne Shaheen's plan to fund
public schools is unconstitutional, finding that her plan to rely
on a package of sin taxes failed to equalize tax rates between
wealthy and poor towns in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The court gave the governor and Legislature until April 1999 to
come up with another solution. Its advisory opinion Tuesday raised
the specter that New Hampshire might have to give up its status as
the only state never to have enacted a broad-based sales or income
tax.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen had crafted her plan, known as Advancing Better
Classrooms (ABC), in response to the court's December finding that
the state's reliance on local property taxes to fund public schools
has resulted in unconstitutional disparities in tax rates and
educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan avoids a property tax system that transfers wealth from
rich towns to poor ones. It calls for using increased state revenue
from taxes on cigarettes and video poker gambling to provide state
aid and tax relief to poor towns.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen argued that this approach would avoid social and
economic unrest. But the court rejected that argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``That all three branches of government must struggle with
difficult decisions which may cause social unrest cannot be a
factor in the court's constitutional review of the bill,'' the
judges wrote in Tuesday's ruling. ``It should not be forgotten that
New Hampshire is not a random collection of isolated cities and
towns. Indeed, all of us live in a single state. The benefits of
adequately educated children are shared statewide and are not
limited to a particular town or district.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say it was no surprise that the court found her plan
flawed since it leaves rich towns paying tax rates that are in some
cases 15 times lower than rates in poor towns. The education
property tax rate in towns with no children in public schools would
be zero under Shaheen's plan, a few dollars per $1,000 valuation in
towns with power plants or shopping malls, and up to $15 in
property-poor communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Read as a whole, the Supreme Court opinion makes very clear
that the taxing scheme of the ABC plan is not only unconstitutional
but akin to some of the oppressive tax policies of the British
Crown in the 1770s,'' said Thomas Connair, a former school board
member from the property-poor town of Claremont and one of the
lawyers who brought the initial 1993 school funding suit that led
to the court ruling in December.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Shaheen's plan also said any further support for
her plan in the wake of the ruling would simply be a stall to avoid
controversy until after the November election. Shaheen is running
for reelection this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeanne Shaheen's lack of leadership on this issue has put us
back to square one,'' said Republican gubernatorial candidate Fred
Bramante. Bramante is making his third attempt to sell the
Legislature and voters on a statewide property tax that would
equalize education funding.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, however, seemed non-plussed by the ruling and
interpreted it as a request to provide the court with more
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased that the court's advisory opinion clearly and
unequivocally states that abatements (like those already granted
veterans and the elderly) and exemptions are constitutional,''
Shaheen said. ``I think it gives us an opportunity to continue to
provide a solution through the ABC plan.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Shaheen said her administration may hire economists to help
convince the court that the abatements requested for entire
communities under her plan are likewise justified because they
would prevent economic warfare between rich and poor towns.
</P>
<P>
   The state's legislative leaders, Senate President Joseph
Delahunty and House Speaker Donna Sytek, both found Shaheen's
optimism unfounded. They agreed that the most likely scenario calls
for holding a special legislative session in September to cope with
the dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``I have to say that I disagree with the governor when she
characterizes it as an opportunity. I view it as an obstacle,''
Sytek said of the opinion. ``It appears less and less likely that
we will be able to fix this in the remaining days of the
Legislature,'' which adjourns June 30 until December.
</P>
<P>
   State Senator Jim Rubens, another Republican candidate for
governor, also lost in court Tuesday. The judges found his modest
state aid plan, which would have left most of the current tax
system in place, also unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen and the Republicans running against her in the fall
agree on one thing. New Hampshire voters do not want an income or
sales tax, and none of the candidates want to become the elected
officials who give voters one.
</P>
<P>
   Rubens said the court's action will only increase support for a
constitutional amendment that would strip the court of power over
school issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruling is nothing more than an order for a broad base tax
in this state,'' said Rubens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
