<P>
   AIDS-REPORT (Geneva) _ AIDS infection rates worldwide are far
worse than previously believed, particularly in parts of Africa
where as many as one in four adults has the virus, according to a
U.N. report. By Lawrence K. Altman. With graphic. 1,700 words.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CLINTON (Beijing) _ At home, President Clinton's fortunes
may wax and wane, but here, on the eve of his first state visit to
China, he is already a star. Not only in the official press but
also among elements of the intelligentsia, he is being lionized as
a great statesman who had the wisdom to change his mind about China
_ turning from his early attack stance to his current policy of
engagement. Clinton's great global vision, it seems, ranks him
right up there with that all-time great strategist, Richard Nixon,
who will ever be revered here for reviving ties between the United
States and China. By Erik Eckholm. (The story has moved)
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-ALBANIANS (Klina, Serbia) _ The gong of church bells
summoned the Serbs up to the weed-choked cemetery with its ancient
stone crosses, marble tombs etched with the faces of the departed,
crooked iron gates and gnarled trees. During the tolling, the open
coffin of Oliver Zaic, 17, his face waxy with the pallor of death,
was carried through the dusty streets, lifted through a hole in the
cemetery fence and borne up the steep hill. He was killed in his
garden, his family said, as he tried to protect his widowed mother
and 10-year-old sister Marica from ethnic Albanian rebels who in
recent days have begun to attack and kidnap Serbian civilians in an
apparent effort to drive them out of their villages in the
overwhelmingly Albanian province of Kosovo. By Chris Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-MISSILES (Washington) _ A Clinton administration official
told lawmakers scrutinizing the possible transfer of missile
technology to China today that the Justice Department is
investigating a second incident in which a satellite company shared
information with the Chinese without prior authorization. By Eric
Schmitt. (Eds.: this is an early summary from wires)
</P>
<P>
   HOG-fACTORIES (Lennox, S.D.) _ The rapid growth of big hog
factories has emerged as perhaps the most contentious issue in the
nation's countryside. Besides driving out small farmers, these
plants with thousands of hogs crowded in small pens _ a practice
known as confinement _ create an almost unbearable stench for
nearby small towns and can threaten groundwater. About a dozen
states are debating laws to curb the big hog plants, including a
South Dakota initiative on the fall ballot that would effectively
outlaw corporate livestock production. By Dirk Johnson. With
graphic. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-TAX-BREAK (Washington) _ How an obscure tax break for
wealthy heirs got into law by mistake and why Congress is expected
to sidestep a chance to repeal it. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   With: CONGRESS-IRS (Washington) _ Republican leaders appear
likely to cut the holding period for investors to get favorable
capital gains tax rates by pushing the measure onto a bipartisan
bill overhauling the IRS. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
