<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-14UP-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY CARRIES ON WITH LIVES OF KIDS, NOW 14 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a photo for use with this story is being sent to NYT
photo clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lucy, voluble as always, is at boarding school these
days; the pressure to become a Princetonian seems irresistible.
Alexis is pretty serious about becoming a marine biologist. And
Luis, no longer homeless but charismatic as ever, has left the
Latin Kings gang in Milwaukee but will soon star as a gang member
onstage in a Victory Memorial Church production.
</P>
<P>
   They are seven years older now, and they're back. That
demographically correct band who became America's darlings in 1991
has returned in a second installment of the documentary series that
is following the lives of 16 children from age 7 through adulthood.
It will be broadcast for 90 minutes as ``14 Up in America'' on
Sunday night on Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series has no beginning, middle or end,'' said Phil
Joanou, the director. ``I like that the project lacks inherent
dramatic structure. It's just life. The drama is in how all these
lives will turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   The American series is based, of course, on the groundbreaking
British documentary that has tracked 14 English children for the
last 35 years as they have segued through school, college, jobs,
marriage, children, success, failure, euphoria and agita.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``a unique longitudinal, psychological and social history
that defies broad definition,'' said the executive producer of the
series, Michael Apted, the English filmmaker who, in 1964, produced
the first of the highly praised ``7 Up'' documentaries.
</P>
<P>
   The documentaries have proliferated across the globe: After the
American version was filmed in 1990, Apted set loose a Russian
documentary crew that filmed 7-year-olds in Russia. That team has
just completed its own version of ``14 Up.'' Subsequently, versions
of ``7 Up'' were started in South Africa, Japan and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Apted, gray-haired, tweedy and avuncular at 57, first filmed his
group of English youngsters when they were 7 and he was 22, then
visited them again when they were 14, 21, 28 and 35. The newest
installment, ``42 Up,'' will be broadcast on the BBC next month.
</P>
<P>
   The series is ``a mix of instant history, sociology and soap
opera,'' Apted said. ``It's either a great Victorian novel, or a
fascinating invasion of people's privacy. It depends on how you
look at it.'' The American version is following the master script.
Joanou interviewed more than 20 7-year-old boys and girls from
disparate ethnic, racial, economic and social backgrounds in New
York, Chicago, Los Angeles, Lincoln, Neb., and Dublin, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the children had well-off parents; six were poor,
including one, Luis, from a homeless family; the rest had
middle-class backgrounds. The group includes children who are
Asian, black, Hispanic and white.
</P>
<P>
   In ``7 Up,'' three Manhattan second graders, Lucy, Alexis and
Kate, were filmed in the elite precincts of the Nightingale-Bamford
School in Manhattan. They wore pressed uniforms and crisp white
blouses.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lucy and Alexis _ who, like the other subjects of ``14
Up,'' are identified only by first names in the documentary and who
spoke on the condition that their last names not be published _
were being casual at Sofia, a Madison Avenue pizza hangout in the
independent-school zone on the Upper East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   They have become minor celebrities not only in their schools but
also as far away as Paris, ``where someone came up to me and said,
`I've seen you on TV,''' Lucy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kate, who couldn't get to Sofia but was interviewed later, said,
``A baby sitter I hadn't seen in years called me when she saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis said, ``When the film comes out, it's sort of a home
video, but it's played for the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy shook her head and said: ``I see what a spoiled brat I was
at age 7. I kept babbling on, and wouldn't let anyone speak.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls lost touch with one another as they changed schools
through the years. ``When I entered the interview room, it was
weird to see Lucy and Alexis again,'' said Kate, 15. ``At first I
was expecting them to be 7.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth grade Alexis transferred to the Chapin School in
Manhattan, which she termed ``intensely competitive.'' Lucy and her
parents moved to Long Island, and in the 10th grade she began
attending Lawrenceville, the New Jersey boarding school, where she
skipped a grade. ``Lawrenceville is totally pro-Princeton, so of
course I want to go there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kate's parents divorced a year ago, and she, her mother and two
sisters have moved to Westchester County. Currently Kate, who
volunteered in a Manhattan women's shelter when she was 7, is
interested in being a social worker.
</P>
<P>
   For Luis, ``right now the church is my life,'' he said. He was
originally filmed in Manhattan in Public School 97 on East Houston
Street, when he was attending school there while his family lived
in a shelter on the Lower East Side. At 7 he had huge, canny eyes
and streetwise indomitability; these days he is a rangy ninth
grader, a running back on his Milwaukee high school football team,
the South Division Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   His current ambition ``is to be the pastor of a church,'' said
Luis, who prefers being called Tony these days. He said of the
documentary series: ``It's nice to feel like a movie star for a
while. When you're in the ghetto, you're not paid too much
attention, and when they did this video, it said they actually
cared.''
</P>
<P>
   Apted said the original, British ``7 Up'' in 1964 ``was an
accident, a one-shot.'' Its immense popularity gave him ``the idea
to go back at seven-year intervals,'' said Apted, who has directed
feature films ranging from ``Coal Miner's Daughter'' (1980), with
Sissy Spacek, and ``Gorillas in the Mist'' (1988), with Sigourney
Weaver, to ``Nell'' (1994), with Jodie Foster, and ``Extreme
Measures'' (1996), with Gene Hackman.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The film that recommended Joanou to Apted was the documentary
``U2: Rattle and Hum'' (1988). Joanou (whose name is pronounced
joe-ON-oh) was the director of ``State of Grace'' (1990), with Sean
Penn; ``Final Analysis'' (1992), with Richard Gere, and ``Heaven's
Prisoners'' (1996), with Alec Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   The American series is ultimately intended for theatrical
release in 2012, when its subjects are 28, following the pattern of
the English series. Until then, an installment is to appear every
seven years as a television special.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am struck with how savvy and worldly-wise the American
14-year-olds are,'' Apted said. ``My English children were a bit
more innocent.''
</P>
<P>
   The original English series has focused on the disparities of
the English class system, as played out in the children's lives.
Joanou said his subjects ``are not as class-bound as the English,
or at least not as aware of class boundaries.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``They see themselves as equal. In our country there
are strong economic boundaries to opportunity, but the kids don't
see them. That's positive for them, but it's also disturbing for
the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   To a reporter who interviewed the ``Up'' youngsters when they
were 7, it is clear that their lives have been transformed by fate
and the meander of time. But their personalities seem fixed _
blurred pictures that are slowly developing before the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their lives are unpredictable, but I'm inclined to think that
their core personality doesn't change,'' Apted said.
</P>
<P>
   To Joanou, ``it is the most important project in my life,'' he
said. ``There is nothing else like it for a documentarian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impossible not to reflect on where you were seven years
ago,''he said. ``Then, the kids were waist high, and now they're
taller than me. I'm 36. Now I have gray hairs, and a little less on
top.''
</P>
<P>
   For Apted, the project is equally consuming. ``Without being
nauseating about it, they are very much like a family,'' he said,
``and our lives are interwoven whether we like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``14 Up'' bunch has found growth to be a painful process.
``At 7 I thought I knew everything, I was so confident of what I
had to say,'' Lucy said. ``Now I'm not so sure if I'm right. I
guess now we're facing the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis said she was ``more aware of being better off and the
advantages it gives you,'' adding: ``But you can have a whole lot
of money and just slack off. It may sound retarded to say this, but
I believe we all have the same chance of succeeding.''
</P>
<P>
   They are quite aware of the documentary process, and at times
are annoyed by it. ``I feel I was stereotyped as some kind of Upper
East Side rich snob,'' Kate said.
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``I don't think that the five minutes they give you
tells anything. It's not a portrayal of the real me. And I don't
know what you can learn about a whole generation from 17 kids. I
had mixed feelings about being in the film again. But they said
that everyone else is doing it, so I felt pressured to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The group ``is supposed to represent our generation,'' Lucy
agreed, ``but we're so much more than what you see on screen. And
of course they have to ask us questions like `Are you having sex?'
I mean, puh-lease! The interview went on so long I began giggling
and couldn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Luis said he ``took the questions like a test'' in the film
interview, and ``I answered them with truth; I don't know if I
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The American teen-agers say they intend to participate in the
next round, at age 21. ``It's risky,'' Lucy said.
</P>
<P>
   Alexis interrupted: ``But it's a cool risk. At least people will
know that you were alive. We'll leave something behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucy smiled. ``I feel we're part of an experiment,'' she said,
``but I think we're taking over the experiment. I'm already making
plans to be hyper and outgoing at 21, versus depressed and solemn
at 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Deadpan, Alexis said: ``Absolutely. I'm working on my wardrobe
for age 21.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard not to come to the aid of some of the children who
are struggling, Joanou said. ``We feel protective of them, but we
can't help them,'' he said. ``We have to remain objective, and show
the truth that we see. We have to let their lives unfold.''
</P>
<P>
   As the years go by, Joanou said, ``sadly, it's not impossible
that there will be tragedy.'' He added, ``Life throws a lot of
curveballs, and no one gets out alive.''
</P>
<P>
   What is the destiny of his subjects? ``It's a cliffhanger,'' he
said. ``Stay tuned for 2005.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
