<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AMERICAN-DREAM-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE DREAM AND THE DRIVE: TO MOVE UP  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American dream is about rise and fall and evolution,''
Anthony Geffen said from his London office. ``It's true that as an
outsider you tend to assume there's a lack of meritocracy in
America. But after a while, you realize that there is a kind of
hierarchy that evolves, based not on your family but more on money
_ and the power it wields.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``American Stories: The American Dream,'' he traces this
evolution through 3 generations of 10 families in their quest for
betterment. Produced by Geffen and his company, Atlantic
Productions, and directed by Richard Bradley, the five-part
documentary, to be shown in its entirety on the Discovery Channel
on Saturday from 6 to 11 p.m., uses oral testimony, archival
footage and personal photographs to examine the yearnings and
expectations, the achievements and the disappointments that have
shaped the national psyche.
</P>
<P>
   The series is built around several events in modern American
history: the Depression, World War II, the civil rights movement,
the student protests of the 1960s and the Reagan era. The result is
an account of the rise _ and, some say, the fall _ of the American
dream since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Over three years, Geffen and his crew discussed the
documentary's focus with academics and writers, and then
interviewed some 17,000 families across the country, consulting
with churches and unions to find ``ordinary Americans that had
powerful stories to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   They ultimately narrowed their search to 10 families whose lives
encapsulated the spirit and scope of the story: people like Dick
Manoff, the son of Russian immigrants who rose from the poverty of
the Lower East Side of Manhattan to become a Madison Avenue
advertising executive; John Gage, a student radical and Vietnam
protester who became an Internet pioneer; Jewell Blankenship, a
refugee from the Dust Bowl whose journey to California in the 1930s
had the trappings of Steinbeck's ``Grapes of Wrath''; Joe Mifsud, a
Maltese sailor who arrived in America in 1927, helped build the
first Model T's in Ford's Detroit plant and became a union
campaigner; Alfredo Vea, the son of a migrant laborer who was
reared by his grandmother in poverty, drafted for Vietnam and is
now a lawyer for immigrants' rights, and General (his real first
name) Baker, who moved from a shack in the Deep South, where he
worked in service for a white family, to Detroit, where he worked
alongside Mifsud on a Ford production line.
</P>
<P>
   That an Englishman should mastermind such a series doesn't seem
ironic to Geffen, who also produced ``The Promised Land,'' a 1995
documentary that traced the migration of five million Southern
blacks to Northern cities.
</P>
<P>
   Coming from the outside was a special thing, he said:
``Repeatedly, the typical response was, `My God, we couldn't have
said this to anybody who was American.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Toni Peabody, whose life as the wife of the Massachusetts
Governor Endicott (Chub) Peabody II, who died last December, was
among those examined, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What came out of this was that Chub spoke about his life in
the most truthful, wonderful way,'' she said. ``He would have never
opened up like that to anyone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
