<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDA-COX </SLUG>
     RECALL RAISES QUESTIONS OVER SPEED OF FDA DRUG
APPROVALS
 &HT;     By JEFF NESMITH 
 &HT;     c.1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Food and Drug Administration, under fire a
decade ago for moving too slowly to get potentially life-saving
medicines approved for sick Americans, is now being criticized from
the opposite direction: for allowing unsafe medicines to reach
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The agency announced Monday that the maker of Duract, a popular
prescription pain reliever, was withdrawing the drug because of
reports linking it to an expected high incidence of liver damage.
It was the third recall of an approved prescription drug in the
past nine months.
</P>
<P>
   The FDA said it had learned of four patients who died and eight
others who have had to undergo liver transplants after taking
Duract, which the agency licensed slightly more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Duract, known generically as bromfenac, belongs to a class of
medicines known as nonsteroidal anti-inflammatories. A comparable
drug is ibuprofen.
</P>
<P>
   At the time the Duract was licensed, clinical trials had
revealed an elevation in enzymes associated with liver failure, and
its recommended use was limited to no more than 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are generally free to prescribe drugs ``off label'' and
ignore such recommendations once the substance is licensed by FDA.
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials and the manufacturer, Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories of
St. Davids, Pa., said that among the more than 2.5 million
prescriptions of the drug written since last September, when it
went on the market, many were for more than the 10-day limit.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst officials, in a letter to doctors and druggists
recommending discontinued use of the drug, said all but one of the
12 known cases of liver failure involved use beyond the 10-day
period.
</P>
<P>
   The ``voluntary withdrawal,'' result of an agreement between
Wyeth-Ayerst and FDA, marked the third time in the last nine months
that prescription drugs have been withdrawn. Posicor, a
hypertension medication, was withdrawn June 8 and the diet drug
Redux _ also marketed by Wyeth-Ayerst _ was pulled from druggists'
shelves last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This drug (Duract) should never have been approved in the
first place,'' said Thomas J. Moore of the Center for Health Policy
Research at George Washington University. ``Here was a drug that
was shown in its clinical testing to be comparable to ibuprofen,
with the exception of its toxicity to the liver.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who co-authored an article in the May 20 issue of the
Journal of the American Medical Association calling for creation of
a national office of drug safety to monitor approved
pharmaceuticals, said FDA was forced to accelerate its review and
approval of proposed new drugs as a result of lobbying by the
pharmaceutical industry in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Studies by the industry-funded Center for the Study of Drug
Development at Tufts University in Boston show that after Congress
passed the Prescription Drug User Fee Act in 1992, the FDA reduced
by more than half the time it requires to approve a typical
application for a new drug license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharma launched a massive lobbying campaign in the 1980s,''
said Moore. ``They spent a very large amount of money and it was a
very effective campaign. The question became, `How quickly can you
approve a drug?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not stamping passports here. Approval of a
prescription drug is one of the most complex and important
scientific judgments that we make in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore and others, including medical school researchers Curt
Furberg of Bowman Gray College of Medicine in Winston-Salem, N.C.,
and Bruce M. Psaty(cq) of the University of Washington in Seattle,
have argued that the FDA has been pushed too far from its
once-criticized slow action on drug evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Moore also questioned why FDA would approve Duract, sometimes
described as a ``me too'' drug because of its similarity to
ibuprofen.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like marketing a car and saying that if you drive it
more than 35 miles an hour it will kill you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He might have pushed the analogy further and said the car would
cost $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   A bottle of 100 Duract pills costs about $103, according to
estimates in industry trade publications when the drug was
released.
</P>
<P>
   A bottle of 100 ibuprofen caplets _ marketed as Advil by
Wyeth-Ayerst's parent company, American Home Products Corp. _ costs
about $10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
