<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENEGAL-SINGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLDLY SENEGALESE SINGER LIKES TO STAY HOME
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By VIVIENNE WALT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal _ This West African capital has been throbbing
for years with nightclubs. Walls are pasted with concert posters,
and street merchants peddling cassettes can talk knowledgeably
about musicians from across the region.
</P>
<P>
   So it's no surprise that any taxi driver can point to a landmark
on the the city's corniche, or seaside road: the home of Youssou
N'Dour, one of the world's best-known African singers.
</P>
<P>
   He composed the theme song for the World Cup soccer tournament
in France. His bluesy ode to the sport may not be his finest work,
but, said Ken Braun of Stern's Music, a specialist record company
in New York, ``it really seals his reputation as  &UR; the &LR;  African star
in the eyes and ears of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   N'Dour's house is a modern structure overlooking the Atlantic
Ocean. Inside, the banisters are decorated with bass clefs, and
there is a 53-inch television in the living room. It hardly looks
like the site for a musical revolution. Still, if N'Dour has his
way, the latest addition to his home could help transform West
Africa's music scene. In an airy room around the back, on hardwood
floors under a mosaic dome, he has just opened a state-of-the-art
recording studio.
</P>
<P>
   It cost him about $300,000 to build, and N'Dour stands to profit
by recording local talent and attracting Western performers eager
to collaborate with African musicians. But that's not the point.
His goal, he said, is to stop the tide of African musicians who
have abandoned the continent for the United States and Europe by
offering them a world-class studio at home, at prices way below
those in New York and Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important to work in your country,'' N'Dour said in
his living room recently. ``The work, the friends, that reality is
reflected in our music. It's important to record this music here.''
</P>
<P>
   Other well-known African musicians, like Papa Wemba from the
Democratic Republic of Congo and Ismael Lo of Senegal, have settled
in Paris, setting up dual careers making popular Western recordings
and, more rarely, authentic African ones. Although N'Dour also
records many albums abroad, he has become a local hero for
insisting on living in Dakar and spending as little time as
possible elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   His smile advertises Colgate toothpaste on billboards around
town, no caption needed, and most weekends he performs downtown in
his own nightclub, which he said he enjoys more than his overseas
concerts. ``The audiences know what we're talking about, they feel
the music,'' he said. ``The international audiences just get the
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, however, N'Dour, at 38, has become an idol for
a new generation of African musicians. After recording the hit
``Shaking the Tree'' with Peter Gabriel in the mid-1980s, N'Dour
became the first Senegalese musician to break out of the local
scene. His biggest hit, ``Seven Seconds'' _ which mixed English,
French, and Wolof, a Senegalese language _ topped the European
charts two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Dakar's music in the future looks as if it might be very
different from the African percussive rhythms that have made
N'Dour's dance songs so successful. The generation born in this
burgeoning city since Senegal gained independence from France in
1960 has cut its ties to the rural villages that N'Dour sings about
and holds none of his romantic affection for them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the youth of Dakar owe as much of their musical tastes to
the South Bronx as to N'Dour's cherished Dakar. Scores of would-be
rap singers barely out of high school have begun recording angry
lyrics in French and Wolof on makeshift machines and selling out
concerts in school halls and clubs. Mimicking the Americans they
see on television and in movies, they have even created a Dakar
form of jive.
</P>
<P>
   Hyperson, the small recording studio for Dakar's most popular
rap group, Positive Black Soul, has become a magnet for groupies
dressed in baggy jeans and baseball caps turned backward. Sometimes
during the day the thumping bass emanating from the building
competes with wailing Islamic chants from the open-air mosque
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   For now, N'Dour is thrilled at Dakar's change in musical
direction. ``It's a direct reaction to the world, which looks at
Africa as being all about jungles and wildlife tourism,'' he said.
As such, Dakar's rap music might allow African musicians to break
out of their traditional mold, said N'Dour.
</P>
<P>
   His brother, Boubacar, helps manage his business affairs and has
begun promoting young rappers. Whether the West will accept such
music is another matter. Positive Black Soul's first U.S. concert
is scheduled for Central Park's Summerstage on Aug. 2. A few other
Senegalese rappers are finding audiences in Europe, where ``people
are far more tolerant of foreign languages,'' said Braun of Stern's
Music.
</P>
<P>
   But the appeal is limited, Braun added. ``In America, people
want to hear English, and if these kids sing in English it comes
out sounding false.''
</P>
<P>
   N'Dour maintains that, ultimately, the most important thing is
to create music at home. ``My generation began playing roots
music,'' he said. `It was very, very different. But it was just 20
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of Dakar's young rappers are to enjoy N'Dour's worldwide
success, they will have to overcome their imitative Western style,
which hurts their chances. But for those who do make it, there is
now a place for them to record their music, right here in N'Dour's
home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
