<HEADER>
A3136 &Cx1f; gen-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CONST-NAT     06-23 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CONST-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     
 &HT;    
 &HT;      CONSTITUTION CENTER CLEARS FIRST $ HURDLE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, June 23 -- Funding for the glitzy, high-tech $130
million National Constitution Center at Independence Mall cleared a
major hurdle Tuesday as a key Senate panel signed off on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution Center would receive $10 million from the
federal government next year to break ground on the project, under
a plan approved by the Senate appropriations subcommittee
overseeing the National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   And another $10 million could be coming soon from the Senate
appropriations subcommittee for education projects, chaired by Sen.
Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a key backer of the Constitution Center.
</P>
<P>
   The funding still has many more hoops to go through before it's
a done deal -- including approval from the Senate Appropriations
Committee, the full Senate and then the House. But Tuesday's turn
of events is a sharp contrast to the doubts expressed for the
project at a field hearing in Philadelphia in March, when a
cash-strapped Park Service said it was unwilling to foot the entire
federal portion of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, fantastic news,'' said John Ullyot, spokesman for
Specter, who is still recovering in Philadelphia from heart
surgery. ``It is just a great win,'' said Sen. Rick Santorum,
R-Pa., who helped broker the deal.
</P>
<P>
   If all funding is approved and the project built, the
Constitution Center will be a 132,000-square-foot multimedia museum
dedicated to the Constitution at the site of its birth in 1787. The
Senate subcommittee also on Tuesday included $3.5 million for a new
Gateway Visitors Center and a new home for the Liberty Bell -- all
part of the more than $200 million in renovations Mayor Ed Rendell
is trying to secure for Philadelphia's most popular historic site.
</P>
<P>
   For the center to be built, the federal government must put up
$65 million over three years, meaning $20 million in 1999 is on
target. Rendell has pledged to raise $35 million from private
sources, and Harrisburg will fund the remaining $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $3.5 million from Washington, the visitors center
and Liberty Bell home will require $63 million from state and local
governments and non-profit foundations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest deal turned on negotiations between Santorum and
Specter and Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., the chairman of the Senate
Appropriations subcommittee on Interior and other agencies such as
the Park Service. Gorton -- a history buff -- supported the
Constitution Center, but thought $20 million was too high a price
considering the Park Service's annual construction budget barely
topped $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   So Gorton agreed to provide $10 million from the Park Service,
as long as Specter provides $10 million from the Education
Department's budget, according to Santorum. ``It was absolutely
essential for (Gorton) to fund the project,'' Santorum said. ``Once
he got on board, it gives Sen. Specter a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a slight stretch for Specter's subcommittee on Education,
Labor and Health to fund a Park Service project, but Senate aides
say they will call the Constitution Center an ``interactive
teaching'' tool for history classes.
</P>
<P>
   Ullyot said no deal has been finalized, and Specter's
subcommittee has yet to hold hearings on the Education Department
budget. But, Ullyot added, Specter will ``fight for as much other
funding as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Santorum is confident Specter will come through, and that the
battle will ultimately be decided in negotiations between the
Senate and House, which is not expected to include the Constitution
Center funding.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
