u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSTOMS-MONEY-HNS &LR;      06-23 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-MONEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT RULING RAISES CONCERN AMONG CUSTOMS AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ Customs officials said Tuesday they would
continue to search for large sums of money that people leaving the
United States fail to declare, despite a Supreme Court ruling that
confiscating undeclared cash may be unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling, which was issued by a sharply divided Supreme Court
on Monday, struck at the heart of an aggressive campaign by the
U.S. Customs Service and other federal agencies aimed at seizing
millions of dollars being smuggled across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had time to even review this decision; our lawyers
are looking at it right now,'' said Bill Anthony, a Customs
spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Customs agents will continue to hunt as aggressively as ever for
hidden cash, Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   Customs agents seized roughly $18 million along the southwest
border in fiscal year 1997 and have kept up a similar pace this
year, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires that anyone who transports more than
$10,000 in cash or other ``monetary instruments'' out of the
country must report that amount. People who fail to report it can
be sentenced to up to five years in prison and fined up to
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires the people to forfeit the unreported money
to the government.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court ruled that forfeiting all of a person's
money amounted to an excessive fine and was therefore
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was rooted in a case in which a man tried to leave
the country at the Los Angeles airport in 1994 with more than
$350,000 that had not been declared.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents in South Texas have found hundreds of thousands
of dollars at a time stashed in hidden compartments in the doors
and ceilings of vehicles or stuffed in suitcases and boxes leaving
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Covertly moving bulk cash is a favorite tactic of drug
traffickers hoping to hide their wealth and to avoid paying taxes,
the agents say.
</P>
<P>
   FBI and Drug Enforcement Administration officials declined
comment Tuesday on the high court's ruling, as did federal
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate the government lying down as a result of
this, but this ruling definitely gives defense counsel another
weapon in its arsenal to retrieve forfeitures,'' said Ronald
Ederer, a San Antonio attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Ederer, a former U.S. Attorney, is currently battling the
federal government over $572,650 that was seized in April from a
courier for a company that specialized in putting armor plating on
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Aldrete De La Cruz pleaded guilty last week to failing to
tell Customs agents about the money, but Ederer said his client
kept quiet because he feared letting anyone know he was
transporting the cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``The money is legitimate,'' Ederer said. ``In Mexico there's
constantly hijacking and kidnapping when there's large amounts of
cash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
