<SLUG> BC-POLAND-JEWISH-CEMETERY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A POLISH PLAYGROUND HAS PLENTY OF GHOSTS TO GO AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: a map-graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(JT) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KALISZ, Poland _ A well-worn school playground, where hard
sports have left more dirt than grass but that was once the site of
a venerated Jewish cemetery, has prompted a bitter dispute between
Jewish organizations and the Polish authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Now a prosperous town bustling with commerce, Kalisz was one of
the earliest Jewish settlements in medieval Poland. Leaders of
Jewish groups say they believe that the body of a distinguished
17th-century rabbi, Abraham Abele Gombiner, is buried beneath the
soccer field.
</P>
<P>
   They say it is an affront to the Jewish religion that the body
of such an important figure, whose legal works and biblical
commentaries are still in use, should be left in such a
sacrilegious way.
</P>
<P>
   A New York City rabbi, Hertz Frankel of the World Council of
Orthodox Jewish Communities, and Jewish leaders in Poland insist
that the playground, and perhaps even the school, which was built
in the 1960s, should be moved. Only then, they say, can the
sanctity of the cemetery, of which there is now no visible trace,
be restored.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with Polish officials and American diplomats that
have dragged on in Warsaw over the last several years, Frankel has
made no secret of his disdain for what he believes to be the Polish
government's lack of sensitivity to a Jewish issue.
</P>
<P>
   The argument is particularly sensitive because the playground is
the main outdoor activity area for the 250 physically and mentally
handicapped children who board at the school. In one of the many
emotional elements of the case, the school is named after Janusz
Korczak, the head of a Jewish orphanage, who during World War II
accompanied all of his charges to the Treblinka death camp, where
they were all killed.
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded letter this year to the Polish Foreign
Minister, Bronislaw Geremek, Frankel said that resolution of the
Kalisz cemetery issue had become a ``litmus test'' of the sincerity
of the Polish government to establish ``some relationship with
world Jewry.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the collapse of the Communists in 1989, the restoration of
more than 1,000 Jewish cemeteries in Poland, many of them
vandalized by the Nazis and then neglected under communism, has
been a matter of friction and cooperation between Jewish
communities abroad and Polish authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, non-Jewish Poles in small towns have taken it
upon themselves to spruce up Jewish cemeteries by scrubbing the
gravestones, tending the gardens and fixing fences. Twenty-five
such unpaid volunteers will be honored by the Israeli government at
a ceremony in July in Krakow. In other places, the Jewish
Historical Institute in Warsaw has sent two preservation
specialists, Eleonora Bergman and Jan Jagielski, to help in the
restoration of dilapidated cemeteries and to photograph gravestones
for the archives.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, here in Kalisz, about 100 miles southeast of Poznan, Ms.
Bergman designed a wall at the 19th-century Jewish cemetery in the
town that encapsulates gravestones that were once in the old Jewish
cemetery at the playground site.
</P>
<P>
   There is little left of the once-vibrant Jewish community in
Kalisz. Before World War II about one-third of the 70,000 people
here were Jews, according to Anna Wozniak, the administrator of
cultural affairs. She said she knew of no Jews still in the town.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazis forced the Jews into a ghetto in the marketplace and
sent them to the death camps. The local synagogue was destroyed by
the Nazis and a bank stands on its site. The Nazis uprooted the
gravestones at the cemetery of the rabbi, which by the end of the
19th century had been supplanted by a new cemetery, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The gravestones were used by the Nazis to strengthen a nearby
river embankment, where they remained until 1989. Then, in an
effort to attract attention to the desecration of the old cemetery,
the Nissenbaum Foundation, a Polish group that pays for the
restoration of Jewish cemeteries in Poland, took some of the stones
from the river and put them on the edge of the sports field. They
were later taken to the new cemetery and set in the commemorative
wall designed by Ms. Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   Stanislaw Sikorski, the school principal, who met recently with
a Polish-Jewish leader, Jerzy Kichler, and Kalisz officials over
what to do about the playground, said he would not object if the
school were moved and rebuilt elsewhere. But who is going to pay
for it? he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel and Polish Jewish leaders say they believe the Polish
authorities should pay for a new school. That would atone for the
Communists' allowing a school to be built on what was known to be a
holy Jewish site, they say. But the Polish authorities say that
given their pinched economic circumstances, they cannot afford such
a gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Under a restitution law passed by the Polish Parliament last
year, religious groups may claim back property that was confiscated
by the Communists and still remains in government hands.
</P>
<P>
   But Kichler said he was pessimistic about a satisfactory
solution. ``We don't mean any harm to the Kalisz community and its
people,'' he said. But, he added, the Jewish religion demanded that
a cemetery remain sacred, no matter what the passage of time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
