</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-COCKTAILS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDE   EFFECTS RAISE DOUBTS ABOUT AIDS `COCKTAILS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Potent AIDS drug combinations that burst on the scene 2 1/2
years ago continue to work wonders for thousands of patients
infected with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV). But not for
Hal, a 41-year-old Boston man.
</P>
<P>
   The pills that are saving many people's lives and restoring
their health were ruining his with their relentless side effects.
So a few weeks ago, against his doctor's advice, Hal (who didn't
want his last name published) stopped taking his AZT, his 3TC, his
nelfinavir and crixivan _ the drugs in his particular daily
regimen.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's wrestling with doubts and fears. ``I hope it's a good
decision,'' he said with a pained expression. ``It's not totally
that I've failed. I really did give it my very best. Hopefully I
can make it until something better comes along.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal's decision reveals the shadowy side of the AIDS treatment
revolution that has recently given respite from the 17-year-old
epidemic _ at least in wealthy societies that can afford the
$10,000-plus yearly cost-per-patient.
</P>
<P>
   While AIDS doctors say few patients are taking themselves off
Highly Active Anti-Retroviral Therapy or HAART, as the regimens are
termed, tens of thousands struggle every day to remember their
medicine, tough out miserable side effects such as chronic diarrhea
and ugly fat deposits, and pray that researchers will soon provide
them with better, simpler alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people feel they're in pill prison,'' said Dr. Calvin
Cohen, a Boston AIDS specialist.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS agencies have lately begun to devise ways to help patients
adhere to treatment regimens. A Massachusetts program, believed to
be the only state-run effort of its kind, has enrolled 412
HIV-infected patients in 17 sites _ out of 18,000 in the state
believed to be in anti-HIV treatment. Trained ``advocates,''
themselves coping with treatment, help others stay on the wagon
with pep talks, late-night phone calls, group sessions, and
compartmentalized pill boxes that beep when it's time to take
another dose.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advocate helps build me up,'' said Herbert Dean, 45, a
recovering addict in the adherence program at Boston Living Center,
an AIDS service organization. ``I was so used to beating up on
myself for missing my doses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This requires a higher degree of compliance than any regimen
I've seen,'' added Dr. Deborah Cotton, associate provost of Boston
University School of Medicine. ``It requires people to
fundamentally reorganize their lives and put this at the top of
their priority list every single day.''
</P>
<P>
   The relentlessness of treatment is making ``treatment fatigue''
AIDS topic number one in developed nations. This, in turn, lends
new urgency to the search for more drug options and more
user-friendly regimens.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS specialists expect these issues _ and the painfully
widening treatment gap between rich and poor nations _ to dominate
the 12th World AIDS Conference beginning next weekend in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Never has strict adherence to drug treatment been more
crucial, for patients themselves and for public health. HIV
patients who take their drugs sporadically are certain to foster
resistant forms of the virus that can elude any current drugs _
putting them on a downward spiral and raising the risk that they
will transmit resistant viruses to others through unsafe sex or
sharing of drug paraphernalia.
</P>
<P>
   This problem ``must be addressed if antiviral therapy is to play
its optimal role in blunting and altering the course of the HIV
pandemic,'' Mark A. Wainberg of Montreal's McGill University and
Dr. Gerald Friedland of Yale warn in the current Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Since mid-1996, when treatment successes were the theme of the
last international AIDS conference in Vancouver, ``we've learned to
appreciate how difficult these drugs are to take over the long
term,'' said Friedland, who will chair a session in Geneva on how
to improve patients' adherence to treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of the regimens _ typically they involve
ingesting 20 to 40 pills a day, some on an empty stomach, others
with food, some requiring copious amounts of fluid _ was an
anticipated problem. So were some side effects, such as diarrhea,
headaches, and pins-and-needles sensation in fingers and toes due
to nerve damage.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, unexpected ``metabolic'' side effects are cropping
up: a redistribution of body fat to the abdomen, the breasts, or
the back of the neck, combined with a wasting of the face and
extremities; an increase in the fat content of blood; emergent
diabetes. No one knows what causes these late effects, how many
will suffer them, or what to do about them.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the main bugaboo of current AIDS therapy _ the number one
worry of patients, doctors, researchers, and public health
officials alike _ is the virus's alacrity in acquiring resistance
to the 11 federally approved AIDS drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Between 650,000 and 900,000 Americans are living with HIV,
according to a new estimate by the US Centers for Disease Control,
and about half of them are aware they're infected. Of those on
anti-HIV drugs, a sizable but unknown percentage are, like Hal,
veterans of treatments available before early 1996, when
triple-drug treatment was first shown to suppress HIV below
doctors' ability to detect the virus in many patients' blood.
</P>
<P>
   Those who began treatment in 1996 are luckier, as long as they
got state-of-the-art therapy. Potent drug ``cocktails'' containing
protease inhibitors and other drug types can make HIV virtually
disappear (except in hidden ``sanctuaries'' within the body) in 80
to 90 percent of patients who were ``naive'' to prior AIDS
treatment. But those who began less-effective treatments before
1996 often have developed resistant strains of the virus that
linger in their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hal is a person who came to me before protease inhibitors
became available,'' said Mazzullo. ``He was on what we considered
the best regimen but it didn't fully suppress the virus. When I
tried to get him on more potent medications, he got terrible side
effects, to the point he was unable to take the drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite taking up to five anti-HIV drugs at a time, Hal never
achieved the coveted status of ``undetectable,'' when the virus
cannot be found by the most sensitive blood tests. Treatment
brought his ``viral load'' down from an alarming 900,000 viral
copies per deciliter of blood (about a thimbleful) to about 30,000,
where it has hovered for months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people would give their right arm for a viral load of
30,000,'' Hal acknowledged, adding that treatment has certainly
``bought me something.'' But his stubborn viral levels in the face
of treatment mean the HIV in his system has mutated into a
resistant form.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes a new regimen will emerge soon that will be both easier
to take and potent against his resistant strain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hal said, ``People can't get complacent about this
disease because the numbers are growing, people are still getting
infected, and the drugs aren't working for everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
