<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-SMITH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD ARTS FORUM TO FOCUS ON RACE, GUNS AND THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna Deavere Smith, the playwright and performer who has created
a summer institute at Harvard University intended to strengthen the
role of the arts in civic discourse, announced Tuesday the first
group of several dozen artists and scholars who will take part in
the six-week program.
</P>
<P>
   The group includes choreographer Donald Byrd and members of his
dance company, who will use the subject of the black minstrel show,
an early American form of popular entertainment, to explore issues
of race, image and stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Wallace, a composer, and Michael Korie, a lyricist, who
together created the opera ``Harvey Milk,'' will develop a new
opera, ``High Noon,'' centered on the Western myth of the
gunfighter and, by extension, guns and violence in American
society.
</P>
<P>
   Shu Lea Cheang, a media-installation artist and filmmaker, will
work on ``The Brandon Project,'' a yearlong narrative on the
Internet that is being developed with the Solomon R. Guggenheim
Museum in SoHo. The project will examine sexual matters on the
Internet and crimes related to them.
</P>
<P>
   Other participants include Judy F. Baca, a visual artist who has
been organizing the painting of murals in neighborhoods across Los
Angeles; Roger Guenveur Smith, the actor and director who created
the one-man show ``A Huey P. Newton Story,'' and Patricia Williams,
a Columbia University law professor and author who will collaborate
with Oliver Lake, a jazz saxophonist and composer.
</P>
<P>
   The Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue, which will be held
from July 6 through Aug. 14, was begun late last year with a grant
of $1.5 million from the Ford Foundation. It is sponsored jointly
by the American Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass., and the
W.E.B. DuBois Institute at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Its purpose is not simply to provide artists with a supportive
environment in which to develop projects that might illuminate
contemporary controversies and events, but also to bring artists
together with scholars, journalists and civic activists. Every
night, some 50 people will sit down together for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can an artist, at an early point in the process, bring in
information and other ways of thinking than their art form normally
invites to the process of creating a work of art?'' Ms. Smith
wondered Tuesday. ``And can they also bring the audience in at an
earlier point and see what happens?''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, the institute will hold, among other things, a
public symposium exploring minstrelsy as a barometer of social and
racial tensions and a town meeting to discuss guns and violence in
America in connection with the development of ``High Noon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm trying to find is a place where we explore the
tension between the audience and the artists, and we try to work in
that tension,'' Ms. Smith said. ``Because I believe that tension is
a source for creativity. We have to be ready to be responsive and
to listen differently.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
