A3143 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX     06-23 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Tall tales and short stories: Kids who read books
grow up to read newspapers
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nice lady had left a message on my answering machine. It seems
that more than a month ago she'd mailed me her grandson's name and
address for a free book. As he reminds her almost daily, he's yet
to receive it.
</P>
<P>
   Join the club.
</P>
<P>
   I think I'll call it the Book In A Couple Of Months Club.
</P>
<P>
   Back in May I made my annual offer of books for kids. Send me a
letter and I'll send you a book, no charge.
</P>
<P>
   If you could include stamps for return postage, I'd appreciate
it. If you didn't have the stamps to spare, no problem. You'd still
receive a book. The deadline was May 30.
</P>
<P>
   So far I've responded to 1,015 requests. I have at least twice
that many letters still waiting to be opened. If I haven't gotten
to yours, please be patient. It looks as if this is going to be a
summer-long project.
</P>
<P>
   I'm overwhelmed and delighted. The letters are wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of some of the comments from kids:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that much, but I feel like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   I know that feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am 9 years old. I am a fourth-grade student. My reading
level is average. May I please have the Top Ten Ways To Get Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd say you were somewhat more advanced than your reading level
indicates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like WCW. WCW stands for World Champion Wrestling. It is
real.''
</P>
<P>
   A volume of science-fiction would be exactly the right book for
you.
</P>
<P>
   A number of readers have been nice enough to send in extra
stamps and even cash contributions. Locally, I've also received a
wide selection of donated books to pass along to the kids.
</P>
<P>
   I've been making an effort, also, to get other newspapers
involved in a similar project to encourage summer reading. So far,
only the Austin American-Statesman has picked up on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Other than the proposition put forth in the column _ kids who
read are kids who succeed _ there are obviously good business
reasons for newspapers to promote books.
</P>
<P>
   I know of any number of people who read the newspaper but don't
read books. I don't know of anyone who reads books but doesn't read
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Books are exciting. Newspapers, for kids, can be dull. Get them
reading books and they'll grow up to read newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Also, with the approval rating of newspapers at an all-time low,
you can't imagine the deeply appreciative mail you will receive
when you do something to help kids learn _ from parents,
grandparents, teachers and the children themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is cheap. I pick up books for a buck. Discount stores
sell classics in paperback _ Mark Twain, H.G. Wells, Kipling _ for
as little as for two for $1. Book rate postage amounts to $1.24 for
most of the packages I send out.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, it's a good investment in the future _ for future
generations and for the future of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Any newspaper interested in giving it a try can give me a call,
and I'll be happy to help in any way I can. Voice and fax is
409-639-4420; email, AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O.
Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915.
</P>
<P>
   (P.S. to the lady who called: I mailed your grandson's book
yesterday.)
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily
</P>
<P>
   News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers.
</P>
