<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORECAST-AD-COLUMN-2T     06-23 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORECAST-AD-COLUMN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: ROSY AND GETTING ROSIER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Remember the disk jockeys on the old Top 40 radio
stations who shouted, ``And the hits just keep on coming!''? Well,
the rosy predictions for domestic advertising spending just keep on
coming from a leading industry forecaster.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Coen, senior vice president and forecasting director at
the McCann-Erickson USA unit of McCann-Erickson Worldwide
Advertising in New York, said Tuesday that he would again raise his
estimate of spending for 1998. The reason: myriad signs of economic
growth that have been more robust than anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a good, strong upward movement,'' Coen said at a
presentation of his predictions at the University Club in midtown
Manhattan. ``The economic climate looks even more favorable.''
</P>
<P>
   So ``barring any unforeseen developments,'' he added, ``things
look better for 1998 than they did in December,'' when he issued
his previous forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Ad spending is closely watched because it is deemed a reliable
indicator of the health of the economy. For instance, advertising
as a percentage of gross domestic product peaked in 1987 and 1988
at 2.35 percent as the economy boomed, and then it fell as a
recession took hold, bottoming out at 2.12 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Coen predicted that marketers would spend a record $200.3
billion in the United States in 1998, up 6.8 percent from a revised
figure of $187.5 billion for 1997. The 1997 figure marks a gain of
7 percent from the $175.2 billion that was spent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If Coen's prediction holds, advertising as a percentage of GDP
will ``match or pass'' the previous peak of 2.35 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While stronger than expected, the growth expected for 1998 would
be the smallest in percentage terms since a 5.2 percent increase in
1993. Yet, if the figure of $200.3 billion is indeed reached, it
will be the first time that domestic ad spending tops the $200
billion level. Overseas ad spending first passed that figure in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions for ad spending overseas will not be as favorable
this year as they will be in the United States, Coen said,
primarily because of the economic downturn in Asia. As a result, he
has trimmed his estimate for overseas ad spending in 1998 for a
second time.
</P>
<P>
   Coen ``has highlighted the concerns in Asia, which are warranted
but manageable,'' said Karen Ficker, an analyst at Furman Selz in
New York who follows the media and advertising industries. Ms.
Ficker, who attended Coen's presentation, said: ``We're encouraged
by his upward revisions in the United States. Everything we see
seems to support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Coen, who has been tracking advertising and media trends since
1948, issues his predictions twice a year, in June and December,
revising them based on updated data.
</P>
<P>
   Though he was once known for overly optimistic forecasts, he
most recently has underestimated spending as the American economic
expansion chugs along.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate of $200.3 billion is the third made by Coen for
American ad spending in 1998. In June 1997, he forecast a 1998
figure of $196.5 billion, which he raised six months later to
$198.4 billion. Yet ``the demand for media time and space''
continues mostly unabated, Coen said, so he has increased his
prediction once more.
</P>
<P>
   Economists are projecting that unemployment and inflation in
1998 will fall from 1997 while housing starts and vehicle sales
will rise, he added, and there are factors, like the Olympics and
elections, that stimulate demand for ads in even-numbered years.
</P>
<P>
   In raising his forecast for 1998, Coen cited the first-quarter
results in several large national ad categories such as
automobiles, up 17 percent from the corresponding period of 1997;
toiletries and cosmetics, up 14 percent; food, up 11 percent;
movies, up 9 percent, and beverages and snacks, up 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In some secondary national ad categories, he said, the gains
were even larger: insurance, up 33 percent; airlines, up 28
percent; computers, up 26 percent, and beer and wine, up 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, several national media enjoyed double-digit
percentage gains in ad revenue during the first quarter of 1998,
Coen said, including cable television networks, up 15.8 percent;
the four biggest broadcast TV networks, up 14.9 percent, and spot
radio, up 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of Coen's forecast of $200.3 billion, $118 billion is in
national ad spending, up 7 percent from 1997, and $82.3 billion is
in local ad spending, up 6.5 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Among the local media registering gains in ad revenue in the
first quarter of 1998, Coen mentioned spot television, up 13
percent; newspaper classifieds, up 9.8 percent; spot radio, up 9
percent; Yellow Pages, up 4.6 percent, and retail newspaper ads, up
4.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like another pretty good year for local newspaper
advertising,'' Coen said, because ``everything we look at suggests
consumers are spending a little more freely'' on the types of
merchandise sold through newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to ad spending abroad, Coen's revised figure for 1998 is
$218.4 billion, compared with a forecast he made in December of
$236 billion and a forecast he made in June 1997 of $240.5 billion.
Overseas ad spending last year totaled $210 billion, down 1 percent
from $212.1 billion in 1996; it was the first decline
internationally since 1993.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Asian crisis ``affects the overseas consolidated numbers,''
Coen said, offsetting strong increases in ad spending expected in
such countries as Brazil, Britain and Mexico. Among the largest
declines Coen predicted were those for Indonesia, down 30 percent
from 1997; Malaysia, down 20 percent, and South Korea, down 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's worldwide total estimate for 1998, then, is $418.7
billion. If it pans out, it will be the first time the total
exceeds $400 billion. It would mark an increase of 5.3 percent from
a final figure of $397.5 billion for 1997. That spending last year
represented a gain of 2.6 percent from $387.3 billion spent in
1996, the smallest annual increase since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Coen's initial worldwide forecast for 1998, made in June 1997,
was $437 billion, which he lowered to $434.4 billion in December.
</P>
<P>
   And making his first prognostications about 1999, Coen estimated
spending in the United States at $212.3 billion, which would be up
6 percent from 1998, and spending overseas at $228.2 billion, up
4.5 percent from this year.
</P>
<P>
   His worldwide total for next year, then, is $440.5 billion, an
increase of 5.2 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond 1999?
</P>
<P>
   ``As we approach the year 2000,'' Coen said, ``we think the
momentum will build'' and may produce something like the ``upsurge
we saw in 1976,'' when ad spending in America rose smartly because
of the Bicentennial celebration.
</P>
<P>
   So, ad spending at the millennium could be ``hitting half a
trillion dollars,'' Coen said.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 people attended Coen's presentation, which was his 25th
annual midyear update. The turnout was lower than usual because
some agency executives and journalists had left to attend the 45th
International Advertising Festival, which continues through
Saturday in Cannes, France.
</P>
<P>
   McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising is part of the
McCann-Erickson World Group unit of Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1938EDT &QL; 
