<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3151 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     06-23 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
     CATCHING THE WAVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   - Birds do it, bees do it, even educated fleas do it. In-flight
in flagrante delicto is the hottest trend in air travel since
frequent-flier miles, says the staid old Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the cases of ``unruly behavior'' aboard Singapore
Airlines last year, for example, were cases involving sexual
misconduct. Aboard a South African Airways jet bound from
Johannesburg to London recently, ``a couple in business class
disrobed from the waist down and began having sex in a seat in full
view of other passengers.'' This was stopped only after the captain
was called in, yelling at the couple that the plane was ``not a
shag house.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline personnel told the Journal that people were becoming
more brazen and expressed the difficulties of acting as police:
``At 37,000 feet,'' said one flight attendant, ``you don't have the
option of throwing people out.''
</P>
<P>
   - The trend in fast-forward men's magazines, says the Columbia
Journalism Review, is to become more like traditional women's
magazines. GQ, Details, Men's Health, Esquire, Maxim and the like
include features that used to be for women only: celebrity
profiles, consumer information, health and appearance tips and
advice about succeeding in relationships. The new reader of these
magazines, says the CJR, is Cosmo Guy.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile,  &UR; Gregory Davidson &LR; , a Cosmo guy reading Cosmo itself,
found a consumer news recommendation for tiny tweezers, ``perfect
for pruning stray pubic hairs at the beach. ... They also work on
brows for secretive at-work or middate touch-ups.''
</P>
<P>
   - Bertelsmann, the German company said to be swallowing Random
House, describes itself, in a newsletter quoted by the New York
Observer, ``as American as Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   - Fitness magazine, always on the lookout for innovative
instruments of torture, suggests HydroForce's Aqua Cruiser, an
underwater stationary bike.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - ``Disappointing and often dreary'' was the New York Times'
verdict on a two-night tribute to  &UR; Judy &LR;   &UR; Garland &LR;  at Carnegie Hall
last week, with one exception: San Francisco's  &UR; Weslia Whitfield &LR; ,
who was described as delivering ``the only live vocal performance
with emotional bite ... a lingering, pungently accented version of
`You're Nearer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whitfield premieres a semiautobiographical one-woman show,
``Life Upon the Wicked Stage,'' off-Broadway this fall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Arianna Huffington &LR;  was among the guests this weekend, &LR;  when
 &UR; Larry Flynt &LR; , 55, married his former nurse,  &UR; Elizabeth &LR; 
 &UR; Barrios &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   - Reading about the possibility of  &UR; Matt Damon &LR;  becoming engaged
to  &UR; Winona Ryder &LR; ,  &UR; Craig Nikitas &LR;  says the actor's preference for
a Ryder over a  &UR; Driver  &LR; (as in  &UR; Minnie &LR; ) proves he likes his women
passive.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jack Nicholson  &LR; is visiting Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   - The New York Post says that  &UR; Sharon Stone  &LR; ``would love to
play Sally Bowles, maybe in San Francisco, so she can go home'' to
her husband every night.
</P>
<P>
   - A pre-``Truman Show'' trailer for ``Six Days, Seven Nights''
at the Regency Theatre the other night ``merely got hissed,''
writes  &UR; Stephen Vincent &LR; . The next trailer, for some
``casino-mob-thug-shoot-'em-up,'' was assessed by a female critic
with a voice loud enough to make everyone laugh. ``Rental!'' she
shouted, alluding in brief to a speedy trip to the cinematic burial
ground.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Richard Knee &LR;  forwards the entire text of an e-mail he
received on Sunday: ``I am writing to you on behalf of America
Online to answer your recent question/comments.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BARKING BEATLES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More suggestions for animal-rights Beatles songs:
</P>
<P>
   From  &UR; Bob Lacey &LR; : ``Lassie, in the Sky With Diamonds,'' ``Roll
Over, Beethoven,'' ``With a Little Help From Man's Best Friend,''
``When I'm 448 (in Dog Years)'' and ``Hey, Duke.'' The album name,
says Lacey, should be ``Meet the Beagles.''
</P>
<P>
   From  &UR; Chris Morano &LR; : ``P.S. I Love Ewe,'' ``Baby You Can Drive
My Cur,'' ``Do You Want to Know an Egret?,'' ``Can't Buy Me Dove,''
``If I Smelt'' and ``I Wanna Hold Your Hen.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``And hello to Dr. Zack Jennings, an Arkansas orthodontist &LR; 
 &UR; who has a wonderful Web site that features chinaware from &LR; 
 &UR; hamburger chain restaurants.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Lo, the wonders of American culture, a bulletin from the
Frankfurter Chronicles.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
