<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-WEAPONS-BILL-BOS &LR;      06-23 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WEAPONS-BILL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES RENAMED WEAPONS BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After taking a tough assault weapons ban bill right to
the legislative firing line, lawmakers Tuesday retreated in the
face of gun industry and owner opposition and approved a weapons
bill that was barely recognizable from its original form.
</P>
<P>
   In fact the bill, which has been hotly debated in the House for
days, was even renamed from an assault weapons ban, to An Act
Relative to Gun Control. Passed Tuesday, the new bill increases
licensing fees and penalties while mandating safe storage of
weapons and training for would-e gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, the bill's name was changed to reflect that
those who already own high-capacity weapons would still be allowed
to own and sell them on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill really is not a ban on assault weapons and the bill
title was reflective of nothing more than a reaction and political
rhetoric. It's an emotional issue,'' said House Minority Leader
David Peters.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Thomas M. Finneran said the comprehensive
legislation -- &UR;  &LR; passed 100-52 -- balances the Constitutional rights
of those who own guns with the dangerous nature of the weapons.
</P>
<P>
   He said that because the bill mirrors the federal assault
weapons ban, the name change means little.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right position was in the middle,'' Finneran said. As for
the new name, Finneran said it is technically correct, ``but by
recitiation of the federal ban it's all in the eye of the beholder.
The House is more interested in substantive progress than illusory
titles.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal ban prohibits the sale of high-capacity weapons made
after 1994.
</P>
<P>
   While the bill was tightened to prevent convicted felons from
buying guns, it stopped short of the outright ban on existing guns
being resold, similar to what the Senate passed last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions of the legislation will have to be rectified in a
potentially volatile conference committee. And Finneran Tuesday
warned that any change that takes away the right of a current owner
to resell an assault weapon would be rejected by the House,
effectively killing the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was amended Tuesday on several key points by:
</P>
<P>
   _ Adopting Attorney General Scott Harshbarger's regulations on
handgun safety, including a ban on the sale of junk guns in the
state and mandatory trigger locks on all handguns sold here.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scrapping the ability for gun owners to have $2 lifetime
firearm identification cards and requires them to renew every four
years at a cost of $25. Licenses to carry handguns will also cost
$25 every four years. Those applying would have to be fingerprinted
and receive mandatory training. Those with hunting licenses and
those over 70 would be allowed to renew free and those between ages
65 and 69 could renew at half price.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restricting access to guns by those convicted of domestic
violence and preventing convicted felons from buying guns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving police chiefs discretion over what guns are allowed in
their communities. But the bill also establishes a seven-member
appeals board to overrule those officials.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing penalties for using handguns in the commission of
crimes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
