<SLUG> BC-MA-TEEN-PREGNANCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE TEEN PREGNANCY RATE CONTINUES SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The percentage of Massachusetts teenagers having babies
is continuing to decline, and state officials give credit to a
range of efforts, including expanded after-school programs.
</P>
<P>
   The birth rate of teenagers hit an 8-year-low in 1996, according
to an annual report issued by the state Department of Public Health
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The after-school programs, comprehensive health education in
grades K through 12 about risk factors, and strong family planning
initiatives all combine to keep teen pregnancy rates low, said
Deborah Klein-Walker, assistant commissioner for the Bureau of
Family and Community Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some good programs and good systems in place,'' she
said. ``We include parents, business, and youth,'' in designing
programs that will work.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts' birth rate for mothers between the ages of 15 and
19 of 32.6 per 1,000 women compares favorably to the US average of
54.7.
</P>
<P>
   Klein-Walker cited the impact of the DPH-funded Challenge Fund
program, which finances a coalition of community organizations,
parents, and business leaders who design after-school programs. The
programs include after-school activities, counseling, mentoring,
and peer leadership opportunities for children.
</P>
<P>
   These are ``things that build on the assets of the young,''
Klein-Walker said, ``and make them feel good about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Media campaigns about responsible sex, and improved sex
education also play a part, she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its not just one thing,'' she stressed, ``teens are becoming
more savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker-Klein said her staff noticed increased abstinence,
improved sex education and a reduction in sexually transmitted
diseases among teens.
</P>
<P>
   The teen birth infant mortality rate also declined in 1995, the
latest year for which data are available. Massachusetts' rate was
7.9 per 1,000 live births compared to 10.8 for the nation. And when
women of all ages are counted, the state infant mortality rate is
half the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, the report showed almost no gap in infant
mortality between racial minorities and whites in 1995, with all
groups showing less than 8 deaths per 1,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
   Racial and ethnic minorities in the state, however, continued to
show higher rates of teen births, low birthweight babies, less
adequate prenatal care, and fewer fathers acknowledging paternity.
</P>
<P>
   Programs giving pregnant teenagers prenatal care and counseling
have lowered the infant mortality rates and closed the gap between
racial groups in 1995, Klein-Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyoke, Chelsea, Lawrence and Springfield have the highest teen
birth rates in the state, project manager Saul Franklin said, but
the rates have declined steadily since 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
