<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS, REPUBLICANS TRADE JABS OVER CLINTON TRIP TO CHINA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democratic and Republican senators battled Tuesday
over President Clinton's trip to China, as conservative GOP members
sought to pass legislation aimed at punishing Beijing for human
rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, furious over what they called attempts by
Republicans ``to embarrass the president'' on the eve of his
departure Wednesday, moved to block the legislation being offered
as amendments to this year's defense authorization bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we take a good look at what message this sends,'' said
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., who threatened to use
parliamentary procedures to block votes on a series of amendments
and resolutions offered by Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., and other
conservative lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is designed to embarrass the president of the United States
on the eve of his trip. That's what this is about,'' Daschle added.
He vowed to bring Senate business to a halt, if necessary, to
prevent the China issues from coming to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson's measures would prohibit U.S.-subsidized World Bank
loans to China and ban the issuance of U.S. travel visas for
Chinese officials suspected of engaging in religious persecution or
advocating forced abortions and sterilizations.
</P>
<P>
   One of the GOP measures would also return the authority for
approving satellite exports to China to the State Department
instead of the Commerce Department, which was granted
responsibility for such decisions in 1996 by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson and his supporters denied that they were trying to
embarrass Clinton prior to his summit meeting with Chinese
President Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the amendments I have offered will strengthen the
president's ability to deal with China,'' Hutchsion told Daschle
and other Democrats as they threatened to shut the Senate down
rather than allow any direct votes on the amendments.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats accused the Republicans of trying to play
election-year politics with the China issue at a sensitive time,
given the economic crisis in Asia and the situation between India
and Pakistan on nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., called the Republican moves not only
``transparent,'' but ``dangerous'' as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no desire to score political points,'' Hutchinson
replied. But he called on his colleagues to support his measures
anyway, saying it was time to send a message ``that human rights
are taken seriously in this country (and) that human rights will
not take a back seat to trade.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the Hutchinson amendments highlighted the sharp
divisions in Congress over U.S. policy toward China, which has
promoted engagement through both Democratic and Republican
administrations ever since President Nixon normalized relations
with his visit in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The policy has suffered some setbacks in recent weeks with
disclosures that the Chinese government may have tried to influence
U.S. elections with surreptitious campaign donations and may have
received missile guidance technology from an American company that
received permission from the Clinton administration to launch its
satellites aboard Chinese rockets.
</P>
<P>
   The highly charged atmosphere could make it difficult to renew
most favored nation trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republican leaders, such as House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, R-Ga., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
favor the reauthorization of MFN, they have not been particularly
outspoken about it.
</P>
<P>
   House Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, said China
is ``the only (economically) stable area'' in Asia, and that
closing off U.S. trade with Beijing would only make a bad situation
worse for in the region and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are not our natural enemies. We can make them our
enemies by our policy or we can encourage a friendly
relationship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Archer did not criticize any of his fellow Republicans
directly, he said ``those people who want to shut down trade with
China'' are mistaken if they believe it will force Beijing to
change its policies on human rights and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a practical matter, that will never happen,'' he added.
``They will turn to Europe and they will turn to Japan and they
will be able to get everything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
