<SLUG> BC-MA-ATM-FEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE MAY FREE BILL TO CURTAIL ATM FEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Under pressure from community banks, consumer advocates
and the Cellucci administration, the House Ways and Means Committee
Tuesday indicated it will soon release legislation regulating
automated teller machine surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure something will come out of the committee,'' said Kim
Rezendes, a spokeswoman for the Ways and Means Committee. She said
a bill would be sent to the House floor after the committee
finishes with the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   What shape the ATM legislation will take is unclear, but
Rezendes indicated the committee is looking to Representative
Philip Travis of Rehoboth for help. Travis, House chairman of the
Banking Committee, did not return calls Tuesday and an aide said
she had no idea what Rezendes was talking about. In the past,
however, Travis has favored setting a cap of $1 on ATM surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   For seven months the Ways and Means Committee has sat on a bill
that would ban the surcharges &UR;  &LR; _ fees banks charge customers of
other banks who use their ATMs. In many cases, those customers are
already paying a fee to their own bank.
</P>
<P>
   The surcharge ban passed the Senate 38-0 last September and has
the support of Acting Governor Paul Cellucci and Attorney General
Scott Harshbarger. It also has the support of half of the current
House membership, which means if ATM legislation reaches the House
floor it could be amended.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Democratic Representative Paul Haley of Weymouth,
who heads the House Ways and Means Committee, and House Speaker
Thomas Finneran have indicated they don't want to pass legislation
telling banks what fees they can or cannot charge.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of May, Rezendes told the Globe that the committee
hadn't acted on the surcharge ban legislation in part because it
wasn't sure whether consumers really cared the issue. That remark
prompted calls from 70 consumers and Tuesday the Community Bank
League of Massachusetts dropped petitions off from 10,000 of their
customers supporting a ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we've shown them that consumers are interested in this
issue,'' said Dale I. Zelony, director of legislative services for
the bank league.
</P>
<P>
   Rezendes acknowledged as much Tuesday. ``Of course they're
interested,'' she said. ``It's there money.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Grabauskas, Cellucci's director of consumer affairs, said
he is not eager to regulate bank fees but he said he thinks it is
necessary in this case. He noted Bank of Boston and Fleet Financial
Group own 60 percent of the state's ATMs. He said he feared
surcharges by those two banks would force customers of smaller
banks to defect to the two larger banks.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston spokesman Bruce Spitzer said he was not aware of any
compromise legislation in the works on ATM surcharges. BankBoston
is currently preparing to impose surcharges if the Legislature
recesses this summer without taking any action.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston, which owns more than 1,200 ATMs in Massachusetts,
has pledged to impose only a $1 surcharge and use the surcharge
revenue to reduce fees paid by its own customers. BankBoston
currently charges its own customers $2 each time they use another
bank's ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said Travis in the past has expressed a hope that banks
would limit their surcharges to no more than $1. ``We said we'd
voluntarily keep it there,'' Spitzer said. ``That's all we know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0358 </DOCNO>
