<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0359 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-NIH-BOS &LR;      06-23 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-NIH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT LOOMS OVER NIH FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Investment guru Peter Lynch, cancer researcher
Judah Folkman and other leaders joined lawmakers Tuesday in calling
for a big boost in medical research funding, amid signs that a
divisive fight is brewing over where to find the money.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and prominent lawmakers from both parties,
including House Speaker Newt Gingrich, say they want to raise more
money for the National Institutes of Health, with some saying the
budget should be doubled over five years.
</P>
<P>
   But a House subcommittee Tuesday moved to raise the money by
killing programs that provide summer jobs to youths and fuel
assistance to the poor, and by cutting in half an education program
called Goals 2000. The move sets up a probable fight with House
Democrats and the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be acceptable to cut education or other health
programs,'' Senator Edward Kennedy said Tuesday at a press event to
promote medical research funding. ``That's robbing Peter to pay
Paul.'' Kennedy said Republicans were planning ``slash and burn
cuts'' in social programs and that money for the NIH could be found
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers say that a balanced-budget deal with President Clinton
will force them to find offsets for most new spending that they
propose. At the same time, expected revenues from a tobacco tax
hike now seem unlikely to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Boston hospitals have said they would probably hire hundreds of
new staff members and add new lab space if the NIH budget is
doubled. The parent company of Massachusetts General and Brigham
and Women's hospitals has said a bigger NIH budget might prompt it
to construct a new building and hire as many as 1,000 new workers.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH received $13.6 billion this year, and President Clinton
has proposed an 8.4 percent increase for next year.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of the GOP-led House Appropriations Committee moved
Tuesday to boost NIH funding by $1.2 billion, to nearly $14.9
billion. The subcommittee also proposed boosting the Centers for
Disease Control budget by $202 million to a total of $2.59 billion.
That is $89 million more than the figure in the president's
proposal, a committee spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee proposed abolishing the summer jobs program to
save $871 million and the fuel assistance plan to save $1.1
billion. It would also cut $245 million from Goals 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy and other NIH advocates called for new research money at
a press event featuring Genzyme Corp. chief Henri Termeer, as well
as Lynch of Fidelity Investments and Folkman of Children's
Hospital, whose work with a new class of cancer-fighting drugs
caused a sensation earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers unveiled a study by the Massachusetts Technology
Collaborative showing that while federal research funding has grown
every year through 1993, when it levelled off, the spending has
fallen dramatically when measured as a share of gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   Federal research spending peaked at close to 2 percent of GDP in
the mid-1960s and fell below 1.0 percent by 1992. The study said
that even under President Clinton's budget, spending continues to
decline as a share of GDP, though the total dollars spent would
rise.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman is known for his work on promising drugs called
angiogenesis inhibitors, which supress the formation of blood
vessels that cancerous tumors need to grow. His drugs have worked
well in mice but have not been proven effective in humans.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman said his work was possible because of 30 years of
uninterrupted support from the NIH, including years when the
research was seen as controversial. ``The government became the
risk-taker,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Folkman also said that even when research proposals win high
marks in the peer-review process, NIH can fund only 25 percent to
27 percent of worthy projects, down from between 37 percent and 40
percent several years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
