<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CLEARS WAY FOR FEMA FUNDS IN EVENT OF MORE TEXAS FIRES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton on Tuesday opened the fire hydrant of federal
aid for Texas, where more than 1,100 wildfires have charred 150,000
acres since May 1.
</P>
<P>
   In declaring a fire emergency in the Lone Star State, the
president cleared the way for the release of Federal Emergency
Management Agency funds for the deployment of high-tech
firefighting equipment and personnel should another major fire
break out.
</P>
<P>
   ``(FEMA) will assist the state in firefighting efforts that will
help save lives, protect property and ensure public health and
safety,'' Vice President Al Gore said in Washington. ``And with
these additional resources, we can help Texas firefighters prepare
for the dangerous fire season ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's declaration came at request of Gov. George W. Bush,
who sought the assistance June 4.
</P>
<P>
   As the state slides into a summer characterized by little rain
and temperatures in excess of 100 degrees, state fire officials are
worried about a repeat of the spring of 1996 when roughly 500,000
acres went up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   That summer was the last time such emergency federal funding was
available for firefighting efforts.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his aid request, Bush noted that 80 percent of
the state was experiencing drought conditions and in severe
jeopardy of fires. As of Tuesday, 115 of the state's 254 counties
had implemented burn bans.
</P>
<P>
   Graham Nance, who will coordinate the program from FEMA's Region
6 headquarters in Denton, said the agency will pay 75 percent of
the cost of moving the equipment, much of it owned by the U.S.
Forest Service, into place.
</P>
<P>
   A second federal program, so-called federal fire suppression
grants, pays for up to 70 percent of the cost of fighting the
fires. Four such grants have already been granted this year.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the state's wish list for firefighting equipment, said
Jo Schweikhard Moss, spokeswoman for the Texas Department of Public
Safety, are planes capable of spraying fire-retardant chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Funds likely also will be used to bring in bulldozers, federal
fire experts and fire prevention teams, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The total value of the federal aid, Moss said, will not be known
for months, but almost $6 million in federal and state money was
spent through the program between February and May 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer of '96 was rainy,'' Moss said, ``and the irony is that
the rains that broke the fires that year are the ones we haven't
gotten this year.''
</P>
<P>
   FEMA's Nance said the program will remain in effect until the
threat of wildfires no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the fires reported thus far this year in Texas have
occurred in the state's parched western and southern counties.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a fired roared for days in Uvalde, Edwards and Real
counties west of San Antonio. More than 5,000 acres were burned in
the conflagration, which were fought by local and state
firefighters and water-spraying National Guard helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   Another May fire in the mountains near Marfa in Presidio County
destroyed more than 60,000 acres before being brought under
control.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent major fire, reported in Cottel County in
Northwest Texas, burned more than 1,000 acres over the weekend,
Moss said. It was declared officially contained Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Crop dusting plans operated by the Texas Forest Service dumped
1,000 gallons of water on the fire every 18 minutes, a Paducah Fire
Department spokesman told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had the blaze been contained, however, Moss said, than
a second fire ignited in the county. By Tuesday afternoon, the
second fire had consumed about 1,900 acres, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fires, many set by a lightning storm that brought little rain,
also were reported last weekend in Falls and Jeff Davis counties.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
