<SLUG> BC-GREASE-THIEVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MEN CONVICTED OF STEALING LUCRATIVE FAST-FOOD GREASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MELISSA PRENTICE  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ During more than two decades with the Texas
Rangers, Al Cuellar helped build cases against dozens of murderers,
rapists and gun-totting robbers.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until Tuesday _ nearly two years into his
retirement _ that Cuellar's efforts helped bring convictions for
people charged with stealing thousands of pounds of used cooking
grease.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting Judge Pat Priest found Tomas and Leonel Aguirre guilty
of felony theft after the men were caught on tape agreeing to
purchase a tanker truck holding $18,000 worth of grease.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Bexar County District Attorney's first effort to
crack down on what it said has become a multimillion-dollar scam
nationwide, and prosecutors admit they couldn't have done it
without Cuellar.
</P>
<P>
   Cuellar was recruited out of retirement to help prevent an
estimated loss of $10,000 per week at Texas branches of Griffin
Industries, the largest of seven companies in the country that
collect the grease from fast-food restaurants and refine it for use
in soaps, makeup, clothes and animal foods.
</P>
<P>
   Using hidden microphones, a surveillance camera and an
undercover informant, Cuellar and Department of Public Safety
officers videotaped the defendants _ both employees of another
company, Imperial Grease Service _ agreeing to purchase 11,350
pounds of cooking grease that they were told was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Priest watched the tape several times Tuesday afternoon before
finding the two employees guilty and acquitting a third defendant,
Mary Ann Abbott, after finding no evidence she knew the grease was
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were sentenced to two years probation and ordered to
perform 120 hours of community service work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope this will send a message to small, independent
operators that if they purchase stolen grease they will be
prosecuted,'' prosecutor John Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin assistant manager Jim Larkin estimates there are about
70 grease thieves in Texas. The grease, which sells for about 14
cents to 18 cents a pound, is stolen from containers outside
fast-food restaurants by thieves who sneak up at night, break locks
or damage container lids and fill tanker trucks with the grease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
