<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TURNS ON THE BOOSTERISM FOR DEMOCRATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY AND ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Wooing the Democrats for the convention in 2000, the
city's first play for a major event since the Fleet Center was
built, is prompting Boston leaders to market the city as never
before _ and in the process, forcing the city to take stock of its
turn-of-the-century identity.
</P>
<P>
   The boosterism is as unfamiliar as Yankees boasting about family
money, but the exercise _ civic, business, and labor leaders are
finding _ is strangely rewarding. It's as if repressed Boston is in
therapy, discovering it's okay to analyze and even talk about
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought outside of the box, it was a mindset that
there are things we can do and things we can't do,'' said Mayor
Thomas M. Menino, who has thrown the city full tilt into its first
convention bid with a surprisingly strong showing so far.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, Boston has fancied itself as very attractive, a
big draw without marketing. ``They come to us, the tourists and
businesses and conventioneers,'' said Thomas N. O'Brien, director
of the Boston Redevelopment Authority. ``This is a new way of
thinking for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to O'Brien at the courtyard reception at the
Boston Public Library on Monday night, Senate President Thomas F.
Birmingham conceded a certain unease in pitching Boston's best
attributes. ``I just remember going to other cities on a tour of
convention centers and stadiums, and there was so much hucksterism
and hyperbole.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham said he welcomes the ``new Boston,'' now that city
leaders have decided to hone their own hyping skills. But still he
favors ``an understated approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, in a spine-tingling fireworks display inside the Fleet
Center and an amphibious Duck Tour that had state party chairwomen
quacking away (literally), it looked like the city had learned to
loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is incredibly healthy for this city,'' said
Michael Taylor,a longtime South Boston resident and a member of the
BRA board, at a dinner in the BPL's stately Abbey room. Boston has
always felt above the fray, perhaps even collectively cynical when
it comes to the game of selling itself, Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The marketing of the ``new'' Boston is buttressed by the
Boston of old, said historian David McCullough, who spoke to a
hushed crowd after dinner. ``This isn't Atlanta. It isn't
Cleveland,'' he declared. ``In a country where everything is
starting to look alike, you can wake up here and look at the red
brick facades and the scale of the buildings and you know you are
in a real place and a very, very American place. This city offers a
chance to bring the message of how we began.''
</P>
<P>
   By seeing its reflection in the glowing perception of outsiders,
local leaders are seeing the worth of their home affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Site committee member Roz Wyman, a 67-year-old Californian who
directed the 1984 San Francisco convention, said she would love to
have Boston's asssets _ from its nationally-celebrated chefs to its
shopping and fine arts venues _ to work with.
</P>
<P>
   ``You drool a bit, because you can do so much with 2000 in
Boston,'' said Wyman, over breakfast atop the John Hancock
building, where an actor playing the company namesake penned
autographs for the assemblage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a native of Los Angeles,'' Wyman said. ``But I love all
these historic buildings and patriotism.''
</P>
<P>
   As home to the nation's first high school and public library,
the city was born for spin, visitors noted.
</P>
<P>
   Menino said the city has helped forge bonds among an array of
communities as he has gone to business and labor and non-profits in
hopes of showing the city's diversity, and to ask for help in
raising money for the convention _ including $32.8 million in
public and private funding ($8 million from the city), $8 million
in state funding, and another $16 million in corporate spending
with in-kind contributions.
</P>
<P>
   As for the darker chapters of busing, and urban renewal, and
racism, they are fading with the writing of new chapterspromoting
tolerance and education, Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   Kiki Moore, a member of the site selection committee who joined
Menino for a 6 a.m. walking tour of the South End Tuesday, said
Boston's maiden voyage in marketing itself _ blending the new and
the old _ is having an impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of stuff we walk away talking about,'' she
said as she walked past the renovated brownstones of Waltham
Street. ``Democrats are neighborhood people. This is where the
rubber meets the road.''
</P>
<P>
   As McCullough exhorted the supper crowd. ``If you're going to
evoke images, evoke real images. There's no place like Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2000EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
