<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, June 24 and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact James Laurin at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   BLOOD-SHORTAGE-REDCROSS (Los Angeles) _ Hoping to thwart what
may be the worst summer blood-supply shortage in 10 years, the
American Red Cross issued an emergency appeal for donations,
especially Group O blood. By Sherry Joe Crosby. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-NINA-THREAT (Los Angeles) _ Sick of El Nino's lingering
drizzle and rain? Good, because long-range forecasts say we could
be in for a very dry summer, fall and winter courtesy of El Nino's
evil twin _ La Nina. And with it could come a severe fire season.
By David R. Baker. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   WHISTLEBLOWER-FIRED (Los Angeles) _ The head of environmental
health and safety for the L.A. Unified School District was asked to
resign last week, two days after he told lawmakers that the
district had allowed the new Jefferson Middle School to be built on
a toxic site. By Terri Hardy and Paul Hefner. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SAVES-DOG (Los Angeles) _ Sammy was just another pooch on
Death Row at the North Hollywood animal shelter until Mark Forbes,
looking for a smart canine who could walk and talk at the same time
for Eddie Murphy's new ``Dr. Dolittle'' movie, spotted and rescued
him. Now he plays Lucky, the animal star of the film, teaching the
doc to talk to the rest of the animals. By Carol Bidwell. (Will
move in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
