<HEADLINE>
SPRAY PAINT MAY HAVE BEEN USED ON FACE OF TEXAS MAN DRAGGED TO
DEATH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ One of the suspects in the alleged racially
motivated murder of a black man may have sprayed the victim's face
with black paint before he was dragged almost three miles along a
winding rural road, court documents show.
</P>
<P>
   The gruesome murder of James Byrd Jr., 49, in the early morning
hours of June 7 has brought international attention to Jasper.
Three white men, including two who may have ties to white supremacy
groups, were quickly arrested and charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   In a search warrant affidavit made public Tuesday, investigators
asked for tests to seek ``chemical compounds forming paint'' on the
hands of Russell Brewer Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs. The affidavit
said investigators found an 11-ounce can of Duplicolor spray paint
among other items at a spot a mile down a dirt road where they
think Byrd was savagely beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The newest affidavit says Shawn Berry, 23, of Jasper, told
investigators that after Byrd was beaten, ``Brewer spray painted
the black male's face with black spray paint.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators think Byrd's killers then used a towing chain
wrapped around his ankles and attached to the bumper of a pickup to
drag him to his death. Along the way Byrd's head and right arm were
ripped from his body.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden granted the search warrant
request. He also granted requests for scrapings from underneath the
fingernails of Brewer, Barry and Bill King, 23, of Jasper. The
scrapings, affidavits said, may reveal evidence ``consistent with a
struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   The affidavits also asked for evidence of injuries to the bodies
of the three accused men that also would be consistent with a
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Golden allowed blood samples, as well as samples of hair from
the defendants' heads, faces, pubic areas and legs to be taken from
the three men. The blood is being compared with blood spatters
found at the scene, the hair with hair samples recovered by
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmen also were allowed to photograph the many tattoos on each
of the defendants. Some of the tattoos, the affidavits said, could
``be consistent with common practices of white supremacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of some groups, like the widespread prison gang Aryan
Brotherhood, often identify themselves with tattoos. All three
defendants have spent time in Texas prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they are still awaiting the results of some
forensic tests, and refused to divulge the outcome of any of the
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The cases against the three men are expected to go before a
Jasper County grand jury July 6. Prosecutors said they expect to
seek the death penalty for at least two of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
