<SLUG> BC-TEMP-EXECS-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROWING NICHE FOR EXECUTIVE SHORT-TIMERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV.: a graphic for use with this story is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling 212 556-4204.) 
(ja) 
 By ADAM BRYANT     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine the following ad in the Sunday classifieds:
</P>
<P>
   ``Help wanted: Experienced CEO needed to turn around troubled
company or division. Executives looking for long-term relationship,
signing bonuses, guaranteed severance, an equity stake or stock
options need not apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering the kind of demands that chief executives typically
make before they sign up with a company these days, an ad like the
one above would probably not draw much of a response. After all,
capable top executives are in short supply, and they can command
substantial compensation for their services.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone wants the typical trappings that come with
lengthy tenure in the upper reaches of corporate America. Many
executives, no longer enamored of steady management jobs, are
signing up to be, in effect, temps. They go into a company for a
short period to fix problems for a daily rate, without all the
bells and whistles that accompany so many pay packages.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, they like to make changes and move on, rather than
manage a stable situation or jockey for position in the hierarchy
of a large corporation. And being a temp gives them the freedom to
focus on the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a huge advantage in objectivity, because you're not
worried about your next position within the company and where you
go from there,'' said J. Steve Davis, who recently completed a
stint running the Wells BDDP advertising agency. ``It's a chance to
soar above the politics.''
</P>
<P>
   So-called interim managers _ outside the corporate suite _ are
not new, of course. As companies downsized managers and
professional staff over the last decade, they often hired
replacements on a temporary basis for these midlevel positions.
</P>
<P>
   And in the fast-paced industries of computers and high
technology, hired guns with specialized skills are commonplace. But
with companies facing more pressure from shareholders to act
quickly, and with the process of finding a new chief executive
growing more complicated and involved, demand for temporary help at
the highest levels is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, it's going to continue to be more accepted,'' said
Alice Snell, senior analyst for Kennedy Information, which
publishes newsletters, directories and research reports on the
executive search and management consulting industries. ``It really
is consistent with a lot of employment trends, including the life
style that more executives are looking to establish.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of interim management firms offer such services. About
15 percent of the executives placed by Imcor in Stamford, Conn.,
for example, go into one of the top three slots at a company. And
many companies that place consultants for a specific industry
sometimes provide top executives on a temporary basis.
</P>
<P>
   But one company, Executive Interim Management, which deals
exclusively with placing chief executive, chief financial and chief
operating officers, is betting that this field will grow even
further in the United States. Although the company has several
offices in Europe as well as in Australia, and has placed more than
2,000 temporary executives around the world, it has only recently
set up an office in New York.
</P>
<P>
   EIM is unusual in that it is much less of a middleman or agent
than are many other firms. Instead, EIM principals determine the
goals and limits of the assignment, then send in a single candidate
for the job. There are no so-called beauty contests in which the
client chooses from several candidates.
</P>
<P>
   EIM works quickly, and can place an executive within days.
Services, not surprisingly, do not come cheap _ the executives earn
$1,000 to $5,000 a day, depending on their experience, and EIM gets
a hefty fee from the employer that is in line with the industry
average, which works out to 30 to 50 percent of the executive's
total pay. EIM charges a stiff penalty to companies that want to
hire its executives full time, because it likes to keep the people
it has found in its fold to do other assignments.
</P>
<P>
   But what kind of people want such a job? It requires a lot of
travel. There is the stress of trying to learn a new industry, new
company and new colleagues and quickly fix problems as soon as they
are uncovered. While there may be performance bonuses, there are
generally no stock options that enable executives to share in the
rewards of their efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, in broad brush, is executives who are financially
independent, have changed careers or businesses several times and
have demonstrated that they can take charge of an entire company or
major division. Perhaps most important, they do not like to stay in
one place for too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had attention deficit disorder before it was fashionable,''
said Davis, one of EIM's more recent recruits.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 53, was tapped to run Wells shortly after the agency was
bought in January by the Omnicom Group. Omnicom was not sure what
the fate of the agency would be _ and it ultimately decided to
shutter it last month _ but it needed to put in somebody quickly to
take charge. Davis was at his desk at Wells eight days after EIM
first got in touch with him.
</P>
<P>
   Installing a temporary chief executive is, of course, not a
perfect situation. It creates uncertainty among employees,
shareholders, customers and suppliers about whether changes will
simply be turned upside down once a more permanent replacement is
installed. But clients say the advantages of a temporary top
executive far outweigh the disadvantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only upside,'' said Michael Greenlees, president and
chief executive of the TBWA Worldwide advertising agency in New
York, an Omnicom subsidiary. ``If it works, the benefits are
obvious. If not, you're not committed and can change direction
quickly.'' Greenlees was chairman of the parent of Wells, GGT,
which hired EIM, and subsequently was acquired by Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   For Davis, EIM provides a support system so that he can
continually scratch a persistent entrepreneurial itch.
</P>
<P>
   He first diagnosed his itch about 13 years ago. After a dozen
years at the Benton &AMP; Bowles ad agency, he had risen to group
account director handling about a third of the business in the
agency's flagship office in New York. He had a corner office and a
blossoming reputation in the industry. There was only one problem:
he was bored to death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife thought it was hormonal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He left to help build a small agency, Altschiller Reitzfeld,
that was later sold to Omnicom. That led to an offer to try to turn
around the troubled Chicago office of J. Walter Thompson. He
shifted the staff around, visited clients and pushed the office to
do everything it could to win new business. ``People started to
feel that they were on a roll,'' he said, ``which is a very
seductive and powerful feeling, especially in an image- and
perception-driven service business.''
</P>
<P>
   After a brief stint at Young &AMP; Rubicam's New York office, he
received a call from EIM, and eagerly signed up for a new career of
permanent impermanence.
</P>
<P>
   Another temporary executive in the EIM stable is Werner Von
Pein, currently president of the U.S. division of Lavazza, a
successful coffee company in Europe that has had trouble making
inroads in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hired for my point of view, not a point of view that
somebody wants to hear,'' he said. ``In a large corporate
structure, if you want to implement change, it's a very lengthy
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Pein has seen his share of large corporate structures. A
native of Hamburg, Germany, he started with Procter &AMP; Gamble 37
years ago, and over the years jumped from one high-level
international marketing job to another at Quaker Oats, General
Foods, Life Savers and Planters.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, he enjoyed seeing the world on an expense
account. But in the mid-1980s, something started to nag at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did some soul-searching about whether I might be better off
as a management consultant, and not be in such a large culture
where people are gun-shy and looking over their shoulder all the
time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went out on his own, and did some work with a number of
companies, including Hebrew National and a peanut farm in Georgia.
When EIM approached him a year ago, he was intrigued by the notion
of being part of a more structured organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``EIM offered the opportunity to have discussion partners of
comparable professional background with whom I could bounce things
around, rather than being a lone ranger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be operating completely alone anymore, but he is not
planning to rejoin a corporate hierarchy anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get up in the morning and know that by the end of the day
you will have probably made some changes,'' he said. ``That is more
rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   True to form, the executive who is in charge of establishing
EIM's presence in North America, Neil Carragher, is himself an
interim executive who has handled a number of projects for the
company. And once his task is complete, he will probably return to
taking, rather than handing out, assignments at companies that need
help quickly. Running something for the long term is simply not in
his blood, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management of change is something that gets built into your
system,'' Carragher added. ``You get bored very quickly and you
need to feed this habit.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
