<HEADLINE>
MARIJUANA TOP DRUG IN BOSTON AREA, RESEARCHER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIE C. SANCHEZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Marijuana remains the drug of choice among young people
in Greater Boston, but LSD, methamphetamines and some prescription
drugs are making inroads, a researcher reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not trends yet, but we're concerned about them and
keeping an eye on them,'' said Thomas Clark, lead author of the
report compiled by the Boston-based Health and Addictions Research,
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Methamphetamine is making its way from the West Coast and
Midwest, he said. ``It's highly addictive, causes direct
neurological damage and unstable psychotic behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Although LSD and hallucinogenic mushrooms are most popular,
after marijuana, among young people, they are still available only
sporadically, he added, and so-called ``club drugs'' such as
``ecstasy'' and ketamines are gaining popularity.
</P>
<P>
   And prescription medications, including Ritalin, a drug used
primarily to treat attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder, are
showing up more, especially among teenage females. People sell
their prescriptions, and since it is so common, Ritalin abuse is
widespread nationally, he told law enforcement officials and
epidemiologists at a workshop in Boston sponsored by the National
Institute on Drug Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get a buzz off it,'' Clark said, ``You can get a high
if you take enough of it, like amphetamines.''
</P>
<P>
   Teen focus groups have offered some reasons why crack use is
declining among youth in Boston, he said: ``Kids are starting to
notice the `older brother syndrome,' the debilitating effects of
crack use on people they know, and are avoiding it. There's also a
stigma attached to being a crackhead.''
</P>
<P>
   These kids, Clark said, ``now have the option of snorting or
smoking heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   While cocaine and crack use continues to level off among young
people, it is still the drug of choice among users overall in
Boston, Clark said. Heroin comes in second in use overall, because
of the large supply, low cost, and high purity. The third most
popular drug overall, remains marijuana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
