<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FURIOUS TECHNOLOGY RALLY PULLS UP ENTIRE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Includes bond market activity) 
(JT) 
 By SHARON R. KING    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors bid up technology shares Tuesday in a
furious rally that reversed a three-day decline in blue-chip stocks
and pulled the entire market higher, but many analysts remained
skeptical about how long the gains would last.
</P>
<P>
   The strong rise among computer-related shares lifted the Nasdaq
composite index more than 2 percent to its highest close since May
19. Other major market indexes gained more than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft led the technology surge, buoyed by a federal appeals
court decision that allows the company to sell its computer
operating software with its own Internet browsing feature,
undercutting an important element of the Justice Department's
antitrust case. Microsoft rose 4 15/16, or 5.15 percent, to 100}.
</P>
<P>
   Other technology shares rose including Intel, Dell, Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard, amid expectations that demand for personal
computers may rise later this year.
</P>
<P>
   However, such gains merely signal a near-term rally for stocks,
some analysts said. Many expressed doubt that the market would
reach new highs against a backdrop of uncertainty about the fate of
Asian economies and domestic problems, such as the General Motors
strike.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, stocks are merely recouping some of the losses suffered
in recent weeks, said Steve Shobin, chief technical analyst at
Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   After three consecutive declines, the Dow Jones industrial
average rose 117.33 points Tuesday, or 1.35 percent, to 8,828.46.
But the blue-chip gauge is still 383.38 points away from its record
close of 9,211.84 on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index gained 16.25 points, or 1.47
percent, to 1,119.49. The rise left the index just 11.05 points
away from its April 22 closing high.
</P>
<P>
   Extending its rally for a third day, the Nasdaq composite index
jumped 38.75 points, or 2.15 percent, to 1,844.57. Despite those
gains, the technology-laden index is still 73.04 points away from
its April 22 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the market still has a pretty skeptical tone,'' said
Robert Brusca, chief economist at Nikko Securities International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks are up on the day, but they're not acting like great
things are happening or Asia is going to be fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people believed that Japan was going to do more, we'd have
a different foreign exchange rate,'' he added, referring to the
yen, which resumed falling on Monday after a sharp rise last week.
The yen fell further Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts attributed the yen's renewed decline to skepticism
that Japan will quickly take additional action to overcome its
worst postwar economic decline.
</P>
<P>
   A strong conviction that Japan is ready to take strong measures
should push the dollar lower to the 130 to 135 range, Brusca said.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar's higher value relative to the yen and other
currencies could make it increasingly difficult for United States
exporters to sell goods overseas, and Brusca said that ``does
create a problem for equities.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet-related shares rose Tuesday for a second day, partly on
persistent takeover speculation.
</P>
<P>
   But such speculation is probably unfounded, said Keith Benjamin,
an Internet stock analyst with Banc-America Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any more premium deals to be done,''
Benjamin said. Individual investors have been strong buyers of the
stocks recently, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some shares are merely retracing lost ground. For
example, Excite is still down 9 percent from its April 16 high. It
had fallen as much as 44 percent. Infoseek is down 31 percent from
its April high and Lycos, which had fallen as much as 37 percent,
is still off about 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the credit markets, Treasury securities rose Tuesday,
deriving strength from a renewed rally in the dollar and vibrant
demand for newly auctioned two-year Treasury notes.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury sold $12 billion in two-year notes, awarded at a
price to yield 5.495 percent, a little less than the 5.50 percent
to 5.505 percent traders had expected. Demand was better than the
average of the last 10 two-year-note sales.
</P>
<P>
   By late in the day the 30-year bond was up 11/32, to a price of
106 30/32, while its yield, which moves in the opposite direction
of price, dipped to 5.64 percent, from 5.66 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Treasury will sell $11 billion of five-year
notes and after that sell the five-year maturity on a quarterly
basis rather than monthly, reflecting the government's diminished
needs to borrow. In when-issued trading late Tuesday, dealers were
offering the five-year notes at a price to yield 5.47 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
