   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ Trade experts and diplomatic sources
warn that any disruption in U.S.-China trade at this time could
send China into a recession, force the country to devalue its
currency and send economies from Bangkok to Tokyo spinning out of
control. By DAVID IVANOVICH.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CHINA (Washington) _ As President Clinton prepares to
leave on his historic trip to China, critics of the
administration's China policy blast his decision to go but urge him
to be tough with Chinese leaders on such issues as human rights,
religious freedom, interference in U.S. politics, trade
restrictions and weapons proliferation. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already
filed)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANICS-DIABETES (Washington) _ A national campaign to make
Hispanics more aware of the dangers of diabetes is launched by
specialists, who say that Latinos and other minorities have a
higher rate of the disease and its complications than Anglos. By
NICOLE TSONG. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS-NOMINEE (Washington) _ President Clinton nominates New
York social scientist Kenneth Prewitt to head the Census Bureau, an
agency mired in a political and legal controversy as it tries to
get an accurate reading for the 2000 population count. By STEVE
LASH. (Already filed)
</P>
