</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-ATTACK (Jasper, Texas) _ Shortly after James Byrd Jr. was
beaten, one of the three suspects in the fatal attack spray-painted
the victim's face with black paint, one of the accused men has told
the police. Also, local officials are urging the Ku Klux Klan not
to hold a march here Saturday. By RICHARD STEWART. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-AIDS (Undated) _ With the World AIDS conference nearing, a
United Nations organization paints a bleak picture of the spread of
the AIDS virus in the Third World. ``In most of the world, AIDS is
winning,'' the head of the group says from Geneva. By RUTH SoRELLE.
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS-MONEY (Laredo, Texas) _ Customs officials say they will
continue to search for and confiscate large sums of money that
people leaving the country fail to declare. The Supreme Court ruled
Monday that seizing vast sums of cash may constitute an excessive
fine. By DANE SCHILLER. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   CONSENT-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas Supreme Court throws
out a Planned Parenthood lawsuit challenging the constitutionality
of a state law that would have withheld funding for birth control
and other prescription pills for minors without parental consent.
The court, however, stops short of actually determining whether the
law is unconstitutional. By KATHY WALT.
</P>
<P>
   GREASE-THIEVES (San Antonio) _ A Texas judge convicts two men
accused of stealing an estimated $18,000 worth of grease from
fast-food restaurants. Authorities say such thefts are not uncommon
since the grease is reprocessed and sold to manufacturers of soap
and other products. By MELISSA PRENTICE. (Already filed)
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-TEXAS (Undated) _ The federal government announces release
aid to deploy firefighting equipment and personnel to fight
wildfires in Texas. Right now, it's more of a precaution because
there are no major fires, but drought conditions continue to fry
the Lone Star State. By ALLAN TURNER. (Already filed)
