<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAC-BERMUDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CHAMPION LEADING NEWPORT-BERMUDA PACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As expected, the pros set the time standard in the 685-mile race
from Newport to Bermuda, as the Maxi Alexia crossed the line at St.
David's Light at 10:16 Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But what a slow race it was!
</P>
<P>
   ``Slow, slow, slow,'' was all Chris Dickson could say as he
sailed his Maxi, Sayonara, into port two hours behind Alexia.
``We've been out there a long long time,'' said the America's Cup
skipper from New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Alexia is an 82-footer from Buenos Aires, skippered by Alberto
Roenners, with Guillermo Parade as first mate.
</P>
<P>
   But the big gun on this trip was John Kostecki, an Olympic
champion and participant in the last two America's Cups, who called
the right moves. Shortly after the Friday noon start off Newport,
Alexia took an extreme easterly course, caught the favorable winds
that put her 29 miles ahead, then ``never looked back,'' said
Kostecki.
</P>
<P>
   Three other Maxis competing for the overall world title were
pressing, but in the light air that followed, they could never make
up the time to catch Alexia.
</P>
<P>
   A third Maxi, Boomerang, owned by George Coumonteros from the
New York Yacht Club, crossed the line third, while the first
race/cruise division boat, Trader, sailed by Fred Detwiler of
Grosse Point, Mich., crossed the line fourth with an all-amateur
crew.
</P>
<P>
   All results are subject to handicap adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   A few other boats were on the horizon at press time, according
to race spokesman Talbot Wilson, but the majority of the 168-boat
fleet is still out in the Atlantic after a prolonged windless
period at sea.
</P>
<P>
   The 90-hour time raised speculation that this might be the
slowest race of the 42 that have been sailed since 1906, but Wilson
insisted, ``It's not even in the top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   The slowest race was 1960, when the fleet sailed for 121 hours
before a winner crossed the line, and the 1978 race took 105 hours
to sail.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest crossing for a monohull came two years ago when
Boomerang roared to a win in 57 1/2 hours, less than half the time
of the slowest race.
</P>
<P>
   The finish of this race will appear on the World Wide Web at
www.rbyc.bm/newportfinlog.htm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
