<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS JOCKEY FOR POSITION ON EVE OF PRESIDENT'S TRIP
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., see related CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-PIRACY, CHINA-VISAS,
CHINA-MEDIA, CHINA-U.S.-ECON, CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-MISSILES.) 
(sw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of President Clinton's trip to China,
Senate Republicans on Tuesday mounted a wide-ranging critique of
the administration's China policy, but Democrats blocked any votes
on politically embarrassing bills.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats rallied behind Clinton in a rare show of unity.
``I'm not going to allow one single vote on China this week,'' Sen.
Thomas Daschle of South Dakota, the Democratic leader, said on
Tuesday. ``We're not going to embarrass this president.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue was a package of amendments sponsored by Sen. Tim
Hutchinson, R-Ark., that would deny travel visas to Chinese
officials involved in religious persecution or forced-abortion
policies, ban new American-backed international loans to China, and
shift the licensing authority for commercial satellites back to the
State Department from the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Through delaying tactics, the Democrats avoided a test vote on
that package and allowed only an ambiguous procedural vote. The
Senate decided, by 84 to 12, not to kill the amendments but to
leave them in legislative limbo.
</P>
<P>
   There is an unwritten rule that Congress will not vote on
legislation affecting a foreign country while the president is
visiting that nation. But some Republicans, angry over what they
perceive as the administration's failure to press Beijing
aggressively on China's record on human rights and religious
tolerance, sought to put the president on the spot before he left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should make our point before the president leaves,'' said
Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-afternoon, Lott agreed to postpone a vote on the China
amendments until after July 6, when Clinton will have returned from
his trip.
</P>
<P>
   The decision appeared to free the Senate to finish consideration
of the a $270 billion military authorization bill for fiscal year
1999, to which the China amendments had been added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
