<SLUG> BC-RENO-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RENO FINDS HER MIND': HYPERQUICK WIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Productioon notes at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reno makes you glad to be a New Yorker. She has had
it with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who ``thinks he's in Athens and
he's fighting Troy.'' (If you want the place where you live and
work to be calmer and cleaner, Reno suggests, move to Wisconsin.)
She is thankful that so many Muslims live in the city, because
alternate-side-of-the-street parking is now suspended on their
holidays. She's totally baffled by the supposed appeal of spending
weekends at a country house. (If everybody goes to bed at 9, how
much fun can they really be having?) She wishes Donald Trump would
move to Malibu, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's newest one-woman show, ``Reno Finds Her Mind,'' at the
Sullivan Street Lounge through July 4, finds her loud, annoyed and
hilarious, which is just as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   A high-energy comedian who has been compared to Bette Midler, a
nuclear reaction and living Cubism, Reno gives new meaning to
``fast-paced.'' She mentions the preppy murderer, the Boston nanny
and Joel Steinberg in one sentence. (They're not this month's news,
but it's not as if we've forgotten them.) No one would ever tell
her to take a moment, because she appears to deal in nanomoments
instead, so fast that the effect is almost subliminal.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of a virtually unrelated joke, she suddenly sings
a few notes from ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' (``See my ears? I can
hardly ... ''), then keeps going with her original thought. If only
one person in the audience catches it, no problem. As Reno says:
``If I think two people will get the joke, I will go for it. Me and
Philip Glass.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno points out things the audience members know but probably
haven't given a lot of thought to. Like the fact that getting your
teeth cleaned hurts. (It didn't always.) Or what the size of the
self-help section at big bookstores says about the state of things.
</P>
<P>
   She does not deal well with the passing of time, long (``If I
haven't been doing anything all these years, why should it
count?'') or short (``The trouble with getting up at 2 p.m. is that
the banks close at 3.'').
</P>
<P>
   The material in ``Reno Finds Her Mind'' ranges from an anecdote
about an attempt to shop at Sears (``three floors of nothing'') and
ends with one about a mammogram, which she has in lieu of a $5,500
brain scan. Here and there, she even makes fun of herself. Of her
recent search for her biological mother, which she turned into an
HBO special, she says, ``You can't really find your mother without
a sound person, can you?'' Works for me.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RENO FINDS HER MIND'
</P>
<P>
   Written and performed by Reno; developed with and directed by
Linda Mancini; assistant director, Russ Ekstrom; assistant
producer, Matthew Elefant. Presented by Chris Williamson and
International Production Associates. At the Sullivan Street Lounge,
189 Sullivan St., Manhattan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2016EDT &QL; 
