<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-AIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AIDS IS WINNING,' REPORTS INTERNATIONAL AGENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Filed in ``a'' and ``i'' categories) 
 
By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the World AIDS Conference approaches, the primary
international AIDS agency paints a bleak picture of the spread of
the AIDS virus in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most of the world, AIDS is winning,'' said said Dr. Peter
Piot, executive director of the Joint United Nations Agency on
AIDS, or UNAIDS,, an international umbrella organization
coordinating the fight across national borders. The World AIDS
Conference begins Sunday in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   In the first country-by-country analysis the group has issued,
its experts estimated that 30.6 million are living with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS, or AIDS across the world, with 16,000 new
infections daily.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 5.8 million new infections and 2.3 million deaths were
attributed to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the disease has become one of the
leading causes of infectious death in the world _ ranking with
malaria and tuberculosis as a mass killer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the industrialized world that includes the United
States, the AIDS death rates and rates of new infection are
stabilizing or dropping, Piot said.
</P>
<P>
   In most of these countries, people with AIDS have ready access
to drugs that fight the virus and the infections to which infected
people are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to prevent the spread of AIDS have met with varying
success.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the industrialized world and some developing nations
have reported declining infection rates. That is not true of Asia
or most of sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   At least one in 10 people living in 13 countries in sub-Saharan
Africa are infected with HIV, an example of how fast the infection
is spreading, Piot said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, South Africa has 3 million people living with HIV,
Piot said. Of those, 700,000 were infected in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of southern Africa _ the part of the world
hardest hit by the disease _ AIDS rates have continued to rise.
</P>
<P>
   In Botswana and Zimbabwe, one in four adults in urban and rural
areas carry the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is doubling and tripling adult death rates in the many of
these countries, Piot said.
</P>
<P>
   HIV is still an emerging epidemic in the nations of Eastern
Europe and Asia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, overall rates of disease are low, but in the
past two years, many have experienced a six- to 10-fold increase in
the numbers of reported cases.
</P>
<P>
   Piot said gaps contribute to the increasing death and infection
rates in countries where people are uneducated and poor.
</P>
<P>
   He said the numerous gaps include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Disparities in access to treatment for all diseases related to
HIV, including tuberculosis and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Differences in the rates of transmission, with spread of the
disease slowing in countries where prevention is stressed and
speeding up where AIDS is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gaps in knowledge about HIV status, leading to increased
spread of the disease and the threat that more children will be
born infected with the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there are bright spots.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand and Uganda have managed to slow the increase of disease
in their burgeoning epidemics.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda has cut its AIDS infection rate by 25 percent _ from 13
percent in 1994 to 9.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand has reduced prevalence of the disease in that country
from 13 percent in 1994 to 9.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, prevention programs stressing condom use, delayed
age at first intercourse and reducing sexual partners played a big
role in lowering infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
