<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3204 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-FEATHERED-FOSSILS     06-23 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-FEATHERED-FOSSILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS SAY NEW FOSSILS STRENGTHEN DINOSAUR-BIRD LINK
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paleontologists examining fossils from animals bearing feathers
think they have found the most persuasive evidence yet that birds
evolved directly from small, meat-eating dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the scientists and their allies contend that the mystery
of bird origins has at last been solved and that the close
dinosaur-bird link is now beyond debate. But a few skeptical
adversaries are not ready to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists said another implication of the newly discovered
fossils, which are from China, was that feathers could no longer be
considered a defining characteristic of birds. Although birds are
the only living creatures with feathers, this was not always so.
Some dinosaurs with putative ancestral ties to birds appear to have
evolved feathers, too, and they were unrelated to flight.
</P>
<P>
   The new findings are being reported this week in the journal
Nature, to be published on Thursday, and are also described in the
July issue of National Geographic magazine. The scientists
displayed the fossils and discussed their interpretations at a news
conference Tuesday at the National Geographic Society in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new fossils represent stages in the evolution of birds
from feathered, ground-living, bipedal dinosaurs,'' the scientists
concluded in their journal report.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the findings in the same issue, Dr. Kevin Padian,
a paleontologist at the University of California at Berkeley, said
the research ``should lay to rest any remaining doubts'' that birds
evolved from a type of turkey-size carnivorous dinosaurs called
coelurosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   The fossils of these animals, discovered in sediments of an
ancient lake in Liaoning Province, in northeastern China, represent
two different species. Their significance was determined by Dr.
Philip Currie of the Royal Tyrell Museum of Paleontology in
Drumheller, Alberta, and Dr. Mark Norell of the American Museum of
Natural History in New York City, working with Dr. Ji Qiang and Dr.
Ji Shuan of the National Geological Museum in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fossil species, Protoarchaeopteryx, had already been
recognized in a preliminary scientific report. But further analysis
showed it to be similar in many respects to the swift predatory
dinosaur Velociraptor of ``Jurassic Park'' fame. The most notable
aspect of the new species, though, was a cluster of feathers at the
end of its tail. Some of these feathers must have been 6 to 8
inches long, Norell said.
</P>
<P>
   The other specimens, at first mistaken for Protoarchaeopteryx,
were of an even more feathery dinosaur, as Currie and his
assistant, Kevin Aulenback of the Tyrell museum, could see on first
examination. Feathers covered the arms and much of their bodies, as
well as their tails. Some were downy feathers; others were more
structured, with shafts and vanes like a quill pen.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that they were seeing a new species, the
paleontologists named it Caudipteryx, for the tall, feathery plumes
the animal likely fanned for display like a peacock. This species,
Currie and his colleagues concluded, should probably be placed on
the dinosaur family tree somewhere between Velociraptor and
Protoarchaeopteryx.
</P>
<P>
   Paleontologists said the two species lived at least 120 million
and perhaps as much as 135 million years ago. The size and
configuration of their primitive feathers, as well as the size of
their forelimbs and other characteristics, probably rendered the
two creatures flightless.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeopteryx, the earliest established bird, which could
apparently fly, lived about 147 million years ago in what is now
southern Germany. The fact that these two feathered dinosaurs lived
after Archaeopteryx did not trouble Currie.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he said that these primitive animals could well
have evolved long before Archaeopteryx. Protoarchaeopteryx, for
example, is a dinosaur that may reflect how ancestors of
Archaeopteryx looked.
</P>
<P>
   If the feathers of these dinosaurs were not used for flight, the
paleontologists said, their earliest functions could have included
body insulation, camouflage, mating displays and species
recognition. Only among animals in the transitional phase leading
to birds, the scientists said, would feathers have been adapted for
flight.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery team emphasized that these two species were still
definitely dinosaurian and not early flightless birds. Currie noted
that of the 90 recognized physiological characteristics for
dinosaurs, 80 were represented in the skeletons of these animals.
</P>
<P>
   For scientists who had been undecided in the dinosaur-bird
origin controversy, Currie said, this kind of evidence, plus the
feathers, ``is going to be the straw that breaks the camel's back
in the whole debate.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most resolute critics of dinosaur ancestry of birds
is Dr. Alan Feduccia, an ornithologist at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill and author of the authoritative ``The
Origin and Evolution of Birds'' (Yale University Press, 1996).
Feduccia says he believes that the skeletal similarities between
dinosaurs and birds can be largely explained in terms of their
parallel but separate evolution. Birds thus did not evolve from
dinosaurs but shared with them a common reptilian ancestor at a
much earlier time.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Feduccia cited several anatomical disparities
between dinosaurs and birds and the difficulty of explaining how
animals could have developed flight from the ground up, rather than
from trees down, as reasons for doubt about a direct ancestral
relationship between dinosaurs and birds. He suggested that the
long feathers on these species could indicate that these animals
had once been able to fly, but had evolved into flightless birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere we're being asked to put a square peg in a round
hole,'' Feduccia said.
</P>
<P>
   But Norell said the ``anatomical similarities between dinosaurs
and birds are overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Hans-Dieter Sues, a paleontologists with the Royal Ontario
Museum, in Toronto, said the critics had no physical evidence to
support their arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only dinosaurs,'' Sues said, ``are anatomically suited to be
the precursors of birds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
