<SLUG> BC-ITALY-NATO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO EXPANSION WINS NARROW APPROVAL IN ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The Italian Parliament voted in favor of NATO expansion
on Tuesday, averting a political showdown that was the most serious
threat to the government's stability to date.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Romano Prodi won a reprieve when a small centrist
opposition party threw him its support at the last minute and his
conservative opposition abstained. But the bitter fight was the
strongest signal yet that the political unity that helped Italy
wage an uphill fight for membership in the European Monetary Union
this year fractured almost as soon as that battle was won.
</P>
<P>
   Had Prodi failed to get the necessary support on such an
important foreign policy matter, he might have been forced to offer
his resignation. ``We cannot reply with a refusal to this request
from Eastern Europe to expand NATO,'' the Prime minister pleaded in
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Former Soviet bloc countries _ including the three new members,
Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic _ cannot join NATO unless
all 16 members of the military alliance vote to approve the move.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign policy disputes were not really the driving force
behind the crisis; domestic political maneuvering was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foreign policy really doesn't mean anything in Italian
politics today,'' said Patrick McCarthy, a professor of political
science in Bologna. ``What this measures is the stability of the
government. This is the first of what are likely to be many
so-called crises.''
</P>
<P>
   Prodi's center-left coalition relies on a less than loyal
Communist Refounding Party for a majority in Parliament, and those
hard-line leftists oppose many of the government's economic
austerity commitments, as well as NATO expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right opposition, led by the media tycoon Silvio
Berlusconi, supports NATO expansion, but it is so eager to see
Prodi tumble that its leaders said they would vote for it only on
the condition that Prodi promise to resign after the vote. Prodi
declined to make such a bargain, and held a meetings with
opposition groups for much of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi's party, Forza Italia, finally chose to abstain from
the vote rather than support Prodi. The vote was delayed until 6
p.m. on Tuesday for the back-room consultations, which conveniently
also gave members of the lower house time to view Italy's afternoon
match against Austria in the World Cup soccer championship.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts say in all seriousness that Prodi was helped
by Italy's victory, which provided even the fractious Parliament
with a quick boost of patriotic pride.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi became prime minister in 1996, pledging to tame the
Italian economy, reduce public debt and meet the fiscal
requirements for inclusion in a single European currency. Italians,
who feared that exclusion would condemn them to third-world status,
supported the government's policy of new taxes and spending cuts,
as did a range of labor unions, political parties and business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Refounding Party forced Prodi to offer his
resignation in 1997 during a dispute over budget cuts. Back then,
its own rank-and-file members were so outraged by the threat to
government stability _ and European membership _ that they forced
the leadership to craft a compromise that would keep Prodi in
office.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Communist Refounding Party refused to vote for
NATO enlargement, no longer fearing that ordinary party members
would object. Italian leftists are generally pacifists who have
long opposed the military alliance, and many ordinary Italians have
expressed reservations about NATO, particularly after American
pilots flying jets on a NATO exercise severed a cable at a ski
resort in the Dolomites in February, killing more than 20 people.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance put up by both Prodi's allies and his opponents
could be a harbinger of political and economic trouble in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Italy goes back to its old habit of bringing down
governments,'' McCarthy said, ``financial markets will get very
irritated, and so will Italy's European partners.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
