<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WORLDCUP-BRAZIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S STUNNING LOSS ELATES NORWAY, DEFLATES MOROCCO  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSEILLE, France _ Norway had just stunned Brazil with two late
goals, but Brazilian coach Mario Zagallo, whose team already had
clinched first place in Group A before this 2-1 setback, was intent
on accentuating the positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost at the right time,'' Zagallo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Moroccan team certainly did not agree. When the final
whistle was blown after its comprehensive 3-0 victory over Scotland
in Saint Etienne, the Moroccan players were smiling and exchanging
jerseys with their opponents, convinced that they, not the
Norwegians, would be joining Brazil in the second round from Group
A.
</P>
<P>
   The games between Morocco and Scotland and Norway and Brazil had
begun at the same time, and the last news the Moroccans had heard
was that Brazil was leading. Considering the fact that even a draw
would have been enough for Morocco to advance, this was rather
reassuring.
</P>
<P>
   But inexorably the final update from Marseille trickled onto the
field in Saint Etienne. Moroccan coach Henri Michel already had
kicked his bench in frustration, and soon his players' smiles were
giving way to anguished expressions and tears. Norway not only had
tied the score with a goal from its long-limbed striker Tore Andre
Flo in the 83rd minute, they had won with a penalty kick from
Kjetil Rekdal in the 88th after a highly debatable foul was called
on Brazilian defender Junior Baiano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all understand that what happened is rather
incredible,'' said Norwegian coach Egil ``Drillo'' Olsen, who shed
some tears of his own in a post-match interview.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil might have won Group A with six points, but Norway was
the only team to emerge from the group undefeated. After two
disappointing draws, the Norwegians' upset of the defending
champions allowed them to finish with five points, one more than
Morocco. The Brazilians, who never lost on their way to the title
in 1994, will face Chile in the second round on Saturday; the
Norwegians will face Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already been thinking a lot about that match,'' Olsen
said. ``We have to come back to earth very quickly.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Since taking over the national team in 1990, Olsen has used his
tactical and psychological gifts to transform Norway from a soccer
backwater into a soccer power whose citizens care as much about his
sport as they do about winter sports. He has not done it by
emphasizing ``the beautiful game''. Aime Jacquet, the French coach,
once said that Norway ``has a gift for making its opponents play
badly.'' Olsen's team does it with a 5-4-1 alignment, with Flo as
the lone striker and the four midfielders turning into four more
defenders as soon as trouble looms.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian scheme clogs up passing lanes and minds, and in a
friendly match last May, it clogged up the Brazilians in Oslo.
Olsen's team won 4-2, putting an end to Brazil's 34-match unbeaten
streak, and though Tuesday's match was meaningless in theory for
Brazil, the memory of that defeat gave the Brazilians a reason to
care about the result. ``I wish them lots and lots and lots of
luck,'' said Brazil's left fullback Roberto Carlos before the
match.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil took the lead in the 78th minute when Denilson, the
world's most expensive player, burst through the Norwegian defense,
regained his feet after being tripped, and launched a cross that
Bebeto headed into the Norwegian goal.
</P>
<P>
   Olsen immediately substituted Flo's brother Jostein Flo for
Vidar Riseth and had his players push forward. ``We knew the result
of the other match with Morocco, and we knew we had to take
risks,'' Olsen said. Five minutes later, Tore Andre got past Junior
Baiano and tied the score with a right-footed blast. He would get
two more decent opportunities in the next five minutes, but it
would take a very questionable decision from American referee
Esfandiar Baharmast to give the Norwegians their second goal.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Mykland, another of Olsen's second-half substitutions,
launched a cross into the box. Tore Andre appeared to fall
backwards into Baiano as the Brazilian defender leaped to head the
cross. Baharmast signaled for a penalty, which Rekdal converted
with a calm that his fellow citizens would not share as they
joyfully streamed into the streets of Oslo to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
