<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHOCOLATE-SMEARED-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CHOCOLATE-SMEARED WOMAN': THERE'S STILL NO VANILLA IN A FINLEY
ENCOUNTER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Much attention has been given to Karen Finley's body,
or at least to what she does with it in public. In her new
performance piece, ``The Return of the Chocolate-Smeared Woman,''
now at the Flea Theater in Manhattan, every inch of that body is
visible. And yes, it is again lathered up in some chocolatey
substance (you can tell that it's chocolate by the smell), a
not-so-sentimental nod to the routine that made her a figure of
angry debate on the floor of the U.S. Senate eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Finley's raw, singular style finally has less to do with
her naked body than with her voice. Or rather, one should say,
voices. There are several of them: a breathy, Marilyn-like purr; a
dominating, nasal bark; an eardrum-wounding scream; and an aching,
evangelical moan.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Finley shifts among these voices, often with an impatient
abruptness, as though none of them really fit, each seems connected
to the others in a dangerous, frustrating chain of identities.
Sexual passivity turns into sexual aggression, which escalates into
strident, out-of-control anger. The end of this cycle, with the
voice that Ms. Finley does best, is usually pain, shame and an
unspeakable sorrow. It is by no means the sound of a self-centered
crybaby; it has a wide, appalled reach of empathy.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Ms. Finley continues to deserve attention in ways
that go beyond her status as the object of the wrath of Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., and others who held her up as an example of how the
National Endowment for the Arts was misspending its funds. ``The
Return of the Chocolate-Smeared Woman,'' directed (as much as one
directs Ms. Finley) by Jim Simpson for the Bat Theater Company and
featuring a sort of backup group of swimwear-clad dancers called
the Furballs, isn't always easy to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Finley's mission, after all, is to make people
uncomfortable. This is achieved not only through anatomical
explicitness, both physical and verbal, but by her insistence on
being the opposite of a polished performer. ``Return'' is
punctuated throughout with acts of self-sabotage. Ms. Finley
frequently interrupts her monologues, which she reads from loose
sheets of paper, to criticize herself before starting over. She
demands that the audience, which sits on plastic buckets because
the Flea Theater is being renovated, share her self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``This is experimental theater!'' &LR;  she yells, by way of
explanation, after asking someone near the stage to readjust a
music stand for her. Wearing nothing but bikini briefs, a pink
feather boa, silver spiked heels and the obligatory coat of
chocolate, she hawks the chance to taste that coat for $20 a lick.
(She says she needs taxi fare.)
</P>
<P>
   Only one person obliged the night I saw the show: a young man
who had only $7 and change. Ms. Finley accepted his bid and told
the man, who had put his tongue on the middle of her leg, that he
could go higher if he wanted to. He did.
</P>
<P>
   That accomplished, Ms. Finley proceeds to explore the chafed
underbelly of this sort of self-objectification. She tells stories,
in rough-hewn prose, of alcoholism and the value of ugliness and
butchered veal calves and rape and self-mutilation. She delivers an
overly long fantasy sequence in which she is the much-sought-after
erotic plaything of politicians who include Helms, President
Clinton, and Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass.; she describes their
particular tastes in unstinting detail. You can only imagine what
Helms, in Ms. Finley's version of him, is into. Revenge takes
unlikely forms.
</P>
<P>
   As sexual as much of this is, none of it is sexy. In Ms.
Finley's world, kinks and fetishism are born of childhood abuse,
emotional neglect and anger. She has traveled this territory
before, and there's not much new in ``Return.'' It's basically a
declaration that she is still here. She includes a couple of
``greatest hits'' routines, both loud laments for the anguished
outcasts of a humiliation-driven society; they remain her strongest
material.
</P>
<P>
   Despite (or because of) the publicity she has received, and
despite her fiercely vivid presence, Ms. Finley is still not a
widely marketable commodity. Other performance artists, she notes
(in her screaming voice), have gotten their own HBO specials. She
has met with a number of agents, she says, one of whom proposed she
appear in a female version of ``Animal House.'' Ms. Finley was
right to think the agent misunderstood her sensibility. Though she
can on occasion be very funny indeed, Ms. Finley is not fun. Life,
as she limns it, is too brutal to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN OF THE CHOCOLATE-SMEARED WOMAN
</P>
<P>
   By Karen Finley; directed by Jim Simpson; sets by Kyle Chepulis;
lighting by Andrew Hill and Chepulis; sound by Mike Nolan; costumes
by Matthew Bedell; choreography by Christine Buscemi; stage
manager, Katherine Lee Boyer; technical direction by David M.
Smith; produced by Dan Dzindzihashvili and Simpson. Presented by
the Bat Theater Company, at 41 White Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Karen Finley and the Furballs: Kathryn Benson, Daniel
Gurian, Jun Kim, Nicole Kovacs, Philippe Leong, Angela Tweed, Nikki
Wooster, Sarah Yorra and Pamela Zimmerman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
