<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3230 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSENT-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      06-23 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSENT-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COURT THROWS OUT PLANNED PARENTHOOD LAWSUIT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
and POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas Supreme Court on Tuesday threw out a
Planned Parenthood lawsuit challenging the constitutionality of a
state law that would have withheld state funding for birth control
and other prescription pills for minors without parental consent.
</P>
<P>
   The court, however, stopped short of actually determining
whether the law is unconstitutional. The justices ruled only that
state District Judge Scott McCown of Austin had jumped the gun when
he ruled that way last year.
</P>
<P>
   In August, McCown found in a lawsuit brought by Planned
Parenthood of Houston and Southeast Texas Inc. that the parental
consent law violated the state constitution's ban on amending or
repealing general law through the budget. That was because
lawmakers had added it as a last-minute provision to the state
spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, however, said McCown's ruling was premature
because it was based on hypothetical arguments about what could or
might happen rather than on any real loss of funds or services.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Tuesday's ruling is expected to have little or no
impact on minors' ability to get prescriptions without a parent's
consent because the Texas Department of Health had already found a
way to abide by the letter of the law without curtailing services.
The department simply shifted the source of funding for such
services to federal programs that did not require state matching
funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that there's no parental consent requirement and
everything goes on like it always did, getting funded,'' said David
Duggins, an attorney who had represented Planned Parenthood.
``We're kind of pleased. We feel like we've accomplished our goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we would have preferred that the court go ahead and
say this is unconstitutional, affirm Judge McCown's ruling, but
absent that this pretty much gets us where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas provides family planning services to about 7,500 minors a
year, said Health Department spokesman Doug McBride. Prior to the
rider in the 1997 spending bill, Texas had paid for such services
from state Medicaid funds, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In writing for the majority, Justice Deborah Hankinson wrote,
``A case is not ripe when its resolution depends on contingent or
hypothetical facts, or upon events that have not yet come to
pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood had argued that the state law jeopardized
more than $90 million in federal aid for Texas because federal
regulations prohibit any requirement for parental consent. But the
justices noted that no federal funds had been cut off and federal
officials had not indicated what they would do if Texas implemented
its current policy of paying for such services entirely from
federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The record does not support Planned Parenthood's assertions,''
the majority opinion said. It cited Health Department testimony
before McCown that Planned Parenthood and its clients would
experience no change in services, but that only the funding source
would be changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This testimony is not sufficient to support the conclusion
that harm to Planned Parenthood is imminent,'' the court found.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Raul Gonzalez, in a concurring opinion, said he would
have barred Planned Parenthood from filing suit in the first place
because Planned Parenthood has no standing to represent the
interests of minor children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Texas law ... only the parents or guardians of a minor
may represent their legal interests,'' Gonzalez wrote. Justice Greg
Abbott joined Gonzalez in the concurrence.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Gonzalez said Planned Parenthood ``does not
identify any implicit right or entitlement owing it under the Texas
Constitution or (state law) ... even if federal funds are cut
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Last session, state lawmakers added a last-minute rider in the
800-page budget bill that required parental consent before state
funds could be used to provide birth control, medications for
sexually transmitted diseases or any other prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Nenney, a vice president of Planned Parenthood, said the
Health Department, while continuing prescriptions for minors, is
taking money from funds intended to provide family planning
programs for low-income women.
</P>
<P>
   ``TDH, to their credit, is doing everything they can to keep
services available to teens,'' Nenney said. ``There is a huge clash
here between good public health policy and the will of the
Legislature, which is counter to the will of the people of Texas
who support family planning services to women of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's a ridiculous effort on the part of the Texas
Legislature. It's bad public policy and the Texas Department of
Health knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Steve Ogden, R-Bryan, who sponsored the parental
consent provision, said it is ``a small but significant victory''
that the court didn't find the rider unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden told The Associated Press that he hopes the ruling will
spur the 1999 Legislature into action. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
