<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CD-BABIES-COX     06-23 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-BABIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ga. newborns to get soothing music
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At a news conference in his office today, Georgia Gov.
Zell Miller plans to present a newborn with a copy of ``Build Your
Baby's Brain Through the Power of Music.''
</P>
<P>
   The classical music album, a pet project of Miller's, will be
handed out to all new Georgia parents, starting in July. It's being
provided free to the state by Sony.
</P>
<P>
   In proposing albums for babies, Miller cites studies showing
classical music can stimulate babies' brain development and, as
children grow, help them excel in math. Classical music is also
considered soothing to fussy infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought the children of Georgia were the smartest
anywhere. With this program, we can now give them an even greater
head start,'' Miller said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Liner notes on the album include a short note from the governor
urging parents to play the music for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Critics, including conservative radio host Rush Limbaugh,
laughed when Miller announced his proposal in January. But Sony
took him seriously and offered to produce and distribute the albums
at no cost to taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The first shipment of cassettes and CDs is expected to arrive at
hospitals by July 4. Wellstar Kennestone Hospital in Marietta, Ga.
already has 100 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put in an order for 5,000. That's about how many babies we
deliver a year,'' said Jill Cain, a spokeswoman for Wellstar.
</P>
<P>
   Miller isn't the only person to promote Beethoven for babies.
Although lullabies remain popular among the diaper and pacifier
set, classical music is starting to inch its way into nurseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has become somewhat of a phenomenon,'' said Bradley
Bamberger, classical music writer for Billboard. ``Almost every
major company has packaged classical for children.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony compiled the music for ``Build Your Baby's Brain'' from its
classical catalog. The company's costs to produce and distribute
the albums weren't available.
</P>
<P>
   But the investment could pay off in increased sales of other
albums. (Sony doesn't plan to market ``Build Your Baby's Brain.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a smart idea for record labels to donate music for
records like these,'' Bamberger said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sony has a vested interest in new emerging audiences, which
start with children. They've got a very large commitment to
classical,'' said Michael Greene, a former Atlantan and president
of the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, Sony has a large presence in Georgia. The plant in
Carrollton, Ga. is one of the largest, best in world.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Russ DeVault contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
