<HEADER>
A3233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REPORTERS-PROSECUTORS     06-23 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPORTERS-PROSECUTORS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: RELATIONSHIP BETWEEN REPORTERS AND PROSECUTORS IS SUBTLE
AND MESSY
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is one of the least talked about corners of journalism: the
relationship of reporters and their prosecution sources. But the
debate in recent days over how much and what kind of information
the independent counsel Kenneth Starr gave reporters about his
investigation of the president has put an uncomfortable spotlight
on the ties between journalists and prosecutors, ties that often
lead to information and sometimes to misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rules that strictly limit what prosecutors are permitted
to say publicly, there is a steady stream of reports describing
investigations and prosecutions across the country. Those news
accounts almost always appear orderly and certain.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews, reporters and former prosecutors said the
process was far more subtle and messy than it appeared. It is
built, some of them said, on often unspoken pacts among people who
advance their careers by getting information before the public.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, prosecutors are able to enhance their
crime-fighting image by reassuring the public that troubling cases
are being investigated. For intensely competitive reporters, leaks
by definition provide an edge over those from other news
organizations and even within their own newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The subtleties of the process, some of the reporters and former
prosecutors said, help explain how information about Starr's
investigation could have reached reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have this image that you call a prosecutor and say
`What are you working on?' and they spill,'' said Joel Kaplan, an
investigative reporter for years in Tennessee and Chicago who is
now chairman of the newspaper department at the S.I. Newhouse
School of Public Communications at Syracuse University. ``That
never happens. It's really a dance and it is often a matter of
having personal relationships built up over a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on prosecutions often involves journalists piecing
together fragments of information, bluffing that they know more
than they do and appealing to ego as well as altruism. Many
prosecutors are extremely reluctant to provide even the most basic
information to journalists, with some keeping reporters at arm's
length.
</P>
<P>
   More often than most people realize, reporters said, it is
defense lawyers who provide information, some that may even appear
damaging to their own clients. Then reporters often get figurative
winks from prosecutors or prosecution investigators to confirm
accounts assembled from many sources.
</P>
<P>
   It is a process that often involves the intuition of a reporter.
The reporter might feel, for example, that the self-interest of a
prosecutor or a mid-level investigator could be served by a
detailing of some aspect of an investigation. Or the reporter might
sense that a defense lawyer wants to provide a fuller account of a
damning detail so that blame is spread more widely.
</P>
<P>
   It is a to-and-fro that has existed for decades, becoming an art
form in the Watergate era and advancing to even higher levels of
refinement in the investigation-clogged Clinton era. It is a
process, some journalists said, that shows why reporters, who need
prosecutors to get their articles and broadcast reports, rarely
scrutinize prosecutors as rigorously as they do other public
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The current intense focus on prosecution-press ties began when
Starr was quoted in an article in a new media magazine, Brill's
Content, acknowledging that he briefed reporters. Starr was then
attacked by presidential aides, which led his allies to say he had
to give information to reporters to counter a campaign of press
manipulation from the White House. Besieged by critics, Starr
attacked the article's author, Steven Brill, saying Brill had
distorted his comments.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the White House intern Monica Lewinsky, whose
relationship with the president is being investigated, the
accusations from both the White House and Starr's office that the
other organization is disclosing information represent a typical
pattern in high-profile cases. Each side tries to tailor new
reports to make its cause appear more just and to counter
disclosures from the other.
</P>
<P>
   Several former prosecutors said it could be tempting to disclose
information to help an investigation. A startling news report can
signal the strength of a case and persuade a defendant to testify
against others. In the insider-trading cases that rocked Wall
Street in the 1980s, a drumbeat of news reports appeared to help
persuade traders and investment bankers to turn on each other.
</P>
<P>
   Often, mid-level prosecutors or investigators have some reason
to talk. They may hope to goad superiors to be more aggressive in
an investigation or to try to make their agencies look good, some
of the former prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the government,'' said Thomas Puccio, who was
the chief prosecutor in the so-called Abscam investigation of
members of Congress in the early 1980s, ``the investigative
agencies, particularly the FBI, viewed their success in getting big
budgets from Congress as tied to how much positive publicity they
got.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Scafidi, a spokesman for the FBI, said he would not
comment on what happened in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the FBI and most investigative agencies,'' Scafidi said,
``are not going to initially give information that's going to ruin
an investigation or damage someone's reputation. But if someone has
leaked and we're getting calls for verification, sometimes we will
discuss things with reporters so they have a context; we don't want
wrong information going out.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers, some reporters say, often begin the process by
telling reporters about investigations involving their clients or
providing details about cases that have already attracted some
attention. The motivations range from vanity to attempts at
management of the news. Defense lawyers are not subject to the
strict limitations that apply to prosecutors and are often privy to
extensive information.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers compete with each other for clients and they
often benefit from warm relations with reporters. A reporter might
not name a lawyer in an article concerning information obtained
this way but might mention the lawyer in some other context that
would help cement a reputation as an important legal player.
</P>
<P>
   The reporters and the defense lawyers often see themselves as
members of the permanent establishment, several reporters said,
with the lawyers' clients mere transients. Sometimes, those
reporters said, defense lawyers seem to be disclosing information
that might be harmful to their clients or other people purely to
build their relationships with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters pursue those relationships as well as relationships
with prosecutors because such ties, as much as hard information,
are their stock-in-trade and a means to their own advancement. In
newsrooms, where it is sometime impolitic to bandy about the names
of sources too publicly, reporters often speak of a prosecution or
defense lawyer who is supplying information as ``my guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Personal ambition is one motivation, but defense lawyers also
use the disclosures to advance strategies for their clients. It is
possible to diminish the impact of negative information about a
client if it comes out before the announcement of an indictment.
</P>
<P>
   From a prosecutor's vantage point, the defense ``spin'' can be
harmful. Among other things, it can influence potential or sitting
jurors, said John Volz, who was the U.S. attorney in New Orleans
for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Volz said he never disclosed secret grand jury information. But
he said he often spoke to reporters, both for attribution and as an
unidentified source, and believed most prosecutors did.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the defense puts out a story, they put their spin on it,''
Volz said, ``and I think someone from the government has an
obligation to step forward and correct the misinformation.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Possley, a reporter for The Chicago Tribune, said top
prosecutors were often ambitious, and as such were savvy about the
details of news coverage. They often recognize, he said, that
because of the nature of journalistic competition, a news
organization will more prominently display an article if it has it
exclusively rather than from an official announcement that goes to
all news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, some reporters said, a prosecutor's desire to
get information out is so strong that the prosecutor will present
an entire account of an investigation to a reporter. One senior
Washington journalist who spoke on the condition of anonymity
recalled that a federal prosecutor who was investigating a friend
of the governor of the prosecutor's state described his
investigation with a promise of anonymity. The prosecutor told the
journalist he had been receiving political pressure from Washington
to curtail his investigation and said he believed news coverage of
the investigation would make such pressure too risky.
</P>
<P>
   Far more common, the reporters said, is a back-and-forth in
which reporters use clues to try to assemble a version of events.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Pound, a longtime investigative reporter at several of
the country's big newspapers who is now at USA Today in Washington,
said he often spoke to investigators or mid-level prosecutors,
checking out tidbits he had learned from defense lawyers and other
sources.
</P>
<P>
   He said he often pieced together an account from six or seven
people and then called someone he knew who was working on the case
for the government. ``I'll say, `Am I there yet?' And they'll wave
you in the right direction once you've done your homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Several former prosecutors said that among federal prosecutors
there was strong social and professional pressure to conform to
Justice Department guidelines prohibiting the disclosure of grand
jury information.
</P>
<P>
   But even among those who said they had never disclosed such
information to reporters, there was widespread acknowledgment that
other prosecutors violated the rules. Some suspected abuses lead to
internal investigations in prosecutors' offices, but they rarely
uncover the source of the disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it is prosecutor's ego,'' said Gregory Wallance, a
former federal prosecutor in Brooklyn, N.Y. ``They think they can
present what they're doing in a more flattering light'' through
leaks.
</P>
<P>
   When Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York was the U.S. attorney in
Manhattan in the 1980s, he heatedly denied that he had leaked
information. But the allegations were so extensive that some judges
attacked him for the tactic in their court opinions.
</P>
<P>
   One judge, Kevin Thomas Duffy, wrote bitterly that Giuliani had
pressed to remove the judge from an important corruption case
because of ``my long-established and often stated belief that cases
should be tried in the courtroom and not in the newspapers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-GOLF-FEATURE     06-23 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GOLF-FEATURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fate delivered title to Janzen
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't just win a U.S. Open. You survive it. It is a mental,
more than physical grind, for seven days. From the moment a player
settles his spikes into the turf of a U.S. Open venue on the first
practice day, he knows that his life indeed might never be the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about winning when I teed off (Sunday),''
Lee Janzen said later that afternoon through a haze of tears. ``I
figured I'd be too nervous if I thought about that.''
</P>
<P>
   This from a guy who already had won a U.S. Open five years
before.
</P>
<P>
   Just imagine if Janzen had missed the green at the 18th Sunday.
Or yanked the 3-footer for par. There are no gimmes in a U.S. Open.
There are no favorites. Fate, not the USGA, handles all official
rulings. Janzen's ball drops out of a tree. Payne Stewart's
trickles into a divot filled with sand. No different than Tom
Lehman's drive on the 18th at Oakland Hills in '96, bouncing into
the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Other forces take over. It happens every year. For three days
Janzen and The Olympic Club's cruel 17th hole are as compatible as
sourdough and ketchup. He manages a bogey, followed by two
double-bogeys. Sunday Janzen two-putts for par when his legs should
have gone Goodyear. On 18, the scariest short hole in golf, he
eventually stands over a 3-footer and, gasp, thinks the
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I putted out the short putt, I thought, `This could be
it. This could be the putt that would win the U.S. Open,''' he
said. ``That's the last thing you want to say to yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, ask Scott Hoch or Hubert Green, who each lost a Masters
because of putts that are kicked away in your Saturday foursome.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the 98th U.S. Open, it also becomes apparent
that:
</P>
<P>
   _ For everything that golf's more recent, earth-toned,
mostly-hip fashions have done to destroy old stereotypes, Payne
Stewart sets back the process a few years every time he shows up.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously, should a man dressed like a thermos win a U.S. Open?
</P>
<P>
   _ For all of Colin Montgomerie's attitude, some of what bothers
him at major championships is not self-inflicted. A fan called him
``fat boy'' last week. Another said, ``Go home, Monty.'' When the
Scot asked who said that, the fellow identified himself at the
ropes. When Monty asked why, the man said, ``Because of the Ryder
Cup.'' Replied Montgomerie, ``The only thing that happened at the
Ryder Cup is that our guys beat your guys.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Casey Martin is the real deal. In his first U.S. Open, despite
all the mess about which cart might keep him from flipping over,
Martin tied for 23rd and finished two shots better than Mark
O'Meara, the Masters champion. You will see Martin again on the PGA
Tour next week at the Greater Hartford Open, where he accepted a
sponsor exemption.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
