<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-HAWKS     06-23 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-HAWKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks have option after option for NBA draft
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About this NBA draft ... .
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Hawks figure they can go a few different ways by the
time their number _ 20 _ is called tonight. They can trade up; they
can hold their ground; they can drop down and get more picks.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for conviction?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's that kind of draft,'' general manager Pete Babcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks have brought about 20 players to Atlanta, tested them,
worked them, discarded some, set up a wish list.
</P>
<P>
   In a draft that contains no single dominant selection, this
field does offer some help to teams that have a core of good
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four players under contract,'' Babcock notes. ``That means we
can go just about anywhere in this draft and improve our team.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nice, but confusing. Monday, Babcock was in his CNN
Center office at 5:30 a.m. He was still returning phone calls on
the way home about 9:30 that night. He endured a similar day
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For all this work, the Hawks have narrowed their target to 13
players, provided they hold at pick 20. Their job will be made
easier, because at least half that number will be taken in the
teens.
</P>
<P>
   If they trade up, they can be more ambitious. If they trade
down, they might be able to land two of the players they like.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Hawks will not trade their four holdovers _ Dikembe
Mutombo, Mookie Blaylock, Ed Gray and Steve Smith _ Babcock can
offer future picks as coin.
</P>
<P>
   Owning lottery-proof picks from Detroit (14 or higher) and
Sacramento (16 or higher), ``we might be able to package something
to get into the low teens or acquire more picks,'' he said. ``Since
our roster is so small, it's a good time to do it.'' Orlando and
Houston have three picks each.
</P>
<P>
   Here is the field:
</P>
<P>
   Centers Radoslav Nesterovic, Kinder Bologna; and Michael Doleac,
Utah; forwards Ruben Patterson, Cincinnati; Pat Garrity, Notre
Dame; Brian Skinner, Baylor; Matt Harpring, Georgia Tech; Andre
Patterson, Indiana; and Roshown McLeod, Duke; and guards Michael
Dickerson, Arizona; Corey Benjamin, Oregon State; Tyronn Lue,
Nebraska; Ricky Davis, Iowa; and Bryce Drew, Valparaiso.
</P>
<P>
   Of that group, the Hawks' wish list includes Doleac and Garrity,
both excellent shooters and defensive liabilities. Skinner is
extremely bright, very athletic and competitive and able to play
forward and center but is limited offensively.
</P>
<P>
   The next grouping includes Patterson, the best defender in the
draft, and a couple of kids _ Benjamin, 20, a slasher with improved
shooting skills, and Davis, a marvelous athlete who will be 19 in
September. Georgia Tech's Matt Harpring also would fit here.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks also have some interest in Lue, a promising point
guard and a terrific athlete, and in Drew, a scorer whose
point-guard skills mighty not be NBA quality.
</P>
<P>
   Nesterovic, a highly-skilled face-up shooter, is a Slovenian who
played in Bologna of the Italian League last season. There are
questions about his availability for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
