<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-THRASHER     06-23 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-THRASHER </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   980623 ATLANTA, GA: Don Waddell (sq) was named General Manager
of Atlanta's National Hockey League expansion team, the Thrashers,
at a press conference at the Omni Hotel in Atlanta, GA on Monday
afternoon, June 23, 1998. (PHOTO BY ROBERT ABRAHAMSON/SPECIAL) for
use in SPT on 6/24.
</P>
<P>
   Don
</P>
<P>
   Waddell, Thrashers GM, plans to emphasize speed in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers to emulate Detroit's example
</P>
<P>
   Headline goes here on Thrashers
</P>
<P>
   By Jeff Schultz
</P>
<P>
   STAFF WRITER
</P>
<P>
   Without a coach or a player under contract, or even somebody to
sharpen skates, Don Waddell nonetheless spent his first day as an
NHL general manager attempting to set the tone for a franchise
still 16 months away from playing its first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right off the bat, our players have to understand what our
commitment is to winning,'' Waddell said after being introduced as
the Thrashers' general manager. ``By the time we start this thing
in 1999, expansion is gone. We'll be a first-year team that's
expected to win. ... Expansion is not a reason for losing.''
</P>
<P>
   For a career minor-league defenseman who played only one game in
the NHL with Los Angeles _ he was knocked down by a teammate on his
first shift, and the opponents scored _ Waddell hardly is
associated with losing. He built IHL expansion teams in San Diego
and Orlando into winning organizations and twice won honors as top
executive; turned around another struggling minor-league team in
Flint, Mich.; and spent the past season as assistant general
manager of the Detroit Red Wings, who won their second straight
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Without saying he will be able to secure the services of Sergei
Fedorov, Steve Yzerman and Chris Osgood, Waddell plans to mimick
the Red Wings in organizational philosophy and playing style. He
wants to build the team around speed, which clearly became the
trend this past NHL season and favored high-scoring teams like the
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in speed and attacking the puck,'' he said. ``The
(defensive) trap is really (overrated). I like in-your-face type of
hockey. Trying to win the game 1-0, 2-0 is not the best thing for
your team or when you're trying to get new fans.''
</P>
<P>
   At 39, Waddell becomes the second-youngest general manager in
the NHL, to Washington's George McPhee (38). But his immediate
duties will not come as a Thrasher but a Red Wing: His contract
does not expire until July 1, so he will accompany the Red Wings to
Buffalo for the amateur draft on Saturday. But he also will spend
the weekend contacting potential candidates for the scout staff,
which he hopes to have put together by mid-July. Waddell said a
coach likely won't be hired until after the 1998-99 season because
``all the best ones are under contract right now to somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell's first hire will be an amateur scouting director, three
scouts in Canada (based in Ontario, Quebec and somewhere in the
West), one for U.S. colleges, one in Sweden and one in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The first realization he was in a novice hockey market came when
team executives showed him 10 offices that could be set up for the
scouting staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them we don't need the offices,'' Waddell said. ``We
want our scouts on the road seeing games, not talking on the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore on Waddell E8
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3242 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      06-23 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Whatever ailment Shane Reynolds came down with must be contagious.
By the fourth inning Tuesday, it was the Minnesota Twins who were
sick to their stomachs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Originally scratched from the starting lineup after spending
Sunday night in the hospital with a case of food poisoning,
Reynolds arrived at the Astrodome on Tuesday 10 pounds lighter and
a whole lot sharper. Though not exactly what the doctor ordered,
the righthander gave a gutsy performance with seven shutout
innings, and the Astros provided plenty of offense in a 9-0 victory
over the Twins before a matinee crowd of 27,157.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, coupled with the Chicago Cubs' 5-4 loss to
Cleveland, increased the Astros' lead in the National League
Central to a season-high five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I felt good enough to pitch, (but) I was tired,''
said Reynolds, who suffered an attack of gastroenteritis two days
earlier and was not in uniform for the series opener with Minnesota
on Monday. ``I felt good. But I didn't feel wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if he thought 24 hours earlier he would be on the
mound, Reynolds replied, ``I was in a hospital with an IV, and I
felt real bad with some kind of food poisoning. It drains you and
makes you feel weak. I stayed on the IV for six or seven hours. I
got a little better, enough to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Twins manager Tom Kelly would probably like to see Reynolds'
medical chart after his squad managed to get only one runner past
first base off him _ on a fourth-inning double by Marty Cordova.
Reynolds (8-5) retired 10 of the first 11 batters he faced and
allowed four hits and no walks in his seven innings. He also had
six strikeouts while snapping a personal two-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came right out of the hospital and straight to the
pitcher's mound,'' Kelly said. ``We couldn't do a thing with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros had their way with 37-year-old journeyman
Bob Tewksbury (4-9), who was tagged for five runs and eight hits in
1 innings. Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio and Carl Everett went a
combined 8-for-10 with seven RBIs in leading the Astros' 13-hit
assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just another example of how unpredictable things are,''
Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``I think among our players we
had one that had success against Tewksbury (catcher Brad Ausmus is
hitting .455 lifetime against the Twins righthander), and he wasn't
playing. Yet we go out and score all these runs off him. You never
know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds arrived at the Astrodome two hours before Tuesday's
12:35 start and was evaluated by team trainers. After warming up,
he appeared tired, and the Astros were prepared to start lefthanded
reliever C.J. Nitkowski. Dierker and pitching coach Vern Ruhle met
with Reynolds, and 20 minutes before the first pitch, the decision
was made to start him.
</P>
<P>
   A seven-inning outing surpassed all expectations, including
those of Dierker, who just wanted to get as many innings as
possible out of Reynolds to save the bullpen for the Astros'
upcoming five-game trip to Colorado and Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they were going to use the bullpen anyway, so why
not let me go two, three or four innings? If I give you five
innings, we're lucky, and then you don't have to burn the whole
bullpen,'' said Reynolds, who threw 97 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Nitkowski pitched two scoreless innings to preserve the Astros'
sixth shutout of the season and sixth win in eight games against
the American League.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros left little doubt about the outcome early, scoring
nine runs in the first four innings off Tewksbury and Dan Serafini.
The Astros went up 3-0 in the first on a two-run double by Bagwell
and an RBI double by Everett. In the second, Bill Spiers (2-for-4)
and Bagwell delivered run-scoring singles to put the Astros up 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put away all the scalpels in the training room, so I
can't slit my wrist,'' said Tewksbury, 1-2 with a 6.64 ERA in his
last three starts. ``I guess I have to get on the plane with the
rest of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio, who was 3-for-3 before leaving the game in the fourth
inning, had a two-run double in the third off Serafini. The Astros
completed the scoring in the fourth on an RBI single by Everett and
Tony Eusebio's double-play grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Cranking up the offense was the least the Astros could do for a
sick teammate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sucked it up for the team,'' Biggio said of Reynolds. ``He
needed to go out there and pitch. That's why he's one of the top
two pitchers on our team. You have to do those things and sometimes
put the team above yourself. Being able to get runs early always
allows a pitcher to put his mind at ease.''
</P>
<P>
   Or in Reynolds' case, his stomach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
