</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NBA-DRAFT-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1998 NBA Draft: Who wants to go first?
</P>
<P>
   By Curtis Bunn
</P>
<P>
   C. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Has there ever been an NBA draft in which so many
teams with high picks were looking to trade them? Perhaps, but not
likely. Even the Los Angeles Clippers, who hold the No. 1 selection
in tonight's annual draft, have made countless inquiries about
dealing the top slot for veteran help.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, it speaks to the eligible talent, or lack of
it. So scattered were teams' thoughts a day before the event in
Vancouver that a mock draft is bound to be a mockery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a weak year, but it's not weak for guys who are
projects,'' was the way Minnesota general manager Rob Babcock put
it. ``Anyone picking 12 and beyond had to look at a lot of
players.''
</P>
<P>
   The general consensus is that, barring trades, the Clippers will
take Arizona point guard Mike Bibby with the first pick. Los
Angeles could surprise and take Pacific center Michael Olowokandi
if it thinks it will not re-sign free-agent center Isaac Austin.
</P>
<P>
   With the second pick, the Grizzlies could go for smooth Kansas
forward Paul Pierce, matching him in the frontcourt with Marietta's
Shareef Abdur-Rahim and center Bryant Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Nuggets, selecting third, would take Pierce or
Olowkandi, whichever one is remaining. Or maybe not. It's that wide
open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're basically going to get as good a player at
(pick) three or four as you would at one or two,'' said Dan Issel,
general manager and coach of the Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   What might turn out to be most interesting about this draft is
the selection of those players whose stock rose during pre-draft
workouts or tournaments. North Carolina guard Vince Carter was so
dynamic physically that he had Sacramento Kings personnel officials
shaking their heads. Carter astonished with his leaping ability
during a drill and impressed with his jump-shooting ability from
3-point range. The feeling is that he could be another Tar Heel who
will flourish _ a la Michael Jordan, James Worthy, Walter Davis _
away from UNC's structured system.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the case of former Florida guard Jason Williams,
who played for three colleges and was dismissed from the Gators
this season because he failed a drug test. Williams has been
sparkling in workouts, and his playmaking skills and ability score
from the perimeter at 6-foot-1 are major attributes. He could go as
high as No. 7, to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   At least four of the five high-school players in the draft
should be taken. The first could be a foreign prospect, 6-11 Dirk
Nowitzki, 19, of Germany, who has scouts excited about his ability
to score inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   Rashard Lewis of Alief-Elsik High in Alief, Texas, is projected
to be taken as high as No. 14 by the Houston Rockets. Lewis is a
6-10 forward with a guard's game. His perimeter shooting ability
rates him higher than Al Harrington, a 6-8 forward from New Jersey,
who might have attended Georgia Tech if he had selected the NCAA
over the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The other prep star who could be drafted is Korleone Young, a
probable second-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
