<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THRASHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers to emulate Detroit's example
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Without a coach or a player under contract, or even
somebody to sharpen skates, Don Waddell nonetheless spent his first
day as an NHL general manager attempting to set the tone for a
franchise still 16 months away from playing its first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right off the bat, our players have to understand what our
commitment is to winning,'' Waddell said after being introduced as
the Thrashers' general manager. ``By the time we start this thing
in 1999, expansion is gone. We'll be a first-year team that's
expected to win. ... Expansion is not a reason for losing.''
</P>
<P>
   For a career minor-league defenseman who played only one game in
the NHL with Los Angeles _ he was knocked down by a teammate on his
first shift, and the opponents scored _ Waddell hardly is
associated with losing. He built IHL expansion teams in San Diego
and Orlando into winning organizations and twice won honors as top
executive; turned around another struggling minor-league team in
Flint, Mich.; and spent the past season as assistant general
manager of the Detroit Red Wings, who won their second straight
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Without saying he will be able to secure the services of Sergei
Fedorov, Steve Yzerman and Chris Osgood, Waddell plans to mimick
the Red Wings in organizational philosophy and playing style. He
wants to build the team around speed, which clearly became the
trend this past NHL season and favored high-scoring teams like the
Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in speed and attacking the puck,'' he said. ``The
(defensive) trap is really (overrated). I like in-your-face type of
hockey. Trying to win the game 1-0, 2-0 is not the best thing for
your team or when you're trying to get new fans.''
</P>
<P>
   At 39, Waddell becomes the second-youngest general manager in
the NHL, to Washington's George McPhee (38). But his immediate
duties will not come as a Thrasher but a Red Wing: His contract
does not expire until July 1, so he will accompany the Red Wings to
Buffalo for the amateur draft on Saturday. But he also will spend
the weekend contacting potential candidates for the scout staff,
which he hopes to have put together by mid-July. Waddell said a
coach likely won't be hired until after the 1998-99 season because
``all the best ones are under contract right now to somebody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell's first hire will be an amateur scouting director, three
scouts in Canada (based in Ontario, Quebec and somewhere in the
West), one for U.S. colleges, one in Sweden and one in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The first realization he was in a novice hockey market came when
team executives showed him 10 offices that could be set up for the
scouting staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them we don't need the offices,'' Waddell said. ``We
want our scouts on the road seeing games, not talking on the
phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
