<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: New York Yankees
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When: 7:35 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Where: Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   TV, radio: ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Probable starting pitchers: RHP Kevin Millwood (9-3, 4.43; first
appearance vs. Yankees) vs. RHP David Cone (9-2, 4.82; 9-3, 2.68
lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: As the four-game set moves to Atlanta, Millwood is coming
off the briefest, and worst, outing of his young big-league career.
Friday in Montreal, he lasted just 1 1/3 innings, as nine of the 12
Expos he faced reached base. Millwood gave up seven hits --
including back-to-back homers by Chris Widger and Shane Andrews --
and seven earned runs. It was the fourth time he's made consecutive
starts against the same opponent, and the third-straight time that
team has pounded him. Cone's 14th start of the year is his 14th
lifetime against Atlanta, all as a Met. He took the loss Friday in
a 7-4 defeat in Cleveland, going 5 1/3 innings and allowing eight
hits, including two homers, and five earned runs. That ended a
career-best, nine-game personal winning streak for Cone, who opened
the season 9-1 for the second time in his career. Since joining the
Yankees on July 28, 1995, Cone is 37-12, 3.41, and the Yanks are
11-2 in his 13 starts this season, averaging 7.7 runs per start.
Now he returns to Atlanta, where he beat the Braves 5-2 in Game 3
of the 1996 World Series to start the Yankees' four-game comeback.
</P>
