<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves keep Weiss, son in mind during important series
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - His jersey still hung in his locker Tuesday here at
Yankee Stadium. His cleats clean and polished, his glove waiting to
be slipped on.
</P>
<P>
   But Walt Weiss is far from baseball these days.
</P>
<P>
   While his teammates faced the Yankees again in this much hyped
interleague series, Braves shortstop Walt Weiss remained at the
bedside of his son Brody, who is back in an Atlanta hospital
stricken with E. coli, a deadly strain of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves, however, are thinking of Weiss and his family,
especially little Brody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of time to think about it,'' said Denny Neagle.
``One of my families' best friends passed away last night from a
heart attack. I can't imagine what Walt must be going through. You
can't let baseball consume so much that you forget about everything
else. To think that he (Brody) might have (contracted) something
like this in a pool just blows my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Added John Smoltz, who has three young children, ``I've gone
through it with (someone in) my wife's family. He had leukemia. You
just have to hope and pray for Walt and his family. In a situation
like that, you wish you could switch with the child because you are
bigger and stronger. People take so much for granted. Something
like that doesn't hit home until it happens to someone close to
you. I've always said whatever happens to you as a family, there is
always others that are worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this is his first season with the Braves, Weiss has
become a very popular player in the clubhouse. One player he has
gotten close with is his double player partner, second baseman
Keith Lockhart, whose wife Lisa has visited the Weiss family at the
Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center the last few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to help,'' Lockhart said. ``I have a
three-year-old and it tears you up. This really puts the game in
perspective for you. When your kid is in a life and death situation
like that, every minute is crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga knows Weiss well, having
spent the four seasons in Colorado with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he is in love with his kids and is a really close with
them,'' Galarraga said. ``I really don't have words for this. I
just know you put your family first and baseball second. He's
probably not even looking at ESPN to see how we are doing, but is
just trying to help his kid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are not concerned about when Weiss will be back with
the club. They have told him to take as much time off as he needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I heard about what happen with Walt's kid, I felt like it
was mine,'' said Javier Lopez, who has a 2-year-old son. ``I felt
very, very scared, I felt like I could be in Walt's position right
now. I pray for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tom Glavine, who has a 3-year-old daughter, ``We can't
imagine what Walt is going through. A lot of us in here have young
kids and this puts things in perspective. The family is always the
most important thing. Always.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
