u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-NOTES24-COX     06-23 0485
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-NOTES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf Notebook
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duval appearance too late
</P>
<P>
   David Duval's game only appeared on alternating days at Olympic
_ 75-68-75-69. Unhappy with the way he struck the ball even during
the 68, Duval took his first full attempt on the range Sunday
morning and declared, ``Well, it's nice my golf swing finally
decided to show up.'' Although never a tournament factor, Duval,
with a tie for seventh that earned $83,794, regained his PGA Tour
money lead over Fred Couples by just over $60,000. It was by far
Duval's best Open finish. Previously, it was a tie for 48th last
year. ``I'm still trying to grasp it and learn about how I'm going
to approach (the Open) next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Undue criticism for Augusta National?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe somebody at Audubon magazine got turned down for a Masters
badge and has never forgotten about it. The publication's
July/August issue ranks golf courses in regard to environmental
friendliness and places Augusta National Golf Club on its ``bad''
list. Among other things, Audubon cites the fact that Augusta
National colors its ponds for television and hints that the club
puts its aquatic life in jeopardy. In truth, Augusta National uses
harmless food coloring in its ponds and is meticulous about
environmental standards. It even washes golf carts at a designated
area, for pesticide and fertilizer control. ``If anything,'' a club
spokesman said, ``we're overly careful. (Course superintendent)
Marsh (Benson) is a nut about things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Chip shots
</P>
<P>
   One of these days it would be nice if Tiger Woods actually
contended in a U.S. Open. Can he do nothing more than win
tournaments in Georgia? Woods, who tied for 19th in 1997, tied for
18th Sunday. He never was a factor at a course he said he knew as
well as any in California, having played there regularly in
college. But all he does during the tournament is complain about
drives he hit to the middle of the fairway that bounced into the
rough? How about playing for the tilt and aiming accordingly? If
you're keeping score at home, Woods now has compiled 13 straight
rounds in the 70s in major championships. ... Olympic sensation
Matt Kuchar of Georgia Tech has been invited to appear on ``The
Tonight Show with Jay Leno'' but isn't sure if it can be scheduled.
... Kuchar nervous? Hitting balls on the range Sunday he said,
``Hey, I heard (Georgia Tech's) Matt Harpring got drafted by the
Hawks.'' ... Of the PGA Tour's top 10 players in the all-around
competition (combined rankings of all categories), John Huston is a
runaway leader at 101, but three have Georgia connections.
Ex-Georgia Tech man Duval is second with 243, Sea Island's Davis
Love III is third (280), and Smyrna's Stewart Cink, another Tech
man, is 10th (322).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
