<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3252 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-ART-NYT &LR;      06-23 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEPTH AND UNCERTAINTY, RATHER THAN IMPACT, UNDERSCORE NBA DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(JT) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ Three years ago, while sitting in
his London apartment, Michael Olowokandi opened up the Peterson
Guide to American Colleges and Universities, turned to the letter
``P'' and dialed the telephone number of the first school his
finger came upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Michael Olowokandi, and I am 7-1, and I want to come play
basketball,'' he told an assistant coach at the University of the
Pacific in Stockton, Calif. ``The coach said `Well, we'll take
you.''' I was so happy. Organized basketball for the first time.
What a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, all the advance scouting in the universe goes for
naught.
</P>
<P>
   Three years after that conversation, Olowokandi (pronounced
Oh-Lo-Wuh-Candy) may be the first player taken in the 1998 National
Basketball Association draft. Wednesday at GM Place, either the
7-foot-1, 265-pound center or a player a foot shorter, Arizona
point guard Mike Bibby, will be selected by the Los Angeles
Clippers with the No. 1 pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be the icing on the cake after everything that has
happened to me,'' Olowokandi said Tuesday. ``What a story, no?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. If you're talking about the son of a Nigerian
diplomat living out a Horatio Alger fantasy, yes. But if it is a
dream realized for Olowokandi, it is a huge conundrum for most NBA
general managers.
</P>
<P>
   That a guy who had not played 5-on-5 basketball until two
seasons ago could be the No. 1 pick is disturbing, almost as
disconcerting as taking an undersized playmaker who has trouble
creating his own shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could be a lot of mistakes made at the top, but in the
middle of the draft you might end up with a better player than you
thought you were getting,'' said the NBA analyst and former coach
Kevin Loughery. ``Those first five or six picks, a lot of people
are going to be faced with the toughest decisions they've had in
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since the Sacramento Kings opted for Pervis Ellison in 1989
_ over Danny Ferry, Sean Elliot, Glen Rice and J.R. Reid _ has
there been such uncertainty with the top grouping of players.
</P>
<P>
   After Olowokandi and Bibby, duos from Kansas (Paul Pierce and
Raef LaFrentz) and North Carolina (Antawn Jamison and Vince Carter)
are expected to be taken in the top 10 along with the St. Louis
shooting guard Larry Hughes, Michigan's immovable Robert (Tractor)
Traylor and Utah's All-American center Michael Doleac.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando and Houston control the middle of the draft, adding to
the possibility of last-minute trades. Through prior trades and
other deals, the Magic and Rockets have three picks apiece between
Nos. 12 through 18. The Magic have the 12th, 13th and 15th picks
while the Rockets have Nos. 14, 16 and 18. Minnesota has the 17th
selection.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks do not have a first-round pick and the Nets have no
pick in either the first or second round. With the 38th and 44th
picks in the second round, the Knicks and are said to be interested
in moving up to acquire the Florida point guard Jason Williams in
the early teens or possibly a young front-line player such as Al
Harrington, the 6-9 center from St. Patrick's High School in
Elizabeth, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington and Rashard Lewis of Alief Elsik High School in
Alief, Texas, are the class of the youngsters. A bevy of foreign
players _ led by the 6-11 German forward Dirk Nowitzki and the
7-foot Slovenian Radoslav Nesterovic _ may also be among the top 20
players chosen in a draft short on potential All-Stars but long on
role players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the top 8 or 9 players set, but you can get the same
guy at 13 or 14 you can get at No. 24,'' Knicks team president
Ernie Grunfeld said. ``As far as impact players, it's not very
good. As far as depth in the draft, it's pretty solid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Celtics, with the 10th pick, are one of several teams
looking to possibly trade their selection in order to acquire a
veteran player. Host Vancouver, which holds the No. 2 pick, and
Toronto, with No. 4, also are said to be interested in dealing
their selections for other players and possibly future draft picks.
The league's needy teams indeed will have their work cut out for
them the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
