<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT OVERTURNS RULING ON WINDOWS 95 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-ASSESS) 
(th) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Undercutting a central argument in the government's
new antitrust suit against Microsoft Corp., a federal appeals court
Tuesday overturned a lower court's order in an earlier, similar
case against the company.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a setback for the Justice Department and for
U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, who issued the
order, which had required Microsoft to offer its Windows operating
system software separate from its software for navigating the World
Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is scheduled to preside over the trial in September for
the new antitrust suit, which was filed last month by the Justice
Department and 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court's ruling Tuesday struck down a preliminary
injunction that Jackson issued against Microsoft in December after
the Justice Department had argued in a separate case that Microsoft
was illegally using its monopoly in operating system software to
gain an unfair advantage in the market for browser software.
</P>
<P>
   But in its ruling Tuesday, the appeals court said that Jackson
had ``erred procedurally'' by issuing a preliminary injunction
without giving Microsoft a chance to present its case, and
``substantively'' by misinterpreting the intent of antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Stating a principle that legal experts say would clearly apply
to the new antitrust suit as well, the court said that Microsoft
had the right to determine what features and functions to include
in its operating system as long as the combination ``offers
advantages unavailable'' if a consumer were to purchase separate
software products and combine them to achieve similar capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The same bundling of browser and operating system is a central
feature of Microsoft's latest version of Windows _ Windows 98 _
which goes on sale Thursday, and it is one of the core complaints
of the Justice Department and 20 states in their current suit
against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   While Tuesday's ruling is not likely to have any immediate
impact on what consumers get when they buy personal computers, it
signals that the Justice Department will likely face a hostile
legal atmosphere as it heads toward the September trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antitrust scholars have long recognized the undesirability of
having courts oversee product design, and any dampening of
technological innovation would be at cross-purposes with antitrust
law,'' said the text of Tuesday's decision by a three-judge panel
of the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggest here only that the limited competence of courts to
evaluate high-tech product designs and the high cost of error
should make them wary of second-guessing the claimed benefits of a
particular design decision,'' the text said.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department issued a terse, three-sentence statement
expressing ``disappointment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're reviewing the opinion to assess our options,'' the
statement said. ``We remain confident that the evidence and our
legal arguments in our antitrust case filed May 18 will demonstrate
that Microsoft's conduct has violated federal antitrust law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Litan, a former senior official in the Justice
Department's antitrust office, said: ``This cuts the legs out from
under the Justice Department on their new case. It's potentially
devastating.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's leaders were jubilant, and investors seemed to share
their enthusiasm, bidding up shares of the company's stock $4.9375
each in heavy trading Tuesday, to a closing price of $100.75.
Meanwhile, shares of Netscape Communications Corp., Microsoft's
only direct competitor in browser software, fell on the news,
ending the day at $26.1875, down 56.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we learned from this decision is that integrating new
features into our products is a good thing to do, and that's what
these judges say is the right thing to do,'' said Robert Herbold,
Microsoft's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   William Neukom, senior vice president for law and corporate
affairs, said he invited Justice Department officials ``to review
the decision carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the department gave no indication that it intended to
modify or drop the case that is scheduled to go trial in September.
</P>
<P>
   The court also ruled that Jackson had erred when he appointed a
``special master'' to advise him on technical matters when he
considered the first case last fall. Microsoft complained that the
individual chosen, Lawrence Lessig, a law professor from Harvard
University, was biased.
</P>
<P>
   The same appeals court had tentatively suspended Lessig's
appointment, and in the ruling Tuesday the court dismissed him from
the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday, Lessig said, ``This is an extremely
difficult case, and I am grateful to both sides for the patience
and respect that they showed me during the brief time that I worked
with them on this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department could appeal Tuesday's ruling to the full
appeals court, or to the Supreme Court. In one sense that might not
seem to be a high priority, since the old case deals with
integrating a Web browser in Windows 95, a product that has been
superseded by Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   But Litan, director of Economic Studies at the Brookings
Institute, suggested that the Justice Department might consider an
appeal as a stalling tactic, in essence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given this ruling today, Microsoft could be expected to come
in with a motion to dismiss the new case _ or for a summary
judgment of the case,'' he said. ``To forestall that, they might
decide they need to appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial on the new case is scheduled to begin September 8, and
the appeal probably would not have been completed by then. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
