A3259 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS &LR;      06-23 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS WARN AGAINST DISRUPTION IN U.S.-CHINA TRADE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To get a feel for the United States' trade
relationship with China, take a stroll through Toys R Us.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie dolls, Lincoln logs, model trains _ all quintessentially
U.S. toys _ are made, at least in part, in China. In fact, more
than half of all toys sold in the United States last year were
manufactured in China.
</P>
<P>
   Now take a look at your shoes. Two out every three pairs worn by
Americans bear the Made-in-China label.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. consumers benefit from Chinese imports in the form of lower
prices, trade experts say. But it is the communist giant, not Uncle
Sam, that is most dependent on trade.
</P>
<P>
   The United States comprises a third of China's total export
market, while the world's most populous nation still represents a
minuscule marketplace for American goods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sell more to us,'' said James Lilley, a former ambassador
to China during the Bush administration. ``More people are employed
by them, and their economy is a lot more fragile.''
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates want to use that leverage to prod Beijing
to improve its record on political dissent and religious freedom,
and trade officials hope to use the U.S. trade muscle to pry open
China's heavily protected market.
</P>
<P>
   But trade experts and diplomatic sources warn that any
disruption in U.S.-China trade at this time could send China into a
recession, force the country to devalue its currency and send
economies from Bangkok to Tokyo spinning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian financial crisis, at least temporarily, has a higher
priority,'' said Winston Lord, former assistant secretary of state
for East Asia and a one-time ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will board Air Force One on Wednesday to
travel to China, becoming the first U.S. president to visit China
since the government's bloody crackdown on student protesters in
Tiananmen Square nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's goal is to improve overall relations with the United
States' fourth-largest trading partner, including to help reduce a
growing U.S. trade imbalance with China that now approaches a ratio
of 5 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   China shipped about $62.6 billion worth of merchandise to the
United States last year, while importing only about $12.8 billion
worth of U.S. goods, according to the U.S. Census Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton is meeting with Chinese leaders, the House Ways
and Means Committee is expected to vote to extend Most Favored
Nation trading status to China for another year.
</P>
<P>
   The full House is expected to approve the measure next month,
but opposition on Capitol Hill is growing.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Congress has investigated allegations the
Chinese tried to influence the 1996 presidential race by providing
illegal campaign funds and whether misappropriation of American
missile technology threatened U. S. national security.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of U.S. policy toward China span the political spectrum,
from liberal presidential hopeful Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., to
conservative Gary Bauer of the Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, lawmakers have heard testimony on issues
ranging from persecution of Christians to the sale of executed
prisoners' vital organs. The battle continued Tuesday in the
Senate, where lawmakers debated whether to block visas for Chinese
officials who engage in religious persecution or promote forced
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese also recently angered U.S. officials when they
banned direct marketing, a move that hurt American cosmetics firms
such as Avon Products and Mary Kay.
</P>
<P>
   Li Zhaoxing, China's ambassador to the United States, is warning
U.S. companies that all the criticism on Capitol Hill could hurt
their chances of landing lucrative contracts as the Chinese spend
$750 billion over the next three years to improve their
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   But despite those threats, no matter how polite, China stands to
lose the most from any trade dispute with the United States, trade
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   While American consumers gobbled up such a large percentage of
China's exports last year, China purchased less than 2 percent of
the goods American companies shipped abroad last year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, South Korea, despite a sputtering economy, purchased
twice as many American products last year than China, U.S. Commerce
Secretary Bill Daley said last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about 1.2 billion people, but only 0.2 are in
the modern economy,'' said Murray Weidenbaum, co-author of the book
``The Bamboo Network.'' A billion Chinese ``are still pushing ox
carts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't buy from anyone that's a 1,000 miles away in their
own country. It's very primitive.''
</P>
<P>
   China's relatively small purchases also reflect the continued
closed nature of that country's economy, a problem that has
prompted U.S. officials to rebuff China's efforts to join the World
Trade Organization, the international trade governing body.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the merchandise China sells to the United States are
low-priced consumer goods, the manufacture of which has migrated
from one low-wage Asian country to another over the decades.
</P>
<P>
   Toys, sporting goods and shoes made up 28 percent of all Chinese
sales to the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
   Any disruption in trade between the United States and China
would send prices of products such as toys skyrocketing, in the
short term, until that manufacturing could be relocated, noted
retail analyst Lewis Alton with L.H. Alton &AMP; Co. in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make it somewhere else, but it would take time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Imports of low-cost items from China and other East Asian
countries have helped keep a check on inflation and allowed the
U.S. economy to continue humming along.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we tried keeping their goods out, we'd have inflationary
pressures here and the Fed would be raising interest rates,'' said
Weidenbaum, who is also chairman of the Center for the Study of
American Business at Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Esserman, general counsel for the U.S. Trade
Representative's Office, told lawmakers last week that U.S.
consumers would be forced to pay abut $590 million more year for
products from items ranging from shoes to small appliances if Most
Favored Nation trading status were denied.
</P>
<P>
   For a country the size of the United States, that amounts to an
annual cost of about $2.21 a person.
</P>
<P>
   The United States' chief exports to China, meanwhile, are
high-tech goods such as aircraft and telecommunications equipment,
as well as agricultural products such as fertilizers and cotton
fibers.
</P>
<P>
   About 180,000 American jobs are tied to trade with China, and
U.S. operations ranging from Boeing Co. to Texas cotton farmers
could be hurt by a trade battle.
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Adler, manager of international issues for the
Washington-based Aerospace Industries Association, noted that when
the United States imposed unilateral sanctions related to missile
technology control, American satellite manufacturers lost $100
million worth of business.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States were to deny Most Favored Nation status to
China and disrupt trade across the Pacific, the Chinese economy
could recoil into recession, trade experts said.
</P>
<P>
   That could prompt Beijing, which has resisted the urge to
devalue the Chinese currency at a time when the Japanese yen and
other Asian currencies have already plunged, to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they devalue their currency it will set off a chain
reaction all over Asia and wreck economies all over Asia,'' Lilley
said.
</P>
<P>
   And that would send economic shock waves racing back across the
Pacific, said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and
Means Committee and a leading advocate of free trade in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese are not our natural enemies,'' Archer said. ``We
can make them our enemies by our policy or we can encourage a
friendly relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
