<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS AND VENUS WILLIAMS ADVANCE IN RAINY OPENING MATCHES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ No sooner had Wimbledon's ever-harried
officials chased away the field mouse that took up residence in a
corner of Center Court on opening day than they had to deal with a
more familiar enemy on Day 2: rain. Unlike the rodent, the rain
refused to decamp, and the result was that only 14 of Tuesday's 70
matches were completed, 15 were left unfinished Tuesday night, and
Martina Hingis had to begin her title defense with the court, and
her Wimbledon-white outfit, coated by a fine mist.
</P>
<P>
   But the 17-year-old Hingis did not let the drizzle affect her
play, winning her first match on grass since she claimed this title
last year to become the youngest Wimbledon champion in 110 years.
And the weather did not stop another teen-ager, 18-year-old Venus
Williams, from her own achievement: her first Wimbledon victory.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis' first-round opponent, 19th-ranked Lisa Raymond of Wayne,
Pa., had not only dealt her one of her five losses of 1997 but did
so right in Hingis' home base of Zurich, and Hingis got her revenge
Tuesday with a 7-5, 6-3 dismissal. Once Hingis weeded out her
forehand errors and began pushing Raymond, a two-time national
collegiate champion, into her backhand corner, she settled herself
into the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come back to play Wimbledon, you don't want to play
the No. 19 player who you lost to the last time,'' said Hingis, who
had recently been accused by her namesake, Martina Navratilova, of
taking her opponents too lightly. ``I was definitely more
concentrated, and I had to give everything just to get through the
first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis defied the slick surface, kept her concentration despite
a 90-minute rain delay just after she had held serve for a 2-1
second-set lead, and made sure she buried her shots deep enough on
the baseline to discourage Raymond's chip-and-charge offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was by no means a flawless performance by Hingis, who
had problems countering Raymond's laser-like backhand slice, it did
prove that she had recovered from her unexpected semifinal loss to
Monica Seles at the French Open this month. That defeat broke
Hingis' streak of reaching five straight Grand Slam finals, four of
which she won.
</P>
<P>
   After that disappointment, Hingis took herself up into the Alps
and did not come down until it was time to sneak in a few practice
rounds in London. ``I got away from all the stress and all the
tennis,'' Hingis said. ``I didn't want to see anybody and nobody
was there in the top of the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hingis got to Wimbledon, Raymond, who has reached the
fourth round here twice, was waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's vulnerable here,'' Raymond said. ``I knew she
hadn't played any grass-court matches, and she's got the pressure
of being the defending champion, and I think the loss at the French
probably affected her as well, so I think she feels like she's got
something to prove again.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Navratilova, a nine-time Wimbledon champion, this
tournament is the perfect place for Hingis to start proving her
reverence not just for her Grand Slam surroundings and the trophy
that awaits the survivor of this two-week haul, but for opponents
like Seles and Steffi Graf who crave the title just as much as she
does.
</P>
<P>
   ``She better shape up emotionally and physically; she's No. 1,
but she needs to step it up,'' said Navratilova, who also
criticized Hingis for being ``a bit dismissive of her opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case Tuesday. Hingis took Raymond very
seriously, especially when it came to fending off all five of the
break points Raymond had in the opening set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd play well to get those break points, and then I wouldn't
execute and break her,'' said Raymond, who was stymied by Hingis'
defensive lobs and by the winning down-the-line recoveries she made
even after being pushed laterally off the court. ``Martina seems to
be able to come up with those shots, and that's one of the reasons
she's No. 1. That's one of her talents.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the seventh-seeded Williams is, owing to her height,
supposed to possess serve-and-volley talents, she has not used them
at Wimbledon. But Tuesday she finally won her first match here, a
6-3, 6-3 decision against 98th-ranked Jana Nejedly of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' mother, Oracene, who broke her left ankle last Sunday
when she took a freakish tumble down the staircase of their rented
home here, watched from a wheelchair at courtside as Venus joined
her 16-year-old sister, Serena, in the second round. The sisters
are on a fourth-round collision course, but Venus refused to say
which of them she thought would soldier on toward the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think going into the tournament your chances are 1 out of
128, so everyone's in the running, and then there are a few who are
really serious and only one who will win,'' she said. ``I try to be
as serious as possible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
