<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-MISTAKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The good life only lasts so long as man is sued for theft
 &HT;    By Scott Hiaasen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What would you do if you found an
unexplained $400,000 deposit in your bank account?
</P>
<P>
   This was the moral dilemma facing Hans-Peter Frey of Wellington,
Fla. in June 1996. What he did was transfer the money to a
cashier's check and fly with it to Switzerland, where he opened an
annuity for his wife, Renate, that pays her about $2,000 a month
for the rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's being sued in Palm Beach County (Fla.) Circuit Court
for civil theft by the Swiss Bank Corp., which erroneously placed
the $400,000 in his account. The money was supposed to pay off a
mortgage for Dr. Hans Frey, a Swiss citizen with the same name. Dr.
Hans Frey's mortgage company had a Swiss Bank account, as did
Hans-Peter Frey of Wellington.
</P>
<P>
   In opening arguments of the jury trial Tuesday, Swiss Bank's
lawyer, Glen Waldman, said a bank employee put the money in
Hans-Peter Frey's account after a computer noted a mismatch in
account numbers when receiving the $400,000 by wire from another
bank.
</P>
<P>
   When Hans-Peter Frey _ who was born in Switzerland himself _
received the deposit along with his regular payment from a family
annuity in Switzerland, he called his local Barnett Bank branch and
Swiss Bank to confirm the deposit was real. Waldman said Frey lied
to a Swiss Bank official and said he was expecting the payment, but
Frey denies it.
</P>
<P>
   Once Swiss Bank learned of its mistake, Frey had already put the
money in his wife's annuity, where no one else could get it,
Waldman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When these types of mistakes happen, you know what people
usually do? They do the right thing,'' Waldman said. ``We made a
mistake, but what they did was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Freys' lawyer, Paul Safran, said the bank is trying to
punish his clients for its own mistake. Swiss Bank had to pay Dr.
Hans Frey's Swiss mortgage because of the error.
</P>
<P>
   Hans-Peter Frey, 56, typically receives about $2,000 a month
from his family's annuity at Swiss Bank, but other family members
sometimes contribute larger deposits to it. Until the bank called
him more than three weeks after the June 28 deposit, he had no
reason to believe the money wasn't his, Safran said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to take any responsibility for their
mistake,'' Safran said. ``It's easier for them to say this is the
Freys' fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Both lawyers said the annuity Hans-Peter Frey set up for his
wife is structured so that the money can't be withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to conclude today.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
