A3264 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SICK-FISH-COX     06-23 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SICK-FISH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toxic algae raises more questions
 &HT;    (EDS: All cities, towns and counties are CQ in Florida)
 &HT;    By Sally D. Swartz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JENSEN BEACH, Fla. _ The mysterious microalgae that may have a
role in making fish on the Treasure Coast sick has been found in
three more sites in the St. Lucie Estuary and as far south as the
Lake Worth lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This adds a whole other dimension and raises even more
questions,'' said Ann Forstchen, a Florida fish health expert.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are studying whether cryptoperidiniopsis is linked to
an outbreak of sick fish this spring on the Treasure Coast. They
have speculated the toxic algae breaks down the protective slime
covering fish, making them susceptible to bacteria in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Crypto was identified earlier at five sites in the St. Lucie and
Indian rivers, Forstchen said. But water and sediment samples taken
from Lake Worth May 18 by a private citizen in Palm Beach County
also proved positive for crypto, along with three samples taken in
the Intracoastal Waterway in Martin County May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Forstchen said the Palm Beach County resident contacted her by
e-mail and offered to help after reading about sick fish problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got six samples and we've been incubating them'' at Florida
Marine Research Institute's laboratories in St. Petersburg, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When a sample turned up positive for crypto this week,
biologists tried to contact the man to find out where it was taken,
but he was on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we need to look at fresh water flows going into Lake
Worth,'' which stretches from Palm Beach Gardens to the Boynton
Inlet, Forstchen said. ``We need to go back and see how many
lesioned fish were reported in Lake Worth. Historically, it's not
an area where we got reports of fish with lesions.''
</P>
<P>
   Fish with sores, lesions and rotting flesh began turning up in
the St. Lucie and Indian rivers in March, following massive dumping
of fresh water from rain-swollen Lake Okeechobee that disrupted the
normally brackish estuary.
</P>
<P>
   But Forstchen said the three positive samples, near the St.
Lucie Inlet, in Peck Lake and north of the Jensen Beach Causeway,
were taken when salt levels in the water were much higher and
considered healthier.
</P>
<P>
   ``So now we have crypto at places where the water was virtually
fresh _ such as the Roosevelt Bridge during the fresh water
releases _ and at places where the salt levels are close to sea
water,'' Forstchen said.
</P>
<P>
   The microscopic algae, which has been found in water in areas
that also have fish with lesions, may be in the water all the time,
she said. ``There are just a lot of questions we don't have answers
for yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
