<HEADER>
A3276 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-KLAN-COX     06-23 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-KLAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No loophole to stop klan rally
 &HT;    By Brad Mayhar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Lawmen and representatives from the state
attorney general's office say they have not developed any loopholes
that would prevent members of the Ku Klux Klan from conducting
their scheduled Saturday rally in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   The officials met Tuesday afternoon following a morning news
conference, where attorney general representatives offered legal
advice to Jasper authorities on how to prepare for Saturday's rally
_ scheduled from noon until 2 p.m. at the Jasper County Courthouse
_ and a possible capital case against at least two of the three
suspects charged with murder in connection with the dragging death
of Joe Byrd Jr. along a rural road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really just sort of provided them with what the law said
and any legitimate information they could use, but that was really
the extent of it,'' Ward Tisdale, spokesman for Attorney General
Dan Morales, said. ``We're always there to help, but it's really up
to the local officials to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Police Chief Harlan Alexander said advice offered by the
AG's office served as a means to get everyone on the same
wavelength.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jasper County Sheriff Billy Rowles' indication that a
group dubbed the ``New Black Panthers'' plans to return to Jasper
on Saturday in conjunction with the KKK rally, some Jasper
officials say have not heard any confirmed reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard the same rumors,'' Alexander said. ``Most of
that's come from the news media. The next rally we have's going to
be against the news media. We're just tired of the circus.''
</P>
<P>
   Department of Public Safety troopers, Texas Rangers, state
intelligence officers and ATF agents have been called to assist the
local deputies and police officers monitoring the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander declined to comment on how many law enforcement
authorities will man the courthouse area Saturday, but said he
feels confident in their abilities to control any excessive
physical or verbal outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be enough to handle the situation,'' he said.
``We've tried to plan for anything we can foresee and we're
confident it will go all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, and John William King and Shawn
Allen Berry, both 23, remain in the Jasper County Jail without
bond. Federal prosecutors have not yet decided whether to pursue
charges against the three suspects
</P>
<P>
   Brad Mayhar is a reporter for the Lufkin Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
