<SLUG> BC-JASPER-RESPONSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jasper to hate groups: Stay away
 &HT;    By Andy Adams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Civic leaders here politely issued a similar
statement Tuesday both to the media and to supremacist
organizations: Leave us alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would help us a lot is for all of y'all to go home, for
all of these radical groups to go home,'' Jasper County Sheriff
Billy Rowles told a group of about 20 reporters and television
cameramen in front of the county courthouse. ``Let Jasper's
citizens, the good people in our county, deal with what has taken
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing an outstanding job. I applaud the citizens of
Jasper County and the Byrd family. We're working on this. I know
this is newsworthy and I know y'all have a job to do. But as soon
as y'all get out of Jasper County, we're going to continue our
healing process.''
</P>
<P>
   Jasper has remained in the national spotlight since June 7, when
James Byrd Jr. was dragged to death behind a pickup on a county
road east of town. Three white men have been charged with murder in
connection with the death of Byrd, who was black.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent developments have focused on Ku Klux Klan
members' intention to stage a rally in Jasper this Saturday. Rowles
said that he also has learned that a faction of the Black Panther
party _ some of whose members brandished shotguns when they visited
Jasper on the day of Byrd's funeral _ plans to return on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The comments of Rowles, who was not scheduled to speak at the
press conference but answered reporters' questions, drew applause
from a small contingent of local residents who were gathered on the
courthouse square.
</P>
<P>
   Five other community leaders offered similar opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The citizens of Jasper in the past weeks have come together to
solve our problems, to work through them,'' County Judge Joe Folk
said. ``What we would like to do is to ask the other people to let
our people, the citizens of Jasper County, continue to work
together to solve our problems and to heal the wounds that we have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly do not represent ourselves to be anything except
a Christian community. We are God-fearing and God-loving people and
we do not condone, in any manner, the mistreatment of any person.
And, of course, we do not like to see outsiders come in to stir up
hatred among our people or to cause mistrust among any people of
Jasper County.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Domenech, chairman-elect of the Jasper Chamber of
Commerce, repeated the request of one of Byrd's daughters. Renee
Mullins said last week that, if the Klan is coming to Jasper to
renounce any association with the murder and lend its support to
the Byrd family, then its members should come in plain clothes
instead of ``in costume,'' with hoods and flowing robes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the opinion of the chamber of commerce that, only by
granting her request, can the Klan show support for her family
rather than add more trauma to their excruciating grief,'' Ms.
Domenech said. ``Jasper's healing process has begun and does not
need to be disrupted by outsiders seeking attention for themselves
or their causes. The best support that organizations such as the
Klan can give Jasper is to respect our privacy. ''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Gatlin, president of the Jasper Independent School District
board of trustees, begged visitors to let the community's children
have a peaceful summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We implore all outside interests, including the group that has
announced that they will be present in Jasper this coming Saturday,
to stay away,'' Gatlin said. ``We have students who are trying to
continue their education process this summer and we have students
who are attempting to relax so that they can be refreshed when
school begins in August of this year. Distractions from outside
groups which truly have no interest in the people of Jasper will
only inhibit the education process of our youth, who are our adult
leaders of tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those outside groups, I will state that, if your concern
for Jasper and our world is for the good, then stay at home on
Saturday and days to come. You will probably be surprised to find
that you have children or grandchildren at your own homes that
could use your own love and attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Snelson, past-president of the chamber of commerce, said he
has done business in Jasper for 24 years and said its residents do
not view each other in racial terms but as people with whom they
trade and with whom they attend school and church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this tragic incident as the difference between good
and evil, between right and wrong _ not between black and white,''
Snelson said of Byrd's murder, calling it ``a cruel and savage
atrocity committed by misfits not represented by the citizens of
our town.''
</P>
<P>
   Folk said that, while Jasper residents may not be able to keep
groups like the KKK and Black Panthers from staging rallies, they
can simply refuse to pay attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize people's constitutional rights and we're going to
see that those rights are guaranteed,'' he said. ``But we're also
interested in working out our problems among ourselves and we're
the kind of people that can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Neff, pastor of the First United Methodist Church in
Jasper, echoed the other leaders' sentiments as he spoke about the
KKK: ``We don't want you in Jasper. Stay home and let our community
continue the healing process as we strive to live together in peace
and harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Adams is a reporter for the Lufkin Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
