<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's frequent flier points hardest to redeem, study says
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new analysis of frequent flier programs suggests
Delta Air Lines makes it harder than other carriers to redeem
mileage.
</P>
<P>
   The July issue of Consumer Reports says Atlanta-based Delta in
1997 booked the smallest proportion of its seats, 5.4 percent, for
award travel on popular routes.
</P>
<P>
   That was down 20.5 percent from a year earlier, giving Delta the
steepest decline among seven airlines listed in the analysis. The
study, by a consulting firm hired by the magazine, was based on 500
domestic routes with the highest award-ticket traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis comes as airlines carry heavy loads of paying
passengers, making it tougher to redeem mileage. Consumer Reports
said the seven airlines booked 152,000 fewer award flights on the
top routes last year. Still, three carriers _ American, United and
Northwest _ showed gains in the percentage of award seats booked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the best mileage-award programs make available the
most frequent-flier seats,'' the magazine says. American and TWA
booked the highest proportion, 8.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta, which claims its SkyMiles program is 'the most ...
rewarding in the industry,' was absolutely the worst,'' the
magazine says.
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokeswoman Laura Gillig said the analysis was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly don't feel that we have cut award seats 20
percent on top routes. In fact, we feel we take very good care of
SkyMiles members,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's annual filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, however, confirm a recent decline. The airline, which
is required to disclose certain frequent flier liability
indicators, said passenger miles logged by award travelers rose
steadily from 4 percent to 8 percent from 1991 to 1996. But in 1997
it dropped back to 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta business travel consultant Chris McGinnis said he often
hears anecdotal complaints about mileage redemption but does not
feel they are necessarily justified.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people have the attitude that these programs are a
divine right,'' he said, adding tighter seat availability is only
logical when demand by paying passengers is high. ``You didn't hear
a lot about this a few years ago when there were plenty of seats,
and you won't hear about it when the next recession hits and demand
drops. It's cyclical,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Reports article is skeptical of mileage programs
generally, calling them a ``dubious scheme'' to entice consumers
with promises of award travel that isn't worth the purchases needed
to earn it. Airline officials and other defenders say the
popularity of the programs speaks for itself. More than 57 million
people are members, many in more than one program.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Transportation last year said it was
reviewing mileage programs to see how many seats are set aside for
award use and how clearly airlines warn consumers about redemption
limits.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman said Tuesday the review is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
