<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3281 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETER-BROOK-THEATER-$     06-23 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETER-BROOK-THEATER-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR PETER BROOK, DECISIONS ARE A FORM OF ART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28)
</HEADLINE>
  (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AIX-EN-PROVENCE, France _ Peter Brook was explaining over lunch
that no one should ever be held to opinions voiced in the past,
which seemed fine as, well, a fresh opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was not quite enough to explain why, having turned his
back on mainstream opera, the legendary theater director was now to
be found rehearsing a new production of Mozart's ``Don Giovanni''
that will open next month's international opera festival in
Aix-en-Provence.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Brook began his professional career at Covent Garden
in the late 1940s, and he had clearly had his fill when he wrote in
``The Empty Space,'' his seminal 1968 book on theater, that grand
opera was ``a nightmare of vast feuds over tiny details.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, while creating stripped-down experimental versions
of ``Carmen'' (seen in New York in 1983) and ``Pelleas et
Melisande'' at his theater in Paris, he has refused innumerable
invitations to work in Europe's leading opera houses and festivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ready to disclaim my opinion, even of yesterday, even of
10 minutes ago, because all opinions are relative,'' the stocky
73-year-old Englishman said with an amused twinkle of his famously
pale blue eyes. ``One lives in a field of influences, one is
influenced by everyone one meets, everything is an exchange of
influences, all opinions are derivative. Once you deal a new deck
of cards, you've got a new deck of cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but what had made him change his mind?
</P>
<P>
   In his new book of recollections, ``Threads of Time,'' published
this month by Counterpoint in the United States, Brook describes
life as a series of accidents and chance encounters, which explains
why, perhaps, improvisation is his preferred way of creating
theater.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, more than serendipity was involved. In
Stephane Lissner, the new director of the Festival International
d'Art Lyrique et de Musique in Aix, he at last found someone
willing to let him do opera his own way, which means helping to
pick the cast, rehearsing for nine weeks, creating an ensemble
spirit and touring the production after the festival. Not
surprisingly, the two men are also allied at Brook's theater
headquarters in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   At Aix, ``everything is shared,'' Brook said about the cast,
chorus and the two conductors, Claudio Abbado and the young
Englishman Daniel Harding. ``We work together, doing exercises,
preparing, all as one big group. We were given the time to do it.
And because there will be more than 60 performances here and on
tour, there is a relationship between everyone's emotional and
creative time and investment and the number of people who will see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, of course, this is precisely how Brook works at
the Theatre des Bouffes du Nord in Paris, where his International
Center of Theater Research (which Lissner manages) has been based
since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps he has surrendered little in coming to Aix. He does
see a challenge in directing his first ``Don Giovanni'' since, he
said, he had never seen a ``convincing'' production of the opera.
Yet he is more concerned with how his version will feel than how it
will look.
</P>
<P>
   ``To find new and striking ways of setting something is of no
interest to me,'' he said. ``If this production has any specific
characteristic, it will be that it is very simple and very
intimate, to get to the heart of it, the essence of it. And I don't
think that is done through staging or interpretation, but something
very different.''
</P>
<P>
   As ever, then, Brook is involved in a search: at Aix, into the
character and motivations of opera's greatest libertine; at the
Bouffes du Nord recently, into the burden of having a prodigious
memory in ``Je Suis un Phenomene,'' or ``I Am a Phenomenon,'' based
on a book by the Russian neurologist Aleksandr Romanovich Luriya.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Qui Est La?,'' or ``Who Goes There?,'' he used excerpts
from ``Hamlet'' to analyze the theater techniques of Stanislavsky,
Meyerhold, Gordon Craig, Brecht and Artaud. In ``L'Homme Qui,''
inspired by Oliver Sacks' book ``The Man Who Mistook His Wife for a
Hat,'' he probed issues of sanity, perception and memory. And in
``The Mahabharata,'' his nine-hour classic based on ancient Hindu
texts and seen, like ``L'Homme Qui,'' at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music, he addressed war and survival.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was his need to continue searching that prompted
Brook to move to France in 1970. In ``Threads of Time,'' he notes
that the book became a lengthy answer to the question, Why Paris?
</P>
<P>
   ``In England, artistic experiment is always viewed with
suspicion,'' he writes, ``while in France it is a natural part of
artistic life.'' He might also have added that unlike England,
France is generous with its theater subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to leave was a great loss to the London stage.
``The British theater in the past 20 years has sometimes felt like
a party being conducted with two of our most fascinating directors
away on French leave,'' the English playwright David Hare said in a
review of ``Threads of Time'' in The Guardian of London. ``Their
absence has haunted us, like a rebuke.'' The other British theater
director to flee to France was Joan Littlewood.
</P>
<P>
   Brook shows no regrets. And, still full of energy, he always
seems ready for a new adventure. Born into a Russian Jewish family
in London in 1925, his first career plan was to become a movie
director. But after studying at Oxford University, where he
directed a stage production of ``Doctor Faustus,'' he could not
break into films and instead found himself, at the age of 22, as
resident producer at the Royal Opera House.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``I entered the opera with one simple aim: to give this sleepy
old-fashioned institution a series of shocks that would jolt it
into the present-day world,'' he writes in ``Threads of Time.''
Reality was otherwise. A veteran tenor advised him: ``Flatter all
the time, flatter shamelessly, never ask if you're overdoing it,
because that's not possible, go on flattering.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was able to direct opera and even the odd film, he was
soon drawn into theater and quickly made his name in the West End
in London and at the Royal Shakespeare Theater in
Stratford-on-Avon. He worked with many present or future stars and
provides delightful pen portraits of some in ``Threads of Time.''
</P>
<P>
   He also describes how he gradually moved from traditional to
experimental theater. In the 1950s, he had veered little from his
early view that ``lights, music and effects were all as important
as acting.'' But by the 1960s, while in France to direct Genet's
play ``The Balcony,'' he was ready to work with his actors as an
ensemble and experiment with what was still, in his words, ``an
unknown new tool called improvisation.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the tool that he needed for his theatrical exploration,
and it was the tool that turned his memorable production of Peter
Weiss' ``Marat/Sade'' into the sensation of London theater in the
mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Brook seemed to feel trapped in Britain. He traveled to
Mexico and Cuba and went on a long trek through Afghanistan with
his wife, the actress Natasha Parry. His fascination with
non-Western culture grew.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris in 1968, Jean-Louis Barrault invited him to present a
Shakespeare production at an international festival, but Brook
proposed instead a workshop of actors and directors from different
cultures. The seeds of today's International Center of Theater
Research were planted. Two years later, he moved to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   At first, working on its own, the ensemble focused on exploring
body language and other nonverbal communication through
improvisation. In time, though, the need for spectators, for the
reactions of a nontraditional theater audience, intensified. The
group began performing before migrant workers in grim hostels
outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it traveled to Iran and, most daringly, to West Africa,
where it would arrive unannounced in villages and ask permission to
perform. It was an approach that would define Brook's work long
after a multinational ensemble was installed at the Theatre des
Bouffes du Nord: endless months of preparation _ even years, in the
case of ``The Mahabharata'' _ go into every new work; then, after
it is presented in Paris, it tours extensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any group anywhere has done so much touring,''
Brook said as he dug into a piece of apple pie. ``This is the way
one tries to be useful. And that is the basic point that I feel
strongly about: one must always try to be useful.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Threads of Time,'' behind the author's exploration of
theater, another, seemingly more crucial, spiritual search emerges
as a constant of his adult life. It is an unusual search in that it
is not religious in a conventional sense but rather inspired by the
esoteric teachings of an Armenian philosopher and mystic, George
Ivanovitch Gurdjieff, who died in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Gurdjieff taught that ordinary people can attain higher states
of awareness and take control of their own lives. In 1978, Brook
directed a movie, ``Meetings With Remarkable Men,'' based on
Gurdjieff's book of the same name.
</P>
<P>
   ``True spiritual search is recognizing that life is as it is,''
Brook said, his ever-present assistant, Marie-Helene Estienne,
already calling him back to rehearsals. ``We are what we are. We're
here, we're born as we are, and at every moment we're following all
sorts of impulses that we cannot possibly understand. But I need to
know something that I don't know. When that is there, one becomes a
searcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing ``Threads of Time'' in The Financial Times of London,
the playwright Simon Callow said that by writing of his spiritual
path, Brook ``reveals himself at the extremities of
vulnerabilities, wide open for mockery.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Callow noted, ``It is unlikely that anyone involved in the
theater will not find themselves questioning their work and their
lives at fundamental levels'' after reading the book.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, for Brook, his theatrical and spiritual searches are
irrevocably linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gurdjieff was based on two things,'' he said. ``One was always
saying, Don't take this for granted, don't believe me, work this
out for yourself _ which is opposite to the common idea of a
teacher. The other is that if you want to understand something
beyond a certain point, you cannot do it alone. And that
corresponds to my experience here. I c`n't understand `Don
Giovanni' alone. What I am discovering is thanks to working as a
group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
