<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3288 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOG-FACTORIES-ART-2TA     06-23 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOG-FACTORIES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDWESTERN CORPORATE HOG FARMS CHASE SMALL FARMERS TO THE BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: a map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling 212
556-4204.) 
 (ps) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENNOX, S.D. _ Clouds the color of gunmetal billowed across the
South Dakota sky as Merlyn Steever slouched in a metal chair in a
now-empty barn, his arms folded in weary resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give up,'' the 50-year-old farmer said as he waited for the
trucks to load the last of his pigs and take them to slaughter,
ending his career as a hog producer. ``I just can't compete with
the big corporates. I don't see how any farmer can.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapid growth of big hog factories, which are more akin to
the corporate efficiency of General Motors than the ethos of the
American family farm, has emerged as perhaps the most contentious
issue in the nation's farm country.
</P>
<P>
   While some big-scale corporate hog farming has existed for
years, it is now starting to dominate this sector of agriculture,
with companies increasingly owning the hog plants, the
slaughterhouses, and the distribution centers.
</P>
<P>
   The desperation of smaller farmers, along with anger among
townspeople in rural areas offended by the foul smell of the huge
hog barns, has stirred debate in a dozen states that are now
considering plans to curb them. A ballot initiative in South
Dakota, to be voted on in November, would effectively outlaw
corporate livestock production. And Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma
recently signed a bill that restricts big hog operations.
</P>
<P>
   These plants with thousands of hogs crowded in small pens can
threaten underground water supplies. The Sierra Club recently
called for a moratorium on such megafarms, saying they pose serious
health and environmental risks in the nation's heartland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nasty,'' said Barbara Dunham, 37, whose house, about a
half mile from a big hog plant in central Illinois, saw its
assessed property value drop 30 percent recently because of the
smell. ``It gets so bad you can't go outside. And you have to scrub
down your inside walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the big hog plants say the producers can scarcely
be blamed for delivering the kind of lean, low-cost pork that
American consumers demand. The hog companies say they operate in
scarcely populated areas, and take every precaution to ensure
health and safety. Moreover, they say they contribute mightily to
state tax coffers and rural regions that are starving for jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue has divided communities and turned neighbor against
neighbor,'' said John Bixler, a spokesman for Dakota Rural Action,
an advocacy group for small farmers in South Dakota. Indeed, the
passions over the big hog plants can become so pitched that people
who work in such plants often decide to live many miles away to
avoid the wrath of local townspeople angry about the odors.
</P>
<P>
   Premium Standard Farms, which is owned by the Continental Grain
Company and is the nation's third largest pork producer, pays about
$200 million in income to about 3,000 workers in Missouri,
according to a study by the University of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Randy Mahoney, a 31-year-old supervisor for the hog company,
said that when he was a teen-ager in the early 1980s, he watched
the terrible pain on his father's face when the family farm was
foreclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a story you could hear from a lot of people around
here,'' said Mahoney, who makes nearly $40,000 a year and never has
to worry about prices in on the hog markets. ``I never dreamed I
could stay close to home, continue doing the kind of work I'm doing
and make a good living.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving work, Mahoney must shower and change clothes. Pig
manure, he concedes, stinks.
</P>
<P>
   That is the smell of money, say the hog plants' defenders,
echoing a refrain that has been used for generations to defend
steel mills, oil refineries and rubber incinerators.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; END OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To people whose image of pig-raising evokes Old McDonald's farm,
the sight of big confinement operations would conjure something
more from George Orwell.
</P>
<P>
   For example, each steel building at a Premium Standard plant
near Harris, Mo., houses 1,150 hogs in 48 pens that measure 20 feet
long and 9 feet wide, each holding 25 pigs. The animals are
genetically designed to produce an identical cut of meat, and their
hooves never leave concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the independent farmers have also moved to the
confinement method, using the pens to reduce labor and save space.
The bottoms of the pens are slatted, so that waste drops and
collects in a lagoon. This water, which is full of hog waste, is
then spread over cropland as fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Craig Hoogestraat, who farms his family's century-old hog
operation near Lennox, 15 miles southwest of Sioux Falls, moves
through the hog pens to check on the newborn piglets.
</P>
<P>
   Hoogestraat, a former biology and physics teacher who said he
returned to farming after realizing that pigs were better behaved
than junior high school students, leaves an oldies rock music
station playing on a radio in the hog pen.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he selected a music station for the pigs, Hoogestraat
deadpanned: ``Because they get upset if they hear the broadcasts of
the hog reports.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his upbeat ways, Hoogestraat worried aloud that if hog
prices fell much lower than $35 per 100 pounds of a live hog he did
not know how he could stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   Many bigger hog companies now breed the animals, own the
slaughterhouses and market the meat. This control of the process _
``gestation to consumption'' as one economist dubbed it _ allows
the big companies to withstand lower hog prices, since they can
make it up on the retail end. For the independent farmers, on the
other hand, a drop in producer prices can spell doom. And lately,
that is exactly what has been happening.
</P>
<P>
   Prices per hundred pounds of live hogs have been in the range of
$33 to $45 this year, the lowest prices in the last
quarter-century, and a disaster for many pig farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have a mixed view about the power of laws aimed at
stopping corporate farming. Nebraska has perhaps the nation's
toughest law of its kind, forbidding any corporation from engaging
in farming. The measure has endured federal court challenges. And
it has, indeed, kept out corporate farmers. The South Dakota
measure was crafted along similar lines, exempting family-owned
corporations. But huge family-owned operations can cause as many
environmental problems as the corporate concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, producer prices are based on national markets. Keeping
the big companies out of state does nothing to help the producer
prices for local farmers. For that reason, the South Dakota measure
is unlikely to help small farmers survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss to understand what would be achieved by the
South Dakota measure,'' said Ron Plain, an agriculture professor at
the University of Missouri. ``In a large sense, this is an
emotional issue.''
</P>
<P>
   As in the rest of agriculture, the trend toward bigger
operations is unmistakable. The average swine farm today produces
432 hogs. Twenty years ago, the average farm produced 87.5 hogs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, about one million farms were raising hogs. Today, about
150,000 farms raise hogs, a number that is inflated by the ``hobby
farmers'' who raise pigs as an avocation.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significant, meat packers get about 30 percent of
their hogs from their own hog-breeding operations, or from
large-scale contracts with farms. That compares with 2 percent in
1970.
</P>
<P>
   When slaughterhouses and breeders have such close arrangements _
or, in fact, are the same company _ the market shrinks for
independent farmers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Hunhoff, a South Dakota Democrat who is running for
governor against the incumbent, William Janklow, contends that this
trend is reducing competition and creating monopolies for big
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you cut off access to markets, that's not free
enterprise,'' said Hunhoff, who grew up on a hog farm near Yankton
and supports the anti-corporate farming measure. ``We're at a
crossroads here. Are we going to defend and protect family farms?
Or are we going to let everything to the control of the
corporates?''
</P>
<P>
   Janklow has opposed the ballot initiative and defends the big
hog farms as good corporate citizens.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; END OPTIONAL TRIM &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The anti-corporate farm measure has also divided farm groups.
Organizations that represent the bigger, more conservative farmers
and ranchers, like the Pork Producers Council, have expressed
opposition to the measure, while the more liberal National Farmers
Union has supported it.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers like the Hoogestraats look down the flat gravel roads
near their farm and recite the names of 10 farmers who have stopped
raising hogs in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might not win this thing,'' said Craig Hoogestraat, talking
about the anti-corporate measure on the ballot. ``But we're not
going down without a fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3290 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL-$     06-23 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGLEWOOD-FESTIVAL-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGLEWOOD: HOW FESTIVE A FESTIVAL?  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tanglewood Music Center in Lenox, Mass., the most
prestigious summer training institute for young musicians in the
United States, has just begun its 49th season, and much attention
will be focused on Seiji Ozawa, who, as music director of the
Boston Symphony Orchestra, oversees artistic matters at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two summers, Ozawa fomented a shakeup, which
provoked angry, noisy resignations from respected leaders of the
center: the pianist and conductor Leon Fleisher, who had been
artistic director for 12 years, and the pianist Gilbert Kalish, who
had served on the faculty for nearly 30 years, the last 12 as
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fleisher is a brilliant, probing musician, he can be
prickly and was not the most hands-on administrator. Still, he had
an inspiring sense of what the center should be, and he supported
invaluable faculty members with lower public profiles, like the
veteran double bassist Julius Levine, who has also resigned in
protest.
</P>
<P>
   To understand Kalish's involvement with the center, one had only
to visit his office, where he kept a master chart with the daily
schedules of the 160-odd students. He pored over it like a worried
parent, concerned that, say, a violinist might be working too often
with the same coaches.
</P>
<P>
   These are not men prone to quitting in pique. So what happened?
The conflict touched on the tension between art and commercialism,
the role of corporate financing in artistic decisions and, perhaps
most critically, Ozawa's concern with his own artistic legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The Tanglewood Music Center is operated by the Boston Symphony,
its board and, particularly, its conductor. But Ozawa, who is 62
and will celebrate his 25th anniversary with the orchestra next
season, conceded last summer that for his first 20 years he was
fairly uninvolved with the center. ``I fired myself,'' he said. ``I
regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   His realization coincided with a crossroads in his career. For
years, there had been talk that Ozawa might be offered a position
with, say, the Berlin Philharmonic. It has not happened, and he
seems to have dug in even deeper in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   His tenure has been uneven. The orchestra can play spectacularly
for him, but the musicians are split over his leadership, and the
tension spills into their playing, which may veer from routine to
overwrought. He evidently began to see Tanglewood as a chance to
leave an important legacy, much as he has done in his native Japan,
where he is revered.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents that precipitated his shakeup started in 1994,
when the splendid Seiji Ozawa Hall was opened. It was financed by
Norio Ohga, then the president of the Sony Corp., a major supporter
of the Boston Symphony.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, Sony approached Ozawa about the possibility of
filming a series of music-education videos, ``Marsalis on Music,''
using Tanglewood students in portions of concert music. Faculty
members vehemently objected, but Ozawa prevailed. But the two-week
project played havoc with schedules, and the results were mediocre.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the center recovered, or so it seemed. In 1996, staged opera
was revived at Tanglewood with Ozawa conducting a cast and
orchestra of students in an acclaimed 50th-anniversary production
of Britten's ``Peter Grimes.'' So it was all the more shocking,
that fall, when Ozawa fired Richard Ortner, a longtime
administrator of the center, who had tried hard to reconcile the
faculty to the Sony video project.
</P>
<P>
   This set up the tensions of last summer, when Ozawa dressed down
the faculty, calling it a ``club'' resistant to change. ``This
summer will be a test,'' Ozawa said. Told later by Fleisher that
the faculty was confused, even scared, Ozawa replied, ``A little
fear is not a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Fear may be a way to run an orchestra, but it is no way to
motivate musicians as distinguished and self-critical as the
violist Raphael Hillyer and the cellist Joel Krosnick. The faculty
struggled with Ozawa to pinpoint and address his concerns,'' Kalish
said, ``but in retrospect, it seems to me he had already made up
his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Ellen Highstein, a former executive director of the
Concert Artists Guild who had taken Ortner's place on a temporary
basis, was appointed to a newly created position: director of the
Tanglewood Music Center. Kalish had already resigned. Now Fleisher
followed suit.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Symphony went into damage-control mode. Its spin,
Kalish wrote in a letter to The Berkshire Eagle late last year,
``is that Richard Ortner, Leon Fleisher and I were manning the
ramparts to guard against the fresh breeze of innovation from
sweeping away the cobwebs of a tired and moribund institution, and
that although Ozawa was desirous of making changes for the past six
years, he was somehow prevented from doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa indeed has the right _ and the power, as he has amply
demonstrated _ to make changes. But he seems to have invented, or
at least exaggerated, a whole scenario of problems at Tanglewood to
justify his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the innovations that have been trumpeted by the new team
at Tanglewood are not new. Boston Symphony guest conductors like
Bernard Haitink have always worked with students when they visit
Lenox.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of the distinguished violinist Robert Mann to
the faculty was actually put in motion by Fleisher. Other
engagements are artistically dubious, like that of the Guarneri
Quartet, consisting of once-fine musicians who have long been
uninspired.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Ozawa has placed himself in charge, he has a lot at
stake. So does Ms. Highstein, whose office, paradoxically, is in
the Leon Fleisher Carriage House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2122EDT &QL; 
