</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-ART-MUSEUMS-2TAKES-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNING MUSEUMS: OFTEN NOT A LIFELY ART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For some, the ``culture wars'' between liberals and
conservatives have been at best a sideshow. The main event (it's
been going on since the Renaissance) has been the struggle between
artists and politicians. Artists understand that creativity invites
destruction. Politicians prefer to snack on sweetness and light.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Newhouse's new book, ``Toward the New Museum'' (The
Monacelli Press), offers a shrewd, biting account of one of the
most conspicuous fields in which this struggle has been joined in
recent decades: the architecture of art museums.
</P>
<P>
   She reviews a broad selection of the more than 1,000 art museums
built in the United States and Europe in recent decades. There are
long, definitive chapters on the Getty Center in Los Angeles and
the Guggenheim Museum's branch in Bilbao, Spain. Less well-known
projects, like the Lingotto Exhibition Spaces in Turin and the
Barcelona Museum of Contemporary Art, also receive sensitive,
straightforward appraisals. The illustrations are many and choice.
</P>
<P>
   Her book is a springboard for further discussion, and bumps up
the intellectual level on which debate will take place. Its point
is simply stated: the design of art museums should be as open to
creative energy as the artworks they exhibit. This is more easily
said than done.
</P>
<P>
   Major art museums are political institutions, staffed by arts
administrators, governed by policies, budgets, operating hours and
codes of public accommodation. They tend to be overly sensitive to
the opinions of critics as well as the desires of donors and
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   But this apparatus has been put together to support a slice of
life that is unruly, irrepressible, not quietly contained. In some
museums, art and politics are brought as fatally close together as
two scorpions in a bottle. Architects design the bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gehry's Bilbao project graces the book's cover, and the
building is plainly her star attraction. She gets off to the right
start by declaring that ``nothing about this building is alien.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's strong relationship to its site may not be apparent
in photographs, but in Bilbao itself the light, the river, the
hills beyond, the industrial waterfront, the bridges and even the
cars all appear magnetically pulled together by the curves, the
scale, the titanium cladding of the design. Its power to effect
urban cohesion is comparable to that of Brunnelleschi's dome in
Florence.
</P>
<P>
   What Ms. Newhouse likes most about Bilbao is the variety of
spaces in which art can be experienced: square galleries of
classical proportion; smaller rooms whose irregularly sculptured
contours evoke the curves of the museum's metal exterior; a ``boat
gallery,'' 450 feet long, that displays work in a loftlike setting.
</P>
<P>
   The Getty Center, last year's other museum-world spectacular,
sits somewhat lower in her estimation. Despite Richard Meier's
impeccable design, Ms. Newhouse likens the experience to visiting a
theme park. She is justly galled by decisions made by the client
that compromised Meier's singular esthetic: using Thierry Despont,
a decorator, to design the painting galleries, and choosing the
artist Robert Irwin to design a large garden.
</P>
<P>
   She points to Carlo Scarpa and Louis Kahn as architects who
created sensitive settings without indulging in historical
reproduction.
</P>
<P>
   She is similarly critical of the Metropolitan Museum of Art's
19th-century European painting and sculpture galleries. Designed in
1993 by David Harvey and Gary Tinterow, a Metropolitan curator, the
ornate, neoclassical rooms were described by Tinterow as an
imagined reconstruction of a turn-of-the-century McKim, Mead &AMP;
White gallery.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
