<HEADER>
A3293 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     06-23 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFMAN'S TOUR MIGHT BE SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Glenn Hoffman, you've just been named to
manage the Los Angeles Dodgers, baseball's newest amusement park.
How do you plan to approach your job?
</P>
<P>
   ``Day to day,'' said Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   This is what you would call good planning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger universe as we once knew it is collapsing like a star
at the speed of light. Inside of three months, the team has
jettisoned two star players, its general manager and manager. The
last person to undergo this quick of a makeover was Courtney Love.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm a groundskeeper for the Dodgers, I start looking for
snakes in my rakes. If I work in scouting, I make sure all of my
airline tickets are roundtrip. The phrase everyone is expendable
has become the new Dodger mantra.
</P>
<P>
   There is every reason to think that the new manager, the
pleasant and wide-eyed Mr. Hoffman, tops the endangered list.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, 99 out of a 100 Dodger fans wouldn't have been
able to name the manager of their Albuquerque farm club. Hoffman
has the look of a name plucked from a hat, the ultimate transition
choice of a franchise that has little experience in selecting
managers.
</P>
<P>
   He has 4{ years of experience as a minor league manager, with
only one winning season. He's 39; only one other major league
manager is younger, Philadelphia's Terry Francona. His last taste
of the major leagues was 1989. Since then, he's either been a minor
league manager or instructor. His only look at the Dodgers the last
few years have been fleeting glances on television.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros, one of the senior Dodgers left in the clubhouse,
was asked what he knows of Hoffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing in Albuquerque when I was in San Antonio,''
Karros said after a long pause. ``He directed our winter workouts
at the stadium, which I attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws great B.P. (batting practice).''
</P>
<P>
   Now there's an endorsement. Karros wasn't trying to put Hoffman
down as much as put the spotlight on how incredible and incredulous
things have become with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman can't change those dynamics, and he doesn't plan to try.
That should be viewed as a redeeming quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get used to them, and they have to get used to me,''
said Hoffman of the players. ``I've had a much different role with
most of these guys (winter workouts and spring training). I've been
thrown at them. I think we're all feeling our way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get into this end of the game when my playing
career was ending, and was fortunate to get a chance. I had no
timetable. The opportunity arose for me suddenly. Sometimes, it
never comes. Only a very few people get to be a major league
manager.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that his tenure may be short doesn't bother him. Before
his official introduction as the new interim manager, sports talk
show hosts and newspaper reporters were already throwing out names
of potential full-time candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyland wants out of Florida. Davey Johnson is unemployed.
Bobby Valentine has a contract with the Mets, but he's the apple in
the eye of new interim G.M. Tommy Lasorda. Kevin Kennedy, once a
Dodger minor league manager and highly regarded, is working for
ESPN. Davey Lopes, a coach in San Diego, is one of a dozen former
Dodgers working elsewhere who belong on any short list.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman shrugged when asked whether this conjecture will bother
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here today, and hopefully tomorrow,'' he said. ``I'll go
one day at a time after that. I may not have been a manager, but
I've been around. I know how these things work.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing Hoffman will learn in the days to come is that the
team he inherited isn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   The only success the Dodgers have had this season is proving
wrong all of those talent-rich assessments. Retrospect being
perfect, the Dodgers weren't that talented before the Mike Piazza
trade, and they are less talented now.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff which has unraveled this season actually
began to tear apart last September, when it coughed up the N.L.
West lead by finishing 10-14. In September, Ramon Martinez, Chan Ho
Park, Hideo Nomo and Tom Candiotti all had ERAs over 5.00, as did
the bullpen as a unit.
</P>
<P>
   So it shouldn't be shocking that Nomo began the season without
velocity after undergoing elbow surgery, or that Martinez would
suffer more rotator cuff problems after missing 10 starts in 1997,
or that the bullpen, which didn't replace Todd Worrell, has blown
up.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were a lousy team a year ago in low-scoring games,
and that was with Piazza, who drove in 124 runs. Without him, they
have no one in the lineup who fills the definition of clutch. Even
those who believe Piazza overplayed his hand in contract talks
would agree the Dodgers miss him.
</P>
<P>
   Most would also agree that the Dodgers overestimated the ability
of several prospects, including about a half-dozen outfielders.
Fred Claire's legacy is Piazza and Karros, but also Karim Garcia,
Roger Cedeno, Todd Hollandsworth and Billy Ashley.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman may also learn that the team he used to manage in
Albuquerque is fundamentally better than the Dodgers, who regularly
miss signs, blow relays and run themselves out of innings.
</P>
<P>
   Change begats change, so there could be even more personnel
shuffling in the weeks to come. As Karros noted, the Dodgers have
set a club record for distractions, ``and we're not even at the
break yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly without a chance to catch the Padres, maybe the
Dodgers should be content catching their breath.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
