<HEADER>
A3294 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARCHITECTURE-ART-MUSE     06-23 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHITECTURE-ART-MUSEUMS-2NDTAKE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: White gallery.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Newhouse discounts the result as kitsch inauthenticity. ``In
the absence of an original Renoir, the Metropolitan would not
commission an imagined one; the Andre Meyer Galleries are the
design equivalent of such an absurd substitution.''
</P>
<P>
   New York museums in general don't do too well here. On Gwathmey
Siegel's 1992 addition to Frank Lloyd Wright's Guggenheim Museum:
``The problem is not so much with the design of the alteration as
with the decision to alter it at all.'' On Michael Graves' 1985
proposed addition to the Whitney Museum of American Art: ``Whatever
the design's undeniable merits, there is no doubt that it
cannibalized the Breuer building, reducing it to a subsidiary
element in a totally new statement.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's historically rich account of building at the Museum
of Modern Art will not bring cheer in Manhattan. Ms. Newhouse draws
a picture of the Modern's consistent failure to live up to the
standards maintained by its own department of architecture and
design.
</P>
<P>
   A low point was reached in 1984, surely, with the opening of
Museum Tower, a condominium high-rise and an escalator enclosure
called the Garden Hall. In these projects, both designed by Cesar
Pelli, architecture was eclipsed by real estate values.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Newhouse praises the clarity and elegance of the Modern's
new expansion plan, designed by Yoshio Taniguchi, but regards the
project as a missed opportunity to reconfigure the museum's
mission. Though museum officials had announced their intention to
use architecture as a vehicle for regeneration, Ms. Newhouse views
the scheme as more of the same: ``a sacred sanctuary for MOMA's
gospel of art.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Libeskind's Jewish Museum Extension in Berlin draws forth
some of Ms. Newhouse's sharpest observations. Conceived as a
Holocaust memorial, the concrete structure is thunderbolt-shaped
and clad in zinc. The core of the design is a three-story void
space, crossed by bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents absence,'' the author observes, ``all that,
because of the Holocaust, is lost to Berlin and to civilization in
general.''
</P>
<P>
   ``From the moment one enters,'' she also writes, ``there is a
feeling of dislocation: the multiple axes; the steep, monumental
main stair crisscrossed by oblique girders overhead; the tortured,
slanted, asymmetrical wall incisions through which light beams
splice the interiors; and acoustics that amplify the slightest
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Bilbao, the Jewish Museum Expansion evokes the struggle and
torment of the creative process. There is, of course, no reason
that all museum architecture must look Laocoonic. Richard
Gluckman's mild-mannered galleries are fine places for viewing art.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Newhouse is right to emphasize buildings that make
creativity's risks and dangers visible. In these buildings, Apollo
is doing his job, protecting Orpheus as the singer descends into
the underworld to explore its caves and labyrinths, the dark
corners where love might be hiding or a new song waiting to be
found.
</P>
<P>
   Her book raises a paradox. With all this honor being paid to
art, why is the present cultural climate so stifled by oppressive
appeals to normalcy? Civility campaigns. Baptists preaching about
woman's place. Health warnings on bags of potato chips. And when
you look at a building as enervated as the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art, you may think, this place is playing right along with
that oppressive band.
</P>
<P>
   Apollo is not wholly benign. His name has been traced to an
ancient Greek verb meaning ``to destroy.'' The sun can be lethal as
well as life-giving. And the building that shows the god's dual
nature teaches something essential about cultural life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
