<HEADER>
A3296 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-CHILAVERT-HNS     06-23 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-CHILAVERT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAINT ETIENNE, France _ If it were hockey, it could be said that
Paraguayan goalkeeper Jose Luis Chilavert ``stands on his head.''
</P>
<P>
   That's puck parlance for contorting oneself into various
positions, all for the sake of turning back every shot.
</P>
<P>
   But this is World Cup soccer. And this is Chilavert, an
eccentric, on-the-edge monster of a goalkeeper who few would argue
is the strangest, most volatile combination of skill and
personality in the 1998 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell Chilavert about ``standing on his head.'' Don't give
him any ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Chilavert has been known to do a bit of everything while
performing for his Argentine professional club and more recently
for surprisingly tough Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   He sits in front of the net while the ball is on the other end
of the field, as if to say, ``Come on, I want some action.'' He
screams at opponents, calling them ``toothless kittens.''
</P>
<P>
   He flexes like a bodybuilder after saves, punches reporters,
calls referees names, kicks penalty and free kicks, occasionally
causes international incidents with his mouth and wreaks havoc in
various other ways.
</P>
<P>
   But here is Paraguay on the verge of advancing to the second
round of the World Cup with a tie or a win against Nigeria today.
And here is Chilavert, backing up his boasts of being the world's
greatest goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I predicted we will move on,'' Chilavert said Tuesday, ``and
we will.''
</P>
<P>
   He is cocky and ultra-skilled. He is brash and funny. He is
controversial and unique.
</P>
<P>
   And without question, if Paraguay does indeed come out of the
so-called ``Group of Death'' today, Chilavert will be the sole
reason why.
</P>
<P>
   In a World Cup tournament that has been wide-open and
high-scoring from the start, Chilavert has kept his otherwise
mediocre team alive with two shutouts in 0-0 ties with Bulgaria and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Against Spain, which was among the pre-Cup contenders to win it
all, Chilavert wowed fans and frustrated the Spaniards with an
array of diving and leaping saves.
</P>
<P>
   He did everything but literally stand on his head.
</P>
<P>
   In the 20th minute of the Spain game, Chilavert set the stage
for his remarkable tournament when Juan Antonio Pizzi headed what
looked to be a sure goal. Chilavert caught up to the ball and
somehow lunged to make an acrobatic save, barely tipping the ball
over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
   The save seemed to zap the life out of Spain, especially when
the burly Chilavert punctuated the save with taunting screams at
Spain's players.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the game, Chilavert made two more awkward and
spectacular saves, both on strong shots by Spain's Luis Enrique,
who is among the game's best goal-scorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had many chances to win,'' Spain coach Javier Clemente said
afterward. ``They were all turned away nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Spain game, Chilavert nearly fulfilled another boast
he had for the 1998 World Cup _ becoming the first goalkeeper to
score a goal.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Chilavert stepped up to take a free kick for
his team, which he does quite regularly for Paraguay and his
Argentine professional team, River Plate. Chilavert's booming
left-footed kick looked to have a chance but deflected off a player
in the defensive wall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is today's game and possibly more opportunities to
come for Chilavert. He might actually be Paraguay's best offensive
weapon as much as its best defensive stopper.
</P>
<P>
   He scored a marvelous 50-yard free-kick goal against Argentina
during World Cup qualifying last year, which led to a 1-1 tie and
assured Paraguay its first berth in the Cup finals since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates carried Chilavert off the field after the crucial
tie with Argentina, and Chilavert said of the Argentine goalie
afterward, ``He needs to concentrate more when I am kicking it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilavert has scored 40 goals in international games and many
more for River Plate.
</P>
<P>
   So valuable has Chilavert, 32, become to his team that when he
was banned for four games for inciting an on-field brawl in 1994,
not only did Paraguay lose all four games but it scored just two
goals. Since then, he has become the focal point for a nation.
</P>
<P>
   As Chilavert goes, so go the Paraguayans. And currently, he is
at the top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very good chance of advancing in front of us,''
Paraguay coach Paulo Cesar Carpegiani said. ``We need all our
players to be at their best (against Nigeria), but, yes, Chila is a
key.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the ``Bulldog,'' a nickname earned because Chilavert
refuses to wear a jersey that does not have an image of a bulldog
emblazoned on it. And, yes, Paraguay allowed Chilavert to alter the
national-team jersey so that he could wear a bulldog during this
World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   He seems to invite controversy and attention with his volatile
ways, which some say overshadow the side to his personality that
last year prompted him to contribute more than $200,000 to a
children's charity in Asuncion, where Chilavert grew up in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   His most controversial moment might have come in 1994, when
after receiving a suspended jail sentence for his part in the
on-field brawl, Chilavert said the Argentines ``can't stand the
thought of a Paraguayan being the best in their country at
something. They think that Paraguayans belong on building sites or
cleaning the kitchens of the rich.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement caused such an uproar that the Paraguayan
ambassador had to make a statement denouncing Chilavert's words and
calming the furor.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Chilavert again was taking shots at the
Argentines, with whom he definitely has a love-hate relationship.
Argentina is where he makes a rich professional living, but it is a
country that he often incites into uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Chilavert, who once called an Argentine goalie a Fiat and
himself a Mercedes, went to the Japanese media to offer a scouting
report before the Japan-Argentina Cup opener, which ultimately
Argentina won.
</P>
<P>
   ``Argentina's problem is in midfield,'' Chilavert said. ``Their
players don't go for pressing much, and they don't like it when
opponents stick too close to them. I am not impressed by them.''
</P>
<P>
   He is the irrepressible bulldog. But like his antics or not, it
is difficult not to be impressed by Chilavert in this World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the best at what I do,'' he said. ``My job is to prove
it.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, he has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
