<SLUG> BC-WORLD-AIDS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AIDS IS WINNING,' REPORTS INTERNATIONAL AGENCY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Sub to correct figures in story) 
 
By RUTH SoRELLE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the World AIDS Conference approaches, the primary
international AIDS agency paints a bleak picture of the spread of
the AIDS virus in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most of the world, AIDS is winning,'' said said Dr. Peter
Piot, executive director of the Joint U.N. Agency on AIDS, an
international umbrella organization coordinating the fight across
national borders. The World AIDS Conference begins Sunday in
Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   In the first country-by-country analysis the group has issued,
its experts estimate that 30.6 million people are living with HIV,
the virus that causes AIDS, or AIDS across the world, with 16,000
new infections daily.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 5.8 million new infections and 2.3 million deaths were
attributed to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the disease has become one of the
leading causes of infectious death in the world _ ranking with
malaria and tuberculosis as a mass killer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the industrialized world that includes the United
States, the AIDS death rates and rates of new infection
arestabilizing or dropping, Piot said. In most of these countries,
people with AIDS have ready access to drugs that fight the virus
and the illnesses to which infected people are vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   While attempts to prevent the spread of AIDS have met with some
success in industrialized nations, that is not true of Asia or most
of sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
   At least one in 10 people living in 13 countries in sub-Saharan
Africa are infected with HIV. Southern Africa _ the part of the
world hardest hit by the disease _ has 3 million people living with
HIV, Piot said. Of those, 700,000 were infected in the last year,
an example of how fast the disease is spreading there.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is doubling and tripling adult death rates in the many of
these countries, Piot said. Specifically, in Botswana and Zimbabwe,
one in four adults in urban and rural areas carry the virus that
causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   HIV is still an emerging epidemic in the nations of Eastern
Europe and Asia, he said. Because of that, overall rates of disease
are low, but in the past two years, many of these nations have
experienced a six- to 10-fold increase in the numbers of reported
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Piot said gaps contribute to the increasing death and infection
rates in countries where people are uneducated and poor.
</P>
<P>
   He said the numerous gaps include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Disparities in access to treatment for all diseases related to
HIV, including tuberculosis and diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   _ Differences in the rates of transmission, with spread of the
disease slowing in countries where prevention is stressed and
speeding up where AIDS is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gaps in knowledge about HIV status, leading to increased
spread of the disease and the threat that more children will be
born infected with the virus.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there are bright spots.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand and Uganda have managed to slow the increase of disease
in their AIDS epidemics.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda has cut its AIDS infection rate by 25 percent _ from 13
percent in 1994 to 9.5 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Thailand has reduced prevalence of the disease in that country
from 2.7 percent in 1994 to 2.3 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In each case, prevention programs stressing condom use, delayed
age at first intercourse and reduction of sexual partners played a
big role in lowering infection rates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
