<HEADLINE>
LAKERS CONSIDER OPTIONS AT NO. 26
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By JIM McCURDIE  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Here we are, right back where we were a year
ago, wondering whether the Los Angeles Lakers will stand by their
man.
</P>
<P>
   The team that gave Nick Van Exel his first big break by
selecting him with the 37th selection of the 1993 Draft is now
believed to be contemplating trading him, and today could be the
day Van Exel is sent packing.
</P>
<P>
   Or could it?
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel's agent is on record saying that Laker executive vice
president Jerry West told him shortly after the Lakers were
eliminated by Utah in the Western Conference Finals that the club
would likely be trading his client. Today's NBA Draft is the ideal
time for wheeling and dealing, particularly with a July 1 lockout
looking more real and ominous each day.
</P>
<P>
   But Laker general manager Mitch Kupchak wouldn't confirm that
Van Exel is on the trading block. While exercising great caution
not to tip his hand and speaking with the kind of forked tongue NBA
executives generally use this time of year, Kupchak indicated that
speculation that the Lakers will shake up their roster a bit in the
wake of the sweeping loss to Utah may be inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not looking to do it,'' he said. ``I would not be
surprised if we did nothing. But as our jobs are defined, whatever
we can do to improve this team we will do. If it means trading a
player for a player or trading a player for a draft choice, or the
remote possibility that a free agent would come here and make a
contribution... that's what we're going to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking... we don't feel a great need to change the
team. But we would.''
</P>
<P>
   So a trade or two (any takers for Elden Campbell at $7 million
per year?) can't be ruled out, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I'll say about our team is that we've been
getting a bunch of calls,'' Kupchak said. ``This time of year, it's
what we do. It's good to know that other teams covet some of our
players. It gives us options, and possibilities to improve the
team. If there's a way to do that, we'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing pat would mean the Lakers would try to uncover a gem
with the 26th selection of today's draft. They've come up big from
similar draft positions before (see Vlade Divac, No. 26 in 1989,
Campbell, No. 27 in 1990, Derek Fisher No. 24 in 1996 and Van
Exel), but this draft isn't exactly brimming with the kind of
player who can move right in and crack the rotation of a team that
won 61 games in 1997-98 and reached the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers go into the draft with the 26th and 31st picks. The
latter, the second choice of the second round, was obtained from
Vancouver in a swap of second-round picks that was part of 1996
trade that sent guard Anthony Peeler and forward George Lynch to
the Grizzlies. They also have the 45th pick.
</P>
<P>
   What's likely to be left at those spots is more of what the
Lakers already have in abundance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always more guards than there are big people,
always,'' Kupchak said. ``That's probably what we'll wind up
looking at down there at the end of the first round and early
second round--- players that range from 6-1 to 6-6, some of which
were small forwards or big forwards in college, and you have to
figure out if they can convert to a shooting guard or a small
forward in our league.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the players who could be available when that 26th pick
comes up are Nebraska point guard Tyronn Lee, who could come in
handy if Van Exel does indeed get traded, St. John's guard Felipe
Lopez, Oregon State guard Corey Benjamin, Valparaiso guard Bryce
Drew, Iowa guard Ricky Davis, Clemson guard Greg Buckner and Baylor
forward Brian Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are facing some uncertainty over their small forward
spot since starter Rick Fox is a free agent and, under the current
salary cap restrictions, the Lakers can't pay him as much as he
could get from another team. The Lakers are approaching this much
the same way they did with forward Travis Knight last season---
hoping that no one makes Fox an offer too good to refuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's indicated to us this is where he wants to be,'' Kupchak
said. ``We want him to be here, and all of our preliminary (plans)
include him. But we are aware that there's a significant
possibility we will lose him. Whether that's 10 percent or 30
percent I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
