<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CENSUS NOMINEE FAVORS POLITICALLY CONTROVERSIAL METHOD
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday nominated Kenneth
Prewitt, a soft-spoken academic and former divinity student, to be
director of the Census Bureau, an agency that is being buffeted by
partisan disputes over its plans for conducting the 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the Senate, Prewitt, 62, would fill a position
that has been vacant since January, when Martha Farnsworth Riche
abruptly resigned as congressional pressure mounted over the
bureau's plans to change its methods for conducting the next
census.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt is president of the Social Science Research Council, a
private foundation in New York City that finances studies to
determine how to approach the investigation of complex economic and
social phenomenon. Clinton administration officials say he is one
of the top social science statisticians in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Prewitt is a person of impeccable credentials and proven
scientific integrity,'' William Daley, the secretary of commerce,
said in announcing the nomination Tuesday. ``The year 2000 is
coming quickly, and the Census Bureau faces many challenges in its
quest to conduct the best census in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau has designed the next census in a way to avoid
a repetition of the 1990 effort, which was the most expensive in
history and yet is widely believed to have missed an estimated 8.4
million people and double-counted or improperly tallied 4.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   To improve its performance, the bureau has proposed taking a
sample of households that do not mail back their census forms.
Using scientific means, statisticians would use that sample to
estimate the size and demographic characteristics of those houses
that failed to return the forms.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's opponents, mainly Republicans, say it is illegal and
subject to partisan manipulation. But both Democrats and
Republicans say the fight is over political power, because many who
are missed using the traditional census method are minorities
living in solidly Democratic areas, while many of those who are
counted twice are whites living in Republican-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, getting a more accurate count could result in the
redrawing of district lines in a way that would make them more
favorable to Democrats and harmful to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Asked his opinions of sampling, Prewitt said he supported it.
But he seemed, in the face of having to be confirmed by a
Republican-controlled Senate, to play down the partisan nature of
the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weight of professional opinion, which I share, is that
sampling, if properly used can contribute to a more accurate
census,'' Prewitt said. ``Reasonable people can come to a different
conclusion. This is a matter of technical and scientific review. It
is not a matter of partisan disagreement. It is not a matter of
ideological positioning, and it is not question of whether data can
be manipulated or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
