</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PIKE-TOLLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT NIXES TURNPIKE TOLL REFERENDUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS C. PALMER JR.  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A move to take down all highway tolls in Massachusetts
was ruled unconstitutional Tuesday by the state's highest court,
which also said Attorney General Scott Harshbarger erred when he
certified the initiative for the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was a victory for officials at the Massachusetts
Turnpike Authority and the Big Dig, who said elimination of the
tolls would exact financial chaos on the state and cause the
pricetag for the $10.8 billion Central Artery/Ted Williams Tunnel
project to skyrocket further.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers, meanwhile, will have to continue paying tolls but will
be spared gas tax increases that likely would have been imposed to
replace the lost toll revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Judicial Court, in a forceful decision, said both
the initiative's proponents and Harshbarger failed to consider the
state's bondholders whose interest payments are guaranteed by
revenue collected from the state's tolls on the turnpike,
underharbor tunnels and the Tobin Bridge. Turnpike bonds, $1.7
billion of which are now committed to help pay for the Big Dig, are
backed up by approximately $200 million a year in toll revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The petition's elimination of toll revenue constitutes a
full-blown appropriation of the bondholders' right to that property
... an interest which was expressly bestowed on them by contract _
and therefore would violate their constitutional rights,'' the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Barth and Harold Hubschman, co-chairmen of a group
called the Free the Pike Coalition, said that the decision would
probably spell the end of their group, which fought for five years
to remove the tolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see no reason to continue,'' Barth said. ``We're going back
to our jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   After an unsuccessful attempt at collecting signatures two years
ago, the group this year collected enough signatures to put the
toll-removal question before voters on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   With their quest snuffed out by the court, Barth and Hubschman
issued a parting shot at the judges, the Legislature and the
Cellucci administration for what they said was putting the concerns
of special interests _ especially Wall Street _ ahead of
Massachusetts taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's institutionalized is the grip of the bond holders on
the political process,'' Barth said.
</P>
<P>
   Barth and Hubschman, who organized a final and last-minute rally
at the State House Tuesday, appeared by themselves. They continued
to assert that the cost of building the Massachusetts Pike has been
paid for since 1984, and that the bond obligations now satisfied by
tolls could easily be handled by the state in other ways.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci, who had conspicuously declined to
take a position on the ballot initiative despite the fact that the
state is in desperate need of toll money, Tuesday issued a
statement unusually favorable to Free the Pike _ though clearly too
late to help the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that the voters won't have a chance to have a say
on this issue in November,'' said Ilene Hoffer, a Cellucci
spokeswoman. ``But Governor Cellucci has his own plan to free the
pike of tolls.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that tolls have been eliminated under the
Weld-Cellucci administration at Exits 1 through 6 and Exit 16.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Kerasiotes, chairman of the turnpike authority, which
depends on tolls and is responsible for managing the Big Dig, has
avoided public debate on the Free the Pike issue.
</P>
<P>
   As perhaps the public official with the most to lose had the
measure reached the ballot and passed, Kerasiotes said, ``From the
day I was appointed I have made sure that we're on a path to
eliminating tolls west of Route 128. ... That's the plan we thought
was the most responsible to maintain the road and help the state to
finance the Central Artery project.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes said he continues to seek non-toll revenues at the
authority to help pay its costs. At Tuesday's turnpike board of
directors meeting, in fact, he suggested the new electronic toll
system, scheduled to begin operating this fall, will be the first
in the nation to have ``a corporate sponsor.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dimino, president of the Artery Business Committee,
which led the challenge to Free the Pike, could not hide his
elation about the court decision. ``I'm psyched,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this did proceed to the ballot and had won, in effect the
taxpayers would have been voting for a hidden tax,'' Dimino said.
Toll supporters estimated that up to 11 cents would have to have
been added to the existing 21-cent-a-gallon state gasoline tax to
offset the loss of approximately $200 million a year in tolls.
</P>
<P>
   The ballot initiative's opponents also argued that elimination
of tolls would have seriously affected the state's overall
financial picture.
</P>
<P>
   The high court agreed with the challengers' position. Writing
for the court, Justice Charles Fried said that, ``in certifying the
petition, the Attorney General should have considered the security
interests held by the 1997 bondholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger's spokesman, Ed Cafasso, said the attorney general
was obligated to answer a narrow set of questions in certifying it
for the ballot. ``We applied those standards, and ... based on his
analysis it was constitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Cafasso acknowledged that the court disagreed with
Harshbarger, who is running as a Democrat for governor, on the
matter of the rights of authority bond holders.
</P>
<P>
   But, Cafasso added, ``Would Scott Harshbarger have voted for
this had it made it to the ballot? No.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe staff writer Adrian Walker contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
