<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: TWO IN THE BUSH  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ I'm melting! I'm melting!
</P>
<P>
   I don't care about the Spot any more. I haven't checked it in
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   I can tell I'm really depressed when I don't even enjoy looking
in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Did you know that seal pups have a million hairs on every square
inch of their bodies? Oh, never mind. My vanishing hair is the
least of my troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Bush. Bush. Bush. That's all anyone's talking about. I can't
believe America wants to elect another George Walker Bush. This
one's missing his Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   I know what it's like to grow up with a presidential spoon in
your mouth. And there's nothing wrong with a little privilege. But
George W. just got his first real job. He's only been governor of
Texas for ten minutes, and he's already beating me in the polls?
 &UR; Excu-u-u-use &LR;  me? Don't we have some dues to pay? W. has never
even run for national office. He's never been dragged by the hand
and humiliated by Ed Koch in a New York primary. He's never had to
shake down Buddhist nuns.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, W. has nice hair, and his Southern accent beats his
daddy's. Shucks, it beats mine. But let's get real. He was just
some do-nothing, know-nothing hothead hanging around his dad's
White House. The only thing W. did the whole four years was tell
John Sununu to clear out his desk. Even his own parents didn't
think he'd be any good as a politician. They placed all their chips
on Jeb.
</P>
<P>
   W. is running a state, but I'm running a country _ until Bill
gets back from China. Let's see how the Smoothie in Chief handles
those sneaky butchers of Tiananmen Square when they bring  &UR; him &LR; 
champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The presidency is  &UR; my &LR;  birthright. I can't let it slip away to
some other scion. I've worked too hard. I've had secret strategy
meetings on Gore 2000 for more than a year. I've invited all those
nasty reporters to my house every Halloween, getting done up in
some silly costume, standing in line for hours to shake their hands
and tell them how adorable their rugrats are.
</P>
<P>
   I'm wearing out Air Force Two on the shrimp-and-pander circuit,
and W. has yet to lift a finger. He's too highfalutin to even
bother leaving Austin to share the stage with Quayle, Forbes, and
Lamar at cattle shows.
</P>
<P>
   So now I'm the past and he's the future? Has everybody forgotten
that I'm the one who got the Earth on line?
</P>
<P>
   I never sowed any wild oats. I've always been the Good Son. And
now they say W.'s carousing past gives him character and manliness.
</P>
<P>
   All the stupid pundits are saying I'm weak. They're asking why
Bill's mud sticks to me and not to him.
</P>
<P>
   They're saying  &UR; I'm &LR;  the one who has inherited George Bush Sr.'s
weaknesses. I'm the wimp. I'm the uninspiring speaker. I've got a
secret plan to raise taxes _ trying to hook up classrooms to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason W. gets more popular with every poll is that
people are confusing their Bushes. My dad was a great man, too _
but who remembers? Gosh, I wish he'd been president.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it's even more embarrassing if people are preferring
W.'s old man to me. I thought they couldn't wait to vote him out of
the White House. This was a guy even the Republicans wanted to
forget. Then he jumps out of a plane and now all of a sudden he's a
great ex-president?
</P>
<P>
   You want to talk about derring-do? I came home from Iowa and ran
the Marine Corps Marathon on three hours' sleep. And without a
parachute.
</P>
<P>
   W. was in Washington for a big fund-raiser the other night. He
raised a mil. I was so upset I called Jeffrey at Dreamworks. He
talked me down.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out, W. I may act like a Boy Scout but I know how to fight
dirty. Why do you think the president and I blocked W.'s little
plan to streamline applications for public assistance in Texas?
He's not going to run on that issue. And why do you think Gary
Mauro, his opponent in the governor's race, is my new best friend?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I haven't been at the top of my game lately. I called
Michael Jordan Michael Jackson. And I messed up by only giving $353
to charity last year. That stupid W. gave $16,500.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I'm not perfect. But even perfect people make
mistakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
