<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3320 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI24-COX     06-23 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A popular kiddie pool area at White Water park north
of Atlanta is the source of an E. coli bacteria outbreak that has
sickened at least a dozen children in three Southeastern states,
Georgia health officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a 98 percent certainty children defecating in the
water resulted in an acute contamination,'' Virginia Galvin,
director of Cobb County Public Health department, said at a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination occurred June 11 and 12 in the White Water
wading pools in an area called ``Captain Kid's Cove.'' Authorities
said it is unclear which specific pool spread the contamination and
which child , or children, triggered the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the children also attended the same day care facility
run out of a private home in Bartow County, Ga., but they were all
taken to play at White Water on those particular dates, Galvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   White Water spokeswoman Deedie Dowdle said it is unclear where
the contamination occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way we could know where the kids played when they
were here,'' she said. ``We do know that the group from the day
care center did play in Captain Kids' Cove area.''
</P>
<P>
   No other link, such as bad beef or juice, or other common risk
usually associated with E. coli 0157:H7 has been established, said
Dr. Kathleen Toomey, director of Georgia's Public Health Division,
which is leading the investigation. ``The single common exposure of
all these cases was attending White Water Park on June 11 and June
12.'' Beef was ruled out when one of the children was found to be
vegetarian, Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   No evidence exists of ongoing risk in the pools, said health
officials who deemed the pools to now be safe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, health experts said children or adults who were
exposed on those days and have not had symptoms of E. coli
infection by now should be in the clear. Symptoms of infection _
including severe abdominal cramping, watery or bloody diarrhea and
urinary tract infections _ typically develop within nine days
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   The number of extremely ill children hospitalized from the E.
coli O157:H7 contamination rose from four to six Tuesday afternoon
in Atlanta hospitals. Ranging in age from 2 to 4 years of age, they
all suffer from hemolytic uremic syndrome, HUS, a serious
complication of E. coli infection that attacks kidneys, blood, and
potentially the brain and heart. It requires treatment by kidney
dialysis, blood transfusions and respirators.
</P>
<P>
   The cases also expanded beyond Georgia's state borders. Two
children from Tennessee and one from South Carolina _ all of whom
played in the White Water kiddie pools during a June 11 visit _ are
confirmed with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 to 7 percent of children under 5 years of age who are
sickened by this E. coli strain develop HUS. Most survive but only
after months of hospitalization and a multitude of problems: severe
dehydration, kidney and respiratory failure. Antibiotics do not
kill the strain and treatment involves keeping the patient alive
while the body rids itself of the toxic matter. The condition is
fatal in 5 to 15 percent of cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``As ill as these these children get, they can regain their full
function, '' Galvin said. ``They need very aggressive and
supportive care.''
</P>
<P>
   The conditions of two girls, 6- and 2-year-old sisters, who were
felled by the bacterial infection were upgraded Tuesday afternoon
to good, while a 3-year-old boy remained in fair condition at
Egleston Hospital for Children. Scottish Rite Children's Medical
Center is also caring for a 4-year-old girl in critical condition
and Brody Weiss, the 3-year-old son of Atlanta Braves shortstop
Walt Weiss. He is in serious condition, one step better than
critical.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals have not identified the children; the elder Weiss
confirmed that the middle of his three boys was among them.
</P>
<P>
   Two older Atlanta-area children, ages 8 and 12, also have
confirmed strains of the bacteria but are not being treated in
hospitals. Only the case of the 12-year-old is considered unrelated
to the other clusters in Atlanta because he did not visit White
Water.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, seven cases of diarrhea in a group of children and
adults who visited the park June 11 and 12 are under investigation.
In Atlanta-area hospitals, emergency rooms have been alerted to
symptoms of the infection that is often brushed off as a less
serious stomach ailment. All public health departments in 50 states
have also been notified by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention to be on guard for more cases from residents who may
have visited White Water during that critical time period.
</P>
<P>
   State and Cobb County, Ga. health officials deemed White Water
now to be safe pools but cautioned parents from letting their kids
swim or wade in any pools while they are feeling sick.
</P>
<P>
   They also revealed the pools did not meet safe levels of
chlorination during an investigation last weekend. The level of
chlorine was 1 part per million, Galvin said. The safe level is
between 1.5 to 3 parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Cobb Health Department officials doing an
inspection at the park found the chlorine level in one of the
kiddie pools was below the required level. The officials requested
that the pool be closed to the public until the level was brought
back up, Dowdle said. But at the time they made the request, the
park was already closed for the day, and the level was back up to
the normal reading by the opening of business on Sunday, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Officials did not characterize the commercial waterpark as
negligent, saying the fecal water contamination is an unusual route
of transmission for the potentially fatal strain of bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   E. coli, a common bacterium that lives in the digestive tracts
of humans and other animals, is most often spread through food,
primarily ground beef. The strain affecting the children, E. coli
0157:H7, is highly toxic, particularly to young children and the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, there were 39 reported cases of 0157:H7 illness in
1996, the last year for which figures are available. Nationwide
each year, E. coli infections will sicken 20,000 people, killing
200 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Still unclear is how the potentially fatal strain of bacteria
managed to survive two days in water treated with chlorine, which
usually kills bacteria. The filtering system at White Water's
wading pools provides a constant hourly circulation, and it is
separate from the bigger swimming pools. Diapers are also not
allowed to be worn in the wading pools, Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's possible some of the bacteria could have survived
overnight or the same sick kid could have come back June 12 to
swim,'' said Jane Koehler, Georgia state epidemiologist. ``He could
have had liquid diarrhea and that's why it went unnoticed. Parents
of the sick children have told me their kids were gulping down
water while playing in this wading pools so that could explain how
the transmission immediately occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is any evidence of negligence (on White
Water),'' Galvin said. ``This is an unusual route of transmission
but if a child had an accident in a pool, it would not take much
bacteria to get in your mouth to lead to infection.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writers Bill Torpy, Doug
Payne, Ellen Lee and Matt Aldag contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
