<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-HEAT-COX     06-23 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-HEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As Florida fires burn, officials worry about Georgia
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Firefighters in deep South Georgia snuffed out two
fires that ignited after a thunderstorm Tuesday, threatening a
repeat of the wildfires that swept woods near the Okefenokee Swamp
until they were extinguished this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the rain, but we didn't need God's lightning,'' said
Deputy S.L. Malcomb of the Charlton County (Ga.) Sheriff's
Department. ``We got on them pretty quickly and got them out pretty
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wildfires continue to spread ruin across north Florida, which
Georgia got a dose of last week, and the heat continues to blister
crops in both states.
</P>
<P>
   The stifling heat shows no sign of easing with temperatures in
the upper 90s forecast for metro Atlanta today. Temperatures should
stay in the 90s at least until the weekend, according to the
National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Atlanta area, which recorded a high of 91
degrees, were mild Tuesday compared to the southern half of the
state, where temperatures reached 100 in Alma, Ga. and 99 in Fort
Benning, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The heat wave played a role in wildfires that swept 16,000 acres
in southern Charlton County and burned timber valued at more than
$14 million. Searing temperatures and lack of rain have cost north
Florida famers $100 million in crop damage and are threatening
Georgia's $159 million corn crop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corn in the southern part of the state is gone,'' said Georgia
agriculture Commissioner Tommy Irvin. ``We already have disaster
situations in as many as 20 counties, and that number could soar to
more than 50.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, two deaths have been attributed to the heat wave. In
Dothan, Ala., a 3-year-old boy died of apparent heat stroke Monday
after being left in a locked van at a Mobile day-care center,
police said. Earlier this month, a 73-year-old Henry County, Ala.,
woman succumbed to heat stroke at her home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
