<P>
   (NYT11) MATAMOROS, Mexico -- June 23, 1998 -- GM-MEXICO, 6-23 --
In one of General Motors' sprawling auto parts plants in a
Matamoros industrial park just south of the Rio Grande, thousands
of Mexican workers make $1 to $2 an hour producing instrument
panels and steering wheels for GM cars and trucks. Misaela Castro
Margaro, 21, earned $1.05 an hour fitting vinyl blades onto wiper
assemblies at the plant until her three-month contract expired
earlier this month. ``I loved that plant,'' she says. (Gerardo
Magallon/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) KLINA, Yugoslavia -- June 23, 1998 -- YUGO-ALBANIANS,
6-23 -- Mourners close the coffin of 17-year-old Serbian Oliver
Zaic, killed in his garden in Bica as he protected his widowed
mother and 10-year-old sister, Marica, from ethnic Albanian rebels,
his family says. ``Have we been abandoned?'' Milic Zaic, 42, the
slain boy's uncle asks the crowd. ``You, Oliver, have shown us our
destiny, the destiny of all who try to defend their homes. I
apologize, my boy, that we cannot bury you in your own village.''
(Wade Goddard/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) EVANSTON, Ill. -- June 23, 1998 -- TEMP-EXECS, 6-23 --
Many executives, no longer enamored of steady management jobs, are
signing up to be, in effect, temps working for a daily rate,
without all the bells and whistles that accompany so many pay
packages. ``There's a huge advantage in objectivity, because you're
not worried about your next position within the company and where
you go from there,'' says J. Steve Davis, who recently completed a
stint running the Wells BDDP advertising agency. (Todd Buchanan/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MILWAUKEE -- June 23, 1998 -- 14UP-FILM-REVIEW-2, 6-23 --
14-year-old Luis, who has moved to Milwaukee and prefers the name
Tony these days. That demographically correct band who became
America's darlings in 1991 has returned in a second installment of
the documentary series that is following the lives of 16 children
from age 7 through adulthood. It will be broadcast for 90 minutes
as ``14 Up in America'' on Sunday night on Showtime. (Morry
Gash/New York Times Photo)
</P>
