<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- June 23, 1998 -- COOKING-GRADS, 6-23 --
Matthew Lauk during a stint at the Marriott Marquis Hotel in
Manhattan, where dozens of workers prepare meals for as many as
3,000 people. He says his job there, which ended last week, paid
better and was far less stressful than a previous job at Trois
Jean, a New York bistro, which he landed after graduating the New
England Culinary Institute. ``It's a pretty weird profession,''
concedes Laux, 22, who will next be the chef at a small resort in
Belize. (Don Hogan Charles/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HYDE PARK, N.Y. -- June 23, 1998 -- COOKING-CIA, 6-23 --
At the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, students learn
business skills, as well as how to cook, and earn college degrees.
Starting at 7:30 a.m., the campus crawls with some 2,100 students,
knife cases in tote and toques bobbing. In 36 spacious and modern
teaching kitchens, the air is filled with the sounds of mixers
whirring, knives tapping on cutting boards and the occasional roar
of an instructor. (Joyce Dopkeen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- June 23, 1998 -- COOKING-SCHOOLS, 6-23 -- Too
many cooks? Not at the French Culinary Institute in New York, where
students look on as Pascal Beric, an instructor, shows students
cooking techniques used by professional chefs. (Fred R. Conrad/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- June 23, 1998 -- HANDMADE-MOZZARELLA, 6-23 --
Giuseppe Cuomo making mozzarella in the kitchen of the Mezzogiorno
restaurant, one of six New York restaurants for which he makes the
fresh cheese on the premises. His family has done the same for
three generations in southern Italy, and Cuomo, 52, continued the
tradition after he moved here 20 years ago. ``The trick is to keep
it pliable and smooth,'' he says. ``If it's in water too long, the
cheese loses too much of its butterfat and gets rubbery.'' (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- June 23, 1998 -- YOUNG-CHESS-STAR, 6-23 --
Kwadwo Acheampong, 14, of the South Bronx, smiles shyly when asked
about his recent appearances on ``Good Morning America'' and ``The
Rosie O'Donnell Show.'' Acheampong is co-captain of the Middle
School 118 All-Star Knights, winners of the 1998 National Junior
High School Scholastic Chess Championship in Phoenix. Next month
the All-Star Knights travel to Moscow for the World Youth Games.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- June 23, 1998 -- FISH-LOGO, 6-23 -- For eight
years this logo depicting the state, an outstretched hand, a family
of four in silhouette and a fish has been used by the town of
Republic, Mo. Recently, controversy has surrounded the logo's fish.
``The fish symbol, also known as an ichthus, first appeared in the
second century and was used as a secret sign of Christianity,''
says volunteer ACLU lawyer Doug Bonney in a letter to the town.
Debates like this one in Republic over the separation of church and
state are coming up with increasing regularity around the country.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
