<HEADLINE>
HINE, SKIP AWAY SET FOR TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With the Hollywood Gold Cup contenders'
major workouts complete, the only question for Skip Away trainer
Sonny Hine is, Where do we eat?
</P>
<P>
   Hine, one of horse racing's real characters, and his wife
Carolyn, owner of Skip Away, claim they haven't taken a three-day
vacation in 35 years of marriage. So the Hines plan to make the
most of a rare visit to Los Angeles to run their popular horse
against Silver Charm, Gentlemen and as many as five others Sunday
in the $1 million Gold Cup for 3-year-olds and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The track is taking us to dinner Saturday night. Maybe I'll
get to go to _ what do they call it? _ the Farmer's Market,'' Sonny
Hine said on the phone from New York. ``Somebody said we should go
to Catalina Island, it's so beautiful. I said, `My wife gets
seasick in a bathtub, how the hell are we going to get over
there?'''
</P>
<P>
   At least it looks certain that Skip Away will make it to
Hollywood Park, site of the 1997 Breeders' Cup Classic romp that
clinched his older-horses championship. Skip Away is booked on a
Thursday-morning flight to LAX.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, with jockey Jerry Bailey aboard, Skip Away
breezed 6 furlongs in a quick 1:11 1/5 at Belmont Park. The effort
eliminated Hine's doubts about the 5-year-old's health.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away had swelling in his forelegs for about a day after an
incident Friday in which he dumped his exercise rider while dodging
a fallen horse during a gallop, and ran free for 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really ready to run,'' Hine said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, the 1997 Kentucky Derby winner, also worked out
Tuesday, going 5 furlongs in :58 3/5, the fastest of 41 at the
distance at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``All systems go,'' trainer Bob Baffert said from his barn.
</P>
<P>
   As well as stars Skip Away, Silver Charm and Gentlemen, the Gold
Cup is expected to draw Puerto Madero, Budroyale, Don't Blame Rio,
probably Bagshot and possibly Mud Route. Entries will be announced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Livening the three-way battle of the nation's richest older
horses is the recent war of words between Hine and Baffert. Hine
accused the Silver Charm camp of ``ducking me'' but says a quote
calling Baffert a coward was taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they want me to wrestle Baffert, that's the last thing I
heard,'' Hine said Tuesday. ``I could probably arm wrestle him. I'm
67 right now. I like a good meal and sitting in a chair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
