<HEADLINE>
PANEL APPROVES DEEP CUTS IN PROGRAMS CHAMPIONED BY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Setting Congress on a collision course with
President Clinton, a House panel on Tuesday approved a proposal to
slash the president's education initiatives as well as the annual
financing for home heating subsidies for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal provides substantial increases for the National
Institutes of Health and the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention, underscoring the Republicans' emphasis on popular
health and research programs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it takes a $2.6 billion bite out of
administration priorities, cutting the Goals 2000 education program
in half, eliminating the Low Income Home Energy Assistance Program,
terminating the Summer Youth jobs program and decreasing money for
tutoring for disadvantaged children.
</P>
<P>
   The energy assistance program, which costs $1.1 billion, pays
for home heating for 4.4 million poor households. Two-thirds of the
recipients earn less than $8,000 a year. The summer jobs program
spends $871 million for employment of 530,000 youths.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal, passed by the subcommittee on Labor, Health and
Human Services by a vote of 8 to 7, calls for the most drastic cuts
so far as the Republican-controlled Congress works its way through
13 appropriations bills that Congress must pass to keep the
government running in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials responded harshly on Tuesday night to
the subcommittee action, saying that the president would almost
certainly veto the measure in its current form.
</P>
<P>
   The president said in a statement that the cuts were
``arbitrary'' and ``extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is out of step with our values and the wrong vision
for America's future,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats said the cuts were so extreme that the
Republicans were setting the stage for a confrontation that could
result in the kind of standoff that shut down the government two
years ago and damaged the Republicans' image with the public _ a
gamble that some aides said Republicans might be willing to take
this year because the president appeared politically weaker than he
has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said they were straight-jacketed by last year's
budget agreement, which virtually froze discretionary spending, and
they played down the need for social programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that we don't have more money to throw at problems,''
said Rep. Robert Livingston of Louisiana, chairman of the
Appropriations Committee. ``But it's the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans also acknowledged that the bill was constructed
by House leaders to attract the maximum support of the House's
vocal conservatives. This is part of the Republican strategy to
activate the party's base of conservative voters in the November
elections, when many other voters, content with the strong economy,
may not be motivated to go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the proposal is so appealing to conservatives
that it may alienate Republican moderates, without whom the
proposal could not pass. This could deepen the factions within the
party and weaken its chances of retaining control of the House.
</P>
<P>
   The full Appropriations Committee is to vote on the proposed
cuts in mid-July, and then the bill will move to the House floor.
Senate Democrats said on Tuesday that they would strongly oppose
the measure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The cuts in domestic social programs help Congress keep within
the spending limits it agreed to last year with the administration
to balance the budget. They are not designed to make room for the
tax cuts that Republicans are promoting as their main election-year
agenda, but they could if Congress changes its rules to allow tax
cuts to come from discretionary spending. At the moment, tax cuts
can come only from entitlements, which are not discretionary.
</P>
<P>
   The president has asked for discretionary spending of about $538
billion for next year, up from $523 billion this year. The House
has proposed spending $532 billion and the Senate about $534
billion, sums that because of inflation amount to a virtual
spending freeze.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. DavidObey, the top Democrat on the Appropriations
Committee, said that the Republicans were cutting programs to come
up with money for medical research that would have come from
tobacco companies under a bill that died last week in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``By killing the tobacco bill, Republicans have made it much
harder to fund the president's health initiatives,'' Obey said.
``In order to pay for an increase in NIH funding, instead of using
money from the tobacco settlement, they have decided to take that
funding out of the hides of the weakest and most vulnerable people
in society.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor-education bill increases financing for the National
Institutes of Health by $1.3 billion, up more than 9 percent from
this year and $126 million more than the president has requested.
It increases money for the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention by $202 million over this year, $89 million more than
the president sought.
</P>
<P>
   On policy matters, the bill bans the use of federal money for
research using human embryos, bans the distribution of needles and
syringes for the injection of any illegal drug and prohibits
federal financing for a rerun of the Teamsters election.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's program cuts in the labor-education subcommittee
follow House votes on Monday to increase spending on local energy
and water projects and on military construction.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved $21.1 billion in energy and water programs,
or about $700 million more than the President requested. These
include about 200 local projects for flood control and stopping
beach erosion, projects eagerly sought by lawmakers in an election
year.
</P>
<P>
   But it slashed Clinton's request for more money for research
into solar power and other forms of renewable energy like wind. It
also cut his request for more money to maintain the nation's
nuclear weapons arsenal.
</P>
</TEXT>
