<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHARES OF MICROSOFT CLIMB AFTER APPEALS COURT RULING
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Microsoft soared 5.15 percent, to $100.75, after a
federal appeals court overturned a lower court's order against the
company. The ruling allows Microsoft to sell its computer operating
software with its Internet browsing feature. The decision was also
a setback for the Justice Department and the 20 states that filed
antitrust lawsuits against Microsoft last month.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ SURGES; DOW RISES 117.33
</P>
<P>
   Investors bid up technology shares in a furious rally that
reversed a three-day decline in blue-chip stocks and pulled the
entire market higher. The Nasdaq composite index jumped 38.75
points, or 2.15 percent, to 1,844.57. The Dow Jones industrials
rose 117.33 points, or 1.35 percent, to 8,828.46, back to levels of
a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury securities rose on a renewed rally in the dollar and
vibrant demand for newly auctioned 2-year Treasury notes. The gain
in the benchmark 30-year bond pushed its yield down to 5.64 percent
from 5.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL EXPECTED TO DELAY CHIP SET
</P>
<P>
   Intel is expected to delay the release of its 450NX chip set,
the newest version of the company's Pentium II technology, by
between six and eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   SEC EASES ARBITRATION RULES
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has decided that
brokerage industry employees will no longer be required to
arbitrate claims of employment discrimination before industry
panels.
</P>
<P>
   FDA APPROVES NEW ANTI-TB DRUG
</P>
<P>
   The Food and Drug Administration has approved a new
anti-tuberculosis drug made by Hoechst Marion Roussell that will be
marketed under the name Priftin.
</P>
<P>
   AD SPENDING ESTIMATE INCREASED
</P>
<P>
   The robust economy will fuel even more spending for advertising
this year than expected earlier, forecasts Robert Coen of
McCann-Erickson. He predicts that marketers will spend a record
$200.3 billion in the United States in 1998, up 6.8 percent from a
revised figure of $187.5 billion for 1997.
</P>
<P>
   YELTSIN CALLS FOR ECONOMIC CHANGES
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to impress the International Monetary Fund, which
is beginning negotiations over billions of dollars in additional
loans, Russian President Boris Yeltsin demanded that legislators
enact measures to restore the confidence of foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN WORKS ON BANK RESCUE PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese government moved a step closer to establishing a
system to help restructure weak banks. Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto and other Japanese officials also sought to reassure
depositors that the government would maintain financial stability,
and tried to allay fears that the Long-Term Credit Bank, one of the
nation's largest, is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAM NAMES HEAD OF MUSIC UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Doug Morris was named chief executive of Seagram's combined
Polygram/Universal Music operation to replace Alain Levy, who
resigned. Seagram agreed to buy Polygram NV last month, but reduced
the purchase price by $200 million, to $10.4 billion, because
Polygram's performance has been weaker than expected. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
