<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-VISAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA CANCELS VISAS FOR RADIO FREE ASIA JOURNALISTS
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds., see related CHINA-CLINTON, CHINA-PIRACY, CHINA-MEDIA,
CHINA-U.S.-ECON, CHINA-PEONY, CHINA-MISSILES, CLINTON-CONGRESS.) 
(ja) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of a state visit the White House has
billed as a chance to encourage greater openness by the Chinese
government, China has canceled visas for three journalists from
Radio Free Asia who had planned to cover President Clinton's trip
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who is scheduled to depart for China on Wednesday,
denounced the Chinese decision as ``highly objectionable'' and said
that ``we will protest it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is depriving China of the credit that it otherwise would
have gotten for giving more visas to a more diverse group of
journalists,'' he told reporters at a White House event. ``We hope
they will reconsider.''
</P>
<P>
   But even as the president was voicing his disappointment over
China's action, Radio Free Asia, which was established by Congress
in 1994 to broadcast news and other programs to China and other
authoritarian nations in Asia, was expressing its disappointment
with the handling of the issue by White House.
</P>
<P>
   It said the Clinton administration could have challenged the
order by allowing the three journalists to board the jet chartered
by the White House for news organizations covering the president's
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists from Radio Free Asia, which has frequently drawn
protests from Beijing over its coverage of human rights abuses in
China, have Chinese visas stamped in their passports.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after the visas were issued last week that the
Chinese authorities telephoned the journalists at home and told
them that the visas had been canceled. The developments were first
reported in The Washington Times and The Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Richter, the president of Radio Free Asia, said in an
interview that he had urged the White House to allow the reporters
to travel to China aboard the chartered jet, leaving officials in
China with the final decision over whether to admit them. But
Richter said that the White House refused to risk a last-minute
confrontation with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McCurry, the White House spokesman, said the White House
had decided to prevent the reporters from going after the airline
handling the charter, Cathay Pacific of Hong Kong, indicated that
``they're going to abide by international aviation requirements,
which state that you have to have a valid visa in order to board
the aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   Radio Free Asia began broadcasting Mandarin-language programs to
China in September 1996, and its programs are routinely jammed by
the Chinese government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3339 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SURGERY-BLOODLESS-SPI     06-23 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURGERY-BLOODLESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS HONING IN ON `BLOODLESS' SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Using ultrasound instead of scalpels, scientists are
honing in on ways to do ``bloodless'' surgery without ever making
an incision.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors are already doing early-stage clinical trials using the
new technique, which is called High Intensity Focused Ultrasound,
to destroy various solid tumors and to stop internal bleeding
without opening the body. The University of Washington is one of
the few institutions in the world studying surgical ultrasound.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers hope that within a few years hand-held ultrasound
devices will be used to detect and stop internal bleeding for
trauma patients in remote locations, such as the mountains, or on
the battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, it may be possible to do ultrasound scans of the
whole body, and eradicate tumors that show up at the same time,
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that far away,'' said Larry Crum, chairman of the UW
department of acoustics and electromagnetics at the Applied Physics
Laboratory. ``It's not a Star Trek thing. People are doing it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Crum's research group is studying how to use the technique to
stop internal bleeding and is doing experiments to determine how
ultrasound can be used to break up blood clots.
</P>
<P>
   The technology was the subject of talks Tuesday at the
Acoustical Society of America Meeting, which is being held in
Seattle this week and has drawn scientists from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is based on the same principle as the old
childhood trick of using a magnifying glass to focus light on an
object, such as a leaf, and causing it to smolder.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the ultrasound waves pass harmlessly through the
skin and other organs without damaging them until they get to the
``focal site.'' At this focal point, they cause a rapid, intense
heating of the tissue, cauterizing it. If the beam is focused on a
bleeding vessel or artery, it will cause the blood to coagulate and
stop the bleeding. If it is focused on a tumor, it will destroy the
tissue, rendering the tumor harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Most people are familiar with ultrasound for its ability to
reflect images of the developing fetus in a pregnant woman. Those
ultrasound waves, which are not harmful, are very low intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrasound used for surgical purposes is 10,000 times as intense
and must be focused using mechanical or electronic means before it
can act to destroy tissue.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of it is how precise it is, said Gail ter Haar f the
Royal Marsden Hospital in England, who was at the Seattle meeting
and is conducting clinical trials on patients with tumors of the
liver, kidney and prostate.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is so precise that doctors can control within six
cells exactly where the ultrasound waves cause the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very sharp boundary,'' she said. ``It's sharper than a
scalpel.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with many surgeries is that ``you do a lot of
cutting and damage to normal tissue to get to something abnormal,''
said Dr. Stephen Carter, a radiologist at the UW School of Medicine
who works with Crum. That's especially problematic in areas, such
as the brain, where damaging normal tissue can have serious
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can not damage normal tissue, it's a tremendous
advantage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrasound, which is very high frequency sound energy, is
ideally suited to surgical applications. Microwaves can't be
focused on such small areas, X-rays damage tissue on the way in,
and lasers can't penetrate the tissue, Crum said.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment is especially promising for tumors in areas where
operating is risky or impossible, such as the liver.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients survive treatment for their primary cancers, only
to die when tumors spread to their livers, ter Haar said.
</P>
<P>
   In other cases, such as prostate cancer, surgery can have
unintended consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In men with advanced prostate cancer, the treatment sometimes
requires removal of the whole prostate, Crum said. But that's
tricky, since severing nerves on either side can cause complete
impotence, or complete incontinence, or both.
</P>
<P>
   So far, ultrasound treatment appears to work with no adverse
effects.
</P>
<P>
   In early trials, patients tolerated the treatments well and
didn't require anesthesia, Crum said. ``It's a fantastic thing for
medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultrasound has other new applications for medicine as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ekos, a Bothell-based company, is developing ways to use
ultrasound to improve the delivery of medications to certain parts
of the body. Ultrasound has been used in conjunction with drugs to
dissolve blood clots and to improve the uptake of the drug at its
intended target.
</P>
<P>
   Sound waves are also being studied as a substitute for needles
for ``injecting'' drugs such as insulin, or interferon directly
through the skin.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, using ultrasound during chemotherapy or gene
therapy appears to increase the effectiveness of these treatments
as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
