<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYGIENE CHOICES ROLL ON AND ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This occurred to me recently as I stood in a supermarket aisle,
puzzling over the array of deodorants available to me.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it seems simple enough to just stick with what you've been
using and move on to the frozen foods, assuming no one has
complained about a funky aura following you around, but the
plethora of choices always amazes me. I stood there for several
minutes as a steady stream of shoppers swirled past, trying to make
a choice.
</P>
<P>
   The rainbow of labels included Suave, Mum, Mitchum, Ban, Arm &AMP;
Hammer, Secret, Soft and Dry, Dry Idea, Degree, Gillette, Right
Guard, Sure, Teen Spirit, Crystal Clean, Degree, Arid, Brut, Old
Spice, Speedstick, Lady Speedstick and Speedstick Ultimate.
</P>
<P>
   Speedstick Ultimate? I love that. Why does the company make any
other kind of deodorant? Who is going to settle for Speedstick
Inferior when they know Ultimate is out there?
</P>
<P>
   But these were just the brands available. Once you've narrowed
that choice down, you still have the various types to contend with:
</P>
<P>
   Wide-ball roll-on, clear soft solid, scented, unscented, wide
solid, ultra-dry soft solid, unscented wide solid, silken solid,
clear gel, invisible dry, powder fresh, shower fresh and, in a nice
nod to a simpler time, regular. &QL; 
THINKING TOO MUCH
</P>
<P>
   Winnow these choices down and you finally . . . wait, one more
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Deodorant?
</P>
<P>
   Antiperspirant?
</P>
<P>
   Or deodorant AND antiperspirant?
</P>
<P>
   The idea, as I understand it, is simply to prevent stinking.
Anything beyond that and you're thinking about it too much.
</P>
<P>
   Across the aisle, I spotted razors. Lots of razors. Bic
Sensitive Skin. Bic Tough Beard. Bic Twin Sensitive Skin. Bic Twin
Tough Beard. Bic Silky Touch. Bic Original (sigh). Gillette Good
News. Gillette Custom Plus. Gillette Sensor XL. Gillette Sensor XL
for Women. Gillette Custom-Plus Pivot. Gillette Daisy Plus.
Gillette Agility. Schick Protector (ah, the anti-Van Gogh model).
Schick Tracer. Schick Tracer FX. Schick Personal Touch Silk
Effects.
</P>
<P>
   I could be wrong, but I don't believe it was always thus. I grew
up in a small town, so maybe stores there didn't stock staples in
so many different varieties.
</P>
<P>
   My father relied on my mom to pick up his hygiene supplies. And
he didn't have to specify his order. ``Pick up some deodorant and
razor blades'' did the trick. &QL; 
FAR FROM FATHER
</P>
<P>
   So, for the duration of my life, anyway, he always used the same
brands. He enveloped himself in a small cloud from sprays with
standard Right Guard in the old brown can, which managed to make
him smell like a doctor's office. He shaved with a single-blade
Gillette razor better suited to scraping paint off furniture (tough
beard).
</P>
<P>
   Proving that the apple sometimes does fall a good distance from
the tree, I am a sucker for variety. I hate to use the same thing
twice, which is why I bought the Schick Protector. I was perfectly
happy with my Gillette Sensor. But the Protector offered, in
addition to an Ultra Glide Comfort Strip, Pivoting Blade,
Rubberized Grip, Protective Cover and Holding Stand, ``Safety
Wires,'' which ``provide unsurpassed safety from nicks and cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   I've not noticed any real difference. I've tried shaving with
one razor and then another. I've even tried shaving half my face
with one razor and half with the other to see whether anyone
noticed a cleaner, closer look.
</P>
<P>
   No one did.
</P>
<P>
   All these choices could drive a man to drink. Let's see, there's
Fat Tire, Shiner Bock, Pete's Summer Brew, Pete's ESB Lager, Pete's
Wicked Ale, Pete's Wicked Strawberry Blonde, Samuel Adams Cherry
Wheat, Samuel Adams Summer Ale, Samuel Adams Boston Lager, Henry
Weinhard's Dark, Henry Weinhard's Blue Boar Ale, Budweiser, Bud
Light, Coors, Coors Light, Miller, Miller Lite, Miller Genuine
Draft, Miller Genuine Draft Lite . . .
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. By the time I decide, I won't be thirsty anymore. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
