<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FDA-HENNEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOMINEE TO HEAD FDA IS CALLED A CONSENSUS BUILDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN.: Kan., N.M.) (ja) 
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six years ago, when Dr. David Kessler was new to
the job of commissioner of food and drugs, he flew to Kansas to ask
a woman he had never met to become one of his chief deputies. Dr.
Jane Henney, a cancer specialist who was an administrator at the
University of Kansas School of Medicine, had a reputation, Kessler
said, for being ``very smart, very talented, very
independent-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next two years, Henney managed the daily activities of
the Food and Drug Administration, a vast agency with 9,000
employees and a mandate to monitor the safety of $1 trillion worth
of products each year. Before leaving in 1994 to become vice
president for Health Sciences at the University of New Mexico, she
hired many of the top officials who now work at the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the cadre of people at the agency, they
certainly reflect Jane's imprint,'' said Kessler, who left the job
16 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Henney, 51, was asked to leave academia for Washington
once again, this time by President Clinton, who nominated her to
fill Kessler's shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said Tuesday they expected Henney to
win Senate confirmation but not necessarily without a fight. Urging
the Senate to hold hearings quickly, Clinton said the agency needs
``a full-time and confirmed commissioner,'' and pronounced Henney
``extremely well qualified to serve as commissioner as the agency
prepares itself to meet the challenges of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Henney say she will be no clone of Kessler, whose
six-year tenure was marked by crusades against tobacco and dietary
supplements and by repeated fights with congressional Republicans
who wanted to wanted the agency to be more cooperative with the
pharmaceutical industry in bringing drugs to market.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, one phrase often chosen to describe Henney is
``consensus builder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She doesn't come into this with a lot of baggage one way or
the other,'' said Chris Jennings, deputy assistant to the president
for health policy. ``She has not really been involved in causes of
the day. David Kessler was the right person for his time but Jane
is the right person for this time.''
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed, Henney will face a daunting task. After years of
debate and resistance from the agency, Congress last year adopted
legislation to speed the review of new medicines; it will be up to
Henney, who says she supports it, to put the new law into effect.
In addition, she will have to navigate a political minefield of
issues, from tobacco control to the safety of the food supply to
questions raised by critics about whether the agency, already using
speedier reviews, has allowed unsafe drugs to reach consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She faces a Republican Congress with expressed antipathies to
her predecessor,'' said Thomas Moore, a senior fellow in health
policy at George Washington University Medical Center who studies
drug safety. ``There are well-organized pressures by industry to
approve drugs more quickly, and on the other hand there are going
to be people beating on the door when there is a safety crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   One agency official, who spoke on condition he not be
identified, said: ``It's a much harder job than when Kessler took
it. He made it into that, in a way. The agency is just so much more
public and so much more visible.''
</P>
<P>
   Henney (pronounced HAY-nee) grew up in Woodburn, Ind.,
population 512. In interviews with local newspapers, she has
recounted how, while watching a good friend die from breast cancer,
she decided to become a doctor. She came of age in medicine at a
time when there were few women in the field; she was one of just 12
in a 250-member class at the University of Indiana Medical School.
If her nomination is approved, she would be the first woman to head
the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But confirmation may not come quickly. ``I don't think it is
going to be easy,'' said one top official of the Department of
Health and Human Services, of which the FDA is a part. ``Most
important is that she is going to make clear that she supports the
law passed last year and is going to fully implement it, and that
is going to be her top priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than expressing an interest in food safety, Henney has
said little about what she would do if she gets the job. She
declined requests for interviews Tuesday, issuing a brief statement
that said she is committed to the new drug legislation. ``There is
no greater honor,'' she said, ``than to be asked to return to
public service and to lead the FDA.''
</P>
<P>
   Henney already knows the agency well and is popular there. ``She
is a person that people like working for,'' said Linda Suydam, who
worked for Henney both at the FDA and at the University of New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But Sidney Wolfe, director of Public Citizen's Health Research
Group, an advocacy organization in Washington that has been
critical of the agency's willingness to approve new drugs quickly,
expressed concerns that Henney would not be tough enough for the
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very worried about the crisis of the FDA, which is the
rush to approve to many drugs.'' Wolfe said, adding that he feared
that Henney ``doesn't handle crisis well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
