<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE BILL PROTECTS INTERNET FROM NEW TAXES FOR 3 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to throw cold water on the frenzy to tax the
Internet, the House passed a bill Tuesday that would bar state and
local governments from imposing new Internet taxes for three years.
</P>
<P>
   Framing the measure as a ``pre-emptive strike'' on taxes during
a period of rapid Internet growth, including the online sale of
goods, the House passed the bill after months of careful
negotiations by state governors, businessmen and the Internet
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information should be made available as freely and widely as
possible throughout the world,'' said Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., who wrote the bill out of concern that new taxes could
slow the Internet's growth. ``It should not be taxed and it should
not be regulated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate wants a six-year moratorium on taxation, and is
expected to take up its bill sometime this year.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would temporarily prohibit most state and local
governments from imposing new kinds of taxes on the Internet, like
taxing users for access. It would also stave off taxes on sales
that would ordinarily not be taxed if they had taken place over the
telephone or by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Eight states already tax Internet access, and the bill would
allow them to continue the tax if they pass a law to do so within
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye on the three-year deadline, the bill would create a
commission to study the issue of Internet taxes and make
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   The bill seeks to balance the interests of those who use the
Internet to find information and buy goods, businesses that want to
use the Internet to sell their goods, and state and local
governments that see an opportunity to expand their tax bases.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the National Governors' Association has opposed the
measure, saying it would unfairly infringe on the right of state
and local governments to levy taxes. The opposition stemmed mainly
from the future possibility of taxing goods sold on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, Internet sales are expected to reach between
$200 billion and $500 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   State and local officials have long sought to plug a legal
loophole that deprives them of billions of dollars in taxes in
mail-order sales, and by extension, Internet sales. Existing law
does not require companies to collect sales taxes from customers in
states where those companies do not have a physical presence.
</P>
<P>
   For the support of the Governors' Association, Cox agreed to
expand the Internet study group's mission to include
recommendations on a way to tax out-of-state customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
