<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-ARBITRATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEC RELAXES ARBITRATION RULES AT BROKERAGE HOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By PETER TRUELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Securities and Exchange Commission said Tuesday
that brokerage industry employees would no longer be required to
arbitrate claims of employment discrimination before industry
panels.
</P>
<P>
   The rule change, which takes effect on Jan. 1, was sought in
December by the National Association of Securities Dealers Inc., an
industry self-regulatory body, after several years of pressure from
disgruntled employees and civil rights groups.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have maintained that the securities industry's
insistence on mandatory industry arbitration in employment disputes
has resulted in a pattern of unfair treatment, including widespread
discrimination against women at securities firms and the frequent
denial of employees' civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Levitt Jr., the chairman of the SEC, who announced the
commission's approval Tuesday, said in a statement that it was ``a
big step in a positive direction,'' and encouraged other
self-regulatory organizations to follow the lead of the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, under pressure from lawsuits, the big securities
firms have changed their stance on the issue of mandatory industry
arbitration of employment disputes. Mandatory industry arbitration
of employment disputes is generally a condition of employment for
brokers and other employees who are registered with self-regulatory
organizations such as the NASD.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, for example, which recently settled a class
action suit alleging employment discrimination brought by eight
former women employees, is now changing its way of resolving such
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   From July 1, it will allow employees who are registered members
of the association to have the option, in certain cases, of going
to court rather than industry arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are supportive of this change and it is consistent with our
new dispute resolution program,'' said Bill Halldin, a Merrill
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. criticized the change, contending that
it would add to the legal costs for securities firms. ``We just
firmly believe that having dispute proceedings in two places _
court and arbitration _ raises the costs,'' said Thomas Taggart, a
Schwab spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics of the securities industry's practices were happy
to hear of the commission's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted,'' said Mary Stowell, a lawyer who helped win a
class-action settlement for hundreds of women from Smith Barney
Inc. after several women at the firm sued, contending that there
was a pattern of discrimination and abuse at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time,'' she said. ``It eliminates one roadblock,
but there's more to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But other critics characterized the move as a belated
concession. ``It's a real slap in the face for'' the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission, said Cliff Palefsky, a civil
rights employment lawyer who has for years sought to end mandatory
industry arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rule change should have been made effective immediately,''
he said. ``The SEC has no jurisdiction for enforcing the civil
rights laws. The EEOC does. The SEC either needs to enforce the
civil rights laws or get out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Other securities industry organizations are also expected to
address mandatory industry arbitration soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do plan to address the matter at our September board
meeting,'' a spokeswoman for the New York Stock Exchange said
Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
