<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      06-23 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS QUIET ON DRAFT, SEE NO KNIGHT IN ARMOR  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Phone lines are open. But while there were plenty of
panic-stricken calls being made concerning trades as the National
Basketball Association draft approached, few of them were emanating
from the New York metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and Nets have been subdued in their approach to this
year's draft, which takes place Wednesday night in Vancouver. The
Knicks have no first-round picks, the Nets have no picks at all,
and neither appears so seduced by this year's pool of prospects as
to think that a move is imperative.
</P>
<P>
   For the Knicks, this could change in a hurry if deals start
coming their way. They are not desperate to move up from their
second-round picks, Nos. 38 and 44, but the Knicks would be
interested in moving Chris Childs and Chris Mills for a top pick.
They might even consider trading John Starks if they could land a
point guard in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to make a trade, it would likely have to be for a
player we felt could come in and give us minutes,'' the team's
president, Ernie Grunfeld, said. ``Right now, it's the status quo.
But if the right opportunity to move up presents itself, we'd
act.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a big if considering how little interest has been
expressed in the Knicks' aging, high-salaried roster. Although
Milwaukee has been testing the market recently to see what trade
value point guard Terrell Brandon has, and Phoenix might be
persuaded to trade Steve Nash, the Knicks have not been able to
entice either team with the players they are willing to offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have been trying to move Childs and Mills for the
last two weeks, but teams are wary of reserves with starters'
salaries and years left on their contracts. At some point, if the
deal were as right, the Knicks might add a more coveted player to
the mix. Although he is erratic and is coming off a season marked
with personal problems, Starks has value.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is still coveted, and still has the potential to win games
for you,'' one general manager said. ``But he is probably in the
best situation for him, playing in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Salary-cap rules would make a trade involving Starks difficult
to work out, too. He is a base-year compensation player, which
means that although his salary is $4 million, his salary-cap slot
with the Knicks is only $1.9 million. Beyond this, he is possibly
the most popular Knick and is Patrick Ewing's close friend.
</P>
<P>
   With their trade possibilities limited, the Knicks may be just
as happy to stick with their second-round picks. In a draft full of
uncertainty, they may find a player who is just as capable of
making their roster at No. 38 as they would with a late first-round
pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``The talent in this draft is pretty close through the top
eight,'' Grunfeld said. ``Then there's another group of about five
or six players. After that, it's a crapshoot. The depth is not bad,
but there isn't the impact players you've seen in the past. There's
no Tim Duncan or Keith Van Horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn was grabbed by the Nets last year in a clever draft-day
trade engineered by Coach John Calipari and General Manager John
Nash. This year, the Nets are not even feigning interest in the
draft. They have no picks, and have little desire to acquire one
because they have a roster bubbling over with young talent.
Calipari is so convinced his team is in for a quiet draft day that
he is on vacation in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no definite, `This guy makes us better,' '' Calipari
said before leaving town. ``There was no Keith Van Horn. We knew he
would make us better. Right now, we like where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are keeping their options open. They have talked
about a trade with teams that have multiple first-round picks, like
Milwaukee (Nos. 9 and 19), Houston (14, 16 and 18) and Orlando (12,
13, 15). To cover themselves, they have worked out Arizona forward
Michael Dickerson, Valparaiso guard Bryce Drew and the curiosity Al
Harrington, a high school forward from Elizabeth, N.J., who could
go in the middle of the first round. If the Knicks stay with their
second-round position, they might have a chance to select St.
John's guard Felipe Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Whomever the Knicks select, the player will be hard-pressed to
find his way into a roster already packed with players who have
long-term deals and cemented positions on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like our nucleus,'' Grunfeld said. ``We do not have much
roster space. We feel like we are pretty solid where we are. Very
seldom do you find a rookie that will come in and have an impact
right away.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
