<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0482 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3360 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWISH-CEMETERY-COX     06-23 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWISH-CEMETERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plans for Jewish cemetery may again be blocked
 &HT;    By Marc Freeman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Plans for Palm Beach County's third
Jewish cemetery are being revived, but a Catholic cemetery
inadvertently could stand in the way again.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, the state rejected a cemetery license application
from a Jewish burial company because Our Lady Queen of Peace _ a
Catholic cemetery in Royal Palm Beach, Fla. _ had an abundance of
open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   The state won't allow new cemeteries in a county if existing
cemeteries have too much room. To the disbelief of Levitt-Weinstein
Memorial Chapels &AMP; Cemeteries, state laws don't recognize that Jews
cannot be buried in gentile graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``To ignore that fact seems to be kind of ridiculous,'' said Ira
Sheskin, the South Florida Jewish community's top demographer and a
paid consultant to Levitt-Weinstein. ``People get buried
religiously for the most part.''
</P>
<P>
   With the county's Jewish population still soaring,
Levitt-Weinstein again is asking the state for a license for its
planned 38-acre Mount Nebo Cemetery of the Palm Beaches in suburban
West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials in Hollywood, Fla. hope that potential changes
in licensing rules will land them the cemetery by year's end. The
property already is zoned to permit Mount Nebo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Mount Nebo was a victim of a rule designed to make sure
that Florida counties aren't stuck with more cemetery plots than
will be needed in 30-year time spans.
</P>
<P>
   New cemeteries are allowed when the projected number of burials
outnumbers available spaces at the time of an application. Without
this legal safeguard, a glut of cemeteries would waste developable
land, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   The state rejected Levitt-Weinstein's 1992 application on the
grounds that Our Lady and other county cemeteries within 12 miles
of the planned Mount Nebo could handle all county burials for the
next 30 years. At the time, there were 334,000 spaces for 238,000
expected burials for people of all faiths.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Grossberg, Levitt-Weinstein's executive vice president,
said it didn't matter that ``the archdiocese is not going to bury
Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Walsh, attorney for Florida's Department of Banking and
Finance, which reviews cemetery proposals, said, ``The (state's)
position is that we don't license religious cemeteries _ the
statutes don't allow us to do that. We just license cemeteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Mount Nebo's rejection was a victory for the county's two
existing Jewish cemeteries, Menorah Gardens in West Palm Beach's
northwestern suburbs and Eternal Light Memorial Gardens in suburban
Boynton Beach, Fla. Combined, they have about 70,000 open spaces;
they had fought against competition.
</P>
<P>
   If Mount Nebo is rejected again and the other cemeteries fill
up, Jewish burials eventually would have to be moved out of the
county. Under another scenario, Levitt-Weinstein or another company
might buy a portion of Our Lady and try to open a new Jewish
cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   But Levitt-Weinstein believes it has a chance to win the Mount
Nebo license this time. That's because, last June, a state
administrative law judge threw out the rule used to tabulate
available cemetery spaces in a county.
</P>
<P>
   That rule required totaling all acres of unused cemetery land to
count spaces. One acre equaled 1,200 spaces.
</P>
<P>
   When Levitt-Weinstein first applied for Mount Nebo, the state
counted all 100 acres of Our Lady Queen of Peace. The state review
found more than enough room in the Catholic cemetery to accommodate
Jewish burials.
</P>
<P>
   Because the space rule is out, Levitt-Weinstein will argue
against counting the Catholic cemetery's acreage against Mount
Nebo, said Bill Furlow, Levitt-Weinstein's attorney in Tallahassee,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state can now use common sense,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the state has proposed a new space rule that differs only
slightly _ allotting about 1,100 spaces for each acre of unused
cemetery land, said Walsh, the state's lawyer. A judge is expected
to review it next month.
</P>
<P>
   To help bolster its case, Levitt-Weinstein is using population
projections and death rates prepared by Sheskin, the Jewish
demography expert.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 209,000 Jews in the county, up from about
161,000 in 1990. The steady increase means the community will need
more Jewish gravesites, said Sheskin, a University of Miami
associate geography professor. ``The Jewish population here has
increased so dramatically it would be very difficult to believe
that there's not enough demand there for a third cemetery,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheskin figures that there will be more than 100,000 Jewish
deaths in the county during the next 30 years _ justifying Mount
Nebo.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Menorah Gardens declined comment, and Eternal
Light representatives did not return phone calls. The archdiocese
has not opposed Mount Nebo.
</P>
<P>
   Story filed by the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
