<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNDREDS OF FIRES BURNING IN RAINLESS FLORIDA
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ With scarce rainfall and record-breaking heat turning
Florida into a tinderbox, about 258 fires were burning across the
state on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Across the state thousands of weary firefighters have for weeks
been chasing dozens of new wildfires a day that have burned about
100,000 acres and destroyed at least $80 million in crops so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The fires have been so extensive and numerous that President
Clinton has declared the entire state a disaster area, and
firefighters from as far as Alaska have come down to help exhausted
local crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``They send us here. They send us there,'' said Robert Kondos, a
firefighter from Holly Hill, north of Daytona Beach. ``We don't
know where we are going to go next.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents are experiencing an array of problems, from
respiratory ailments and heat exhaustion to thick smoky haze,
highway closings and town evacuations.
</P>
<P>
   Since Memorial Day, more than 650 wildfires have sprung up in
rural areas of north and central Florida, spanning a wide swath in
the northern part of the state from Pensacola to Jacksonville and
south nearly to Orlando, state emergency management officials said.
The chief factors are the relentless heat, with temperatures from
the mid-90s to more than 100 degrees, and meager rain. Only 2
inches of rain has fallen in northern Florida in May and June,
compared with the normal amount of 10 inches, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere that fires are contained they're not actually put
out. Thunderstorms come along and lightning strikes and re-ignite
the fires,'' said Craig Fugate, bureau chief of the state division
of emergency management.
</P>
<P>
   Florida has not been this dry in at least 50 years, the
officials said. With the worst drought in 50 years, 66 of Florida's
67 counties have already had fires, ranging from a few acres to
several thousand acres.
</P>
<P>
   The damage from the fires and dry weather totals about $100
million, the officials said, including $80 million worth of corn,
peanuts, hay and other crops in the Panhandle and northern Florida
(about one-third of the region's $242 million annual harvest) and
another $10 million of commercial timber.
</P>
<P>
   About 23 people have been injured, many of them firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is used to hot summer weather, but this is the worst,
state officials agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, we get three or four days of hot weather and then we
get rain,'' said Greg Thayer, a spokesman for the state Department
of Community Affairs' fire information center. ``We've been over a
month and there hasn't been a break.''
</P>
<P>
   County workers in some areas have sometimes had to go door to
door ``to find out who's breathing and who isn't,'' Thayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although residents have been spared the brunt of the damage,
about 116 homes have been destroyed and 600 to 800 people have been
forced from their homes because of smoke. Hospitals have reported
more cases of respiratory problems and heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of other residents have had to cope with hazy skies
and highway closings, and on Monday, Agriculture Commissioner Bob
Crawford encouraged counties to refrain from setting off fireworks
displays for the Fourth of July celebrations. In some counties,
barbecues have been banned.
</P>
<P>
   In Volusia and Flagler Counties, health officials urged
residents on Tuesday to stay indoors as firefighters fought
desperately to stop 16 new wildfires that burned timber and brush
and threatened water pumps and power lines not far from Interstate
4. In some neighborhoods, homeowners had sprinklers soaking their
roofs while others hovered in small groups, waiting for word to
evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   Ash fell like snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people are holding out,'' said Lon Hull as he kept water
spraying on his home near the city of Port Orange in Volusia County
while his wife, Kelly, and their two children went to stay at a
church.
</P>
<P>
   In Taylor County, near Tallahassee, 127 firefighters from other
states, including Tennessee, North Carolina, and South Carolina,
fought a fire on 17,300 acres of pine trees and commercial timber
property that has been burning since Thursday; it was about 40
percent contained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough on them,'' A.C. Almarode, a fire official from
South Carolina, said in a telephone interview, referring to the
crews. ``The humidity and temperatures are dragging them down
quick. You need a lot of shade breaks.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the state, the smoke was so heavy that National
Guard helicopters had to use infrared equipment to find some of the
fires.
</P>
<P>
   The fire hazard can only subside with rain and lower
temperatures, but neither is expected immediately. Andy Devanas, a
state meteorologist, said relief will likely come in July and
August, months in which the state averages 8 to 10 inches each
month. But on Tuesday, it actually rained in parts of northern
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could go a good week like this it would be over,''
Devanas said as he watched the light shower that fell on
Tallahassee. ``We're going from flooding to drought to hurricanes.
I've never seen anything like it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
