<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO EXECUTIVES TAKE NEW JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Two top agency executives are changing jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Riches, 54, chairwoman and chief executive at Ogilvy One
North America in New York, part of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide
division of WPP Group PLC, is leaving after almost three years to
join the toy maker Hasbro Inc. in Pawtucket, R.I., in the new
position of president for global direct marketing and electronic
commerce. A successor at Ogilvy One is not being named.
</P>
<P>
   BBDO South in Atlanta, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit of
Omnicom Group, named Art Mellor executive creative director.
Mellor, 54, is now executive vice president and senior creative
director at BBDO New York. He will assume duties that had been
handled by Larry Tolpin, who left in September to become a
worldwide creative director at J. Walter Thompson Co. in San
Francisco, a unit of WPP.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Curtis had served as the creative head at BBDO South on an
interim basis after Tolpin's departure. With Mellor's arrival, Ms.
Curtis, 36, is leaving to pursue other interests, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   WOOLMARK IS NAME FOR 2 WOOL GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   Two organizations that promote and market wool apparel _ the
International Wool Secretariat in Melbourne, Australia, and its
American unit, the Wool Bureau in New York _ are changing their
names to Woolmark Co. The Woolmark symbol identifies clothing made
from 100 percent wool. Advertising about the name change is
scheduled to appear in September issues of magazines; it will be
created by Abbott Mead Vickers BBDO in London.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   ACCOUNTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Seattle Seahawks to Publicis, Seattle, part of Publicis SA, to
handle advertising for the National Football League team,
previously handled in-house. Billings were estimated at more than
$1 million.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   HONORS
</P>
<P>
   _ American Advertising Federation, Washington, elected Richard
Schade, vice president for central and national field sales at NBC,
Chicago, part of General Electric Co., as chairman. Schade, who had
been vice chairman, succeeds Philip Guarascio, vice president and
general manager for marketing and advertising at the North American
operations of General Motors Corp., Warren, Mich. In addition,
Janet L. Robinson, president and general manager at The New York
Times, New York, was elected vice chairwoman. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
