<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-BASQUES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PREMIER OF SPAIN DENIES CONDONING ANTI-BASQUE TERROR
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID _ Former Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez repeated under
oath in the Supreme Court here on Tuesday what he has said for
years: he never ordered his Socialist government to conduct illegal
counter-terrorism against armed Basque separatists in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me to break the law,'' Gonzalez said in
the trial of 12 political aides and police officers who served
under him. They are accused of kidnapping a suspected Basque rebel
in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors, in this and four related cases, are seeking to
prove that Gonzalez's government sponsored a ``dirty war'' from
1983 to 1987 that killed 27 suspected Basque rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome is considered crucial not only for the former
interior minister, Jose Barrionuevo, the most senior ex-aide on
trial, who faces 23 years in jail if convicted of kidnapping and
belonging to an armed group. It could also affect Gonzalez's own
political future.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who led Spain from 1982 to 1996, is now being
mentioned as a candidate to head the 15-nation European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gonzalez, 56, is not a defendant in any of the
lawsuits, many in Spain have accused him of complicity in the
illegal counter-terrorism, notably the deputy prime minister,
Francisco Alvarez Cascos. Cascos testified on Monday that Gonzalez
must have been involved in organizing and running it.
</P>
<P>
   The man who was kidnapped, Segundo Marey, 66, testified last
week that on the night of Dec. 4, 1983, two men abducted him in the
southern French Basque region.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first action claimed by a group called the
Anti-Terrorist Liberation Groups. It apparently aimed to strike at
the French sanctuary of the Basque separatist group ETA.
</P>
<P>
   But Marey, it turned out, was a furniture dealer, not a Basque
rebel. His captors, realizing their mistake, released him after 10
days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
