<HEADER>
A3375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POPLIFE-NYT &LR;      06-23 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPLIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POP LIFE: CREATION OF A SHINY, HAPPY BAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the era of the Spice Girls and the Backstreet
Boys, the notion of a manufactured band _ carefully molded and
shaped by record executives _ has become a repellent one. But in
decades past, whether it was Motown's Berry Gordy putting the
Supremes through an intensive program of dancing, singing, manners
and biography adjustment or Phil Spector constructing the sound and
image of bands like the Crystals and the Ronettes, acts that today
would seem manufactured recorded some of the greatest songs of
their era.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, there is a noble pop experiment taking place at
Mercury Records. The band is called Swirl 360, and in many ways its
aim is to make manufactured pop credible and artistically valid
again.
</P>
<P>
   The band's members and Mercury executives resist the label
manufactured _ it has such bad connotations in the '90s _ but the
facts are these: Swirl 360 consists of two tanned, handsome
28-year-old twin brothers who came to Mercury Records looking for a
record deal. They signed with Steve Greenberg, known for producing
the nine-CD stax/volt boxed set as well as bringing the group
Hanson to Mercury. In an attempt to make a pop record he had always
wanted to hear, he put them into a 10-day songwriting program in
Scotland and gave them pop tips like veering toward a high note
instead of a low one at the end of a sung phrase.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of trying to turn them into vapid pinups, Greenberg
and the band decided to try something new. They sat around and
listened to as much catchy '70s pop as they could. Afterwards,
Greenberg compiled two tapes titled ``Sugar Pop'' (three hours of
bands like the Sweet, Badfinger, Edison Lighthouse and Cheap Trick)
and gave it to Swirl and most everyone else involved in the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Next, he and the band recruited alternative music songwriters
known for making albums that reach for a shiny, happy, pre-grunge
era of classic pop yet who have remained consigned to a small
college-rock audience. (The songwriters were from the Posies,
Eugenius, Superstar and Fountains of Wayne, though mainstream
hit-makers like Desmond Child also helped.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We approached a lot of really sophisticated alternative rock
writers and said, `What if instead of writing a song for college
radio or the music press, you wrote a song that would go straight
to the heart of every teen-aged girl you ever saw?''' Greenberg
said. ``And those people were thrilled to take up the challenge,
because that's what they all really want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is an infectious, upbeat, guitar-driven album that
looks to pop in its simplest guise, as an escapist balm to lift the
spirits. The experiment is one that will either create a ubiquitous
summer single on the order of Hanson's ``MMMBop'' or slip by
unnoticed. Mercury is banking on the former outcome. Though the
band's music won't be commercially available until next month, its
first single, ``Hey Now Now,'' was the most added new song on
modern-rock radio for the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president of Mercury came in and played it for me,
and I put it right on the radio,'' said Jon Zellner, the director
of programming at KMXV-FM in Kansas City, Mo. ``I hadn't done that
in a long time. The great thing about Swirl is that it's pure
straight pop. It's a great summer song: It should be on in every
car that has its top down and every radio on the side of a pool.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the record's ambitions seems to be to bring pop (as
opposed to popular) music back to the radio, and to make music
that, like an old Warner Brothers cartoon, can be appreciated on
two levels. ``I wanted a record that those who love pop history
will have a field day with and will love because it will remind
them of so many things from long ago, while at the same time a
15-year-old is going to love it because it sounds cool,'' Greenberg
said. ``It's not that easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Monday, the Swirl brothers, Denny and Kenny
Scott, waxed rhapsodically about their love of pop, from the
Beatles and Kiss to Jellyfish and Redd Kross to Beck and Imani
Coppola. Born into a Navy family that moved around the country, the
brothers first thought about a career in music after winning a
high-school talent show with a version of the Cheap Trick-inspired
Poison song ``Talk Dirty to Me.'' A year and a half ago they moved
from Jacksonville, Fla., to Los Angeles, recording several EPs by
themselves before meeting their future manager, Christopher Sabec,
at the South by Southwest music convention in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the fact that Sabec also manages Hanson and met its
members at South by Southwest, there are a number of similarities
between the two bands. Like Hanson, Swirl's members are attractive,
clean-cut brothers, they work with Greenberg at Mercury, they make
upbeat pop music with beautiful harmonies, they used two of the
same songwriters and they are music fans with wide-ranging tastes.
Though the Scotts aren't blond like Hanson, they sound like they
should be. Though Hanson admirers, the Scott brothers resist such
comparisons, citing obvious differences like Hanson's youth and
allegiance to classic soul over later pop-rock. ``It's been
frustrating because our stories are similar,'' Kenny Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Is Swirl 360 prepared to be hated as much as Hanson? ``Yes,''
Kenny Scott said. ``I see Hanson has 20 or 25 hater Web sites, and
I know there are going to be some Swirl 360 hater Web sites. It's
definitely going to happen. It's going to be funny to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about the band's long-range plans, Denny Scott said:
``We don't want to come in as a one-hit wonder. We want to come in
and be an incredible band that plays pop music that girls and guys
are going to like, and then hopefully maintain a career of that.
But music now is like fast food, so Kenny and I are being
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism is the theme of the band's debut album. Its lyrics
serve as transportation to an imaginary world where life is as
simple and sweet as eating a chocolate bar, as demonstrated in
lyrics like ``Don't ask how but dreams come true,'' ``I know a
place where the sun is always shining,'' and ``If you think that
innocence is dead, I'll say it's all inside your head.'' When
someone threatens to rupture that bubble, the band warns ``Don't
shake my world.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether that world really exists, the brothers
respond, laughing, ``No, it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   A Tamer Woodstock
</P>
<P>
   The producer Danny Socolof announced that there would be a new
festival at a very familiar place with very familiar artists this
year. It is called a Day in the Garden and will take place on the
site of the original Woodstock festival in Bethel, N.Y. The
festival is to feature a mix of Woodstock veterans and
first-timers, including Stevie Nicks, Don Henley, Ziggy Marley and
Ten Years After on Aug. 14 and Joni Mitchell, Pete Townshend, Lou
Reed and Richie Havens on Aug. 15. There will also be several acts
performing on Aug. 16, though the lineup won't be announced until
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Where the first Woodstock concert became a free-for-all, Socolof
said that this one was made for baby-boomers who have matured, have
families and want a tame atmosphere. To that end, he is letting
children under 12 in free. ``We want to send a very clear message
out there that this is going to be safe, it's going to be
comfortable and it's going to be gracious,'' he said. ``The adults
that we're targeting for this don't want to be hassled, they don't
want to wait in line and they want conveniences.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 30,000 tickets for each day will go on sale beginning
Saturday at 10 a.m. at Ticketmaster outlets. The price is $69.98
per day plus service charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
