<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALTERNATIVE-SCHOOLS-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT AN ALTERNATIVE SCHOOL, PRESENTATION MEANS ALL  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MACARENA HERNANDEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ While his friends were out in the halls scribbling
``don't ever change'' in their yearbooks, Jermaine Harris was
sweating it out scribbling math problems on the chalkboard in Room
600 at the School of the Future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, this is how the stock would do,'' he said,
pointing to a chart he had prepared on the computer his grandmother
bought him. ``X represents years, and y represents money.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 18, a senior at the school, on the East Side of
Manhattan, was trying to convince a committee of five that
investing $5,000 in Nike and Xerox stocks and $5,000 in mutual
funds would be a sound idea.
</P>
<P>
   But for Harris, the stakes were higher than a mere $10,000. His
high school diploma was on the line. As part of requirements for
graduation, students at the School of the Future, as well as at 20
other small alternative public schools in New York City, must pass
four such ``exhibitions'' in their last four years there. For an
exhibition, students write and present a research paper in science
and math and two in humanities.
</P>
<P>
   Topics have ranged from the Vietnam War to Israel, slavery to
racism, immigration to New York City tenements.
</P>
<P>
   Kasia Kedzia, 18, a junior, presented her first humanities
exhibition last year on The Relationship Between Love and Death in
Poetry. After months of analyzing sonnets, she concluded that the
focus of her own poems was not broad enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``My poems had the same plot: You like this guy, and then it
doesn't work out,'' Ms. Kedzia said. ``And then the
you-are-miserable-at-the-end type of poem. The exhibition forced me
not to be narrow. I can use symbolism now. I can write about grass,
things that I never thought about before.''
</P>
<P>
   The school, which has 525 students from grades 6 through 12,
focuses on technology, with an emphasis on computer science. It
models itself on the theories of Theodore Sizer, the school
reformer and author who emphasizes an interdisciplinary curriculum
and small class sizes where students can actively engage in their
own learning. Forty New York City schools are members of the Center
for Collaborative Education, the local affiliate of Dr. Sizer's
national Coalition of Essential Schools. At least half of the
Collaborative Education schools require exhibitions from their high
school students.
</P>
<P>
   The schools currently operate under a five-year waiver that
exempts them from administering the state's standardized tests. No
graduates have received a Regents diploma, given to students who
pass advanced state tests, but almost all have gone on to college,
said Kathy Pelles, the principal of the School of the Future, whose
third class is graduating this week.
</P>
<P>
   While students at the School of the Future receive traditional
grades for course work, the exhibitions provide another way to
gauge progress. They are evaluated by four categories: mastery with
distinction, mastery, satisfactory and needs improvement.
</P>
<P>
   For her presentation, Caryle Ann Francis, 17, analyzed why black
male characters in Toni Morrison's ``Beloved'' and ``The Bluest
Eye'' struggled with issues of intimacy. She had written five
drafts _ now dogeared and stuffed into a folder decorated with an
enlarged passport photo of herself as a tot. She had recited her
paper three times in front of the mirror in the girls' restroom,
and even tacked a huge sheet of paper with her outline on the wall
she would be facing when presenting.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Ms. Francis was given only a mastery. She plans to
appeal for a higher evaluation. Although she is one of the school's
top students, she may have had a harder time because she stocked
her committee with literature teachers and students. Presenters can
select their own panelists, as long as there are at least two
teachers. Students tend to take the task seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine Harris sat on the committee of his friend, his friend
Shangari Meleschi, in March, and Meleschi sat on his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to let him off easy,'' said Meleschi, who had
also researched the stock market for his exhibition, as did
Jermaine's twin brother, Tremaine. ``But I wasn't going to fail
him, either. I know how hard he works.''
</P>
<P>
   Jermaine's presentation, which lasted more than an hour, was
full of graphs and statistics, and in his grilling he was asked to
rethink a number of equations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does x always represent years and y represent money?'' one
teacher asked.
</P>
<P>
   Harris coughed nervously.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher rephrased the question: ``Is time dependent on
money, or is money dependent on time?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked for a hint in the teacher's face but couldn't find it,
and though he had done well on other questions, in the end, he was
awarded a mastery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
