<HEADER>
A3383 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-CUP-SCOTLAND-HNS &LR;      06-23 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-SCOTLAND-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scotland wastes another second chance
</P>
<P>
   Brazil also loses, but defending World Cup champions still
advance to next round
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN P. LOPEZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAINT ETIENNE, France _ And so the disaster called the World Cup
only continues for Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   Could it just be beginning for powerful Brazil?
</P>
<P>
   Scotland, a nation with a history rooted to the game and
boasting the vocal and loyal ``Tartan Army'' of fans, had a chance
to advance to the second round of the World Cup for the first time
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20,000 Scottish fans descended on this quaint, refined
city of artists and street musicians, turning the town center into
a sea of plaid. The whole place buzzed with hope, anticipation and
World Cup scenes as memorable as any.
</P>
<P>
   Kilted Scot fans danced their way into the stadium. Chants of
``We will win'' rang in the air. An estimated 8,000 ticketless
Scots filled a town square where the game would be shown on
giant-screen TVs. Scottish players saluted the boisterous masses
moments before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   But Scotland forgot that Morocco had been invited to this party,
too.
</P>
<P>
   The Scots were overwhelmed 3-0. Morocco left little to chance,
hammering in goals in the 22nd and 47th minutes against a
sluggish-looking defense and adding a third goal just before the
final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Scotland yet again disappointed its enthusiastic supporters, as
was clear in the waning moments when a Scottish fan ripped off the
red-haired wig she wore and threw it in the direction of the Scots'
bench.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was enough to pull your hair out.
</P>
<P>
   Morocco's victory swept away Scotland's cursed World Cup hopes
and extended to eight the streak of World Cup tournaments in which
Scotland has failed to reach the second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to apologize to Scotland,'' team captain Colin Hendry
said. ``We will keep trying our damnedest to make it. This is tough
to take.''
</P>
<P>
   It was no consolation that the result of Morocco's victory
proved to be meaningless, since Norway stunned Brazil with a late
goal and 2-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian victory means that in the next round it will join
Brazil, which already had guaranteed a berth with victories in its
first two games. It also meant that even had Scotland won, Norway
would have advanced.
</P>
<P>
   But Norway did not score its inspired go-ahead goal against
Brazil until after it was announced in Marseille that Scotland was
being romped. Scotland's troubles definitely seemed to jolt the
Norwegians into a higher gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed that we didn't take advantage of the chance
we had,'' Scotland coach Craig Brown said. ``We came out and hoped
to fight bravely. I thought we had the heart, but we didn't have
the game. Morocco was the better team.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprising news in the Group A games, however, was that
Norway was better than Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the defending Cup-champion Brazilians had little
to play for in the game, but as coach Mario Zagallo said, ``Brazil
never takes a loss well. We wanted to win, and we expected to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   But it lost for the first time since the 1990 World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just very pleased; I'm also very very proud,''
Norwegian coach Egil Olsen said. ``It's quite amazing what's
happened tonight and that we're moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   In its round-of-16 game next week, Norway will play Italy, which
eliminated the Norwegians four years ago despite playing with only
10 men because of a disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil moves on to face Chile at the Parc des Princes in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   And Scotland goes home. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in expecting to play well and expecting to get it
done,'' Brown said of Scotland's defeat. ``We didn't expect to be
outplayed, but we were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
