<SLUG> BC-WILLIAM-CONGDON-ART-$ADV28-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITING THE PASSION OF ART AND THE PEACE OF THE SOUL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JUNE 28) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: R.I.)   Christopher Reardon, an arts journalism fellow at Columbia
University, first met William Congdon in 1985.  
 (af)  
 By CHRISTOPHER REARDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ The death of any artist, from the unsung to the
oversold, is an occasion for looking back. With the work complete
and the artist no longer subject to slights and flattery, criticism
can be more candid and conclusive than before. Yet taking the
measure of William Congdon, who died April 15 on his 86th birthday,
proves trickier than that.
</P>
<P>
   As a painter associated with the New York School, the cluster of
Abstrac Expressionists who shook up the art world in the late
1940s and 50s, Congdon distinguished himself with his spirited
cityscapes of New York and Venice, often rendered in thick strokes
of black and gold. Like many of his peers, most notably Jackson
Pollock, he worked with a swift intensity that kept the intellect
at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, though, his interest in action painting focused less
on baring his psyche than on tapping into a higher consciousness.
And in 1959, after years of creative and emotional crisis, he went
to Assisi, Italy, and converted to Catholicism. Gradually
retreating from public view, he spent his last decades painting in
a Benedictine monastery on the outskirts of Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Famous, then forgotten, Congdon left one of the more puzzling
artistic legacies in recent memory. While some of his earlier
pieces have entered the collections of leading museums in Boston,
New York and Washington, a trove of later paintings sits in a
climate-controlled vault near Milan, waiting for someone to open
the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 1960 or so he just disappeared,'' said Fred Licht, a
curator at the Peggy Guggenheim Collection in Venice, which owns
three Congdons. ``I heard about his conversion, but there was such
silence after that that we all thought he was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The assumption, as Licht discovered a few years ago, was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   One foggy afternoon last January, Congdon sat in his studio at
the monastery, a working farm that is home to a dozen monks, and
tried to explain his artistic creed. ``I paint the same way that I
always painted,'' said Congdon, a tall man with striking cerulean
eyes. ``An image forms within me, and I give birth to it.''
</P>
<P>
   If few Americans recall Congdon and his work, it's not because a
writer made him up. Unlike Nat Tate, the shadowy Abstract
Expressionist celebrated in a recent book by William Boyd, Congdon
is the genuine article. And in many respects his true story is both
stranger and more illuminating than Tate's.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Providence, R.I., the night the Titanic sank, Congdon
was the second of five sons of an Episcopal steel baron and a
cotton heiress. After some early success as a sculptor, he
volunteered as an ambulance driver in World War II, nursed
survivors back to health after the liberation of the concentration
camp at Bergen-Belsen and then helped rebuild villages in Italy
before going to New York in February 1948 to resume his career as
an artist.
</P>
<P>
   Troubled by the shallowness of America's growing consumer
culture, he rented a cold-water studio just off the Bowery and
began to see Hermann Vollmer, a psychoanalyst who trained under
Freud. Living among the city's downtrodden and wrestling with his
inner demons each contributed to the expressive nature of his
painting, which he took up that winter in a new professional tack
he later called ``my first conversion.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically Congdon applied paint with a palette knife, then
incised the encrustations of oil with a jackknife or awl. The
technique suited him to the end. ``With a brush, it's a kiss,'' he
said after painting one of his final landscapes last winter. ``You
have to fight with a knife.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949 he held his first show at the pioneering Betty Parsons
Gallery. His tangled views of the city, hovering between
representation and abstraction, sold out, and before long he was
profiled in Life magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congdon had the feeling,'' Parsons later said. ``He didn't
give a damn for pretty pictures. He wanted to capture the
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Guggenheim, who liked to say that Congdon was the
reincarnation of her father, who went down with the Titanic, called
him ``the only painter since Turner who has captured Venice, its
mystery, its poetry, its passion.''
</P>
<P>
   While closely allied with the New York School, Congdon never
fully fit in. One factor was his wanderlust, which repeatedly drew
him away from the gallery openings and carousing of his
contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   A list of his paintings reads like an itinerary: ``Mexico Sand
Birds'' (1950), ``Paris No. 1'' (1951), ``Piazza Venice No. 12''
(1952), ``Istanbul No. 1'' (1953), ``India Temple (Tanjore)''
(1954), ``Sahara No. 12'' (1955).
</P>
<P>
   Travel wasn't his only inspiration. He also used alcohol and
sleeping pills. In a letter from Guatemala City in 1957, he
described his motive to his cousin, the poet Isabella Gardner, a
descendant of the Boston collector Isabella Stewart Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to have a pure birth,'' he wrote, using his favored
metaphor for painting, ``I must go through scenes little short of
suicide and not a bit short of madness and destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   The pace proved untenable, and not just for him. Between 1948
and 1970, four New York School artists _ Arshile Gorky, Pollock,
David Smith and Mark Rothko _ met early, violent deaths, cementing
a reputation for nihilism. Congdon seemed destined to be among
them.
</P>
<P>
   Then he found God.
</P>
<P>
   Peers called his religious conversion artistic suicide, and for
a time he seemed to confirm their fears that loyalty to the Church
would erode his artistic integrity. Playing the Prodigal Son, he
traveled to India with the entourage of Pope Paul VI and turned out
representational biblical tableaux that greatly pleased the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   The overt liturgical subject matter stood in contrast to major
works of modern religious art like Barnett Newman's 14 abstract
``Stations of the Cross'' (1958-1966) and the nondemoninational
Rothko Chapel in Houston (dedicated in 1971).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Even Congdon came to rue some of his first work as a Catholic.
Near the end of his life, while still approving of his series of
abstract crucifixions, he singled out ``The Conversion of St.
Paul'' (1961), a piece owned by the National Gallery of Art in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a betrayal,'' he said, ``as if it was painted on
commission.'' To Congdon, the self-referential painting became a
mirror; when he looked, he saw an artist who had lost his faith in
the creative moment and was instead putting his talents to use as a
pious propagandist.
</P>
<P>
   As a tractor droned outside, Congdon continued his story. Not
long after his final show at the Parsons Gallery in 1967, he
underwent his third and last conversion. ``I pulled back from the
Church because I felt it was threatening my freedom,'' he said.
``The religious subject got in the way, and so I stopped it.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving from Assisi to Milan in 1968, Congdon slowly saw his work
open up. It was the result, he said, of striking a better balance
between his art and spirituality. Just as an inheritance from his
wealthy parents had freed him from the art market, his role as the
monastery's artist in residence (he never became a monk or gave up
his American citizenship) loosed his creativity again.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong bachelor, he had an apartment to himself, with an
adjoining studio that overlooked two fields cleft by an irrigation
ditch and a stand of trees.
</P>
<P>
   He painted the scene hundreds of times, but made a point of
never looking out the window while painting. He preferred to
observe at his leisure and then, if the urge arose, paint from
emotional memory. Repetition was not a concern. ``To paint the same
subject is to paint no subject,'' he once wrote, ``but rather
always one's ever changing self.''
</P>
<P>
   His work grew quieter and more abstract, in many ways resembling
Rothko's Color Field paintings. Yet it retained much of the
spontaneity and texture that he had always sought. And though he
gave up religious subjects, his faith still suffused the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't that much good religious painting going on in our
period,'' said Peter Selz, who, together with Licht and Rodolfo
Balzarotti, wrote a 1995 monograph on the artist. ``But Congdon did
it with immense conviction and the result was the direct opposite
of all that pious stuff you usually see.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of his paintings have been acquired by the Solomon R.
Guggenheim Museum, the Metropolitan Museum of Art, the Museum of
Modern Art and the Whitney Museum of American Art. But none of them
comes from his monastic period, and none of them are on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the Rhode Island School of Design Museum of Art in
Providence, which recently hung ``The Colosseum'' (1951) and
``Christ on the Lake No. 2'' (1961), most museums store their
Congdons with countless other works deemed too marginal to show and
too meaningful to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for a man who liked to paint in the late afternoon, racing
dusk's advance, it seems somehow fitting that Congdon's reputation
as an artist should remain in twilight.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, his place in history will likely turn on how critics
and curators answer the question of whether he was a Catholic who
painted to save his soul, or a painter who embraced the Church to
save his art.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen O'Brien, curator of painting and sculpture at the Rhode
Island School of Design's Museum, has reached her conclusion. ``I
wouldn't want to put Congdon in a niche where he's a Catholic
artist,'' she said, taking a position that is shared by few of her
peers. ``As an art historian, I think the painting stands on its
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Brien visited Congdon last winter and was pleased with
what she found. ``There's the great physicality of paint handling
like Pollock,'' she recalled, ``the scriffiti that comes out of
Klee and Mark Tobey, and the luminosity of Rothko's Color Field
paintings.''
</P>
<P>
   This fall the Whitney will present a major retrospective on
Rothko, and the Modern will mount one on Pollock. Congdon, in a
lesser way, will also get some attention. In November, the
foundation he set up to preserve and promote his work will pull 70
paintings from its vaults, and the walls of its private collection,
for a show in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   But Congdon was never overly concerned with worldly success.
``Any true painting is a state of soul, not an exercise in
esthetics,'' he wrote in a notebook in 1953. ``I don't paint with
physical colors but with spiritual combinations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
