<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Michael Jordan sounds like a man who's staying
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Michael Jordan wore no shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Some 45 minutes after his expected arrival, he emerged, flanked
by two uniformed police officers, from a back entrance at the
Austin Convention Center. He was nattily dressed in a burnt orange
pullover shirt, light khaki slacks and ... white cotton socks.
</P>
<P>
   The shoes stayed behind, presumably because they were golf
cleats. He'd already played 20 at the Great Hills Golf Club and was
at the turn before being transported by a white limousine to Barton
Creek Country Club for the back 18.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball royalty's preeminent member might have been casually
dressed _ this is Austin, after all _ but this wasn't a case of the
emperor wearing no clothes. Anyone with six rings on his fingers
qualifies as fully clothed.
</P>
<P>
   Fully satisfied? Hardly. Golf's his love, basketball's his life.
</P>
<P>
   It's fine for Kobe Bryant and Grant Hill to be like Mike, but
they're not Mike. We're not as interested in the next Michael
Jordan as we are the current Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   As Dallas Mavericks forward Michael Finley said at a recent
charity basketball clinic, ``The only slippage in his game is he
doesn't dunk as much as he used to. But that's not slippage. Half
of the players in the NBA want him to stay because of what he does
for the game. The other half wants him to leave so they have a
chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since MJ and those coattail-riders put the Utah Jazz out of
their misery in six games a week ago for the Chicago Bulls' sixth
NBA championship in eight seasons, this country has become obsessed
with his retirement. Get out now while you're on top, the experts
tell Michael, before you tarnish our memory of you as the best
basketball player in the history of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more selfish? Why are we so eager to send the
Michael Jordans and John Elways out to pasture before they're
ready? Can't we just revel in their still-spectacular skills? If
their decline is too precipitous, their play will determine that.
MJ could play at this level another _ what? _ two, three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Are we too scared to see our heroes stumble? Can we not accept
their legitimate challenge to rise above the encumbrances of
advancing age and more youthful rivals?
</P>
<P>
   For every floundering Willie Mays or Johnny Unitas far past
their primes, we should salute the Cal Ripken Jrs., Paul Molitors
and Reggie Whites as they continue to bring credit to their sports
with an enviable work ethic and lasting legacies.
</P>
<P>
   We are so consumed with interest in Jordan, the kids wanted to
know everything about him, from the size of his shoes (13) to the
brand of gum he chews (in the playoffs, Doublemint). We can't get
enough of MJ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to continue to play,'' MJ said, ``but I want to
continue with the same guys I've played with. If not, it's been
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, 35, should forget us and do what he wants to do. Play if
he wants to play. Retire if that makes him happy.
</P>
<P>
   More than 730 campers flocked around MJ as he fielded their
questions for half an hour. The once-wide circle tightened around
him like animals after their prey, adolescents practically pawing
at his pant legs, thrusting hands toward him to physically touch
his greatness.
</P>
<P>
   As 8-year-old camper Taylor Oran said, ``He should stay if he
wants to.''
</P>
<P>
   Javier Gutierrez, a lanky 14-year-old wearing a red No. 23 Bulls
jersey and one of his 16 pairs of Jordan shoes, thinks MJ's ``too
good to retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Buzz-headed Kirby Wottrich from West Ridge Middle School said if
MJ is as fatigued as he said he was from this season's 103 games,
he should ``maybe play half a season.'' If so, make it the last
half, MJ.
</P>
<P>
   Thrall's Janice Mitchell, a brown-eyed seventh-grader, wants
Jordan to ``prove to the world he can win without Phil Jackson,''
his coach until he officially resigned Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's decision came as news to MJ, who said he would
consider it a rumor until he heard it from Phil. Jordan once said
he wouldn't play for another coach, but the ebullient tone in his
voice suggests he's not the least bit ready to leave the game.
</P>
<P>
   He adamantly insisted he won't return to baseball and will not
fantasize about the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   MJ could follow Larry Bird into the coaching ranks or be a
player-coach, but he said he doesn't think he has the discipline to
handle that. ``But I can't ever say never,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestling, like Dennis Rodman?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wrestle, and I don't watch a lot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't his departure leave the NBA in disrespectful hands?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still enjoy the game,'' he said. ``And there are a lot of
young players in the league who still need some lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   MJ left behind more hints that he'll remain in the league than
he does defenders in his wake. He said he hopes Scottie Pippen and
Rodman return, adding, ``And there's a strong possibility they
will.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he wanted to leave these youngsters with the advice of
listening to their parents and teachers ``if I don't see you again,
but I'm pretty sure you will.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Bohls writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
