<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FORGET ABOUT IT, GEORGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Another night, another event, another thumbs-up
referendum on the state of George Steinbrenner's baseball team and
the stadium it reluctantly calls home.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez against the Turnersville Braves was only the
latest in a season of fascinating attractions that continue to just
wash ashore, bringing with them hundreds of thousands of fans.
After 53,000 showed up at Yankee Stadium on Monday night, another
50,000-plus braved the rain, the traffic, the parking and the
prices Tuesday night to watch El Duque try to baffle the best
bullpen-challenged team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal, Steinbrenner huffed, albeit good-naturedly, in the
Yankee clubhouse beforehand. ``This is a natural setup, with the
World Series,'' he said. ``What will we do with the Phillies next
week? That's more of a test.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell us another one. Keep raising obstacles in the Bronx and
daring New York to cross them. Face it, big guy, they will build a
nuclear test site in Manhattan before they build you a ballpark.
You blew it. You put together this splendid team, brimming with
homegrown stars and smart and intriguing acquisitions, and nurtured
by a calm, street-smart native New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   You have let it breathe, like an excellent wine. You said you
learned that you ``can't go undefeated in baseball'' and you proved
it by not overreacting after losing in the playoffs to Cleveland
last October. Now New York loves your Yankees for how they are
doing and what they stand for, and its fans are visiting the
Stadium at a near-record pace that will only improve now that
school is out. By the end of the season, your cries and those of
the mayor for a park on the West Side of Manhattan will sound like
whistles in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   In your advancing age, you have become too smart for your own
good, even if you did get yourself stuck in two hours' worth of
traffic after landing at Newark International Airport from Tampa,
Fla., on Monday night in the middle of rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what some of these people have to go through to get to
the games,'' Steinbrenner said. ``You have to love the Yankees to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Spotting a couple of kids in Yankee caps in the next car, he
said, ``I rolled down the window and said, `Don't worry, they ain't
starting until I get there.'''
</P>
<P>
   He's still the Boss, but these kids, Steinbrenner said, didn't
even know who he was, and why would they? While busily romancing
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani these past few years, he has surrendered the
back pages of the tabloids, allowed his players to be the stars of
his baseball team. They are merely authoring one of the most
feel-good stories in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any bad apples, no one barking at the manager,
and that's why people like this team,'' said Darryl Strawberry. ``I
know that we have a feeling like the Chicago Bulls have _ the
unity, knowing how to play, how to win, that you don't panic. We've
won a World Series, been together a while. Today in sports, it's
very rare.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Braves visit baseball's 24-hour supermarket for rich
teams later this summer, the Yankees are more charismatic, deeper
and have the vastly superior bullpen. Best team in baseball. As the
20th century nears its end, we have reached the point where
Steinbrenner's franchise is one of the sport's two or three most
reliably stable, the one El Duque and Hideki Irabu chose over all
the others. The Yankees are what the Dodgers were until Rupert
Murdoch took over in Los Angeles and the era of television
executives bypassing the general manager to make multiplayer trades
commenced.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Foxies have fired the Dodger manager, for the first
time in 45 years, and jettisoned an accomplished general manager to
boot, there is already a whisper circulating that they also want
the elegant Dodger uniforms changed. By the time Murdoch is done,
Steinbrenner's respect for history and tradition will be compared
to Wimbledon's. Sooner or later, he will realize he isn't getting
the Manhattan stadium, that he would be insane to go to New Jersey
and that luxury boxes, a Metro North train stop plus improved
highway access and parking will solve most, if not all, of his
riddles. He will embrace the Bronx, make himself a hero.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Steinbrenner will continue to insult New York
by comparing it to Cleveland and Baltimore, limp tourist towns with
only one team. He will persist in contradicting his own turnstiles'
count.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do not come up here for mid-week night games,''
Steinbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Go tell that to the Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
