<SLUG> BC-E-COLI-OUTBREAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E. COLI SICKEN 8 IN GEORGIA AND 4,000 IN CHICAGO AREA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ill.)  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ At least eight children who played in a wading pool in
northwest Atlanta were infected by a potentially lethal strain of
E. coli bacteria, state and local health officials reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the children were said to be suffering from kidney
failure, including Brody Weiss, 3, son of the Atlanta Braves
shortstop Walt Weiss. The boy was reported to be in serious
condition Tuesday at Scottish Rite Children's Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Although tests at the wading pool at White Water Recreation Park
on Saturday revealed chlorine levels below the level adequate to
kill the bacteria strain, E. coli 0157:H7, Virginia Galvin,
director of the Board of Health of Cobb County, Ga., said, ``It
would have been difficult to prevent this.'' She added, ``There is
no evidence to suggest negligence on the part of White Water.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, public health officials in Illinois reported Tuesday
that another form of E. coli bacteria rarely seen in the United
States had sickened more than 4,000 people in the Chicago area. It
was the largest outbreak of its kind in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Of 20 people taken to hospitals, most were treated in emergency
rooms for dehydration and released, said Sean McDermott, a
spokesman for the Cook County Department of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   The strain of bacteria, enterotoxigenic Escherichia coli, is
believed to have come from potato salad served by a popular
delicatessen and caterer at more than 530 parties over the weekend
of June 6, which was a busy weekend for graduations.
</P>
<P>
   Cook County health officials are waiting for test results from
the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta,
which are expected to confirm that the bacteria was in the potato
salad, said McDermott, but officials have closed Iwans Deli and
Catering, in suburban Orland Park, Ill., until they can determine
exactly how the food was contaminated.
</P>
<P>
   The strain causes a much less serious illness than that of E.
coli 0157:H7, the strain that caused the illnesses at the Atlanta
wading pool. That strain has been linked to the deaths of several
people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials in Atlanta declined to identify any of the
stricken children, but Brody Weiss' family confirmed that he was
among them. Two other children with kidney failure were in critical
condition at Scottish Rite hospital. No information could be
obtained about the fourth child with kidney failure. All of them
were between the ages of 2 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgia Health Department has deemed the water at the wading
pool safe for all visitors and the park remains open. Public health
officials do not expect many more cases to surface from the
exposure, which occurred almost two weeks ago, since the E. coli
infection's incubation period is usually three or four days. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
