<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMUTERS BRACE FOR NEW WAVE OF CROWDS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In 10 days, the Metropolitan Transportation Authority
will roll out the biggest discounts in the history of the city's
subway and bus system: a package of monthly, weekly and daily
passes that officials say will draw hundreds of thousands of riders
to a system that is already saturated with passengers attracted by
past fare deals.
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials say they are ready to handle the extra 100
million trips a year that subway and bus riders are expected to
take with the new passes. But the officials have few concrete plans
to add service _ no new trains have been ordered, and the only
scheduling change they have made is the cancellation of the
traditional summer service cut.
</P>
<P>
   The transit officials said that in the fall, when the full
impact of the passes is felt, they will monitor the flow of
passengers and add service only if needed _ a process that could
take months.
</P>
<P>
   The expected surge in new riders will come on top of a
significant increase in passengers since New York City Transit
began offering discounts: free bus-to-subway transfers last July
and an 11-rides-for-the-price-of-10 bulk discount in January.
Weekday subway ridership for the first four months of 1998 is up by
nearly 400,000 a day compared with the same period in 1996, the
last year for which comparable figures are available _ an 11
percent increase. But the number of trains has increased by only 4
percent during that time, transit officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And the Straphangers Campaign, an advocacy group that released a
report on the state of the subway system Tuesday, said the
situation is even bleaker. The group contends that the transit
agency's own documents show an increase of only 15 trains a day
since 1996, a rise of 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although the M.T.A. has no current figures for how crowded its
buses and subways are, the Straphangers analysis found that from
October 1995 to October 1996, a subway commuter's chances of
getting a seat at the height of rush hour fell to 29 percent, from
31 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bus ridership, too, spurred by the free transfers, is up by 37
percent since 1996. But while the authority boasts that it has
added 2,300 buses a day since then, that amounts to only a 5
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher P. Boylan, an executive deputy director of the
authority, said that the crowding was generally within the agency's
service guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there more people on the trains and buses?'' he asked.
``Yes. That's good. But have you heard of any customers who were
unable to use our service because there was no room for them? No.
We're moving huge numbers of people and everybody gets where they
want to go. We don't leave anyone anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the agency expected a fairly gradual increase in
ridership beginning in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But Joseph Rappaport, staff coordinator for the Straphangers
Campaign, said that providing the bare minimum of service was no
way to introduce the new passes, which will be available starting
July 4 and offer unlimited rides for $63 a month, $17 a week or $4
a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will there be a huge crush in the fall?'' he asked. ``Well,
there's already a crush. The proper response would be to add enough
service so that riders who are already being crushed can more
comfortably get to or from work.''
</P>
<P>
   Many regular commuters on the N train _ ranked last in the
Straphangers Campaign report, which measured frequency,
reliability, cleanliness and crowding _ said last night that they
feared the new passes as much as they looked forward to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been very crowded, especially during rush hour, over the
past few months,'' said Raquel Herreros, 48, an editorial assistant
in midtown on her way home to Bay Ridge, Brooklyn. ``You can never
even think of getting a seat. People are pushing more to get on the
train. With new cards giving more free rides it's going to be
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials are expecting only a small surge in ridership
during the summer, when school is out and many commuters are on
vacation. To accommodate it, they canceled the traditional summer
service cut of 5 to 10 percent. But as for fall, Lawrence G.
Reuter, the president of New York City Transit, the M.T.A. arm that
runs the subways and buses, stated in a letter to the parent
agency, ``We have an extensive monitoring program to measure
ridership and will use the information from this program to
determine where and when additional service is required.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
