<SLUG> BC-NY-LIVOTI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICERS DISCUSSED '94 ARREST BEFORE GIVING STATEMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A New York police officer testified Tuesday that he
and other officers, who had been present at the 1994 incident in
which Officer Francis X. Livoti was accused of using a choke hold
on a Bronx man who later died, met at the police union's
headquarters to discuss the incident before giving statements to
the police or prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony, which suggested that the officers were trying to
coordinate their accounts to support Livoti's contention that he
had not used a choke hold on Anthony Baez, came on the sixth day of
a trial in U.S. District Court in Manhattan in which Livoti stands
charged with depriving Baez of his civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   In a related development, a Supreme Court justice in the Bronx
unsealed portions of a deposition that gives more details about a
former supervisor's recommendation in 1991, three years before the
death of Baez, that Livoti be transferred from a Bronx precinct
because of the number of police brutality complaints against him.
</P>
<P>
   In federal court Tuesday, Officer Anthony Farnan, who was
testifying for the defense, said he had not seen Livoti use a choke
hold, an assertion that has been made by other officers who were at
the scene outside Baez's home on Cameron Place in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination, Farnan acknowledged that he and
four to eight other officers who were at the scene met with their
lawyers in the offices of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association to
discuss the events that occurred on a wintry night in December
1994, when Baez died after a struggle with Livoti.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a police sergeant, William Monahan, testified that he
and Livoti had met at union headquarters to hear Livoti's version
of events before they gave official statements.
</P>
<P>
   Farnan's account expands the number of officers who met after
the incident and appeared to bolster an assertion made last week by
federal prosecutors to the jury that it might hear testimony from
police officers ``who covered up what happened on Cameron Place on
Dec. 22 in order to protect a fellow officer and in order to
protect themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Livoti's lawyer, Stuart London, who had no comment after court,
told Judge Shira Scheindlin that he expected to rest his case
Wednesday. He says that his client is innocent and that Baez's
death was caused by a severe asthma attack.
</P>
<P>
   In the deposition that was partly unsealed in the Bronx on
Tuesday, William Casey, a former supervisor of Livoti's who is now
a deputy police chief, testified that he had recommended that
Livoti be transferred from the 46th Precinct because of the number
of police brutality complaints against him.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition, which was taken in a pending wrongful death
lawsuit filed against the Police Department by the Baez family,
shows that by 1991 there were 12 complaints against Livoti, of
which nine were assertions that he had used excessive force. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
