<SLUG> BC-NY-QUEENS-BLAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LACKS POWER TO CURB ILLEGAL MANUFACTURING, OFFICIAL SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN with DAVID ROHDE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after an explosion and fire destroyed what
officials called an illegal storefront furniture shop in Queens and
badly burned five people, the city's buildings commissioner said
Tuesday that there were hundreds of illegal manufacturing
businesses operating in New York, but that city officials lacked
the power to close them quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston Silva, the buildings commissioner, called on the City
Council to grant his agency increased power to close manufacturers
that operate without proper city permits. Current city ordinances
lacked the power to stop the furniture maker from operating in an
area that was not designated for manufacturing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the furniture shop that exploded on Monday afternoon,
R &AMP; N Custom Furniture at 102-26 Jamaica Ave. in Richmond Hill,
were fined in May 1997 for operating a manufacturing business in a
commercial area.
</P>
<P>
   But Silva said current city laws allowed the Buildings
Department to close an illegal manufacturer only if it was
operating in a residential neighborhood. Building officials do not
have the same power in neighborhoods that are designated as
commercial areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In those areas, like the Jamaica Avenue location, the Buildings
Department can only fine an owner for illegal use of the building,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I am proposing is an additional enforcement tool that
would allow us to close up illegal manufacturing facilities in
commercial districts,'' Silva said. ``The goal is not to fine
people or to punish people but to get compliance with the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Silva said he could not say precisely how many illegal
businesses there are in New York City. He said they varied from
furniture manufacturers like the shop in Queens and garment
manufacturers to improper service companies like auto repairing or
metal working concerns. They can be hazardous or merely a nuisance
to their neighborhoods, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silva said he would ask the City Council to for an ordinance
that would allow the Buildings Department to close dangerous
manufacturers operating in commercial as well as residential areas.
</P>
<P>
   Since a 1994 law allowed the Buildings Department to close
manufacturers in residential neighborhoods, it has closed 257
illegally operated businesses, department officials said. The
department does have the power to ask a judge to close an illegal
business operating in a commercial district, he said. But such a
proceeding, called a nuisance abatement, can take months and is
usually only begun after repeated complaints against the business
have been received, Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we can do up to now is give violations that could be paid
or not paid but do not force people to leave,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Buildings Department records, the Queens furniture
shop was fined $800 in a May 1997 hearing and ordered to stop using
the building as a factory by Aug. 11, 1997. Ilyse Fink, the
Buildings Department spokeswoman, said there was no indication in
the department's records that R &AMP; N complied with the order.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to the person that city officials identified as the owner
of the building, Yongwattie Betat, were not returned Monday or
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Gribbon, a Fire Department spokesman, said fire marshals
still believe that highly flammable fumes from contact cement
workers were improperly using in the basement caused Monday's
explosion and fire. But he said fire marshals were still trying to
determine what ignited the fumes.
</P>
<P>
   An employee of the manufacturer of the contact cement, Pilot
Chemical Co., which is based in Long Island City, said the product
must be used with proper ventilation. The employee, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the company sold it only to
businesses, not to individuals, because it is so dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't sell this to people if they walk in the off the
street,'' the worker said. ``If they brought it in any kitchen and
set it next to a stove, or any flammable thing, they're risking an
explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the federal Occupational Safety and Health
Administration office and the federal Department of Labor's Wage
and Hour Division said Tuesday that they were investigating whether
the store had been violating federal safe workplace and child labor
regulations. A 15-year-old and 17-year-old apparently working at
the site were among the injured.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond Hill residents complained Tuesday that they warned city
officials more than a year ago that the store was releasing noxious
fumes. And city officials confirmed Tuesday that at least three
city agencies had inspected the store prior to Monday's accident.
</P>
<P>
   In response to complaints of fumes from a woman living in the
apartment above the shop, city buildings inspectors visited the
store on March 11, 1997, and issued the illegal manufacturing
violation that resulted in the $800 May 1997 fine, records show.
But the store remained open.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980623.0515 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3419 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-HUGS-NYT &LR;      06-23 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-HUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARING LAWSUITS, TEACHERS GROW MORE RETICENT WITH THEIR TOUCHES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When a charter school opened last fall in Hoboken, N.J.,
director Lydia Becker warned her small staff of teachers to be
careful not to hug students who do not want to be hugged or
otherwise touched.
</P>
<P>
   The topic has also dominated discussions that Ms. Becker has had
at home with her husband, a third-grade teacher at another school.
So, she was asked recently, when was the last time she hugged a
student at the Elysian Charter School?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, about 10 minutes ago,'' she said, laughing. ``Today was
the last day of school, and the kids were sure gushy-mushy.
Sometimes kids want to be loved. It would be a sad world if we cut
all of that out, especially in early childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Monday's Supreme Court decision that schools may not
be held liable for sexual abuse by a teacher when school officials
were not aware of the offense, teachers and principals everywhere
have been quietly but determinedly changing the way they act toward
their students, touching less, hugging not at all in some schools
and making sure they are not alone with them.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of criminal legal action against them _ and there have
been plenty of cases nationwide _ has left many teachers and
teacher groups wary that a squeeze of the shoulders or a pat on the
back will be misconstrued.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools tell their teachers during seminars or workshops
not to touch children, under any circumstances. Others make them
aware of what can lead to claims of sexual abuse and train them how
to identify the problem and report it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We advise our members not to touch the children, especially as
the children get older,'' said Karen Joseph, a spokeswoman for the
New Jersey Education Association, the teachers' union in the state.
``We have to be careful because there have been so many false
accusations against teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joseph knows that the changes are hard for many teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People enter the teaching profession because they like kids,''
she said. ``But we tell them that there are many, many ways to show
positive reinforcement besides touching.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Joel Berger, a teacher for almost 30 years in the New York City
schools, said that all his colleagues have been warned to watch
themselves with students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told, if you have to have an after-school conference
with a kid, especially with someone of the opposite sex, don't do
it one-on-one if you can help it,'' said Berger, who teaches social
studies at Intermediate School 383 in Brooklyn. ``When you have to
have a conference, keep the door open at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Berger said, if a student wants comfort, he might give
him a handshake or an encouraging look. ``If a child hugs me, I
don't push them away,'' he said. ``But if they're expecting a hug
in return, they usually don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The changes have left some teachers and other educators,
especially those dealing with small children, in a quandary about
whether to follow their nature to nurture or to hold back, possibly
at the cost of alienating a child.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Recchia, a professor of early childhood education at
Teachers College at Columbia University, said teachers of very
young children have to help them with such things as tying their
shoes or putting on their coats. It is easy, and indeed part of the
nurturing, to touch, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The child's own learning takes place on a really physical
level,'' she said. ``It is part of our own training in early
childhood to hold when they are hurt, to comfort when they are
upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea of somehow removing that from the curriculum is not
something we would even consider,'' she said. ``On the other hand,
the heightened awareness of sexual abuse raises some issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality of claims of sexual abuse has changed the scene for
everyone, she acknowledged. In New York State, Dr. Recchia said,
all teachers must take, as part of their certification, training in
child abuse identification and reporting, and workers at day care
centers and other places with very young children can change a
baby's diaper only in the presence of another worker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a heightened sense of suspicion for everyone,''
said Dr. Recchia, who is also the director of Teachers College's
Center for Infants and Parents. ``And that colors your interaction
with a child, if you're constantly thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Educators also say some children need hugs more than others, and
sometimes that is determined by their culture, home situation, age
and emotional development.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see kids who don't come from loving households, and
sometimes a hug is what they need to boost their self-esteem,''
said Norm Tankiewicz, a teachers union leader in Perth Amboy, N.J.
``But we're living in a very litigation-happy society now. I used
to openly hug my kids, but I don't do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   In special education, in which children are more apt to need
physical contact, the hugging issue comes up in another way.
Michelle Massimi, whose daughter has Down's syndrome and attends a
public school in Fair Lawn, N.J., said that teachers try to help
the children learn appropriate hugging. They have them draw a
circle on a piece of paper, and the names of people it is
appropriate to hug, like mothers and fathers, are written inside,
and those whom it is not appropriate to hug, like strangers, go
outside the circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they want children to go up and hug everyone,''
Mrs. Massimi said. ``Some teachers hug the kids more than others.
For some, it's just a way of saying you did a great job. Some
people just like kids. It's still very important for the kids and
the teachers to know that what they're doing is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At the Daniel Webster School in Pelham, N.Y., principal Diane
Ramos Kelly said she does not tell teachers not to hug students,
but leaves it to their own professional judgment to discern when
hugs are appropriate and when they are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the culture created in each classroom has to be a
nurturing one,'' she said. ``A place where the children can grow
socially, emotionally and academically. Do I think it's sometime
natural for little kids to throw their arms around a teacher? Of
course. The cornerstone of early childhood education involves
touching. You have to tie their shoes, wipe away tears, hold
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
