<SLUG> BC-NY-ZODIAC-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYERS CONTEND EVIDENCE WAS MOLDED IN ZODIAC CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By VIVIAN S. TOY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In impassioned final arguments Tuesday, lawyers for
the man accused of being the Zodiac killer depicted police
investigators as so desperate to close a case that had haunted them
for six years that they shaped and molded evidence to connect their
client to the crimes.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for the defendant, Heriberto Seda, 30, also sought
to discount a confession from Seda as tainted and unlawfully
obtained because, they said, police officers ignored repeated
denials and refusals to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Masters, an assistant district attorney, countered with
what he termed ``an avalanche of evidence'' that included 45
witnesses' testimony and 150 exhibits said to link Seda to the
Zodiac crimes without a doubt. The evidence included fingerprints,
DNA, ballistics and handwriting samples. Seda's lawyers did not
call any witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The trial in State Supreme Court in Queens, which lasted six
weeks, was turned over to the jury for deliberation Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The gunman who came to be known as the Zodiac terrorized the
city in 1990 and again in 1992 and 1993 when he randomly shot at
people and sent letters to police and to news organizations
promising to kill one person for each of the 12 signs of the
Zodiac.
</P>
<P>
   Seda is accused of killing three people and wounding one in
Queens. He has also been charged with shooting three people in
Brooklyn and one in Manhattan. If convicted in the Queens case, he
faces a maximum of 83 years to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Although the courtroom has largely been empty throughout the
trial, with Seda's mother appearing only a few times, the room was
packed Tuesday with members of the prosecutor's office, including
Queens District Attorney Richard Brown. ``This was a case that
captured the imagination of the entire city,'' Brown said. ``And
hopefully when the jury comes in, it will close that chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing the scene at the station house of the 75th Precinct
in East New York, Brooklyn, where Seda was first linked to the
Zodiac crimes in 1996, John Wallenstein, one of Seda's lawyers,
said the squad room was ``wall to wall'' with police chiefs eager
to see an end to one of the city's most notorious unsolved crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't think that's a lot of pressure for the detectives?''
he said. ``With all that brass in the next room, failure was not an
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, Wallenstein and the other defense lawyer, David
Bart, said that ``failure was not an option'' for police
investigators and experts who, the lawyers asserted, felt obliged
to say that the fingerprints, DNA and handwriting of the Zodiac
killer matched Seda's.
</P>
<P>
   The experts were merely offering their opinions, Wallenstein
said. ``They've decided he's the Zodiac and that's what the puzzle
looks like,'' he said. ``And if the pieces don't fit, then you've
got to trim them a little bit to make them fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Seda, known as Eddie, was arrested in June 1996 in the shooting
of his half-sister, of whose friends he was said to disapprove.
Police tied Seda to the Zodiac slayings when they noticed that he
signed his confession to shooting his half-sister with the Zodiac
killer's familiar symbol, a circle with an overlapping cross and
three sevens surrounding the cross.
</P>
<P>
   Bart said that once that link was made, police detectives set
out to ``badger'' a confession out of Seda. The lawyer said that
during 20 hours of interrogation, Seda repeatedly said, ``I'm not
the man,'' and, ``I don't have to talk to you.''
</P>
<P>
   And though Seda refused to sign a card saying he was willing to
answer questions, Bart said, detectives persisted with a variety of
tactics to wear him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask yourselves, did Eddie Seda invoke his right to remain
silent, and whether that right was trampled on,'' Bart said to the
jury.
</P>
<P>
   But Masters, the prosecutor, said that the confession was not
only voluntary but ``almost proudly announced'' and that Seda was
told four times of his rights to remain silent and to have a
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Masters produced a huge color-coded chart for the jurors listing
each of the crimes and the evidence that linked Seda to them. ``I
submit that each of these pieces of evidence alone would prove that
he is the Zodiac,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He contended that if detectives were so bent on coercing a
confession out of Seda, they would not have included information
that was inconsistent with the evidence. For example, Seda's
statement says he both shot and stabbed one of his victims, when
only stab wounds were found on the victim. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
