<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DEMS-TAPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONX DEMOCRATIC OFFICIALS AT ODDS OVER SECRET TAPES
</HEADLINE>
  (ja) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Assemblyman Roberto Ramirez, the Bronx Democratic
Party chairman, demanded Tuesday that former state Sen. Pedro
Espada Jr. release secretly recorded tapes on which Espada says
Democratic officials are heard planning to undermine his campaign
to recapture his seat.
</P>
<P>
   Espada has said he recorded his meetings with Ramirez and other
officials in the spring. During those meetings, Espada claims,
Ramirez said he would ask District Attorney Robert Johnson to call
off an investigation into the finances of a health clinic operated
by Espada if the former senator withdrew his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Ramirez said, ``I demand that Mr. Espada release
all recordings to myself, to the press and to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Espada announced June 12 that he would run for the seat he lost
two years ago. A week later, he was indicted along with two
employees on charges of illegally diverting $221,000 in Medicaid
money to his failed 1996 re-election campaign and to that of his
son Pedro Gautier Espada, who was then an assemblyman and is now a
city councilman.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Ramirez said Espada ``is trying to portray
himself as a victim hoping that he will distract people from
focusing on the charge that he embezzled more than $200,000 to run
his failed re-election campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Espada released a secretly videotaped
conversation that took place on May 23 between his son and state
Sen.David Rosado. On that tape, Rosado boasted of the Democratic
Party's ability to influence Johnson to drop the investigation if
Espada pledged not to run against him.
</P>
<P>
   Espada maintains that he also has audiotapes on which various
Democratic officials, including Ramirez, suggest that Johnson's
office was collaborating with Ramirez and other Democratic leaders
to keep Espada out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Ramirez said he met with Espada six times
between March and early June. ``I will not allow anyone to suggest
that I have tried to illegally influence the criminal justice
system in any way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Espada said, ``I have never been good
at following Ramirez's orders, and I'm not going to start now.''
</P>
<P>
   Espada added that he plans to release all of the tapes over the
next several months ``to journalists and to law enforcement
officials who have expressed interest in them.'' He said the pace
of the release would depend on the advice he received from his
lawyers and from investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Espada said state and Federal investigators had listened to
several of the tapes, but he declined to identify them. He said he
had tapes of ``several dozen conversations'' with a number of
Democratic officials in the Bronx. The conversations in their
entirety, Espada said, make it clear that Bronx Democratic
officials had urged him to make a deal with Ramirez to refrain from
seeking office.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Ramirez has insisted that there never was a deal with
Espada, Johnson has said political considerations have never played
a role in his office's investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Espada's allegations have rocked the political landscape
in the Bronx and created the most serious crisis for Ramirez since
he became party chairman four years ago. Under Ramirez's
stewardship, Democratic politics in the Bronx have largely avoided
the scandals of previous years, which led to convictions of party
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several Bronx politicians and political strategists
maintain that the indictment and the tapes have placed a blemish
not only on Espada but also on the borough's Democratic
organization. They suggest that Espada's allegations against
Johnson and Ramirez might resonate with many voters because the
party worked vigorously last year on the successful campaign of
Dianne Renwick, who is Johnson's wife, to become a Bronx Civil
Court judge.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez complained Tuesday that the allegations had begun to
tarnish his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For four years, I have worked to raise the level of discourse
and openness in this county,'' Ramirez said in an interview. ``I
have walked a very straight line. Mr. Espada, with his despicable
action, has put into question four years of hard labor. It's a pure
political attempt to jaundice the indictment that was brought
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Gautier Espada, Espada's son, said Tuesday that his family
and their supporters planned to hold a candlelight vigil ``calling
for justice'' Thursday evening outside the catering hall where the
Bronx Democratic Party will be holding its annual dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Espada's brother Jose R. Espada is running for the Assembly seat
held by Ruben Diaz Jr., another Bronx Democrat. And the younger
Espada is running against Rosado for district leader.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
