</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STEINBRENNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEINBRENNER PLAYS DOWN UPCOMING MET SERIES
</HEADLINE>
   (ja) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ George Steinbrenner, the ultracompetitive principal
owner of the New York Yankees, said Tuesday that his team's
three-game series against the New York Mets next weekend really
wasn't that big a deal.
</P>
<P>
   He said it at 4:20 p.m., at Yankee Stadium, in the middle of the
Yankees' clubhouse. There were many witnesses. It should be noted
that his right hand was at his side. Should the Yankees fall behind
the Mets in the fist inning on Friday night, it will be the owner's
prerogative to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hype that is being generated about this series _ to me,
that's for the city championship,'' Steinbrenner said. ``I'm more
concerned with getting to the world's championship.''
</P>
<P>
   So if the Yankees lose two of three games to the Mets, it isn't
important? ``No,'' Steinbrenner said. ``What does it mean? I'm not
bitter against the Mets. They have a very good team; I'm happy for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stories of Steinbrenner's reacting angrily to exhibition losses
against the Mets are legendary. Maybe the defeats galled him in his
early years as the Yankees' owner, conceded Steinbrenner, who has
owned the team for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe early on, in the first years,'' he said. ``I didn't want
to lose to anybody. I thought you could go undefeated, when I first
came into baseball. I had a hard time understanding you can't go
undefeated in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``But right now, my focus is entirely on October and getting the
New York Yankees into the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at length, Steinbrenner discussed many matters:
</P>
<P>
   _ Chili Davis, the designated hitter who is coming back from
surgery on his ankle, is ``working very hard'' in Tampa, Fla.,
Steinbrenner said. ``You'd hardly recognize him.'' Steinbrenner
said Davis' weight has dropped to 232 pounds from about 245.
``Chili challenges me,'' Steinbrenner said. ``He works out twice a
day so he can catch me on one of the days I work out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steinbrenner said Bernie Williams, who is coming back from a
sprained knee, is getting close to returning; others in the
Yankees' organization continue to hope Williams will rejoin the
lineup this weekend. ``Bernie wants back bad,'' Steinbrenner said.
``He's working very hard down there _ very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steinbrenner is impressed by the 1998 Yankees, who have won 51
of their first 69 games. ``In the Reggie-Munson-Chambliss era,
there was a little difference, a little bit of turmoil, but they
were champions and they won back to back,'' Steinbrenner said,
referring to the 1977 and 1978 teams featuring Reggie Jackson,
Thurman Munson and Chris Chambliss that won World Series titles.
``This team is very focused. I've never had a team any more focused
than these guys, on a game-to-game basis.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Steinbrenner, who is trying to get a new stadium, acknowledged
that he was surprised by the crowd of some 53,000 in the Bronx on
Monday night for the first game of the interleague series with the
Atlanta Braves. But he noted the difficulty some fans had in
getting to Yankee Stadium and parking, citing his own experience.
Steinbrenner flew into Newark and drove to the stadium, winding
through the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough, but I saw what some of these people have to go
through to get to the games,'' Steinbrenner said. ``You have to
love the Yankees to do that, and they do, and I give them credit.
Bumper to bumper to bumper to bumper. I pulled up alongside one
wagon full of kids and the driver. I could tell they were all upset
_ they all had their Yankees hats on. I rolled down the window and
said, `Don't worry, they ain't starting until I get there.' They
didn't have any idea who I was.''
</P>
<P>
   Word was later relayed to Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, that
Steinbrenner had played down the importance of the series against
the Mets. ``That's what he tells you,'' Torre said, grinning
slightly as he walked away from a crowd of reporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
