<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENTED BALLPLAYERS CAN BE FOUND IN CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reggie didn't need a last name. Junior doesn't need a
name at all. El Duque is just El Duque to so many people that some
don't even know he has a name.
</P>
<P>
   When he made his fourth start for the Yankees against the
Atlanta Braves at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday night, Orlando
Hernandez was not the name emanating from the throats of the crowd
of 54,775. The fans cheered for El Duque, or just plain Duque, the
remarkable Cuban expatriate who has become an instant honorary
citizen of New York.
</P>
<P>
   The fans, however, were not the only people at the Stadium who
had arrived eager to see El Duque make the fourth start of his
major league career.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before El Duque threw his first pitch, Leo Mazzone, the
Braves' pitching coach, sat on the top step of the visitors' dugout
and said: ``I'm looking forward to seeing him pitch. They say he
has a lot of motion and good control, a lot of different arm
angles. It's kind of refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   What Mazzone saw, though, was not the El Duque of his first
three starts. His form was the same all right, but his control and
his effectiveness were not and he suffered his first major league
loss in a 7-2 Braves victory. Hernandez did not survive the fourth
inning, leaving after he issued two consecutive bases-loaded walks
and gave up a two-run single to Chipper Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a highlight here and there,'' Jones, the Braves' third
baseman, had said before facing El Duque. ``He throws strikes and
changes speeds a lot. We have to come out and be aggressive, and
hopefully some balls will fall in for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Braves' hitters were aggressive, swinging at El
Duque's pitches early in the count. Ryan Klesko singled on the
second pitch he saw in the second inning, and Michael Tucker sent
him home later in the inning with a first-pitch single.
</P>
<P>
   The two-run single by Jones that finished El Duque's night came
on the first pitch, too. Others took many pitches as El Duque went
to three-ball counts six times in the third and fourth innings.
</P>
<P>
   This was the El Duque who had dazzled Tampa Bay, Montreal and
Cleveland, allowing 4 runs and 23 base runners in 23 and two-thirds
innings. That was why he took a 2-0 record and a 1.52 earned run
average into his meeting with the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi, one of the Yankees' catchers, attributed El Duque's
early success to ``his location and the many different arm angles
he can give a hitter and still make quality pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi added: ``Hitters aren't able to see a lot of the same
arm angles consistently. It's like facing a different pitcher every
time at bat. It makes it tough on hitters. He can change any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his mind he knows how to pitch. He knows what he's doing.
He changes pitch to pitch. Maybe a couple pitches the same way and
then he'll change. He knows what he's doing out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Girardi thought for a moment and added, ``It must have been hard
for amateurs.''
</P>
<P>
   He referred to the players around the world who encountered El
Duque in international tournaments, no professionals allowed. Those
matches often were mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   If Mark Grudzielanek, the Expos shortstop, could go hitless in
three at-bats, striking out twice, what was a kid from Taiwan
supposed to do?
</P>
<P>
   With the emergence of El Duque and Rolando Arrojo, the Devil
Rays' nine-game winner, and shortstop Rey Ordonez, the Mets' human
highlight film, it is clear what an impact Cubans would have had on
the major leagues the past 40 years if they had been allowed to
leave their country to work elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``From one end of Cuba to the other,'' said Jose Valdivielso, a
former Cuban major leaguer and now a New York sportscaster,
``they've got thousands and thousands of Duques and Ordonezes,
great ballplayers who if given an opportunity would fill the major
leagues. But they don't have the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdivielso, who left Cuba in 1960, during his major league
career with the Washington Senators and Minnesota Twins, said he
was sure ``a lot of scouts'' would go to Cuba if Castro unlocked
the borders and allowed the baseball-hungry youngsters to seek
fortunes in America.
</P>
<P>
   That is an understatement. It would be the modern baseball
version of the gold rush, scouts from every organization flocking
to Havana and all of the island's tiny towns as well. If the
Dominican Republic and Venezuela are fast becoming the most fertile
hunting grounds for American scouts, Cuba would be Shangri-La.
</P>
<P>
   You like El Duque? Make sure you see those 15-year-olds with the
wicked curves. You like Ordonez? Check out those players who make
him look as if he had limited range. If only the Cuban commissioner
named Castro would accept reality and let his people go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our scouts who saw those teams said so many could play in the
big leagues right now,'' said Bobby Cox, the Braves' manager.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, American teams and fans settle for the advance guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's zippy quick,'' Cox said of El Duque. ``Not fast, but
sneaky, and those are the toughest guys to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the manager thought about El Duque's saga. ``Fleeing an
island, a dictatorship and two months later you're pitching in
Yankee Stadium,'' he said. ``It's quite a story.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
