<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GREEN-SPACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENVIRONMENTAL ENTREPRENEUR CLOSES A DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fortunately for Tom Fox, the story of his little
yellow water taxis no longer works as a perfect metaphor for his
life.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the boats were supposed to have been buzzing around the
waterfront several times a day, moving people to various stops from
the Brooklyn Bridge to the Intrepid museum, but Fox had to shut
down the whole enterprise in August after only three months because
the boats didn't have enough power to navigate the harbor. New
York's currents proved too much for them.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine what a halfway imaginative biographer could make of this
detail if Fox were still the blue-jeaned environmentalist of his
youth, hopelessly proselytizing for more green space in the city of
mortar, writing position papers on the importance of community
gardens. But Fox makes money these days as an environmental and
development consultant, wears a tie to work (some days), and last
week watched a longtime dream come true when the state and city
finally agreed on how to build and operate a pulsating strip of
park along the Hudson River on Manhattan's West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has been crusading for that park for years, including three
as founding president of the Hudson River Park Conservancy, which
drew up the plans for the five-mile park and worked out its
fundamental compromises with the surrounding communities, deciding
when the green of chlorophyll should give way to the green of
economic development. The Pataki administration replaced him in
1995, preferring someone with more direct loyalty to the governor's
staff, but the plan that will now proceed is virtually unchanged
from the one developed by him and his staff, and so the moment is
finally sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it feels like closure,'' he said this week in his
consulting-firm offices at 42nd Street and Fifth Avenue. ``We're
actually going to have the largest riverfront park in the United
States right here in river city, and we the people made it
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the people, of course. There are still those who oppose
the park as a development grab, environmentalists once on the same
side as Fox in fighting Westway and other large projects around the
city, who now spit out his name in derision as a sellout. In the
never-ending wars that rage between real estate interests and
Manhattan's community boards, he is the necessary go-between,
someone who can talk to both sides but is not trusted fully by
either one.
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Benstock, the implacable (but increasingly marginalized)
foe of Westway and the proposed park, says Fox was never an
environmentalist and calls the park twice as bad as Westway. Gene
Russianoff, senior attorney for the New York Public Interest
Research Group, says he knows of no other advocate in the city as
focused and ferocious as Fox, but fears that the ``develo-park''
will be slowly whittled by economic interests.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is frustrating for Fox, who used to lob seeds into
vacant lots as a leader of the Green Guerrillas and remembers with
pride working to stop Mortimer Zuckerman's proposed tower at the
southwest corner of Central Park. He says his colleagues have
become so used to stopping things that they can no longer create
and the Hudson park would never happen without developments like
the Chelsea Piers to pay for its operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're naive,'' he said, windmilling his arms around as if to
shed some of his excess energy. ``In the 21st century, without all
the government funding we used to have, you have to find other ways
to finance and build parks. And if there's any contribution I've
made, it's the idea that parks can be self-financing, so that the
money generated in the park can only go to its design,
construction, management and operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, 51, grew up on Ocean Avenue in Flatbush _ only a few blocks
from the rambling Victorian where he and his wife and son live now
_ and he played in Prospect Park as a boy, but he never cared much
about the spaciousness of nature until he volunteered for the Navy
in Vietnam, serving in combat from 1966 to 1968. Seeing jungles and
marine life up close transformed him, and he came home to study
biology at Brooklyn College and to develop environmental programs
as a ranger in the federal Gateway National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
   If the war didn't quite radicalize him, it made him realize the
value of fighting for a cause, and he spent years fighting for
community gardens and open space on various boards and commissions
around the city. But he says there was always a pragmatic aspect as
well. He enlisted the support of construction unions by convincing
them that open space in a city generates development and economic
activity, citing Frederick Law Olmsted's arguments for Central Park
more than a century earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Though some advocates criticize him for trying to cash in on the
planned park with his water taxi plan after being removed from the
conservancy, he says it was a natural way to ``do well by doing
good'' with a service that will benefit the public and, perhaps
someday, his own bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to be an environmental entrepreneur here,'' he
said. ``Some environmentalists just call attention to problems. I
come from the group that tries to figure a way to solve those
problems, and as near as I can tell, that almost always involves
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Of which he needs $2 million for boats with a bit more power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
