<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-MAIN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves rip Hernandez in 7-2 win
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was no drama this time. Round 2? Atlanta, in
Tom Glavine's favorite place: The road.
</P>
<P>
   Despite allowing two homers, Glavine got his 10th win of the
season Tuesday with a 7-2 victory over the Yankees before 54,775 at
Yankee Stadium. In raising his road record this season to 7-0 in
eight road starts, Glavine (10-3) worked eight strong innings and
got lots of help throughout the lineup as Yankees starter Orlando
Hernandez lasted just 3 2/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen, batting ninth, had two doubles, two key walks and
scored three times. Ryan Klesko, back in the lineup against the
right-handed Hernandez, singled three times and scored twice while
Keith Lockhart had two RBIs. A night earlier, the Braves had
squandered three leads in a 6-4 loss. This time, before another
boisterous Bronx crowd and in their first look at ``El Duque''
Hernandez, there was no bullpen trepidation for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban defector and older brother of the Marlins' Livan
Hernandez, El Duque won his first two starts after being called up
from the minors before getting a no-decision last Thursday. He got
some early help Tuesday: Derek Jeter's opposite-field, first-inning
homer for a 1-0 Yankee lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tied it in the second on three straight one-out hits.
After the first of Klesko's three straight singles, Javy Lopez
doubled into the right field corner. Michael Tucker singled in
Klesko, then took second on the throw home. But on Andruw Jones'
fly to fairly shallow right, Tucker was doubled off when Tino
Martinez cut off the throw home.
</P>
<P>
   Guillen then drew vital walks in each of the next two innings.
After walking to lead off the third, he took third base on a single
to right by Curtis Pride, leading off as Bobby Cox's left-handed
designated hitter. Guillen then scored on Lockhart's slow roller.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta broke it open in the fourth inning. After Klesko's
leadoff single, Lopez just missed a third-deck homer before
walking. When Scott Brosius booted Andruw Jones' grounder, the
bases were loaded. Guillen fell behind 1-2, then took three
straight balls just off the outside corner to score Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez then walked Pride on a full-count fastball that forced
in another run. El Duque fanned Lockhart but Chipper Jones struck a
two-out single to center to score two and make it 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
