<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USSOCCER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPSON: JOB OFFERS AWAIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)(SLANG) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTES, France _ Steve Sampson's future remains uncertain with
the U.S. national soccer team in the wake of its World Cup failure,
but that's not to say he's refusing to look at his options.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. coach, who lives in Agoura Hills, has acknowledged
there are others interested in what he can provide if U.S. Soccer
is not. But U.S. Soccer has not made any public declarations about
who might guide its top team after it returns from France.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Rothenberg, U.S. Soccer's president, said before Sunday's
2-1 loss to Iran, which ended the Americans' chances to reach the
second round, he envisioned Sampson remaining in charge. After the
match, he wasn't so specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to be replaced during the tournament (such as
Saudi Arabia's Carlos Alberto Parreira and South Korea's Cha
Bum-kun), that's for sure,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly a vote of confidence. Sensing that, Rothenberg added:
``As I was watching the game, I was thinking if there was something
I would've done differently. And I couldn't think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampson, who took charge in April 1995 after Bora Milutinovic
was fired, wasn't U.S. Soccer's first choice. Portugal's Carlos
Queiroz turned down an invitation and so did Parreira, who guided
Brazil to the 1994 title.
</P>
<P>
   Sampson said the Americans achieved their most pressing goals in
this tournament, demonstrating to the world they can play the sport
with a certain level of prowess and sophistication. He's repeatedly
said it is important an American be coach of the squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gained enormous international experience,'' he said.
``I'm one of two coaches out of 40 in North and Central America to
have survived this process. That experience is very rare and hard
to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope U.S. Soccer will want to continue to use that
experience. If not, I've already had offers the last six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what kind of offers, whether from foreign national teams
or Major League Soccer clubs, he replied: ``International offers.
It wouldn't be right for MLS to make offers at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation Sampson might become head coach of
the San Jose Clash once the sale of the team to a group headed by
Rothenberg is finalized. Rothenberg, when asked about that, said he
wasn't sure Sampson would be the Clash's coach because ``that would
mean he's no longer'' coaching the national team.
</P>
<P>
   If U.S. Soccer decides his tenure is over _ and a strong
performance against Yugoslavia here Thursday might convince
officials otherwise _ there are several coaches waiting in the
wings. Queiroz would have been the most likely, but he resigned as
the federation's technical director last week to accept the
national-team job with United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   Parreira, who like Queiroz coached the New York/New Jersey
MetroStars, is available, and three American coaches also are in
the pool:
</P>
<P>
   __ Clive Charles, an English-born assistant to Sampson and the
U.S. Olympic coach, who also is in charge of the men's and women's
programs at the University of Portland.
</P>
<P>
   __ Thomas Rongen, the Dutch-born coach of the New England
Revolution, also a Sampson assistant.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bruce Arena, who has guided D.C. United to the first two MLS
titles after leading the University of Virginia to five NCAA crowns
in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Arena is widely considered the best coach in America, but he is
arrogant and has made enemies within the federation. ``He'll never
be the U.S. coach as long as the (current regime) is in charge,''
one U.S. Soccer official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
