<SLUG> BC-WIN98-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIN 98 WON'T BE ANOTHER WIN 95 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - WINDOWS 98   By David Einstein  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Prospects for Windows 98, which goes on sale tomorrow, pale by
comparison with the phenomenal success of Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   But before you start feeling sorry for Bill Gates, consider
this: Windows 98 is still expected to be the best-selling new
software of the year, and one of the top hits in any
consumer-product category.
</P>
<P>
   As the latest version of the operating software that runs most
of the world's personal computers, Windows 98 can't possibly miss.
International Data Corp. estimates that Microsoft will sell 12.8
million copies by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   But by comparison, some 19.5 million copies of Windows 95 were
sold in just four months after its release in August of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Why the ``modest'' forecast for Windows 98? Analysts say it's
because the software is just a modest upgrade with the same look
and feel as Windows 95 and no new killer features.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't really a very big product,'' said analyst Eric
Brown of Forrester Research. ``It's bug fixes, a couple of nice new
features and Internet Explorer.''
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95, on the other hand, was a radical new piece of
software that redefined the way users interact with PCs. In
addition, the computer industry badly needed Windows 95, which
ushered in a new generation of faster applications and powerful
systems.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 will make it easier for PCs to run the latest
hardware, such as DVD drives, but there is no sense of urgency
attending its introduction.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many corporations and small businesses are expected to
eschew Windows 98, preferring to wait for Windows NT 5.0. That's
the next version of Microsoft's network operating system, which is
due out in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business decision-makers are confused whether Windows 98,
Windows NT or some other technology is the best choice,'' said
IDC's William Peterson. ``When confused, business decision-makers
wait for the dust to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft itself is discouraging corporations from switching to
Windows 98, claiming that they'd be better off with the current
version of Windows NT, which is more powerful (and at $149 to
upgrade, more expensive) than Windows 98.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely downplaying Windows for business,'' said
Cara Walker, a spokeswoman with Microsoft's public relations firm.
``This is the first OS Microsoft has ever marketed strictly for
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   According to IDC, some 6.9 million consumers are expected to buy
Windows 98 this year to upgrade their systems. Priced at $89, it
will be available at computer superstores, software stores and
warehouse stores.
</P>
<P>
   PC-makers will put Windows 98 on most new multimedia systems _ a
move that's expected to boost sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said all along it will be an enhancement,'' said Dell
spokesman T.R. Reid. ``A new version of an operating system helps
folks who might have been looking for that last excuse to trade up
to a new system.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry executives said PC sales may have dropped off
during the past two months as consumers put off purchases while
waiting for Windows 98. ``Retailers especially were not eager to
take in new inventory that did not have Windows 98,'' said Mal
Ransom, vice president of marketing for Packard Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 98 is expected to gain steam during the next few years.
IDC said that by 2000, Microsoft will ship 66 million copies of it,
surpassing the 53 million copies of Windows 95 in its third year. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
