<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET SMARTS/MARK VEVERKA 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS   Merger Mania Has Finally Penetrated the Internet `Space'  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Pssst. Lycos is on the block.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Or at least everybody and their brother is darn certain that it
is. And they're probably right. Even Lycos management is saying as
much. The Waltham, Mass., company is considered one of the next,
ahem, Internet portals that is expected to hook up with a media
giant or telecommunications behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, merger mania has penetrated the Internet ``space,'' as they
say on Sand Hill Road. Last week, Disney acquired 43 percent of
Infoseek for more than $70 million. Just recently General Electric,
which owns NBC, acquired 5 percent of Cnet for $26 million, and
agreed to buy as much as 60 percent of its Snap! online portal
(there's that word again) for $38 million.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, there was Zapata Corp. of Houston, the fish
meal folks who made an unsolicited and unsuccessful bid to buy
Excite to get a piece of the Internet pie.
</P>
<P>
   You can be sure that all of this deal-posturing has investment
bankers ordering a lot of take-in these days. What's more, all of
the merger talk has Internet stocks frothier than ever. Yesterday
Yahoo soared $8.50 a share, hitting a 52-week high of $148, and
Lycos closed at $68.75, up $4.25. (Yahoo's rise was attributed to
false rumors that it would be added to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index.)
</P>
<P>
   Now that Disney, which owns ABC, and GE, which owns NBC, have
made acquisitions that could make them the first stop for Web
surfers, conventional wisdom is that the likes of Time Warner or
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. are sure bets to invest in the
remaining free-agent Internet portals. (And now that News Corp. has
wreaked havoc with its Los Angeles Dodgers investment, it can
concentrate on an Internet deal.)
</P>
<P>
   But the point is that an investment in Lycos, or in most other
portal companies, is akin to making a wager at the tables in Tahoe.
It's a bet that the company will be bought out, says Michael
Murphy, publisher of the California Technology Stock Letter in Half
Moon Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fad going on to turn your (company) into a portal
company because the contest to become the dominant search engine''
is close to over, with Yahoo being the winner, Murphy says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now everybody's scrambling for partners, including Lycos,''
says Murphy, who has a short position on Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy generally believes that there is too much hot air in
Internet stocks, and recently published a blanket recommendation
shorting almost all Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   He, like many other stockpickers and analysts, contends that
these Internet companies are grossly overvalued and don't possess
the basic earnings and revenue streams to support their prices.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Internet stocks continue to defy gravity, squeezing the
short-sellers and causing them severe financial pain.
</P>
<P>
   So it's not surprising that the majority of financial analysts
on Wall Street recommend that their clients buy Lycos at its
current price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it. I don't love it,'' says analyst Keith Benjamin of
BancAmerica Robertson Stephens, who rates the stock ``long-term
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   At its current price of about $68, Lycos shares are approaching
his 12-month price target of $72, which is based on annual earnings
projections for 2001 of $1.45 a share. (That's right, 21/2 years
from now.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if someone like Time Warner made an
investment in Lycos,'' Benjamin says.
</P>
<P>
   Or someone like News Corp. Or Germany's Bertelsmann AG, Lycos'
joint-venture partner in Europe. Or a telephone company, such as
AT&AMP;T, which last month teamed with Lycos to develop a co-branded
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   Another Lycos bull is analyst Andrea Williams of Volpe Brown
Whelan, who has issued some skeptical and cautious research on
Internet concerns in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, she's more upbeat. Given the red-hot
merger and acquisition climate, Williams is high on Lycos and rates
it a ``strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent (Cnet and Infoseek) deals have kind of woken up a
number of media companies and that seems to have created an urgency
in their (M&AMP;A) talks,'' Williams says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do expect Lycos and others to announce new partners.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Lycos chief operating officer and CFO Ted Philip
is doing little to dispel notions that his company is for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've stated publicly that we would be interested in an
investment by the appropriate media or entertainment company,''
Philip says.
</P>
<P>
   The Lycos executive would not comment on what companies have
shown an interest in Lycos. Nor would he characterize what size
stake management might be inclined to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he sounded like someone who is willing to cut a
deal. Shareholders can only hope.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-23-98 2315EDT &QL; 
