<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE BIRD 
MAD-UH-LINN OR MAD-UH-LINE? 
HANGING OUT 
RANCHER DAVE 
I-MAN TO BUILD
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This may rank right up there with the notion of
alligators in the sewer: a bright blue parakeet on a Park Avenue
doormat. Now he is living in _ what else? _ a gilded cage. And the
bird is a he. The salesclerks at Bernardaud, a store better known
for Limoges porcelain than for avian biology, checked.
</P>
<P>
   But first they had to coax him off the doormat and into the
store, at Park Avenue between 60th and 61st Streets. ``We tried to
encourage him to do something _ get on a pencil _ but no, he was
uncomfortable with that idea,'' said Mary Kay Denning, a
spokeswoman for the store. ``We were able, with the help of a
chauffeur who pulled a beach towel out of the car and someone
passing by who told us that if we covered him, we could handle
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schwarz, a lawyer who passed by while prospective brides at
Bernardaud were watching the salesclerks chase the parakeet, said
that the bird was ``swooping around the moldings and too close to
the $200 wine glasses.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Denning said that the bird, whom the salesclerks have named
Barbu (it means bearded, in French), ended up in a high-ceilinged
stockroom. He eventually did a, uh, swan dive for a snack, landing
on someone's muffin, and was moved to a restroom (``so no one could
go to the bathroom for the next six hours''), then to the cage.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Denning said she had hoped to hear from Barbu's previous
owner, but so far, not a peep.
</P>
<P>
   Madeline Moves to the Big Screen
</P>
<P>
   All together now: ``In an old house in Paris that was covered
with vines lived 12 little girls in two straight lines.'' That
sentence was uttered more than once at a party at Tavern on the
Green after the New York premiere of ``Madeline,'' a film based on
the Ludwig Bemelmans series of books, the first of which begins
with that much-memorized line.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews from the crayons-and-ice-cream set were generally
positive. ``I liked when she sank into the water,'' said Adrienne
Fishman, who will be 6 next month, after reciting the opening line
with her sister, Julia, 9.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lawford was doing no such recitations. ``Not on your
life,'' he said. He had a question about pronunciation: ``Is it
Mad-uh-linn or Mad-uh-line?'' A chorus that included his daughter,
Savannah Rose, 8, favored the second. ``I'd never read it until I
had my daughter,'' Lawford said.
</P>
<P>
   Table Hopping
</P>
<P>
   Table 45 has become the hangout for literary types at Della
Femina, a restaurant in East Hampton, N.Y. One night, Salman
Rushdie, who went underground after the Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
pronounced a death sentence against him in 1989 after the
publication of his novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' had dinner at
Table 45. The next night, Leonard Riggio, the chief executive of
Barnes and Noble, was seated at the same table ... ``Inflation has
taken place, to the tune of 6 cents,'' said Danny Meyer, an owner
of Gramercy Tavern and the Union Square Cafe. He was talking about
the fixed-price lunches being offered by more than 100 restaurants
this week, a custom begun in 1992, when the price was $19.92. ``Our
two restaurants were completely booked even before it was
announced,'' he said ... Tim and Nina Zagat, compilers of
restaurant guides, issued their predictions for food in the 21st
century at the restaurant 21: They foresee computerized cookbooks
and kitchens with ``essentially one computerized food storage
unit'' that can freeze or cook.
</P>
<P>
   Give Them Land, Lots of Land
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman may accumulate more than just speeding tickets
in Montana. He reportedly has his eye on a ranch in bear country.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Salmond, a fourth-generation rancher, says that Letterman
is considering buying a chunk of the Salmond Ranch in northwestern
Montana. ``We're in the talking stage now,'' said Salmond, who
would not say how much land or how much money was being talked
about. He said that he had listed 10,000 acres for sale last fall
for $7 million but had taken the land off the market.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman, who has made his speeding on parkways in Connecticut
a running gag on his late-night talk show, visited Montana last
month and was stopped in Darby for, yes, speeding. He also passed
through Choteau, 250 miles northeast of Darby, where he told the
Choteau Acantha newspaper, ``I've never seen anything so beautiful
in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Salmond, he is not a big ``Late Show'' watcher. ``Don't
know very much about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nesting
</P>
<P>
   With his wife expecting, the radio personality Don Imus wants a
house with a nursery and a nanny's room.
</P>
<P>
   Imus has filed plans to build a seven-bedroom, seven-bath house
on 3.8 acres he owns in Westport, Conn. A public planning and
zoning hearing is scheduled July 23. Imus needs a construction
permit, as well as a demolition permit to tear down the existing
two-story house on the property, which he bought last year for $4.6
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
