<SLUG> BC-MINORITY-CRITICISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON COUNCILWOMAN SEES TOO MANY BLACKS IN CITY DEPARTMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Councilwoman Martha Wong complained in a letter to
Mayor Lee Brown that the city's Health and Human Services
Department has too many black employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an obvious over-representation of African-American
employees and a shockingly low representation of Asian American and
Hispanic employees,'' Wong wrote in a letter to Brown and Health
and Human Services Director Mary desVignes-Kendrick.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Kendrick, both of whom are African-American, responded
carefully to Wong's letter Tuesday, saying they both share Wong's
interest in diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to see is that we have a city government that is
open to everybody, in terms of the benefit of employment, and no
one should be left out,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Kendrick said the 53 percent black work force in her department
reflects in part the past inability of African-American health-care
workers to find better paying jobs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (Wong's letter) negates the past history in this
department and many others where individuals for racism-related
reasons were unable to get positions in many of the white
hospitals,'' Kendrick said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Marsh, the director's office liaison for Kendrick, said
the city department is 53.2 percent black, 16.3 percent Anglo, 27.7
percent Hispanic and 6.9 percent other, which includes Asians,
Native Americans and other groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern is a diverse work force to meet the needs
of the community we serve, and we take affirmative action very
seriously in this department,'' Marsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the department places ads for employment
opportunities in Houston's Asian and Hispanic community newspapers,
Marsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the department has made recent gains in hiring
Asians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making progress,'' Brown said. ``When you have a long
history of under-representation of any group, it takes some time to
bring it up because you just can't lay off people in order to make
up for a lack of Asians.''
</P>
<P>
   Wong said Tuesday her problems with the department also include
concerns about the ``work ethic'' of employees, although she did
not raise that issue in her letter to Kendrick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the (ethnicity) issue is important because Mayor Brown
said he wanted the staff to look like the city, and in this case it
doesn't,'' Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the work habits in the department, Wong said a
friend of hers recently took a job there, and told the council
member the employees were lax.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was told that if she worked too hard, she was going to be
in trouble,'' Wong said. ``So I have a concern that the work ethic
isn't there in that department.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he has never heard that complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what she means by that,'' Brown said. ``I have
not heard anyone say that nor have I heard her say that. I have
confidence in the director of that department.''
</P>
<P>
   With an annual budget of $55 million, the city's Health and
Human Services Department employs 1,067 workers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to setting the city's health policy, the department
provides animal regulation, inspects food service vendors and
swimming pools, and treats nearly 200,000 patients a year at city
health clinics, among other services.
</P>
<P>
   Many of its programs are funded by state and federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
