<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEDICARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PROTECTION FOR MEDICARE CONSUMERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, June 24:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's new Medicare regulations will
provide important consumer protections for 38 million elderly and
disabled beneficiaries as more of them move into the managed-care
system. Given Medicare's size and reach, these regulations could
also set an operating standard for the rest of the health insurance
industry.
</P>
<P>
   By moving aggressively to protect Medicare recipients, President
Clinton has seized on a powerful political issue. Republicans who
have opposed consumer protections for the millions covered by
private insurance must now explain why they would deny working
families the safeguards that publicly funded Medicare patients will
enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, a wide array of health
insurance plans, in addition to health maintenance organizations,
will be allowed to compete in the Medicare market against the
traditional fee-for-service coverage that serves most beneficiaries
now. Only 17 percent of Medicare recipients are now enrolled in
some form of managed care. That is expected to increase to 30
percent by 2005, making the need for managed-care guidelines more
urgent.
</P>
<P>
   The new regulations contain many key elements of the ``patients'
bill of rights'' proposed by a presidential advisory commission.
Women may demand direct access to women's health specialists for
routine and preventive care. Patients with chronic illnesses must
also be allowed reasonable access to specialists, and emergency
care must be covered in all cases where a prudent person has reason
to believe an emergency exists.
</P>
<P>
   The rules guarantee swift review by an independent panel for
patients appealing a denial of services. They would require all
plans participating in Medicare to release information about how
doctors are paid and to keep medical records confidential.
</P>
<P>
   Leading health plans already provide many of these protections
to all patients. The Medicare regulations will probably encourage
more plans to adopt these standards for all enrollees since that
would be easier than applying different standards to different
patient groups. Even so, a fair-minded Congress would extend these
basic protections to all consumers, including those trapped in
low-quality plans. States have very limited ability to regulate in
this arena. The administration's approach to Medicare could have a
positive effect on the managed-care system as a whole, but more
needs to be done. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
