A3606 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WADDELL-COX     06-23 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WADDELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waddell flush with recent success
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Some people suspect that their career has gone into
the toilet. Eleven years ago, Don Waddell could say it without
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   His hockey-playing career winding down at the age of 27, Waddell
entered the portable-toilet business in 1987. In his words, ``I was
Mr. Port-A-John,'' proudly selling and setting up his product.
``It's all part of the Waddell history that some of us would like
to forget,'' Waddell said, smiling, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell not only returned to hockey, he evolved into one of the
game's top young executives. He accepted the position as the
Thrashers' first general manager after spending only one year in
his ``dream job'' as an assistant GM with the Detroit Red Wings,
the team he grew up following.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell's success in the front office of three minor-league
teams and his ability as a talent evaluator had drawn the attention
of several NHL teams. Waddell said he turned down ``a half-dozen''
offers from NHL teams during his two years with Orlando of the IHL
``because they just weren't the right job,'' and had been
interviewed for the general manager's position in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would be a general manager one day, and I thought it
would be with one of the expansion teams,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even Waddell didn't imagine himself as Atlanta's general
manager when the city was awarded a team last year. He had signed a
lucrative four-year deal with the Red Wings, expecting to complete
at least half of it. But Thrashers president Harvey Schiller, who
became aware of Waddell through a casual conversation with Orlando
Magic/Solar Bears executive Bob Vander Weide, soon realized he was
the best available candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for somebody with leadership qualities,''
Schiller said, ``somebody with a knowledge of the game and somebody
who could draw the best people and had a formula for success.''
</P>
<P>
   Waddell once was named the IHL's defenseman of the year, but his
playing career might be known more for two low points: He made the
1980 Olympic team but suffered a broken leg in a pre-Games
exhibition. And less than a minute into his first shift in his only
NHL game, with Los Angeles, Waddell was knocked down inadvertently
by teammate Jerry Korab, allowing New York's Ron Greschner to
score.
</P>
<P>
   He had greater success off the ice. As a rookie GM, he turned
around a minor-league team in Flint, Mich., in 1989-90. Then came
seven years in the IHL and two executive-of-the-year awards. In
Orlando, Waddell also was instrumental in the construction of a new
practice facility shared by the Magic and Solar Bears. Here, he
will assume the responsibility to land a site for the Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   In Detroit, he was put in charge of minor-league Adirondack,
evaluated NHL players before potential trades and free-agent
signings and negotiated some contracts for general manager Ken
Holland. Detroit went on to win the Stanley Cup, and Waddell's
stock rose again.
</P>
<P>
   Even as late as Saturday, Schiller was receiving phone calls
from hopeful GM candidates. He declined any further interviews and
selected Waddell Monday over agent Mike Gillis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don was first choice,'' Schiller said. ``My only choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
