<SLUG> BC-CBS-MOLINARI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
...) MOLINARI QUITS CBS, ENDING ANCHORWOMAN EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(SUBS 8th graf pvs, A senior-level ..., to SUB anonymous quote with
paraphrase from several producers; Pickup 9th graf, Her hiring(nk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was either CBS News' experiment with creating an
anchorwoman from a congresswoman, or Susan Molinari's experiment
with transforming herself from a Republican Party star into a
television star. From either perspective, the experiment failed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ms. Molinari and CBS News president Andrew Heyward
announced that she would leave the network, nine months after she
began as the co-anchor of ``CBS News Saturday Morning'' with Russ
Mitchell. Saturday's broadcast will be her last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel she was terribly comfortable with the format or
material, even though she was very devoted to it and worked very
hard at it,'' Heyward said in a telephone interview. ``I think she
has a lot of ability and a lot to offer, but the program was not
the best venue for her. I think she missed the political arena _
not being in politics per se, but political commentary and
analysis. There's very little of that on a Saturday morning show.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Molinari, in a statement, praised everyone she had worked
with at CBS News and added: ``I look forward to my next opportunity
in broadcasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Her statement said she had accepted a visiting fellowship at
Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government starting in the
fall, and was considering ``several broadcasting options, including
commentary.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference 13 months ago announcing her hiring,
after almost seven years as a congresswoman from Staten Island, Ms.
Molinari described her vision for the program as ``a sort of `60
Minutes' meets Rosie O'Donnell,'' in which she could report on
important issues but also interview celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   A close friend of Ms. Molinari's, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said she had been dissatisfied because the program dealt
with substantive issues less often than she had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Several producers at CBS News said that, while diligent and
intelligent, Ms. Molinari was not adept at certain skills needed in
television and often seemed stiff when reading the prompter or
interviewing guests.
</P>
<P>
   Her hiring was widely criticized for blurring the line between
politicians and the journalists who cover them. Many media
personalities have gone into politics, and vice versa, although
some former politicians appear on television as commentators rather
than as reporters or anchors.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Molinari's popularity as a politician did not attract
many viewers. The show, a new venture for CBS News, has averaged a
1.3 Nielsen rating (each rating point represents 980,000
households), lagging about two points behind the more established
Saturday edition of NBC's ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   The show will continue with Mitchell and various substitute
co-anchors until a permanent successor to Ms. Molinari is named.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Molinari had a multiyear contract, but the settlement terms
were not disclosed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
