<SLUG> BC-NY-LI-POWER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIPA CHAIRMAN SAYS HE DIDN'T KNOW ABOUT LILCO PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARMINGDALE, N.Y. _ The head of the state agency that bought
part of Long Island Lighting Co. testified Tuesday that he did not
know beforehand about the special payments LILCO made later to
executives totaling $67 million, and had he known, he would have
tried to block the takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Richard Kessel, chairman of the Long Island Power
Authority, also said he had not raised the issue in negotiations
with LILCO because he believed that New York state's takeover
contract had a superseding clause barring such payments.
</P>
<P>
   His statements came in often tense and even bitter hearings here
as two state Assembly committees, Energy and the Committee on
Corporations, Authorities and Commissions, opened an investigation
into the payments, with Kessel as the first witness.
</P>
<P>
   The power authority bought part of LILCO on May 28 in a plan by
Gov. George Pataki to cut local electricity rates. The rest of
LILCO merged with Brooklyn Union Gas and its affiliates to form
Marketspan, which operates the electricity system under contract
with the authority. LILCO executives took new but similar jobs at
Marketspan.
</P>
<P>
   A week after the takeover, Pataki and Kessel disclosed the fact
that special payments had been made, including $42 million to
LILCO's chairman, William Catacosinos, who is now chairman of
Marketspan. The governor denounced the payouts as ``a secret act of
greed'' that violated the agreement and demanded that Catacosinos
return the money and resign.
</P>
<P>
   Kessel said that ``neither I nor the governor nor LIPA knew
anything about it at all _ they concealed it from us.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the takeover, who contend it was a giveaway to
LILCO, have pointed to numerous public documents that said LILCO
executives would get benefits upon a change of control of the
company. They say the governor and Kessel chose to ignore them to
avoid stirring an outcry that might jeopardize the takeover deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Documents exist _ of course documents exist,'' Kessel
testified. ``We all know that, of course. But because they weren't
terminated, they shouldn't have been paid. Our agreement says you
can't make the payments.''
</P>
<P>
   For the payments to have been made properly, Kessel said, a
second condition had to be met besides LILCO's change of control:
The executives had to be dismissed. And that was supposed to be
blocked by a clause barring dismissals and any resulting benefits,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But former LILCO officials dispute that, citing other clauses
specifying that the demise of LILCO meant they would be dismissed
and would thus qualify for benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the conflicting legal interpretations, Assemblyman
Paul Tonko, a Democrat who presided over the hearing as chairman of
the Energy Committee, said: ``There are two wildly diverse tales
here.'' He added: ``There had to be a discussion of the issue'' in
the LILCO negotiations. ``At least I hope there was,'' he said,
``and if there wasn't, something was really wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But the hearings revealed a major failure to communicate on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   A statement that a lawyer for Marketspan read into the record
concluded: ``Prior to closing, LIPA officials did not express the
view that anything in its agreement with LILCO prevented LILCO from
making these payments.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kessel said that although he sat at the same table
with Catacosinos during negotiations and at the final signing
ceremony, ``He never said a word to me about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had raised the issue with LILCO, Kessel said: ``Why
would I ask them a question about something they were prohibited
from doing? I am saying it was not an issue of concern, because it
was prohibited.''
</P>
<P>
   Kessel conceded that ``this was not an issue that dominated the
discussions'' with LILCO. One reason was that any such payments
would have come from shareholder profits. ``I was not as concerned,
because it was not ratepayer money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Kessel said: ``I would have recommended we not go
through with the LIPA deal, had I known. I would have held up the
deal till the money was given back. That would have been my
recommendtion to my board.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the session began, an unexpected guest arrived outside
the building. Betsy McCaughey Ross, who is running in the
Democratic primary for governor, attacked Pataki, a Republican.
``What did George Pataki know, and when did he know it?'' she said.
``Did he conceal the $42 million payout, or was he asleep at the
switch?'' She said the Assembly should call him and his aides as
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Two important witnesses were no-shows: Dr. Catacosinos and
Marketspan's president, Robert Catell. Instead, a company lawyer,
John Reilly, read a statement with numerous attachments to show
that the payments were proper. ``Because there are a number of
legal proceedings concerning those payments,'' he said,
``Marketspan cannot amplify on this statement or answer questions
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Voicing frustration, Assemblyman Tonko insisted that Catacosinos
and Catell would be recalled, and, ``if necessary, we will do a
subpoena.'' Assemblyman Steven Englebright, a Democrat, said: ``It
looks like they're trying to hide something.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
