r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-23 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW IT'S LASORDA'S TURN TO DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Surrounded by thick, black smoke, the Dodgers
opened all the windows. Perhaps now they'll set about putting out
the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 season is a three-alarm blaze that'll smolder or worse
until president Bob Graziano and interim general manager Tom
Lasorda tend to all the hot spots.
</P>
<P>
   Expect Lasorda, in particular, to exert far more energy looking
for a left-handed power hitter, a left fielder and/or a closer than
someone to take his place. It says here Lasorda, at last ensconced
in the seat he long has coveted, will search for a general manager
about as diligently as O.J. Simpson did for the killer of his
ex-wife and her friend.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers have no Fireman of the Year candidate in their
bullpen. Fiery new interim manager Glenn Hoffman is fine. But what
the Dodgers really could use is his brother Todd, a closer for the
division-leading San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   That much was borne out for the umpteenth time Monday night
against regional rival Anaheim, when Scott Radinsky entered the
game in the eighth inning with a 4-1 lead and exited three batters
later with the score tied at 4. The Dodgers would eventually lose
by one when right-hander Jim Bruske walked in the winning run with
the bases loaded in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make Dodgers fans yearn for the return of Todd
Worrell. When they're not crying in their coffee over Pedro
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' starting rotation was supposed to be their strength
this year, but it has struggled. Ismael Valdes and Chan Ho Park
haven't lived up to their billing, another rotator cuff injury has
shelved ace Ramon Martinez and irreconcilable differences ushered
Hideo Nomo out the door.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, everyone knows life can throw some pretty wicked curves.
The Angels have had to fend off a few themselves. Their manager,
Terry Collins, recently returned from an eight-game suspension.
They went into Tuesday's game against the Dodgers at Edison Field
without injured pitchers Mike James and Allen Watson.
</P>
<P>
   But on the strength of breakout performances by the likes of
pitcher Jarrod Washburn, who got the starting nod against the
Dodgers on Tuesday, and second baseman Justin Baughman, who has hit
safely in 15 of 27 games, the Angels haven't slipped a bit. Never
in its history has the team been on a streak as scintillating as
its current one, in which it has won 19 of 22 games to set the pace
in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Dodgers' real rivals, the second-place San
Francisco Giants, who enjoyed an eight-game cushion over the
Dodgers at Tuesday's start. They lost catcher Brian Johnson to a
fractured wrist at the start of the season and Brent Mayne stepped
forward and filled in nicely. Their regular first baseman, J.T.
Snow, has gotten off to a slow start. But it has been but a blip on
the screen because Charlie Hayes has spelled him so well.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers haven't had any players fill the voids created by
injury and inertia. Outfielder Roger Cedeno's talent can't hide his
tenuous grasp of the fundamentals. Paul Konerko homered and singled
in a run in his first two at bats, but he has struggled with his
consistency. Wilton Guerrero's defense, which cost the Dodgers a
run Tuesday, and lack of discipline at the plate continue to
confound.
</P>
<P>
   No player stepped up, so manager Bill Russell and executive vice
president Fred Claire were designated to take the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Russell probably was too laid back, as his critics claimed, and
Claire too indecisive. But that's not what killed them. A few
well-placed knives in the back by Lasorda did the trick, though
none too cleanly.
</P>
<P>
   You can say Claire effectively signed his pink slip by not
pursuing the likes of closer Rod Beck during the offseason and for
failing to deliver the deal in spring training that would have
brought Seattle pitching ace and former USC standout Randy Johnson
to the Dodgers for Valdes and Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   But it takes money to sign a free agent such as Beck, a Grant
High product who eventually landed with the Cubs, and the Dodgers
had tightened their purse strings in anticipation of their sale to
Murdoch's Fox Group. Claire was left to scrounge around for change
to sign infielder Jose Vizcaino.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Claire might have survived without a closer if he had
only had a closer's mentality. General managers, like relievers,
have to be able to recover quickly from their mistakes and move on.
</P>
<P>
   But Claire was a little hesitant to deal young players after
trading Pedro Martinez to Montreal for Delino DeShields in 1993. He
bore the brunt of the criticism when that trade turned out to be
laughably one-sided, never mind that Lasorda, the manager at the
time, hadn't exactly been shocked and dismayed to see Martinez
moved.
</P>
<P>
   If Claire had a fault, it was his fealty to young players such
as Cedeno and Guerrero. He believed in them to the bitter end.
</P>
<P>
   As one general manager recently told the Seattle Times,
``Whether they believe it or just try to sell it around, (the
Dodgers) rate their players so highly it creates tension in dealing
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are the ones who will feel the tension now. After
all, they're the only ones left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
