<DATE_TIME> 1998-06-23 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3617 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-SPI &LR;      06-23 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-RULING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT WINS KEY LEGAL BATTLE; STOCK SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WARREN WILSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. won a key legal victory Tuesday that it said
affirms its freedom to design its software without outside
interference and erodes claims by antitrust regulators that it
doesn't compete fairly.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling by the U.S. District Court of Appeals in Washington,
D.C., propelled Microsoft's stock to a record high and prompted
jubilation among the company's top executives.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Operating Officer Bob Herbold proclaimed Tuesday ``a great
day for consumers'' and said the decision ``reaffirms the central
principle ... that every company should have the freedom to improve
its products and integrate new features on behalf of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and legal experts agreed that the ruling was a
significant win for the company. But they warned that the issues
are far from settled, and that in any case Microsoft's market power
and hard-nosed business tactics will continue to draw regulators'
scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are anything but out of the woods,'' said industry
analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group. ``They have an image
that leads people to assume they're guilty until proven innocent
... until they fix their fundamental image problem, their exposure
to litigation remains significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice said little. It issued a
three-sentence statement saying it was disappointed with the
ruling, which came in a relatively narrow case filed last fall, but
remained confident it would prevail in the broader antitrust case
it filed last month along with companion litigation filed by 20
states and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Central to all of the cases has been the claim that Microsoft
has abused its Windows software monopoly by forcing computer makers
to also accept its Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of computers sold today are equipped with the
Windows operating system. Computer makers had no real alternative
to Windows if they wanted to replace Internet Explorer with an
alternative browser _ such as Netscape Navigator _ for computer
users to navigate the Internet and the World Wide Web, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft claimed it had combined the browser and the operating
system in a single ``integrated'' product on the basis of consumer
demand.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel supported that view, voting 2-1 in Tuesday's
ruling that it was ``inclined to conclude'' that the combined
operating system and browser was a ``genuine integration''
permitted under the 1995 consent decree at the heart of that case.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the Justice Department had not shown a ``reasonable
probability of success on the merits,'' the appeals panel decided
unanimously to cancel a preliminary injunction issued in December
by U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson that required
Microsoft to offer computer makers a browserless version of
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   It also was unanimous in vacating Jackson's decision to refer
the case to a special master, saying it found the case ``devoid''
of anything ``remotely `exceptional''' to trigger that procedure.
</P>
<P>
   In a rebuke to Jackson, the appeals court said his decision to
refer the case to Harvard Law School Professor Lawrence Lessig was
``either a clear abuse of discretion or an exercise of wholly
non-existent discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the appeals court had tentatively suspended Lessig's
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday Lessig said, ``This is an extremely
difficult case, and I am grateful to both sides for the patience
and respect that they showed me during the brief time that I worked
with them on this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The appellate judges did not rule on Microsoft's claim that
Lessig was biased against the company.
</P>
<P>
   Most heartening to Microsoft, however, was that the ruling went
far beyond those procedural questions to scrutinize major issues of
product design and the proper role of courts _ issues at the heart
of the case filed last month.
</P>
<P>
   That portion of the appeals ruling will be an ``important and
weighty authority in guiding the trial court,'' Bill Neukom,
Microsoft's senior vice president for law and corporate affairs,
told reporters and analysts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out passages in the ruling that he said supported two
of Microsoft's most important points: that the law should encourage
innovation and integration in pursuit of better products for
consumers, and that courts should generally avoid interfering in
such decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antitrust scholars have long recognized the undesirability of
having courts oversee product design, and any dampening of
technological innovation would be at cross-purposes with antitrust
law,'' the panel said in one passage that Neukom took care to point
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a validation of the company's legal right to continue
to do what it has been doing,'' Neukom said.
</P>
<P>
   Browser rival Netscape Communications issued a statement late
Tuesday stressing that the ruling ``most certainly did not decide
the broad antitrust case'' filed last month and echoing the Justice
Department's view that Microsoft would ultimately lose that case.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, D.C., antitrust expert Phil O'Neill said the
government would likely seize on a portion of the dissenting
opinion in which the judge outlined an alternative view that she
said the two other judges hadn't adequately considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's basically saying ... `Since I am able to come up with an
equally plausible construction, you ought to wait until the
fact-finding is done before you declare the game over,''' O'Neill
said.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neill agreed that overall, the ruling was a ``huge
victory'' for Microsoft, both symbolically and practically, and
predicted that Jackson would ``probably read this thing 100 times''
in weighing the next case, scheduled for trial on Sept. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically said (to the lower court judge), `You got
nothing right here,''' O'Neill said. ``He's got to be pretty
discouraged by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the appeals ruling was replete with nuggets that looked
like gold to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The integrated version of Windows and Internet Explorer offers
more functionality than the sum of the two products separately, it
said, adding, ``This strikes us as an essential point.''
</P>
<P>
   And the integration must logically be done by Microsoft; it
would be ``absurdly inefficient'' for computer makers or end users
to do it, the panel said.
</P>
<P>
   It suggested in several places that courts should try to stay
out of the way, noting at one point, ``Courts are ill equipped to
evaluate the benefits of high-tech product design.''
</P>
<P>
   It even questioned the value of pursuing the consent-decree
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In view of our interpretation of the consent decree, tentative
though it be, the Department (of Justice) may well regard further
pursuit of the case as unpromising,'' the panel said, ``especially
given the alternate avenues developing in its recently launched
separate attacks on Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether those avenues lead anywhere is also far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cuts the legs out from under the Justice Department on
their new case,'' Robert Litan, a former senior official in the
Justice Department's antitrust office, told the New York Times.
``It's potentially devastating.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
