u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-DRAFT-RUMORS-HNS &LR;      06-23 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-DRAFT-RUMORS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rumor mill churns out &QL; 
its annual assortment
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia _ They're everywhere you go in the
Great White North these days as today's NBA draft draws near.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects?
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, there are more than a few of those wandering the streets.
You can't go more than 50 feet without bumping into North
Carolina's Antawn Jamison, Pacific's Michael Olowokandi or
Arizona's Michael Bibby.
</P>
<P>
   But what we're referring to are the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, reports of trades and maneuvers, both real and
imagined, start flying as the draft nears. This year is no
different. Some are truly far-fetched (``Hey, did you hear that
Philadelphia is shopping Allen Iverson?'') while others are, well,
not so far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Knicks shipping Chris Mills, Chris Childs and John
Starks to Houston for picks Nos. 16 and 18 in today's draft? That's
one of the rumors that's out there. Sources close to the team
pretend to be amazed that something like that even gets started,
but that rumor has been floating around for more than two weeks, so
it can't be news to anybody in the Rockets' front office.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here is a sampling of the rumors floating around the
league right now as the draft approaches:
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Clippers need a point guard desperately. And
Michael Bibby, a true point guard who led Arizona to the 1997 NCAA
title, is there for the taking. It's a natural. Bibby is the son of
Henry Bibby, who helped UCLA to three straight titles in the early
'70s.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers, who were definitely taking Bibby two days ago,
are now reportedly considering taking Olowkandi instead. Why?
Because they're afraid they will look like idiots down the line for
not taking Olowokandi should the native of Nigeria blossom (see the
Portland Trail Blazers and Michael Jordan for historical reference
here).
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are supposedly offering Nick Van Exel and Elden
Campbell, or Eddie Jones and Campbell, in exchange for Vancouver's
No. 2 pick.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk the Grizzlies will take Olowokandi, if he's
available, and then ship Bryant ``Big Country'' Reeves to Phoenix
for point guard Steve Nash, a Canadian by birth. It's hard to
picture Reeves fitting in with whippets like Antonio McDyess and
Jason Kidd, but the Suns have been looking for an offensive-minded
center since Alvan Adams retired, so anything is possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another rumor swirling around Olowokandi has Milwaukee offering
Terrell Brandon and two first-rounders (Nos. 9 and 19) to move up
far enough to take the 7-1 center. Hard to see anyone biting on
this.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a rumor that doesn't involve Olowokandi _ Cleveland
sending suddenly expendable Bobby Sura to Orlando for one of its
three first-round picks (Nos. 12, 13 or 15). The Magic loves Sura,
who's from Florida State, and the Cavs don't have a first-round
pick but want one. And with Wesley Person and Derek Anderson at
shooting guard, the Cavs can afford to ship Sura out. It could
happen.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the usual quota of veteran players being shipped
out, like Golden State's Latrell Sprewell, who may be headed to
Miami for P.J. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect Philadelphia to trade Iverson so the Sixers can
move up in the draft. No way. After selling the fans on Jerry
Stackhouse, the No. 3 pick in the 1995 draft, the Sixers traded him
away two years later. They can't afford another fiasco like that
with Iverson, who is too talented to be dealt anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Philly did offer Tim Thomas and the No. 8 pick to move up to No.
2 trying to get _ who else? _ Olowokandi, but the Grizzlies thought
that Thomas was too much like Shareef Abdur-Rahim.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
